<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, May 15, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman Testifies 
<LI>McIntyre Homicide 
<LI>Cabbie Attacked 
<LI>Henderson Reaction 
<LI>Tory Nomination 
<LI>Taro Aftermath 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman Testifies </H3>

<P>
Accused killer Rory Foreman took the witness stand today in his
own defense. Foreman is charged with the first degree murder of
his 25-year-old former girlfriend Joan Heimbecker March 30th,
1994 in her McMaster University residence. 
<P>
<I>Remembering his former girlfriend, Rory Foreman testified that
when Joan Heimbecker walked into a room, the whole room lit up
around her. &quot;She had that radiance. you couldn't hate her.
It was impossible.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>When Foreman went to Joan's McMaster University residence the
night of March 30th, 1994, it was to ask for a reconciliation.
Foreman testified: &quot;I just wanted her to face me with what
happened. I thought if she saw me, everything would change.&quot;
Instead, Foreman says Joan told him she didn't love him, and never
did, and she repulsed his attempt to hug her. Foreman said: &quot;I
felt like dirt after that... it made me feel like road-kill was
better than I was.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Foreman left Joan's apartment, and when he came back, he was
carrying a sawn-off shotgun. Foreman's lawyer, Peter Bawden, asked:
&quot;what did you think you would do with the gun?&quot; Foreman
replied: &quot;she would have had to listen to me then... I was
going to scare her... have her sit there and think about everything.
I would torment her, same as she did to me.&quot; Bawden asked:
&quot;did you give her the impression you were going to kill her?&quot;
Foreman answered yes. </I>
<P>
<I>Bawden asked: &quot;what did you think was going to end it?&quot;
Foreman answered: &quot;I thought I was going to leave. just drop
the gun and walk out.&quot; But when one of Joan's room-mates
came to the apartment door, Foreman says he panicked. &quot;At
the same time someone screamed. I think it was Joan... I turned
around with the gun, and it went off.&quot; Bawden asked: &quot;are
you telling me it was an accident?&quot; Foreman answered: &quot;it
wasn't intended. I wasn't supposed to shoot anybody. It went off.
It didn't hit Joan. I was angry. I just snapped after that. The
next shot hit her in the leg. She was falling. I don't remember
the third or fourth shot. I remember as soon as she hit the floor
there was another shot that hit her in the neck.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>Just before he fired the final shot, Foreman says he became
aware of what he was doing, and pulled up the gun so the shot
hit the wall. He tearfully told the court: &quot;I didn't intend
anything. I was just angry. I lost control... just kept firing.
I couldn't stop myself until the last shot, and then it was too
late...&quot; I didn't know what I was doing. It was like... she
wasn't even human then&quot;.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>McIntyre Homicide </H3>

<P>
Halton Regional Police have reopened their investigation into
the death of an Oakville man twelve years ago. 
<P>
33-year-old William McIntyre was found in his home with a single
gunshot wound to his head. No one was ever charged but now police
say new information has led to the possibility of DNA testing
on substances found at the scene. 
<HR>

<H3>Cabbie Attacked </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton cab driver was mugged while walking home from work
overnight. 
<P>
Two men, one with a sawed off rifle, the other with a knife, forced
the cabbie down onto a sidewalk in central Hamilton, and rifled
through his pockets. Police are looking for two white men in their
late teens, both with baseball caps. One of the suspects was wearing
a black and white jacket. 
<HR>

<H3>Henderson Reaction </H3>

<P>
The Hamilton Wentworth Health Action Task Force is still under
fire by the medical community following the submission of it's
final report to the Regional District Health Council. 
<P>
The most controversial recommendation in that report is one that
calls for the closure of one acute care hospital in Hamilton.
The report doesn't name which one, but that hasn't stopped those
fearing the demise of their institution from taking to the streets...Jamie
West reports... 
<P>
<I>Several hundred doctors, nurses support staff and members of
the public rallied out front of Henderson General Hospital during
the noon hour to remind themselves and the public that they are
strong and won't go down quietly. </I>
<P>
<I>Although the Health Action Task Force has not specifically
earmarked the Henderson for closure, there is concern by staff,
especially since an earlier report suggested that St. Joseph's
Hospital take over the Henderson which serves not only Hamilton.</I>
<P>
<I>Another report by the city's hospital CEO's under the moniker
the Academic Health Care Network called for the Henderson to become
a scaled down urgent care centre specializing in cancer treatment
and major joint reconstruction surgery.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Tory Nomination </H3>

<P>
The Tories have named their candidate for the June 17th by-election
in Hamilton east. Angela Tomasic, a 35-year-old bank employee
will seek the seat left vacant by Sheila Copps' resignation. 
<P>
Tomasic's entry into the race brings the number of candidates
to six. Ian Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>It was Angela Tomasic's night and no one was going to ruin
it, not even Andy Sweck the Reform Party candidate who made appearance
that some Tories found daring and desperate. </I>
<P>
<I>Tomasic's nomination was contested by Quincy Morgan, the president
of an OPSEU local. </I>
<P>
<I>Tomasic ran against David Christopherson in Hamilton centre
in the last provincial election. It was an election she lost but
not by much. Tomasic hopes her popularity carries over into the
June 17th election. </I>
<P>
<I>Elsie Wayne, the other half of the federal Tories was the guest
speaker.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Taro Aftermath </H3>

<P>
City council in Stoney Creek will not request an environmental
assessment hearing into a proposed industrial waste dump site.

<P>
But the Hamilton Region Conservation Authority has requested the
review. It's now up to environment &amp; energy minister Brenda
Elliott. Anthony Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>Like the community it represents, Stoney Creek city council
is sharply divided on the Taro dump issue. Last night, after a
protracted and sometimes acrimonious debate, council tied on the
question of requesting an environmental assessment hearing into
the industrial waste dump site proposal. That means their original
decision not to ask for a hearing stands. </I>
<P>
<I>But the Hamilton Region Conservation Authority... almost as
sharply divided... voted last week to request a hearing. But Harry
Dahme, legal counsel for a community study group that reviewed
all of the technical data both for and against conversion of the
Taro aggregates east quarry, says that the issues have already
been examined to death. </I>
<P>
<I>The ball is now squarely in the court of environment and energy
minister Brenda Elliot. She had allowed until this Friday for
submissions on the question of whether a hearing should be held.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
For the third consecutive day, the value of Canadian stocks in
Toronto climbed to record highs. 
<P>
Interest rates in bond markets are dropping. 
<P>
Bay Street analysts are expecting the rally to continue into the
summer. 
<P>
