<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, May 14, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman-Day 13 
<LI>DNA Hamilton Lab 
<LI>OMA-First 
<LI>Tsubouchi Dundas 
<LI>Burlington Tourism 
<LI>Projects Completed 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman-Day 13 </H3>

<P>
The man accused of the shotgun slaying of a McMaster University
graduate student is expected to take the stand in his own defence
tomorrow. 
<P>
Today, the crown rested its case against 25-year-old Rory Foreman,
who's on trial in Hamilton for first-degree murder. His ex-girlfriend,
25-year-old Joan Heimbecker, died of multiple gunshot wounds in
her McMaster University residence on March 30th, 1994. 
<P>
As Deborah Walker reports, the final three crown witnesses to
testify were Joan's best friend, another close friend, and a former
girlfriend of Rory Foreman's. 
<P>
<I>Val Percival and Joan Heimbecker became close friends while
working together in the summer of 1993. That fall, Joan moved
to Hamilton, and Val to Ottawa, to pursue their masters degrees,
but they kept in touch by mail. </I>
<P>
<I>In November Joan wrote: &quot;I'm still seeing Rory. I didn't
want to get emotionally involved with anyone, but I did ... I
enjoy being with him, he's mushy though... like kissing in public
and holding hands all the time, but I kinda like it.&quot; Three
months later, and exactly four weeks before she died, Joan sent
another letter to Val, saying she'd broken off her relationship
with Foreman to go out with a new boyfriend. Joan wrote: &quot;things
were (are) still a bit &quot;messy&quot; with Rory. He was not
happy. I felt bad because he's a sweetie and he's like a big teddy
bear. However we really didn't have that much in common.&quot;
</I>
<P>
<I>Around the same time, Rory Foreman was leaving notes at the
Kitchener home of his former girlfriend, Debbie McCorkindale.
In a March seventh note left on her windshield, Foreman wrote:
&quot;I care about you a lot and I may never see you again...
something bad happened and I wanted to talk to someone... I don't
know where to turn anymore.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>On March 29th, Debbie McCorkindale found another note, and
some flowers on her doorstep. Foreman wrote: &quot;I'm just writing
to say goodbye since this is probably the last time you will ever
hear from me. I'm almost 90 % positive I won't be back... I will
always care about you and I hope you have a good life.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>McCorkindale says she tried unsuccessfully to telephone Foreman
to find out what the letter was about. Twenty-four hours later,
Joan Heimbecker was dead.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>DNA Hamilton Lab </H3>

<P>
In many murder trials and sexual assault cases DNA evidence has
become an essential part of the trial. In response to the demand
for DNA tests, Ontario's Centre for Forensic Science is doubling
the size of its DNA crime lab. But even with the hiring of 25
extra staff, the centre will still have to send extra work out
to private labs. Kathy Renwald visited a private facility in Hamilton.

<P>
<I>John Waye looks at the DNA profile that will settle a paternity
suit. Its the kind of work his Ident Lab gets from the Center
for Forensic Science. </I>
<P>
<I>The center in Toronto is doubling the size of its DNA crime
lab. That will help it clear a backlog of work that in the past
has involved high profile cases including Paul Bernardo and Guy
Paul Morin. </I>
<P>
<I>From his Hamilton lab John Waye provides DNA testing and consulting.
Even though the wait for DNA test results from the Centre for
Forensic Science is up to 5 months ... Waye doesn't see that prompting
the start up of many private labs. The newest equipment for DNA
testing is 210 thousand dollars ...a prohibitive price for small
labs. But the demand will continue to increase according to Waye
..who says DNA evidence is vital in murder and sexual assault
cases.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>OMA-First </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Medical Association says healthcare in Ontario is
nearing a crisis. 
<P>
At news conferences held across the province today doctors say
budget cutting by the Harris government is putting patients at
risk. The OMA is inviting people to voice their concerns about
the future of medical care and they've launched a series of radio
and television ads to encourage people to write their MP's. 
<P>
Doctor's say the public must decide the priority of medical services
in Ontario not just doctors and medical economists. 
<HR>

<H3>Tsubouchi Dundas </H3>

<P>
Depending upon whom one talks to, the Harris government is either
on the right track or moving too far too fast, creating a lot
of pain along the way. It is, of course, up to members of the
cabinet to try and convince Ontarians of the former. 
<P>
Today... it was the turn of community and social services minister
David Tsubouchi... at a Rotary Club luncheon in Dundas. Channel
11's Anthony Pooley was there. 
<P>
<I>Typically, after a government brings down a budget, cabinet
members are temporarily turned into salesmen. It's up to them
to hit the rubber chicken circuit and preach their particular
economic gospel. And that's what community and social services
minister David Tsubouchi did in Dundas today... </I>
<P>
<I>Before a luncheon meeting of the Rotary Club... and he was
on friendly and affluent turf at the Dundas Valley Golf and Curling
Club. He told Rotarians... many of whom are small business people
... of the interconnection among the provincial tax cut, government
cost-cutting and job creation, sticking to the party line that
the first two lead to the last one... as well as deficit reduction
toward a balanced budget by the turn of the century. </I>
<P>
<I>But where are the 725,000 new jobs promised during the election
campaign? one Rotarian asks. And later he told reporters that
Workfare... a plan to get welfare recipients who can to work for
their monthly stipends... is coming... hinting that Hamilton could
be one of the initial test communities.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Burlington Tourism</H3>

<P>
The Burlington Visitor and Convention Bureau launched an aggressive
campaign to attract tourists today... complete with mascots...
at Spencer Smith Park. 
<P>
Attractions in Burlington may be more of a secret than anyone
would like them to be... hence a promotion campaign. The bureau
is building its push with the city's museum. 
<HR>

<H3>Projects Completed </H3>

<P>
The city of Niagara Falls is celebrating the completion of 7.6
million dollars worth of infrastructure projects...28 in all,
including a 2.1 million dollar storm and sanitary sewer on Victoria
Street, improvements and reconstruction of roads, sidewalks and
watermains, upgrade to recreation facilities including Niagara
Falls Memorial Arena; and roof repairs to the public library.

<P>
The projects completed under a municipal, provincial and federal
partnership, also created the equivalent of more than a thousand
year-long jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Some encouraging economic information from the United States injected
more confidence into financial markets. 
<P>
New evidence suggests tame inflation in the United States will
help to keep American and Canadian interest rates stable. 
<P>
Markets reacted with a decline in interest rates and another big
gain in stocks. Share prices in Toronto hit new record highs.

<P>
