<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, May 13, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Health Final
<LI>Business First
<LI>Student Employment
<LI>Foreman 12
<LI>Policing Centre
<LI>Police Cuts
<LI>Policing Seniors
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Health Final</H3>

<P>
Reduce the number of acute care hospitals in Hamilton Wentworth
from four to three. Period. No mention of which hospitals. That's
the bottom line of the Health Action Task Force's final draft
of recommendations being submitted to the District Health Council.

<P>
When &quot;Our Health Our Future&quot; was released in March it
created a huge public outcry, especially over its recommendation
to close St. Joseph's Hospital. The final draft is now in the
hands of the Regional District Health Council for approval, before
it makes it's way to the Ministry of Health. As Jamie west reports,
it appears the controversy is far from over. 
<P>
<I>That was Hamilton Wentworth Health Action Task Force chair
Ray Johnson March 4th. On the release of the report that among
other things recommended the closure of St. Joseph's Hospital
downtown Hamilton in favour of moving it to the building now occupied
by Henderson General. A recommendation that was widely criticized
by health care workers, hospital CEO's and the general public.
</I>
<P>
<I>The outcry was so loud that the District Health Council extended
it's period for public response by two weeks. And respond they
did...the CEO's of Hamilton's hospitals formed a united front
under the name &quot;The Academic Health Care Network.&quot; Their
recommendations... save St. Joes and turn the Henderson into an
urgent care hospital with a focus on cancer and major joint reconstruction.
</I>
<P>
<I>The document even seemed to catch the task force chairman's
eye. But then the doctors of the Hamilton Civic Hospitals banded
together to release their own report, one critical of the lack
of attention being paid to patient care.</I>
<P>
<I>In all the task force heard from nearly 50-thousand people
by phone, fax, and mail. Nearly 85-thousand signed petitions to
save St. Joseph's. But after two and half months, the task force
is still recommending that one hospital close it's doors.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
A volatile day on financial markets finished in positive territory.
Renewed fears over another Quebec referendum caused an early devaluation
of the dollar. 
<P>
The Canadian currency finished the day stronger while the value
of stocks in Toronto and new York climbed to records highs. 
<HR>

<H3>Student Employment </H3>

<P>
In Burlington today... the Canada Employment Centre for Students
officially opened its doors... as it tries to find summer jobs
for those who go back to school in the fall. 
<P>
Their objective this summer... 900 placements. Last year, they
found jobs for 875 students seeking summer work. New this year...
computer software to help clients come up with a resume... now
required by most prospective employers. 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman 12 </H3>

<P>
A Brantford woman testified today she watched Rory Foreman pull
a package from the trunk of a car, less than a half-hour before
a McMaster University student was shot to death. Foreman is charged
with first-degree murder in the 1994 shotgun slaying of his ex-girlfriend,
Joan Heimbecker. Deborah Walker is covering the trial in Hamilton.

<P>
<I>Joan Heimbecker was hit by four shotgun blasts in her on-campus
residence just before ten o'clock, the night of March 30th, 1994.
Less than a half-hour earlier, Barb Hazzard was parked in this
McMaster University parking lot, waiting to pick up her daughter,
when she saw a tall black man striding towards her. Hazzard identified
the man as Rory Foreman. </I>
<P>
<I>She testified... &quot;he had on a long coat and it was flapping
behind him as he was walking briskly.&quot; Hazzard says Foreman
walked to a blue Taurus parked two spaces away from her and...
&quot;...opened the trunk. His hand reached in and took out a
package.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Barb Hazzard told the court the car's trunk was full of things,
but Foreman found the item he was looking for easily. It was wrapped
in a garbage bag, with twine or tape wound around it in two places.
After closing the trunk, Hazzard says Foreman walked to the driver's
side, with the package clutched to his stomach. He opened the
door, put the package inside, got in himself and drove off. </I>
<P>
<I>Around the same time, engineering student Ed Palmer watched
a blue Taurus pull in right behind him in the circular driveway
outside Bates Residence, where Joan Heimbecker lived. Palmer went
into bates for a few minutes, then left again. as he walked to
his car, he saw a tall black man standing by the opened door of
the Taurus, a man he identified in court as Rory Foreman. Less
than a half hour later, Joan Heimbecker lay dying in a pool of
blood in her second floor apartment at Bates. </I>
<P>
<I>In other testimony, a forensic document expert told the court
she examined a driver's license, birth certificate, and Conestoga
college student card recovered when Rory Foreman surrendered to
police in Colorado. On all the documents, Christine Warias says
someone used a pen to change the &quot;F's&quot; to &quot;E's&quot;,
in an unsophisticated attempt to make &quot;Foreman&quot; look
like &quot;Eoreman&quot;. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Policing Centre </H3>

<P>
Community based policing in Hamilton took another step forward
today. The Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police Service officially
opened its third store front centre... this one at Centre Mall.

<P>
It was also the kick-off to police week... as well as the new
highway help program... in which motorists can buy inexpensive
signs asking passers-by to call police in the event of unexpected
car trouble. 
<HR>

<H3>Police Cuts </H3>

<P>
If you get stopped for a boating violation on Hamilton Harbour
this summer you may be dealing with a cop from Hamilton, Halton
or the RCMP. As Kathy Renwald reports, Hamilton's Police Marine
unit may be reorganized to save money and step up efficiency.
The change would create a joint forces police team on the water.

<P>
<I>It costs about 480 thousand dollars a year for the Hamilton
Wentworth Regional Police to operate its marine unit. Both police
administration and regional politicians are looking for ways to
trim that cost while delivering the same amount of policing. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton's Police Services Board should get a report by the
end of this week that proposes a sharing of Harbour policing between
Hamilton and Halton forces and the RCMP. Deputy chief Ken Robertson
says that could even mean officers from Hamilton and Halton sharing
the same patrol boat. </I>
<P>
<I>The chairman of the Police Services Board endorses the potential
efficiency. A joint police effort between Hamilton Halton and
RCMP could reduce duplication and some equipment costs associated
with the marine units. Regional police in Hamilton are even looking
at transferring winter rescues on the water to the fire department.
</I>
<P>
<I>If the proposed joint forces approach to policing on Hamilton
Harbour and the lakefront is approved ..changes could be underway
by June,</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Policing Seniors </H3>

<P>
...and police in Hamilton also paid a visit to seniors at the
Sackville Hill Recreation Centre today... where this year's police
week theme &quot;Partners in Community Safety&quot; was evident.

<P>
It was a seminar designed to address the concern for the victimization
of the elderly in our community. Police were offering crime prevention
advice related to personal safety, telemarketing scams and con
artists. Other services like Hamilton ambulance and the Hamilton
and Dundas fire department were also there... as well as the elder
abuse task force and several other volunteer organizations. 
<P>
