<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, May 3, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>WHO - Ivermectin
<LI>Clean Soils? 
<LI>Copps Fundraiser 
<LI>Young Offender 
<LI>Biker Follow 
<LI>Missing Man 
<LI>Cross Missing 
<LI>Halton Conflict 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>WHO - Ivermectin</H3>

<P>
The World Health Organization has turned its attention on a home
for the aged in Dundas, where an unusually high number of residents
died after taking a drug considered perfectly safe. 
<P>
The drug is called Ivermectin. It has been used extensively, and
successfully since the 1970's by agencies like the WHO, to treat
tropical parasitic diseases. Last November, it was administered
to forty-seven patients at Wentworth Lodge in Dundas. As Deborah
walker reports, fourteen of them died within five months of taking
the drug. 
<P>
<I>it started last June, with a scabies outbreak among residents
of Wentworth Lodge in Dundas. Months of conventional treatment
failed to rid residents of the irritating, itchy rash. In desperation,
staff turned to a consultant, who recommended Ivermectin. Because
the drug is not approved for use in Canada, Wentworth Lodge had
to apply to the Federal Health Protection branch for permission
to use it. </I>
<P>
<I>All forty-seven residents suffering from scabies took a single
dose of Ivermectin last November. Within five months, fourteen
of them had died, a death rate that's two-and-a-half times higher
than the rest of the Wentworth Lodge population. </I>
<P>
<I>Doctor Barkwell says there's nothing to indicate Ivermectin
caused the deaths, but right now, it's the only thing all fourteen
had in common. Doctor Barkwell has notified the coroner's office,
the health protection branch, and the drug's manufacturer. He
says it will take months of epidemiological research to determine
what role Ivermectin, or any other factor, played in the deaths
of the fourteen residents.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Clean Soils? </H3>

<P>
A company operating a soil cleaning business on the edge of Hamilton
Harbour has provoked both the Hamilton beach strip residents and
city council. As Kathy Renwald reports city council wants to force
Clean Soils Limited to move or close down. 
<P>
<I>Hamilton city and regional politicians are dogged by a decision
4 years ago not to oppose the start up of this waste processing
site on pier 26 in the east Harbour. </I>
<P>
<I>Clean Soils Ltd said they expected up to 90 per cent of their
petroleum contaminated soil to arrive by ship to. Then at the
Eastport site the soil would be heated to remove gas and oil.
The municipality regarded this as a marine use and did not object
to the facility. But so far the soil has arrived by land. And
the Hamilton Harbour Commission confirms no ships have delivered
to this site. </I>
<P>
<I>Now under pressure from beach strip residents who say the facility
is a nuisance the city wants Clean Soils out. Beach strip residents
delivered a petition to councilors about their concerns. </I>
<P>
<I>Today Clean Soils president Gordon Weis said the uncovered
pile is the treated soil. But the Ministry of the Environment
confirms Clean Soils Limited was fined last summer for violations
..and that the ministry has asked the company to voluntarily address
three concerns. Tarping of soil, stack emissions and storage of
soil. </I>
<P>
<I>But alderman Collins says there's not much the company can
do to change his mind. Clean Soils president Gordon Weis said
the company never indicated when they would start receiving their
contaminated soil by ship.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Copps Fundraiser </H3>

<P>
Located in Hamilton east, that story could well turn into an issue
in the June 17th by-election. Federal leader Alexa Mcdonough will
kick off the NDP campaign next Thursday, when the new democratic
candidate will be elected. 
<P>
And Sheila Copps got a boost to her re-election bid last night
when she was named Hamilton's political woman of the year at a
Hamilton Status of Women dinner. And at a Liberal fundraiser,
Copps was presented with a pair of boxing gloves, so she could
indeed come out fighting in next month's by-election. 
<HR>

<H3>Young Offender </H3>

<P>
A fifteen year old boy is in police custody after being charged
in what police describe as a reign of terror in east Hamilton.
Police were called after a 54-year old man was shot at several
times with a pellet gun. It was later determined that the boy
was a suspect in two separate sexual assaults on two 14 year old
girls. Furthermore after comparing notes with other officers,
police discovered the boy's fingerprints matched those found during
four break and enters at an east Hamilton apartment building.

<P>
The boy who cannot be identified under the Young Offenders Act
is facing several charges including sexual assault with a weapon,
forcible confinement, four counts of break and enter and a number
of weapons charges. 
<HR>

<H3>Biker Follow </H3>

<P>
And the latest now in what could become a biker reign of terror,
since Niagara police announced on Monday that they will hunt down
bikers and wipe the gangs out a number of incidents have occurred.
Lauran Sabourin has this update. 
<P>
<I>Early Tuesday morning a fire that arson investigators are calling
suspicious started on the back porch of a home rented by an Outlaws
gang member. Thirty three year old Jay Deming had lived at the
Allanport Road house for a few years. The fire spread to from
the porch to a back bedroom and gutted most of the inside. A rottweiller
who lived at the house was killed in the blaze. </I>
<P>
<I>Then later that day in a rural section of Port Colborne police
were alerted to a helicopter flying only a few feet off the ground
near a farmer's field. Three scruffy looking men were seen in
the area of concession two after the helicopter left. They got
into a car and drove off. </I>
<P>
<I>Meanwhile police are continuing to scour home and property
owned by Outlaws St. Catharines president Mario Parente. Parente
has fifty acres of land on Sodom road in Niagara falls. Police
have been there since Monday and have seized a number of items.
They've also seized weapons, ammunition and drugs. Cocaine and
marijuana with a street value in excess of 700 thousand dollars.
</I>
<P>
<I>With all of this evidence police say they will spend the next
several months building their case against Parente. While keeping
a watchful eye on the activities of gang members.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Missing Man </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Wentworth police are asking for the public's help in
locating a man who went missing yesterday. 
<P>
Gary Joseph Ziegler is twenty five years old, medium build, five
foot ten, a hundred and seventy pounds, light complexion, blonde
shoulder length hair, and blue eyes. He was last seen wearing
a black and red nylon jacket with black nylon pants, and grey
and white running shoes. 
<HR>

<H3>Cross Missing </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile a ground search by Halton Regional Police has turned
up no clues in the disappearance of an Oakville woman. 
<P>
27 year old Diane Cross is a teacher at St. Mildred Lightbourn
School in Oakville. She was wearing a dark green coat, a blue
and black tweed jacket and skirt, and white running shoes. Cross
is a diabetic, and it's not known if she has any medication with
her. 
<HR>

<H3>Halton Conflict </H3>

<P>
The taxpayers coalition in Burlington is preparing to take legal
action against several Halton board of education trustees. 
<P>
Coalition Education chair Frank Gue says the board is unable to
grasp quality and cost problems. He claims part of the inability
is paralysis caused by what he feels is a conflict of interest
through several trustees having close relationships with board
employees. 
<P>
A taxpayers coalition legal fund account has been opened. Taxpayers
may contribute at any Canada Trust branch in Halton. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
The leaders of Stelco and Dofasco today criticized the lack of
action by the federal government to deal with foreign companies
that dump cheap steel in Canada. Both of Hamilton's big steel
companies held their annual shareholder meetings today. Stelco
also announced the retirement of president Robert Milbourne. 
<P>
