<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, May 2, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton East 
<LI>Harris - Hamilton 
<LI>Foreman 6 
<LI>Sex Charges - Teacher 
<LI>Halton Rape 
<LI>Cross Missing 
<LI>Milton Fatal 
<LI>Water Park Fire 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton East </H3>

<P>
Less than 24 hours after a tearful resignation, the campaign in
on! It may have been a surprise to Sheila Copps but the resignation
of the deputy prime minister yesterday doesn't seem to have caught
campaign workers in Hamilton East flat-footed. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris - Hamilton </H3>

<P>
Ontario premier Mike Harris got a first hand look this afternoon
at what residents may be spending their proposed 30 per cent tax
break on. 
<P>
Harris toured the Stoney Creek Furniture showroom and no, he wasn't
there looking to rearrange his cabinet. He was at Stoney Creek
Furniture to hear about plans for a 3 million dollar expansion,
to begin in July. The expansion will add 30 new jobs, bringing
the total workforce to about one-hundred and 5. 
<P>
Premier Harris told employees he hopes more people will be buying
furniture when his 30 per cent provincial income tax break comes
into effect. 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman 6 </H3>

<P>
A McMaster University graduate student, wounded by four shotgun
blasts, showed no signs of life when ambulance attendants arrived
at her residence apartment. 
<P>
25-year-old Joan Heimbecker was shot to death on the Hamilton
campus two years ago. Her ex-boyfriend, 25-year-old Rory Foreman,
has pleaded guilty to manslaughter in her death, but not guilty
to first-degree murder. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Ambulance attendants Paul Zenchuk and Seamus O'Connor say Joan
Heimbecker had no pulse, and had stopped breathing when they arrived
at her McMaster University residence minutes after ten o'clock
the night of March thirtieth, 1994. </I>
<P>
<I>O'Connor testified he noticed a shotgun near the apartment
entrance, and saw the shooting victim lying face-down on the floor,
covered with a blanket, her face pale and ashen. As he and his
partner worked to revive her, O'Connor says he noticed gaping
wounds in both shoulders, and the left side of her neck. Both
arms were broken, and her left knee-cap was missing. </I>
<P>
<I>About six hours earlier, the man who admits he killed Joan
Heimbecker, was singing along with two Conestoga College class-mates,
as he gave them a lift home from school in a rented car. Marsha
Chapman, who attended nursing classes with Rory Foreman at the
Kitchener college, says he wished her and her room-mate happy
Easter when he dropped them off. </I>
<P>
<I>Chapman, her room-mate and nursing professor Mary Colley all
encountered Foreman in the Conestoga college cafeteria the day
Joan Heimbecker died. They testified he told them he'd been up
most of the night before, visiting a friend in Toronto who had
been shot. </I>
<P>
<I>Another witness has said Foreman did go to Toronto the day
before Heimbecker was killed in order to pick up a gun. Professor
Colley told the court she had the impression Foreman was going
back to Toronto, to try to find the person who shot his friend.
She says she warned Foreman &quot;don't do anything to get yourself
into trouble.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>The jury has now been excused until Monday morning, so the
judge can hear legal arguments over the admissibility of evidence.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Sex Charges-Teacher </H3>

<P>
Twenty additional sexual assault charges have been laid against
an elementary school teacher in Niagara Falls. 
<P>
Last week a charge of sexual assault and sexual interference were
laid against the 55 year old teacher. After further investigation
17 other students came forward with sexual assault allegations.
The students are 8 and 9 year olds. Two are girls the other 16
are boys. 
<P>
The teacher was removed from the classroom in mid April when the
first charges were laid. The accused was set to retire at the
end of this school year. 
<HR>

<H3>Halton Rape </H3>

<P>
Halton Region Police have released details of another sexual assault
in Burlington, but said they don't believe it was committed by
the serial rapist being sought for brutal attacks on three youngsters.

<P>
A 14-year-old girl was sexually assaulted April 24 as she walked
home from a baby-sitting job. She was approached by a man and
forced into a secluded driveway, where she was assaulted. But
the suspect's description does not match that of a man who raped
three youngsters, aged eight, 10 and 15, in Kitchener, Brampton
and Oakville over the past four years. 
<HR>

<H3>Cross Missing </H3>

<P>
And Halton police are concerned about the disappearance of a 27
year old Oakville woman. 
<P>
Diane Cross is a teacher at St. Mildred Lightbourn school in Oakville.
Cross hasn't been seen since noon yesterday, when she left the
school during lunch hour. There is no known reason for her disappearance,
and her family is worried about her health. 
<P>
Diane Cross is a diabetic, and needs her medication daily. Ms.
Cross was last seen wearing a dark green coat, a blue and black
tweed jacket and skirt, and white running shoes. Anyone with information
is asked to call Halton Regional Police. 
<HR>

<H3>Milton Fatal </H3>

<P>
A single car crash last night in Milton claimed the life of a
man from Storrington Township. It happened on Tremaine Road just
before 9:30 ...a pick-up truck left the road and struck a tree.

<P>
38-year-old Edward Huntbach was pronounced dead at the scene.

<HR>

<H3>Water Park Fire </H3>

<P>
Firefighters are describing a major fire in the Niagara Falls
tourist district as highly suspicious. They were still on the
scene today after the early-morning blaze burned through a gift
shop, restaurant and change rooms at the Whitewater Waterside
park on Lundy's Lane at the QEW. Damage is estimated at 200-thousand
dollars. 
<P>
A maze of water slides and the park's wave pool were not affected.
The cause of the fire is under investigation. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Investors dumped stocks in Toronto and New York today as interest
rates in bond markets moved higher. The selloff was sparked by
new economic data in the US showing a stronger than expected economy.

<P>
Philip Environmental of Hamilton reported another healthy profit
for the first quarter of this year. 
<P>
