<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, May 1, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Copps Quits
<LI>Copps History 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Foreman 5 
<LI>Hit &amp; Run 
<LI>Bikers-Brock 
<LI>Bomb Robot 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Copps Quits</H3>

<P>
She said she would resign if her government failed to scrap the
GST. And today Sheila Copps kept that promise. And on this same
day the prime minister called a by-election in Hamilton East,
for June 17th. 
<P>
Copp's announced her resignation at a packed news conference held
inside her east Hamilton constituency office over the noon hour.
Copps had been on the hot seat since she said last Thursday the
GST promise she had made prior to the last election was a fast
lip comment. 
<HR>

<H3>Copps History </H3>

<P>
The Copps name in Hamilton is synonymous with scrappy, down to
earth politics. Sheila Copps grew up with the imprint of her flamboyant
father who had a hand in shaping this city as mayor for 13 years.
Reporter Kathy Renwald looks back at the political and family
climate that shaped Sheila Copps. 
<P>
<I>Sheila Copps absorbed politics in her east Hamilton home. Father
Vic was one of this city's most popular mayors who had the common
touch with the people of his home town and a sense of flair that
daughter Sheila would mine as she scrapped her way into politics.
</I>
<P>
<I>At 9 campaigning for her sisters election to a catholic youth
group she showed joy in the political process. At home with mother
Geraldine who would go on to become a city alderman.. and her
dad the mayor ..Copps thrived in the atmosphere of lively conversation
and public spot light. At 24 she ran provincially and lost.. but
went on to work for liberal leader Stuart Smith.. the next time
Sheila Copps won the Hamilton Centre riding and would go on to
run against David Peterson for the leadership.. she finished second.
</I>
<P>
<I>In 1984 Sheila Copps was elected to the House of Commons, defeating
former Hamilton mayor Jack Macdonald. There her badgering and
baiting style quickly inked her membership in the Liberal rat
pack along with John Nunziata. She chased foes down staircases
and sparred in the commons like a street fighter. Her give and
take with John Crosby made nightly headlines. </I>
<P>
<I>Throughout her political career, Sheila Copps would draw on
the memory of her father who died in 1988 for inspiration. Copps
was the first woman to run for the federal liberal leadership.
And her daughter in the family tradition.. traveled in political
circles at an early age. </I>
<P>
<I>Just last week, deputy prime minister Copps sat with royalty
in the area named after her father ..but the storm was building
for her to resign and today she looked back to her roots for her
explanation to quit.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stock prices climbed to new record highs again today,
helped by a strengthening dollar and easing interest rates in
bond markets. 
<P>
Air Canada reports a loss in this year's first quarter. 
<P>
MasterCard and Bell Canada are launching Canada's first combination
calling and credit card. 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman 5 </H3>

<P>
Two more friends of the man accused of killing a McMaster University
student say he talked about buying a gun shortly before she died
of four shotgun blasts. And another says the accused withdrew
at least fifteen-hundred dollars in student loan money from a
bank account, just days before Joan Heimbecker's murder. 
<P>
All three testified today at the Hamilton trial of 25-year-old
Rory Foreman, who has pleaded guilty to manslaughter, but not
guilty to first-degree murder. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Jason Stolper attended Conestoga College in Kitchener with
Rory Foreman. Two weeks before Joan Heimbecker was gunned down
at McMaster University, Stolper says he had a &quot;strange&quot;
conversation with Foreman while parked outside a Kitchener bar.
</I>
<P>
<I>Stolper testified Foreman said &quot;what I'm about to say
will get you and me in a lot of trouble if you tell anybody ...I'm
thinking about buying a gun.&quot; Stolper asked &quot;what do
you need a gun for? you're a big guy. you can take care of yourself.
you'd never shoot anybody anyway.&quot; Foreman replied &quot;oh
you don't know me. I would.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Stolper says he thought Foreman was joking. But the day Joan
Heimbecker was shot to death, Stolper encountered Foreman in the
Conestoga College cafeteria. When Foreman mentioned he'd rented
a car, Stolper asked if he'd been to Toronto, and Foreman nodded
&quot;yes&quot;. Stolper says he assumed Foreman went to Toronto
to buy the gun. </I>
<P>
<I>Another close friend, Jody Bishop, ran into Foreman the day
before Joan Heimbecker died. Bishop says Foreman mentioned he
was going to Toronto to pick up a gun. The day of the murder,
Bishop briefly saw Foreman again. Bishop says Foreman told him
&quot;he'd picked it up.&quot;</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Hit &amp; Run </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton woman remains in hospital with serious injuries after
a two car hit and run accident in the city's east end last night.
Police say a blue Chevelle hit the woman's car after running a
red light. The driver and a passenger in the suspect car fled
the scene. 
<P>
Police say 64 year old Vivian Wells is expected to recover from
multiple injuries but are looking for the public's assistance
in finding the driver responsible.
<HR>

<H3>Bikers-Brock </H3>

<P>
Last night we told you how police in Hamilton are bracing for
new neighbours: about 20 members of Satan Choice. Simmering tensions
between rival bike gangs in Ontario and Quebec have police everywhere
on high alert. 
<P>
Today at Brock University in St. Catharines bomb disposal experts
from around the world were sharing information. And as Lauran
Sabourin reports biker activities was near the top of their agenda.

<P>
<I>The battleground for the biker wars up to now has been around
Montreal. The Hell's Angels the largest motorcycle gang on the
continent wants to extend its influence. Word is that Hell's Angels
want a foothold in the lucrative southern Ontario drug and prostitution
market. </I>
<P>
<I>Christian Nantel is a tactical officer with the Montreal police.
He's seen first hand the destruction that can result when bikers
declare war on each other. Bikers are dead. Innocent people killed.
Biker gangs are difficult to infiltrate. New recruits to prove
their loyalty are often required to kill someone. </I>
<P>
<I>There is a barrier between police and full fledged members
that is as thick as the concrete that protects their clubhouses.
Police in southern Ontario have launched a zero tolerance program
against bikers. The target in Niagara is the outlaws. But the
Hell's Angels have their eye on the peninsula. Turf wars usually
begin with strong intimidation tactics. Hundreds of rival bikers
treading on the others turf. And if the dispute in Montreal is
any indication these are wars that are not settled quickly.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Bomb Robot </H3>

<P>
During a break at the conference on international explosives and
terrorism experts got a look at the latest in bomb disposal hardware.

<P>
Remote control robots demonstrated how they could destroy active
explosives. The machines can climb stairs, deliver weaponry and
perform other functions in high risk situations. 
<P>
