<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, April 30, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Biker Follow 
<LI>Foreman 4 
<LI>Youth Forum 
<LI>Joe Brant - Cuts 
<LI>Mac Donation 
<LI>Orr - United Way 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Biker Follow</H3>

<P>
More tonight on the police crackdown on biker activity in the
golden horseshoe. Last night after a series of raids, Niagara
Police Chief Grant Waddell vowed bikers who engage in illegal
activity will be hunted down and put behind bars. And that pre
emptive strike against the outlaws motorcycle gang in St. Catharines
may only be the beginning of a full fledged war between police
and bikers in southern Ontario. <BR>
As Lauran Sabourin reports police intend to destroy the gangs
by attacking their leadership. A man police have identified as
an outlaws kingpin appeared in court this morning. 
<P>
<I>Mario Parente president of the local Outlaws chapter in Niagara
appeared in a Hamilton court today on charges of cocaine trafficking
and uttering death threats. </I>
<P>
<I>A small army of police officers gathered at Parente's Niagara
falls farm today. They were there to conduct that intensive search
of the 50 acres of land. The Outlaws have significant control
over prostitution and drug dealing throughout the peninsula. </I>
<P>
<I>Other motorcycle gangs, Satan's Choice and Hell's Angels have
their eye on Niagara. Hell's Angels have been trying to gain a
foothold in Ontario for some time.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Foreman 4 </H3>

<P>
A long-time friend of a man accused of first degree murder testified
today an upbeat Rory Foreman talked out reconciling with his ex-girlfriend
just days before she was hit by four shotgun blasts at McMaster
University. But the same friend says Foreman talked about buying
a gun eight to ten weeks earlier. Reporter Deborah Walker is covering
the trial in Hamilton. 
<P>
<I>25-year-old Joan Heimbecker was gunned down in her on-campus
residence at McMaster University on March 30th, 1994. Six days
earlier, Heimbecker's ex-boyfriend, Rory Foreman, went drinking
with his buddy Dan la-ree in a Kitchener bar. </I>
<P>
<I>La-ree says Foreman told him he was going to Hamilton on the
weekend to patch things up with Joan. La-ree testified foreman
&quot;seemed in very good spirits. he was very spunky ...lots
of life ...and in a good mood.&quot; Under cross-examination La-ree
testified Foreman seemed to believe a reconciliation was possible.
He also said that, eight-to-ten weeks earlier, he was surprised
when Foreman told him he wanted to get a gun. La-ree testified
he asked Foreman &quot;what for?&quot; he said &quot;for protection.&quot;
La-ree said &quot;protection from what?&quot; He said &quot;just
...protection.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>In other testimony, defence lawyer Peter Bawden suggested two
witnesses had embellished their accounts of threatening phone
calls Foreman made to Joan Heimbecker after their relationship
ended. Paul Litt, who lived with the victim for five years in
her hometown of Clifford, says he talked to Joan two days before
she died. She told him Foreman told her &quot;if I can't have
you, nobody will.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Bawden found it surprising that of all the friends, room-mates
and class-mates police interviewed, only Litt and his niece reported
Foreman's threats. But when the defence lawyer tried to point
out discrepancies between trial testimony, and initial statements
to police, Litt retorted... &quot;I didn't think it was that important
because everyone knew who the murderer was.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Rory Foreman admits he killed Joan Heimbecker, but he says
her death was unintentional. At the outset of his trial, Foreman
pleaded guilty to manslaughter, but not guilty to first degree
murder.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Youth Forum </H3>

<P>
The victims of crime lobby group CAVEAT says young criminals commit
more than 100 crimes before they are first arrested. 
<P>
The number of murder arrests among 18-year-olds and younger has
climbed 93 per cent in the last decade and the number of 12 to
17-year-olds charged with violent crimes in general has skyrocketed
by more that 131 percent. 
<P>
CAVEAT has sponsored a number of forums including its <I>Safetynet
</I>conferences which have already resulted in changes to the
justice system. But tonight CAVEAT's Youth Council will sponsor
it's own public forum on the young offenders act and the role
it plays in youth crime. 
<HR>

<H3>Joe Brant - Cuts </H3>

<P>
Burlington's Joseph Brant Hospital has sounded the alarm. Officials
there are saying today the hospital is looking at disaster in
the face of a six million dollar - or ten percent - budget shortfall
this year. Joe Brant has already closed 59 beds and cut the equivalent
of 80 full-time jobs. 
<P>
Chief of Medical Staff, Dr. Ben Carruthers, says further cuts
will have to come at the expense of seniors awaiting scarce beds
in nursing homes. 
<P>
The Halton District Health Council is looking at the regions'
450 patient waiting list for nursing home beds. One suggestion
is to use some of the hospital beds being closed by Joe Brant.

<HR>

<H3>Mac Donation </H3>

<P>
Better news over at McMaster University today. One of the largest
corporate donations to the new university centre campaign. 
<P>
140-thousand dollars from the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce.
The 54-thousand square foot complex will combine student services,
lecture theatres, conference rooms and retail space. Six million
of the estimated 19-million dollar cost has already been raised
by students. The university is seeking another six million from
the private sector. CIBC chairman Al Flood was on campus today
to officially deliver the cheque. 
<HR>

<H3>Orr - United Way </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Wentworth United Way Chief Executive Officer Jody Orr
is resigning effective June 7th. She intends to develop her own
consulting firm. 
<P>
Orr has headed up the United Way for five challenging years. Resource
Development Director Barry English has been appointed interim
CEO.
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Shares of Philip Environmental of Hamilton were among the most
active stocks traded in Toronto today. The share priced jumped
by a dollar and 25 cents as the company announced its plans to
issue more shares. 
<P>
Financial markets paused today with little change while oil prices
dropped. 

<P>
