<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, April 29, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Outlaws Bust 
<LI>Gambling Bust 
<LI>Drug Bust 
<LI>Foreman 3 
<LI>Abductor Sentence 
<LI>Robbery Suspect 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Outlaws Bust</H3>

<P>
An outlaw motorcycle kingpin is behind bars tonight after raids
on six biker clubs in the Hamilton - St. Catharines area. 
<P>
One hundred heavily armed police officers raided the clubhouse
and the homes of the outlaws biker gang in Niagara this morning.
They executed search warrants at five Niagara locations and one
in Hamilton. Police say this is only the first step toward eradicating
the bikers in the peninsula. 
<HR>

<H3>Gambling Bust </H3>

<P>
A crackdown on illegal gambling is underway in Hamilton Wentworth.
Last Friday, vice squad officers arrested two men and seized nine
illegal video gambling machines. As Jamie west reports...the raids
are the result of family concerns... 
<P>
<I>These video gambling machines are not set up for fun and games,
but for serious profit by their operators. And they're being discovered
by the dozens in small establishments around Hamilton Wentworth.
They're rigged to give the house the upper hand... they accept
bills not quarters... gamblers buy and bet credits that can later
be exchanged for cash. </I>
<P>
<I>Each machine can be programmed for the amount of money it will
pay out as a percentage of what amount of money is played. The
average is for every 100 hundred dollars played the machine will
allow the gambler to win 10 to 90 dollars back. The machine generates
about a  thousand dollars a day in profit for the operator. The
house never loses, but families do. </I>
<P>
<I>Friday night's raid on two Stoney Creek bars netted police
nine machines and 95-hundred dollars in cash. Charged with keeping
a common gaming house are 35-year old Antonia Mascia of Hamilton
and 34-year old Salvatore Vastano of Hamilton. And vice officers
warn,, you could be charged just for being inside a place that
operates these machines.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Drug Bust </H3>

<P>
A street level drug dealer sweep by Halton police netted 16 arrests
this morning at residences in Hamilton, Burlington, Oakville,
and the Mississauga area. 
<P>
Project WISK began as an undercover operations three months ago,
targeting illegal drug dealers trafficking in crack cocaine, marijuana,
hash and LSD. With seven people already served, today's arrests
being the total to 23 charged with a total of 66 offenses and
more are expected. 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman 3 </H3>

<P>
Just days before she was gunned down in her university residence,
prosecutors say a McMaster graduate student told friends she was
scared by a barrage of threatening phone calls from her ex-boyfriend.

<P>
As the victim's parents and friends sat in a Hamilton courtroom
today, testimony began in the first-degree murder trial of 25-year-old
Rory Foreman. Foreman has already admitted he's responsible for
the death of 25-year-old Joan Heimbecker. But he says he did not
intend to kill her. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>In her opening address, assistant crown attorney Alexandra
Paparella told the jury the evidence will show that Joan Heimbecker
called a friend two days before she was shot to death, and told
him Rory Foreman told her &quot;if I can't have you, nobody will.&quot;
</I>
<P>
<I>The day she died, Joan Heimbecker called another friend to
complain about threatening phone calls from Foreman, and to ask
&quot;do you think he'll do anything to hurt me?&quot; One hour
later, Joan Heimbecker was shot four times with a shot-gun in
her on-campus apartment at McMaster University's Bates Residence.
</I>
<P>
<I>The first witness to testify, a Hamilton- Wentworth Regional
Police officer, took the jury on a tour of the crime scene using
a videotape and photographs he shot the night Joan Heimbecker
was killed. Sgt. Frank Pedersen drew the jury's attention to a
sawed-off shot-gun abandoned near the apartment entrance, six
spent shotgun shells, blood-soaked towels, blood stains on the
rug, blood splatters on a wall, and two holes in the same wall
caused by shotgun blasts. </I>
<P>
<I>Paparella says evidence will show that before Joan Heimbecker
died, Rory Foreman pointed the shotgun at her, and while caressing
it ...said &quot;you've made me suffer. I'm going to make you
suffer now.&quot;</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Abductor Sentence </H3>

<P>
In another Hamilton courtroom today a would-be abductor received
a seven-year prison sentence. 
<P>
25-year-old Shawn Jamis was convicted in January of attempted
kidnapping and forcible seizure. He was arrested after a McMaster
co-ed was shoved head first into the trunk of a car. A police
officer heard her screams and thwarted the abduction. Mister Justice
Nick Borkovich called Jamis a danger to the public. 
<HR>

<H3>Robbery Suspect </H3>

<P>
Police in Welland are asking for the public's help in identifying
a man who held up the same bank twice last winter. Both robberies
occurred at the Bank of Nova Scotia branch on Niagara Street.

<P>
Police released a composite sketch of the suspect. He's described
as white, in his early 20's, with a slim build. He was wearing
a dark colored balaclava, blue jeans and dark colored jacket.

<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
The value of Canadian stocks in Toronto rose to their 21st record
high today as the dollar and interest rates remained stable. 
<P>
Small capitalized companies are one of the strongest performing
sectors for investors. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

