<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, April 24, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Busker Profile 
<LI>Meiler Arrest 
<LI>Meiler Background 
<LI>Canal Drag 
<LI>Gibson Photo 
<LI>Booze-Sewers 
<LI>Charles Details 
<LI>Taro-Elliott 
<LI>1005 Vote 
<LI>Budgets 
<LI>Business First
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Busker Profile</H3>

<P>
An arrest has been made in the beating death of a friendly Hamilton
street musician. 
<P>
Police are still trying to piece together details of the crime
and the background of the quiet, well-liked man who died 12 days
after a violent encounter. Kathy Renwald reports. 
<P>
<I>His face was familiar to customers at the liquor store on York
Boulevard. 45 year old Michael Welsh played the guitar daily outside
the entrance and quietly accepted handouts. Now he's dead ..and
a police command post is set up outside the beer store on Dundurn
Street ..where Michael Welsh was beaten 2 weeks ago. </I>
<P>
<I>Charged with manslaughter is 33 year old Sandor Patocs, but
the investigation is still active. Police are trying to piece
together the details of Michael Welsh's life. </I>
<P>
<I>Though he appeared to be a loner, he has a wife, a daughter
and son, though they went their separate ways. He lived in this
apartment building for a while..but the superintendent cant place
the face..and couldn't find a record of Michael Welsh as a tenant.
</I>
<P>
<I>At the liquor store where he strummed the guitar employees
remember Welsh had a friend.. police have located her. The friend
lived at the other end of Queen Street..and for the last little
while Michael made his home here. During the last 12 days of his
life, Edna visited him in hospital, she said he could barely remember
his name. now his 19 year old son is coming to claim the body.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Meiler Arrest </H3>

<P>
And police in Kitchener have their man. Late this afternoon ...
murder suspect Mike Meiler was picked up in Kitchener Waterloo
Hospital. 
<P>
Waterloo Regional Police Sgt. Dennis Butcher was attending another
suspect at the hospital, when he spotted Meiler in the treatment
room and made the arrest, without incident. Police say he was
being treated for hypothermia at the time of his arrest. 
<HR>

<H3>Meiler Background </H3>

<P>
Just who is this man, who was the subject of a Canada-wide murder
warrant? Scot Urquhart reports. 
<P>
<I>Police raided this quiet home in west Flamborough last night
... looking for Mike Meiler. Meiler once lived here with his wife
... that was before the divorce ... before a man tried to confront
his estranged spouse... here in Kitchener; before Nicholas Biuk
was shot and killed ...trying to intervene. </I>
<P>
<I>After the split; Mike Meiler lived here briefly. The man who
answered the door of this Burlington residence, didn't want to
go on camera. He said Mike Meiler was a really good guy. A quiet
guy, who wanted to get back together ... with his wife. That Mike
Meiler was accused of murder was, he said: a real shock. </I>
<P>
<I>Vince Farkas was shocked too. not only did Mike Meiler once
work for him ... he was a friend of the family as well: and Vince
Farkas, echoes that sentiment.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Canal Drag </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Police are searching a drainage canal along
Highway 403 after some fisherman reeled in what appears to be
human hair. 
<P>
The marine unit was called in and dragging operations subsequently
snagged some articles of clothing. The major crimes unit is investigating.

<P>
The marine operations were hampered somewhat by the barriers installed
to keep carp out of Cootes Paradise. 
<HR>

<H3>Gibson Photo </H3>

<P>
Niagara Regional Police are asking for the public's assistance
in their investigation into the death of 41 year old John Gibson.
The body of the Welland cab driver was discovered in a drainage
ditch behind Nectar Donuts on the afternoon of Sunday April 14th.

<P>
An autopsy revealed that Gibson had drowned. Anyone with information
on Gibson's whereabouts is asked to call Niagara Regional Police
in Welland. 
<HR>

<H3>Booze-Sewers </H3>

<P>
The Canada Customs warehouse in Niagara Falls is overflowing with
booze. Smuggled liquor that has been seized at the border. 
<P>
But as Lauran Sabourin reports Canada Customs and Niagara Region
have come up with a plan that will see all of this contraband
go down the drain. 
<P>
<I>This is just one storage room at the custom warehouse in Niagara
Falls. A room that is wall to wall liquor cases. This is pretty
well packed... six thousand liquor bottles are stored in this
room. Bottles that have been here for more than a year because
it has been too time consuming to dispose of them. </I>
<P>
<I>Under the law Customs couldn't pour the liquor down the drain.
They had to pour it into bins and then transport those bins to
the treatment plant. </I>
<P>
<I>Customs probably has a better selection than the liquor store.
The number of liquor seizures at the border have remained the
same. But the commercial seizures of smuggled booze has gone up
significantly. Rusted out gas tanks. Placed into tubing. Smugglers
use all kinds of techniques to hide the contraband. </I>
<P>
<I>What can be seen is that the smuggled liquor is piling up.
Customs asked for new rules that would allow them to dump the
liquor down the drain. Ottawa and Niagara region have come to
an agreement, where customs can pour the liquor down the drain.
Liquor that can safely be treated. As long as they pay a surcharge.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Charles Details </H3>

<P>
Tickets are sold out for the noon-hour ceremony at Copps Coliseum
in honour of the Prince on Friday. But there will be one thousand
seats added to the trade show area at Copps Coliseum, this area
will have a television feed of the ceremonies. 
<P>
Tickets for the extra seating can be picked up at Copps Coliseum
box office beginning at 10 a.m. tomorrow. Organizers ask that
you be inside the coliseum no later than 11:30. 
<P>
Around 1:30, his motorcade will slow down in front of Gore Park,
on the way to the Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum in Mount Hope.
The Prince will arrive to open the museum shortly before 2 o'clock,
but you'll have to be there before one o'clock when parking will
be closed. The museum will be hosting an open house during the
event, and no tickets are required.
<HR>

<H3>Taro-Elliott </H3>

<P>
A preliminary hurdle has been cleared, paving the way for plans
for a Stoney Creek landfill site to go ahead. 
<P>
Environment Minister Brenda Elliott has approved the first stage
of an environmental assessment for the Taro Landfill site. Taro
plans to expand its current industrial landfill site just off
Highway 20 on Stoney creek mountain. 
<P>
Elliott's approval is only for the planning process, so there's
still a long way to go before the site is rejected to approved.

<HR>

<H3>1005 Vote </H3>

<P>
Steelworkers at Stelco's Hilton Works are voting again today,
on an early contract. The first deal between their union and Stelco
was rejected by only 9 votes. This second deal is essentially
the same as the first, but with wage improvements. 
<P>
Local 1005's current contract expires on July 31st. If ratified,
this agreement would give the steelworkers a six year deal with
Hilton Works. 
<HR>

<H3>Budgets</H3>

<P>
The Halton Board of Education has approved a budget with a 1.9-percent
increase over last years. That translates into a 28-dollar tax
increase for the average homeowner. The budget calls for six million
dollars worth of concessions to be negotiated from the boards
employees. 
<P>
Meanwhile, the Hamilton- Wentworth Separate Board has a deal with
its elementary school teachers. They've agreed to staff reductions
through attrition and to a restructuring of benefits to avoid
layoffs. Secondary teachers have so far refused to reopen their
contracts to help the separate board deal with its 6.4-million
dollar budget shortfall. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Stelco of Hamilton reports a drop in its sales and profits for
the first quarter of this year. 
<P>
Foreign investors spent more than three billion dollars in February
buying Canadian stocks and other securities. 
<P>
The dollar lost value today, stocks and bonds remained stable.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

