<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, April 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman 2 
<LI>Meiler Photo 
<LI>Busker Death 
<LI>Most Wanted 
<LI>Thorold Fatal 
<LI>Scrap Yard Mishap 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>St. Kitts Restruct. 
<LI>Halton Budget 
<LI>Jo Brant Money 
<LI>Prince-Choirs 
<LI>Charles Details 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman 2</H3>

<P>
Prospective jurors were asked today if the issues of race or domestic
violence might influence their verdict in the first-degree murder
trial of a former Kitchener college student. 
<P>
25-year-old Rory Foreman is on trial in Hamilton for the shotgun
slaying of a McMaster University graduate student. The twelve-member
jury was finally chosen after a day-long selection process.
<HR>

<H3>Meiler Photo </H3>

<P>
Waterloo Police have released this photo of a Burlington man wanted
in the second degree murder of Nicholas Biuk of Kitchener. 
<P>
Michael Meiler is 34 years of age, 6-foot-one, 220 pounds. He
was wearing blue jeans, hiking boots and a blue thinsulate coat.
Meiler lives on Mountainside Drive Burlington. Biuk died of a
shotgun blast over the weekend. 
<HR>

<H3>Busker Death </H3>

<P>
Regional Police in Hamilton are looking for witnesses; to help
them solve this city's first homicide, of 1996. 
<P>
45 year old Michael Walsh, was a well-known street busker, who
often played his guitar in front of the LCBO., at York and Caroline.
On Thursday April 11th however, he was stationed near the Dundurn
beer store, when he became involved in an altercation with an
unknown suspect. Walsh received severe head injuries in the clash,
and died in hospital this morning. 
<P>
Police are looking for anyone who may have witnessed the incident.
They are also attempting to locate a young woman with a French
accent, who was seen leaving the area carrying the victim's guitar,
and it's case. 
<P>
Starting tomorrow, the police will establish a command post at
the Dundurn Street location. Anyone with information in the case
can talk to investigators there, or contact either the major crimes
division ... or Crime Stoppers. 
<HR>

<H3>Most Wanted </H3>

<P>
And police in Hamilton- Wentworth are still looking for a suspect
in a serious assault and robbery that took place in March. 
<P>
Attempts to locate Jay Thomas Lewis have been unsuccessful so
far even though police believe he is still in the Hamilton area.
He is described as white, 30 years of age, 6-foot-three with short
curly brown hair, a moustache and a tattoo of a skull on his right
shoulder. The victim of that Hamilton Rebecca street address is
still in hospital. 
<HR>

<H3>Thorold Fatal </H3>

<P>
The tenth traffic fatality in Niagara this year has claimed the
life of a 20-year-old Pelham man. 
<P>
The victim was killed instantly this morning when he ran a stop
sign on a rural road in Thorold and smashed into a pickup truck.
The accident happened at the intersection of Barran and Allanport
roads. 
<P>
The man whose identity has not been released pending the notification
of family members was pronounced dead at the scene. The driver
of the pickup walked away from the crash. 
<P>
This is the tenth traffic fatality in Niagara this year. 
<HR>

<H3>Scrap Yard Mishap </H3>

<P>
A Niagara Falls man is in critical condition after being impaled
in a freak accident at a Welland scrap yard. 
<P>
Niagara Regional Police say 38-year-old Wayne Falconer was operating
a wrecking ball crane when a piece of metal came flying off some
old machinery. The chunk of metal smashed through the cab of the
crane and falconer's abdomen. After being pinned to the seat,
Falconer managed to free himself and fell to the ground from the
cab. He was found by a co-worker and taken to hospital. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Ottawa today announced a merger of the GST and provincial sales
taxes in Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and PEI to create a new 15
per cent national tax. The government hopes the other provinces
will come onside eventually. 
<P>
In other business news today..... Canadian stock prices rose to
record high levels for the second day in a row. 
<P>
New economic data and corporate earnings point towards an improving
Canadian economy. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Restruct. </H3>

<P>
Four of St. Catharines top city bureaucrats have been fired as
a result of restructuring. The four departments they headed have
been downsized into two. 
<P>
Jim Coughlin, Tom Derreck, Bill Lefeuvre and Jim Brady made emotional
public appeals to council last night to keep them on. But in the
end council decided to hire two outsiders.
<HR>

<H3>Halton Budget </H3>

<P>
Trustees with the Halton Board of Education will tackle the 1996
budget one more time tonight, after voting it down last night
by a slim margin. 
<P>
It happened when they voted against a motion to reallocate money
in order to bring in a zero percent tax increase. They'll again
tonight at 8 o'clock. 
<HR>

<H3>Jo Brant Money </H3>

<P>
Good news for Joseph Brant Hospital in Burlington. It's going
to receive more than 1.5-million dollars in provincial funds.

<P>
It's a share of 25-million dollars announced by health minister
Jim Wilson to offset provincial grant reductions in high growth
areas. Burlington South MPP Cam Jackson says a total of almost
four-million dollars will go to the four hospitals in Halton.

<HR>

<H3>Prince-Choirs </H3>

<P>
Prince Charles has touched down in Ottawa for a week-long Canadian
visit as hundreds of school children prepare for his arrival in
Hamilton Friday. They're rehearsing a giant musical celebration
in his honour at Copps Coliseum. Annette Hamm sat in on a rehearsal
at one of the school's involved, and has this report. 
<P>
<I>These students, choir members at Ancaster's Fessenden Public
School, are in a hurry to get it right. They've had only a month
to rehearse a four piece repertoire for a performance before prince
Charles on Friday afternoon. </I>
<P>
<I>This choir of 50 grade 4, 5, and 6 students will perform along
with hundreds of others from the Hamilton Wentworth area. They
know the notes, melodies and words of the pieces they'll sing
together, but it will be just hours before the Prince arrives
when everyone gets it all together, under the direction of Wayne
Strongman from the Bach Elgar choir. </I>
<P>
<I>These students will be part of a panorama of Hamilton music,
which begins around noon on Friday at Copps Coliseum.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Charles Details </H3>

<P>
There are a limited number of free tickets available for the ceremony
at Copps Coliseum on Friday. You can reserve tickets by calling
Hamilton Mayor Bob Morrow's office at 546-2790, or the Sesquicentennial
office at 546-1996. 
<P>
Organizers ask that you be inside the coliseum no later than 11:30.
The Prince will arrive at quarter at twelve, and be on stage for
about an hour. 
<P>
Around 1:30, his motorcade will slow down in front of Gore Park,
on the way to the Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum in Mount Hope.

<P>
The Prince will arrive to open the museum shortly before 2 o'clock,
but if you want to see him there, you'll have to before one o'clock
when parking will be closed. The museum will be hosting an open
house during the event, and no tickets are required. 
<P>
