<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, April 22, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Meiler Wanted 
<LI>Ohsweken Murder 
<LI>Foreman Trial 
<LI>Beverage Charges 
<LI>Tiger Attack 
<LI>ITT Cuts 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Meiler Wanted </H3>

<P>
Police across southern Ontario are searching for a Burlington
man tonight, wanted for murder. 
<P>
Waterloo Regional Police are issuing a Canada-wide warrant for
34-year-old Michael Meiler of Mountainside Drive, Burlington,
after a man died of a shotgun blast in an apparent domestic dispute
last night. 
<P>
Meiler is described as white, 6 foot-one, 220 pounds, he was wearing
jeans, hiking boots and a blue thinsulate coat. A shotgun was
recovered at the scene. Anyone with information on his whereabouts
should contact police. 
<HR>

<H3>Ohsweken Murder </H3>

<P>
An Ohsweken man has been charged with first degree murder after
a woman's body was found in a Brantford motel. 
<P>
39-year-old Paul Hill was arrested at the scene. The victim was
identified as his wife, 31-year-old Paula hill. Police say she
was stabbed to death. 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman Trial </H3>

<P>
The man accused in the shotgun slaying of a McMaster University
graduate student admits he's responsible for her death. 
<P>
However, on the opening day of his trial in Hamilton, 25-year-old
Rory Foreman pleaded not guilty to first degree murder. Deborah
Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>25-year-old Joan Heimbecker, a McMaster University graduate
student, died two years ago of multiple gunshot wounds. She was
gunned down in her residence on the Hamilton campus. Heimbecker's
former boyfriend, Rory foreman of Kitchener was charged with first-degree
murder in her death. </I>
<P>
<I>On the opening day of his trial, Foreman was arraigned before
a jury panel of 155 citizens. Foreman's lawyer said his client
had instructed him to plead not guilty to first degree murder,
even though foreman admits responsibility for Joan Heimbecker's
death. </I>
<P>
<I>However the defence lawyer says Foreman did not intend to kill
Joan Heimbecker, and therefore pleads guilty to the lesser charge
of manslaughter. However crown attorney Alexandra Papparella says
a guilty plea to manslaughter is unacceptable to the crown, and
that she is prepared to proceed with a first degree murder case
against Foreman.</I> 
<P>
Jury selection for the Foreman trial will begin in earnest tomorrow
morning. Nearly half the members of the jury panel were excused
today for reasons ranging from medical problems to financial hardship.

<P>
Among those excused today was Glanbrook Mayor Glen Etherington,
who explained to the court he was scheduled to share the podium
with Prince Charles on Friday, when the prince officially opens
the Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum in his municipality. 
<HR>

<H3>Beverage Charges </H3>

<P>
Four golden horseshoe men are facing a string of fraud and theft
charges after a two-year investigation into in a Burlington-based
beverage distributorship plan. 
<P>
The investigation involved global resources incorporated and related
companies all over Canada and the United States and the marketing
of an in-home carbonation device. Losses are expected to be in
the area of two million dollars. 
<P>
Charged are: 44-year-old Phillip Chan of Guelph, 46-year-old Randolph
Hay of Hamilton, 48-year-old Richard Vanderploeg Sr. of Stoney
creek, and 52-year-old William Chadderton of Mississauga. The
investigation is continuing and police say it does not pertain
to the merits of the beverage device itself. 
<HR>

<H3>Tiger Attack </H3>

<P>
That tiger attack on a couple last Friday has apparently not scared
off visitors to the African Lion Safari in Rockton. 
<P>
A man and woman are in Hamilton General Hospital after being mauled
Friday by a Bengal tiger. They drove through the tiger area with
their car windows down. 
<P>
Park spokeswoman Donna Clements says there does not seem to be
a difference in attendance since the attack. Park officials say
the tiger remains in isolation and under observation.
<HR>

<H3>ITT Cuts </H3>

<P>
Another major job exodus in St. Catharines. ITT automotive is
cutting 100 jobs almost a third of its workforce as it transfers
machining work to a sister plant in Tonawanda, NY. A spokesman
says it will be more cost-effective. 
<P>
Last Thursday, Cadbury Beverages Canada announced it was closing
its Mott's division in St. Catharines by the end of the year,
wiping out about 175 jobs which pay an average of $16 to $19 an
hour. 
<P>
The ITT phase-out meanwhile, is to begin in may or early June.
The company makes brake drums and rotors. The foundry will continue
to produce the castings, which will then be shipped for finishing
at the American plant. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
The value of Canadian stocks in Toronto rose to record highs today
as short term Canadian interest rates dropped while the dollar
remained stable. 
<P>
Canadian banks are lowering their short term mortgage rates. 
<P>
Laidlaw of Burlington is offering to buy Scotts Hospitality. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

