<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, April 19, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Safari Bite 
<LI>Protest 
<LI>Tsubouchi-Women 
<LI>Slain Woman Fund 
<LI>Education Follow 
<LI>School Search 
<LI>Teacher Sex Assault 
<LI>Strip Club Charges 
<LI>Eisenberger - Prostitution
<LI>MOT Closure 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Safari Bite </H3>

<P>
A man and woman have been rushed to hospital in Hamilton after
they were attacked by a tiger at the African Lion Safari near
Cambridge. 
<P>
A spokesperson at the safari says a the couple were in a car with
the windows rolled down among a group of tigers. We have a crew
at the scene and will bring you more details as we receive them.

<HR>

<H3>Protest </H3>

<P>
Another day of protest against the Ontario government is over.
20 to 40-thousand people ... the crowd size depends on who you
believe, police or organizers ... gathered under sunny skies in
Kitchener over the noon hour to rally against spending cuts by
Mike Harris' government. 
<P>
Unionized workers shut down at least 15 major factories, and disrupted
mail service and garbage pickup in the Kitchener, Waterloo and
Cambridge area. Police officers from several local towns stood
by, but the demonstration was peaceful. 
<HR>

<H3>Tsubouchi-Women </H3>

<P>
While the Tories were being jeered in Kitchener- Waterloo; a group
of women were politely applauding if not singing their praise
in Hamilton- Wentworth. Scot Urquhart explains: 
<P>
<I>Hard on the heels of a five week public sector strike ... on
a day when the Harris government was being vilified in KW one
of its most widely criticized ministers, got to come to Hamilton;
towing a wagon-load full of cash. </I>
<P>
<I>Only two of the four local Tories were on hand to see Tsubouchi
drop nearly five million dollars into the region ...that's close
to half of the eleven million dollar total to be spent on capital
construction costs for 9 women's shelters, across the province.
But will there be more provincial money available to run those
new buildings? </I>
<P>
<I>Still ... the operators of both Inasmuch House, and Interval
House are grateful. Their shelters are bursting at the seams;
and literally falling apart. The money is truly appreciated. But
do they really believe that the Tories are serious about supporting
women? </I>
<P>
<I>The irony in all of this: even as Tsubouchi was making his
announcement; a 30 year old Hamilton woman was fighting for her
life ... after being stabbed repeatedly in her Roxborough Avenue
home. Police arrested a suspect: the woman's former common-law
husband. He was charged with attempted murder, and breach of probation:
that being a court order, to stay away from his former spouse.
</I>
<P>
<I>Tsubouchi says, the government found eleven million dollars
to build new women's shelters through administrative efficiencies,
and wiser spending practices. Women across Ontario are hoping
that he can find a lot more .... before it's too late. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Slain Woman Fund </H3>

<P>
The co-workers of a Winona woman murdered last year by her estranged
husband have established a memorial scholarship in her name. 
<P>
26-year old Alayne Bryk a GO Transit enforcement officer, was
shot in a murder-suicide at her home last August by her husband,
Michael Auer. 
<P>
Bryk's co-workers have established the Alayne Bryk memorial scholarship
to support second-year law and security students at Hamilton's
Mohawk College. Bryk completed the college's law and security
program in 1990 after attending Nelson High School in Burlington.

<HR>

<H3>Education Follow </H3>

<P>
It's official. Public school supporters in Hamilton will face
an education tax hike this year. It's just over 3-percent. But
as Anthony Pooley reports tonight... that assumes five million
dollars in concessions from unions. 
<P>
<I>After putting low seniority teachers through hell with layoff
notices en route to what taxpayers believed was to be a hold the
tax line budget, Hamilton's Public School Board trustees veered
sharply to the left last night, handing down a budget that calls
for a 3.16- percent hike in education taxes ... twice the rate
of inflation. </I>
<P>
<I>The board will spend 254 million dollars of your money this
year. A typical realty tax hike is about 31 dollars. All of this
assumes that five million dollars can be saved with co-operation
from teachers unions ... but a rough ride is still expected. </I>
<P>
<I>Despite provincial reductions in transfer payments to school
boards, Education Minister John Snobelen has washed his hands
of responsibility for layoffs and local tax hikes, saying those
decisions rest with local trustees. But without a doubt ... certain
unpleasant things roll down hill.</I>
<HR>

<H3>School Search </H3>

<P>
Police in Hamilton are on the look out for a suspicious male who
has been entering city schools attempting to steal purses or money
from staff members. 
<P>
Yesterday, police were called to three schools in less than a
hour after a man walked in, but fled when confronted. He is described
at white, 40 to 50 years old, about 6 feet tall with a medium
build and a pock marked face. He has grey curly hair and was seen
wearing blue jeans, cowboy boots, a baseball cap and ski jacket.
Anyone with information should contact Hamilton Regional Police.

<HR>

<H3>Teacher Sex Assault </H3>

<P>
A long-time catholic school teacher stands charged with sexually
assaulting one of his students. Other charges may be pending as
police interview other alleged victims -- both boys and girls.

<P>
The 55-year-old lives in Pelham, but teaches at a small, Niagara
Falls elementary school. He's to appear in court May 2nd on one
count of sexual assault and one of sexual interference. Investigators
refuse to identify the specific school involved. 
<HR>

<H3>Strip Club Charges </H3>

<P>
A raid on a strip club in Niagara Falls has netted police 17 arrests,
including the owner of the club. 
<P>
Police conducted a month-long investigation into lap dancing and
other activities at the club. The owner of the Sundowner Inn,
47-year-old Chris Rudan, is among four employees charged with
keeping a common bawdy house. 
<P>
Four customers were charged as found-ins, and nine dancers face
charges of being inmates of a common bawdy house. Niagara Regional
Police say further charges are pending. 
<HR>

<H3>Eisenberger - Prostitution</H3>

<P>
Hamilton alderman Fred Eisenberger thinks he may have a solution
to the city's prostitution problem... create a red light district.

<P>
Eisenberger says &quot;Hamilton needs to come to terms with the
fact that prostitution is not going away&quot; to that end he
says creating a red light zone away from residential areas may
be a solution. The suggestion is being received positively by
fellow alderman Dave Wilson and Lansdale Neighborhood Watch vice
chair Stella Woock. 
<HR>

<H3>MOT Closure </H3>

<P>
If you're about to book your appointment for a driving test take
note... the drivers exam centre located at the Mountain Plaza
Mall in Hamilton is one of 12 across the province slated for closure.
Exam centres are also being closed in Cambridge, Guelph Kitchener
and Brantford. 
<P>
Employees at the Hamilton Centre will be relocated to the city's
only remaining driver exam location on Kenora Avenue in east Hamilton.
No word on the official date for the Upper James closure.
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Some expected economic data on US inflation and American retail
sales helped to stabilize financial markets in the US and Canada.

<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened while interest rates eased. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

