<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, April 18, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Snobelen - Cuts 
<LI>Skills Development 
<LI>Sesqui Murals 
<LI>1005 Newser 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Boutcher Sentence 
<LI>Pole Damage 
<LI>Break In 
<LI>Nabbed Off Duty 
<LI>CHAT Anniversary 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Snobelen - Cuts </H3>

<P>
If you live in Hamilton, what happens over the next few hours
could affect your children and your tax bill. 
<P>
In one-half hour's time, trustees with the Hamilton Board of Education
will meet to finalize the budget, a budget that has been fraught
with controversial cutting in efforts to meet dramatically reduced
provincial funding. 
<P>
Yesterday, the Separate School Board announced it would not have
to resort to layoffs. Will the public board will able to match
those efforts and what about junior kindergarten? Education Minister
John Snobelen in Hamilton this afternoon said he regrets that
cutbacks could result in layoffs but its up to the local boards
to try to protect the futures of young teachers. 
<HR>

<H3>Skills Development </H3>

<P>
Well if there won't be many teaching jobs in the future, where
will young people find work? 
<P>
One area is trades and skills. This year's skills competition
is underway at Copps Coliseum in Hamilton. It's comprised of a
series of contests where young people showcase the skills that
just may guarantee them employment in this shrinking economy.

<P>
<I>They're building they're future. Hundreds of students entered
in the annual skills competition. Brick layers, carpenters, future
engineers. These contestants are combing, shaving trimming their
way to a career as a hair stylist. </I>
<P>
<I>Everything has to be just right. These culinary high school
students are creating masterpieces on plates. Looks too good to
eat but the discriminating palates of the judges are difficult
to satisfy. </I>
<P>
<I>Even if these contestants don't win this competition, they
can take heart in the fact that their skills will almost guarantee
them a future.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Sesqui Murals </H3>

<P>
A group of 20 young people are putting their skills to the test,
giving downtown Hamilton a bit of a facelift at the same time.

<P>
They're painting murals, depicting the history of Hamilton in
30 year segments, on the abandoned Lister Block Building. Annette
Hamm has the details. 
<P>
<I>150 years of Hamilton's history will soon cover the graffiti
on the Lister Block. And with each brush stroke, the 20 young
people working on the Sesqui Silhouette Project, are doing more
than painting murals. </I>
<P>
<I>The painters, not all of them artists, are on six month contracts,
funded by Youth Service Canada and the Hamilton and Region Arts
Council. Some are learning marketing skills. </I>
<P>
<I>Once this mural is complete, they'll have to push their work
to owners of other downtown Hamilton buildings, in hopes of putting
up four large outdoor murals. </I>
<P>
<I>They're also learning people skills, explaining to passers-by
what they're doing. this group hopes to unveil their larger murals
by August.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>1005 Newser </H3>

<P>
Steelworkers at Stelco's Hilton Works are going back to the ballot
box next week. Two weeks ago, they turned down the first contract
by only 9 votes. The membership itself is split between aging
workers who want pension improvements, and younger workers who
want better wages. 
<P>
The president of local 1005 thinks this second attempt will please
everyone. Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>In a Hamilton hotel room, Local 1005 president John Martin
and his union executive called a news conference to give a summary,
but not the exact details of their latest contract with Stelco's
Hilton Works. </I>
<P>
<I>The second attempt at getting an early contract is exactly
the same as the one members narrowly rejected a few days ago,
but it has improvements. The contract is for six years, a length
Martin feels may break an infamous tradition with his union. </I>
<P>
<I>Since its inception in 1946, Local 1005 has gone on strike
every third contract. That unlucky number three would come up
in 1999, but if this deal is ratified, Martin hopes it would take
them past that without a dispute.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Bad economic news for St. Catharines. The Motts Beverage Company
is closing down its plant throwing 175 people out of work. Company
officials say the termination of a licensing agreement with US.
giant Ocean Spray is to blame. 
<HR>

<H3>Boutcher Sentence </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton man has been sentenced to five years in penitentiary
after pleading guilty to impaired driving. 
<P>
35-year-old Daniel Boutcher was involved in a two-car crash which
took the lives of two children. Sonia Salazar told the court that
losing a 9-year-old son and 12-year-old daughter has stolen her
life. 
<P>
Boutcher has two prior impaired driving convictions and 16 other
criminal convictions. Along with the five year sentence, he lost
his licence for ten years. 
<HR>

<H3>Pole Damage</H3>

<P>
A ten minute vandalism spree in downtown Hamilton last night caused
several thousand dollars in damage, and landed one man in custody.

<P>
It started when a man destroyed an office desk and a phone, and
kicked a four inch hole in the wall at a James Street North address.
He then ran outside, grabbed a seven foot steel pole from a parking
lot and tried to ram it through a phone booth, where two people
were making a call. They were lucky enough to get out of the way
as the suspect went on to destroy another phone booth. 
<P>
Before the spree ended, several double pane windows and a glass
door at a CIBC branch were smashed. 
<P>
28 year old Odion Ihimogie of no fixed address faces several mischief
charges, including two counts of mischief endangering life. 
<HR>

<H3>Break In </H3>

<P>
Another warning from police to keep your doors and windows locked
up, even when you're home at night. This after yet another overnight
break-in on Hamilton's west mountain. 
<P>
A woman woke up at 4 this morning to find someone with a flashlight
in her living room. The intruder escaped, but some property was
recovered outside the house. Police say the suspect got in by
removing a screen on a kitchen window. 
<HR>

<H3>Nabbed Off Duty </H3>

<P>
An alert neighbour and an off duty cop spelled trouble for a group
of young car thieves on Hamilton mountain. 
<P>
A woman called her neighbour, detective Warren Korol, when she
saw five teens casing out a car on her street. Korol ran a check
of the vehicle's license plates and discovered it had been reported
stolen. He caught up with the kids as they were parking the car
just around the corner. 
<P>
Four passengers took off after he identified himself, but Korol
was able to chase the driver on foot and hold him until on duty
officers arrived. 
<P>
A 15 year old boy has been charged with possession over 5-thousand
dollars and possession of a prohibited weapon. Police found a
can of pepper spray while making their arrest. 
<HR>

<H3>CHAT Anniversary </H3>

<P>
Police, fire and the medical community got together this afternoon
to celebrate three years of the CHAT program. 
<P>
CHAT stands for Community and Hospital Against Trauma. The educational
program focuses on young people showing them first hand the dangers
of risk-taking behaviour. 
<P>
Students are given tours of hospital ER's, ICU and rehab areas
with the hope that the message will sink in. Drama students from
Westdale Secondary School unveiled a new play about safety that
will tour schools all over the Hamilton area. 

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

