<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, April 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Crooked Cops 
<LI>Cop Charged 
<LI>Stelco - 1005 Deal 
<LI>JK Hamilton 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Surgery Delays 
<LI>Ozone Warning 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Crooked Cops</H3>

<P>
Two Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police officers have been charged
with profiting from people's misfortune. 
<P>
They stand accused tonight of using confidential information to
send business to a Hamilton auto repair shop. Both officers have
been suspended with pay. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>The arrests follow an intensive six-month investigation by
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police, an investigation sparked
by complaints over the last few years. </I>
<P>
<I>45-year-old Ted Chrysler of Hamilton, a nineteen year veteran
with the Hamilton- Wentworth police, is charged with two counts
of criminal breach of trust. 25-year-old Dino Morandin of Beamsville
is charged with criminal breach of trust and receiving a secret
commission. He is also charged with theft in connection with a
missing police radio, and fraud in connection with an insurance
claim. </I>
<P>
<I>Morandin was honored as chosen officer of the year for 1994.
The owner of Parkdale auto collision, 45-year-old Antonio Costa
Cunha of Hamilton, has also been charged with giving a secret
commission. </I>
<P>
<I>Police say further arrests or charges are possible.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Cop Charged </H3>

<P>
And a patrol officer with the Hamilton- Wentworth force appeared
in court today on an assault charge. 
<P>
Officer Glen Marshall, a 20-year-veteran, was arrested following
a domestic dispute in Stoney Creek last night. The incident involves
allegations that a common-law wife had been shoved and slapped
by her common-law husband, during an argument. 
<HR>

<H3>Stelco - 1005 Deal </H3>

<P>
For the second time in as many months, a tentative agreement has
been reached between Stelco and steelworkers local 1005. The first
one was turned down by members by a mere 9 votes. Anthony Pooley
reports. 
<P>
<I>Steelworkers 1005 executive members will be briefed on the
proposed new deal tomorrow morning. They'll talk to reporters
tomorrow afternoon... although standard practice is not to reveal
the details until union members have been briefed. That will happen
at the convention centre starting with stewards on Sunday at six...
the membership meeting will take place at eight. For those who
can't make that meeting, there'll be another one Monday morning
at ten. </I>
<P>
<I>Two weeks ago, union members turned thumbs down on a six year
deal, as union members split along age lines. A big part of that
proposed deal was a hike of 240 dollars a month in pension benefits...
which appealed to the half of the membership that will soon be
able to retire. But those who won't be able to do that any time
soon killed the proposed pact. </I>
<P>
<I>As for Stelco ... they're looking for stability of production...
voting on the deal will begin at the Hilton Works plant gates
with the first shift next Wednesday morning.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>JK Hamilton </H3>

<P>
it appears the Hamilton board of education wants to hang on to
junior kindergarten... even though it will cost 800 thousand dollars.
last night in committee, trustees voted 10-3 to save the program.
some trustees say they want to revisit the issue again Thursday
night though. the trustees managed to slash another million dollars,
mainly in transportation cuts for special education students but
they still have another 5.6. million to trim. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
The National Transportation Agency has grounded Greyhound Air&#133;
at least for the time being. 
<P>
But the head of Tradeport International, the group that runs Hamilton's
Airport says don't worry. Tony Battaglia says air service licensing
is a complicated issue and that he still expects Greyhound Air
to start flying out of Hamilton as of May 22nd. 
<P>
All flights will be to Winnipeg with connections to other western
Canadian destinations. Return fares to Vancouver will start at
269 dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Surgery Delays</H3>

<P>
There's been a lot of talk about healthcare reform in Hamilton
Wentworth over the last few months, but one element that has taken
a back seat to all the political aspects of the story are the
patients, and as Jamie West reports, one Hamilton man is sending
out a message to all taxpayers...wake up and speak up 
<P>
<I>George Savelli is talking about his brother Reno. The 70 year
old man just underwent cancer surgery at Hamilton General Hospital,
but it came in the wee hours of the morning after an on again
off again relationship with the healthcare system. </I>
<P>
<I>Reno Savelli was prepped and ready for surgery but at the last
minute it was canceled.. ,.because there was no intensive care
bed available. So he was sent home. </I>
<P>
<I>George cast's no blame but instead credits the people who are
on the front-line of a healthcare system in critical condition.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Ozone Warning </H3>

<P>
The sun came out today just in time for this warning from Environment
Canada. 
<P>
The protective ozone layer over Canada is expected to be below
normal this summer. The ozone layer filters out harmful ultraviolet
radiation. 
<P>
Even at normal ozone levels, UV rays are strong enough in the
summer to cause health problems such as skin cancer, eye damage
and a weakening of the immune system. 
<P>

