<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, April 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Diabetic Driver 
<LI>Homolka 
<LI>Charlton Fire 
<LI>Foolish Thieves 
<LI>Downtown Taxes 
<LI>School Funding 
<LI>Pension Hearings 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Grand River Rising 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Diabetic Driver </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton woman says she'll do all she can to prevent another
tragedy like the one that killed her daughter and grandson. 
<P>
Four people were killed in a fiery car crash near Brantford are
outraged a diabetic man who caused the crash is still driving.
44-year-old Gordon Wood was charged with four counts of dangerous
driving causing death in connection with the 1994 crash that killed
two adults and two children. 
<P>
Yesterday, Mr. Wood walked out of court a free man after the crown
withdrew the charges. Wood's defence was based on a condition
called &quot;hypoglycemic unawareness&quot; a condition that causes
a diabetic to lapse into a state where they are not aware of their
actions. 
<HR>

<H3>Homolka </H3>

<P>
A committee of people opposed to Karla Homolka's plea-bargain
showed up on Parliament Hill today to demand a federal inquiry.

<P>
The group presented a lengthy petition to back up its call for
the deal to be overturned. Group members also showed support for
a bill tabled by a liberal senator in hopes of overturning the
plea-bargain. 
<P>
The bill, introduced by Anne Cools in the upper chamber in February,
would also quash future plea-bargains if incriminating evidence
is found after the deals are made. 
<P>
Homolka received 12 years in prison in exchange for testimony
against her ex-husband, Paul Bernardo, in the sex killings of
Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy. 
<HR>

<H3>Charlton Fire </H3>

<P>
The Fire Marshall was on the scene today of an early morning fire
that caused fifty-thousand dollars damage to a Hamilton apartment
building, and left two tenants suffering from smoke inhalation.

<P>
The fire started in a basement storage room, and sent heavy smoke
through the thirteen-unit building on Charlton Street East. Everyone
who lives there has found temporary accommodation elsewhere. 
<P>
Meanwhile, a furnace room fire caused over 100-thousand dollars
damage to an east Hamilton home yesterday afternoon. two adults
escaped the Strawberry Drive residence safely, but their pet cat
suffered smoke inhalation. 
<HR>

<H3>Foolish Thieves </H3>

<P>
They had the tools, but not necessarily the brains for the job
at hand. Two teenagers used a pair of bolt-cutters to pry open
the back door of a Hamilton surplus store yesterday. Trouble is,
it was one o'clock in the afternoon, and as they waltzed through
the door they encountered a warehouse full of workers. 
<P>
Two employees of Quality Surplus on Cavell Street chased the pair
for ten blocks before cornering one of them in an alleyway. Two
seventeen- year-olds from Hamilton are charged with break-and-enter
with intent. One of them is also charged with possession of a
dangerous weapon, and breach of recognizance. 
<HR>

<H3>Downtown Taxes </H3>

<P>
Downtown Hamilton businesses could still be in for a tax break.
Today, the city's finance committee asked staff to prepare a report
showing the impact of giving downtown businesses anywhere from
a ten to fifty per cent cut in their business and realty taxes.

<P>
As Deborah Walker reports, those who support tax relief believe
it's the only way to stop the city centre from dying. 
<P>
<I>Hamilton Alderman Vince Agro says it's time for city politicians
to stop talking, and actually do something to halt the decline
of the downtown. </I>
<P>
<I>But some aldermen are skeptical about claims downtown taxes
are too high. They want to see comparative figures to prove it.
Others fear a blanket tax break will simply encourage speculators
to sit on vacant properties. </I>
<P>
<I>A staff report comparing taxes, and outlining the implications
various tax breaks, should be ready in three weeks.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>School Funding </H3>

<P>
There will be no layoffs of teachers or support staff in schools
run by Hamilton's Separate School Board this year. This from Director
of Education Jim Daly today, as he and public school board counterpart
Don Goodridge faced business people, students and others in a
panel discussion on education funding. Channel 11's Anthony Pooley
was there. 
<P>
<I>Some good news today for Separate School educators and education
in Hamilton- Wentworth from director Jim Daly ... no lay-offs.
</I>
<P>
<I>But despite the good news, some separate high school students
remain at once worried and concerned. </I>
<P>
<I>At the same time... the view through the window into public
education funding through the eyes of director Don Goodridge is
significantly less appealing. Lay-offs galore, as trustees and
administrators crunch numbers in an attempt not to raise local
taxes. </I>
<P>
<I>Indeed, millions of dollars have been cut from public school
spending already... and this episode in Philip Environmental's
&quot;Let's Talk Education&quot; speakers series was well received.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Pension Hearings </H3>

<P>
The cross country hearings on the future of the Canada Pension
Plan stopped in Hamilton today. 
<P>
The hearing panel is getting input from ordinary citizens on how
to keep the pension plan operating. There are dire warnings that
the fund could run dry by the next century. To avoid that the
government is talking about raising contributions and lowering
benefits. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
They were all smiles in the Chrysler boardroom today. The number
three automaker first quarter earnings are seventy percent higher
than a year ago. 
<P>
Chrysler earned just over a billion dollars from January through
March... a first quarter record for the company. 
<HR>

<H3>Grand River Rising </H3>

<P>
The waters of the grand river were running fast and furious today.

<P>
Levels rose 10 to 12 millimeters in the upper part of the grand
river watershed overnight after all this rain we've been having.
The flowrate has dropped somewhat but the conservation authority
warns the water will remain dangerous for the next several days.

<P>

