<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, April 15, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Niagara Casino 
<LI>Task Force - Region 
<LI>Student Employment 
<LI>B.B. Bargoons 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Body Found 
<LI>Accident Victim 
<LI>Lab Busted 
<LI>Wedding Mayhem 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Niagara Casino</H3>

<P>
Maple Leaf Village has hit the jackpot. The one time amusement
complex has been chosen as the site for the province's newest
casino in Niagara falls. 
<P>
The tourism minister made the announcement this morning at a news
conference in the honeymoon capitol. Lauran Sabourin was there.

<P>
<I>Dino Di Cienzo and his business associates are up on cloud
nine. The Di Cienzo group beat out two other strong contenders.
</I>
<P>
<I>The Casino Corporation felt that Maple Leaf Village had superior
facilities. It was just on the other side of the Rainbow Bridge.
Curious tourists are enticed by the facade. </I>
<P>
<I>Inside the building is empty. Stores abandoned. Tourists attractions
shut down. But replace the ski ball machines with gaming tables
and this place will come alive. </I>
<P>
<I>The government is counting on 80 percent of the revenue taken
in at the tables to be in U.S. dollars. That works out to about
650 million a year. And Maple Leaf Village was seen as the best
site to exploit that opportunity. </I>
<P>
<I>The casino project is expected to create three thousand jobs.
Six thousand jobs for Niagara region. And nine thousand jobs for
the province as a whole. </I>
<P>
<I>Niagara Falls attracts about 20 million tourists a year. With
the casino as another major attraction its hoped those tourists
will stay longer, spend more money and keep coming back.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Task Force - Region</H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth regional councilors are betting on a plan
to keep all Hamilton hospitals open, while still achieving the
savings expected by the provincial government. 
<P>
Today's the deadline for responding to the Health Action Task
Force report that recommends closing St. Joseph's Hospital, and
transferring its operations to Henderson Hospital. Instead, members
of the region's health and social services committee unanimously
back a plan proposed by the people who run the hospitals themselves.
Deborah walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Last Friday, hospital administrators unveiled a plan to keep
all four acute care hospitals in Hamilton open. However, Henderson
Hospital would lose half its beds, and its emergency department
would be down-graded to an urgent care unit. Regional councilors
representing Hamilton mountain still agreed to support the plan,
but they did so reluctantly. </I>
<P>
<I>The hospital CEO's estimate their proposal would save 92-million
dollars, and they want that money to stay in Hamilton to expand
non-hospital health services like nursing homes and chronic care
facilities. Regional councilors agree. </I>
<P>
<I>It's now up to the Hamilton- Wentworth District Health Council
to decide if it prefers the CEO's plan, or the one suggested by
the task force. The health council will forward its final recommendations
to the province by the end of May. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Student Employment </H3>

<P>
Student groups held a news conference today to say it's unacceptable
for people to have to take out loans to feed their children. They're
protesting a government plan to cut post-secondary students with
children off welfare. Annette Hamm will have more on the story
in our next half-hour. 
<P>
This comes as many students are looking for summer jobs. The Canada
Employment Centre for Students opened its doors in Hamilton's
Jackson Square this morning. 
<P>
The office will be open Monday to Friday, 8:30 to 4:30 daily.
Employers are encouraged to place job postings as soon as possible.
Students are welcome to use the service. 
<HR>

<H3>B.B. Bargoons </H3>

<P>
The home decorating chain B.B. Bargoons is closing its doors in
Burlington, St. Catharines and a number of communities in southern
Ontario, leaving more than 50 employees without jobs. 
<P>
The company slipped into receivership last week. The one-time
Canadian retailing phenomenon says the already slimmed-down 10-store
operation is cutting back to two outlets in the hopes of waiting
out its founder calls a terrible economic climate; as consumers
save their money instead of spending it at retail outlets. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Flamborough based Wescam Incorporated continues to grow. Today
they announced they had purchased TV-2 Limited of Wellingborough,
England. No purchase price was announced. Their primary activity
is broadcasting sporting events. Wescam is the world leader in
the design and manufacture of aerial cameras and transmission
systems. 
<HR>

<H3>Body Found </H3>

<P>
Niagara Region Police are not ruling out foul play following the
discovery of a body in a ditch in Welland. 
<P>
The grisly discovery was made by a group of children early yesterday.
The dead man has been identified as 41-year-old John Gibson. 
<HR>

<H3>Accident Victim </H3>

<P>
A Niagara Falls man has died of injuries suffered in a car crash
earlier this month. 55-year-old John Vanderlee's car crossed into
on-coming traffic on Morrison Street during bad weather and struck
a second vehicle. That driver was not hurt. No charges will be
laid. 
<HR>

<H3>Lab Busted </H3>

<P>
Halton police have busted another hydroponic marijuana lab. This
one on Abbeywood Drive, Oakville. 
<P>
They seized more than 10-thousand dollars in cash, 15 pounds of
marijuana and about 40 plants together worth about 160 thousand
dollars. 
<P>
Two Oakville men are charged: 43-year-old Keith John Nisbet and
Lutchi San Pedro, 36.
<HR>

<H3>Wedding Mayhem </H3>

<P>
Uninvited guests did more than just crash a Hamilton wedding ceremony
yesterday. One of them punched the groom in the mouth. 
<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police say five people showed up
at the morning ceremony at the Sikh Temple on Covington Street.
One of them knocked off the groom's head-dress, then punched him.

<P>
The groom's former brother-in-law, 37-year-old Manjit Sandhu of
Brampton, is charged with assault, and disturbing a religious
ceremony. Four others from Brampton and Mississauga are charged
with disturbing a religious ceremony. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

