<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, April 12, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Alternative Plan 
<LI>House Lottery 
<LI>Drugs Stolen 
<LI>Brock Appeal 
<LI>1005 - Stelco 
<LI>Hamilton Education Cuts
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Alternative Plan</H3>

<P>
There was a &quot;love-in&quot; at a downtown Hamilton hotel this
afternoon. Nearly all of Hamilton Wentworth's big players in healthcare
gathered before the media to present the Health Action Task Force
with their response to the report &quot;Our Health Our Future&quot;
that was released over a month ago. 
<P>
The controversial report contains recommendations that includes
the closure of St. Joseph's Hospital and it's internal re-location
to the site now occupied by Henderson General. 
<P>
As Jamie west reports...CEO's of all the major hospitals joined
forces coming up with what they call a &quot;made in Hamilton
solution&quot;... 
<P>
<I>Just an hour before the CEO's released their response, a group
from St. Joseph's Hospital arrived on the door step of the Health
Action Task Force with thousands of names on a petition to save
St. Joe's. </I>
<P>
<I>Meanwhile, just a block away at the Hamilton Sheraton, CEO's
and board members of all Hamilton hospitals issued their response
to the task force report.... the highlights include.... leaving
St. Joseph's and the Henderson intact ... the Henderson would
reduce it's beds from 323 to 160. It would focus as a center of
excellence in cancer treatment, and major joint reconstruction
and become an urgent care centre. </I>
<P>
<I>Those with emergency's would be treated and stabilized but
not admitted, they would instead be transferred to other hospitals
or sent home. Most of Henderson's obstetrics would move to McMaster
and it's respiratory and urology moved to St. Joe's. The Hamilton
General would increase it's capacity to deal with psychiatric
patients. </I>
<P>
<I>The CEO's group has named itself the Academic Health Care Network,
and says their response meets the goal of 18 percent provincial
funding cuts while maintaining a strong healthcare system. But
the question is how much impact will the response have on the
task force. </I>
<P>
<I>The deadline for public feedback on the task force report is
Monday. The district health council will consider both reports
and other public submissions until May 27th, at which time final
recommendations will be made to the minister of health.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>House Lottery </H3>

<P>
Hamilton's St. Joseph's Hospital hopes you'll take a chance on
supporting healthcare in our community. 
<P>
The hospital's foundation today unveiled its winners choice lottery.
Unlike other fund raising lotteries, this one give winners their
choice of the top prize. Included in the choice: a 300 thousand
dollar plus Alterra home in Ancaster. But that's not all. Foundation
officials hope to sell 85-thousand tickets. They go on sale Monday.

<HR>

<H3>Drugs Stolen </H3>

<P>
Niagara police have issued a warning about potentially lethal
drugs and syringes stolen during a break and enter at a Welland
veterinary clinic. 
<P>
Most of the missing drugs are harmful if taken and potentially
fatal. Anyone with information is asked to call Niagara police
or Crime Stoppers. 
<HR>

<H3>Brock Appeal </H3>

<P>
Brock University is seeking leave to appeal a court ruling in
a decade-old harassment complaint. 
<P>
Brock has filed notice with the Ontario Court of Appeal that it
intends to appeal a lower court's rejection of its claim that
it couldn't receive a fair hearing at the Ontario Human Rights
Commission. 
<P>
Mary Warner, a former history department secretary, filed a complaint
in February 1986 stating she was sexually harassed by two professors.
The complaint also now includes allegations she was fired six
months later in retaliation for testifying in June 1985 about
students' complaints against one of the professors. A series of
legal maneuvers has delayed resumption of a hearing that started
in may 1993. 
<P>
It's not known when the appeal court might consider the university's
request. 
<HR>

<H3>1005 - Stelco </H3>

<P>
Stelco Steel and local 1005 are headed back to the bargaining
table in Toronto. 
<P>
The two sides are working with a provincial mediator in an attempt
to reach a new agreement. The union also announced today that
250 workers are being recalled for summer relief. 
<P>
Local 1005 president John Martin said the main bargaining issues
are contract length and profit sharing. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Education Cuts </H3>

<P>
The Hamilton Board of Ed is ready to pick the pockets of its employees
... to keep Hamilton taxpayers from digging further into theirs.

<P>
The board is looking for five million dollars in contract concessions
to help it climb out of a multi-million dollar budget hole. Scot
Urquhart has more: 
<P>
<I>The reaction from teachers unions, is no surprise. When the
Hamilton Board of Ed decided last night to negotiate five million
dollars in budget cuts from the contracts of eleven different
unions, there was bound to be resistance .... but board members
are beginning to feel they have nowhere else to go.</I>
<P>
<I>With a total budget of 264 million ... the board will spend
roughly 30 million to operate the schools .... more than 18 million
on taxes and other debts .... roughly 7 and a half million, for
central administration .... and more than five million dollars,
on transportation. </I>
<P>
<I>But the lion's share of all the cost ... comes from the salaries
paid to more than 38-hundred employees. The problem is, taxpayers
are demanding more for less, and becoming far less willing to
pay. Even if the board gets it's five million dollars from the
unions; they will still have to find another six and a half million
in other areas ... to hold the line on taxes, in 1996. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Business First</H3>

<P>
Some expected economic data on US inflation and American retail
sales helped to stabilize financial markets in the US and Canada.

<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened while interest rates eased. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

