<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, April 11, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Cuts - Hamilton 
<LI>Downtown Taxes 
<LI>Jo Brant Layoffs 
<LI>Halton Ed. Cuts 
<LI>Serial Rapist? 
<LI>Most Wanted 
<LI>Const. Accident 
<LI>Pelham Driver 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Cuts - Hamilton </H3>

<P>
Six billion dollars in provincial spending cuts ...it's a figure
that has been tossed around for months... but it took until today
for the government to get specific about how it will affect the
operation of individual towns, cities and regions. And as Anthony
Pooley reports tonight... cuts to social services spending are
twice what the chairman of Hamilton Wentworth's Social Services
Committee thought they would be. 
<P>
<I>The Harris government has now answered the question many Ontarians
have been asking for months... where will the 6 billion dollars
in spending cuts come from? </I>
<P>
<I>Ten thousand public service jobs will be slashed; 17,000 single
parents and married couples who are full-time college or university
students will get student loans instead of welfare; tenants in
some public housing units will have rents increased to market
levels; 60 of 251 provincial parks will be closed; programs to
prevent violence against women will be cut by $2.9 million and
the Ontario Advisory Council on Women's Issues will be disbanded.
</I>
<P>
<I>The 900 million dollars in cuts to social services spending
is about twice the amount anticipated, says Hamilton- Wentworth's
Social Services Chairman. Ted McMeekin says that means cuts to
other programs in addition to welfare payments. He wants some
consultation. </I>
<P>
<I>Today's announcement comes about a month before Finance Minister
Ernie Eves hands down his first budget.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Downtown Taxes </H3>

<P>
Part of the Harris government's logic for slashing spending is
the promise to offer Ontarians a tax break. 
<P>
In Hamilton the subject of tax relief is very topical in the downtown
core. But this time its businesses looking for property tax relief.
Kathy Renwald reports on the plan to rejuvenate the downtown core.

<P>
<I>Inside a downtown Hamilton hotel the Grey Cup committee was
promising a splashy festival next November. But outside they face
a challenge to fizz up an ailing city core. </I>
<P>
<I>Co chair Marnie Paikin says all of Canada will be watching
Hamilton during Grey Cup week. So they will borrow some strategies
from last years host Regina. </I>
<P>
<I>The struggling businesses could be helped by tax relief. Lower
taxes in the downtown core and raise them elsewhere. But city
council sent the tax scheme packing ..sending it back to committee
for more study. </I>
<P>
<I>Sid Leon's heard it all before..he's operated a clothing store
on this James Street corner for 33 years. </I>
<P>
<I>But the Deputy Mayor of Stoney Creek says the suburbs would
be willing to pay for the revitalization of the downtown core
if the concept is marketed right. Grant Shaw firmly believes the
downtown is the hub of the region. </I>
<P>
<I>Back at the Grey Cup confab .. the football championship is
being touted as the start of the new Hamilton.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Jo Brant Layoffs </H3>

<P>
35 union employees of Joseph Brant Hospital in Burlington received
layoff notices today. Layoffs are effective October 11th for 27
registered practical nurses and eight other members of the Canadian
union of public employees. 
<P>
Another 100 CUPE employees who have low seniority also received
notices of potential layoff because they could be bumped by more
senior employees. It's expected that up to 50 nurses will be given
notice in May for July layoffs. 
<HR>

<H3>Halton Ed. Cuts </H3>

<P>
After a seven-hour marathon debate last night, Halton School trustees
were back at it again this afternoon, trying to nail down the
board's 96 operating budget. 
<P>
Members of the finance committee managed to cover half of the
sixty amendments last night aimed at trimming 16 million dollars
from the budget. Some of the proposals being considered include
staff lay-offs, reduced bussing and limiting equipment purchases.

<P>
The full board will likely vote on the 1996 operating budget early
next week. 
<HR>

<H3>Serial Rapist? </H3>

<P>
Police in Halton and Niagara are now downplaying media reports
that an attempted abduction and sexual assault of an 11 year old
girl in Niagara falls may have been committed by the man wanted
in a series of vicious assaults across southern Ontario. 
<P>
The girl was walking home from Centre Variety in the Falls when
she was pushed into a car by a man in his 20's. Police say the
child was sexually assaulted but the man let her go when she started
to scream. 
<P>
The description the girl gave police of her attacker is similar
to the description of a rapist being hunted by a Halton Police
task force. But while similarities exist police don't believe
it's the same man. 
<HR>

<H3>Most Wanted </H3>

<P>
Police in Hamilton have issued warrants for the arrest of a suspect
in a brutal assault and robbery that involved death threats. 
<P>
Jay Thomas Lewis is white, 30 years old, 6 foot-three and 190
pounds. He has short brown hair, blue eyes, a mustache and a tattoo
of a skull on his right shoulder. 
<P>
The victim of the assault at a Rebecca Street address last month
is still in hospital recovering from serious injuries. Police
believe Jay Thomas Lewis is still in the Hamilton area and urge
anyone with information to call Crime Stoppers. 
<HR>

<H3>Const. Accident </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton man is in hospital tonight after a freak industrial
accident. 
<P>
Michael Turco was working in a trench at the intersection of Victoria
and Burlington Streets, when he was struck in the back with a
concrete barricade. A mobile crane at street level was turning
when it accidentally knocked the chunk of concrete into the hole.

<P>
Mr. Turco was taken to hospital in good condition. The Ministry
of Labour is investigating. 
<HR>

<H3>Pelham Driver </H3>

<P>
Police have arrested and charged a man who cut a five kilometre
swath of destruction in Pelham early this morning. 
<P>
Police say the driver of a car drove on sidewalks and in ditches
while he mowed down garbage containers, mail boxes and small trees.
Garbage was strewn across lawns and roadways. 
<P>
The license plate of the offending vehicle was found at the scene.
Damage was pegged at five thousand dollars. Arrested and charged
with criminal negligence and mischief is 23 year old Christopher
Cram of Centennial Drive, Welland. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First</H3>

<P>
For the second day in a row there was more strong evidence that
Canadians are buying homes again. The sale of existing homes across
the country increased more than 40 per cent in march. 
<P>
Canadian stock prices and the dollar strengthened today. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

