<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, April 10, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Halton Board Budget 
<LI>Ham. Board Meet
<LI>Civics-Layoffs 
<LI>CAS Adoptions 
<LI>Miss. City Hall 
<LI>Robberies 
<LI>Drugs 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Halton Board Budget</H3>

<P>
We begin with education tonight and cuts, lots more of them to
try to offset provincial funding cutbacks. 
<P>
Painful budget sessions are taking place within school boards
everywhere. The alternative would be a tax increase that nobody
seems to want. 
<P>
In Halton, its 16 million dollars in cuts from a 285 million dollar
budget just to hold the line. The finance committee has been meeting
this afternoon. 
<HR>

<H3>Ham. Board Meet </H3>

<P>
In Hamilton last night, a packed session at the Board of Education
offices as the finance committee grappled with a sixteen million
dollar budget cut. 
<P>
A thousand layoff notices went out to board employees in February.
Staff members and parents wanted to know what the trustees have
in mind. 
<P>
The full board won't vote on cuts until next week But last night
the committee approved some reductions that would chop forty six
and a half teaching positions, seven principal jobs and two and
a half administrative assistants. 
<P>
In other developments in education news, the Lincoln County Board
of Education has decided to end its junior kindergarten program.

<P>
The Norfolk Board has sent layoff notices to 85 employees, including
50 teachers. 
<P>
And now high school teachers are talking strike. Ontario Secondary
School Teachers' Federation President Earl Manners says bargaining
units unable to reach a deal should quickly take a strike vote.
The plan is to have as many teachers as possible across the province
in a strike position by September 1st. 
<HR>

<H3>Civics-Layoffs </H3>

<P>
Cuts continues to take their toll in health care. Hamilton Civic
Hospitals are calling it a worst case scenario that they hope
can be improved in the next six months. 125 support staff at the
civics were given layoff notices today. 
<P>
As Jamie West reports the hospitals are wrestling with tough provincial
budget cuts and they're hopeful that not all of the workers given
notice will actually end up losing their jobs. 
<P>
<I>Hamilton Civic Hospital officials announced the layoffs to
begin in six months, at the Hamilton General Division this morning.
Those departments affected include support staff, ward clerks,
housekeeping services, nutrition services as well as registered
technologists. </I>
<P>
<I>CUPE officials as expected are not happy... the civics had
expected to be working with 10 to 13 million dollars less in the
next fiscal year due to provincial cuts, but an additional unexpected
cut of 4 million dollars announced in February put added pressure
on management to reduce costs.</I>
<P>
<I>Meanwhile the civics are continuing discussions with the Ontario
Nurses Association. Nursing layoffs are also expected in the near
future.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>CAS Adoptions </H3>

<P>
A storm is brewing over the impact welfare cuts are having on
poor families. 
<P>
In Simcoe County the Children's Aid Society says two families
considered adopting out their children as a way of coping with
extreme poverty. But other child care agencies say that is a practice
that ended 40 years ago and has no place in today's society. Kathy
Renwald reports. 
<P>
<I>The director of Hamilton's Children's Aid Society says he has
not heard of any families forced by poverty to give up their kids.
But at Queens Park politicians are being grilled over the story
out of Simcoe County that poor families have considered giving
their kids up. Premier Mike Harris has a harder take on the story.
</I>
<P>
<I>But the reduction in economic support should never force families
to make such a dire choice to give them up according to Mainville.
As some families absorb welfare cuts..the Children's Aid Societies
juggle their own budgets after reductions. </I>
<P>
<I>Government cuts trimmed nearly 700 thousand from the Hamilton
CAS budget resulting in 10 staff cuts.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Miss. City Hall </H3>

<P>
Police arrested a man who was throwing furniture and fire hoses
out of the second-floor windows of City Hall in Mississauga early
today. 
<P>
Peel Region officers responded to an alarm inside the building
around 4 a.m. When they arrived, they found the man barricaded
inside. Police moved in around 5 a.m. and apprehended the man.
He faces numerous charges. 
<HR>

<H3>Robberies </H3>

<P>
Halton police are looking for a twice-lucky gunman who made off
with cash from a pair of shell stations last night. 
<P>
In both incidents, the man entered the kiosks, asked for cigarettes,
and then pulled a gun. No shots were fired and there were no injuries.

<P>
Police are looking for a 25 to 30 year old white male ...5-feet,
ten inches tall with long, light-colored hair. 
<HR>

<H3>Drugs </H3>

<P>
And, a couple of drug busts last night. 27 year old Horace Knight
of Hamilton faces trafficking charges after cocaine was sold to
a Halton undercover officer. 
<P>
And, an Oakville man, 20 year old Iain Fleming was picked up on
possession charges after a search warrant was executed at his
home. Police found drugs and money. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Stock prices in Canada and the dollar moved higher today while
US investors continued their selling. 
<P>
Stelco's Hilton Works is named by Chrysler as its best supplier
of steel. 
<P>
Philip environmental issues new stock while an investment firm
increases its control of Hamilton's Wescam to 10 per cent. 

<P>

