<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, April 9, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton Air 
<LI>Education Cuts 
<LI>Blythe Protest 
<LI>Workfare Reconsider 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Air</H3>

<P>
For years Hamilton has been the brunt of nation wide jokes about
it's air quality. According to a new study Hamilton's air isn't
that great, but it's not as bad and in some cases even better
than a lot of industrial cities of the same size around the world.

<P>
The problem seems to be that the steel city still has an abnormally
high rate of respiratory problems as we hear in this report from
Jamie West.
<P>
<I>How much of this smoke spewing from Hamilton's industrial core
is getting into your lungs? Probably a lot right?... at St. Joseph's
Hospital Dr.'s Malcolm Sears and Fred Hargreave will team up to
try and find out the answer. </I>
<P>
<I>What the researchers do know is that of six Canadian cities
recently surveyed, Hamilton, despite placing lower for smoking
and allergies, placed first for those taking medication for asthma
at 8 percent of those surveyed and five percent had to change
jobs because of breathing problems. </I>
<P>
<I>The number of patients arriving at St. Joseph's Firestone Chest
and Allergy Unit is on the rise, but doctors say the problems
are not as simple as people working in buildings with poor air
circulation and dirty vents. </I>
<P>
<I>The next step... a new diagnostic test in which the patient
breathes in warm salt mist and then exhales forcefully will allow
for the collection of lung secretions, pinpointing the exact origin
of the respiratory problem.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Education Cuts </H3>

<P>
It's not so much the quality of the air but the quality of education
on the minds of some parents tonight ...... Scot Urquhart reports.

<P>
<I>It doesn't matter what program you're talking about ... no
one wants to cut: whether it's French immersion, junior kindergarten
or transportation programs for special education students.</I>
<P>
<I>Ellen Horak is no expert. She is an every day citizen, and
parent. Although she lives in Burlington, the issues she has considered
in dealing with the Halton Board, may provide some lessons in
Hamilton Wentworth as well.</I>
<P>
<I>When looking at the big picture in Hamilton, you start to get
an idea of what Ellen Horak is talking about. The Hamilton Board's
total budget is a whopping 269 million dollars. By comparison,
government cuts of six or seven million ... are a pittance. Even
cutting another 19.4 million dollars means that the total budget
is down by less than ten percent. </I>
<P>
<I>If you had to cut ten percent from your household budget; could
you do it?. Sue Giardano says she can, and did.  And would parents
be willing to pay more for transportation or special interest
programs? And Ellen Horak thinks therein: lies the ultimate answer.
let communities decide for themselves what to spend the money
on.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Blythe Protest</H3>

<P>
The village of Blythe, near London meanwhile, plans to stop collecting
education property taxes levied by school boards and has sent
letters seeking their protest to 754 municipalities across Ontario.

<P>
Reeve Mason Bailey says the revolt is aimed at provincial law
requiring municipalities to collect that portion of the property
tax. Bailey says a similar protest by farmers some three decades
ago led to the farm tax rebate program. 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare Reconsider </H3>

<P>
It's being described as a job killer and a punitive action against
poor people ... but it looks like Workfare is still a go in Hamilton
Wentworth. 
<P>
Regional councilors say they need to be at the table with the
province in order to mold a made in Hamilton solution to the problem.
Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>This delegation came to Hamilton Wentworth's Health and Social
Services Committee urging members to take the lead among other
municipalities and walk away from Workfare. But the region wants
to take the lead by working closely with the Ontario government
on its Workfare policy. </I>
<P>
<I>While it's highly unlikely the region will reconsider its Workfare
motion with the Ontario government, members of the Health and
Social Services Committee are open to suggestions on how to bring
the best possible Workfare options to Hamilton Wentworth. </I>
<P>
<I>Some of those suggestions may come from a Workfare forum being
held this Saturday at the Rotary Self Help Centre on West Avenue
in Hamilton. It begins at 1 o'clock.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Financial markets settled today after yesterday's volatile selloff
of stocks and bonds. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar and interest rates were stable Tuesday while
share prices in Toronto rose. 

<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

