<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, April 5, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Niagara Abduction 
<LI>H &amp; R Car 
<LI>Critical Accident 
<LI>Cambridge Victim 
<LI>Good Friday Walk 
<LI>Burl. Food Drive 
<LI>Ukrainian Eggs 
<LI>Easter Egg Hunt 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Niagara Abduction</H3>

<P>
In Niagara Falls, police are looking for a suspect in an attempted
abduction and sexual assault tonight. The incident last night
involved an 11 year old girl. 
<P>
The girl was walking home from Centre Variety store when she was
accosted by a man and forced into a vehicle parked behind the
building. Police say the suspect pushed her out of the car when
she screamed. He then drove westbound on Kitchener Street in a
dark colored, four door vehicle. 
<P>
The man is described as white, 19 years old, 5 foot 8, 180 pounds.
He had long brown hair in a ponytail and was wearing jeans and
a sweatshirt. Any one with any information is asked to call Niagara
Regional Police. 
<HR>

<H3>H &amp; R car </H3>

<P>
Ontario Provincial Police are asking for the public's assistance
in their investigation of the hit and run death of Constable Mike
Gula. Constable Gula was struck and killed by a sport utility
vehicle while he was standing on the shoulder of the QEW Tuesday
night. 
<P>
There is extensive damage to the vehicle's front end. Police are
seeking the public's help in tracking the movements of the that
vehicle on the night the officer was killed. 
<P>
Sixty seven year old Frank Vanderkley has been charged with failure
to remain at the scene of the accident in connection with Constable
Gula's death. Further charges may be laid. 
<HR>

<H3>Critical Accident </H3>

<P>
Yesterday's icy road conditions landed a Niagara Falls man in
Hamilton General Hospital in serious condition. 
<P>
The car driven by 53-year-old John Vanderlee crossed into on-coming
traffic on Morrison Street in Niagara Falls and struck a second
vehicle. That driver was treated for minor injuries. Police are
still trying to find out just what happened. 
<HR>

<H3>Cambridge Victim </H3>

<P>
A former Cambridge resident is listed as one of the 35 casualties
in Wednesday's plane crash in Croatia. 
<P>
54-four-year-old Robert Donovan, a past president of the engineering
firm Babcock and Wilcox, was among the business executives killed
when a plane carrying US Commerce Secretary Ron Brown crashed
into a mountainside near Dubrovnik. 
<P>
Officially, Donovan's status is &quot;whereabouts unknown.&quot;
He was listed on the flight register as president of ABB Incorporated
of Connecticut. 
<P>
Donovan was president of Babcock and Wilcox from 1985 to 1987.
The bodies of all victims have now been recovered and are being
flown back to the US. for identification.
<HR>

<H3>Good Friday Walk </H3>

<P>
Christians around the world were retracing the final steps of
Jesus Christ today. 
<P>
Hundreds turned out downtown St. Catharines this morning for the
annual Good Friday church walk. 
<P>
Congregations from each of Christian denominations participate
in the event. It's a traditional Good Friday service held outdoors
in the community. Participants walk from church to church stopping
to hear each pastor's Good Friday message. 
<P>
The walk is a remembrance of the trip Jesus took from Jerusalem
to the hill of Calvary. This is the 15th anniversary of the event.

<HR>

<H3>Burl. Food Drive </H3>

<P>
Volunteers with Burlington Food Share were busy today sorting
donations from the Easter food drive. 
<P>
The campaign runs until Monday ..donations are being accepted
at fire halls in Burlington and at supermarkets. In February 1,300
visits were made to food banks in Burlington, this Easter drive
will go to support the needs of the Salvation Army, and other
agencies in Burlington. Donations of canned fish and meat are
especially needed. 
<HR>

<H3>Ukrainian eggs </H3>

<P>
And a Burlington parking lot was full at 9.a.m with hundreds of
people waiting anxiously at the door. On sale were bread and eggs.
But those basic foodstuffs are transformed at the hands of Ukrainian
artists. Reporter Kathy Renwald joined the crowd at St. Mary's
church. 
<P>
<I>Ukrainian artists expected to sell eggs ..but not by the dozen.
But the appetite for these luxuriously crafted eggs was nearly
insatiable. As the eggs changed hands at the selling table ..an
artist demonstrated the work behind the creations..and talked
about their meaning. </I>
<P>
<I>The eggs were selling from 5 to 30 dollars. At another table
you couldn't even put your hands on the perogies advance orders
and early birds gobbled up all the available stock. </I>
<P>
<I>For three days members of the Ukrainian Catholic Women's League
occupy the kitchen at St. Mary's to cook for the sale. It's a
good fund raiser for the church. Another sale will be held in
June.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Easter Egg Hunt </H3>

<P>
A little further down the peninsula, hundreds of Grimsby-area
children got a head start on their hunt for Easter eggs today,
thanks to the Grimsby Kinsmen Club. 
<P>
The kinsmen staged their eighteenth annual Easter egg hunt in
the rose garden at Centennial Park. The lingering snow actually
made it a little easier to spot the chocolate treats. 
<P>
The event has grown so popular that for the first time this year,
the Grimsby Kinsmen enlisted the help of corporate sponsors to
defray costs. Seven-hundred children and a thousand adults turned
out last year, and despite the brisk temperatures, attendance
came close to that number today. 
<P>
The co-chairmen of the event, Frank Snow and Mark Wasilewski,
say the Easter egg hunt is the Kinsmen's way of saying thank you
to the town of Grimsby for its year-round support of Kinsmen fund-raisers.

<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

