<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, April 4, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Winter Weather 
<LI>New Orchestra(s) 
<LI>Cooke - Region 
<LI>UI. Stats 
<LI>Teacher Cuts 
<LI>Welfare Fraud 
<LI>Business-First 
<LI>Vanderkley Bail 
<LI>Stewart ID'd. 
<LI>Bernardo 
<LI>Sportsman Lanes Fire 
<LI>Key Theft 
<LI>St. Joes Research 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Winter Weather</H3>

<P>
Enough is enough, that's the feeling of most southern Ontario
residents who woke up to another winter style blast from mother
nature. 
<P>
Snow mixed with freezing rain and ice pellets was whipped around
by gusty winds throughout the area.  The storm caught many off
guard and caused a number of problems not only with morning commuter
traffic, but with the things we take for granted in the morning
like Hydro and water. 
<P>
Sections of Hamilton mountain Ancaster, and some parts of Niagara
were without both because of a problem with a water pumping station
and high winds and ice weighing down power lines. Temperatures
expected to climb above the freezing mark this afternoon did not
materialize, and a number of accidents on area highways were touched
off as cold winds of lake Ontario picked up strength. 
<P>
One accident involved nearly a dozen vehicles on the westbound
403 near York Boulevard just after the noon hour. No word on any
injuries but traffic was delayed for several hours. As of air
time, there were still some reports of sporadic power outages
throughout the golden horseshoe. 
<HR>

<H3>New Orchestra(s) </H3>

<P>
How about a fanfare to greet spring when it finally arrives? And
how about two orchestras to play it? Today two groups are making
it known that they want to be suppliers of classical music in
the city but if Hamilton couldn't support one philharmonic, how
could they possibly back two?. Kathy Renwald reports on what could
be another musical maelstrom. 
<P>
<I>Boris Brott has been running a summer music festival in Hamilton
for 8 years. Now his group has asked for government funding to
form the new academy orchestra which could become this city's
replacement for the defunct philharmonic. </I>
<P>
<I>Bruce Hamilton is chairman of the board for the new orchestra.
But having Boris Brott step in to fill the Hamilton classical
musical scene is not what Robert Waxman has in mind. He's been
hand picked by the Smith Macdonald group to put their plan into
action to rebuild an orchestra. </I>
<P>
<I>But the new academy orchestra has already applied for government
funding.. the Waxman group hasnt.  Bruce Hamilton thinks that
holds the key to the future. Brott's group expects to hear a decision
on funding by mid April.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Cooke - Region </H3>

<P>
The fiscal realities of the nineties have forced Hamilton- Wentworth's
regional government to down-size its workforce, to re-organize
what's left, and to privatize many of its public services. But
when the dust settles, regional chairman Terry Cooke insists Hamilton-
Wentworth can emerge as an economic winner, if its citizens and
politicians are willing to embrace change. Deborah Walker reports
on Cooke's &quot;state of the region&quot; address, delivered
to the Hamilton Rotary Club today. 
<P>
<I>Hamilton- Wentworth's regional chairman says the dramatic change
the public sector is now experiencing, is nothing new to the private
sector. </I>
<P>
<I>Terry Cooke says Hamilton- Wentworth can emerge as an economic
winner, only if its government remains committed to creating safer
neighborhoods, a cleaner environment, and an effective transportation
infrastructure. And he says the region must work to reform the
punitive tax structure that is largely responsible for the decline
of downtown Hamilton. </I>
<P>
<I>Cooke also urged his audience to take a stand on the constituent
assembly's final recommendation to move to one-tier municipal
government in Hamilton- Wentworth. Cooke says blindly defending
the status quo is a recipe for mediocrity, when excellence is
possible. </I>
<HR>

<H3>UI Stats </H3>

<P>
Unemployment edged higher in the golden horseshoe over the last
couple of months. That's despite a lower national rate. 
<P>
After holding steady at 9.6 per cent in January and February,
Canada's unemployed level dropped to 9.3 per cent in March. But
a big reason for the drop is that thousands of people became discouraged
and stopped actively seeking employment. 
<P>
During march, the economy lost eight-thousand jobs, ending a three-month
job-creation surge. 
<HR>

<H3>Teacher Cuts </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the Haldimand Board of Education is the latest to announce
major staff cuts to cope with reduced provincial funding. 
<P>
Fifty-three teachers are among 160 board employees to receive
layoff notices in the area south of Hamilton. All educators with
less than three years experience face layoff in June, while early
retirement is being offered to others. 
<P>
Education assistants, lunch supervisors, janitorial and administrative
staff make up the remainder of the job cuts. 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Fraud </H3>

<P>
A police fraud squad has cracked a welfare scheme in Hamilton.

<P>
From December 1992 to December of last year, 38-thousand dollars
were collected by a suspect not entitled to benefits. Police say
he was using someone else's name. 
<P>
57 year old David Thomas of Hamilton faces two counts of fraud
over 1-thousand dollars and two counts of impersonation. 
<HR>

<H3>Business-First </H3>

<P>
Banks, government offices and financial markets will be closed
tomorrow for Good Friday. Financial markets finished the week
with stock prices and the value of the dollar moving lower while
interest rates remained stable. 
<P>
Canada's unemployment rate dropped in March, but that's because
a lot of young people left the work force. 
<HR>

<H3>Vanderkley Bail </H3>

<P>
The Niagara Falls man, charged in Tuesday nights hit-and-run death
of an OPP officer has been granted bail. 
<P>
67-year old frank Jacob Vanderkley was set free this afternoon
after signing a thousand dollar bond. He's to reappear in court
on failing to remain charges, May 2nd. 
<P>
Vanderkley turned himself in after an intense police search yesterday
for the driver of a vehicle which slammed into a police officer
knocking him into traffic on the Queen Elizabeth Way. 
<P>
52-year old Constable Michael Gula died from injuries sustained
in the accident. Funeral services are planned for him Saturday.

<HR>

<H3>Stewart ID'd. </H3>

<P>
Human remains found in Pelham, have now been positively identified.

<P>
Niagara Regional Police say the remains are those of Dawn Alaine
Stewart of Niagara falls and a six-month-old fetus. 
<P>
Stewart was last seen September 29th in Niagara falls, where she
was known to work as a prostitute. A hiker found the remains Sunday.

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo </H3>

<P>
A judge has ruled videotapes that show Paul Bernardo and Karla
Homolka torturing two girls should be destroyed when they are
no longer needed for legal purposes. Families of Kristen French
and Leslie Mahaffy had gone to court in an effort to keep the
tapes out of public view. 
<P>
In a written ruling, Justice Patrick Gravely said he has no hesitation
in accepting evidence that the tapes can be classified as pornography
of the worst kind. The families' lawyer, Tim Danson, says the
two remaining copies of the tapes will be kept in safe keeping,
likely until Bernardo's death. The tapes are still needed , however,
in several pending court cases.
<HR>

<H3>Sportsman Lanes Fire </H3>

<P>
Hamilton fire crews were called out to the building that used
to house the Sportsman's Bowling Lanes on Charlton Avenue just
after 10-thirty this morning. 
<P>
It took nearly an hour to get what fire officials describe as
a well involved basement fire under control. The building has
been vacant for several years and no one was hurt. 
<P>
Damage is pegged at nearly 40-thousand dollars. The Fire Marshall
is investigating the cause of the blaze. 
<HR>

<H3>Key Theft </H3>

<P>
A suspicious car has prompted police in Hamilton to lay a rare
criminal charge. 
<P>
A patrol sergeant had turned around to follow a Honda Accord but
by the time he found it, the driver had taken off, leaving the
car running. The suspect was arrested nearby, where police also
found two other Honda Accords, both with the ignition punched
out. 
<P>
18 year old Khong Yong of no fixed address is charged with possession
of a master key. More charges are expected to be laid.
<HR>

<H3>St. Joes Research </H3>

<P>
St. Joseph's Health Care System, an alliance of five facilities
in central Ontario announced a unique research network today.

<P>
The Father Sean O'Sullivan Research Centre at Hamilton's St. Joseph's
Hospital will work with hospitals in Brantford, Kitchener and
Guelph. 
<P>
The first order of business for the network will be to focus on
the study of aging and the elderly and to place an emphasis on
creating a continuum of care between the community and the hospital.

<P>

