<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, April 3, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Death Follow 
<LI>Hamilton Arrest 
<LI>Ride-Stolen 
<LI>1005 Rejects Deal 
<LI>Welfare Study 
<LI>Workfare Pilot 
<LI>Constituent Recs. 
<LI>HRCA Cuts 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Death Follow</H3>

<P>
Police have made an arrest in the hit and run death of OPP. Constable
Michael Gula. 
<P>
The arrest was announced at a news conference late this afternoon.
Constable Gula was struck on the QEW in Niagara Falls last night,
just months away from retirement. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Arrest </H3>

<P>
Police from Quebec, raided an apartment on Queen Street North
in Hamilton, last night; and, with the assistance of Hamilton
Wentworth Regional Police; arrested a suspect wanted for two murders
in St. Eustache, Quebec. 
<P>
The victims, were a middle aged couple, whose bodies were found
in their home, in august 1993. Charged in connection with the
deaths; is 38 year old Ronald Kelly Simon, of Hamilton. Simon
was held in custody overnight, and returned to Quebec this afternoon,
to face charges. 
<HR>

<H3>Ride-Stolen </H3>

<P>
A pair of car thieves took the wrong way home last night. 
<P>
Just twenty minutes after picking up a sports car in Stoney Creek,
they ran into a police Ride program on Hamilton mountain. The
pair was arrested when officers noticed the car's ignition had
been punched and the driver still had a screwdriver in his lap.

<P>
Jointly charged with theft and possession over 5-thousand dollars
are 21 year old Mark Fothergill and 19 year old Tanya Hutchinson,
both of Hamilton. Fothergill is also charged with possession of
burglary tools. 
<HR>

<H3>1005 Rejects Deal </H3>

<P>
The result is as close as the Quebec Referendum, but steelworkers
at Stelco's Hilton Works have turned down an early contract agreement.
The deal would have given union members improvements to their
pension and a cost of living allowance increase, but no wage hikes.
Now the deal is null and void. Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>9 votes are all that separated steelworker's local 10-0-5 and
Stelco's Hilton Works from a six year contract. It's a deal that
would have seen pensions increase by 240 dollars a month. The
union needed a 51 per cent acceptance to ratify the deal, they
had 49-point-86. And just as the vote is split almost 50 50, so
is the union membership. </I>
<P>
<I>About half of the nearly 5-thousand workers the union represents,
have more than 30 years of service and can retire immediately,
the other half can't. After spending three months hammering out
the deal, both the union executive and Hilton Works say they're
disappointed with the outcome. </I>
<P>
<I>Bob Jones, the director of human resources says there weren't
customers hanging on the vote results, but a long term contract
would benefit both the company and the membership.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Study </H3>

<P>
Two-thousand people disappeared from Hamilton- Wentworth's welfare
rolls between October, when the Tories cut benefits twenty-two
per cent, and the end of last year. And Hamilton- Wentworth's
Social Planning and Research Council wants to know why. 
<P>
In order to answer the question, social planners hope to conduct
confidential interviews with as many of those two-thousand people
as possible. If you're willing to take part in the study, you
can drop by the Social Planning and Research Council at 255 West
Avenue North in Hamilton, and pick up a questionnaire. Or you
can simply call the Council at 522-1148, and give your answers
over the phone. 
<P>
The council hopes to release the findings of its study in June.

<HR>

<H3>Workfare Pilot </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Hamilton- Wentworth wants to be a pilot site for the
provincial government's Workfare program. Councilors voted last
night to apply to become one of 15 test sites. 
<P>
Social Services Commissioner Mike Shuster says there could be
three million dollars in it for the region. Some 5-thousand general
welfare recipients in Hamilton- Wentworth would be involved. 
<P>
Shuster says a made in Hamilton -Wentworth solution could ensure
that the program is humane and best for the people here. Workfare
is supposed to provide welfare recipients with some form of training,
part-time or volunteer work.
<HR>

<H3>Constituent Recs. </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth taxpayers could save tens of millions of dollars
if regional councilors are willing to accept grass roots proposals
for municipal government reform. 
<P>
The constituent assembly, created a year ago to fulfill a campaign
promise by Regional Chairman Terry Cooke, presented its final
report to a special committee meeting this afternoon. Deborah
Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Hamilton- Wentworth's constituent assembly recommends abolishing
Regional Council, the six local councils and their bureaucracies,
and replacing them with one municipal administration, one municipal
council with no more than thirty members plus a chairman, and
an unspecified number of community committees. </I>
<P>
<I>The CA wants to eliminate Hamilton- Wentworth's &quot;city
versus the suburbs mentality&quot;, by recommending more balanced
representation on the new super council. </I>
<P>
<I>The constituent assembly believes its recommendations will
produce a more accountable, more efficient, more cost-effective
municipal government. </I>
<P>
<I>If it rejects the constituent assembly's proposals, regional
councilors risk inviting the province to dictate terms for reform.</I>

<HR>

<H3>HRCA Cuts </H3>

<P>
Faced with a 1-point-4 million dollar funding shortfall this year,
the Hamilton Region Conservation Authority is having to conserve
a lot of money. 
<P>
The authority has had to re-evaluate its mandate, meaning some
environmental services will be reduced to eliminated, but its
watershed management will not be abandoned. 
<P>
By the middle of next year, 9 of 60 full time positions will be
gone, and seasonal staff wages will be cut by 10 per cent. Gate
fees at several conservation areas will be increased by 1-dollar
per vehicle, and visitors to the Dundas Valley Conservation Area
will be charged a daily entry fee. 
<HR>

<H3>Business-First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stock prices moved lower today along with the value of
the dollar. 
<P>
Diamond Fields Resources said it will accept the four and a half
billion dollar takeover offer from Inco. 
<P>
Dropping oil inventories are pushing gasoline prices higher. 

<P>

