<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, April 2, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<UL>
<LI>1005 Vote 
<LI>Regional Budget 
<LI>Resale Hamilton 
<LI>Seaway Opens 
<LI>Business-First 
<LI>Drug Bust 
<LI>Burned Body Arrest 
<LI>Gentles Mother 
<LI>Pelham Bones Update 
<LI>Copps - Teacher 
<LI>Barton - Arrest 
<LI>HW Enviro Update
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>1005 Vote</H3>

<P>
As striking Ontario civil servants return to their jobs and other
union leaders threaten strike action, a different story tonight
about Hamilton steelworkers. 
<P>
The five thousand members of local 1005 and Stelco reached an
early tentative agreement on a long-term contract that if accepted,
will take Canada's largest steelmaker through the next six years.

<HR>

<H3>Regional Budget </H3>

<P>
Regional councilors in Hamilton Wentworth stamped their final
budget today and it means a nine dollar increase on the regional
portion of the property tax bill. 
<P>
As Kathy Renwald reports, most councilors felt it would be too
painful to bring in a zero per cent increase. 
<P>
<I>There could be more potholes and maybe fewer flower pots as
the bottom line of the regional budget. Hamilton Wentworth regional
councilors looked over the final figures today and approved a
further five per cent cut in funding to the Royal Botanical Gardens.
The Regional Police will defer hiring another 25 officers until
1997.. and a 1. 5 million dollar reduction in maintenance to regional
roads was approved. </I>
<P>
<I>But staff promised those cuts wont be noticible..the money
will be saved through productivity improvements.. and whats not
saved there.. will be made up by dipping into the reserve budget
for snow removal. </I>
<P>
<I>Councilor Bob Charters among others found that cost saving
plan vague. An extra inning motion was promoted by Regional Chairman
Terry Cooke.. who wants to see people using the regional transfer
stations charged a user fee. </I>
<P>
<I>Staff said that would generate over 300 thousand in extra revenue..
but the scheme was lost on a tie vote. The final budget passed
brought in a 1.6 per cent increase ..amounting to about 9 dollars
more on the regional portion of the property tax bill.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Resale Hamilton </H3>

<P>
The Hamilton area housing market is off to a strong start this
year and will continue to strengthen through 1997. 
<P>
In its spring forecast, Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation
says the sale of existing homes will reach 84-hundred this year
and rise by about nine per cent next year to 86-hundred units.
Moderate mortgage rates and low unemployment in the Hamilton area
are luring buyers back into the housing market. 
<HR>

<H3>Seaway Opens</H3>

<P>
The Welland Canal is open for another shipping season. 
<P>
St. Lawrence Seaway president Glendon Stewart presented the traditional
top hat to the captain of the year's first ship through the waterway
at lock number three this morning. It's the canal's 168th season.
And, says Stewart, the St. Lawrence seaway may soon be operating
more like a private business. 
<HR>

<H3>Business-First </H3>

<P>
More big gains in stock markets today as the Canadian dollar and
interest rates remain stable. 
<P>
Canada's big cable companies are forming an alliance to take on
the phone companies in a battle for high speed data and voice
transmission markets. 
<HR>

<H3>Drug Bust </H3>

<P>
A joint forces drug raid this morning has netted police about
half a million dollars worth of drugs, cash and property. 
<P>
20 people have been arrested after police raided a number of homes
in Hamilton, Stoney Creek and Toronto. Police say with the raids,
they have effectively shut down two cocaine operations with roots
in Venezuela. 
<P>
Investigators say the rings had the potential to make quite an
impact on the drug market. 
<HR>

<H3>Burned Body Arrest </H3>

<P>
Police have arrested a man in connection with the murder of Sinniah
Rajan Mamankaran two years ago. 
<P>
The victim's charred body was discovered on the side of Tufford
Road in Beamsville in July, 1994. Investigators believe the Sri
Lankan immigrant was abducted from a Mississauga parking lot hours
before he was killed. 
<P>
Charged with kidnapping, forcible confinement and first degree
murder is 29 year old Nehruji Natkunam of Toronto. 
<HR>

<H3>Gentles Mother</H3>

<P>
The mother of a Kingston Penitentiary inmate who died after a
confrontation with jail guards was back in court today. 
<P>
Carmeta Gentles is trying to get charges against the guards reinstated.
The Attorney General withdrew the charges of manslaughter against
the six guards. The court was to hear arguments today and tomorrow.

<P>
Robert Gentles died in October 1993 after being dragged from his
cell and maced. 
<HR>

<H3>Pelham Bones Update </H3>

<P>
Niagara Region Police say the human remains found in a field near
St. Catharines are those of a pregnant woman. 
<P>
The grisly discovery was made Sunday afternoon by a hiker in Pelham.
Investigators say they are checking missing persons reports in
hopes of identifying the woman. Foul play has not been ruled out.

<HR>

<H3>Copps - Teacher </H3>

<P>
This woman has been honored for her special efforts. Holly Garrett,
a special education teacher at Parkdale Public School in east
Hamilton, has been given a Prime Minister's award for teaching
excellence in science, technology and mathematics. 
<P>
Mrs. Garrett has hooked up her class so they're interactive with
the Jason project as it explores the world underwater. They started
studying the project when it was working on the Hamilton Scourge
warships back in 1990. 
<HR>

<H3>Barton - Arrest</H3>

<P>
And over at Hamilton's Barton Secondary School, quite a commotion
this afternoon. 
<P>
English teacher Steve Kennedy was arrested and charged with truancy,
and vagrancy inside the school cafeteria. The prank was a ploy
by the student council to raise enough money to bail Mr. Kennedy
out of jail, and help support the upcoming Mothers Day Telethon
in support of Chedoke McMaster Children's Hospital. 
<P>
The students managed to raise 145-dollars in spare change. And
Constable Rob (my-yay) ran into a little resistance as he loaded
Mr. Kennedy into his cruiser to be booked. 
<HR>

<H3>HW Enviro Update </H3>

<P>
There was an environmental jam session of sorts at Hamilton City
Hall today. 
<P>
Groups involved in environmental issues gathered to present status
reports on where Hamilton stands as a sustainable community. The
purpose was to update regional politicians on Hamilton achievements
in cleaning up the environment. 
<P>
The region has won several international awards on efforts to
balance the environment with economic issues. 


<P>

