<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 04/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, April 1, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<UL>
<LI>Workfare Demo 
<LI>Back to Work 
<LI>Strike Warning 
<LI>Teenager Dies 
<LI>Pelham Bones 
<LI>Mystery Body 
<LI>Canatom Demo 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Workfare Demo</H3>

<P>
They think it's a joke, a bad one at that, and they chose April
1st to make their point. 
<P>
A consortium of Hamilton social agencies say Workfare is not fair.
They staged a march and rally late this afternoon to show their
outrage to the Mike Harris government plan to make welfare recipients
work for their benefits. 
<P>
The protesters, including church workers, child care activists
and university members were also demonstrating against the Canada
assistance program. They marched from the Employment Canada offices
at King William and Wellington to Gore Park, proclaiming Workfare
is salve labour and threatens union jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Back to Work </H3>

<P>
The end to OPSEU's five week strike is being met not only with
a collective bargaining agreement, but also with a collective
sigh of relief, and today workers and management in government
offices across the province set out to catch up on unfinished
business that had piled up during the work stoppage. Jamie West
reports.... 
<P>
<I>Despite a scene that looks like the remnants of a war zone
outside the Hamilton Psychiatric Hospital... the fact is the war
is over and all that's left of the Ontario public service union's
first strike are a few empty chairs, a couple of cooled off steel
drums and a quiet trailer.</I>
<P>
<I>Management and staff are friends again... the story was very
much the same at Burlington's Ministry of Transportation office
where workers beamed as they went back to work. </I>
<P>
<I>At Hamilton's Ellen Fairclough Building employees, management
and the public moved in and out with ease...for the first time
in five weeks. Hamilton land registrar Elgin Farewell couldn't
be happier... the backlog of registrations is significant both
for real estate transactions and for companies seeking to incorporate
and it will take time to clear.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Strike Warning </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, one union leader is warning of more strikes. The Bob
Rae government's social contract which froze wages and forced
workers to take unpaid days off expired at midnight last night.

<P>
CUPE Ontario president Sid Ryan says if his members walk out,
it will be more noticeable than the OPSEU strike. 
<P>
CUPE represents workers at hospitals, school boards and social
agencies, and garbage collectors. 
<HR>

<H3>Teenager Dies </H3>

<P>
A teenage driver involved in a police chase two weeks ago in St.
Catharines has died from his injuries. 
<P>
Sixteen year old Kenneth Miller was driving a stolen van that
crashed into a utility pole on Queenston Street. Two other passengers
were injured. The province's special investigation unit is investigating.

<HR>

<H3>Pelham Bones </H3>

<P>
Niagara Regional Police Investigators are still on the scene in
rural Pelham where the partial skeleton of a woman has been found.
A child made the gruesome discovery and as Lauran Sabourin reports,
it could be another day before the remains are removed. 
<P>
<I>Investigators cordon off the area, preparing to scour what
may be a homicide crime scene. .. the remains belong to a woman.
Police are still not sure of her age. A skull lies about 30 feet
from the carcass. The feet have been arms have disappeared, probably
carried off by animals who have been gnawing at the bones. </I>
<P>
<I>Two neighbourhood dogs who were romping through the crime scene
were rounded up and locked in the back of a police cruiser. White
flags mark the area where bone fragments have been found. </I>
<P>
<I>The remains will be taken to Hamilton to be closely examined
for any clues that to how the woman died. Investigators will begin
scouring the scene, while identification officers try to determine
the identity of the woman.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Mystery Body </H3>

<P>
Halton police have either a macabre April fools joke or a bizarre
homicide on their hands. 
<P>
Their appealing for anyone who may have a car stopped on Highway
401 near Highway 6 Sunday evening to contact them. It's the latest
in a story that began last evening after some witnesses reported
seeing the driver of a dark coloured jaguar dump a human body
into the car's trunk or onto the shoulder of the road. 
<P>
The car was found and the driver questioned and today the car
was to be examined for forensic evidence. An extensive search
of the area yesterday, failed to turn up any body. 
<HR>

<H3>Canatom Demo </H3>

<P>
A nuclear waste transfer station is now up and running in Oakville,
and some residents aren't very happy about it. 
<P>
A group of people, calling themselves &quot;Citizens Organized
for Responsible Process&quot;, gathered outside the Canatom plant
to protest its opening. Canatom will handle everything from contaminated
gloves, syringes and lab coats to by products of cat scans and
x-rays. 
<P>
The protesters are concerned because the nuclear waste storage
facility is located close to a densely populated residential area
and several schools. 

<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

