<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 03/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, March 29, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton Pickets 
<LI>Hamilton Orchestra 
<LI>Public Salaries 
<LI>Suspect Suicide 
<LI>Heroine Bust 
<LI>Dope 
<LI>403 Rollover 
<LI>Car Theft 
<LI>Business-First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Pickets </H3>

<P>
Good evening. The haggling continues. This time last night we
were telling you an end to the OPSEU strike was imminent. But
24 hours later, negotiators for striking Ontario public servants
and the Harris government remain huddled over a Toronto bargaining
table ... trying to hammer out the final details of a tentative
agreement that would end the 5-week old strike by provincial workers.

<P>
But a stumbling block remains... the disagreement now is over
whether workers designated essential who refused to work should
be disciplined. On picket lines in Hamilton today, meanwhile,
there was an air of hope and optimism... as Anthony Pooley reports.

<P>
<I>For these workers, it has been day after day of walking picket
line duty in front of the Ellen Fairclough building... walking
the line despite the weather and just about anything else. They
are, at once, both weary and energized... weary of the strike
and its effect on them... but energized by word of the status
of negotiations. </I>
<P>
<I>And there has been suffering... at the Hamilton- Wentworth
Detention Centre they are not only strike weary... but weary of
the extra scrutiny under which corrections officers found themselves...
a portion of them compelled to work amid the heightened danger
of skeleton staffing. </I>
<P>
<I>They are... not surprisingly... sensitive to media coverage
and suspicious of news media... but one young corrections officer
sums up the personal adversity faced by many during the work stoppage.
And there is the hope that very soon, they will be back doing
their jobs. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Orchestra </H3>

<P>
It will take a million dollars, wage concessions from musicians,
and zero tolerance for deficits in order to breathe life back
into the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra. Today, members of the
task force investigating Hamilton's ability to support a philharmonic
orchestra outlined a twelve-step plan for a musical revival. Deborah
Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>The co-chairmen of the task force bluntly explain what caused
the demise of the 113-year-old Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra.
They're equally blunt in explaining what it will take to bring
music back to the city. A new board and management who won't tolerate
the accumulation of any deficit. </I>
<P>
<I>A half-million dollars in private donations, and another half-million
in advanced subscription ticket sales. All ticket revenues must
be held in trust, and not squandered on operating expenses. Musicians
must give up any claim to wages lost under the former HPO, and
negotiate a new, less lucrative contract with the new orchestra.
</I>
<P>
<I>The new orchestra will need rent relief at Hamilton Place,
and grants from all three level of governments, including Hamilton-
Wentworth region. But the region has already used this year's
orchestra grant to cover losses it sustained paying off the old
HPO's debts. </I>
<P>
<I>Even if every one of these conditions are met, the task force
believes a new orchestra cannot survive in the long-term, unless
it co-operates with other local orchestras to form a regional
philharmonic. And the co-chairmen suggest it may be necessary
for government agencies to force struggling orchestras to regionalize,
by making regional affiliations mandatory in order to qualify
for grant money. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Public Salaries</H3>

<P>
Have you ever wondered what some of the top administrators in
hospitals, colleges or city hall are paid? Well as of Sunday you
have the legal right to know. That's when Ontario's new public
sector salary disclosure act officially kicks in, but as Jamie
West discovered today many institutions have already released
their numbers.... 
<P>
<I>Since the cost of healthcare is one of the hottest topics in
the news lately let's begin there. In 1995 the Hamilton Civic
Hospitals (the Henderson and the General combined) had 27 people
on their payroll earning better than 100-thousand dollars. Topping
the list is Dr. David McCutcheon the President and CEO earning
just under 230-thousand dollars a year. Dr. M.H. Malik a nuclear
medicine specialist pulled in almost 176-thousand... and Dr. J.H.
Thornley a laboratory physician earned over 171-thousand dollars.
</I>
<P>
<I>Across town at Chedoke McMaster Hospitals the top salary went
to President and CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman at 281 thousand dollars.
Close behind is Dr. Sat Somers a radiologist with a salary of
over 269-thousand. Third on the list is Dr. Geoffrey Coates at
just over 244-thousand dollars a year. </I>
<P>
<I>On to McMaster University itself. In 1995 there were 82 people
earning over 100-thousand dollars a year. World renowned Dr. John
Bienenstock tops the list at nearly 207-thousand dollars a year.
President and Vice Chancellor Peter George earned 180-thousand,
while his predecessor Geraldine Kenney Wallace pulled in over
178 thousand dollars herself. </I>
<P>
<I>At Mohawk College one name appears on the list...the top man
himself Keith McIntyre...making just over 126-thousand dollars
last year. </I>
<P>
<I>And at City Hall there are seven people in the top category
starting with... Patrice Noe-Johnson at 128 thousand dollars a
year. Hamilton's Public Works Commissioner came in second at 118-thousand
dollars... and Hamilton CAO Joseph Pavelka earned over 117 thousand
dollars.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Suspect Suicide </H3>

<P>
A suspect who died in his St. Catharines police cell hours after
he was charged with attempted murder hanged himself using his
own belt. 
<P>
Ontario's Special Investigations Unit says autopsy results show
Donald Yacura, 43, died of asphyxiation. He was found hanging
in his cell Wednesday night. 
<P>
Yacura, a father of two who was separated from his wife and lived
in Hamilton, also had been charged with unlawful confinement.
He was caught fleeing from the home of a woman who managed to
call 911 Wednesday morning after being taken captive in her home.

<HR>

<H3>Heroine Bust </H3>

<P>
A joint two-month undercover investigation by Halton Police and
the RCMP has resulted in the arrest of a Burlington man. 
<P>
The operation began in January when a suspect on parole from a
Hamilton half-way house sold heroine to an undercover officer
at Burlington's Mapleview mall. Charged is: 48-year-old Vincenzo
James Pitaro. 
<HR>

<H3>Dope </H3>

<P>
Cayuga OPP have busted what they say was an elaborate hydroponic
marijuana-growing operation. 
<P>
Their raid on a rural York house netted more than 560 plants and
18 pounds of cannabis. Charged with a number of drug and weapons-related
offenses is 43 year old john Krywokulsky. 
<HR>

<H3>403 Rollover </H3>

<P>
A bit of a slow drive in for anyone traveling Highway 403 westbound
in Hamilton. A van flipped over near the Main Street West exit
during this morning's rush hour. Police say the female driver
was not seriously injured. 
<P>
Two lanes were blocked for a while as rescue crews moved the van
out of the way.
<HR>

<H3>Car Theft </H3>

<P>
Last year nearly 57-hundred vehicles were stolen in Hamilton Wentworth.
That's up 160 per cent over the previous three years, and many
of the cars stolen were used by teens for joyriding. 
<P>
It's the aim of this group of 15 federally funded students to
stop auto theft through prevention. Over the next seven months,
they'll be targeting high risk 12 to 17 year olds through a mentor
program, trying to convince them car theft is not a game. 
<HR>

<H3>Business-First</H3>

<P>
Canada's economy grew at a stronger rate than was expected during
January. That latest evidence of economic expansion in Canada
helped the dollar strengthen by more than a quarter of a penny
today. 
<P>
And Cara Foods, has agreed to buy controlling interest in Canada's
biggest specialty coffee shop chain. 
<P>

