<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 03/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, March 28, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Strike Over? 
<LI>Death in Custody 
<LI>Media Ban 
<LI>Access Crash 
<LI>Fortino's Update 
<LI>Man Found 
<LI>Strange Robber 
<LI>Grants Committee 
<LI>Civic Briefing 
<LI>Business-First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Strike Over?</H3>

<P>
Good evening. The four and a half week old civil service strike
could end tonight. That according to OPSEU President Leah Casselman
who says it's all but over now and a tentative agreement is only
hours away. 
<P>
Casselman says the only unresolved issue is the return to work
protocol. Thousands of jail guards, hospital workers and other
government employees have been manning the picket lines and tensions
mounted during a protest at Queen's Park today once again. but
the prospect of a tentative deal comes as welcome news to these
OPSEU members manning the line at the government building on King
Street West in Hamilton. 
<HR>

<H3>Death in Custody</H3>

<P>
The province's special investigations unit is probing the death
of a man while in the custody of the Niagara Regional Police service
last night. 
<P>
The man, 43 had been arrested earlier on charges of attempted
murder and unlawful confinement and was found unconscious in his
cell at 11 Division, St. Catharines. His identity has not been
released pending notification of next of kin. 
<P>
Yesterday, a man, aged 43 was arrested on the same charges after
a dramatic call to 9-1-1 from a Beamsville address. A woman was
heard crying and whimpering and the operator also heard a male
voice in the background. Police arrested a man after what they
are calling a very violent struggle that injured the officer and
the suspect. A woman was found unconscious lying a bed, bound
and gagged. Constable Donald Laing removed the duct tape and she
revived. 
<P>
Donald Yacura of Hamilton was charged and was to appear in court
this morning. police will not say if the incidents are related.

<HR>

<H3>Media Ban </H3>

<P>
A major disappointment for the families of Paul Bernardo's murder
victims Kristen French and Debbie Mahaffy. 
<P>
The Supreme Court of Canada has denied their request to take part
in a hearing on closed courtrooms. Justice Peter Cory said in
his ruling that he recognized the grief of the families of Kristen
French and Leslie Mahaffy. But he said hearing from the families
would not help the court. 
<P>
The case before the Supreme Court could have a wide affect on
the media's ability to report on sex-offense cases. 
<HR>

<H3>Access Crash </H3>

<P>
Police say alcohol was a factor in a serious crash on a Hamilton
mountain access last night. 
<P>
A car going up the Kenilworth access and a car doing down collided
head on around 9 o'clock. A passenger in the downbound car is
in serious condition, the driver is fair. The driver of the upbound
vehicle is in critical condition. 
<P>
The access was closed for three hours. charges are expected. 
<HR>

<H3>Fortino's Update </H3>

<P>
A large west Hamilton supermarket is back in business, a day after
an explosion and fire caused 600-thousand dollars damage. 
<P>
A group of about 50 Fortino's workers spent the night tossing
out food contaminated by smoke, and cleaning every inch of their
store at the Dundurn Plaza. They were still doing a few last minute
clean ups moments before the store reopened this morning. A propane
cylinder is believed to have touched off the explosion. 
<HR>

<H3>Man Found </H3>

<P>
A Burlington man reported missing earlier this week is back home
safe and sound. 
<P>
20-year-old Jeremy Jones had left home on his bicycle Saturday
morning and hadn't been heard from since. Well a Toronto police
officer recognized Jeremy from a missing person poster. It seems
his bicycle had been stolen and he was unable to get back to Burlington.

<P>
Jeremy requires several types of medication and there were fears
for his health and safety. 
<HR>

<H3>Strange Robber </H3>

<P>
Police can't explain it, but they're thankful a robber in Thorold
gave them advance warning early today. Investigators say the man
walked into a doughnut shop, pulled out a big knife, and told
the clerk to call police because she was being robbed. She did,
and the cops arrested the suspect just outside the store. 
<HR>

<H3>Grants Committee </H3>

<P>
From the Wesley Drop-in Centre, to women's waterpolo... fifty
groups and organizations will share 234-thousand dollars in grants
approved by Hamilton City Council today. 
<P>
That's well short of the million-dollars worth of grants requested.
But the combination of provincial cutbacks and a city tax freeze
left the grants budget about thirty-thousand dollars lower than
last year. 
<HR>

<H3>Civic Briefing </H3>

<P>
After all the controversy over the Hamilton Health Task Force
Report, another hospital committee is looking for public input.

<P>
The Transition Committee of Chedoke McMaster and Hamilton Civic
Hospitals was set up before the task force report was released,
and it looking at merging their facilities into one hospital with
one board and one chief executive officer. Annette Hamm reports.

<P>
<I>The Transition Committee has been working towards merging Chedoke
McMaster and Hamilton Civic Hospitals since late last year. Now
they're updating the public on the where they stand. </I>
<P>
<I>By this time next year, Chedoke McMaster and the civics will
be one, creating one of Canada's largest hospitals. Joining forces
will help both boards use shrinking health care and research dollars
more effectively. Only one CEO will run the merged hospitals,
and buying power for supplies could be increased. </I>
<P>
<I>The Transition Committee is leaving budget issues and staffing
problems to the new, as yet unnamed hospital. It's not touching
any issues arising from the task force report, namely the suggestion
that the Sisters of St. Joseph take control of the Henderson Hospital
from the Civics board. The committees only concern is making the
merger of the Hamilton Civic and Chedoke McMaster hospitals a
reality.</I>
<P>
<I>The transition committee hopes to make its recommendations
by June, and have the merger complete by December. If you have
any questions or ideas you can call the merger hotline at area
code 905, 527-3545, or you can fax the committee at 905, 577-8025.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Business-First </H3>

<P>
Hamilton steel maker Dofasco says it will add eleven to 13 million
dollars of gross income to its balance sheet in the first quarter
of this year. The newfound money is recovered from deposits on
anti dumping duties paid to the united states. 


<P>

