<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 03/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, March 27, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Court - Bomb 
<LI>Fortino's Blast 
<LI>Sulphur Springs Fire 
<LI>B &amp; E Warning 
<LI>Johnson - Demo 
<LI>Nia. School Layoffs 
<LI>Halton Budget 
<LI>Kay's - Ti-cats 
<LI>Agostino No Run
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Court - Bomb</H3>

<P>
Good evening. Police have determined a suspicious package found
in the downtown Hamilton Provincial Courthouse is a bomb. Main
Street East is closed this hour between John and Walnut. 
<P>
<I>It was around ten thirty in the morning ... when a call came
into the regional clerk's office ... the result ... chaos on main
street. </I>
<P>
<I>The main artery of the city was blocked by police barricades;
and traffic slowed to a crawl. The Provincial Courthouse was evacuated
... and some 30 prisoners who had business before the court; were
removed; remanded, and returned to jail. </I>
<P>
<I>Anxious OPSEU workers ... picketing on the street, looked on
in dismay... many believing that they would be blamed for the
incident. </I>
<P>
<I>Police meanwhile, working on the assumption that they were
looking for three bombs rolled in the bomb squad... and specially
trained officers searched the courts; eventually turning up one
suspicious package in the men's washroom, on the second floor.
That discovery prompted police to begin the cautious, and time
consuming ritual; of remote robotic retrieval.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Fortino's Blast </H3>

<P>
The structural damage is relatively minor, but the food losses
are huge after an explosion and fire at a Fortino's supermarket
in west Hamilton overnight. As Annette Hamm tells us, close to
half a million dollars in perishable goods may have to be thrown
out before the store reopens tomorrow. 
<P>
<I>Marsha Mino won't be getting her groceries at Fortino's today.
Her supermarket with a heart is covered with a thin veil of soot.
</I>
<P>
<I>Five workers were stocking shelves overnight when they heard
a blast at the back of the store. they made it out safely after
calling the fire department. </I>
<P>
<I>A year ago, 2-and-a half million dollars were poured into this
store, making it the first Fortino's superstore in the chain.
Now they'll spend 300 to 500-thousand dollars to replace damaged
goods. </I>
<P>
<I>The Environmental Health Branch Director has ordered all produce,
dairy and bulk products and some grocery items to be disposed
of because of smoke damage. </I>
<P>
<I>A store official won't tell us how much closing for the day
will cost him, but stresses he worries more about inconvenienced
customers than lost sales.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Sulphur Springs Fire </H3>

<P>
An investigator with the Fire Marshall's Office is probing a fire
at an empty house in Ancaster last night. 
<P>
Arson is believed to be the cause. The two story wooden home was
partially gutted, and damage is estimated at 60-thousand dollars.

<HR>

<H3>B &amp; E Warning</H3>

<P>
After a series of similar break-ins on Hamilton's west mountain,
police are warning residents to make sure their doors and windows
are locked, even when they are home. 
<P>
In the past month, there have been 9 break-ins in a neighbourhood
near Upper Paradise and two more in the scenic woods subdivision.
The thieves get in through doors or windows, usually while the
homeowners are sleeping, and grab electronics and cash. 
<HR>

<H3>Johnson - Demo </H3>

<P>
He's become one Hamilton Wentworth region's most controversial
figures, and today, Health Action Task Force chairman Dr. Ray
Johnson spoke publicly about his groups report for the first time
since it's release three weeks ago. 
<P>
As Jamie West reports, Johnson had a welcoming committee that
included a number of angry healthcare workers.... 
<P>
<I>This was about all the applause ray Johnson could muster during
his lunchtime presentation to members of McMaster University's
Alumni Association. </I>
<P>
<I>Johnson spent twenty minutes reviewing the process and recommendations
contained in the Health Action Task Force report ....among them
the closure of St. Joseph's Hospital and the Hamilton Psychiatric
Hospital. </I>
<P>
<I>CUPE took the opportunity to feast on what they see as the
report's lack of credibility... demanding more time for union
and public input ... other stakeholders like St. Joseph's board
member Gordon Dean kept up the heat... afterward Johnson said
the task force is willing to talk to labour groups separately,
but an open forum is out...</I>
<HR>

<H3>Nia. School Layoffs </H3>

<P>
Government cuts to education taking their toll in Niagara. More
than five hundred employees at two Niagara school boards have
become the latest to receive layoff notices. 
<P>
Two hundred, seventy seven staff including 205 teachers will be
laid off in the Lincoln County Board of Education. And at the
Niagara South Board of Education 250 layoff notices have been
sent out. Affecting 218 teaching positions. 
<HR>

<H3>Halton Budget </H3>

<P>
Despite government cutbacks, there will be no increase in taxes
for Halton homeowners. 
<P>
Regional Council approved the 1996 budget today, resulting in
a 0.6 percent decrease in property taxes. Regional Chairman Joyce
Savoline noted this is the third consecutive year that Halton
has approved a budget without a tax boost. 
<HR>

<H3>Kay's - Ti-Cats</H3>

<P>
Has Kay's given up? The courtroom battles between the Hamilton
Tiger Cats, and Kay's Authentic Concessions ... have been put
on hold, temporarily. 
<P>
The Cats changed the locks at Ivor Wynne Stadium yesterday; in
a bid to keep the current concession holder out of the kitchens.
An informal meeting with Mr. Justice David crane yesterday, did
not produce an order to remove the new locks. 
<P>
Kay's president Jon Raffay has now instructed his lawyers not
to proceed with any further legal efforts in regard to the matter.
The reasons behind the request are not clear.
<HR>

<H3>Agostino No Run </H3>

<P>
Hamilton East MPP Dominic Agostino announced today that he will
not run for the leadership of the Ontario Liberal Party. 
<P>
There had been strong speculation that the Hamilton Liberal would
run. But he says he decided it was not the right time for him.


<P>

