<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 03/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, March 26, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Marrow-No Transplant 
<LI>Kidney Man 
<LI>Oakville Drown Follow 
<LI>St. Kitts Killing 
<LI>School Arson 
<LI>Red Hill Squabble 
<LI>403 Limberlost 
<LI>Burl-Krantz Reaction 
<LI>Burl-Mulvale Reaction 
<LI>HW Budget 
<LI>Halton Ed Cuts 
<LI>Kays - Cats 
<LI>Stelco Contract 
<LI>Niagara Accidents 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Marrow-No Transplant </H3>

<P>
Good evening. Quality of life and life itself hang in the balance
for two southern Ontario residents tonight. We begin with a 4-year-old
Welland boy. 
<P>
Damon Albanese has a rare bone disorder. He's had two bone marrow
transplants that both failed. Because of the failure rate, OHIP
is reluctant to pay for another. Now Damon's parents are appealing
for the public to help save the life of their son. Lauran Sabourin
reports. 
<P>
<I>Damon Albanese lies in a bed at children's hospital getting
another blood transfusion. Treatment to keep this very ill child
alive until he can get another bone marrow transplant. </I>
<P>
<I>Damon suffers from a disorder called osteo petrosis. A rare
bone disease. So rare that Damon's is the first case of osteo
petrosis doctors at Children's Hospital have ever seen. Damon's
only hope is a successful bone marrow transplant. </I>
<P>
<I>Two previous transplants have failed. OHIP is reluctant to
pay for another costly procedure. Doctors in Chicago are willing
to do the transplant. a procedure that will cost Damon's family
160 thousand dollars. </I>
<P>
Anyone wishing to help the family can make a donation to the Damon
Albanese fund at any branch of the bank of nova Scotia. account
number 75787. 
<HR>

<H3>Kidney Man </H3>

<P>
And now David's story. 
<P>
David Boyle of Dundas is one of 187 people waiting for a kidney
transplant in Hamilton alone. March is kidney month and David
is hoping his battle will help raise awareness of kidney disease.
Jamie West reports. 
<P>
<I>That's how 31 year old David Boyle describes the sad ending
to his first kidney transplant, seven years after his mother gave
up one of her own kidney's to save her son. </I>
<P>
<I>The twist's of fate for David have been somewhat cruel, especially
when he and Kim discovered that her kidney was a possible match...
the test results continue to go against them... but despite the
ups and down's they remain positive ...and hope to have a child
in the near future. </I>
<P>
<I>David spends four hours a day Monday Wednesday and Friday hooked
up to a dialysis machine... the only permanent solution to David's
kidney failure, is another transplant, but organs are in short
supply... in Hamilton Jamie West Channel Eleven News.</I> 
<P>
You can make your organ donation wishes known simply by filling
out the back of your driver's license, and if you do it's legally
important that you tell your family what your wishes are. 
<HR>

<H3>Oakville Drown Follow </H3>

<P>
A 19-year-old Brampton man is very much alive and in police custody
in Oakville tonight, following a lengthy police search around
Six Mile Creek. 
<P>
He had been pursued as a suspect in a rash of house break-ins
and ended up in the creek as a result. Police feared he had drowned.
But this afternoon, Rodney Ryan turned himself in at Halton Regional
Police 20 Division headquarters. 
<P>
Charges against him are still pending. Two other suspects have
been charged in connection with the same series of incidents,
a 16-year-old youth and 18 year-old Michael Vanier of Oakville.
They face two counts each of break and enter and breach of probation.

<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Killing</H3>

<P>
A St. Catharines woman has been charged in Niagara Region's fifth
homicide of the year. 58-year-old Emmannuel Rodrigue of Welland
was found shot in the neck in a Keele Street St. Catharines home
last night. 
<P>
Police say the shooting occurred after a heated argument. 30-year-old
carol Patricia Andrews is facing a charge of second degree murder.

<HR>

<H3>School Arson </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Fire Marshall's Office on the scene today of an overnight
fire at Cardinal Newman High School in east Hamilton. And it looks
like it's arson. 
<P>
A school caretaker heard an alarm shortly before 11 last night,
and spotted two males running across Centennial Parkway. The fire
caused 2-thousand dollars damage. 
<P>
And a few hours earlier ... crews were putting out a small fire
at the construction site of the new Saltfleet High School in Stoney
Creek. It's believed overheated roofing tar may have started that
fire. 
<HR>

<H3>Red Hill Squabble</H3>

<P>
Meetings continue at Queen's Park this hour between Transportation
Minister Al Palladini and Hamilton- Wentworth Chairman Terry Cooke
staff. 
<P>
It's all over the Red Hill Expressway bill. The minister denies
that he is going back on his word. Last Thursday he agreed to
a third party independent review of the funding dispute. 
<P>
The region says it will cost an additional 50-million dollars.
Palladini says those figures are wrong. Earlier today, in the
legislature, Hamilton east liberal MPP Dominic Agostino accused
the minister of short-changing the region. 
<HR>

<H3>403 Limberlost </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the 403 extension between Ancaster and Brantford is
rolling along. A lawyer representing residents of the Limberlost
subdivision of Ancaster has withdrawn a request for a legal hearing
to fight the expropriation of some of their land. 
<P>
The property is needed to build a critical overpass near shaver
road. There's no official word on why the seventeen residents
have given up the fight, but Brantford MPP Ron Johnson says he's
thrilled that the project can now proceed. 
<HR>

<H3>Burl-Krantz Reaction </H3>

<P>
As expected, Burlington City Council has rejected the notion of
joining the greater Toronto area. Instead, council will tell the
province it wants to stay in a restructured Halton region. At
least one other Halton mayor is willing to investigate that option.

<HR>

<H3>Burl-Mulvale Reaction </H3>

<P>
But another Halton Mayor says it's too soon for her town to turn
its back on the GTA. Oakville Mayor Anne Mulvale first wants to
see how the province responds to the golden report that recommends
reforming the GTA. 
<P>
Mulvale also wants a dollars-and-cents assessment of the costs,
and benefits, of joining the GTA. Municipal Affairs Minister Al
Leach has indicated he hopes to introduce recommendations for
GTA reform by the middle of next month.
<HR>

<H3>HW Budget </H3>

<P>
It's unlikely that Hamilton- Wentworth council can come up with
a zero percent tax increase this year. Politicians agreed to another
round of cuts this afternoon, bringing the increase down below
two percent - or about ten dollars for the average homeowner.

<P>
Plans to hire 25 new police officers would have to be deferred
for another year. A proposed five dollar fee for taking garbage
to the dump was trashed. There are still a few more cuts to be
debated before the final budget is set - probably next week. 
<HR>

<H3>Halton Ed Cuts </H3>

<P>
good news for some teachers tonight. of the nearly 6-hundred who
received layoff notices from the Halton board last month, 325
will keep their jobs. that's because the province's educational
tool kit doesn't allow the board to reduce teacher planning time.
but now, faced with a 16 million dollar shortfall in funding,
the board is looking at a potential mill rate increase of 7-point-6-4
per cent.
<HR>

<H3>Kays - Cats </H3>

<P>
When one partner in a troubled relationship decides to change
the locks, it's a clear signal the relationship is over. And that's
exactly the signal the Hamilton Tiger-Cats intended to send today,
when they changed the locks on all the concession stands at Ivor
Wynne Stadium. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>The Hamilton Tiger-Cats and Kay's Authentic Concessions each
claims the other owes it hundreds of thousands of dollars, and
it's now up to the courts to decide which one is right. But that's
not the only reason the Ticats decided to lock Kay's out of Ivor
Wynne Stadium. </I>
<P>
<I>But Kay's lawyer says he'll be back in court with an application
for injunctive relief before the week is out. With the Tiger-Cats
first pre-season home game less than three months away, the football
team says it will start looking for a new concessionaire, while
the legal spat with Kay's plays out before the courts. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Deborah Walker, Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Stelco Contract </H3>

<P>
Members of steelworkers local 1005 will vote a week from today
on an early contract offer that provides no wage increases, but
does offer significant improvements to Stelco's pension and income-sharing
plans. 
<P>
Five-thousand unionized employees at Hamilton's Hilton Works are
eligible to vote on the six-year contract. If accepted, pension
benefits would increase by twenty-five per cent, effective august
first of this year. Additional increases over the life of the
contract would raise pension income forty-one per cent by the
year 2001. 
<P>
The contract offer also provides improvements to benefits and
vacation scheduling, and would eliminate all combo jobs within
a year of ratification. The union executive unanimously recommends
acceptance of the contract. 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Accidents </H3>

<P>
Bad weather forced provincial police to close the Fort Erie bound
Queen Elizabeth Way for about an hour this morning. In the most
serious accident near Niagara Falls, two people were hurt. 
<P>
Ministry of Transportation employees, responsible for keeping
the highways clear, are on strike. 

<P>

