<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 03/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, March 25, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Highway Six Latest 
<LI>Red Hill Options 
<LI>Teacher Grievance 
<LI>Burl. Missing 
<LI>Drug Charges 
<LI>Lakeport-Sesqui.
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Highway Six Latest</H3>

<P>
Good evening. 
<P>
It's been a weekend of highway carnage. Accidents on Ontario roadways
have claimed fourteen lives since Friday night. 
<P>
The largest single crash occurred on early Saturday morning, on
highway six north near the village of Millgrove. Annette Hamm
tells us that fatal crash has fueled yet another look at safety
on highway six. 
<P>
<I>This head on crash early Saturday morning killed 23 year old
Frank Nicolazzo of Ancaster and four Guelph residents. It's one
of the worst single crashes on a highway infamous for accidents.
</I>
<P>
<I>Chris Rose knows the dangers of six ... he lives on one side
of the highway and works on the other. </I>
<P>
<I>Getting drivers to slow down is one way of preventing crashes,
but the trauma prevention council is also calling for engineering
changes. one change being pushed for by residents along the highway
is a stoplight near the village of Millgrove. A stoplight, they
say, would leave a gap in traffic flow allowing drivers to turn
left on or off the highway. </I>
<P>
<I>It is hoped with this latest fatal crash on highway six, the
ministry of transportation will seriously consider putting the
stoplight in. </I>
<P>
<I>Near Flamborough, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Red Hill Options </H3>

<P>
And another controversial highway in the news tonight but this
one isn't even built yet. 
<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth's Chairman hopes to resolve a funding feud
with the province, when he meets with transportation minister
Al Palladini tomorrow to discuss the Red Hill Creek Expressway.

<P>
The province and the region are at odds over the total bill for
the freeway, and over who should pay for what. And as Deborah
walker reports, some councilors are miffed with Palladini's suggestion
the region has inflated its cost projections. 
<P>
<I>Three years ago this month, Conservative leader Mike Harris
met with Hamilton- Wentworth's Citizens' Expressway Committee,
and made a promise. But once elected, the Harris government allocated
100-million dollars to the Red Hill Creek Expressway, only half
of what Hamilton- Wentworth would have received under the original
provincial funding agreement. And the Tories want the region to
pay the cost of linking the expressway to the QEW at the Centennial
Parkway interchange. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton- Wentworth's Chairman believes Transportation Minister
Al Palladini will commit more money to the expressway, if an independent
review confirms the region's cost estimates. </I>
<P>
<I>Whether or not the province pays up, Hamilton- Wentworth region
will consider soliciting private bids to build the expressway,
in order to speed up construction of the north-south leg of the
freeway. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Deborah walker, Channel Eleven News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Teacher Grievance </H3>

<P>
The union representing Hamilton public high school teachers has
launched a labour grievance over layoff notices recently sent
out by the school board. 
<P>
More than 200 high school teachers were pink slip recipients...
but OSSTF District 8 President Doug Robb, says the step-by-step
collective agreement process was not followed. 
<H3>Teacher Tag </H3>

<P>
The Hamilton Board of Education, meanwhile, insists that there
was no violation of the collective agreement in sending out layoff
notices. 
<HR>

<H3>Burl. Missing </H3>

<P>
Halton Regional Police have issued an alert for a young Burlington
man who went missing over the weekend. 
<P>
20 year old Jeremy Jones left on a bike ride around 9 a-m on Saturday,
and hasn't been heard from since. He's been on long cycling treks
before, riding in secluded areas, but has never been gone overnight.

<P>
Jones needs several types of medication, which he did not take
with him. 
<P>
Jeremy Jones stands about 5-10, weighs 185 pounds and was last
seen wearing black track clothing with a faded brown leather jacket.
he was riding a black 12 speed racing bike with yellow paint splashed
all over it. 
<HR>

<H3>Drug Charges</H3>

<P>
A Milton man is facing drugs and weapons charges tonight, after
a police raid on a Guelph line home netted another hydroponic
lab and marijuana plants, along with two firearms. 
<P>
The seizure is estimated to be worth 150-thousand dollars. 43-year-old
Thomas Patrick Button has a court date next month. 
<P>
And two Burlington residents are facing narcotics charges after
police confiscated crack cocaine and drug paraphernalia from a
Ghent Avenue Burlington home over the weekend. Charged are 57-year-old
Patrick Walsh and 34-year-old Hayden Nelson. An Elmvale resident
was also charged. 
<HR>

<H3>Lakeport-Sesqui.</H3>

<P>
A Hamilton brewery has brewed up a plan to publicize the city's
sesquicentennial celebrations. 
<P>
Lakeport Brewing Corporation has unveiled a sesquicentennial label
which will be applied to the neck of Laker Premium Lager bottles.

<HR>

<H3>Business-first </H3>

<P>
Canadian interest rates in bond markets opened the week moving
lower while stock prices rose. Financial markets are focused on
tomorrow's policy committee meeting of the American central bank
which will decide what to do with US interest rates. 
<P>

