<HEAD>

<TITLE>Planning Circle Financial Group: Mackenzie: A Proven Investment Strategy</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="images/pcfgbkgd.jpg">

<A HREF="../pcfg/"><IMG SRC="images/pcfgsm.gif" ALT="Return to the Planning Circle Financial Group Home Page" WIDTH=75 HEIGHT=71 BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT></A>

<P>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>A Proven Investment Strategy</H1>
<P>
In the world of professional money management, there
are many different styles. And styles can change. They can be
popular one day and not the next. So it's reassuring to many investors
that Mackenzie has just one basic strategy and two complimentary
approaches, none of which will ever go out of fashion.<BR>
<P>
For The Industrial Group of Funds, Mackenzie managers
follow what can best be described as a &quot;top-down&quot; stock
selection approach. That is, they review the short and long-term
outlook for the Canadian economy and, based on this analysis,
choose specific market sectors that offer the promise of better
performance. From there, individual securities are selected, based
on detailed research and the likelihood that the market will ultimately
value them more highly. The same process is taken by the managers
of Universal Canadian Equity Fund and Universal Canadian Resource
Fund.<BR>
<P>
For the Ivy Funds, Mackenzie managers take a &quot;bottom-up&quot;
approach, starting with an in-depth, fundamental analysis of promising
companies. When value is identified, the Ivy managers assess industry-specific
and economic considerations before investing. <BR>
<P>
Across the board, Mackenzie managers take an  independent
view of the world and constantly question conventional wisdom.
 They identify and buy undervalued securities that represent good
value and sell those that may be over-priced and facing decline.
 And they share the full resources of Mackenzie, including research,
ideas and access to our international investment advisors.  Overall,
the long-term objective for every one of our equity portfolios
is the same: to maximize total return and protect invested capital.
 Which approach is right for you?  Past performance indicates
that you are in good hands with either, or both, over the long
term.<BR>
<P>
But by investing in each of these complimentary fund
families, you build in additional diversification and the potential
for greater growth.

<P>
<HR>
