</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Planning Circle Financial Group: Star Registered Conservative Income & Growth Portfolio</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="images/pcfgbkgd.jpg">

<A HREF="../pcfg/"><IMG SRC="images/pcfgsm.gif" ALT="Return to the Planning Circle Financial Group Home Page" WIDTH=75 HEIGHT=71 BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT></A>


<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Mackenzie</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>A Stellar RRSP Performance:</H2>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Star Registered Conservative Income &amp; Growth Portfolio</H2>

<P>
According to Gordon Garmaise investing is more than just an art-it
is an art that can be measurably improved by science.  Since 1977,
in conjunction with major Canadian trust companies and Wilshire
Associates of Los Angeles, Garmaise Investment Technologies has
measured the performance of over 1,000 Canadian pension portfolios
worth over $60 billion.
<P>
Given his almost two decades of experience gathering and analyzing
historical portfolio performance data, it's only natural that
certain observations would have been honed to a razor's sharpness.
<P>
To begin, it's proven very difficult to find portfolio managers
who are consistently able to outperform the market.  The market
is remarkable for its capacity to elude even the most sophisticated
efforts to time it in advance.
<P>
Second, recent research has indicated that approximately 90 per
cent of any individual's investment return will be determined
by their long-term strategic asset allocation.  In plain language,
this means it is important to select the best combination among
various investment assets.  There are four major asset classes:
equities, fixed income, cash, and precious metals.
<P>
Mackenzie secured the talents of Garmaise Investment Technologies
to offer Canadian investors a financial product-the STAR Strategic
Asset Allocation Service-that concentrates on more efficiently
diversifying their mutual fund portfolios in light of how markets
are actually behaving.  The idea is to minimize unnecessary investment
risk.  By setting the focus on long-term performance, once can
largely avoid the inevitable disappointments that accompany market
timing.
<P>
<I><B>Strategic Asset Allocation</B></I>
<P>
The process begins with a simple, yet comprehensive questionaire,
that allows us to discover a more accurate profile of your tolerance
for risk.  This accomplished, risk is controlled by efficiently
diversifying your holdings in a portfolio of up to 7 mutual funds.
 These are scientifically combined according to asset class, geographic
region, how all 7 fund correlate with one another over time, and
the investment style of each fund manager.
<P>
The value of this investment approach is quickly becoming less
academic, and more a matter of record.
<P>
The chart below illustrates what even the most rick-adverse RRSP
investor would have been able to achieve since January of 1995,
using the strategic asset allocation approach of STAR, in the
Registered Conservative Income &amp; Growth portfolio.  This portfolio
emphasizes both predictable income flow and protection of capital.
 It is designed for investors with moderate tolerance for volatility
in year-to-year returns.
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="images/star1.jpg">
</CENTER>
<P>
The heavy line traces how STAR smoothed out the more volatile
paths of the 7 underlying Mackenzie funds over the course of the
past year.  More importantly, the conservative portfolio's first
year demonstrates that by learning to live more in harmony with
the market's own rhythms you can substantially lessen risk without
compromising returns beyond repair.  While performance will certainly
vary in the future, the rather generous return for those invested
in this portfolio throughout the year was 15.8%.
<P>
For investors who are comparison shopping, these results are bound
to be eye-opening.  If you want more information about STAR, please
talk to your financial advisor.  By putting together the most
modern thinking with leading-edge technology, they can help you
to improve the performance of your RRSP investment.


<P>
