<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, December 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Local Governance    
    <li>Doctors Dispute     
    <li>CAI Negotiations    
    <li>Baby Death          
    <li>Bernardo 
    <li>Tobacco Rush 
    <li>Best Cars           
    <li>Chanticleer         
    <li>Hanukkah 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Local Governance</b><p>
A provincial committee is recommending that the Harris government do away with the five regions in the greater Toronto area and replace them with a super city structure.<br>   Bob Ireland has the story from queens park.
<i><br>  The chair of the "who does what" panel, David Crombie, is suggesting that regional governments in the GTA be scrapped, and that city's in Halton such as Burlington and Oakville, and Mississauga and Brampton in Peel, and the Durham Region east of Toronto, be merged with metro Toronto into a greater Toronto services board. Membership in the new government structure would be based on population..the new supercity would be responsible for regional roads, waste management, sewer and water, police board co-ordination, as well as infastructure and social planning. But it would have no direct taxing authority. <br> Crombie says regardless of what amalgamations take place, communities will still be able to retain their local identities. <br>  The report also gives options for amalgamation of Toronto and its five metro cities. It suggests either one mega city, or have Toronto absorb the cities of York and East York, leaving the other larger metro partners alone. Toronto mayor Barbara Hall is against the one mega city concept. <br>  But Anne Golden, the original author of the GTA government concept says amalgamation is the wave of the future. </i>
<hr>
<b>Doctors Dispute</b><p>
The next few days are expected to be critical in the provincial doctors' dispute.<br>   Negotiators for the Ontario Medical Association and the province are talking today and tomorrow in Toronto.<br>   The exact location isn't being disclosed.<br>   OMA president Dr. Gerry Rowland says they hope to have something worked out this weekend.
<hr>
<b>CAI Negotiations</b><p>
It looks like an agreement might be close on the restructuring plan for Canadian Airlines International.<br>   Transport minister David Anderson says Canadian and holdout union leader Buzz Hargrove have resolved most of their difficulties.<br>   In Toronto, Hargrove also notes some progress on the issues but says there's still no deal yet.
<hr>
<b>Baby Death</b><p>
Provincial police are investigating the discovery of the body of a male infant, found on a side road in Delhi Township.<br>   A post mortem is being performed to determined the cause of death.<br>   Police say they're attempting to gather information on the baby and try to locate the mother.<br>   They're asking anyone with any information in the case to get in touch with them.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo </b><p>
Paul Bernardo is nursing a black eye and a cut cheek.<br>   The convicted sex-killer was punched in the face today by another inmate at Kingston Penitentiary.<br>   He was being escorted to his cell after taking a shower when the attack occurred.<br>   Bernardo is serving life for abducting, raping and killing southern Ontario teenagers Leslie Mahaffy and Kristen French.
<hr>
<b>Tobacco Rush </b><p>
Health minister David Dingwall is defending his anti-smoking legislation, saying tobacco company money is not such a big factor in supporting the arts.<br>   He's told a committee studying the legislation that the amount of money the industry gives to the arts has been overblown.<br>   His legislation would put strict limits on tobacco company sponsorship of sports and arts events.
<hr>
<b>Best Cars</b><p>
Looking for the perfect gift for that special someone this Christmas...<br>  how about a car.<br>  As Dwight Ryan reports, ...a German sports coupe has been named the best car of the year by a group of auto industry reporters.<br>  The one catch ... its costly. <br>  
<i><br>  Foreign cars sales are again on the rise. And the best of the bunch is the BMW M3.  That's according to the Automotive Journalists Association of Canada.<br>  For four days, the association members put 112 vehicles through their paces looking at them from every angle to determine the best...  <br>  The Ford Motor Company came up with the most winners coming in first in four categories.<br>  The Escort topped both the economy car and station wagon sections.  As well the Ford F150 was the best pickup, and the new expedition topped the enormously popular sport utility vehicle category.<br>  Other favourites of the journalists included the new Cadillac Catera as the best luxury car, the Mercedes Benz E420 in the prestige group. Hyundai's new Tiburon topped the sports coupe and convertible section..and the just introduced Chevrolet Venture was the best minivan.<br>  The awards were presented in Toronto. <br>  A suitably equipped BMW M3 sells for about 62 thousand dollars.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Chanticleer</b><p>
Chanticleer, the only full-time classical vocal ensemble in North America, has developed a remarkable reputation for its interpretation of vocal literature, from long-ago music to jazz and gospel.<br>  Alex Reynolds says this "orchestra of voices" will celebrate Christmas at the Ford Centre in North York tonight.
<i> <br>  The group takes it name from "Chanticleer," the rooster in Chaucer's "Canterbury Tales," although the word comes from a medieval French story ....meaning to sing clearly. <br>  The twelve men celebrated for a seamless sound ranging from bass to countertenor voices, visit the North York Recital Hall tonight.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Hanukkah </b><p>
This year, the tradition of Hanukkah is being discoveredby some Jewish immigrants.<br>  For them, the holiday means a time to celebrate their long-lost heritage.. and their new-found freedom.<br>  







<P>
