<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, December 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Specialists Protest 
    <li>Canadian - CAW
    <li>Toronto Supercity   
    <li>QP Thurs.           
    <li>Bank Protest        
    <li>Shuttle a Day       
    <li>Sabbath Holy War    
    <li>Hanukkah Netanyahu  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Specialists Protest</b><p>
The deadline looms in less than 24 hours.<br>   But the Ontario Medical Association says it's confident of a settlement in the doctors dispute with the province.<br>   A coalition of medical specialists is calling for a province-wide closure of all their members' offices, beginning next Friday.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Canadian - CAW</b><p>
CAW chief Buzz Hargove still hopes there can be a negotiated settlement to his union's dispute with Canadian Airlines.<br>  The federal government has ordered CAW members to vote on a restructuring plan that would result in another pay cut.<br>  The union is opposed to the vote but says it won't take it to court.<br>    The unprecedented move by the feds, to get the union members to vote, has many in the Canadian labour movement uneasy.<br>  Dwight Ryan has the story. <br>  
<i><br>  Canadian Airlines workers who are members of the Canadian Auto Workers union are clearly upset at their leader, Buzz Hargrove.<br>  Hargrove has steadfastly refused to let his members vote on a deal that would again see workers taking a pay cut.  But the workers want to vote.<br>  He says the government must put more money into the pot to save the airline and the jobs ...and that the airline industry must again be regulated..   <br>   But, in an unprecedented move, the federal government says the workers will vote, and soon.  <br>    Wayne Marston heads up the Hamilton and District Labour Council.   <br>    CAW representatives are still meeting with airline officials in an attempt to come up with a negotiated settlement.<br>  In another news conference a short time ago, Buzz Hargrove said no settlement to the issue is imminent.<br>  But, time is running out.  <br>    </i>
<hr>
<b>Toronto Supercity</b><p>
Tomorrow the government's "who does what" panel will announce its plans for re-structuring metro Toronto and its four outlying regions.<br>   A leaked document says one recommendation will be to  get rid of metro and the regions and have a GTA wide commission made up of metro mayors and representation from major cities in Halton, Peel and Durham regions.<br>  Municipal affairs minister Al Leach says he favors folding Toronto and its five metro cities into one super city.
<hr>
<b>QP Thurs.</b><p>
It looks like the Canadian-led military aid mission to central Africa is off.<br>   Defence minister Doug Young also says it's unlikely any airdrops are going to be required.<br>   Young says a large, new movement of up to 400-thousand Rwandan refugees returning home from Zaire and Tanzania all but eliminates the need for a military mission.<br>   And he adds history will smile on Canada for its role in the crisis.
<hr>
<b>Bank Protest</b><p>
On a day when more banks announced record profits, two groups spoke up, saying there needs to be more oversight of banks.<br>  The Council for Canadians staged a demonstration outside the Royal Bank.<br>  They were protesting what they consider excess bank profits.<br>  Protesters say in a world of unemployment and poverty, profits like these shouldn't be allowed.
<hr>
<b>Shuttle a Day</b><p>
The crew of the Shuttle Columbia.. will get yet another day in space.. after all.<br>  Cloudy weather over Florida's Cape Canaveral.. put this morning's scheduled landing on hold.<br>   The original landing had been set for Friday, but NASA moved it up a day.. because of a naviational system problem.. and the threat of bad weather at Kennedy Space Center.        <br>   NASA considered having Columbia land.. at Edwards Air Force Base in California, but that was scratched as well.<br>   The delay will make Columbia's 17 day mission.. the second longest shuttle flight ever.
<hr>
<b>Sabbath Holy War</b><p>
Israel is having trouble with its neighbors... but there are growing religious problems inside the country.<br>  It's a problem with the bible and how it's to be interpreted.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Hanukkah Netanyahu</b><p>
With his wife, Sarah, and two sons at his side, Isreali prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu took time out today for the ceremonial lighting of the hanukkah candle.<br>  The prime minister appeared relaxed as he held his youngest son.<br>   His wife stood next to him with their oldest boy. Ushering in the hanukkah holiday, israelis lit the first of eight candles today, in commemoration of a victory over the syrians two thousand years ago.







<P>
