<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, December 4, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Canadian Extra      
    <li>Pricey Consultants  
    <li>Harris - 407          
    <li>Doctors Protest     
    <li>Yugo / Milosovic      
    <li>Paris Bomb          
    <li>Jane Eyre 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Canadian Extra</b><p>
The Canadian Auto Workers Union plans to go to court to challenge a federal order to hold a vote on the restructuring plan for Canadian Airlines.<br>   CAW president Buzz Hargrove says the union is seeking legal advice on the matter.<br>     In the house of commons earlier today, labor minister Alfonso Gagliano moved to force a vote by Hargrove's union on the restructuring plan.<br>   Gagliano says 16-thousand jobs are at stake.<br>   And he says he expects the vote to be held within days.
<hr>
<b>Pricey Consultants</b><p>
Provincial politicians will be working overtime this winter.<br>   Premier Mike Harris has called a "special session" of the Ontario legislature to deal with government restructuring.<br>  Part of that restructuring will include hiring outside consultants at up to 26-hundred dollars a day, to figure out how to get rid of 13 thousand civil servants.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Harris - 407</b><p>
The new highway 4-0-7 may be the most expensive toll road in North America.<br>   Rush-hour commuters could pay as much as 22-hundred dollars a year if they were to drive the entire length of the expressway daily.<br>  The Ontario Trucking Association says the toll road will be too costly for truckers to use.<br>   But premier Mike Harris says because it is convenient, he expects the highway will attract commercial traffic.            <br>  The 36 kilometre section of the tollway, connecting Highway 410 in Brampton to Highway 404 in Markham, is expected to be open by March 31st.
<hr>
<b>Doctors Protest</b><p>
Don't look for a doctor in the nation's capital next Thursday or Friday.<br>  Ottawa doctors will close their offices for two days next week.<br>  This after a meeting with provincial officials to discuss the current labor dispute with Queen's Park.
<hr>
<b>Yugo / Milosovic</b><p>
Opposition parties and students in Yugoslavia staged their biggest protest yet today.<br>   It's the 17-th day of protests against president Slobodan Milosevic, and his annulment of opposition victories in local elections.<br>  And now some 90 judges have added their voices to the protest... saying the election issue should be re-examined.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Paris Bomb</b><p>
French police say a Canadian woman was one of the two people killed in a Paris train bombing yesterday.<br>   Another Canadian -- a man -- was among the more than 80 people injured in the attack.<br>   The woman's name is not known.<br>   But the Canadian man has been identified as 30-year-old Frank Stonebanks, who works for a Montreal firm and was recently transferred to Paris.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Jane Eyre </b><p>
A novel ....three movies ....and now a stage musical.<br>  The Royal Alexandra Theatre was the scene last night of the world premiere of Charlotte Bronte's classic "Jane Eyre".<br>  The story, set-to-song had the audience cheering, but as Alex Reynolds reports, critics wonder if the public will embrace this century old love story.
<i> <br>  "Jane Eyre" has become a woman of our time.<br>  With fine tuning by 20th century crafts people, the heroine of the 19th century novel now sings.<br>  The overlong first act approximates three-quarters of Bronte's narrative.... the show is heavy with detail.... Jane's life between her teens and adulthood is glossed over.<br>  Excising would wrap it up neatly, leading into the post intermission romance between Jane and Edward Rochester.<br>  The dark brooding Thornfield Hall on the Yorkshire Moors matches that of the owner's manner.... harboring a sinister secret, which eventually leads to tragic consequences.<br>  Chris Parry's lighting design superbly captures the dark mood of John Napier's massive set.<br>  Comparisons will be made to "Les Miz."<br>  For the most part, there's a sung-through narrative.....and here Paul Gordon's songs underline the drama, as well as romance....but, aside from "Secret Soul," a melodious ode to Jane's inner feelings....lack the soaring feeling the story calls for.<br>  It's a serious first time theatre outing for Gordon who's songs have been recorded by many pop stars.<br>  Director John Caird, who also adapted the book to the stage, and is affiliated with the Royal Shakespeare Company has created a massive theatre piece that imposes challenges to the audience.<br>  There are no special effects to astonish.... just a classic story.  It's like reading the novel but with visuals added.<br>  It's a $6 million risk for producer David Mirvish...spit and polish, nip and tuck would do wonders.<br>  Oh! Did I mention Marla Schaffel and Anthony Crivello?<br>  She's appropriately virginal, he dark, brooding and vulnerable ...they're a good team.<br>  The show packs the emotional wallop of the book....with music added.<br>  There are critics who'll say the story should have stayed on the book shelf.... with doctoring the musical has a chance.<br>  </i>







<P>
