<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 29, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Liberals - Hamilton   
    <li>Ont. Liberals       
    <li>Tobacco Smuggling   
    <li>Drummond on Hold    
    <li>Salvi Dead          
    <li>Zaire Extra 
    <li>Wang Dan            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Liberals - Hamilton</b><p>
Ontario Liberals are choosing a new leader.<br>  The leadership convention is now under way at Maple Leaf Gardens in Toronto.<br>  The front-runner is considered by many too left-wing to lead the party.
<hr>
<b>Ont. Liberals</b><p>
The biggest task facing Liberal delegates at this weekend's convention is to pick a leader who will ulimately bring the party to power in the next provincial election.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Tobacco Smuggling</b><p>
Taxes on tobacco went up today, several years after having been cut in order to stop a rampant smuggling problem in central Canada and the maritimes.<br>  Liberal minister Don Boudria, whose eastern Ontario riding includes parts of the St. Lawrence River Valley where cigarette smuggling flourished, doesn't expect the problem to surface again.
<hr>
<b>Drummond on Hold</b><p>
The trial of a woman accused of shooting her fetus is on hold for three weeks.<br>  An Ontario judge has reserved judgment.<br>  Both sides have made their opening arguments on the Brenda Drummond case.<br>  The defence says Drummond can't be charged with attempted murder because she did not shoot a human being.<br>  Drummond's lawyers say because the fetus was not yet legally a human being, the issue is really about abortion.
<hr>
<b>Salvi Dead</b><p>
The man convicted of murdering two people during a shooting rampage at two abortion clinics in the Boston area has died.<br>   A corrections department spokesman says John Salvi was found dead in his prison cell.<br>   Salvi's mother says he killed himself.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Extra </b><p>
Canada refuses to back away from a plan to air drop food to refugees in Zaire.<br>  The Zairian government, aid workers, and even the Canadian commander of the aid effort are concerned about the proposed air drop.<br>   But in Ottawa foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy says Canada has the support of as many as 20 countries to set up a military headquarters in Entebbe, Uganda.
<hr>
<b>Wang Dan</b><p>
Prime minister Chretien has made no secret of his desire to increse trade with China.<br>  Earlier this week, the PM was in Shanghai signing the final contract to sell China Canadian nuclear reactors.<br>  Today, a group of human rights activists demanded Chretien do more to support human rights in China.<br>  In particular, they asked him to seek the release of Chinese dissident Wang Dan, one of the student leaders of the 1989 Tienanmen Square protest.







<P>
