<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 28, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Eves Statement      
    <li>Drummond - Crown    
    <li>Mattison Paroled    
    <li>Cigarette Tax       
    <li>Olsen Videos        
    <li>Zaire 
    <li>Macey's Parade      
    <li>Holiday Windows     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Eves Statement</b><p>
Finance minister Ernie Eves, deliveried a rosy economic picture for Ontario today. But opposition critics called the ministers statement window dressing. 
<hr>
<b>Drummond - Crown</b><p>
The Brenda Drummond case may not re-open the abortion deabate after all.<br>  It was thought the case of the woman charged with shooting her fetus with a pellet gun would become a new battleground over the rights of the fetus.<br>  But today the crown attorney agreed with Drummond's lawyer in saying that a fetus is not considered a person, but it is still protected under the criminal code.<br>  The crown says that because the fetus survived the gun shot and was born alive, the mother can be charged with attempted murder.
<hr>
<b>Mattison Paroled</b><p>
 Another case from the courts is causing some negative reaction from women's groups; disturbed that a wife-killer, and ex-cop, has been paroled after serving only three years of a ten year sentence. Scot Urquhart has more:
<i><br>  It was one of the most gruesome slayings in recent memory. Nicole Mattison ... 52 years old, shot and killed by a police revolver, in this Fonthill residence ... by her husband David; a 25 year veteran of the Metro Toronto Police force. Her body was then cut into pieces and scattered in various locations ... including Lake Ontario ... the investigation caused an extensive search by police divers, that stretched over a period of months.... and resulted in a conviction against David Mattison, not for murder ... but for manslaughter. He was sentenced to ten years in prison; and this week, after serving three years ... he was released on day parole. Did Mattison get a soft ride in the justice system because he was a cop? Jill Rumble heads up a working group of some 30 different organizations committed to ending violence against women. She says, Mattison may have got preferrential treatment ... but it had nothing to do with his police background: <br>  The irony in this ... Mattison's release comes at the end of wife assault prevention month. <br>  Rumble says the Mattison case will be discussed by her working group ... and letters of protest to the federal justice minister could follow. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cigarette Tax</b><p>
Taxes on cigarettes are going up -- but only in the four provinces that lowered their provincial tobacco taxes in 1994.<br>   The federal government will hit smokers in Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia and New Brunswick with a 70-cent per carton hike.<br>   At the same time, those provinces will match the tax increase.<br>   Finance minister Paul Martin has also extended a surtax on tobacco manufacturers for three years, a measure he says will raise 65-million dollars a year.           <br>     The tax increases take effect at midnight local times.
<hr>
<b>Olsen Videos</b><p>
Videos made by notorious killer Clifford Olsen have victim's rights groups concerned.<br>  An Ottawa group says the videos, which detail Olsen's killings, puts the ownership of the tapes in question.<br>  They say Olsen has duped prison authorities into giving up the videos.<br>  But solicitor general Herb Grey says there is no danger of the tapes falling into the wrong hands.
<hr>
<b>Zaire</b><p>
Canada will spearhead a plan to airdrop humanitarian aid to Rwandan refugees.<br>  Foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy says 15 countries have pledged their support for a scaled down relief operation.<br>  Although the movement of refugees several weeks ago had thrown the operation into question, Axworthy says Canada's help is still needed.
<hr>
<b>Macey's Parade</b><p>
Today is Thanksgiving south of the border and many Americans spent the day feasting on turkey and spending time with loved ones.<br>   And for many, Thanksgiving wouldn't be complete without the mother of all parades... the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade in New York.<br>  Hundreds of thousands of people braved the cold to get an up-close look at the procession.<br>  An estimated 45-million others watched it on TV.<br>   The 70-th edition of the parade featured a number of celebrities, more than 500 clowns, 13 marching bands, 17 floats and 18 huge helium balloons.
<hr>
<b>Holiday Windows</b><p>
Anyone who's visited New York City during the holiday season has probably seen the elaborate displays at some of the major retailers...<br>  Some are more elaborate than others..<br>   Well known chains spend up to half a million dollars on their window displays ..but are they worth the cost?<br>  







<P>
