<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 27, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Drunk Suspensions   
    <li>No Mini Budget      
    <li>Drummond            
    <li>Latimer Appeal      
    <li>School Bus Fatal    
    <li>Air Bag Dead        
    <li>Gun Law             
    <li>Boris Pasternak     
    <li>Cancer Connection   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Drunk Suspensions</b><p>
The Harris government is getting tough with drunk drivers.<br>   Starting Friday, anyone caught drinking and driving in Ontario, will automatically lose their licences for 90 days.<br>  
<hr>
<b>No Mini Budget</b><p>
The province has put off its announcement of another three-billion dollars in spending cuts.<br>   Finance minister Ernie Eves says instead, a statement will be issued tomorrow and will focus on providing a snapshot of the province's current finances.<br>  The Tories have already outlined about five-billion dollars in cuts.<br>  But they say they don't have all the information needed to make the new cuts.<br>  Opposition parties think otherwise.
<hr>
<b>Drummond</b><p>
Opening arguments have begun in what could be a ground-breaking attempted murder trial near Ottawa.<br>   The lawyer for a Carleton Place woman says his client was trying to kill herself or provoke a miscarriage when she fired a pellet shot at her unborn child in her womb.<br>   Lawrence Greenspon says neither act is a crime.<br>   Brenda Drummond is charged with the attempted murder of her son, who was born two days after the shooting with a pellet lodged in his head.
<hr>
<b>Latimer Appeal</b><p>
Meanwhile, a Saskatchewan man's appeal to be re-tried for the murder of his disabled daughter is in limbo.<br>  The Supreme Court decided today to reserve judgement in the case of Saskatchewan farmer Robert Latimer, meaning it may be months before a decision is made.<br>  Latimer was convicted of murdering his disabled daughter two years ago.<br>  In a taped confession, Latimer said he killed his daughter to end her pain.<br>  The defence is arguing that Latimer's confession was obtained illegally.
<hr>
<b>School Bus Fatal</b><p>
One person is dead after a school bus collided with a car this morning in the Port Perry area, north of Oshawa.<br>   Provincial police say the male driver of the car is dead.<br>   There were no serious injuries on board the school bus, which was loaded with high school students.<br>   It happened around 9 a-m on highway 7a between Port Perry and Blackstock.<br>   The name of the victim has not been released.
<hr>
<b>Air Bag Dead</b><p>
It was just a minor fender-bender -- but it resulted in the death of a one-year-old girl who was decapitated by an air bag.<br>   Police in Boise, Idaho, say the accident in a parking lot triggered the passenger-side air bag in the car being driven by the girl's mother.<br>   Air bags have been blamed in the deaths of more than 30 American children in low-speed crashes.
<hr>
<b>Gun Law</b><p>
Ottawa has tabled its new gun registry which governs the way firearms are stored and transported.<br>  Federal justice minister Allan Rock says the new registration system will curb firearm trafficking and theft and make it easier for the police to track stolen guns.<br>  Ian Dovey reports.                
<I><br>  Ottawa says buying a firearm will under the proposed regulations be straightforward and practical.<br>  The new process will be much like a credit card purchase.<br>  The swipe of a license and registration card will verify that the buyer is authroized to buy the gun and that the store is authorized to sell it. <br>    Beginning in 1998 everyone who owns a gun will have to have a license.<br>  The five year license will range from 10 to 80 dollars depending on the calibre of the weapon.<br>  Regarding the storage of weapons...<br>  Non restricted firearms will have to be stored unloaded, locked or deactivated in a separate location from the ammunition.<br>  Restricted or prohibited weapons must be stored in the same fashion but with a trigger lock in a locked case or cabinet.<br>  Rock says the existing permit to transport firearms will replaced with simpler rules. <br>    Rock says the regualtions will apply to aboriginal peoples as well, but enforced with respect for the aboriginal way of life.<br>  The gun registry has been widely opposed in rural areas.<br>  Ontario along with Alberta, Manitoba, Saskatchewan and the territories say they will not enforce the registry.<br>  Alberta is challenging the regulations in court.<br>  </I>
<hr>
<b>Boris Pasternak</b><p>
For many years, Boris Pasternak...the author of Doctor Zhivago, maintained a secret love life ...worthy of ...well, a Russian novel.<br>  And now, you can read all about it.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Cancer Connection</b><p>
There's a new service up and running now across Ontario to help cancer patients deal with their disease and its treatment.<br>  Through "Cancer Connection", patients or their caregivers are matched up anonymously with a cancer survivor who's been through a similiar experience.<br>  Their contact is by phone, with the Canadian Cancer Society picking up the tab for any long distance charges.  
<br>  If you have cancer and want to hear from someone who shares your experience, or if you're a cancer survivor who'd like to help, you can call "Cancer Connection" toll free at 1-800-263-6750.







<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

