<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 26, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Docs Update         
    <li>Witmer WCB          
    <li>MTO Layoffs         
    <li>Homolka Parole      
    <li>Ont. Immigration    
    <li>Auditor General
    <li>Ethiopian Hijacking 
    <li>Simpson Tuesday     
    <li>Sands Blown         
    <li>Safest City         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Docs Update</b><p>
As of next Monday, it could be hard trying to get an after-hours appointment with a family doctor in Ontario.<br>  That's the day thousands of doctors in the province are being asked by the Coalition of Family Physicians to stop booking evening and weekend appointments.<br>  The move means more after-hours clinics will likely close their doors.<br>  And it's the latest escalation in the dispute between doctors and the province over cutbacks to the health-care system.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Witmer WCB</b><p>
Benefits to injured workers are being cut as the Harris government reforms the Workers Compensation Board.<br>   Labor minister Elizabeth Witmer announced today the WCB will be replaced by another agency and benefits will be cut by five percentage points.<br>   Injured workers will receive 85 per cent of their pre-injury earnings.<br>   The new government body that will replace the WCB will be called the Workplace Safety and Insurance Board.
<hr>
<b>MTO Layoffs</b><p>
Meanwhile, hundreds of provincial government employees were told today they are losing their jobs.<br>   Transportation minister Al Palladini says the work of about 700 ministry construction workers is being contracted out to the private sector.<br>   Many of the workers are safety inspectors.<br>   Palladini says he's confident that engineers from the private sector can carry out highway construction inspections at a lower cost without compromising safety.
<hr>
<b>Homolka Parole</b><p>
One of canada's most infamous criminals is due for day parole in just over one month -- but she shows no signs of wanting it.<br>  Karla Homolka is eligible to apply for day parole as of January 6th.<br>  Homolka is serving a 12-year manslaughter sentence in Kingston's prison for women in the deaths of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy.<br>  Homolka's ex-husband, Paul Bernardo, is serving a life sentence for killing the girls and has been declared a dangerous offender.
<hr>
<b>Ont. Immigration</b><p>
A federal study confirms that Ontario gets the lion's share of immigrants to Canada.<br>   More than half the 1.5-million immigrants who arrived in the past six years settled in Ontario -- most of them in Toronto.<br>   British Columbia was the second favorite spot, taking in 20 per cent of immigrants, while Quebec absorbed 12 per cent.<br>   Virtually none went to Saskatchewan and only two per cent went to the atlantic provinces.
<hr>
<b>Auditor General</b><p>
The federal auditor general has released his quarterly report -- and it covers everything from dangerous criminals to objects gathering dust in federal warehouses.<br>  Denis Desautels says criminals are slipping through the system because of lack of co-operation between federal and provincial governments.<br>  He also says the federal government could lose hundreds of millions of dollars because it does not know who owns what in government warehouses around the country.
<hr>
<b>Ethiopian Hijacking</b><p>
A South African couple on their honeymoon in the Comoro Islands, witnessed the Ethiopian Airlines plane crash Saturday as they sunbathed on the beach.<br>  Mr. and Mrs Dolph Hooz recorded the last moments of the plane's flight, before it crashed and broke up in the sea.<br>  They believed the low flying plane was an air show for tourists which is why Mrs. Hooz began recording.<br>    These are the first pictures to be shown of the ill-fated ethiopian airliner's final seconds.<br>  At least 120 people died in the crash.<br>  The  aircraft was hijacked on a flight from Addis Ababa to the Kenyan capital of Nairobi, when the pilot was ordered to fly to Australia.<br>   It crashed just offshore from the tourist beach as onlookers watched in horror.
<hr>
<b>Simpson Tuesday</b><p>
The OJ Simpson civil trial has recessed until next week after his lawyer made a tactical decision not to cross examine his client.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Sands Blown</b><p>
Talk about going out with a bang.<br>   A Las Vegas landmark, the 44-year-old Sands Hotel was demolished this morning to make way for a two billion-dollar resort.<br>   This was the third major casino to be destroyed in the past four years.<br>   The Sands once showcased the world's leading entertainers.<br>  It was the glamorous playground of top entertainers such as Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr., Joey Bishop and Peter Lawford, who collectively became known as the Rat Pack.
<hr>
<b>Safest City</b><p>
Thinking about moving south of the border?<br>   Looking for a safe place to live?<br>  Well the good news is you don't have to go very far.<br>  Andrew Siff takes a look at why Amherst, New York is considered one of the safest cities in the United States.       







<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

