<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 22, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Grey Cup - Family   
    <li>Back to Basics      
    <li>Zundel Internet     
    <li>Cochrane - Falls      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup - Family</b><p>
With just over 48 hours to go to the Grey Cup kick-off, thousands of football fans have descended on Hamilton.<br>  The city's hotels are filled to capacity.<br>  And the pace is picking up at the Grey Cup street festival.<br>  
<br>  Hamilton's population has ballooned with the influx of Grey Cup fans.<br>  Many are from out-of-town.<br>  And many more are are hometown fans, still loyally dressed in their Hamilton Ticat colours.<br>  But no matter where these people come from, they're united by one characteristic.<br>  And that's a love of football ... Canadian football.
<i> <br>As people lined up for a second day of free pancakes, served up Calgary-style, the Woolridge family was in the thick of things. Eleven-year-old Chris, and his six-year-old brother Scott skipped school today, with their father's blessing.  <br>Vern wants his kids to have the same kind of memories he has from 1972, when Hamilton hosted and won the Grey Cup.  <br>And on game day this year, Vern and his sons will be in the stands, although they won't be cheering for the same team.  <br>Dave and Bonnie Drury travelled from Sarnia to volunteer. Bonnie signed up a year ago.  <br>Fourteen-hundred volunteers are working 'round the clock to make sure Grey Cup fans have a good time.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Back to Basics</b><p>
In other news tonight...<br>  It's back to the basics for elementary students across Ontario.<br>   A new core curriculum was introduced today that will emphasize reading, writing, math, science, geography and Canadian history.<br>   Education minister John Snobelen says he wants to improve the quality of Ontario's education system and make it more accountable to parents.<br>   The provincial government is also implementing standardized report cards and province-wide testing.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Zundel Internet</b><p>
Ernst Zundel is back in the news.<br>  The well-known Toronto man who denies the existence of the holocaust, is now touting his views on the Internet.<br>  And, for the first time, the Canadian Human Rights Commission is investigating hate messages on the net.<br>  The complaints were filed by a Toronto Civic Committee on Race Relations and Toronto resident Sabina Citron. They allege the material on the computer site could expose jews to hatred or contempt on the basis of their race.<br>  No date has yet been set for the probe.  <br>  
<hr>
<b>Cochrane - Falls</b><p>
The Niagara Parks Commission has refused to allow skywalker Jay Cochrane to walk across the Niagara Gorge on a tightrope.<br>  Cochrane formally made his request to the commission board Friday morning.<br>  But the board banned stunting in the parks in 1887 and will not make an exception for Cochrane.<br>  The last walk over the gorge occurred more than a hundred years ago.







<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

