<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 21, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Grey Cup Evening
    <li>Petrocan - Oakville   
    <li>bernardo Aid        
    <li>Rent Control Reaction
    <li>Phantom 3000        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup Evening</b><p>
If you've never been to a Grey Cup before, then you've got a lot to learn about the fine art of putting on a party.<br>  Today, Hamilton kicked off its four-day Grey Cup festival, with free food, free entertainment, and free cheer good fun.<br>  Reporter Deborah Walker is standing by live in downtown Hamilton.<br>  
<br>  I never imagined you could pack so much excitement and enjoyment into a single event.<br>  If you took the grumpiest person you know, and sent them down here, I guarantee you that within minutes, they'd have a smile on their face.<br>  And if you want to really understand what the word hospitality means, then come on down to the Grey Cup Street Festival.
<i> <br>In quick succession they re-routed traffic, and fenced off King Street, so the first official event of the Grey Cup Street Festival could begin.  <br>The usual utensils just won't do when your whipping up a pancake breakfast for more than four-thousand people.  After forty-nine years, the Calgary Grey Cup Committee has it down to a fine art.  First in line, a class from Our Lady of Lourdes Elementary Cchool.  <br>And high school teacher Bob O'Connor brought his english-as-a- second language class down for a taste of Canadiana.  And no one was served unless they were willing to sport a paper stetson.  <br>The Calgary Committee says easterners are quick to embrace this western brand of spirit.  And even reporters with two left feet are drawn into the dance.  <br>Football fever is everywhere... you can even find the ghost of Grey Cups past.  <br>Hamilton has a tough act to follow, after Regina's magnificently successful Grey Cup.  But last year's hosts have faith in Hamilton's ability to rise to the occasion.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Petrocan - Oakville</b><p>
Greenpeace is launching a legal challenge to stop the expansion of a Petro-Canada refinery in Mississauga.<br>  The environmental agency says the expansion will increase the health hazards for people living near the installation.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Aid</b><p>
Convicted killer Paul Bernardo won't get legal aid for his appeal.<br>   Bernardo plans to appeal his September 1995 first-degree murder convictions in the sex-slayings of two southern Ontario teenagers.<br>   Officials with the province's legal aid program aren't saying why his request for legal aid was turned down.<br>   Bernardo now has applied for so-called "inmate appeal."<br>  No lawyer is required for that proceeding, which is not heard before a full court.<br>  Bernardo is serving life in the Kingston Penitentiary.<br>  His dangerous offender status means he likely won't ever be eligible for parole.
<hr>
<b>Rent Control Reaction</b><p>
The Ontario government is going to make it easier for landlords to significantly raise the rent by partially removing rent controls.<br>  But as Lauran Sabourin reports tenants complain the changes go too far...<br>  while landlords charge it doesn't go far enough.
<i> <br>  That means that rent controls hikes of 2.8 percent will remain on apartments that are occupied.  <br>  But as soon as an apartment or house becomes vacant landlords will be allowed to raise the rent higher.  <br>  Eugene Linley is vacating the room he has in St. Catharines. He's looking for somethng more affordable.<br>  And with the prospects of the rents going even higher he doesn't what he's going to do.<br>  Landlords have been complaining that rents need to be raised more than the 2.8 percent that's allowed by law right now.<br>  They say builings are becoming rundown.<br>  They can't afford to renovate or repair the buildings.<br>  Even though the rent controls will be lifted on vacated units.<br>  Landlords say that creates serious inequities.<br>  One tenant paying one rent - the other paying a much higher rent for the same sized unit.<br>  The government says the intention of partially lifting rent controls is to encourage more building of rental housing.<br>  To give landlords more money to do needed repairs.<br>  But critics charge that the likely result of this new tenant protection legislation will be tenants paying higher rents for run down apartments. </i>
<hr>
<b>Phantom 3000</b><p>
Another milestone for the canadian production of "The Phantom of the Opera".<br>  Tonight, the Pantages Theatre curtain will rise for the three thousandth time, adding to the numerous records the show has amassed since opening in 1989.<br>   Now in it's eighth year, the Toronto "Phantom" is the longest running musical hit in the history of Canadian theatre.







<P>
