<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 20, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Grey Cup Advance    
    <li>Ontario Math        
    <li>Nat. Child Day Demo 
    <li>Compulsive Gambling 
    <li>Fergie - Toronto    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>grey cup advance</b><p>
The barricades are up.<br>  The beer tents are ready.<br>  And if football fans would only buy up more tickets, organizers of Hamilton's Grey Cup would be blissfully happy.<br>  This is the eve of a four-day celebration that will culminate in Sunday's CFL final between the Toronto Argonauts and the Edmonton Eskimos.<br>  
<br>  The party doesn't officially start until tomorrow.<br>  But party tents have already sprouted up all over the city of Hamilton.<br>  And bars and restaurants are already doing a brisk business.<br>  That's because the Grey Cup invasion is already underway.
<i> <br>The media has formed the advance guard.  250 journalists and photographers from coast-to-coast have registered for Grey Cup accreditation, with another two-hundred standing by for live coverage on game day.  <br>And the media aren't the only ones in town. The Argonauts and the Eskimos are here. And you can't walk through a hotel lobby in Hamilton without spotting football legends like Tommy Joe Coffey and Angelo Mosca. Everywhere, organizers are putting the finishing touches on plans for the four-day party leading up to the Grey Cup game. </i>
<br>  Three-quarters of the 42-thousand Grey Cup tickets have now been sold.<br>  Ironically, when we stopped by the ticket office earlier today, orders were coming in from New York state.<br>  It seems a shame we have to count on Americans to help sell out Canada's national game.
<hr>
<b>Ontario Math</b><p>
An international study of educational standards was released today, and surprisingly, Ontario's students don't fair very well, even against the other provinces.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Nat. Child Day Demo</b><p>
Today is national child day.<br>  And a group called "Justice for Children and Youth", are calling on the Harris goverment to make changes to stop the abuse of young offenders in detention centres across Ontario.<br>   The group demonstrated at Queens Park today in an effort to focus attention on the death of teenager James Lonnie.<br>  Lonnie died from head injuries last September after being put into an adult cell at a Guelph jail.<br>  The group is also demanding solicitor general Bob Runciman stop the inhumane treatment of young inmates at two provincial dentention centres.
<hr>
<b>Compulsive Gambling</b><p>
Casino and racetrack gamblers in Ontario will soon be able to try their luck on video lottery terminals.<br>   The Tory government recently passed legislation to allow the VLT's at casinos and racetracks.<br>  And while many of the province's gamblers are excited, opponents fear the worst.<br>    
<hr>
<b>Fergie - Toronto</b><p>
Sarah Ferguson is in Toronto to promote her autobiography "My Story."<br>   The 37-year-old Duchess of York will appear on several shows today.<br>   Fergie spent the past week on the U.S. talk show circuit.<br>   One British newspaper, The Guardian, recently ran a front-page headline reading "Exclusive! No Fergie Interview Inside!"







<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

