<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 19, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Education Cuts      
    <li>Nurses Demo         
    <li>Workfare Update     
    <li>Palladini - 407       
    <li>Weeping Icon        
    <li>Young Offenders     
    <li>Chunnel             
    <li>Ghali Vote          
    <li>Israel Beating      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Education Cuts</b><p>
Education minister John Snobelen was under attack on two fronts today, because of his cuts to education spending.<br>   Both public school directors of education, and angry parents are demanding input into educational reform being contemnplated by the Harris government.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Nurses Demo</b><p>
Hundreds of nurses converged on the lawn at Queens Park today.<br>  They were demanding a meeting with premier Mike Harris.<br>   The nurses, who marched up University Avenue to the Ontario Legislature, were protesting government cuts to hospital funding.<br>  Those cuts have resulted in hudreds of nurses being laid off.<br>  They say such wholesale cuts are not necessary, and the nurses want to get that message to the premier.
<hr>
<b>Workfare Update</b><p>
The pressure is on municipalities to come up with a plan of how they're going to implement workfare.<br>  Municipalities that are dragging their feet on workfare, are being threatened with paying the start up costs.<br>   But Niagara Region isn't worried about a penalty.<br>  It plans to be one of the first to get its welfare recipients to work for their money.
<hr>
<b>Palladini - 407</b><p>
Ontario's auditor, Erik Peters says safety standards were lowered in a deal with the former NDP government, so that the new 407 highway could be built for a maximum price of 930-million dollars.<br>  Transportation minister Al Palladini says the highway is safe, but he is prepared to conduct an independant inspection, just to be on the safe side.         The independent safety audit could delay the opening of the new highway, which was set for next month.
<hr>
<b>Weeping Icon</b><p>
The jury is still out on whether it's a miracle, but Toronto police say there's no evidence of fraud in claims of a weeping icon in a tiny church.<br>   Police say there's no proof of any financial gain by those involved with a Greek Orthodox church in East York.<br>  The icon, a copy of a 12 hundred-year-old painting of the Virgin Mary, allegedly began weeping last August.<br>  Large amounts of cash were donated when reports of the icon became public.
<hr>
<b>Young Offenders</b><p>
Most youths over the age of 14 found guilty of serious violent offences should be transferred to adult court for sentencing.<br>  That is the advice of a task force of federal, provincial and territorial justice officials.<br>  Under reforms passed last year, 16 and 17 year olds charged with serious violent crimes must be tried as adults unless they can persuade a judge that they should stay in youth court.
<hr>
<b>Chunnel</b><p>
Turning to international news, a smoky fire broke out in the middle of the tunnel under the waters separating Britain and France...injuring several people.<br>   It was the worst accident since the fifteen-mile-long "Chunnel" opened two years ago.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Ghali Vote</b><p>
The United States has vetoed Boutros Boutros-Ghali for re-election as U.N. secretary- general.<br>  But Boutros-Ghali won't go quietly.<br>  He has refused to withdraw his candidacy despite the veto.<br>  That sets the stage for a protracted battle in which the United States has so far found itself diplomatically isolated.<br>   Washington announced in June that it intended to block Boutros-Ghali's re-election, saying the U.S. wanted new leadership to implement reforms.
<hr>
<b>Israel Beating</b><p>
Israel's border police arrested two officers after they were caught on video beating and kicking a group of Palestinians.<br>   The video shows the troops apparently unaware of an amateur Palestinian cameraman nearby as they attacked the six Arab men.<br>   One officer kicked a man in the head and the footage also shows the israelis apparently forcing the Palestinians to do push-ups.<br>   A passerby who stops to ask questions is smacked in the face.






<P>
