<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 14, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Smoking Rates Up    
    <li>Ontario Quebec      
    <li>Days of Action      
    <li>C.A.A. - Roads      
    <li>Hong Kong #4        
    <li>Jacksons Bride      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Smoking Rates Up</b><p>
Ontario's Chief Medical Officer of Health has sounded an alarm to an emerging health crisis in the province.<br>   He says increases in the number of people who smoke... is a deadly time bomb that will have enormous consequences, if governments don't take tough action to butt it out.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Ontario Quebec</b><p>
Quebec's separation would devastate Ontario's economy.<br>   That's according to secret government studies.<br>   The Globe and Aail reports provincial research has found that if Quebec departs, increased spending and a loss of taxes would cost this province 16 and a half billion dollars a year.<br>   The studies also suggest most people leaving Quebec would move to Ontario, driving up social assistance costs.<br>     The newspaper has been trying to obtain the studies, but the Harris government is refusing to make them public.
<hr>
<b>Days of Action</b><p>
A top Ontario labor leader has dropped some strong hints about where the next "Days of Action" protests will be held.<br>   Sid Ryan, the head of CUPE Ontario, says Sudbury is among several cities that could be picked for protests next year.<br>   Other cities in the running are North Bay -- which is the premier's home riding -- as well as Thunder Bay and Windsor.<br>   Ryan says the protests would start in February and run into the summer.
<hr>
<b>C.A.A. - Roads</b><p>
Groups representing canadian drivers say the federal government has to shift into high gear to save the country's highways.<br>  The Canadian Automobile Association and the Coalition to Renew Canada's Infrastructure had two people drive from Victoria to St. John's ... they say our highways are falling apart.
<hr>
<b>Hong Kong #4</b><p>
There are continued warnings from Hong Kong about the security of democrat rights and freedoms, after China takes over the colony next year.<br>  Beijing has warned it will not tolerate attacks on its leadership after the takeover.<br>  For the young, coping with China is a worrying uncertainty.<br>  Tonight in "countdown in Hong Kong", we'll meet some Canadian students who live in the colony.<br>  They have surprising observations about the future of Hong Kong's freedoms.
<hr>
<b>Jacksons Bride</b><p>
Michael Jackson is marrying the woman carrying his baby.<br>   The king of pop was expected to exchange wedding vows today with six-months pregnant Debbie Rowe during a private ceremony in Sydney, Australia.<br>   Jackson is 38 and the bride-to-be, a longtime friend and nurse to his plastic surgeon, is 37.<br>  


<P>
