<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 13, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Crombie - Education   
    <li>Docs Dicipline      
    <li>Clinton Zaire       
    <li>Hong Kong #3         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Crombie - Education</b><p>
The provincially appointed so-called "who does what panel" has recommended several changes to the education system in Ontario.<br>  At the forefront is a suggestion that the Ontario government pay a bigger share of the cost of education...<br> The panel chaired by David Crombie also wants the number of school boards cut in half.<br>  As Jamie West reports... initial reaction to the recommendations is mixed.
<i><br>  Reducing duplication in government is the mandate of the who does what panel.<br>  To that end the panel recommends school boards focus on activities that relate directly to classroom activity, and leave maintenance transportation and construction to private firms or municipalities.<br>  The panel wants the number of school boards cut in half with most boards having the same boundries as counties or regional governments...in some cases that will put more money into the hands of some boards that have a lower tax base ...<br>  Further school boards would be allowed to collect up to 5% of their budgets from property taxes instead of an average 50 percent levee, the province would pick up the rest of the cost.<br>  Provincial grants to school boards would be based on a new per-pupil grant, and a new province wide rate for industrial and commercial property taxes imposed. To be monitored by an advisory body of school trustees, educators, business and parents... Other union leaders say the recommendations if accepted would produce thousands of layoffs. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Docs Dicipline</b><p>
Ontario's College of Physicians and Surgeons has rejected a request from the Harris government, to punish doctors who are taking part in in a province wide protest. 
<hr>
<b>Clinton Zaire</b><p>
The United States will participate in "a limited fashion" in a Canadian-led military operation to help refugees in Zaire.<br>   U.S. president Clinton is considering deploying about one-thousand ground troops in the operation.<br>   France, Spain and several African countries are also expected to provide soldiers.<br>   Prime minister Chretien has said the first members of the force could be on the ground in Zaire 48 hours after the United Nations approves the operation.
<hr>
<b>Hong Kong #3</b><p>
Only a few years ago, 80 percent of all of China's exports passed through Hong Kong on the way to international markets.<br>  The colony made a lot of money as China's middleman.<br>  But that's changing.<br>  After the Chinese takeover, Hong Kong will be a Chinese city, and a very expensive one.<br>  Already, many companies have moved their operations to chaper Chinese centers.<br>  


<P>
