<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 12, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Zaire - Chretien      
    <li>Police Funding      
    <li>Catholic Teachers   
    <li>Plane Crash         
    <li>Hong Kong 2
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Zaire - Chretien</b><p>
Canada, has stepped to the forefront of the world stage ... in a bid to end the suffering of more than a million refugees, in Zaire. The prime minister announced today, that Canadian troops are heading to that African nation, in a bid to referee the ethnic battles, that are killing more than a thousand civilians a day:
<i><br> The refugees are pouring out ... but only a trickle of relief supplies are making their way in... to war torn Zaire.<br>  Viscious ethnic warfare has made it impossible for the United Nations to reach those who need help the most: <br>  Its estimated that a million refugees are on the move without food or water; and up to a thousand a day are dying, as they flee the horrors of war. <br>  Raymond Chretien, nephew of the prime minister ... and U.N. special envoy ... has been negotiating with the two factions, and today ... there was a breakthrough:  <br>  And back home, the response was immediate: the prime minister will send a 350 member rapid response team ... followed by more Canadian troops, and support units; to separate the warring factions, and bring aid to the refugees: <br>  Chretien's announcement was immediately hailed by UN secretary general Bhoutros Bhoutros Gali ... <br>  Putting foreign nationals under Canadian command may keep a reluctant president Clinton on the sidelines in this dispute. Whether Canada has the muscle to go it alone in Zaire, without American military might... could determine whether this mission of mercy is ultimately successful... or not. </i>
<hr>
<b>Police Funding</b><p>
A government panel recommends the province start charging almost 600 municipalities for police services they currently get for free.<br>   That would save the tory government 100-million dollars annually. But some rural areas that would be forced to pay, are objecting.
<hr>
<b>Catholic Teachers</b><p>
Metro Toronto's Catholic high school teachers are on a work-to-rule campaign.<br>   That means no extra-curricular sports or programs at 37 high schools.<br>   Picket lines went up between class time at the region's Catholic high schools.<br>   Some students joined teachers on the line.<br>   The 21-hundred teachers want an extra 15-hundred dollars a year in wages.<br>   The Separate School Board says the pay hike would cost it eight-million dollars a year.
<hr>
<b>Plane Crash</b><p>
Hundreds are feared dead in an aviation disaster near New Delhi.<br>   Two airliners collided near the Indian capital, falling to earth in two fireballs that showered wreckage over a wide area of farmland.<br>   About 350 people were aboard the aircraft -- a Saudi Airways jumbo jet and a Kazak airliner.<br>   It's believed all aboard were killed -- as well as some victims on the ground.
<hr>
<b>Hong Kong 2</b><p>
Less than 8 months remain until China takes over Britains last colony.<br>  But, hundreds of thousands of people have taken the precaution of acquiring a foreign passport.<br>  Many are nervous about living under the same rulers that ordered the massacre in Tianamen Square.<br>  Canada leads the international community, doling out more passports to people in the colony that the U.S. or even Britain, 40 thousand last year alone.<br>  But many of the new Canadians didn't stay in Canada ... they've returned and are hoping for the best.


<P>
