<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 11, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Ottawa Remembrance  
    <li>Toronto Remembrance 
    <li>Vets - Battleship     
    <li>Doc Update          
    <li>Countdown - Hong Kong 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Ottawa Remembrance</b><p>
Today is Remebrance Day ... the day Canadians gather to remember the sacrifices of those who fought and died for freedom, in the wars of this century.<br>   Millions across the country wore poppies and observed two minutes of silence in honor of Canada's fallen heroes who offered the ultimate sacrifice.<br>   On a chilly November morning in Ottawa, prime minister Chretien led a steady stream of dignitaries and veterans who placed wreaths at the Canadian War Memorial.
<hr>
<b>Toronto Remembrance</b><p>
Several thousand people braved a biting wind to pay their respects during Remembrance Day ceremonies in Toronto.<br>   Wreaths were laid at the cenotaph in the downtown core.<br>    And at Queen's Park, a cannon was fired to commemorate the armistice in the first world war.<br>   Earlier today, veterans attended a sunrise ceremony at prospect cemetery, where more than five-thousand soldiers from the first world war are buried.
<hr>
<b>Vets - Battleship</b><p>
And while thousands of people across the country payed their respect to the nations war dead, a Toronto social action group took advantage of Rememberance Day, to protest against an Ontario government lottery, which it says promotes war.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Doc Update</b><p>
The head of the Coalition of Family Physicians in Ontario says clinic closures and the refusal of doctors to see new patients are just the tip of the iceberg.<br>  Dr. Paul Friedman says people are just starting to feel the impact of the doctors' protest against the Harris government.<br>  Doctors are embroiled in a bitter dispute with the province over clawbacks on their earnings and a demand by the government that new doctors work in underserviced areas.
<hr>
<b>Countdown - Hong Kong</b><p>
On July first, 1997, Britain will give up its last colony.<br>  Hong Kong will be turned over to China.<br>  More than a half a million Canadians can trace their roots to Hong Kong, more than 20 billion dollars of Canadian debt is held there.<br>  Canadians also make up the largest minority in the city.<br>  China has said it will leave Hong Kong as is for at least 50 years.<br>    


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

