<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 8, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Wilson vs Docs      
    <li>Where to Find A Doctor 
    <li>Homolka Parole      
    <li>Unemployment 
    <li>Pot Bust            
    <li>TWA
    <li>Sinatra             
    <li>Belafonte           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Wilson vs Docs</b><p>
Health minister Jim Wilson  has ordered the College of Physicians and Surgeons to punish doctors who turn away new patients, in a protest against the Harris government.<br>  Wilson says if the college doesn't comply, the government will bring in legislation to force the doctors back in line.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Where to Find A Doc</b><p>
This is supposed to be the day that family physicians across Ontario begin refusing to take new patients.<br>  But that job-action will likely have little effect in Niagara.<br>  There is an acute family physician shortage in the peninsula and doctors have been refusing to take on new patients for the last few years.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Homolka Parole</b><p>
Ontario's solicitor general and attorney general want to make sure Karla Homolka doesn't get out on parole.<br>   Homolka began serving a 12-year sentence in 1993 for her role in the sex-slayings of two schoolgirls.<br>  She is eligible to apply for day passes in just two months.<br>  Next July, Homolka will be eligible to apply for full parole.<br>  The Toronto Star reports the two ministers intend to intervene with the National Parole Board.
<hr>
<b>Unemployment </b><p>
Unemployment gained one-tenth of a point last month.<br>   The federal government calls it a sign of rising confidence in Canada's economy.<br>   The rate hit 10 per cent.<br>   Statistics Canada says the economy created 42-thousand jobs last month -- not enough to offset a rising number of job-hunters.<br>   Finance minister Paul Martin says the rise in joblessness is a sign of rising confidence in the economy.
<hr>
<b>Pot Bust</b><p>
Drug charges have been laid against 14 Ontarians in a marijuana smuggling operation in North America.<br>   The OPP worked with the RCMP and Canada Customs during the investigation of a smuggling ring that moved marijuana from Mexico through the U.S. into southern Ontario.<br>  14 people from southern Ontario are charged with conspiracy to import and traffic a narcotic.<br>   They are to appear in court in St. Thomas on November 12th.
<hr>
<b>TWA</b><p>
The FBI is furious over the latest allegation of a coverup in the investigation of the TWA flight 800 explosion and crash.<br>   This, after a former newsman claimed he had new information that supposedly proves the jet was downed by American friendly fire.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Sinatra</b><p>
Frank Sinatra remains in a Los Angeles hospital amid reports that his health problems may be more serious than originally announced.<br>   When the 80-year-old singer entered hospital a week ago, his publicist said it was for treatment of a "pinched nerve."<br>   But a Los Angeles TV station says sinatra is being treated for both heart failure and pneumonia.
<hr>
<b>Belafonte</b><p>
More than 800 students received their degrees, as McMaster University held fall convocation ceremonies today at Hamilton Place.<br>  But as Alex Reynolds reports, a familiar, famous face, that of singer Harry Belafonte, was among the recipients.
<i> <br>  Over the years, the Great Hall has been home for Belafonte as an entertainer.<br>  On this occasion, he was being honored academically.<br>  His work in the cause of human rights, and that of his wife Julie, has been recognized by McMaster University...the hoarse-voiced singer was obviously overwhelmed. <br>  During his convocation address, the singer paid hommage to those who pioneered the path for black entertainers. <br>  Hamilton fans feel Harry is one of their own ...the doctor of laws degree is an added symbol. <br>  There are many honors for the calypso singer- turned-doctor, who believes "the role of art isn't just to show life as it is....but to show life as it should be."<br>  </i>


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

