<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 7, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>MPP - Probe          
    <li>Hospital Cuts       
    <li>Ortho Docs          
    <li>Truck Rules         
    <li>OFL Protest Follow
    <li>Chlorine Water      
    <li>Migraine Drug       
    <li>Christopher Retires 
    <li>Mars                
    <li>Fergie Book         
    <li>Best Cities         
</ul>


<hr>
<b>MPP - Probe</b><p>
 Attorney general Charles Harnick has ordered a criminal investigation of two New Democrat MPPs. Harnick says Welland Thorold MPP Peter Kormos and Sudbury East MPP Shelley Martel are alleged to have breached security at the province's family support plan offices near Toronto. 

<hr>
<b>Hospital Cuts</b><p>
Ontario hospital bed closures could be far more extensive than previously expected.<br>   The powerful Health Services Restructuring Commission says the province could lose roughly 20 per cent of its acute-care beds in a major overhaul.<br>   That's one out of every five beds currently in use.<br>   However, commission chairman Duncan Sinclair says the public shouldn't judge the quality of health care by the number of beds.<br>   He says you can no longer equate the number of beds with the level of service provided by a hospital.
<hr>
<b>Ortho Docs</b><p>
    Thousands of Ontario doctors meanwhile, are poised to stop taking new patients tomorrow.<br>   Negotiations with the government failed to settle their demands for more money and the right to work where they choose.<br>   Some doctors have already stopped seeing new patients.<br>   The doctors and the government are still talking in Toronto.
<hr>
<b>Truck Rules</b><p>
Queen's Park is out to make it tougher for unsafe truck operators.<br>  A bill introduced today by transport minister Al Palladini, would give the province's registrar of motor vehicles new powers... including penalizing trucking companies who operate rigs that don't meet safety standards and refusing to give new licenses to disreputable firms.<br>   Safety records of trucking firms would also be made public.
<br>  Once the bill becomes law... firms caught operating unsafe trucks would be brought to justice sooner.
<hr>
<b>OFL Protest Follow</b><p>
To shut down or not to shut down -- that seems to be a tough question now for Ontario's labor movement.<br>   At a Toronto meeting of the Ontario Federation of Labor today, Ontario's most powerful unions appeared split over the future of labour's "days of action".<br>   Sid Ryan of the Canadian Union of Public Employees in Ontario, says the old standard will be upheld.<br>   But John Murphy of the Powerworkers Union says mass protests like the recent one in Toronto, have not succeeded in winning public support.
<hr>
<b>Chlorine Water</b><p>
A new study suggests that chlorine-treated drinking water could be killing people.<br>   In studying five-thousand Ontario residents, Health Canada suggests chlorinated water causes more than 500 cases of cancer and 140 deaths each year.<br>   It concludes the reaction of chlorine with decaying organic material, creates carcino-genic by-products known as THM's in the water.<br>   Researchers think these by-products cause bladder and colon cancers.
<hr>
<b>Migraine Drug</b><p>
Three and a half million Canadians suffer from migraine headaches and now there's a new product being touted as a relief from the affliction.<br>  A nasal spray called Migranal has been approved for use in Canada.<br>  The drug itself has been around for 50 years, but has never been available in spray.<br>  Doctors say pills are less effective because they aren't absorbed as qickly in the system.<br>  Specialsists claim that migraines account for almost seven million lost work days, every year in Canada.
<hr>
<b>Christopher Retires</b><p>
America's top diplomat is stepping down.<br>  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher announced his resignation earlier today at the white house.<br>    
<hr>
<b>Mars</b><p>
An U.N.-staffed U.S. spacecraft is on its way to Mars after a successful noontime launch from Cape Canaveral, Florida.<br>   Interest in further exploration of the "red planet" is high, following recent scientific findings that primitive life forms may have existed there.<br>   NASA officials say sending humans on a mission to Mars may not be that far off.            <br>  The "Global Surveyor" will replace a Mars probe that was lost three-years ago.<br>   After a 10-month journey, it will enter an orbit and map the planet's surface with a high-resolution camera.<br>  It's the first of 10 spacecraft the U.S. will send to Mars in the next decade.
<hr>
<b>Fergie Book</b><p>
Scarlet hussy or persecuted flop?<br>   Take your pick from two new, unabashed books about Sarah Ferguson.<br>   One called "My Story" describes life in the royal family by Fergie herself...<br>  The other "Her Secret Life" is an unflattering version written by a former pal Allan Starkie.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Best Cities</b><p>
Vancouver, Toronto, Zurich and Geneva are the best cities in the world for expatriates to live in.<br>   That's the finding of a study published by the Geneva-based Corporate Resources Group.<br>   It ranked Toronto and Vancouver at the top because of their "combination of social stability, excellent infrastructure and good leisure facilities."<br>   Sarajevo ranked at the bottom of the list.


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

