<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Ford Settles        
    <li>Harris - Ipperwash    
    <li>GRE Taxes / Charges   
    <li>Harris Breakfast    
    <li>U.S. Elex Over       
    <li>Flu Update          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Ford Settles</b><p>
There will not be a strike at Ford of Canada.<br>  A tentative deal between the number two auto maker and the Canadian Auto Workers Union, was reached within hours of a 7 p-m strike deadline.<br>  CAW president Buzz Hargrove says some loose ends remain, but he hopes the membership can begin voting on the pact this week.
<hr>
<b>Harris - Ipperwash</b><p>
Questions surrounding the death of a naltive protester at Ipperwash Provincial Park more than a year ago continues to plague the Harris government. A Sarnia area Tory MPP says he was relaying information both to the OPP and the premier's office about the confrontation at the park. 
<hr>
<b>GRE Taxes / Charges</b><p>
One of the largest employers on the Six Nations Reserve outside Brantford is in limbo after the RCMP laid charges over the weekend against its founders.<br>  32 people work at Grand River Enterprises, a cigarette manufacturing plant.<br>  The company was looking to expand, but some on the reserve feel that very expansion is where the charges stem.<br>  Annette Hamm explains.
<i><br>  The general manager of Grand River Enterprises says the cigarette plant is now operating on a day to day basis.<br>  This after he and eight other founding members of the business were charged late last week by the RCMP.<br>  Police say GREe has illegally made and sold cigarettes without a licence since early 1994.  <br>  GRE recently applied for a licence to service other nations across Canada.<br>  They were waiting for a response to that application when the charges were laid.  <br>  Six Nations Band Council chief Wellington Staats feels there's more at issue here than Grand River Enterprises ... he feels it's a violation of tax privileges.<br>  And he's worried about the implications for other businesses on the reserve.  <br>  Chief Staats says he may ask the Ministry of Native Affairs to intervene in the case.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Harris Breakfast</b><p>
Ontario premier Mike Harris has launched a school nutrition program.<br>   The eight-million dollar "Ontario Breakfast for Learning" program will be funded mostly by the province.<br>   About three-million dollars will come from the Grocery Industry Foundation.<br>   The Canadian Living Foundation will co-ordinate an expected 400 programs across the province by the end of this school year.<br>   Communities can also find out how to set up their own children's breakfast programs by calling a toll-free number (1-800-627-7922).
<hr>
<b>U.S. Elex Over</b><p>
U.S. president Bill Clinton has easily won a second term in office.<br>   He's the first Democratic president to be re-elected since Franklin Roosevelt six decades ago.<br>   But Republicans will keep control of congress.<br>   Clinton says by splitting the balance of power in Washington, Americans are saying they want all parties to work together to "get the job done."<br>  Meanwhile, Bob Dole's political career has ended after 35 years in congress.<br>  He says today is the first time in his life he doesn't have anything to do.
<hr>
<b>Flu Update</b><p>
Well it's that time of year again.... the time when that nasty flu-bug attacks unsuspecting victims with a vegeance.<br>  But there is a way of preventing an unwelcome bout with the flu.... get a flu shot.<br>  Employers are just beginning to recognize the economic benefits of the flu vaccine.


<P>
