<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/evng_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The Evening News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Roux Resigns        
    <li>Yeltsin Update      
    <li>Bhutto Fired        
    <li>U.S. Elex            
    <li>Health - Debate     
    <li>Gambling Survey     
    <li>Leach - Supercity     
    <li>Ford Talks          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Roux Resigns</b><p>
Quebec leftenant governor Jean-louis Roux has quit.<br>   Roux, who was named to the post in September, has been under fire from separatist and Jewish groups over an admission that he was a fascist sympathizer during the 1940s.<br>   Roux has said he regrets taking part in anti-semitic demonstrations while he was a youth, but a spokesperson for the Canadian Jewish Congress, says they are still looking for a direct apology.<br>  In Montreal today, the vice president of the B'nai Brith Society reacted this way.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Update</b><p>
Good news for Russian president Boris Yeltsin.<br>   Doctors say today's seven-hour bypass operation to clear his clogged arteries was a success and he should suffer no complications.<br>   American heart pioneer Dr. Michael Debakey was on hand for the surgery carried out by a team of 12 top Russian doctors.<br>   Debakey says Yeltsin should recover quickly and return to work after a six to eight week recovery period.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Bhutto Fired</b><p>
Pakistan's president is calling for new elections to replace the prime minister and her government.<br>  He has dismissed Benazir Bhutto's government, accusing her of rampant corruption and mismanagement.<br>  He's named a former leader of her party as interim prime minister.<br>  Soldiers are standing guard outside Bhutto's residence and a spokesman says Bhutto's husband has been arrested along with 20 other party members.
<hr>
<b>U.S. Elex</b><p>
It's all over but the counting, in the race for president of the United States.<br>  President Clinton is preparing for what may be a big win, while Bob Dole and Ross Perot are hoping for a miracle.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Health - Debate</b><p>
 A group that lobbies for better healthcare is challenging the Canadian Medical Association to a formal debate.<br>  The Canadian Health Coalition is challenging the CMA to co-sponsor a national debate on the future of healthcare.<br>  The coalition wants the debate to focus on the role of private companies in healthcare delivery.<br>  It says the private sector has no business in healthcare.
<hr>
<b>Gambling Survey</b><p>
A new public opinion poll shows that 62 percent of Ontarians, don't want video gambling machines installed in their neighborhoods.<br>  The Harris government is on the verge of passing legislation to bring video slot machines into Ontario racetracks and chartity casinos.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Leach - Supercity</b><p>
The Harris government is keeping a watchful eye on the city of Toronto, to make sure it doesn't dip into its 250-million dollar "reserve fund" to shore up its infastrucuture, should the province decide to amalgamate metro's six cities into one super-city.<br>  Municipal affairs minister Al Leach says if Toronto's politicians should go that route, the government would have no qualms about appointing a trustee to control Toronto's finances.
<hr>
<b>Ford Talks</b><p>
We could find out shortly about the chances of a deal between the Canadian Auto Workers and Ford Canada.<br>  The CAW called a news conference earlier this afternoon... but so far no word on the outcome.<br>  There is a strike deadline of 7 p.m. tomorrow, but CAW leader Buzz Hargrove has been sounding hopeful about reaching a settlement.


<P>
