<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, November 1, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>OHA - Closures        
    <li>Doctors Talks       
    <li>Cyberporn           
    <li>Ford Update         
    <li>U.S. Election        
    <li>Cleopatra           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>OHA - Closures</b><p>
The head of the Ontario Hospital Association says the Harris government is taking too long in its restructuring of hospitals in the province.<br>   And David Mackinnon warns that a prolonged delay could result in a deterioration of health care.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Doctors Talks</b><p>
Meanwhile, the province and its doctors are heading back to the bargaining table.<br>   Negotiations will resume tomorrow.<br>   Health minister Jim Wilson hopes they can reach an agreement on fee payments to prevent doctors from taking job action.<br>   Physicians have threatened to stop taking new patients starting on Friday.<br>   One of the big issues is the government's demand to fill the shortage of doctors in northern Ontario and other remote areas.
<hr>
<b>Cyberporn</b><p>
Police are calling it the largest seizure ever of child pornography.<br>   A Kirkland Lake man faces numerous charges after the OPP's anti-pornography squad raided his apartment.<br>  Seized were his computer and discs containing 30 thousand kiddie porn images.<br>  Investigators were working with California police and the FBI in tracking cyberspace pedophiles.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports.
<i><br>  Behind the walls of this non descript industrial mall in a Toronto suburb, a team of police officers investigate the darker side of cyberspace.<br>  Kiddie porn on the Internet.  <br>    A Kirkland Lake man faces a number of charges after police raided his aparment and seized his computer and discs containing 30-thousand pornographic images of children.  <br>  Police say 22 year-old Trevor Davis downloaded the images on his home computer then re-distributed them on the Internet.  If convicted, he faces ten years in prison.   <br>    For officers though, fighting the crime in the computer age, is not only difficult, but frustrating.     <br>  Provincial police in Ontario have made the fight against kiddie porn a priority.  More officers will be added to a task that even takes its toll on veteran investigators.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Ford Update</b><p>
Canadian auto workers leader Buzz Hargrove says if Ford accepts the pattern agreement signed by Chrysler and G.M., a contract could be nailed down tonight in Toronto.<br>   Hargrove says he's optimistic, but adds that if the pattern agreement isn't adopted, Ford employees will go on strike Wednesday night.
<hr>
<b>U.S. Election</b><p>
President Clinton and Bob Dole are cramming thousands of miles into their last 24 hours on the campaign trail.<br>   Even with the latest CBS News/NY Times poll showing the president headed towards a landslide victory tomorrow, he's taking nothing for granted while Dole is pushing his fight, and his stamina, to the limit.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Cleopatra</b><p>
Divers have found an ancient love nest under the Mediterranean Sea.<br>   It's the two-thousand year-old city where Antony and Cleopatra had a love affair.<br>  A French archeologist found the ancient court under 20 feet of water on the eastern side of the old harbor at Alexandria, Egypt.<br>   


<P>
