<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, October 30, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Grapes In           
    <li>Docs - Deal           
    <li>Students       
    <li>Bus Ads             
    <li>Spouse Rule         
    <li>Taxi-24 Sussex      
    <li>Halloween Business  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Grapes In</b><p>
The grape harvest season is just about over and Niagara Grape Growers are calling 1996 a year they would rather forget.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more now on this years dismal growing season.
<i><br>  The cool wet weather has taken it's toll on the grape crop and the Niagara grape growers this year. <br>  The vineyards are full of mud.. so muddy that on some days it's almost impossible to get the harvesters running without getting bogged down.<br>  The rains started just as the harvest was beginning... <br>  The Grape Growers Marketing Board keeps a runing tally on how much rain has fallen in Niagara .. <br>  Since the harvest began a foot of rain has fallen in the vineyards.<br>  The average rainfall is about half that... <br>  Excessive rain can have a damageing effect on a grape crop.<br>  The grapes need warm weather and lots of sun to produce sugar.<br>  Sugar makes a better quality grape.<br>  A better quality wine.<br>  The more sugar in the grapes, the more the grower is paid. <br>  A challenging year because the quality of the crop is down.<br>  The quantity of the crop is down.<br>  While consumers wont' notice any difference in the quality of the wines. <br>  In 1996 there are fewer premium grapes produced.<br>  There will be fewer premium wine bottles on the shelves.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Docs - Deal</b><p>
Ontario doctors are putting together a last minute offer to their leadership aimed at avoiding a mass withdrawl of services which could take place on Friday. <br>    Doctors have been voting by mail on a deal worked out by the province and the Ontario Medical Association, which would give doctors more money.<br>   But new doctors would have to go to underserviced areas in order to receive billing numbers.<br>   A group of physicians representing family doctors and specialists want government assurances that negotiations will still take place even if the deal is turned down. <br>  Votes will be counted tomorrow, but it could be as late as midnight before the results are made public.
<hr>
<b>Students</b><p>
A published essay in the Toronto Star gives very poor marks to the thousands of students who head off to university each year after completing high school.<br>  The article was written by 22 university professors.<br>  Dwight Ryan has the story..       
<i><br>  They're a sorry lot.  The thousands of students who each year graduate from Ontario high schools and head off to university.<br>  In a lengthy article published in the Toronto Star, nearly two dozen professors detail their dismay.<br>  They say 'new students are less and less well prepared for the university."<br>  In fact they are "less and less able to comprehend the same books..to listen attentively..to take lecture notes...to prepare for an exam...to write a paper." and the list goes on.<br>  To top it off the profs "see a steady and alarming long-term decline."<br>  Among the professors signing the article was Dravko Planinc, who teaches religious studies at Hamilton's McMaster University.<br>  He notes in new students a lack of curiosity.  <br>    Professor Planinc believes the malaise begins as early as daycare and puts the blame partly on television...    <br>  The professors believe province-wide testing will help parents learn how their local schools measure up.<br>  And its something the Tories at Queens Park have in the works.   <br>    McMaster president Peter George also believes in province-wide testing.  But he believes the majority of undergraduates are qualified.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Bus Ads</b><p>
Education minister John Snobelen says he's not totally opposed to advertising on school buses.<br>   But the minister says many parents won't like the idea.<br>   Some school boards plan to sell advertising on their buses.<br>   Snobelen says the province doesn't want it to look like the school system is endorsing commercial products.
<hr>
<b>Spouse Rule</b><p>
An Ontario court has upheld the legality of the Harris government's contentious "spouse-in -the-house" rule for welfare recipients.<br>   The regulation, which took effect a year ago, says live-in partners of the opposite sex, are a "spouse" with an obligation to support the welfare recipient.<br>   Social services minister Janet Ekker says however the rule is not all inclusive. <br>  Although a three judge panel of the court says the rules are within the power of the legislature, the judges were split over whether the rules breach the Charter of Rights of those on welfare.
<hr>
<b>Taxi-24 Sussex</b><p>
The prime minister's residence at 24 Sussex has had its share of break-ins over the past year, but nothing like what happened today.<br>  A taxi coming out of the governor- general's residence across the street, lost control and smashed into the wall that surrounds 24 Sussex.<br>  The embarassed driver apparently had no intention of taking a closer look at the prime minister's house.
<hr>
<b>Halloween Business</b><p>
From treats to costumes, masks to wigs, Halloween is no longer just for kids.<br>  In fact as we see in this report, it's become a multi-billion dollar business.



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

