<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, October 29, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Schools - Snobelen    
    <li>Harris - Docs         
    <li>Memo 
    <li>Immigration Plan    
    <li>MMT Study           
    <li>Collapse Survivor   
    <li>Mideast Tension     
    <li>New Money           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Schools - Snobelen</b><p>
Education minister John Snobelen is warning school boards he won't accept larger classroom sizes or education tax increases as a way to compensate for cuts in provincial funding.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Harris - Docs</b><p>
Premier Mike Harris today urged doctors to vote in favor of a deal worked out between the government and the Ontario Medical Association.<br>   Doctors have been angered by education minister Wilson who says no matter how the vote goes on Thursday, he is going ahead with a ban on new doctors in certain over-serviced areas of the province.<br>  Premier Harris says the agreement is only short term and doctors should show good faith by radifying it, so bargaining can continue. <br>  If doctors vote down the deal, it likely will mean come November first, many physicians will refuse to take new patients.
<hr>
<b>Memo </b><p>
A memo being sent to federal Liberals, outlines a strategy to make the Reform Party look bad to the voters.<br>   The memo, which was obtained by a Toronto newspaper, comes from the prime minister's office and suggests that Liberals say the Reform Party is in the pocket of the gun lobby, and uses the rhetoric of the extreme right in the U.S.<br>  It also says voters should be told that Reform is trying to boost its fortunes by exacerbating the tensions with Quebec and between rich and poor.
<hr>
<b>Immigration Plan</b><p>
Immigration minister Lucienne Robillard says Canada could handle a big increase in immigration -- but Canadians aren't ready to accept it.<br>   Robillard says Canada expects to welcome between 195 and 220-thousand immigrants next year.<br>   That's the same target as this year and last.
<hr>
<b>MMT Study</b><p>
An oil industry group says a controversial fuel additive that is slated to be banned by the federal government is not harmful... and they have tests to prove it.<br>  The government says the additive, "MMT", wrecks vehicles diagnostic systems and leads to increased air pollution.<br>  But the Canadian Petroleum Product Institute says it commissioned an independent test that shows MMT is safe.
<hr>
<b>Collapse Survivor</b><p>
Turning to international news, rescue workers in Cairo say it is a miracle.<br>   They pulled a Los Angeles teen-ager from the ruins of a collapsed apartment building in the Edyptian capital earlier today.<br> 18 year-old Samantha Makscher was bruised and bleeding after her 36-hour ordeal, but alive.<br>  At least 22 survivors have been found since Sunday's collapse.<br>  The unofficial death toll stands at 18.<br>   It's not known what caused the cave-in, but the city has a reputaiton for poor construction standards.
<hr>
<b>Mideast Tension</b><p>
While peace talks between Palestinians and Israelis appear deadlocked, fears are now growing that Syria may try to move the diplomatic process along with military might.<br>   
<hr>
<b>New Money</b><p>
The Ruble will never win any beauty contests, with it's majestic scenes of hydroelectric plants it may make the engineering crowd proud but other Russians have a more poetic vision of their Ruble.<br>   A campaign is underway to get the faces of famous Russians on the bills but so far the government is not agreeing to a revision.




<P>
