<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, October 28, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Ford Talks          
    <li>GM Talks U.S.       
    <li>GM - CAW              
    <li>Wilson - Docs         
    <li>Nursing Home Bill   
    <li>Runciman Bluewater  
    <li>Liberal Convention  
    <li>Trucking Poll       
    <li>Higher Fines        
    <li>Bank Rate           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Ford Talks</b><p>
Ford faces a strike deadline by its unionized workers next week.<br> The Canadian Auto Workers announced today it has set the strike deadline for 7:00 p-m, Wednesday, November 6th. Ford and the CAW began contract talks today in Toronto.<br> CAW president Buzz Hargrove thinks an agreement can be reached with Ford without a strike but he says the talks with Ford won't be a cakewalk.
<hr>
<b>GM Talks U.S.</b><p>
Meanwhile, a strike deadline has passed in the U.S.... but United Auto Workers remain on the job at General Motors' plants across the country, and the two sides are still trying to hammer out a new labor contract.<br> 
<hr>
<b>GM - CAW</b><p>
The Canadian Auto Workers union says it will back its American counterpart if it goes on strike against General Motors.  Even though bargaining continues, a strike against GM in the states would likely mean layoffs in Canada, where GM workers recently settled a three-week strike.  GM of Canada workers rely on parts from the U.S.
<hr>
<b>Wilson - Docs</b><p>
Health minister Jim Wilson is talking tough in a dispute with the province's 20-thousand doctors.<br> Wilson says his government has no intention of renegotiating a tentative agreement reached with the Ontario Medical Association.<br> Under the deal, the province would claw back about three per cent of doctors' earnings instead of the current 10 per cent.<br> However, new doctors would be forced to work in underserviced areas, like the north.<br> While the OMA supports the deal, groups representing a large number of doctors are recommending that it be voted down.<br> If there is no agreement by November 1st, some doctors say they will stop taking on new patients.<br> Doctors with the Ottawa Academy of Medicine voted against a deal with the province, they met at an Ottawa hospital yesterday and decided they cannot support an agreement that doesn't put more money into health care.  The OMA will count votes from doctors across Ontario Thursday.
<hr>
<b>Nursing Home Bill</b><p>
Hamilton East Liberal MPP Dominic Agostino is blaming the Harris government's spending cuts for a 93 year old Burlington woman being billed nine thousand dollars for her stay in Joseph Brant Hospital. Catharine Duffy has been charged 120-dollars a-day since April because she would not accept being moved to a nursing home outside the Halton region. In the legislature today... Agostino asked health minister Wilson to come to Mrs. Duffy's aid. <br>    Halton has the worst shortage of nursing home beds in Ontario.
<hr>
<b>Runciman Bluewater</b><p>
Several young offenders who say jail managers beat them following a riot last winter are suing Ontario's solicitor general over the incident.<br> The suit was delivered to solicitor general Bob Runciman today and alleges the 12 youths were "abused, tortured, manipulated and incited to riot."<br> A statement from the complainants' lawyer, Jeffrey Wilson, says "the minister apparently couldn't care less" about the youths.<br> The statement says the "young offenders seek judicial accountability, compensation for their pain and suffering."<br> Ontario's children's advocate has said that 40 young offenders were beaten after being transferred to the Elgin-Middlesex Detention Centre in London during a civil service strike last March.<br> The alleged beatings occurred after the youths were taken from the Bluewater Youth Centre in Goderich after a riot there.<br> London police and the province are investigating the allegations.
<hr>
<b>Liberal Convention</b><p>
The federal Liberal party has approved a resolution that would allow doctor-assisted suicide in Canada. But, wrapping up the party's four-day convention in Ottawa, prime minister Chretien admitted it's a delicate issue that won't be resolved swiftly. Riding high in the polls and with an election expected next year, Liberals watered down or withdrew controversial resolutions that could divide the party.  Chretien told delegates they must speak with one voice in all parts of the country.
<hr>
<b>Trucking Poll</b><p>
A new poll suggests Canadians are worried about commercial trucking safety.<br> An Angus Reid survey finds 80 per cent of respondents feel the growing number of transport trucks is making driving more dangerous.<br> The group; Canadians for Responsible and Safe Highways, is also pushing for a lower limit on the number of hours truckers can drive without a break.
<hr>
<b>Higher Fines</b><p>
New and higher truck and bus fines have taken effect in Ontario.<br> Transportation minister Al Palladini announced today that new legislation will more than triple minimum truck and bus fines from 60 dollars to between 200 and 400 dollars.<br> The legislation increases maximum trucking and bus fines by 10 times -- to 20-thousand dollars.<br> Palladini says "safety violations will simply not be tolerated on Ontario roads."<br> A statement from the minister says many companies consider existing truck fines "nothing more than the cost of doing business."<br> Palladini says he feels these higher fines will act as stronger deterrents.<br>   These changes apply equally to commercial truck drivers and intercity bus drivers.
<hr>
<b>Bank Rate</b><p>
If you're in the market for a bank loan....tomorrow could be the day. There will be another drop in interest rates. Canada's major banks are cutting their benchhmark prime lending rates tomorrow to five per cent.<br> That's down a quarter percentage point.<br> The central bank dropped its bank rate today to 3.5 per cent because the dollar has been rising on exchange markets.<br> The drop is the tenth the central bank has made this year in an effort to stoke a sputtering economy. It will likely spark another round of interest rate cuts in mortgages which are already at generational lows. The Bank of Montreal led the way this morning, cutting some of its variable mortgage rates up to a quarter of a per cent. 




<P>
