<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, October 25, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Toronto Protest 
    <li>Traffic             
    <li>Docs Vote           
    <li>St. Pete's Riots    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Toronto Protest </b><p>
Toronto stood still today.<br>  Thousands of anti-government protesters converged on the city today.<br>  Factories were shut. Schools closed. And many workers simply stayed home.<br> It was all part of Labour's Days of Action.
<hr>
<b>Traffic</b><p>
They were predicting traffic chaos.. and many people stayed home to avoid the headaches of trying to get into and around the city.... <br>    But those who did that, missed a real treat today... traffic that actually moved... traffic reporters described the pace as being that of a Sunday ... far fewer cars than usual and no problems to report... in fact the OPP could have done a booming business handing out speeding tickets the flow was so smooth and so fast.
<hr>
<b>Docs Vote</b><p>
The Harris government is facing another big test this weekend other than the big rally... a voted by Ontario's 20 thousand doctors could kill the tenative deal that the Ontario Medication Association has struck with the government. And if that happens, this province will be facing a widespread strike by doctors in exactly one week from today... Lauran Sabourin reports.
<i><br>  The doctors objections centre on a section of the agreement that bans new physicians from location in overserviced areas such as Toronto for the next two years.<br>  Dr. Robert Fallis, a family physician in St. Catharines is voting against the agreement this weekend. <br>  As he sees it forcing newer doctors into underserviced areas is canibalizing young physicians.<br>  The 2.9 foot rope is in reference to the percentage of billings the government is asking doctors to give back. <br>  Tthe Harris government was demanding a 10 percent clawback.<br>  It's agreed to reduce that to 2.9 percent. And in 1998 get rid of the clawback altogether. <br>  But the doctors say they've been cheated and lied to before and government promises down the road are probably only empty promises. <br>  The Ontario Medical Association represents the province's 20 thousand doctors.<br>  The OMA negotiated long and hard for this deal. </i>
<hr>
<b>St. Pete's Riots</b><p>
A riot erupted in St. Petersburg, Florida after a black suspect was shot and killed by a white police officer... it happened during a traffic check... the officer says the suspect was going to run him down, but witnesses say the man was standing with his hands on the hood of the car when he was killed...<br>  Appeals for calm failed... and full scale riots erupted with cars and buildilngs set on fire...<br>  Firefighters couldn't get past rioters to douse the flames...<br>  Now the mayor is calling for a review of race relations in the city.




<P>
