<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, October 24, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Protest Update      
    <li>Abbott Murder       
    <li>Meds - Warning      
    <li>Jobs Survey         
    <li>Chretien - Redbook 
    <li>Rabin - Israel        
    <li>Simpson Trial       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Protest Update</b><p>
The chairman of Toronto's transit commission says commuters should expect delays and disruptions during the two days of protests against the Harris government in Toronto. Paul Christie says, despite an injunction granted today by the Ontario Labor Relations Board, he cannot guarantee there will be transit service at all. the injunction limits picketing at transit system facilities during the days of protest. 
<hr>
<b>Abbott Murder</b><p>
The peace and quiet in the sleepy community of Fergus, northwest of Guelph, has been shattered by a murder. The body of 40-year-old Patricia Abbott was discovered by co-workers yesterday when she failed to return to work after lunch. Police are not saying how she died. Fergus police chief Rod Freeman says as far as he knows it is the first homicide in the town's history. 
<hr>
<b>Meds - Warning</b><p>
Jean Chretien is giving himself a pat on the back. The prime minister says he's kept most of his red book promises from the 1993 election. But he frankly admits the Liberal government hasn't been able to deliver on some big-ticket items. But while the PM was doing that, the Canadian Medical Association was giving the Liberals a failing grade on health care funding. They say cuts to transfer payments have had a devastating effect on the system.
<hr>
<b>Jobs Survey</b><p>
The mouth piece of Canadian small business is blaming Ottawa for a lack of job creation.<br>  In a survey of 18-thousand businesses, the Canadian Federation of Independent Business found that payroll taxes such as unemployment insurance premiums are preventing the hiring.
<hr>
<b>Chretien - Redbook </b><p>
Prime minister Jean Chretien has given himself a report card and he gets a healthy passing grade.<br>  Chretien says in the three years since the last election his government has kept seventy eight per cent of its red book election promises ... that includes things like deficit cutting and a claim by the PM that unemployment has dropped...<br>  Other promises like the one to scrap the GST, he calls "works in progress".<br>   
<hr>
<b>Rabin - Israel</b><p>
Israel's prime minister is urging unity as the Jewish state mourns Yitzhak Rabin. Benjamin Netanyahu says the choice is to unite or fall apart. Rabin's family holds Netanyahu partly to blame for the climate that led to the murder. Israelis lit candles, wept and said prayers for Rabin today to mark the year since his assassination, according to the Hebrew calendar.
<hr>
<b>Simpson Trial</b><p>
The defence has told O.J. Simpson's civil trial that the former football star remained close to Nicole Brown Simpson after their break-up. Robert Baker told jurors today that Simpson was "her confidant, her friend, not her stalker." Baker started his opening statement after John Kelly wrapped up remarks for the plaintiffs in the wrongful death suit -- the families of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ron Goldman. He said Simpson had an "uncontrollable rage" toward his ex-wife and a volatile chain of events prompted him to kill her.




<P>
