<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, October 22, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>G.M. Settles         
    <li>Days of Action      
    <li>Days Action Follow   
    <li>Kitchener Crash     
    <li>OPP Blitz           
    <li>California Fires    
    <li>Godfrey Milliken    
    <li>Flu Season          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M. Settles</b><p>
After marathon bargaining, negotiators for General Motors and the Canadian Auto Workers union today reached a tentative contract in their talks in Toronto.<br>   CAW president Buzz Hargrove calls it a "win-win" agreement while GM chief negotiator Dean Munger calls it a good deal.<br>   The agreement includes a pledge by GM to recognize limits on contracting out work and the sale of facilities.<br>   The union has agreed to let GM sell two parts plants in Windsor and Oshawa, affecting 35-hundred members.<br>   But Hargrove says the union has negotiated terms that protect the workers' wages and benefits.                 <br>     Ratification votes will be held tomorrow and some striking workers could be back on the job as early as tomorrow night.
<hr>
<b>Days of Action</b><p>
Labor groups are vowing to shut down Toronto on Friday in a protest against the Harris government.<br>  Today the first rally marking the beginning of "the Days of Action" got under way.<br>  Meanwhile lawyers for the Toronto Transit Commission and Pearson Internatinal Airport are in court trying to get injunctions to keep both facilities from being closed down by picketers on Friday.
<hr>
<b>Days Action Follow</b><p>
Not everyone is concerned about how Friday's massive protest will affect business in Toronto.<br>   A survey shows downtown Toronto hotels are booked solid for Thursday night.<br>  And the rooms have not gone cheap.<br>   The average single occupancy for a room is more than 120 dollars.<br>   That same room today can be had for just 78 dollars.<br>   Many restaurant owners in downtown Toronto also expect to cash in during the labor protest.
<hr>
<b>Kitchener Crash</b><p>
Waterloo region police say it's a miracle that five teens survived the crash of a van being driven by a 13-year-old Toronto boy.<br>   The stolen van swerved off a Kitchener street around one o'clock this morning and smashed into a tree.<br>  Three of the people in the car were from Etobicoke, two from Kitchener.<br>  All suffered injuries.<br>   Police say the speedometer on the van was frozen at 93 kilometres an hour.
<hr>
<b>OPP Blitz</b><p>
Provincial police in the greater Toronto area are launching a crackdown on people who drive without insurance.<br>   And they're getting some corporate help.<br>   Cantel is providing officers with free cellular service so they can call insurance companies to check whether a drivers' policy is valid.<br>   The Insurance Bureau of Canada is having its member companies field the calls.               <br>     The blitz, which begins November 1st coincides with an increase in fines for driving without insurance, from a minimum of 500 dollars to a minimum of five-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>California Fires</b><p>
Firefighters in southern California have their hands full as they battle wind-driven wildfires.<br>   The latest count has about 100 homes damaged or destroyed by the fires.<br>   Thousands of hectares have gone up in smoke.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Godfrey Milliken</b><p>
Two Liberal MP's have introduced legislation in the commons to spoof the U.S. Helms Burton Act.<br>   That's an American law aimed at punishing foreigners, including Canadians, who profit from the property American investors lost in the Cuban revolution.<br>   John Godfrey and Peter Milliken say the same punishment should apply for the U.S. revolution when Canadian ancestors lost their property.
<hr>
<b>Flu Season</b><p>
Along with the changing of the seasons comes another kind of season... flu season.<br>  The Lung Association is encouraging people to get a flu shot.<br>  Some people are more at risk than others.




<P>
