<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, October 21, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>G.m. Settles        
    <li>Doc's Deal          
    <li>Gerard Kennedy      
    <li>QP Mon.             
    <li>Smoke - Minors      
    <li>Election Law        
    <li>Rose Speech         
    <li>Belgium Pedophiles  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M. Settles</b><p>
The head of the Canadian Auto Workers union says he hopes to have a tentative settlement ironed out with General Motors by the end of the day.<br>  Buzz Hargrove told reporters at a briefing in Toronto that the two sides have made enormous progress over the last 40 hours of marathon bargaining.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i> <br>  The 26 thousand striking auto workers were receiving mixed messages all day.<br>  News reports from Toronto this morning said a deal has been struck on the critical issue of outsourcing.<br>  Phone calls to members of the master bargaining team said hold on ...<br>  Then this afternoon at 3:30 CAW leader Buzz Hargrove said no deal yet.. <br>  But members of the strike committee in St. Catharines have been summoned to Toronto tomorrow.  <br>  They want to learn the details on the critical issue of outsourcing.<br>  They want all other smaller issues resolved. <br>  Workers on the picket line aren't elated yet.<br>  They want to know what they're going to have to give up to ensure their jobs are here for at least another three years.<br>  Despite the fact that their leader Buzz Hargrove is optimistic about a deal, the membership wants to see it first.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Doc's Deal</b><p>
An agreement between the Ontario government and the province's doctors  was reached over the week-end.<br>   The deal should end a threatened job-action by physicians set for november first.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Gerard Kennedy</b><p>
MPP Gerard Kennedy has established himself as the man to beat in the Ontario Liberal leadership race.<br>   Kennedy, a former director of Toronto's Daily Bread Food Bank, has the strongest support among delegates to next month's Liberal Leadership Convention in Toronto.<br>   Unofficial results of delegate selection during the weekend show Kennedy has the backing of 469 delegates.<br>   Toronto MPP Joe Cordiano took 338 while labor critic Dwight Duncan of Windsor is third with 279 delegates.<br>   Also in the race are Ottawa member Dalton McGuinty, former Kingston mayor John Gerretsen, Toronto legislator Annamarie Castrilli, and Ottawa businessman Greg Kells.
<hr>
<b>QP Mon.</b><p>
Taxpayers shouldn't hold their breaths waiting for a broadly based tax cut.<br>   Finance minister Paul Martin dismissed the notion Monday, but hinted there may be selective tax reductions. He gave no details.        <br>   Martin was pressed in the Commons by Reform Party MPs who have argued that tax cuts after the federal budget is balanced, would boost the country's economy.
<hr>
<b>Smoke - Minors</b><p>
Manufacturers, distributors and retailers have joined forces to launch an I.D. card program.<br>  In an effort to stop children from smoking, a coalition of tobaco companies, distributors and retailers have announced a new "zero tollerance" policy for cigarette sales.<br>  It's called operation I.D.<br>  The coaltion says it will provide training for retail level employees to ensure those without proper identification can't get cigarettes.
<hr>
<b>Election Law</b><p>
The federal government today tabled legislation that would shorten the length of elections and create a permanent list of electors.<br>  Instead of going door-to-door, federal enumerators would use government records to create a permanent list.<br>  Canada's chief electoral officer says the new list could save the government time and money... over 30 million dollars for each election.           <br>  Elections currently last for 47 days.<br>   The bill would shorten the campaign to 36 days.<br>  Any possible changes to polling hours across the country are contained in a private members bill.
<hr>
<b>Rose Speech</b><p>
The former commander of U.N. forces in Bosnia says countries like Canada, should have an emergency force ready for U.N. emergencies.<br>  General Sir Michael Rose is in Ottawa for meetings with external affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy.<br>  Rose says the United Nations must be able to get peacekeepers on the ground quickly to keep crises from getting out of control.
<hr>
<b>Belgium Pedophiles</b><p>
In international news, hundreds of thousands of people marched in Brussels in an outpouring of anger over the killing of four girls by a gang of pedophiles.<br>  




