<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, October 18, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Physcians Update    
    <li>Tobacco - Cancer      
    <li>Protest - Roundup     
    <li>Rae - Book           
    <li>Children - Survey     
    <li>Guelph Flood        
    <li>BC Storm            
    <li>Car - Restaurant      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Physcians Update</b><p>
Pediatricians in Niagara are the latest group to add their voice to the chorus of agitated Ontario doctors.<br> The pediatricians are talking about withdrawing services from area hospitals, unless the government drops its demand to reduce doctors pay.<br>  Also in southwestern Ontario the Coalition of Family Physicians of Ontario is urging family doctors to refer patients only to specialists who support their job action.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  Physicians in Niagara are developing a reputation of being among the most militant in the province.<br>  First it was the obstetricians who  are refusing to take new patients.<br>  Then the orthopedic surgeons refusing to treat emergency cases.<br>  Now it's the area pediatricians who are talking about withdrawing their services from area hospitals.<br> Talk that makes hospital administrators nervous. <br>  What will the hospitals do.<br>  Provisions can be made to rush kids to Buffalo or Hamilton.<br>  But when you're dealing with an injured child that plan doesn't seem workable.<br>  Still the pediatricians feel job action may be the only way to make the government listen.<br>  The government's position is that it has to reduce health costs.<br>  Fee clawbacks and other monetary cutbacks are necessary.<br>  An arugment the peditricians don't buy especailly when they hear reports that arrangements have been made to deliver some babies at hospitals in Detroit.<br>  At fees running into the thousands. </i>
<hr>
<b>Tobacco - Cancer</b><p>
For years, tobacco companies have been saying there is no scientific proof to link cigarettes to lung cancer. Now there is. Scientists have now established a direct link between the "tar" in cigarette tobacco; and the development of cancerous cells in lung tissue. The results of the study are reported in the latest issue of the journal, "Science".
<hr>
<b>Protest - Roundup</b><p>
The battle of Toronto, is turning into a rough, and bloody affair.<br>  Protest organizers for next Friday's days of protest rally in Toronto ... say they may have to drop a promise not to interfere with the prestigious "Breeders Cup" horse race at Woodbine Race Track, next Saturday.<br>  Ontario Federation of Labour president Gord Wilson says; protestors may be forced to disrupt the race; because the federal government has gone to court; seeking an injunction that would prevent pickets from shutting down pearson airport.<br>  that's not the only injunction the courts have to consider; the TTC is also seeking relief from protest pickets.<br>   They want an injunction to keep protestors from blocking access to the system, during the two day labour demonstration.
<hr>
<b>Rae - Book </b><p>
On September 6th, 1990 Bob Rae and the New Democratic Party of Ontario celebrated one of the most stunning election victories in provincial history.<br>  Five turbulent years later, Rae's New Democrats went down to defeat as Mike Harris's Tories swept to power.<br>  Mr. Rae has since left the political arena and is now a partner at the Canadian international law firm of Goodman, Phillips and Vineberg.<br>  He has documented his political career in a new book entitled "From Protest to Power ... Personal Reflections on a Life in Politics."<br>  
<hr>
<b>Children - Survey</b><p>
 Ward and June Cleaver may be alive and well, and living in Canada. The fictional TV family of the 60's sitcom Leave it to Beaver... may have more in common with modern Canadian families, than you might think. That; according to Statistics Canada. A new, landmark survey of children in this country by Statscan, reveals that the vast majority under the age of 12: ... live in a two-parent family. Most, with their biological parents. The most obvious difference between modern families, and the Cleavers ....for 36 percent of the two-parent families in this country; mom is at work, and not in the kitchen. And despite that extra effort to earn money for the family ... 28 percent of children in this country live in families with incomes below the poverty line.
<hr>
<b>Guelph Flood</b><p>
Two investigations are underway in Guelph today, after vandals broke into a control room at a dam on the Speed River, and opened one of five flood gates. The breech sent water levels soaring to ten times their normal rates of flow ... and caused widespread flooding and minor damage, along the banks of the river. The OPP are looking into who was responsible. The regional conservation authority is investigating how the vandals managed to by-pass security, and activate the gate.
<hr>
<b>BC Storm</b><p>
Meanwhile, on the west coast, cleanup efforts are underway in British Columbia following the worst storm in more than three decades. Environment Canada called the storm, "a marine bomb"... and said at times, windspeeds reached hurricane force. More than 30 milimeters of rain fell on southern BC.  Hardest hit was Vancouver Island where more than 17-thousand homes .... most in the Victoria area... are still without power. At least one traffic death is blamed on the storm; and damage to boats and pleasure craft in the area, will run into the millions.
<hr>
<b>Car - Restaurant</b><p>
Three women were injured in Toronto this afternoon ... when a car smashed through the window of a restaurant in the Yonge, and Lawrence area ...and travelled the length of the eatery, before coming to a halt against a wall. One of the injured women was pinned beneath the vehicle. She was taken to hospital; but her condition is not known at this time. Police are still investigating the cause of the accident.




<P>
