<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, October 17, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>Reform Announcement 
    <li>G.M. - St. Kitts      
    <li>Labor Ruling        
    <li>Peres 
    <li>Russia Coup         
    <li>Hurricane Lili      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Reform Announcement</b><p>
Reform Party leader Preston Manning is offering Canadians lower taxes and more spending on social programs.<br>  The party unveiled a six point campaign platform in London Ontario today, designed to win back mainstream support.<br>   Reform promises to maintain or increase spending on health and social programs, while at the same time cutting taxes. 
<hr>
<b>G.M. - St. Kitts</b><p>
The head of the Canadian Auto Workers union says he hopes there's a deal to end the GM Canada strike by Monday.<br>   Until yesterday, there was little optimism for a quick end to the two-week strike by 26-thousand workers.<br> But , the break came during a meeting with General Motors chair, Jack Smith.
<hr>
<b>Labor Ruling</b><p>
An Ontario Labor Relations Board ruling could set a legal precedent for next week's planned labor demonstration in Toronto.<br>   The ruling, says the walkout by General Motors employees during last December's Labor Day of Protest in London, was illegal.<br>   But the head of the Ontario Federation of Labor says he'll ignore the ruling.<br>   Gord Wilson says the board is becoming more controlled by the province and he considers it "biased."
<hr>
<b>Peres </b><p>
He is an eternal optimist for peace in the middle east ...and last night, former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres was in Hamilton.<br>  Peres shared his dreams for peace before an audience of close to 800 people.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Russia Coup</b><p>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin has dismissed his security chief, Alexander Lebed. He announced the news on national television. The decision comes one day after Russia's interior minister accused the ambitious Lebed of building his own rogue army in an attempt to seize power. A scowling Yeltsin told the TV audience the behavior of the controversial former general was damaging to the country. The move comes after weeks of bitter feuding between Lebed and other senior members of the government that culminated in charges this week that the former general was plotting a coup.
<hr>
<b>Hurricane Lili</b><p>
Forecasters now say they're "cautiously optimistic" that hurricane "Lili" will miss the United States. The storm's outer fringes are already dumping rain in Cuba and the Florida Keys. But the National Hurricane Centre in Miami says the system should make a sharp turn to the east. If the computers projections are right that would keep "Lili's" worst winds offshore. On the other hand, even a tiny error in those projections could spell trouble for Florida -- so the experts are urging residents to stay tuned. Some residents have already started stocking up on supplies just in case.




