<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, October 16, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>GM Sit In          
    <li>Breast Screening    
    <li>Post Secondary Panel
    <li>Chretien            
    <li>Britain Gun Ban     
    <li>Hitler Painting     
    <li>Jagger Divorce      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM Sit In</b><p>
Striking autworkers have ended their sit-in at the General Motors fabrication plant in Oshawa.<br>   They had occupied the building to stop the company from removing dies it says would be used in the production of auto components for a non-GM customer.                 <br>   GM agreed to stop efforts to obtain an injunction to remove the equipment -- if the striking workers left the building.<br>   The truce is to last until noon on Monday.
<hr>
<b>Breast Screening</b><p>
The Tory government says its decision to boost funding for breast cancer screening will save thousands of lives.<br>   Premier Mike Harris says the province will spend 24.3-million dollars over the next four years to create about 30 new mamogram screening sites over the next four years.<br>   Harris and health minister Jim Wilson say that means about four times the number of women who can now be screened will have the service available.
<hr>
<b>Post Secondary Panel</b><p>
Meanwhile, coping with less is an issue colleges and universities are trying to deal with.<br>  A provincial panel is touring Ontario seeking answers to the problem and today they came to Hamilton.<br>  The panel heard that Ontario's colleges and universities can learn a lesson from the health care system.<br>  Dwight Ryan has the story.
<i><br>  The advisory panel on post secondary education is travelling the province looking for answers.<br>  How is Ontario's post secondary education system going to remain effective and competitive with fewer government dollars.<br>  In Hamilton, a myriad of answers from college and university executives coping with less.<br>  Mohawk College president Keith Macintyre told panel members that 25 percent of total educational costs should be paid by the student.<br>  As well, second degrees or post graduate studies should not receive any government funding.  That money should be diverted to undergraduate studies in universities and colleges, thus giving more young people a chance.   <br>  He believes its the wave of the future.   <br>       McMaster president Dr. Peter George believes amalgamation makes some sense ...sometimes.<br>  First, he says, the government must remove barriers to cooperation and provide funding for the transition.   <br>    Amalgamation is just one issue the advisory panel will mull over before making a final report to education minister John Snobelen by December 15th.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Chretien</b><p>
Canadians are being told that social programs should come before tax cuts.<br>   Prime Minister Jean Chretien says once Canada's deficit is eliminated, he'd rather sink tax dollars into new social programs than return them to taxpayers.<br>   Chretien told the party faithful in Toronto last night that Liberal policies are kick-starting the economy by permitting low interest rates.         <br>  The prime minister also took shots at the Reform Party's call for tax relief and job creation.<br>   Preparing for an election, Preston Manning is expected to reveal his economic platform tomorrow while on a tour of Ontario.
<hr>
<b>Britain Gun Ban</b><p>
Britain's government has some strict new gun laws.<br>   All but the smallest calibre handguns are being outlawed.<br>   In addition, 22-calibre and smaller handguns must be stored at licensed gun clubs.<br>   The crackdown was prompted by the massacre last March in Dunblane, Scotland.<br>   A madman who had a licence for four handguns killed 16 children, a teacher and then himself.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Hitler Painting</b><p>
Jewish groups in Britain are calling the auction of Nazi memorabilia in Lincolnshire offensive.<br>  One of the lots is a water colour, apparently painted by Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler when he was a student.<br>  The painting, which military experts claim is genuine, has attracted widespread interest and controversy.
<hr>
<b>Jagger Divorce</b><p>
Jerry Hall can't get any satisfaction from Rolling Stones' lead singer Mick Jagger, so she wants a divorce.<br>  Britain's "Sun" tabloid says the 40-year-old model is furious over reports Jagger had two recent liaisons in Los Angeles -- one with actress Uma Thurman and another with a Czech model.<br>  Jagger and Hall have been married for six years, but have lived together for nearly 20 and have three children.





<P>
