<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, October 15, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>GM Strike U.S.       
    <li>Auditor's Report    
    <li>Tobin               
    <li>Somalia Book        
    <li>Hussein Jericho     
    <li>Pope Home           
    <li>Madonna Mom         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM Strike U.S.</b><p>
The GM Canada strike has now forced the layoff of 10-thousand General Motors workers in the U.S. and Mexico.<br>   As talks to end the strike resumed in Toronto today, Canadian Auto Workers president Buzz Hargrove said he was optimistic a deal could be hammered out this week.<br>   GM, in the meantime, reports third-quarter profits of 1.27 billion dollars -- up nearly 100 per cent from last year.<br>   The union is likely to use that to argue GM can afford the CAW's job security demands. 
<hr>
<b>Auditor's Report</b><p>
Whether you're on welfare or have a seat in the corporate boardroom... it's still too easy to cheat the government. That's the finding of provincial auditor Erik Peters. His annual report says the government isn't doing enough to weed out tax and welfare cheaters. But he's also critical to the government's record in enforcing environmental standards, especially air quality. 
<hr>
<b>Tobin</b><p>
Quebec's natural resources minister says a 1984 document which says Hydro-Quebec was willing to re-negotiate the controversial Churchill Falls power agreement was never formally approved by both sides.<br>   Newfoundland Premier Brian Tobin says the document indicates that Hydro-Quebec and Newfoundland and Labrador Hydro officials agreed that Newfoundland should be given more compensation.<br>   But Quebec natural resources minister Guy Chevrette says while the document was signed by two secretaries, it was never formally approved.
<hr>
<b>Somalia Book</b><p>
Accusations of waste, neglect and abuse in Canada's military.<br>  A new book on Canada's Armed Forces says soldiers in the field are suffering for the bad decisions of bureaucrats.<br>  "Tarnished Brass" says national defence has wasted more than 4 billion dollars while denying troops the equipment they need.<br>  It's author also has some advice for the military's new chief.
<hr>
<b>Hussein Jericho</b><p>
Palestinian president Yasser Arafat says he's ready to have U.S. troops guard Jewish settlers in the west bank town of Hebron, if that will help calm Israel's security fears.<br>  Arafat was speaking to the media during a news conference today with Jordan's King Hussein.<br>  Hussein flew to the west bank on Tuesday to meet with the Palestinian leader.<br>  This is his first visit to the region since Israel captured the territory in 1967.<br>  King Hussein told the media that he will do anything he can to help with the peace process in the region.
<hr>
<b>Pope Home</b><p>
Doctors removed stitches from Pope John Paul today and gave him the green light to return to the Vatican a week after his appendix removed.<br>   Before leaving hospital, the pontiff bid farewell to young patients on the floor.<br>   Doctors said they hope the 76-year-old Pope takes it easy as he recuperates.<br>  He resumed work from his hospital bed, days after the operation last week.
<hr>
<b>Madonna Mom</b><p>
Madonna is now a mama.<br>  The singer-actress delivered a healthy six-pound, nine-ounce baby girl in Los Angeles yesterday.<br>  The baby's name is Lourdes Maria Ciccone Leon.<br>   The baby's father is Carlos Leon, a personal trainer and Madonna's boyfriend.<br>  





<P>
