<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, October 14, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>GM 
    <li>Moms - Support      
    <li>Unity Rally         
    <li>Hydro Sale          
    <li>Morin Inquiry       
    <li>Manning - Ontario     
    <li>Year 2000 Bug       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM</b><p>
Not much to be giving thanks for today....if you work for General Motors.<br> Negotiations aimed at ending the strike at GM Canada are to resume tomorrow but substantial progress is not expected. More than 26-thousand union members have shut down GM's Canadian operations to back their demand that the automaker limit the practice of contracting out jobs. The number of General Motors employees on layoff south of the border continues to grown as well, almost 43-hundred are affected, because plants either can't get parts from Canada, or can't ship their parts to Canada. In Oshawa today those on the picket line are digging in for what they feel could be a long dispute.     
<hr>
<b>Moms - Support</b><p>
There are a lot of frustrated single mothers who are still waiting for familty support payments. They are the ones who have little to be thankful for today as they try to make ends meet while trying to keep their children sheltered, clothed and fed.<br>  Jamie West has the story of one woman who's up to her neck in red tape...
<i><br>  Agnes Scheer hasn't received a family support payment since August. The now unemployed collections clerk, has a son to support and is worried about making ends meet. <BR>Specifically the family support plan...several offices including Hamilton were closed this spring as part of a money saving centralization plan.<br>  Now eventhough Anthony's father pay's support faithfully, a number of beaureaucratic errors have forced Agnes to create a paper trail of documents trying to recover what's rightfully hers ...<br>  No cheque ever arrived...and the frustation is building...<br>  The closest thing to an explanation is a letter from the government apologizing for the errors, and an appeal for understanding during the re-adjustment of staff working for the family support plan.<br>  At last word Agnes has been promised the 15-hundred dollars owed within the next two days.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Unity Rally</b><p>
A lawyer for a group of Ottawa-area residents says Quebec has no right to charge people who live outside the province.<br> The charges relate to last year's huge unity rally in Montreal before the October referendum.<br> Marc-andre Fabien will ask a Montreal court tomorrow to throw out the charges against 17 people, companies and groups from both inside and outside the province.<br> They're accused of illegal spending under Quebec's Referendum Act.
<hr>
<b>Hydro Sale</b><p>
The Harris government appears to be putting any sale of Ontario Hydro on the backburner.<br> Energy minister Norm Sterling says any action is two to four years away, suggesting a sale wouldn't take place before the next election.<br> Ontario Hydro is the largest electric utility in North America, with 43-billion dollars in assets, but it also carries huge debts.<br> Investment bankers and a provincial commission have urged the government to sell off some assets but public support for that is lukewarm at best.
<hr>
<b>Morin Inquiry</b><p>
January 27th is the tentative start date for the public inquiry into Guy Paul Morin's wrongful murder conviction.<br> That was the date discussed by lawyers at a closed-door meeting last week.<br> Sources say that a number of legal issues are already brewing. They include whether inquiry commissioner Fred Kaufman should warn parties at the start of the probe that findings of misconduct might be made against them.<br> Morin was convicted in 1992 of the first-degree murder of his next-door neighbor, nine-year-old Christine Jessop of Queensville.<br> He was acquitted last year because of DNA evidence.
<hr>
<b>Manning - Ontario</b><p>
Preston Manning is calling it a fresh start.<br> But some believe his four-day tour of voter and riding-rich southern Ontario this week could help decide whether there is any future for the Reform Party as a national political force.<br> Manning's fresh start campaign opens tomorrow in Newmarket, just north of Toronto.<br> His goal is to outline an election plan that will persuade voters there's more to reform than a right-wing party opposed to gun control and gay rights.<br> Manning will announce an economic program that includes plans to eliminate the deficit, slash taxes and create jobs, all while maintaining spending on social programs.
<hr>
<b>Year 2000 Bug</b><p>
It seems its a condition that everyone just forgot about. Computer use in the last few years has grown from simple games to a device that plays a major role in every facet of our lives. The condition everyone forgot about is the date, and come the year two thousand...plus one second, your computer could face a near fatal bug. A bug they are calling the year 2000 bug. 





<P>
