<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, October 11, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>School Bds. Nixed    
    <li>GM Robinson         
    <li>Toronto Hash
    <li>Victims' Services   
    <li>House of Horror     
    <li>Nobel Peace Prize   
    <li>Vickery Obit        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>School Bds. Nixed</b><p>
An education ministry spokesperson denies that the Harris government is on the verge of scrapping all school boards in the province, and replacing them with regional councils.<br>   Such a move could save the government one billion dollars in education costs.<br>   
<hr>
<b>GM Robinson</b><p>
Striking General Motors workers got some support today from a prominent New Democrat.<br>   MP Svend Robinson walked the picket line outside a GM plant in St. Catharines, Ontario.<br>   Negotiations to end the strike are pretty much on hold over the Thanksgiving weekend, with only top negotiators standing by in case of a change in position.<br>   A report by a U.S. newspaper says GM stockpiled parts in American plants to prevent the Canadian strike from quickly idling many U.S. operations.
<hr>
<b>Toronto Hash</b><p>
A twelve year old Toronto girl has been arrested and charged with trafficking .... after police seized more than 100 grams of hashish: part of a missing brick of hash that was cut up and distributed to Toronto school kids.<br>  Police say the girl had made elaborate plans to distribute the cache of hash, and cover her tracks, while cashing in, on the sale of the drug.
<hr>
<b>Victims' Services</b><p>
The Ontario government wants to right  the wrongs that have been perpetrated by the justice system against crime victims.<br>  Attorney general Charles Harnick acknowledged today that crime victims are often treated shabbily by the system.<br>  And the government is taking the first step toward treating crime victims fairly.
<hr>
<b>House of Horror</b><p>
It was about this time last year that the home, where Paul Bernardo carried out his notorious crimes, was demolished.<br>  Ironically, a hauntingly similar scene is now being carried out at a house of horors in London England.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Nobel Peace Prize</b><p>
In Oslo this morning...the Nobel Committee awarded the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize to two "resistance movement" leaders from east Timor ...a former Portuguese colony ...annexed by Indonesia in 1975.<br>    The award of 1-point-twelve million dollars went to Bishop Carlos Bay-low and Jose Ramos-horta.<br>    
<hr>
<b>Vickery Obit</b><p>
Meanwhile, some sad and shocking news about another Nobel Prize winner.<br>   Three days after winning the Nobel Prize for economics, Canadian born economist William Vickery has died.<br>  Columbia University announced that the 82 year old professor of economics died behind the steering wheel of his car, this morning.





