<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, October 10, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>GM - Windsor      
    <li>Bowmanville Court   
    <li>Education Cuts      
    <li>Enviro Policy       
    <li>Auto Insurance      
    <li>Young Photo         
    <li>CBC Inquiry         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM - Windsor</b><p>
There won't be a quick end to the strike by General Motors workers in Canada.<br>   The two sides in the dispute are taking a break from negotiations.<br>   Talks are on hold until after the Thanksgiving holiday weekend.<br>  All of the 25 thousand Canadian GM workers are now on strike, including 22 hundred at the plants in Windsor.<br>  The workers expect to be in for a long haul saying their future remains uncertain, unless "outsourcing" is stopped.
<hr>
<b>Bowmanville Court</b><p>
A suspect in the abduction and sexual assault of a four-year-old girl kicked at reporters as he entered an Oshawa court house today.<br>   Police arrested the man yesterday after the girl was found in a garden shed several hours after she vanished from her home in Bowmanville.<br>  21 year-old Coulson Donald Woolner of no fixed address is charged with sexual assault, kidnapping, forcible confinement and breaking and entering.<br>   Woolner tried to cover his face with his clothing during the brief court appearance.
<hr>
<b>Education Cuts</b><p>
Parent groups across the province are mobilizing to protest the Harris governments cuts to education.<br>  They say the budget cuts are having a direct effect on their children's education.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Enviro Policy</b><p>
Ontario's environment commissioner has slammed the harris government for changing environmental regulations too fast and without enough public input.<br>  Eva Ligeti says she suports progressive environmental reform, but she says poor decisions are made when experts and the general public are excluded from the process. <br> Ligeti calls on the Harris government to give Ontarians more time, information and opportunity to comment on proposed changes to envirenmental laws.
<hr>
<b>Auto Insurance</b><p>
Car insurance in Ontario will be dramatically different starting three weeks from tomorrow.<br>  By now, your auto insurer has probably sent you some pamphlets outlining changes to the system.<br>   You'll probably pay less for car insurance under the new rules, but you'll also be getting less.<br>  The story tonight from Dwight Ryan.  
<i><br>  Dramatic changes are about to take place in Ontario's auto insurance industry.<br>  For two years, the industry has been working under the New Democrats' bill 164.   Rates didn't drop the way we thought they would...and we lost the right to sue in the event of an accident.<br>  But the Tories promised yet another revamp of auto insurance. And starting November 1st, it'll be here...bill 59.   <br>    But, for more money you can have more coverage.<br>  Hamilton insurance broker Russ McEdwards says most people buy their insurance on price alone.   <br>    As a broker, Russ McEdwards represents seven insurance companies.  Each will offer different options.  You have to make your own decision on what's best for you.   <br>      If your renewal date comes after November 1st, you'll get the old coverage at the new rate. And you could be in for a premium rebate.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Young Photo</b><p>
The military says strange things happen when people deal with death day-to-day.<br>  A Vancouver newspaper has obtained photographs showing Canadian soldiers posing with the corpse of an Iraqi killed by a mine at the end of the gulf war.<br>   Soldiers formerly based in Chilliwack, B.C. are shown posing in front of the corpse and body parts during their six-month U-N mine-sweeping mission.<br>   Military officials admit the photos come across as distasteful, but say the soldiers did "nothing illegal or rude" to the body.<br>   But defence minister Doug Young disagrees.
<hr>
<b>CBC Inquiry</b><p>
The federal government's commissioner of official languages says budget cuts to the CBC may isolate anglophone and francophone minorities across the country.<br>  That's why commissioner Victor Goldbloom is launching a formal investigation into the CBC cuts.           <br>  Goldbloom has written a letter to heritage minister Sheila Copps, asking her to reconsider the CBC budget cuts.<br>  He is also studying whether the cuts violate the spirit of the Official Languages Act.<br>  The act says Ottawa is obligated to support the vitality of official language minority communities.





