<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, October 9, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Bowmanville Girl    
    <li>Corrupt Gambling    
    <li>Education Changes   
    <li>Gas Prices          
    <li>Med School Booze    
    <li>Smoke In Eyes       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bowmanville Girl</b><p>
A four year girl who was taken from her home in Bowmanville early this morning was sexually assaulted.<br>  The girl was found in a shed about five hours after her disappearance.<br>  A 21-year-old man has been taken into custody.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Corrupt Gambling</b><p>
Solicitor general Bob Runciman says he hasn't seen a police report warning of organized crime involvement in Ontario casinos and lotteries.<br>   Premier Mike Harris says he hasn't read it either.<br>   The report by the criminal intelligence service is so secret, the legislature's own justice committee was denied access to it earlier this year.<br>   It warns Ontario's multi- billion dollar gaming business is virtually unpoliced, and open to mob infiltration.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Education Changes</b><p>
Ontario education minister John Snobelen announced today that standardized report cards will be introduced in the province's schools as early as this November.<br>   Three different models of the standard report card will be field-tested in about 900-english and french language schools across Ontario in time for the first set of exams in November.<br>  According to the education minister, the new report cards will give parents more precise and consistant information on their children's progress in school. <br>  The education minister says the final report card for grades one through nine is to be introduced in all schools, for the 1997-98 school year.
<hr>
<b>Gas Prices</b><p>
If an Ontario Liberal MP gets his way, the big oil companies will have to give 30 days notice of gas price hikes.<br>  Dan McTeague's private members bill has passed two major hurdles in the house of commons.<br>  The bill would ammend the competition act to force oil companies to warn the government whenever they intend to raise gas prices by one percent or more.<br>  Industry minister John Manley says that would effectively end competiton in the retail gas industry.
<hr>
<b>Med School Booze</b><p>
The subject and the problem of substance abuse doesn't get the attention by doctors that it deserves.<br>  That from Ontario's five medical schools which have now teamed up to create an undergraduate education program, that will steer student doctors towards a better understanding of addiction....<br>  Jamie West reports...
<i><br>  It's actually an embarrasing situation. <br>  That's how McMaster University medical professor Doctor Doug Wilson describes the lack of formal undergraduate training in medical schools on addictions.<br>  Now a five year co-operative venture between Ontario's five medical schools and the Addiction Research Foundation will produce solid teaching strategies to help med students and faculty better understand alcohol and other drug problems.<br>  Dr. Wilson says millions of healthcare dollars could be saved...and lives if doctors treated the problem much more seriously...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Smoke In Eyes</b><p>
Researchers have been searching for what causes one of the most common types of blindness that primarily strikes older people.<br>  A new study has some answers.<br>   





