<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, October 8, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>Boyle Resigns       
    <li>Canada Post         
    <li>Auto Talks          
    <li>Harris - Libraries    
    <li>Sweatshop Demo      
    <li>Diana               
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Boyle Resigns</b><p>
General Jean Boyle has resigned as the head of the military.<br>   Boyle sent his resignation letter to prime minister Chretien, who promptly accepted it.<br>   Both Boyle and David Collenette, who resigned as defence minister last Friday, were under fire for weeks over the Somalia affair.<br>   But the departing chief of the defence staff says his conscience is clear and the criticism that he has endured is unfounded.
<hr>
<b>Canada Oost</b><p>
Canada Post will no longer deliver unaddressed flyers in most communities.<br>   Diane Marleau, the minister in charge of the post office, has decided to end ad-mail deliveries by Canada Post, if there's a private company available to deliver it.<br>   The recommendation was part of a review of Canada Post.<br>   The review found that private companies had a point when they complained that Canada Post uses stamp revenue to undercut the competition in other delivery services.
<hr>
<b>Auto Talks</b><p>
The head of the Canadian Auto Workers says there's no way to stop the strike at GM Canada from expanding into its final phase.<br>   More than 20-thousand General Motors workers are on strike and Buzz Hargrove says another five-thousand CAW members will join them tomorrow at midnight.<br>   Hargrove says workers in London, Woodstock and Windsor, will join the strike, following the lead of workers in Oshawa and St. Catharines, and Ste. Therese Quebec.<br>   Meanwhile GM in the United States has begun closing some plants that supply parts to operations in Canada.<br>   However some industry watchers say GM anticipated the Canadian strike by stockpiling both parts and vehicles.
<hr>
<b>Harris - Libraries</b><p>
Premier Mike Harris says his government will take action against school boards that cut into classroom education.<br>  Harris made the statement after opposition MPPs claimed his government's spending cuts were responsible for the closure of some school libraries.
<hr>
<b>Sweatshop Demo</b><p>
Ontario labor minister Elizabeth Witmer has promised a compete review of the province's employment standards act.<br>  The minister was taken to task in the legislature today for allowing sweatshops to operate in Ontario.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Diana</b><p>
It looks like that videotape that was said to show Princess Diana frolicking with her former riding instructor is bogus.<br>   The Sun newspaper published shots from the video but now says it was the victim of "one of the most elaborate hoaxes of the decade."<br>   The paper has apologized profusely to the Princess and riding instructor James Hewitt, with whom she had a five-year affair.<br>  The 80-second tape, also broadcast on Sky TV News, shows a woman looking very similar to diana stripping down to her sports briefs and bra, frolicking with a man who resembles Hewitt.






<P>
