<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, October 7, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>GM - Tonawanda       
    <li>Defence Chief       
    <li>Bourassa            
    <li>Spanking            
    <li>TTC Shutdown?       
    <li>Smoking By-law      
    <li>Pope Surgery        
    <li>Fergie - Book         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM - Tonawanda</b><p>
As we've been hearing all day, the strike at General Motors Canada is leading to more layoffs on both sides of the Canada-U.S. border.<br> A GM official says 800 workers will be laid off tonight at a transmission plant in Ypsilanti (ip'-sil-ant-ee), just outside Detroit. Earlier today, workers were sent home from a GM powertrain plant in Tonawanda, New York, near Buffalo. More than 20-thousand members of the Canadian Auto Workers are on strike at plants in St. Catharines and Oshawa, Ontario, and Saint Therese, Quebec. About 15-hundred workers at GM suppliers in the Toronto-area are now on layoff. That includes 500 employees of two trucking companies that haul parts, and more than 500 workers at Lear Corporation, which builds seats for GM cars. No progress was reported in contract talks this morning and as Lauran Sabourin reports the union is predicting this could be a long one.
<I><br>  Pickets are posted at all of the plant gates in the St. Catharines operations.<br>  Pickets who on day one of this labour dispute are promising that they can hold out on signing a contract one day longer than General Motors is willing to. <br>  The issue here is outsourcing. To the striking workers outsourcing means losing their jobs to workers from other factories who are willing to supply parts to GM for less.<br>  To GM outsourcing means remaining competitive.<br>  Less than a week into their strike and its already having an impact south of the border.<br>  At the GM Tonawanda engine plant, twelve hundred workers were laid off today.  And more layoff notices are expected within days.<br>  One engine line been shut down in Tonawanda.<br>  Another engine line is threatened with a shutdown.<br>   Still the U.S. GM workers are supportive of their striking counterparts in Canada. <br>  General Motors is negotiating the United Auto Workers in Detroit right now.  But a strike deadline has not be set. </I>
<hr>
<b>Defence Chief</b><p>
According to Canada's new defince minister Doug Young, Canada's military is in a major crisis that goes far deeper than its leadership. ``The armed forces and Canada is faced by a major crisis,'' Young told the commons after taking over the portfolio Friday from David Collenette, who resigned over a breach of government guidelines.<br> Young met embattled Gen. Jean Boyle earlier today to discuss restoring morale in a military disheartened by the Somalia affair. At the end of their meeting Boyle was still chief of defence staff, but Young has promised to lift the cloud hanging over the military, tainted by the regiment's controversial mission to Somalia in 1992-1993.         
<hr>
<b>Bourassa</b><p>
Quebecers said a last goodbye today to ex-premier Robert Bourassa, filling Notre Dame Basilica for a state funeral that drew everyone from political prominents to ordinary citizens.<br> Thousands of people who couldn't get into the crowded basilica listened to the service outside.<br> Bourassa, who was premier for a total of 14 years, died in hospital of cancer last Wednesday at the age of 63.<br> The mourners in the basilica included prime minister Jean Chretien, Quebec premier Lucien Bouchard, conservative leader Jean Charest and ex-Quebec premier Jacques Parizeau.<br> Several other premiers also attended.<br> Prior to the funeral service, Bourassa's body lay for two days in a closed coffin in the ornate red room of the legislature in Quebec City.<br> Police estimated more than 10,000 people filed past the coffin on Saturday and Sunday.<br> Bourassa's widow, daughter Michele and son shook hands with the stream of mourners.
<hr>
<b>Spanking</b><p>
To spank or not to spank, that is the on-going question.<br> The latest answer delivered by the Canadian Pediatric Society is a firm "no"... literally.<br> The group of doctors says firm reprimands and time-outs are much more effective.<br> As Jamie West reports tonight ...there are clearly two schools of thought on the issue.
<i><br>  Spanking... even short open handed taps on the bottom could lead to more serious behavioural and self esteem problems down the road.<br>  That's the message from the Canadian Pediatric Society in Ottawa. <BR>The message isn't really new, but over the last decade has led to the abolision of corporal punishment in many school boards including the Hamilton Public and Separate boards.  <BR>This privately run school in Copetown features kindergarten to grade 12 under one roof...<br>  Corporal punisment is doled out sparingly but according to god's word "withold not correction".<br>  Several warnings are issued long before the dreaded strap is used.<br>  The school says the strap sees daylight about twice a year and is an effective deterrent.<br>  But this family counsellor sides with pediatricians who want the rod thrown away to spare the child.<br>  And for parents who feel there are no other alternatives but to spank, Ricketts says take a time out yourself and pick up the phone.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>TTC Shutdown?</b><p>
Toronto's transit union has voted to join labor's day of protest later this month.<br> The Ontario Federation of Labor had been pushing for toronto's bus, streetcar and subway drivers to stop work on October 25th to protest Harris government cutbacks.<br> Labor's goal is to shut down the city.<br> Transit commission chairman David Gunn has made it clear there will be no disciplinary action against workers who take the day off.<br> But they will lose a day's pay.<br> With the TTC onside, the labor federation is now hoping that workers at GO Transit and Pearson International Airport will also join the protest.
<hr>
<b>Smoking By-law</b><p>
Some Toronto councillors are proposing a compromise today aimed at taking the edge off the city's tough new anti-smoking bylaw.<br> New regulations -- due to go into effect January 1st -- would place a smoking ban on all City of Toronto restaurants and bars.<br> Councillor Peter Tabuns wants his colleagues to reconsider the stringent measure.<br> He is suggesting they return to an earlier proposal for separate, glassed-in areas for smokers.<br> The compromise doesn't have the support of the Ontario Restaurant Association.<br> They say building separate, ventilated areas is not a realistic option for thier members.
<hr>
<b>Pope Surgery</b><p>
On the world stage today, Pope John Paul is said to be feeling well as he awaits surgery to have his appendix removed.<br> His surgeon says the Pontiff is in excellent spirits and is not worried about the operation.<br> Officials say he underwent a scan of his abdomen and two heart tests at a Rome hospital.<br> The Pope is 76 and has been plagued by recurring bouts of fever and illness.<br> The Vatican has strongly denied that something more serious than an inflamed appendix is to blame.  Before entering the hospital, the Pope conducted a special three hour ceremony, to send 16 catholics, down the final road to sainthood, and ended the mass by asking the faithful, to pray for his health.
<hr>
<b>Fergie - Book</b><p>
According to the British tabloids the Queen has apparently worked out a deal, that would bail her daughter in law out of debt... and get Sarah Ferguson out of her royal hair.<br>  Fergie, as she is popularly known, has caused little but shame and embarrasment to the royal family; and her lavish lifestyle has run far beyond her current means.<br> The offer from the Queen will apparently provide Fergie with enough millions to bail her out of debt ...but the price Fergie will pay in return; is custody of her children.






<P>
