<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, October 3, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>G.M.
    <li>Boat Sinking        
    <li>Education Funding   
    <li>New Speaker         
    <li>Book Banning        
    <li>Grand River Deal    
    <li>Recycle             
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M.</b><p>
15 thousand General Motors workers at operations in two cities in Ontario and Quebec are walking the picket lines tonight.<br>   And economists say the strike couldn't have happened at a worse time.<br>   Canada Trust chief economist Patti Croft warns that an auto strike will be a major drag on economic recovery.<br>   And it doesn't appear the strike -- which will spread to other operations next week if no deal is reached -- will be over quickly.<br>   The Canadian Auto Workers Union and GM are at odds over the issue of contracting out work.
<hr>
<b>Boat Sinking</b><p>
One person is dead and two others are missing after a boat with 11 people on board, capsized in the St. Lawrence River near Cornwall.<br>   American reports suggest the small open boat was being used last night to take illegal immigrants from Canada to the U.S.<br>   Nine people were pulled from the river, however a woman died later in hospital.<br>   A military helicopter is being used in the search along with a police boat and several private vessels.
<hr>
<b>Education Funding</b><p>
The Harris government is getting closer to deciding on a new way to finance education in Ontario. A special goverment committee is expected to give its recomendations on education financing next week. 
<hr>
<b>New Speaker</b><p>
Conservative maverick Chris Stockwell was elected the new speaker of Ontario's legislature Thursday.<br>   Stockwell, whose rowdy behavior in the house has often got him in trouble, won on the seventh ballot, beating out seven other candidates from all three parties.<br>   The post was vacated last week when Al McLean resigned in the midst of a sexual harassment controversy.<br>   The 39 year old Stockwell, was first elected in 1990, and denied a cabinet post after the Tories won the election last year.<br>   Since then, he has spoken out against his own government repeatedly.<br>  Most recently, he took exception when government house leader Dave Johnson suggested that McLean step down until the harassment charges against him were resolved.
<hr>
<b>Book Banning</b><p>
The St. Catharines library board is meeting at this hour to decide whether or not to ban another book on killer Paul Bernardo from their shelves.<br>  The book "Invisible Darkness" written by Stephen Williams is yet another graphic description of the assaults and murders of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy.<br>  As Lauran Sabourin reports the library board is finding itself in the position of being accused of censorship.
<br>  <I>It's a controversy the St. Catharines library board wishes it could avoid.<br>  Whether or not to buy copies of the hardcover book "Invisible Darkness" for the library system.<br>  Board chair Rick Dykstra personally is voting against aquiring the book.<br>  A book that he sees as something that re-opens old wounds.<br>  To Dykstra this is not a censorship issue.   As he sees it the board is rather acting as the conscience of the community.<br>  The St. Catharines libary board policy on books that detail the crimes of Paul Bernardo and Karla Homolka is not carved in stone.<br>  The library carries two other books on the pair.<br>  The libary has 12 copies of the paperback Deadly Innocence.<br>  Copies that are so popular with the public that one copy is kept in the special collections section and can't be signed out. </I><br>  
<hr>
<b>Grand River Deal</b><p>
The voices of the Six Nations Women Singers have ushered in a new relationship concerning land around the Grand River.<br>  14 parties, representing the federal and provincial governments, ten municipal governments and two native band councils, signed the Grand River Notification Agreement this morning.<br>  Under the deal, any one of the parties is obligated to notify the others immediately of land use proposals.<br>  The agreement isn't legally binding, but is seen as an important first step in establishling goodwill and cooperation between those involved.
<hr>
<b>Recycle</b><p>
While the profits of recycling have dwindled of late, a prominent U.S. environmentalist says it still good value over the long term.<br>  Delegates to a Hamilton conference on recycling heard today that while the practise of recycling is under heavy criticism.. its still worthwhile.<br>  Dwight Ryan has that story.
<i><br>  Reduce, reuse and recycle were the key words just a decade ago.<br>  Critics said we wouldn't do it, but we did.<br>  We took our newspapers, winebottles, and cans and separated them from our garbage.<br>  The market was hot for the recycled goods and some people were making a lot of money.<br>  But delagates to this Hamilton conference heard there was still a long way to go.  <br>  The Washington based environmentalist says recycled goods must be treated as a commodity.<br>  When commodity prices go down, investors should look at their long-term value.   <br>    While the debate rages on over the value of recylcing, it still takes a hundred years for a tin can to decompose and up to a thousand years for a glass bottle.<br></i>
  







<P>
