<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, October 2, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>GM - CAW
    <li>Bourassa
    <li>Child Support       
    <li>Gay Spouse Benefits 
    <li>Middleton Tragedy   
    <li>Mid East Peace      
    <li>Octuplets           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM - CAW</b><p>
The hours are ticking by toward a midnight strike deadline for thousands of General Motors workers.<br>   Negotiators for GM and the Canadian Auto Workers are searching for common ground at a downtown Toronto hotel.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Bourassa </b><p>
The man who took on Quebec separatists and won a number of battles against them died today.<br>  Former Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa was 63.<br>  He finally succumbed to the skin cancer he had been battling for years.<br>  And as Anthony Pooley reports tonight... tributes have been pouring in all day long.
<i><br>  Robert Bourassa believed passionately in Quebec's role within Canada... while at the same time agreeing that his beloved province... the North American habitat of french culture and language... had been short- changed. He sought to strengthen Quebec's position within the Canadian federation... and depending upon one's point of view... he either succeeded or failed.<br>  After losing Quebec to Rene Levesque's separatists in 1976... Bourassa left politics. But a few year's later, he engineered the big daddy of political comebacks... and by 1985, he was Premier of Quebec once more. He played a major role in drafting the Meech Lake Accord... and bet the farm that the constitutional ammendment would galvanize Quebec's enhanced place within Canada. But as history records ... what he thought was the favourite turned out to be a longshot... and the accord was never ratified.<br>  Bourassa had three different battles with skin cancer... the last of which claimed his life today. Tributes have been pouring in. <br>  Bourassa will be remebered, among other things, as the father of James Bay... the huge power project that harnessed northern Quebec's massive hydroelectric resources.<br>  Former Quebec Liberal Premier Robert Bourassa ... dead at 63. </i>
<hr>
<b>Child Support</b><p>
Deadbeat parents could have their driver's licences yanked under legislation introduced today in Ontario.<br>   The announcement comes as the Conservative government faces persistent criticism over cuts to the office devoted to enforcing support payment orders.<br>   Close to one-billion dollars of those payments are in arrears.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Gay Spouse Benefits</b><p>
Ontario's municipalities are going to have to pay spousal benefits to employees involved in same-sex relationships.<br>  That ruling came from the Ontario Human Rights Commission this week.<br>  And gay rights activists are celebrating the decision.
<hr>
<b>Middleton Tragedy</b><p>
A quiet suburban Toronto neighborhood has been shocked by the death of an elderly resident.<br>  A 78 year old women died after she and her husband tumbled down their stairs.<br>  The couple wasn't found until days later.
<hr>
<b>Mid East Peace</b><p>
Briefly in international news tonight,<br>     U.S. president Clinton says Israeli and Palestinian leaders failed to settle their explosive differences during a two-day summit in Washington.<br>   But he says the two sides will step up peace talks beginning Sunday with an American mediator.<br>   Clinton acknowledged the summit outcome fell short of his hopes -- but says things are in better shape than two days ago.
<hr>
<b>Octuplets</b><p>
A 32-year-old British woman who had been trying against medical advice to give birth to eight babies, lost the last four fetuses today.<br>  King's College Hospital in London made the announcement this afternoon.<br>   Mandy Allwood prematurely gave birth to three boys on Monday -- and a girl this morning.<br>    All have died.<br>  She conceived the eight fetuses after taking fertility drugs.
  







<P>
