<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 10/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, October 1, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>Earthroots - Court    
    <li>Local Redistribution
    <li>Child Porno Inter.   
    <li>QP - Tues.           
    <li>Guns - Cost         
    <li>Mideast Peace       
    <li>Octuplets           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Earthroots - Court</b><p>
A bid to stop the logging of old-growth forests in Ontario's Temagami region has failed.<br>   A Toronto judge ruled against a temporary injunction being sought by the environmental group Earthroots. The conservationists argued that the provincial government is violating its own forestry practices code by allowing logging in the area.<br>   They say they fear that all the trees may be gone by the time the civil trial goes ahead.
<hr>
<b>Local Redistribution</b><p>
The Harris government introduced legislation today to cut the number of provincial politicians from 130 to 103, going into the next Ontario election. <br>  Bob Ireland has the story.<BR>
<i>       It was against the background of this graphic demonstation, that  Premier Mike Harris announced that legislation would be introduced in the legislature today, cutting the number of provincial ridings from 130 to 103. In the next provincial election, Ontario electoral boundaries will match the federal boundaries. Premier Harris says he is fulfilling an election campaign promise to cut the cost of government. And he says it must start at the top.<br>  Harris says cuting 27 MPPs positions with all their expenses, could amount to direct savings of around 13-million dollars. While the Peel Region will gain one seat, the regions of Niagara, Halton and Hamilton Wentworth will lose one riding each. Premier Harris says he expects to get support from both the Liberals and the NDP, for the re-drafting of electoral boundaries.<br>  Christopherson says many ontario voters will be angry that they will not have a say in how their ridings are carved up. <br>  The new riding boundaries will be in place in time for the next provincial election, expected in 1998 or 1999. </i>
<hr>
<b>Child Porno Internet</b><p>
A Cambridge man connected with the Internet to download illegal child pornography is facing jail time.<br>  
<hr>
<b>QP - Tues.</b><p>
Canada's top military man is trying to turn down the volume on questions about his leadership as he continues his morale-boosting tour of atlantic Canada.<br>   General Jean Boyle insists morale at the military bases he has visited is excellent.<br> Meanwhile in Ottawa, the fall out from the Somalia Inquiry brought about this heated exchange between the defence minister and a Reform MP.
<hr>
<b>Guns - Cost</b><p>
The cost of gun control is cheaper than the cost of gun deaths and injuries in Canada, says a group of doctors.<br>  Over six billion dollars is spent per year on gun injuries, according to a study published last year.<br>  And pediatrician, Doctor Katherine Leonard says there are other costs as well.
<hr>
<b>Mideast Peace</b><p>
Good news out of Washington on the Israeli- Palestinian talks.<br>   Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian chairman Yassar Arafat are talking... and while that is seen as a positive sign.. there is no word as to whether the dialogue will result in the two resolving thier many differences.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Octuplets</b><p>
In Britain...a woman who has been carrying eight babies has lost some of them.<br>   The woman's million-dollar pay-per-baby deal with a tabloid newspaper, provoked controversy earlier this summer.<br>  
  







<P>
