<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, September 30, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>GM Latest           
    <li>High Park Rapist    
    <li>Minister Acquitted  
    <li>Baby Update         
    <li>McLean Speaker      
    <li>Workfare            
    <li>Runciman - OPP        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>GM Latest</b><p>
The head of the Canadian Auto Workers will be holding a news conference any moment now to update the media on how talks with General Motors are going... and whether or not the union will walk away from the table... <BR>Earlier today... Buzz Hargrove said that General Motors had moved forward on some issues at contract talks in Toronto. But Hargrove says there has been no progress on the key concern of contracting out. GM says it needs to outsource more work to get to a similar level as Ford and Chrysler. Hargrove says that argument may work in the U.S., but not in Canada, where GM has contracted out more jobs than its competitors.<br>  
<hr>
<b>High Park Rapist</b><p>
A Toronto prosecutor calls a convicted serial rapist &quot;the embodiment of a contemporary urban nightmare.&quot;  Thirty-five-year- old Michael Giroux was sentenced today to 20 years in prison after pleading guilty to 40 charges, including five sexual assaults. Three attacks occurred in Barrie and two in the High Park area in Toronto's west end. Giroux was dubbed the "high park rapist." The court was told that Giroux "preyed" on young women and planned his attacks meticulously.
<hr>
<b>Minister Acquitted</b><p>
A Dunnville minister has been acquitted on seven counts of sexual assault. 44-year-old reverend Ian Wills had been accused of the assaults on the same woman in 1993 and '94. He was charged in May 1995. Last Friday, a jury decided that the pastor of Dunnville's Word of Faith Church was not guilty.
<hr>
<b>Baby Update</b><p>
B.C.'s health minister has ordered a review of security at all hospitals in the province after a newborn was abducted in Kelowna last week. The child was found safe in the woods about 10 hours after Friday's kidnapping. A woman and two teenagers are charged and appeared in court today.
<hr>
<b>McLean Speaker</b><p>
Former legislative speaker Al McLean says he will continue to represent his constituents in Simcoe East. The Tory MPP says he is determined to continue his political career even though he resigned as speaker last week. He had been under pressure from the opposition to step down over allegations he sexually harassed a former employee. McLean denies the allegations by Sandi Thompson.
<hr>
<b>Workfare</b><p>
 Ontario Liberals are calling for the government's workfare program to be scrapped, and are demanding the minister responsible for welfare be fired. 
<hr>
<b>Runciman - OPP</b><p>
 Beginning tomorrow, every OPP officer working during the rush hours in the greater Toronto area will patrol the 400 series highways.  The patrolling blitz named &quot;All Hands on Deck&quot;, is an extension of the Highway Ranger program that started last August. Tomorrow during the rush hour..there will be 31 extra OPP cruisers checking for bad drivers on highways 400, 401 and 403. Solicitor General Bob Runciman denies opposition charges that it will be taking police officers away from other crime duties. <br>
  







<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

