<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, September 26, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Thompson - McLean     
    <li>Doyle Speaker       
    <li>Runciman - Gun Law    
    <li>Reform - Nomination   
    <li>Homolka Bill        
    <li>Mideast Peace       
    <li>Armenia Tanks       
    <li>Shuttle Lands       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Thompson - McLean</b><p>
The woman, accusing the former speaker of the legislature, Al McLean, of sexual harrassment wants money from the Harris government.<br>  Sandi Thompson says she wants a new job and, at the very least her legal expenses paid.
<hr>
<b>Doyle Speaker</b><p>
Meanwhile, a Conservative backbencher Wentworth East MPP Ed Doyle, was acclaimed interim speaker of Ontario's legislature today.<br>   The vote came one day after Al McLean quit the post under intense political pressure.<br>   The house will vote on a permanent replacement for McLean next Thursday.
<hr>
<b>Runciman - Gun Law</b><p>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman says Ontario is supporting Alberta's challenge to the federal government's new gun law.<br>   The federal law calls for owners to register and licence all firearms.<br>  Runciman says the new law will do nothing to stop the use of guns to commit crime.              <br>   Runciman says administering the program would cost ontario hundreds of millions of dollars that could be better spent beefing up front-line police services.
<hr>
<b>Reform - Nomination</b><p>
<br>  With a federal election on the horizon, the Reform Party is starting early.<br>  The party is the first in Canada to choose a candidate and it  picked a rural Ontario riding sumbolic of where Reform sees it's biggest opportunity and it's greatest challenge.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Homolka Bill</b><p>
A bill, proposed by Liberal senator Anne Cools to quash plea bargains such as the notorious deal made by Karla Homolka, got a cold reception today from her colleagues.<br>  The bill would change the criminal code so that plea bargains could be scrapped if the person involved failed to disclose relevant facts, as Homolka did.<br>   In exchange for her testimony against Paul Bernardo, Homolka was able to plead guilty to manslaughter for her part in the deaths of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy.<br>   She was sentenced to 12 years in prison.<br>   But she didn't admit to a role in the rape of an unconscious teenager known to the court as Jane Doe, until after the Bernardo videotapes were found.

<hr>
<b>Mideast Peace</b><p>
Fighting between Palestinian police and Israeli soldiers threatens efforts to work out a mideast peace.<br>  As the police and soldiers battled today, thousands of enraged palestinians attacked two Jewish settlements.<br>  In the past two days, at least 40 palestinians, including a 12-year-old girl, have been killed.<br>   Eleven Israelis have died in today's clashes.<br>  The violence marks the third day of Palestinian rioting set off by Israel's decision to open an archeological tunnel, alongside one of Islam's holiest sites.
<hr>
<b>Armenia Tanks</b><p>
Army tanks entered Armenia's capital of Yerevan today and sealed off the main square as parliament was due to  hold an emergency session.<br>  This after thousands of opposition demonstrators stormed the building late lst night.<br>   The demonstrators beat up the parliament's speaker, in protest against results  of Sunday's presidential election.<br>   They allege the voting was rigged.<br>  Officials said about 50 people were injured as troops broke up the protest with water cannons.
<hr>
<b>Shuttle Lands</b><p>
A few weeks late, but astronaut Shannon Lucid has finally come back down to earth.<br>  The shuttle "Atlantis" landed in Florida this morning.<br>  NASA says Lucid is in good health after her six months weightless in space aboard the Russian "Mir" Space Station.<br>  The space agency adds that she even insisted on leaving the shuttle under her own power.






<P>
