<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, September 25, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Girl Shot           
    <li>McLean Quits        
    <li>Wilson Doctors      
    <li>Goldrush Billions   
    <li>Twoonie Popularity  
    <li>First Grade Kiss    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Girl Shot</b><p>
A handgun used in the near-fatal shooting of a St. Catharines girl has been linked to an Oshawa gun store robbery in 1990.<br>  The 14-year-old girl is on life support in a Hamilton hospital after being shot in the forehead at her home last night.<br>   A 17-year-old male is charged with attempted murder.<br>   Niagara Region Police say the 45-calibre semi-automatic handgun used in the shooting, was stolen from Gagnon's Gun Shop in Oshawa in 1990.
<hr>
<b>McLean Quits</b><p>
The embattled speaker of the Ontario legislature, Al McLean, has resigned, just one day before provincial MPPs were to vote on a motion to fire him.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Wilson Doctors</b><p>
Ontario health minister Jim Wilson wants the College of Physicians and Surgeons to get tough with doctors who refuse to provide emergency services. <br>    There have been reports in the Windsor area of medical specialists refusing to work week-ends, not wanting to see hospital patients, and refusing to participate in base hospital programs.<br>   The health minister says the college must deal with any misconduct by doctors. <br>Health minister Wilson says he is still confident that negotiations between the government and the doctors will avert any job action.<br>  But he hastened to add that if a job action does occur, the government has a contingency plan to make sure patients get proper medical treatment.
<hr>
<b>Goldrush Billions</b><p>
A mysterious story has surfaced about a lost fortune and efforts by it's heirs to recover what they say is rightfully theirs.<br>    It's a tale that begins over one hundred years ago, crosses borders and is linked to the town of Port Colborne.<br>  Jamie West explains...
<i>The story begins during the battle of Buena Vista in the Mexican American war.<br>  Quebec born Francois Gagnon, having lived in California for a decade became a decorated American soldier.<br>  The land was apparently rife with gold, and Gagnon along with 3 cousins who had just arrived from Quebec, proceeded to amass a fortune from mining, operating general stores, and more land speculation. <br>   By 1898 Francois, his cousins Gilbert, Pierre and Eloi all unmarried with no children owned half of Bute Montana and at least 45 buildings back east in Boston. In all a net worth of about 50 million turn of the century dollars.<br>    Then it happened. <br>  The four disappeared mysteriously...no bodies ever found.<br>  No official explanation....<br>  So who would collect the fortune?<br>  About 100 heirs laid claim all from Quebec...the story has it the American government kept the money in their Central Bank in Washington. In any case their claims were refused by the government of California.<br>  Those claiming to be heirs tried again in 1926, 54, 60, 79, and 1980.<br>  In 1995 as many as 13-thousand heirs from across Canada including 300 plus from Niagara and the United States have each paid 50 dollars to register and are fighting on to recover the fortune...<br>  Maurice and the Quebec historical research firm investigation Lapointe think they're getting closer...to the fortune that has over time grown to 56 billion dollars.<br>  The Quebec government has refused to help.<br>  The Canadian government the same.<br>  The U.S. feds say it's a Californina state matter.<br>  and California simply denies that the fortune exists. </i>
<hr>
<b>Twoonie Popularity</b><p>
The coin that Canadians loved to break has finally met with acceptance.<br>   It seems the two-dollar coin is so popular the Royal Canadian Mint had to step up production.<br>   The first 300-thousand two-dollar coins have been produced, a full year ahead of schedule.<br>   The coin has no official name but is ususally referred to as the "toonie."
<hr>
<b>First Grade Kiss</b><p>
An innocent kiss turned into sexual harassment.<br>  That was the case for a first grade boy who gave his classmate a peck on the cheek.





<P>
