<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, September 24, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Legislature - McLean  
    <li>Opposition Q.P.      
    <li>U.S. Canada Hearings
    <li>Clinton - U.N.
    <li>Yeltsin Health      
    <li>Bernardo AIDS
    <li>Carrey Marries      
</ul>



<hr>
<b>Legislature - McLean</b><p>
The NDP accused the Harris govenerment today of trying to put off until Thursday, a resolution calling for the firing of speaker Al McLean. Both the Liberals and the NDP wanted to deal with the matter today. 

<b>Opposition Q.P.</b><p>
Opposition members were quick to jump on the Al McLean issue when the house resumed.<br>  Although controversial, the common sense revolution still enjoys the support of a majority of voters.<br>  A new poll indicates the Tories are still in the lead amongst decided voters...even though the Liberals are narrowing the gap.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports that opposition members will have their hands full turning the tide.
<i>Members of the legislature weren't even in their seats when the McLean issue arose...  <br>  For opposition members fighting the Harris majority, the Al McLean issue is a gift.  Although the NDP motion to oust the speaker was defeated, it still gave the New Democrats and Liberals a chance to lambaste the Tories.<br>  After devastating defeats, both parties are trying to rejuvenate themselves.  The New Democrats have a new leader ..  His name is Howard Hampton and he didn't take long to show off who's in charge now.   <br>    The Liberals don't have a new leader yet, but they will in November.  Lyn Mcleod is moving aside after her party's humiliating defeat last year.<br>  Seven liberals, six MPPs and an Ottawa businessman,  are seeking the opposition leader's spot.  </i>
<hr>
<b>U.S. Canada Hearings</b><p>
 Tomorrow in Washington, a congressional sub-committee will hold a hearing into the potential impacts of Quebec's separation.<br>  A recent essay on the issue, that's been published world wide, is raising some serious questions about how a Canadian break-up would effect the United States.<br>  The essay and tomorrow's hearings, may help shed some light onto what Canadians could face in the future.
<hr>
<b>Clinton - U.N.</b><p>
U.S. president Clinton says he hopes a treaty he signed at the United Nations today will result in a "better, safer world."<br>   The global treaty bans nuclear test explosions, including underground blasts. Representatives of the world's other nuclear powers -- China, France, Russia and Britain -- followed Clinton in signing the document.<br>   A total of 65 countries will sign the treaty.<br>   Foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy signed for Canada.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Health</b><p>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin insists he's not too sick to work.<br>   Doctors are concerned he might be too ill to undergo heart surgery.<br>   Russian television, shows Yeltsin smiling weakly and sitting slightly hunched in a chair as he chats with Russia's prime minister at the hospital.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Bernardo AIDS</b><p>
Paul Bernardo has been ordered to be tested for AIDS, and other sexually transmitted diseases.<br> A Toronto judge made the order yesterday at the request of a woman who was raped by Bernardo in the garage of a Scarborough apartment building in 1989.<br> The woman is suing for 10-million dollars.<br> Bernardo did not contest the order and was not represented at yesterday's hearing in Toronto.<br> The testing is to be performed within the next 45 days.
<hr>
<b>Carrey Marries</b><p>
Burlington born actor Jim Carrey and his girlfriend, actress Lauren Holly, have married.<br>   Carrey's spokeswoman says Carrey and Holly tied the knot in Los Angeles yesterday.<br>   It's the second marriage for both.<br>   The couple however, won't be heading off on a honeymoon.   Carrey has to be back on the set of his movie, "Liar, Liar" tomorrow.





