<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, September 19, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Baby Murder Sentence
    <li>Body Parts          
    <li>CBC Cuts
    <li>Municipal Education 
    <li>Occupational Health 
    <li>Bailey Back         
    <li>3-D Games            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Baby Murder Sentence</b><p>
It will be years before two crack-addicted parents in Toronto will be able to apply for parole after being convicted of killing their six-month-old daughter.<br>  33-year-old Michael (pod-na-wits) will spend at least 25 years in prison before being eligible for parole.<br>    His common-law wife, 30-year-old Lisa Olsen must wait 15 years to apply for parole.<br>  Their daughter Sara had more than 20 broken bones when she died in 1994.
<hr>
<b>Body Parts</b><p>
Toronto police are investigating a grisly murder in suburban East York.<br>   A headless corpse has been found in a closet of a fourth floor apartment.<br>   Police say the discovery was made last night by three tenants of the apartment who were preparing to move out.<br>   Detective Peter Gibson says they have no suspects.<br>   The apartment had been rented to three men described as recent immigrants.<br>   All three are being questioned.
<hr>
<b>CBC Cuts</b><p>
Big cuts at the CBC.<br>  The corporation is cutting another 25-hundred jobs and slashing an additional 127 million dollars from its spending to cope with government ordered budget cuts.<br>   Although no stations will close, there will be noticeable changes to the network, including the additoin of commercials in news and current affairs programming.<br>   The announcement follows two days of emotional debate among CBC board members.<br>   The cuts are to be completed by April 1998.
<hr>
<b>Municipal Education</b><p>
Education remained the big item on the agenda as the Ontario Tories wrapped up a three-day caucus meeting in the Niagara area.<br>   A day after suggesting education spending may be slashed by a further 600-million dollars, education minister John Snobelen announced school boards might be scrapped.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Occupational Health</b><p>
<br>  Provincial NDP leader Howard Hampton, is accusing the Harris government of tampering with an independent report, that recommends closing four occupational health clinics across Ontario.<br>  Hampton says Ontarians will pay hundreds of thousands of dollars more in health care costs, if the clinics close.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Bailey Back</b><p>
The world's fastest man has some catching up to do -- with his family.<br>  Donovan Bailey, the 100-metre Olympic gold medallist, arrived back in Canada last night.<br> It's the first time he's been on Canadian soil since before the Atlanta Games.<br>  After the Olympics, he competed in Europe and Asia.<br> For now, the Oakville sprinter says he just wants to rest and spend some time with his family.<br>   But he will be the centre of attention this Saturday when Oakville throws a parade for its favorite son.
<hr>
<b>3-D Games</b><p>
The computer industry has agreed on a new technical standard that could bring 3-D Internet games into your home within a few years... for little more than the cost of a traditional game.<br> 



<P>
