<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, September 18, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Al McLean - Sick Leave
    <li>Tories - Economy      
    <li>Cop Beating Video   
    <li>Violence Inquiry    
    <li>Chrysler Deal       
    <li>Bosnia Elex         
    <li>Korean Sub          
    <li>Agnew Obit          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Al McLean - Sick Leave</b><p>
Ontario's embattled legislature speaker is taking sick leave.<br>   A source close to Al McLean confirms the speaker is taking an "undetermined amount of time" off because of problems with his diabetes.<br>   The Tory member of the legislature has been under pressure to step aside from the speaker's post, over allegations that he sexually harassed an employee.<br>   McLean has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.<br>   A report on the allegation is expected to be completed by the time the leislature resumes sitting on Tuesday.
<hr>
<b>Tories - Economy</b><p>
<br>  The allegations against the speaker will undoubtedly be on the minds of members when they resume sitting next week.<br>  But another area that is sure to dominate discussion... budget slashing.<br>  That topic was front and center today as the tories met in Vineland to plan their agenda.<br>  Lauran Sabourin reports.

<i><br>  Victoria Hall in Vineland was the setting for day long caucus session.<br>  The economy was the main item on the agenda.<br>  Harris promises more budget cutting. more public sector layoffs.<br>  The government says it's legislative priorities are improving the education, law enforcment and health care services.<br>  But the public is questioning where the improvements are in particular with health care when the government is talking about closing hospitals. <br>  The Harris government is preparing for clash with the province's teachers unions over education cutbacks.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cop Beating Video</b><p>
A video tape, depicting the last minutes of a prisoner, being held at a Toronto police station, was released to the public today.<br>  The dramatic 30-minute tape, was shown to the jury at the trial of Const. Paul Van Seters.<br>  The 15 year police veteran is charged with criminal negligence causing death and criminal negligence causing bodily harm, in the death of Kenneth Allen.<br>  Allen died while in police custody in November 1991.<br>  Court has already heard testimony from witnesses who described Allen as violent and paranoid when he attacked a streetcar driver the night he died.
<hr>
<b>Violence Inquiry</b><p>
<br>   Ontario's coroner and child welfare groups are joining forces in a multi-pronged attempt to reduce child abuse deaths.<br>   It's a growing problem that officials admit, was treated too lightly in the past.
<hr>
<b>Chrysler Deal</b><p>
The Canadian Auto Workers Union will announce its next strike target next week.<br>   The union won job security in an eleventh-hour deal hammered out with Chrysler Canada last night.<br>   Chrysler has agreed to replace any job it contracts out with a similar job at one of its plants.<br>   It also promised not to sell or close any plants over the life of the new contract.<br>   The deal will be used as a blueprint in talks with Ford and General Motors.<br>   Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  The picket signs were ready, but not needed.  <br>  Minutes before the strike deadline of midnight, the CAW executive announced a deal had been reached with Chrysler Canada.  <br>  The deal gives the nearly 13-thousand union members at Chrysler a two per cent wage hike for each of the contract's three years.<br>  That's on top of cost of living increases.<br>  Currently, the average Chrysler worker makes 22 dollars and one cent an hour.<br>  Over the life of the new contract, they'll be paid for an extra ten days off.  <br>  As long as it's making money, Chrysler has agreed to replace any job it contracts out with a similar job at one of its plants.  <br>  Chrysler workers will vote on the agreement this Sunday.<br>  The Canadian Auto Workers will announce on Monday the second target company for negotiations.<br>  It's likely to be Ford, but the union warns General Motors will have to live up to the same provisions reached in the Chrysler deal, or face a nasty strike.</i>
<hr>
<b>Bosnia Elex</b><p>
The Bosnian election results are in and it appears, Bosnia's Muslim president will likely lead the new government's three-man presidency.<br>   Unofficial results show 72-year-old Alija Izeht-beg-o-vich received the most votes in Saturday's eleciton. Izeht-beg-o-vich has vowed to steer Bosnia away from war and separatism.<br>  His strongest opponent, a Serb nationalist, advocated making the Serb half of Bosnia a separate state.<br>    Both men will serve on the three-man presidency, along with the candidate of the leading Croat party.
<hr>
<b>Korean Sub</b><p>
The bodies of 11 North Koreans have been found on South Korea's east coast near an abandoned North Korean submarine.<br>   One man has been taken into custody.<br>   The South Korean Defence Ministry says it's not known how the 11 died.<br>  But a state-run TV station says they apparently committed suicide rather than risk capture.<br>  There has been no reaction from North Korea.
<hr>
<b>Agnew Obit</b><p>
<br>   Spiro Agnew, the only US vice president forced to resign in disgrace, is dead.<br>  Agnew died yesterday afternoon in a Maryland hospital.<br>   The cause of death has not been revealed.<br>  Agnew was Richard Nixon's point man and attacked the news media as "hopeless, hysterical hypochondriacs of history."<br>  He was forced to resign in 1973 after pleading guilty to tax evasion.<br>  Spiro Agnew was 77.



<P>
