<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, September 17, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>





<ul>
    <li>Chrysler
    <li>Simpson             
    <li>Temagami            
    <li>Underwater Logging  
    <li>Plowing Match       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Chrysler </b><p>
<br>  Canadian Auto Workers Union boss Buzz Hargrove says they are working under the presumption there will be a strike at Chrysler Canada.<br>   The CAW is poised to go on strike against the automaker at midnight.<br>   Hargrove says even though there was one breakthrough there has been virtually no movement today on other key issues.<br>   A Chrysler vice-president describes the talks at a Toronto hotel as &quot;very tense&quot;.<br>  Ian Dovey reports.                 
<BR>
<I>Day shift workers at Chrysler's Brampton and Windsor Assembly Plants have finished for the day not knowing if they'll be back tomorrow.<br>  In Toronto, Chyrsler and the Canadian Auto Workers Union are involved in intense eleventh hour in contract talks.<br>  The two sides have been hard at it hoping to avoid a strike deadline.<br> CAW president Buzz Hargrove says time is now a problem despite having cleared one of the major roadblocks.<br>  Chrysler has agreed to replace any job it contracts out with a similar job at one of its plants.<br>  The automaker has also promised not to sell or close any plants during the life of a new three year contract. <br>Wages, benefits and time off are stand in the way of new contract but with an unextendable deadline of 11:59 tonight time of the essense.</I><br>  
<hr>
<b>Simpson</b><p>
<br>  The judge in the O.J. Simpson civil trial has shown his no-nonsense approach to the case.<br>  He has made a number of quick rulings on issues of evidence that indicate he will not allow the Simpson team to put the Los Angeles Police Department on trial.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Temagami</b><p>
<br>   The battle between environmentalists and loggers in Temagami is heating up.<br>   Police arrested two more environmental protesters today after they chained themselves to a bridge on a logging road leading to an old-growth forest where cutting is to begin next week.<br>   Eleven other protesters were arrested in the area yesterday.
<hr>
<b>Underwater Logging</b><p>
<br>  Logging is also a contentious issue south of the border.<br>  From Maine to California, most of the old forests are gone.<br>  But CBS reporter Hattie Koffman has found someone logging old growth, and amazingly, he's not being called a villain.<br>  He's an underwater treasure hunter.<br>  You see, this story is about underwater logging, to get to the forest, you have to dive beneath the surface.
<hr>
<b>Plowing Match</b><p>
<br>  Following several days of rain, the Haldimand Norfolk International Plowing Match has been plowed under.<br>  Day one of the event was cancelled after a brief opening ceremony.<br>  Since mud wrestling is not a scheduled event, organizers will try again tomrrow.<br>  


<P>
