<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, September 16, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Copps - Return      
    <li>Chretien
    <li>Charest - House       
    <li>Enviro Protest      
    <li>Teachers College    
    <li>Obesity Epidemic    
    <li>OJ New Trial       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Copps - Return</b><p>
<br>  The House of Commons is back to business after its three month summer break and, while not exactly a rookie in the House of Commons, Sheila Copps is nonetheless the newest MP.<br>   Copps was sworn in today and brought in to the house on the arms of Prime Minister Chretien and defence minister David Collenette.<br>   She was re-elected in a summer byelection in her Hamilton riding, after resigning to fulfil a promise to quit if the GST was not abolished.<br>  Just hours into the new session, Copps and her new heritage ministry came under attack.
<hr>
<b>Chretien </b><p>
<br>     Prime Minister Jean Chretien has come out in support of his beleaguered defence minister, and the chief of the defence staff.<br>   Chretien has told the commons that David Collenette, General Jean Boyle and the Somalia inquiry, have jobs to do and the opposition parties should let them get on with them.<br>   The opposition parties have been calling for the resignation of Collenette and Boyle because of evidence given at the Somalia inquiry.
<hr>
<b>Charest - House</b><p>
<br>     Parliament may be back after its summer break, but statisticians are wondering if Tory leader Jean Charest should be returning to school.<br>   Today Charest blamed the Liberal government for presiding over the longest period of sustained high unemployment since the great depression.         <br>  Statistics Canada figures show that when charest served in the Tory government of Brian Mulroney, the unemployment figures were higher than they are now.
<hr>
<b>Enviro Protest</b><p>
<br>     Dozens of university students demonstrated at Queen's Park today to protest environmental moves by the Harris government.<br>   The group, Stop Environmental Deregulation in Canada, says Tories are taking "irresponsible" steps backward by allowing businesses to ignore the environment.<br>   It says many companies that have been charged with environmental offences in the past are now being allowed to regulate themselves.
<hr>
<b>Teachers College</b><p>
<br>   The Ontario government says a new R has been added to reading writing and arithmetic in the province's schools.<br>  And that new R stands for responsibility.<br>   Today, education minister John Snobelen unveiled the details of its new college of teachers.<br>  Mike Murphy has the story.
<i> For the first time... Ontario teachers will soon be able to police themselves. Teachers ave already begun registering with the province's new College of Teachers. A college that will set out training and professional standards for up to 200 thousand Ontario teachers.<br>  The college will be able to weed out the ones that are unfit. <br>   While teachers can stand for election appointed to the college's 31 member governing council..parents will also be involved. <br>  But the teachers unions haven't blunted their criticism of the college they call it an attack on teachers.<br>  Still says education minister John Snobelen many rank and file teachers are in favour of the college.<br>  And parents are demanding more accountability.<br>   Parents who are unhappy with their child's teacher can take their complaint to the new college. It's expected to be up and running early next year.</i>
<hr>
<b>Obesity Epidemic</b><p>
<br>    Scientists are warning that an obesity epidemic is threatening the world.<br>  And they say if present trends continue, by the year 2030 most of the population of the United States will be obese.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i>Scientists clain that obesity poses one of the fastest developing and most serious public health problems in North America.  And it's only getting worse.<br>  Young people gravitate toward fast food.  Fast food jingles that are ingrained in the young person's mind.<br>  We live in a society where bigger is often seen as better. <br>  At M.T. Bellies Restaurant in Welland customers are invited to take the M.T. Bellies challenge.   Four pounds of beef, bread and vegetables were delivered to Glen Mc Cluskey's table on a garbage can lid and if he eats it all the meal in 100 minutes it's free.<br>  Mc Cluskey was few minutes short the target.  He's hit with a bill of 35 dollars and get's his picture added to the wall of shame again. <br>  The M.T. Bellies challenge is all in fun, but medical experts say eating too much, being overweight isnt' a laughing matter.<br>  The increase in pounds brings with it a myriad of health problems, iincluding strokes, heart problems, infertility, diabestes and certain types of cancer.  Not the mention the stigma of being labelled fat.<br>  Books, videos weight loss seminars are big business in North America. <br>  The most disturbing part of this problem to the experts is that society isnt' as disturbed about obesity as it should be. </i>
<hr>
<b>OJ New Trial</b><p>
<br>    It may be hard to imagine an OJ Simpson trial without lights, cameras and action...but this week in Santa Monica ...the civil suit against Simpson begins and the all seeing eye of the TV camera is not invited.


<P>
