<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, September 10, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Bill 49             
    <li>Blood Ministers     
    <li>Truck Safety        
    <li>Shoecam Court         
    <li>Hortense-Rico       
    <li>Weather Fran        
    <li>China Typhoon       
    <li>Bosnia Politics     
    <li>Kurd Refugees       
    <li>Mother Teresa       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bill 49</b><p>
<br>   A union representing textile workers in Ontario claims proposed amendments to the province's Employment Standards Act, will only serve to create more sweatshops across Ontario, that pay their workers below  minimum wages.<br>   The union made the claim today, in a brief to a government committee studying the proposed legislation.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Blood Ministers</b><p>
<br>     The future of the Red Cross as a blood agency hangs by a thread as Canada's health ministers meet in Toronto.<br>   They're looking at setting up a new national blood agency to try to restore confidence in the system.<br>   Ontario's Jim Wilson says the big sticking point in yesterday's talks, was what role the Red Cross might play.
<hr>
<b>Truck Safety</b><p>
<br>  The OPP and provincial inspectors are pulling unsafe rigs off the road in a truck safety blitz along Highway 400 from Toronto to Barrie.<br>   Today, transportation minister Al Palladini visited one of the eight inspection stations that has been set up.<br>  At one station alone, almost half of about 40 rigs checked, were taken out of service because of safety violations such as bad brakes, suspension problems and bald tires.<br>  The two- day blitz continues tomorrow.
<hr>
<b>Shoecam Court</b><p>
<br>   A retired high school teacher accused of peering under women's skirts with a shoe-camera at the Canadian National Exhibition, appeared in a Toronto courtroom today.<br>  62- year-old George Walter Campbell of Cornwall, was ordered to reappear in court October 8th on charges of sexual assault and mischief.<br>   Police allege, dozens of women were secretly videotaped by a man using a fibre-optic camera hidden in his shoe.<br>  Campbell was arrested over the Labor Day weekend.
<hr>
<b>Hortense-Rico</b><p>
<br>  In world news tonight, at least five people were killed and another four are missing and feared dead after hurricane "Hortense" blasted through Puerto Rico.<br>  Torrential rains sent rivers over their banks, washed away cars and caused power outages in much of the island.<br>  The storm is expected to strike a glancing blow to the Dominican Republic, then head in a west- northwesterly direction toward the Turks and Caicos and southernmost Bahamas.
<hr>
<b>Weather Fran</b><p>
<br>   Meanwhile, North Carolina's governor is calling hurricane "Fran" the worst disaster to hit his state this century.<br>   No immediate overall damage estimates have been issued, but it's expected to be in the billions.<br>  At least 36 people were killed, most in North Carolina.
<hr>
<b>China Typhoon</b><p>
<br>   And typhoon "Sally" killed at least 112 people and left 110 missing when it slammed into southern China.<br>  The typhoon sliced across the province of Guangdong yesterday.<br>   Officials say fierce winds caused the collapse of more than 215-thousand homes.<br>  Rail and highway traffic has been suspended and water and electricity supplies cut off.<br>   The storm has moved into vietnam but has weakened.
<hr>
<b>Bosnia Politics</b><p>
<br>  In Bosnia... there is no freedom of movement and little progress on arresting indicted war criminals who continue to poison the political environment. Even minimum requirements for free and fair elections haven't been met... and there's virtually no freedom of expression or association. Nonetheless the international community wants to press ahead saying things are unlikey to get better anytime soon. 
<hr>
<b>Kurd Refugees</b><p>
<br>   Iraqi president Saddam Hussein has issued a broad amnesty to Iraqi Kurds in Northern Iraq.<br>   That is after his forces helped one Kurdish faction defeat another.<br>   The Iraqi government is declaring a victory over the US.<br>  American missiles targeted Iraqi military sites, when Saddam began his northern incursion.
<hr>
<b>Mother Teresa</b><p>
<br>    Mother Teresa arrived in a wheelchair today to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the order she founded and urged her followers to keep serving the poor.<br>  200 "Missionaries of Charity Sisters" surrounded the 86-year-old Roman Catholic nun.<br>  Mother Teresa thanked her colleagues and other well- wishers from around the world, who had prayed for her health.<br>   She returned last Friday after two weeks of hospitalization.


<P>
