<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, September 9, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Harris - Paris      
    <li>McLean Lie Detector 
    <li>Bluewater Follow     
    <li>Temagami Bridge     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Harris - Paris</b><p>
<br>  A bold, "in your face" message to Quebec today from Ontario Premier Mike Harris.<br>  Five days into a trade mission to Europe, Harris made a direct pitch to French business leaders and investors to set up shop in Ontario.<br>  The move challenges Quebec's traditional close economic ties with France.<br>  But Harris maintains he's just telling the French where they can make a dollar, and he left untouched the question of what his actions will do to relations between Quebec and Ontario.<br>  
<hr>
<b>McLean Lie Detector</b><p>
<br>  Back at Queen's Park, meanwhile, controversy continues to surround Ontario legislature speaker Al McLean. Today, McLean's lawyer said his client passed a lie detector test on whether he sexually harassed one of his employees. Martin Teplitsky says McLean took the test, hoping to prove his innocence. This after aide Sandi Thompson formally complained two weeks ago that McLean sexually harassed her while she was working for him. 
<hr>
<b>Bluewater Follow</b><p>
<br>  Child advocates are calling for a judicial inquiry into the beating death of a sixteen-year-old inmate at the Wellington Detention Centre in Guelph.<br>  James Lonee died in Hamilton General Hospital on Saturday of massive head injuries sustained in the beating.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> Even though the Ministry of the Solcitor General is investigating James Lonnee's death, and an inquest will be held, champions of children's rights say that's not good enough.  <BR>Lonee's lawyer wants to know why he was transfered to the Wellington Detention Centre in Guelph, and put in a segregation cell with another inmate, even though the cell was meant for one person.  <BR>Lonnee's cell-mate has been charged with murder. Both of them had been at the Bluewater Detention Centre in Goderich, the scene of a riot last February. Lonnee's lawyer says her client had previously complained about being beaten up by other inmates, because he was co-operating with police investigating the riot.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Temagami Bridge</b><p>
<br>  There are growing fears tonight that violence could erupt in the Temagami region of northern Ontario after police uncovered more steel spikes driven into trees to sabotage logging. Provinvial Police say they've found 60 spikes so far ... they are a deadly hazard for forest workers... and are raising tensions in a standoff that has erupted in violence once already. 

<P>
