<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, September 6, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Prov. Unemployment   
    <li>Woodstock Explosion 
    <li>Temagami            
    <li>Runciman - Jails      
    <li>Day Care Reaction       
    <li>Party Poll          
    <li>Prez Poll           
    <li>Fran                
    <li>Croat Quake         
    <li>Iraq Calm           
    <li>Teresa - Hospital     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Prov> Unemployment</b><p>
 Ontario led the country in job creation last month, as the provincial unemploment rate dropped to 8.5 per-cent. That's down from 9.2 per cent in July and well below the national average of 9.4. 
<hr>
<b>Woodstock Explosion</b><p>
Residents of a trailer park near Woodstock are being allowed to return home following a propane explosion this morning.<br>   Police say the blast happened while a propane truck was making a delivery at the Braemar Trailer Park.<br>   One trailer was engulfed in flames.<br>   Two people inside were treated for minor burns.<br>   The truck driver is in critical condition in a London hospital.
<hr>
<b>Temagami</b><p>
Environmentalists accuse the Ontario government of ordering a crackdown on demonstrators who are blocking a logging road.<br>   Police made 21 arrests yesterday in the northern region of Temagami.<br>  An earthroots spokesman, says police were ordered to make sweeping arrests.<br>  The demonstrators are protesting planned logging in an old-growth pine forest.
<hr>
<b>Runciman - Jails</b><p>
<br>  Ontario's jail system is about to be overhauled.<br>   Solicitor General, Bob Runciman announced today that jail guards will be required to meet new qualification standards, and will have to complete an extensive training program. The changes also include a review of management accountability, and an examination of the workplace culture within provincial jails.<br>  Runciman says problems at the Bell Cairns Insitution in Hamilton and more recently at Elgin Middlesex,  made these changes necessary.           <br>    Runciman says the changes, which will take place beginning October first, will result in a loss of 26 jobs.
<hr>
<b>Day Care Reaction</b><p>
<br>  A proposed overhaul of Ontario's child care system, is coming under fire from day-care advocates.<br>  Yesterday, the Harris government announced a plan to create more spaces and subsidies for poor parents.<br>  But critics argue the proposal would cut millions of dollars from non-profit day care centres while forcing workers to take huge pay cuts.
<hr>
<b>Party Poll</b><p>
<br>   The federal tories should be pleased with a new opinion poll suggesting the party is bouncing back following last month's policy convention.<br>  The Angus Reid survey shows the Liberals still well ahead with the support of 53 per cent of those asked.<br>    But the big surprise is the five-point rise in Tory popularity, to 17 per cent.<br>   The Reform Party stands at 12 per cent and the New Democrats have six per cent support among those surveyed.
<hr>
<b>Prez Poll</b><p>
<br>    Pollsters south of the border have been busy as well.<br>  The latest American presidential poll shows President Clinton with an 18 point lead over Republican Bob Dole.<br>  The New York Times/CBS News poll, suggests Clinton has the support of 54 per cent of decided voters, while 36 percent said they back Dole.<br>   Eight per cent of those surveyed support billionaire third-party candidate Ross Perot.
<hr>
<b>Fran</b><p>
<br>   Hurricane "Fran" has left North Carolina, but her wrath will be felt for days and weeks to come.<br>    The clean up is just beginning for the coastal city of Wilmington, which took the brunt of Fran's fury.<br>  The storm caused millions of dollars in damage and killed at least 12 people.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Croat Quake</b><p>
Mother nature showed off her destructive side in another part of the world last night.<br>  A large earthquake rumbled through Croatia with a magnitude of 6 on the Richter Scale.<br>  Large scale damage was reported to buildings in the small town of Ston and nearby settlements.<br>  Appeals have gone out from the small town for help in the evacuation of stranded residents.<br>  Croatian army units and civilian groups are trying to clear the debris.<br>  So far there have been no reports of deaths.
<hr>
<b>Iraq Calm</b><p>
<br>   All is quiet in Northern Iraq today, but a United Nations official says tension remains in the air.<br>  For the first time since Saturday, there's no fighting in the region.<br>  But the UN official says Iraqi troops are digging in near the city of Irbil (ur-beel').
<hr>
<b>Teresa - Hospital</b><p>
Mother Teresa is resting at home after being released from a hospital in Calcutta, India.<br>   The 86-year-old nun -- winner of the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize -- spent 16 days in the hospital being treated for heart problems, malaria, and pneumonia.<br>   Although doctors say Mother Teresa is getting stronger, she still needs plenty of rest.


<P>
