<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, September 5, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>McLean Resigns?     
    <li>Child Care Changes  
    <li>Doctors React          
    <li>Harris Trip         
    <li>Yeltsin             
    <li>Fran                
</ul>
<hr>
<b>McLean Resigns?</b><p>
<br>   Pressure is mouting for the speaker of the ontario legislature, Al McLean to step down.<br>  Three weeks ago, a female staff member of McLean's filed an informal complaint against the speaker alleging sexual harassment.<br>  Today that complaint was formalized when it was filed with the Ontario Human Rights Commission.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Child Care Changes</b><p>
<br>  A provincial government report released today, suggests Ontario give less money to non-profit day care centres, and spend more on private, home child care. <br>    Ontario currently spends 125-million dollars a year in wage subsidies to day-care staff.<br>  Most of that money goes to non-profit centres.<br>  The report says the money should be phased out over three years to put private and non-profit centres on a level playing field.<br>   The report also says rules should be loosened to allow each day-care worker to look after more children and qualifications should be relaxed.<br>  Social services minister Janet Ecker, who compiled the report, says there should be a test to deterine who is eligible for subsidized daycare.              <br>  The social services minister says the money saved could provide 12-thousand new daycare spaces to families that realy need it.
<hr>
<b>Doctors React</b><p>
<br>   Now that the Ontario government and its doctors are getting back to the negotiating table the doctors are reconsidering their strike threat.<br>  Doctors in Niagara led the strike initiative.  The fact that both sides are talking is a good sign.
<hr>
<b>Harris Trip</b><p>
<br>     Premier Mike Harris is in Frankfurt, Germany, today to start a nine-day trip to Europe.<br>   Harris will attend a private dinner tonight with German business people and investors.<br>   Tomorrow he will speak at a Canadian German business club luncheon and meet with banking officials.<br>   Harris will also visit Paris, London and Edinburgh as he tries to attract investment to Ontario.<br>   The Premier says he won't hesitate to boost Toronto's bid for the 2008 Olympics during his trip.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin</b><p>
<br>     It seems the rumors about Boris Yeltsin's heart trouble were true.<br>   The 65-year-old Russian president says he will undergo heart surgery at the end of this month.<br>   He says his doctors gave him two choices -- an operation or a less stressful routine.<br>   Yeltsin has had two heart attacks in the past year and has virtually vanished from public sight since June.
<hr>
<b>Fran</b><p>
<br>   Hour by hour, the rain is getting heavier and the wind is getting more ferocious on the Carolinas' coast. Hurricane "Fran's" outer edge has begun swirling over a broad stretch of shore, north and south of the state line.<br>  People are still leaving the area in droves, trying to move inland -- away from Fran's expected landfall tonight.<br>  

<P>
