<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, September 4, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Specialty Channels
    <li>Morin Inquiry       
    <li>Speaker Harassment  
    <li>Iraq                
    <li>Reaction            
    <li>Mother Teresa       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Specialty Channels</b><p>
<br>   Canadians will soon be able to pick and choose from a variety of new television channels.<br>   The federal broadcast regulator today approved 23 new specialty TV channels.<br>   They will offer services ranging from news and science to gardening and pre-school programming.<br>  The first group of the services is expected to be on the air by next September with the rest appearing by September of 1999.<br> Ian Dovey has more.                                        
<br>  <I>There will be more reasons to fight over the converter as the CRTC appoved 23 of 40 applications for specialty TV channels. <br>    Many of the new licencees are already big palyers in the TV industry, namely Chum and CTV. <br>     Some of the new channels will be operational within the year ...others by the fall of 1999.<br>  But the big challenge facing all 23 new specialty channels is whether they can win over enough subscribers to support their services.<br>  </I>
<hr>
<b>Morin Inquiry</b><p>
<br>   Guy Paul Morin spoke today as a commission of inquiry opened in Toronto to probe his wrongful conviction in the 1984 sex-slaying of nine-year-old Christine Jessop of Queensville.<br>   Morin says he's relieved a public examination of his wrongful murder conviction is finally under way.<br>   The previous NDP government had promised to hold an inquiry into the case.<br>   And Ontario premier Mike Harris included the inquiry among his election promises.<br>   Morin was eventually cleared of a 1992 conviction after new DNA evidence was presented.
<hr>
<b>Speaker Harassment</b><p>
<br>   MPP's may force the speaker of the legislature to step down, if charges of sexual harassment haven't been resolved before the legislature resumes sitting.<br> Government house leader Dave Johnson says speaker Al McLean could face resolutions calling for his removal if he's still in the speaker's chair September 24th.<br> McLean refuses to step down and denies the accusation made by female aide Sandi Thompson that he repeatedly sexually harassed her.<br>   Leaders of the two opposition parties have both called on McLean to step down until the matter is resolved. But premier Mike Harris has said he intends to let the investigative process unfold.
<hr>
<b>Iraq</b><p>
<br>     US president Clinton has declared the cruise missile strikes in Iraq a success.<br>   He says Saddam Hussein now knows there's a price to pay for attacking Kurds in northern Iraq.<br>   Clinton also says missiles have smashed air defence sites that might have threatened US warplanes.<br>   He says he discussed the situation in the Persian Gulf with prime minister Chretien last night.
<hr>
<b>Reaction</b><p>
<br>  International support for the US attack on Iraq, meanwhile, has been limited.<br>  The US decision to attack unilaterally, may also take its toll on gulf-war alliances.
<hr>
<b>Mother Teresa</b><p>
<br>     Mother Teresa may return home this week.<br>  Her doctors in Calcutta say the 86-year-old nun is making progress against a chest infection and heart problems.<br>    The Nobel Peace Prize laureate was admitted to hospital last month with a fever brought on by malaria.

<P>
