<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 09/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, September 3, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Iraq                
    <li>Kurd 
    <li>OPSEU Strike        
    <li>Bertrand 
    <li>Prostate Treatment  
    <li>Tears Update        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Iraq</b><p>
<br>     US president Clinton says Saddam Hussein must pay a price for the weekend assault on a Kurdish enclave in northern Iraq.<br>   Early today, the US launched a cruise missile attack against Iraqi military targets in retaliation for the incursion.<br>   Clinton says the US is also extending the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.<br>   Saddam has ordered his troops to ignore "no-fly" zones and to go after foreign aircraft.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Kurd </b><p>
<br> The US attack on Iraq is getting mixed international reviews.<br>  Britain, Germany and Japan support the attack.<br>  Russia and China are opposed.<br>  And in Ottawa, foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy says the Chretien government supports the missile strikes completely.
<hr>
<b>OPSEU Strike</b><p>
<br>  The Ontario Public Service Union is involved in its second strike this year. But this time around, "it" is the target.<br>  The dispute involves OPSEU and it's very own staff.
<hr>
<b>Bertrand </b><p>
<br> A Quebec city lawyer might not go ahead with his case challenging future referendums on Quebec sovereignty.<br>  But Guy Bertrand says that is only if the Parti Quebecois government decides not to proceed with a challenge to his argument.<br>  Bertrand maintains that Quebec can't unilaterally declare sovereignty.
<hr>
<b>Prostate Treatment</b><p>
<br>   There's new hope for men who suffer from prostate disease.<br>  Fifty percent of men over the age of sixty, suffer from the disease that causes an enlarged prostate.<br>  But as Lauran Sabourin reports a new drug developed by a canadian researcher shows promise in controlling the disease.
<i><br>  The drug is called Proscar.<br>  It was tested on 13 hundred men in a number of Canadian cities during six clinical trials.<br>  The results indicated that the drug caused an enlarged prostate gland to shrink. <br>  A reduction in the size of the prostate gland improves urine flow and relieves painful symptoms. <br>  The Canadian specialists who conducted the study are excited about its findings.<br>   They say the drug Proscar treats the underlying cause of the disease rather than just the symptoms.<br>  By blocking the production of the hormone linked to the disease.<br>  It reduces the need for invasive and expensive surgery. <br>  The prescription drug is taken orally once a day and has few side effects.</i>
<hr>
<b>Tears Update</b><p>
There is a growing controversy over an apparent religious miracle in Toronto.<br>  The Toronto Sun is reporting the church, where a religious icon is said to be weeping, is run by a priest, accused of being a brothel employee.<br>   The newspaper says ecclesiastical records show Father Leronimos Katseas was excommunicated from the traditional Greek Orthodox Church back in 1993.<br>   Despite those allegations, worshippers continue to line up waiting to see the weeping painting of the virgin Mary.<br>   The alleged tears were first noticed sunday at the small church, which is a member of a breakaway Greek Orthodox sect.


<P>
