<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, August 21, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Bailey Bashing      
    <li>Gerretsen for Libs  
    <li>Boyle - Wednesday     
    <li>Dental Health       
    <li>Gorilla Boy         
    <li>Tainted Blood       
    <li>DeKlerk            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bailey Bashing</b><p>
 Canadians, fed up with Americans who refuse to acknowledge Donovan Bailey as the world's fastest man, are fighting back with their pocketbooks. The battle is being spearheaded by a Niagara Falls man and Bailey's hometown newspaper. Bob Ireland has the story.
<i><br>  Mike Leskiw is a quiet Niagara Falls body shop owner who usually minds his own business. But when he say the American tv show Entertainment Tonight, refer to US Olympic runner Michael Johnson as the fastest man in the world, not Canadian Donovan Bailey, he saw red.<br>  Both Donovan Bailey and Michael Johnson broke world records at the Atlanta Olympic games. Johnson ran the 200 metres in 19.32 seconds. But Bailey, seen here in another race, ran the 100 metres in 9.84 seconds, and is considered the fastest man in the world. Although Entertainment Tonight appologized to Leskiw, the 41 year Niagara Falls man said that is not enough. He has donated one thousand dollars of his family's vacation money,towards a full page ad in 'USA Today' to remind Americans who really is the fastest man in the world.<br>  The Oakville Beaver, the newspaper in Bailey's home town has also jumped on the band wagon, and has already bought the five thousand dollar full page ad which will run next week in the USA Today edition distributed in Johnson's home town of Dallas Texas. Beaver publisher Ian Oliver says suuport from local people and business has been fantastic.<br>  Oliver says more than the required 5-thousand dollars has been raised and he hopes to have the ad run in other American cities as well. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Gerretsen for Libs</b><p>
<br>     A former mayor of Kingston is joining the Ontario Liberal Leadership race.<br>   John Gerretsen is now the MPP for Kingston and the islands.<br>   Gerretsen -- who plans to officially announce his candidacy tomorrow -- is the fifth MPP to seek the job currently held by Lyn Mcleod.<br>   Two party activists are also seeking the leadership.<br>   Gerretsen says he's running because Ontario is becoming a province of haves and have-nots, and he doesn't like that.
<hr>
<b>Boyle - Wednesday</b><p>
<br>   General Jean Boyle says the Somalia Inquiry commissioners should look at his overall record if they're questioning his leadership skills.<br>   Boyle accuses the inquiry of spending too much time on what he considers to be a minor mistake by his staff in altering documents and not telling him.<br>   Boyle says the public affairs branch was only one aspect of his job before he became chief of defence staff.<br>   The general said the defence minister seemed to be pleased enough with his record before he elevated him to the top post.
<hr>
<b>Dental Health</b><p>
<br>     A Health Canada report out today, says there's no reason to ban the use of dental fillings containing mercury or to have them removed.<br>   The deparment has rejected findings from an earlier study that suggested that having more than four amalgam fillings posed a health risk.<br>   The department statement says current evidence does not indicate that fillings containing mercury, are causing illness in the general population.
<hr>
<b>Gorilla Boy</b><p>
<br>   A three year old boy, rescued by a gorilla after falling six metres into a gorilla pit, has been released from hospital.<br>   The boy, whose name has not been released, was upgraded to good condition and released yesterday from a Chicago-area hospital.<br>   He suffered mild bruising of his brain tissue after falling into a gorilla compound at the Brookfield Illinois, zoo on friday.<br>   Doctors say he'll probably recover fully.<br>   They also say he does not remember being carried by Binti, a mother gorilla whose protective, maternal actions in the incident made her famous.
<hr>
<b>Tainted Blood</b><p>
<br>   Canada is not the only country undergoing a tainted blood scandal.<br>   Japan's top supplier of blood and blood products, was raided by government officials, after being charged with deliberately selling HIV-tainted products over the last ten years.
<hr>
<b>DeKlerk</b><p>
<br>  It was an apology many South Africans feel was long overdue.<br>  Former South African President FW De Klerk, today accepted responsiblility for human rights abuses committed while he led that country's white minority government.

<P>
