<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, August 20, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Escarpment Future   
    <li>CMA
    <li>Boyle 
    <li>Labrador Helicopter 
    <li>Cougar Attack        
    <li>Belgium Horror House
    <li>Korea Wrap          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Escarpment Future</b><p>
<br>   Environmental groups say the ontario government has quietly given gravel companies freer reign to dig quarries in the Niagara Escarpment.<br>   The groups say the province recently exempted many aggregate firms from legislation designed to protect the escarpment.<br>   A lawyer for the Canadian Environmental Law Association says it's clear what he calls "the scorched-earth policy" of the government has now been extended to the escarpment.              <br>  Environment minister Norm Sterling could not be reached for comment.
<hr>
<b>CMA</b><p>
<br> They support a publicly funded, universal health-care system.<br>   But Canada's doctors want to start talking about a private system of delivering health-care.<br>   Both apparently conflicting resolutions, have passed at the Canadian Medical Association meeting in Nova Scotia.<br>   The vote comes a day after health minister David Dingwall told delegates the federal government won't support a two-tier medical system.
<hr>
<b>Boyle </b><p>
<br>     Canada's top soldier suggests he was betrayed by military staff who altered documents for release to the media without telling him of the changes.<br>   General Jean Boyle has told the Somalia Inquiry that if that's how his staff acted, they lacked integrity and moral fibre.<br>   The chief of defence staff added he did not know the documents that were released to the media had been altered, even though he signed them.
<hr>
<b>Labrador Helicopter</b><p>
<br>  Newly released federal documents say the engines on Canada's helicopters are notoriously unreliable.<br>  But crews are going to have to live with them because upgrading to safer engines would be too expensive.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Cougar Attack</b><p>
<br>     A 36-year-old British Columbia woman has made the ultimate sacrifice in saving her six-year-old son from a cougar attack.<br>   Cindy Parolin went after the cat with a stick when it attacked her son during a family horseback outing late yesterday.<br>   Her two other children then managed to rescue their injured brother and seek help from campers.<br>   But by the time they returned, it was too late and the woman was later pronounced dead in hospital.
<hr>
<b>Belgium Horror House</b><p>
<br>   In Belium, police have made a new discovery in their investigation into a kidnapping ring run by pedophiles.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Korea Wrap</b><p>
<br>   South Korean riot police stormed a university building to end a seven-day occupation by students.<br>   A battle between police and about one-thousand students left much of a classroom block smashed and gutted by fire.<br>   But the casualty list has risen into the hundreds.

<P>
