<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, August 19, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>AMO - Leach           
    <li>McGuinty - Leadership 
    <li>CMA                 
    <li>Bernardo Girlfriend 
    <li>Yeltsin Sick        
    <li>Chechnya Victims    
    <li>Gorilla Follow       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>AMO - Leach</b><p>
 Ontario voters in municipal elections may soon be able to cast their votes by telephone or computer. And municipal elections may be held in October instead of November. These are just some of the possible changes advanced at a convention of Ontario municipalities in Toronto. 

<hr>
<b>McGuinty - Leadership</b><p>
<br>  Ottawa area MPP Dalton McGuinty, is now the third person to enter the Ontario Liberal Leadership race.<br>   With his family at his side, McGuinty arrived at Queens Park this morning to announce that he will seek his party's leadership at a convention to be held this November in Toronto.<br>  McGuinty, who has been an MPP for six years, says unlike premier Harris who believes in less government, he believes government should play a significant role in shaping the type of environment in which most Ontarians wish to live.             <br>  Although there could be as many as six candidates in the running for the Liberal leadership, to date, only two other MPPs, Dwight Duncan of Windsor and Gerard Kennedy of Toronto, have declared their intentions.
<hr>
<b>CMA</b><p>
<br>     The Canadian Medical Association isn't getting any support from Ottawa, as it prepares to debate the merits of a two-tier medical system.<br>   Health Minister David Dingwall told the association's annual meeting today, the rich will not be allowed to receive better care simply because they can afford it.<br>  But members of the association say they are being forced into a two-tier system because of cutbacks in funding by Ottawa.             <br>       The issue of a two-tiered medical system is expected to be debated tomorrow at the association's meeting in Sydney, Nova Scotia.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Girlfriend</b><p>
<br>   A woman, who wishes to keep her identity a secret, says she has renewed an old relationship with convicted killer Paul Bernardo.<br>   The woman, who is in her late 20s, has told Maclean's Magazine she still has a strong emotional attachment to Bernardo.<br>   She says she simply can't explain why she is still attracted to a man who has been convicted of the sex-slayings of two Niagara-area teens and the rape of 18 other women.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Sick</b><p>
<br> In world news tonight, the Kremlin is denying an American magazine report that Russian president Boris Yeltsin is ailing.<br>   Time Magazine says Yeltsin is so sick, he is considering going abroad for heart surgery.<br>   He has been seen publicly only once since winning re-election.<br>   That was at his inauguration and he appeared weak and frail.
<hr>
<b>Chechnya Victims</b><p>
<br>   A cease-fire is said to be in place in the Chechen capitol of Grozny.<br>   But, that doesn't mean the violence is over.
<hr>
<b>Gorilla Follow</b><p>
<br>  Here's an update now on a story we first brought you Friday.<br>  Doctors in Brookfield Illinois have upgraded the condition of toddler who was seriiously injured at a local zoo.<br>  The three year old boy, climbed over a metre high fence and plunged six metres into the concrete Gorilla pit that housed seven Gorillas.<br>  With her own baby on her back, a female Gorilla, approached the child, cradled him in her arms and brought him to a gate where he was retrieved by paramedics.<br>  



<P>
