<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, August 14, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Mclean - Harassment   
    <li>Somalia Inquiry     
    <li>Axworthy        
    <li>Preemies - Life     
    <li>Big Baby            
    <li>Lucky Chutist       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Mclean - Harassment</b><p>
<br>  The speaker of the Ontario legislature, is denying accusations that he sexually harassed a female employee.<br>  Sandi Thompson, a special assistant to Al Mclean, has hired a lawyer and filed a complaint against the 59-year old veteran Conservative member of the legislature.
<hr>
<b>Somalia Inquiry</b><p>
<br>     Chief of defence staff general Jean Boyle continues to be grilled at the Somalia inquiry over document tampering.<br>   The military's top officer denies giving the o-k to release altered briefing notes.<br>   Others have told the probe that Boyle -- who was then associate deputy minister responsible for policy and communication -- did in fact authorize the release of the documents.            <br>   During three days of testimony before the commission, the general has distanced himself from a scandal over tampered documents related to the ill-fated mission to somalia.
<hr>
<b>Axworthy </b><p>
<br>  For the second time in just over a month, a Canadian tourist has been sexually assaulted while visiting the island of Bermuda.<br>  Last month, 17 year old Rebecca Middleton was raped and killed.<br>  Just yesterday, a Canadian woman was sexually attacked during a home robbery.<br>   Bermuda police say the attackers also bound and robbed two other Canadians that were in the home, one of whom is a Canadian senator.<br>   Canadas foreign affairs minister believes it may be time to issue a travel warning to canadian tourists.
<hr>
<b>Preemies - Life</b><p>
<br>  For nearly 25 years doctors and nurses at Hamilton's Chedoke Mcmaster Hospitals have been pulling off miracles as they help pre-mature infants begin life outside the womb...<br>  Many of those preemies develop normally, but others do not... and as Jamie West reports...a recently published study indicates that despite disabilities, years later those preemies say they're doing just fine...
<i><br>  Cara is just over a month old, weighs 790 grams is a part of a group known as extremely low birth weight babies...<br>  Three in every thousand check in at under three pounds...and their survival rate has climbed to 75 percent over the last twenty years. <br> 25 percent of this study group have disabilities ranging from visual impairment to severe cerebral palsy ...but after 16 years of tracking they've told researchers their quality of life is about the same as full term youngsters...<br>  Quality of life included their mobility, vision hearing, mental functioning, emotional well being, pain and self care abilities.<br>   The information could eventually help doctors and ultimately parents grapple with the often difficult dilemma of knowing how much technology to apply in order to save the life of a baby born in the 23 or 24 week of gestation. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Big Baby</b><p>
<br>  And from underwight babies to the story of an overweight baby who simply cannot stop growing.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Lucky Chutist</b><p>
<br>  What at first appeared to be a picture perfect dive, ended in a terrifying free fall for a rookie parachutist... and it was all captured on tape.



