<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, August 13, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Somalia         
    <li>Alberta Train       
    <li>Train Derailment    
    <li>Ipperwash Demo      
    <li>Hospital Closings   
    <li>Electronic Cop      
    <li>Gun Control         
    <li>Fidel at 70         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Somalia </b><p>
<br>    The military's top officer says he can't guarantee a public inquiry will ever get all the documents it wants to investigate the Canadian Airborne Regiment's ill-fated mission to Somalia.<br>   General Jean Boyle told the inquiry today that he found out late last week that some intelligence documents were destroyed as late as February.<br>   He ordered an investigation of the unit that was responsible for the destroyed reports.<br>   The commission spent three hours grilling Boyle -- in his second day of testimony -- about the defence department's tardiness in turning over some documents and complete failure to deliver others.
<hr>
<b>Alberta Train</b><p>
<br>  Three people are now said to be missing and presumed dead, after a CN Rail freight train collided with a block of misplaced cars and caught fire in west-central Alberta.<br>   The crash occurred last night on CN's main line in a forested area about 200-kilometres west of Edmonton.<br>   Two crew members and another man have been missing ever since.<br>   Several of the cars in the BC-bound train were carrying products classified as dangerous materials.<br>   But it appears there's no threat to the environment or people in the area.
<hr>
<b>Train Derailment</b><p>
<br> Investigators meanwhile, have pinpointed a likely cause of Saturday's train derailment in Kerwood, Ontario, west of London.<br>   CN Rail officials are focusing on an empty  car, which was the first of 37 to leave the tracks.<br>   They're checking for worn wheels, axles or suspension -- all of which may have caused the car to lift off the tracks.<br>   More than 200 people were forced from their homes for about 12 hours, after one of the derailed cars began spewing sulphuric acid.
<hr>
<b>Ipperwash Demo</b><p>
 <br>  Business at the Sarnia courthouse continued without interruption today, despite the noise and tension of an angry protest outside.<br>  The provincial police officer accused of shooting a Chippewa protester at Ipperwash last year was making a court appearance.<br>  Alex Reynolds reports.
<i> <br>  Police fought to keep about 30 aboriginal demonstrators away from more than 80 cottagers who are upset with the continued occupation of Ipperwash Provincial Park. <br>  The cottagers call themselves "on-fire" - an acronym for Ontario Federation for Individual Rights and Equality.<br>  The group was showing support for police efforts to end the occupation of the park.<br>  Acting provincial police Sgt. Kenneth Deane made a brief court appearance on a charge of criminal negligence causing the death of Dudley George.<br>  George was shot in September 1995 when protesters occupying Ipperwash Provincial Park clashed with police at the gates. <br>  The aboriginals claim racism is at the root of "on-fire's" support for the police.<br>  They deny there has been any harassment of cottagers or residents around Ipperwash.<br>  Sarnia police kept the two groups apart as the protesters hurled insults at each other for about 30 minutes.<br>  Aboriginal groups and even the federal indian affairs minister have called for a public inquiry into the shooting, but the province has refuse.</i>
<hr>
<b>Hospital Closings</b><p>
<br>     Hospital administrators are reacting with shock at reports the Ontario Health Ministry wants to close an extra four hospitals in metro Toronto.<br>   That would bring the total on the chopping block to 15.<br>   The Toronto area currently has 44 hospitals.<br>   A final decision on the cuts is expected by fall.
<hr>
<b>Electronic Cop</b><p>
<br>  Run a red light in toronto, and you may soon be captured on tape, facing a hefty fine.<br>   Toronto is just one of many Candian cities considering the traffic light version of photo radar, to catch motorists who fail to obey traffic signals.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Gun Control</b><p>
<br>  The rejection of a law calling for handgun control, has triggered a political fight in Britain.<br>   For many, it's an emotional issue following the school massacre in Dunblane, Scotland.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Fidel at 70</b><p>
<br>  He has been Cuba's maximum leader for more than half of his life-time.<br>  And by all accounts, he may continue to lead Cuba for some time to come.<br>  Fidel Castro turned 70 years old today and despite a number of assassination attempts, and the efforts of nine US presidents, he has emerged as one of history's ultimate political survivors.<br>  

<P>
