<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, August 12, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Doctors - Update      
    <li>Olsen - Faint Hope    
    <li>Perot - Conv.         
    <li>Ireland Standoff    
    <li>China Floods        
    <li>Octuplets           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Doctors - Update</b><p>
 The clock is ticking as segments of Ontario's doctors threaten to stop taking new patients, unless the harris government comes through with an extra half -a-billion dollars. So far the province is saying no. 
<hr>
<b>Olsen - Faint Hope</b><p>
  <br>  One of Canada's most reviled serial killers is eligible to apply for early parole today.<br>  Clifford Olson was sentenced in 1982 to life in prison for killing eleven children in British Columbia.<br>  But as Lauran Sabourin reports the families of those children feel they're being victimized all over again.
<i><br>  Eleven victims ...eleven tormented families.<br>  The legacy of Clifford Olson.<br>  The man brutally tortured his young victims.<br>  Is now eligble to apply for early parole.<br>  A loophole in the justice system that causes Ray King to relive the pain.<br>  The section of the criminal code that first degree murderers to apply for early parole is section 745.,  a section that public, the police victims' rights groups want changed.<br>    CAVEAT, Canadians Against Violence Everywhere Advocating its Termination has been leading the fight for changes to the criminal code.<br>  They dont' believe that Clifford Olson will get the opportunity to apply for early parole. But as they see it, that's not the point.<br>  The messages in CAVEAT literature shout that instead of locking a killer up for life.<br>  745 gives them a revolving turnstile to freedom. <br> And while the propoents of section 745 argue that in a convict sentenced to life should be rewarded for good behavior,  the victims families will say that they too have been handed a life sentence. A  sentence that comes with no rewards. </i>
<hr>
<b>Perot - Conv.</b><p>
Not far from the Republican Convention, American reformers are meeting in Long Beach, California.<br>  Two candidates, billionaire Ross Perot and former Colorado governor Richard Lamm are battling for the reform party presidential nomination.<br>   Lamm, is hoping against long odds to steal the nomination from party founder Perot.<br>   Perot founded the reform party and won 19 per cent of the vote as an independent in the 1992 presidential race.
<hr>
<b>Ireland Standoff</b><p>
<br> A tense weekend of demonstrations in northern Ireland ended peacefully today, when a protestant march was allowed to pass through a largely roman Catholic village after a lengthy stand-off.<br>  Police and clergymen brokered an end to a 20-hour confrontation between pro-irish catholics and protestants loyal to Britain.<br>  Police had feared the weekend parades would spark a repeat of widespread rioting a month ago.
<hr>
<b>China Floods</b><p>
<br> The death toll continues to rise as heavy rains continue to lash southeast China.<br>   250 have died and nearly 300,000 people dispalced by the flood waters.<br>   In neighbouring Fujian Province, the torrential rains have killed at least 233, with 284 missing.<br>  Economic losses have been estimated at more than 200 billion dollars.
<hr>
<b>Octuplets</b><p>
<br>  The issue of selective abortion made headlines in Britain recently, in the case of a low income mother who chose to abort one of two healthy twin-fetuses.<br>  Another case that's drawing attention also concerns multiple-embryo's and controversial health issues.


<P>
