<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, August 9, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Jobless             
    <li>New Jobs Harris     
    <li>Rates      
    <li>Pension Hit         
    <li>Engine Trouble      
    <li>Discount Flying     
    <li>Parrott Accused     
    <li>Becky Fund          
    <li>Women - Abuse    
    <li>Food Drive          
    <li>Yeltsin             
    <li>Chechnya            
    <li>Ireland Update      
    <li>Buck House          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Jobless</b><p>
<br> Analysts are pouring over the latest unemployment figures... nationally it was slightly improved last month over June.<br>   Stats Canada says the rate was 9.89 for July, down a bit from 10 per cent in June.<br>   Ontario's jobless figures fell slightly to 9.2 per cent from nine and a half.<br>   Compared to an average of the previous three months, the July employment picture looked brighter in Hamilton and St. Catharines- Niagara.<br>   But there were more people out of work in Oshawa, Toronto and London.
<hr>
<b>New Jobs Harris</b><p>
<br>   About 89-thousand jobs have been created in Ontario in the last 13 months. But an economist says premier Mike Harris cannot take credit for those jobs... even though they've come since he took office.<br>   MMS International economist Andrew Pyle says the strength of the American economy has more to do with the new jobs than any government policy here.
<hr>
<b>Rates</b><p>
 Rates on the move again today.. the Bank of Canada has cut its lending rate one-quarter percentage point, to 4.5 per cent. That, in turn, has triggered a quarter point cut in the prime at the banks to six per cent. 
<hr>
<b>Pension Hit</b><p>
 Low income workers and their employers could be hit with hefty increases in Canada Pension Plan premiums if Ontario and Quebec have their way. Sources out of Ottawa say, ontario is pushing the federal government to reduce the amount of wages that are exempt from CPP premiums. 
<HR>
<b>Engine Trouble</b><p>
<br>  The dog that flies was forced to limp home, with its tail between its legs, this morning. A Greyhound Air 727 bound for Winnipeg out of Hamilton, was forced to abort the flight and return for an emergency landing at Mount Hope Airport; due to an electrical problem with one of the aircraft's three engines. No one was injured; but the incident; has raised new questions about the safety of discount airlines.
<hr>
<b>Discount Flying</b><p>
<br>   It was a shakey start for greyhound airlines which suffered many setbacks and months of delays. But the low cost carrier says business is been booming since it began trans-continental service last month.<br>  Today the airline said it expects to fill 85 of its available seats this month.<br>  The question is can cut-rate carriers like Greyhound survive?<br>  Industry watchers say a lot depends on its safety record and Canadians long-term committment to no-frills travel.
<hr>
<b>Parrott Accused</b><p>
<br>   Frank Roy denies he raped and killed 11-year-old Alison Parrott 10 years ago.<br>   The 38-year-old is charged with first-degree murder in the Toronto girl's brutal death.<br>   Roy says he'll plead not guilty.<br> And he denounces as "hogwash" the police investigation into whether he's behind the slayings of several Vancouver prostitutes.
<hr>
<b>Becky Fund</b><p>
<br>   A trust fund set up by a Bermuda dentist to honor murdered Belleville teenager Rebecca Middleton.<br>   Dr. Ian Campbell has raised sixty two thousand doolars in the scholarship trust fund so far. Middleton was was raped and stabbed to death in Bermuda last month.  The two men charged in the teen's death will appear in court again August 22nd.
<hr>
<b>Women - Abuse </b><p>
<br>   A study released today puts a huge price tag on sexual assault and abuse of women in Canada. According to a the new comprehensive report examines violence against women costs 4.2 billion dollars a year.  Over four hundred million is spent on medical treatments alone. <br>  
<hr>
<b>Food Drive</b><p>
<br>     Donations of non-perishable food items are still badly needed in a province-wide food drive.<br>   The food drive by 180 food banks began two weeks ago. but not nearly enough food has been collected...<br>   donations can be made at IGA, Food City and other stores with the Oshawa Food Group.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin</b><p>
 <br>  Boris Yeltsin has been sworn in as Russia's president at a colourful ceremony at the Kremlin. In his speech, Yeltsin promised to uphold the Russian constitution and protect human rights. But the 65-year-old president spoke for just 45 seconds as he took the oath of office in his first public appearance since June 26th. Yeltsin had two heart attacks last year and his disappearance in the run-up to the inauguration had prompted speculation that he was ill again. He has been resting in a sanatorium near Moscow for the last three weeks and is expected to take a longer vacation soon.
<hr>
<b>Chechnya</b><p>
 Meanwhile, a political headache for Yeltsin continues to worsen. Russian troops have retreated from parts of Grozny. Rebels have tightened their grip on the Chechen capital and say they have seized two buildings held by the Moscow-run government. Journalists trapped in the battle zone have issued appeals for help and say some of the government buildings are on fire.
<hr>
<b>Ireland Update</b><p>
Tension is running high in Londonderry, Northern Ireland, where a Catholic March is planned for tonight and a Protestant parade is set for tomorow. Extra police and british soldiers will be on patrol amid fears that each side will violently protest the other's march. Unrest sparked by the route of a protestant march in Portadown last month left one man dead and scores injured in the mainly roman catholic city.
<hr>
<b>Buck House</b><p>
<br> Britain's royal family is in disrepute as never before. But that's not putting off the crowds queuing up to walk the same halls and gaze at the same walls as the royals. Buckingham Palace has just opened again to the public for two months while the Queen's away, and this year is looking just as lucrative as ever.


<P>
