<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, August 8, 1996</H2><BR>

<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Casino Rama         
    <li>Smoking Suit
    <li>Mortgage       
    <li>Royal Trust         
    <li>Bad Boss Hotline    
    <li>Pregnant Complaints 
    <li>Glue Sniffer      
    <li>Train Crash         
    <li>Spain Floods        
    <li>Immigrant Beating   
    <li>TWA Bodies          
    <li>Mars                
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Casino Rama</b><p>
<br>   Ontario's newest casino wants to get the message out: bring your cash -- but not your kids. <br>   
Up to a hundred kids were seen roaming around the parking lot of Casino Rama on Saturday... left to entertain themselves by parents eager to make a buck.. after that, the casino started turning people away who arrived with chidren under nineteen in their cars ...<br>  At one point, casino officials went on the PA system and asked people to retrieve their kids, who were wandering around unattended.
<hr>
<b>Smoking Suit </b><p>
<br>   The battle over the city of Toronto's tough new anti-smoking bylaw is going to end up in the courts. <br>     The Ontario Restaurant Association has announced a legal challenge of the bylaw due to go into effect January 1st of next year.<br>   The by-law prohibits smoking in all Toronto bars, restaurants, pubs and night clubs.<br>   Association president Paul Oliver says they will argue that the bylaw restricts people's freedom of choice because it reduces the public's ability to decide where they can eat and drink.  <br>  
<hr>
<b>Mortgage </b><p>
<br>     Consumers are in for more interest-rate relief.<br>   Long-term mortgage rates are falling at both the Royal and the Bank of Montreal.<br>   The five-year rate falls to 7.95 per cent, down from 8.10 per cent.<br>   The move follows cuts in short-term mortgages and other consumer lending rates last week.  <br>  
<hr>
<b>Royal Trust</b><p>
<br> Meanwhile thousands of Canadians were left short of cash after Royal Trust accidentally withdrew their mortgage or loan payments twice over the weekend. The bank says the problem was caused by human error at the London processing centre. All affected customers were to have their accounts corrected today.
<hr>
<b>Bad Boss Hotline</b><p>
 Ever feel like ratting on your boss... well now there's a way to do it. The Ontario Federation of Labor says the Harris government's intention to relax employment standards, is encouraging some employers to short change their workers. And now the OFL has introduced its "bad boss" hotline, where workers can tell all.  
<hr>
<b>Pregnant Complaints</b><p>
<br>     The impact of the bitter battle between Ontario's doctors and the Harris government is already being felt.<br>   A spokesman for the Ontario College of Physicians and Surgeons says they are getting hundreds of calls from pregnant women who are having trouble finding doctors who will deliver their babies.<br>   Dozens of obstetricians, and other specialists, are refusing to take on new patients in the dispute with Queen's Park.<br>   Most of the calls are from southern Ontario, especially parts of Toronto, nearby Peel Region, Niagara and Windsor.<br>   The doctors want the health ministry to fully restore subsidies for their malpractice insurance and to stop clawbacks of their fees.
<hr>
<b>Glue Sniffer</b><p>
  The controversial case of a pregnant woman hooked on glue sniffing is in the news again. <br>  The woman has won a stay of a judge's order that would force her into a treatment centre for her addiction. Social workers sought the order because of the damage she could due to her unborn child. She has two other kids already suffering developmental problems due to her glue sniffing.<br>  The father of the baby says even though the woman doesn't have to go the the treatment centre now.. she will stay in hospital and received care.
<hr>
<b>Train Crash</b><p>
 <br> Two people are believed dead and up to 40 trapped after a crowded commuter train crashed into an empty train just north of London. The accident happened at the height of the evening rush-hour just north of the busy Watford Junction. Police say about 100 people are injured.
<hr>
<b>Spain Floods</b><p>
Flash floods are now being blamed for more than 60 deaths at a campsite near the border between France and Spain. The flooding has swept away trees, tents and pieces of furniture. Officials say about 140 people were injured in the torrent of water, rocks and mud. divers and firefighters looking for more victims today fear the death toll will rise. When the heavy rains started last night, up to 800 people were camped at the site. Dozens of people, including many children, have been evacuated and put up in hotels, police stations and private homes in the area.
<hr>
<b>Immigrant Beating</b><p>
 <br>   A California sheriff's deputy has lost his job over the videotaped beating of two illegal immigrants. Today's "Los Angeles Times" says Riverside County fired Tracy Watson yesterday.  TV news crews videotaped Watson and another deputy beating two Mexicans after an April chase. The officers involved are appealing ..they say their use of force was justified.
<hr>
<b>TWA Bodies</b><p>
 <br>   A medical examiner concludes most of the TWA crash victims met a sudden end. Doctor Charles Wetli says most of the victims suffered "massive whiplash" that snapped their necks -- right after an explosion rocked the 747 off New York. Two hundred and thirty peole were killed when the plane blew up last month. Officials don't believe they will ever find the remaining thirty five bodies that have not been recovered yet.
<hr>
<b>Mars</b><p>
<br>  And a footnote now to our life on Mars coverage yesterday... <br>     NASA researchers are challenging other scientists to prove them wrong. They have claimed that microscopic particles inside a meteorite from Mars contain signs of life. But other experts say organic material is not necessarily proof that life exists or existed. NASA says it welcomes skepticism, in the hope some one will find the definitive truth. The answer to the eternal question ...are we alone.


<P>
