<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 08/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, August 2, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Parrott Newser 
<LI>Four Dead 
<LI>Ontario Reform 
<LI>Doctors Off 
<LI>Ontario Embryos 
<LI>Marijuana Bust 
<LI>Aidid Dead 
<LI>Yeltsin Health 
<LI>Truck Penalty 
<LI>Economy Poll 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Parrott Newser </H3>

<P>
Metro Toronto Police are doing damage control after a media feeding
frenzy on the man charged in the murder of Alison Parrott. Thirty
eight year old Francis Carl Roy is charged with first degree murder
in the rape and strangulation of the eleven year old girl, back
in July of 1986. 
<P>
The police have indicated that Roy is now being investigated for
other crimes across the country... but today the lead investigator
in the murder case, told reporters to use extreme caution when
quoting unidentified sources referring to Roy as a serial killer.

<HR>

<H3>Four Dead </H3>

<P>
A man is under police guard at a Toronto hospital after four people
were shot to death on Manitoulin Island. Police say a man first
shot 37-year-old Eugene Cada and Gloria Jean Morden, who was 34,
as the two sat in a house having coffee yesterday near Gore Bay.
A man then allegedly drove to nearby Elizabeth Bay and turned
a shotgun on Arthur and Elizabeth Long, both in their late 80s.

<P>
Forty- four-year-old Eli Nahwaikezhik is in serious but stable
condition with a self-inflicted gunshot wound. no charges have
been laid. 
<HR>

<H3>Ontario Reform </H3>

<P>
The Reform Party seems to be losing popularity in Ontario, as
is its leader Preston Manning. The latest public opinion poll
should give comfort to Ontario's Tory premier Mike Harris. 
<HR>

<H3>Doctors Off </H3>

<P>
Ontario doctors want Queen's Park to pay up for more than half
a billion dollars worth of services that exceed the health care
budget. If they don't get the money, the Ontario Medical Association
says doctors will decline more work. OMA president Gerry Rowland
says government funding fails to meet growing patient needs. 
<HR>

<H3>Ontario Embryos </H3>

<P>
There's a heated debate raging in Britain over a law that calls
for frozen human embryos to be destroyed after five years of storage...in
British fertility clinics. Some religious leaders have lashed
out at the law...saying it offers no other options for the preservation
of life... as Jamie West reports... here in Ontario ...parties
with a stake in reproductive technology have only begun to explore
the very complicated moral issues... 
<P>
<I>This was the scene yesterday in Britain, hundreds gathered
to mourn what they see as the death of tiny human beings... 3000
human embryos, each consisting of four living human cells frozen
in test tubes for the last five years with no owners to lay claim.
The law calling for their destruction unless owners come forward
to demand otherwise.</I>
<P>
<I>Prominent Hamilton doctor Carmelo Scime is active in the pro-life
movement and agrees with the condemnation ... and although Ontario
is on the leading edge of new reproductive technologies... there
are literally no laws on the books to govern the storage and handling
of frozen human embryos.</I>
<P>
<I>Another prominent Hamilton ob-gyn Dr. John Lamont, says the
British law was conceived to hastily and that Canada must continue
to gather data before jumping on the British bandwagon.</I>
<P>
<I>The Canadian National Reproductive Technologies Commission
has just completed a two volume report that the medical community
hopes politicians will consider before drafting any legislation.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Marijuana Bust </H3>

<P>
Seven-thousand marijuana plants have been seized by the OPP near
Mount Forest. Police used chainsaws to cut down some of the huge
plants. Police also seized several guns, including a semi-automatic
rifle and cultivation equipment. 
<P>
Five suspects have been remanded in custody on drug charges. Charged
are 30-year-old Alan Whittaker of Brampton, 23-year-old Mike McGuigan
of Milton, 41-year-old William Kyle of grand valley, 30-year-old
Alan Dunnigan of Wasaga Beach and 26-year-old Elizabeth Miller.

<HR>

<H3>Aidid Dead </H3>

<P>
Somali faction leader general Mohammed Farrah Aidid has died.
His militia says he died of a heart attack yesterday after being
shot in factional fight last week. 
<P>
Thousands of weeping Somalis poured into the streets of south
Mogadishu today. 
<P>
Aidid, the self-proclaimed president of Somalia, was the target
of a manhunt by U.S. troops in 1993. He was never caught, but
18 U.S. soldiers were killed during an attack on his stronghold.

<HR>

<H3>Yeltsin Health </H3>

<P>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin needs a few months of peace and
quiet. A top Kremlin aide says he's suffering from &quot;colossal
weariness&quot; from the recent election. 
<P>
The 65-year-old Yeltsin, who had two heart attacks last year,
moved into a sanitarium outside Moscow in mid-July. But his aide
denies he's suffered a recurrence of heart trouble. 
<HR>

<H3>Truck Penalty </H3>

<P>
A Montreal trucking company has been handed a light penalty for
a toxic spill that caused one of Ontario's worst traffic snarls.
Provost Bulk Transport will be prohibited from operating part
of its fleet in Ontario for 10 days. 
<P>
In June of last year, a tanker toppled over on Highway 401 in
Toronto, spilling potentially explosive liquid. The accident happened
during morning rush-hour and closed part of the busy highway for
six hours. The Transportation Ministry was seeking a tougher penalty.

<HR>

<H3>Economy Poll </H3>

<P>
A new poll suggests Canadians think better economic times are
just around the bend. An Angus Reid poll finds optimism has risen
significantly since January, with 75 per cent of those asked expecting
the economy will stay the same or improve in the coming year.

<P>
Quebecers are the most gloomy about their provincial economy --
they have been since the October referendum. Other Canadians say
they're perking up, with one in three respondents seeing better
times. 



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

