<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/31/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, July 31, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Vaughan Explosion 
<LI>Parrott Arrest 
<LI>Cyclist Killed 
<LI>Toronto Accident 
<LI>Environment Regulations 
<LI>Kitchener Doctors 
<LI>Bomber Update 
<LI>Valujet Memorial 
<LI>407 - Toll Road 
<LI>Angus Reid Poll 
<LI>Reform Back 
<LI>Casino Opens 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Vaughan Explosion </H3>

<P>
A 14-year-old rescued his grandmother from the debris of her collapsed
house north of Toronto today after the house next door exploded.
Christopher Wice says he was helping to clean his grandparents'
garage in Vaughan when the neighbor's house blew up. 
<P>
The blast caused the home to explode around Wice and his grandmother.
Wice lifted the debris from 66-year-old Peggy McLaughlin and rushed
her out of the house. 
<P>
The blast destroyed two houses and severely damaged two others,
sending debris throughout the quiet neighborhood.
<HR>

<H3>Parrott Arrest </H3>

<P>
An arrest has been made in the ten-year-old murder case of a Toronto
girl. Metro police say 38-year-old Francis Carl Roy of Toronto
has been charged in the first degree murder of Allison Parrott.

<P>
In July of 1986 the girl left her mid- Toronto home to meet a
photographer near varsity stadium. Her body was found two days
later in the Humber Valley. An autopsy determined she had been
sexually assaulted and strangled. 
<HR>

<H3>Cyclist Killed </H3>

<P>
Another cyclist was struck has been killed in downtown Toronto
... the biker was hit by a tractor trailer on Commissioners Street
in the east end. The cyclist was caught under the wheels of the
rig. Commissioners Street is a popular link for cyclists to the
east end beaches. 
<P>
Just over a week ago, 25-year-old Erin Krauser of Toronto was
killed when she was hit by a truck while cycling in downtown Toronto.

<HR>

<H3>Toronto Accident </H3>

<P>
One of those injured in yesterday's bus shelter crash has died...
an elderly man died today from the injuries he suffered when he
was hit by a car at a transit shelter in Toronto. Eighty-year-old
Chris Petrou of Toronto suffered a heart attack and died in a
hospital where he was being treated for a broken pelvis. 
<P>
Petrou was among about a dozen people injured when a car crashed
into the transit shelter after colliding with another car yesterday.
Three- year-old Michael Quintanilla is in critical condition with
head and leg injuries, including bleeding in his skull. Twenty-
six-year-old Thuy Thanh Ly of Westminster, California, is been
charged with running a red light. 
<HR>

<H3>Environment Regulations </H3>

<P>
An Environment Ministry report released today is recommending
big changes to environmental protection rules in Ontario. The
report suggests dumping half of the province's environmental regulations.

<P>
Although the government insists the changes won't hurt the environment,
environmental groups think otherwise. 
<HR>

<H3>Kitchener Doctors </H3>

<P>
Nine surgeons in Kitchener- Waterloo took the day off to protest
the closure this week of operating rooms at both the Kitchener-
Waterloo Health Centre and St. Mary's Hospital. Only emergency
cases were being taken. 
<P>
The shutdown is to allow staff to take summer vacations. 
<P>
Dr. Gerald Lansky, a general surgeon, says he doesn't care about
the impact on patients. He says the public has been spoiled rotten.
patients who need urgent surgery will be transferred to hospitals
out of town. 
<HR>

<H3>Bomber Update </H3>

<P>
U.S. federal agents have towed away the pickup truck belonging
to Olympic security guard Richard Jewell. This, after bringing
in a dog to search his Atlanta apartment. 
<P>
Jewell was praised as a hero for spotting the bomb at Centennial
Olympic Park. but now, he's under investigation for the attack
that killed one person and injured 110 others. 
<HR>

<H3>Valujet Memorial </H3>

<P>
&quot;They are loved, and they are remembered.&quot; Those words
accompanied the reading of the names of people who died in a Valujet
crash in the Florida Everglades. Nearby were 50 caskets, each
with a single rose on top. 
<P>
National transportation safety board chairman Jim Hall read a
message to the mourners from U.S. president Clinton. 
<P>
Yesterday, at the everglades crash site, a memorial service was
held for all 110 victims of the May 11th crash. 
<HR>

<H3>407 - Toll Road </H3>

<P>
Phase one of Canada's first privately managed toll highway will
open before the end of the year; but will there be enough users
to pay for the one billion dollar cost? Critics of the all-electronic
toll highway say taxpayers might not recover their money because
of a lack of information about how to use the new highway. George
Szostak has more. 
<P>
<I>Stressful traffic congestion on Canada's busiest highway, the
401 near Pearson Airport. Ontario's answer to avoid or reduce
heavy traffic flows on the 401 is the 407 express toll route;
Canada's first all electronic toll highway that will be managed
by a private company. </I>
<P>
<I>Six lanes of white concrete will span 62 kilometres north of
the 401 from Oakville to Scarborough. Video cameras will photograph
each license plate and the driver will be sent a bill. Frequent
users can get a transponder for their vehicle for electronic tracking.
</I>
<P>
<I>The first phase of Highway 407 will run 36 kilometres from
Brampton to Markham. That's scheduled to open by the end of the
year. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Angus Reid Poll </H3>

<P>
A new Angus Reid poll shows support for the Reform Party is still
strong in Alberta, but slumping elsewhere. The survey conducted
this past week shows the party's approval rating nationwide is
just 12 per cent -- the same as it is for the Tories. 
<P>
The Liberals still lead with 57 per cent support among those questioned.

<HR>

<H3>Reform Back </H3>

<P>
The results come as Reform tries to put to rest, the controversy
over remarks made by members Dave Chatters and Bob Ringma about
homosexuals and visible minorities. Reform held a mid-summer caucus
session today. 
<HR>

<H3>Casino Opens </H3>

<P>
Canada's biggest native- run casino opened near Orillia today.
This after a judge made a crucial decision affecting the distribution
of profits. The province has been ordered to give Metis and non-status
Indians a share of the 100-million dollars a year in expected
profits from the casino. Originally, the money was to be shared
by the province and aboriginal bands recognized by Ottawa. 



<P>
