<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, July 30, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Hospitals Re: Doctors 
<LI>Irving Up 
<LI>Crime Statistics 
<LI>G7 Meet 
<LI>Olympic Park 
<LI>TWA Update 
<LI>Drowning 
<LI>Hwy. 427 Crash 
<LI>Roof Collapse 
<LI>Consumers Woes 
<LI>Casino Advance 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hospitals Re: Doctors </H3>

<P>
First it was the obstetricians refusing to accept new patients.
Now it's orthopedic surgeons who are threatening to strike. This
evening Niagara residents are being warned that beginning September
1st because of a dispute with the government over fees they may
have to cross the border to get treatment for broken and fractured
bones, because specialists in the peninsula are walking off the
job. Lauran Sabourin has the details. 
<P>
<I>On a normal day staff in the St. Catharines General emergency
room don't' have a moment to rest. 62 percent of the cases that
come through the emergency are broken and fractured bones. Cases
looked after by orthopedic specialists. But because of a dispute
over fee clawbacks with the government the orthopedic surgeons
in Niagara are threatening to strike. </I>
<P>
<I>What hospital administrators and doctors at St. Catharines
General are predicting is that patients will be stabilized in
emergency. But may have to be transported by ambulance to hospitals
in New York state. But if the doctors do refuse to care for patients
they admit they will be hurt.</I>
<P>
<I>Waits will be longer in the emergency room for everyone. Patients
with broken and fractured bones could be traveling miles by ambulance,
waiting hours for treatment. But the doctors who support the strike
action recount just how much money they are losing because of
government cutbacks.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Irving Up </H3>

<P>
Canada's environment minister toured the Irving Whale site today.
Sergio Marchi says he's relieved that an environmental threat
is being looked after. 
<P>
The barge was carrying oil and PCBs when it sank in 1970 north
of Prince Edward Island. The Irving whale was raised from the
floor of the gulf of St. Lawrence to the surface of the water
this morning. 
<HR>

<H3>Crime Statistics </H3>

<P>
Thunder Bay has the highest violent crime rate among major cities
in Ontario. Statistics Canada based the 1995 violent crime rates
for Canadian cities on criminal code incidents per 100 thousand
people. 
<P>
The 1995 rate in Thunder Bay was just over 18-hundred incidents
per 100-thousand people -- but it was down 6.5 per cent from 1994.
Hamilton was next, followed by Sudbury, Ottawa and London. 
<P>
Toronto placed sixth among nine Ontario cities in terms of violent
crime rates. 
<HR>

<H3>G7 Meet </H3>

<P>
Major industrialized countries have agreed &quot;to close ranks
against terrorism.&quot; Foreign and security ministers from the
G-7 countries and Russia have agreed to a set of concrete measures
to fight terrorist activity. A key promise involves finding ways
to share information that could uncover planned terrorist attacks
before they take place. 
<HR>

<H3>Olympic Park </H3>

<P>
A ten-minute delay is under the microscope tonight. Officials
are piecing together the minutes leading up to Saturday's Olympic
bombing in Atlanta. A source says emergency operators took ten
minutes to find the address of Centennial Park, after receiving
a call warning of a bomb. All of this as the park re-opened today.

<HR>

<H3>TWA Update </H3>

<P>
Off Long Island, New York, recovery teams are focusing on the
front section of TWA flight 800. While recovery of bodies remains
the top priority ... officials are pressing ahead with efforts
to determine what caused the jetliner to explode, killing all
230 aboard. 
<HR>

<H3>Drowning </H3>

<P>
An afternoon swim in Mississauga turned tragic yesterday when
a teenage girl drowned after jumping into the Credit River to
help her 11-year-old brother. 
<P>
13-year- old Annie Fernandez was jumping off a railway trestle
with her brother and a friend when it appeared her brother was
in trouble. She jumped in, but never surfaced. Divers recovered
the girl's body a couple of hours later. 
<HR>

<H3>Hwy. 427 Crash </H3>

<P>
The southbound express lanes of highway 427 in west end Toronto
have been reopened after a serious traffic accident. Two tractor
trailers collided around 4:30 this morning. One trucker is in
critical condition in hospital. 
<P>
The transfer lanes from the southbound collector lanes to the
express lanes remained closed... but are due to re-open any time
now. 
<HR>

<H3>Roof Collapse </H3>

<P>
Heavy rain overnight is being blamed for the collapse of a roof
on a Cambridge apartment building. Fourteen apartments in the
building were evacuated. Police say one person was shaken up by
the incident and taken to hospital for treatment. 
<P>
The overnight storms also caused flooding in low-lying areas in
several communities including parts of the Toronto area. 
<HR>

<H3>Consumers Woes </H3>

<P>
The Consumers Distributing chain of retail stores is closing a
large number of its outlets across the country, and is looking
for new money to bail it out of a financial crunch. 
<HR>

<H3>Casino Advance </H3>

<P>
The Orillia area is looking more and more like Las Vegas. There
was a glittering sneak preview of Casino Rama last night for seven
thousand invited guests. 
<P>
Trade minister bill Saunderson, who was on hand for the festivities,
said the casino development will provide direct and indirect jobs
for six thousand people. 
<P>
Casino Rama has two thousand slot machines along with blackjack
tables, roulette wheels, and poker tables. It opens to the public
tomorrow. 



<P>
