<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, July 29, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Atlanta Blast 
<LI>TWA Update 
<LI>Terrorist Meet 
<LI>Doggy Dragged 
<LI>Scarborough Murder 
<LI>Churchill Crash 
<LI>Parachute Down 
<LI>Heart Study 
<LI>Dirty Dancing 
<LI>Food Banks 
<LI>Highway 407 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Atlanta Blast </H3>

<P>
The spirit of the Olympics has been untouched by the bombing at
the Atlanta games over the weekend .. but the attention of the
political world is focused on terrorism. 
<P>
First, the latest on the bombing... Atlanta officials say they
are closing in on a suspect in the blast at a concert early Saturday
morning in Olympic village... and tomorrow they will re-open Centennial
Park where the bombing happened, with a memorial service to the
one dead and scores injured. 
<HR>

<H3>TWA Update </H3>

<P>
And investigators say a key piece of metal could prove a theory
that TWA flight 800 was destroyed by a bomb. A source close to
the investigation says a piece of the plane's aluminum coating
close to the explosion would probably tell what caused the blast.
They believe the plane was severed in two between the first class
and coach cabins by a bomb, possibly being carried in the front
cargo hold. 
<P>
The search is focusing on a debris field about 30 metres below
the Atlantic where the first wreckage settled. Searchers are working
around the clock. 
<HR>

<H3>Terrorist Meet </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. president Clinton is looking for a freer hand
in fighting terrorism... today he called together congressional
leaders to consider several ideas, including expanded wiretapping
and putting chemical tracers in gunpowder... tomorrow.. the fight
against terrorism will be on the global agenda as ministers for
the G-7 Nations gather in Paris. 
<P>
The meeting was called before the explosion on board TWA flight
eight hundred and the Atlanta games blast, but the two events
have added a renewed sense of urgency to the talks. 
<HR>

<H3>Doggy Dragged </H3>

<P>
A story that has shocked and sickened people throughout the province
today... an elderly Shelburne area woman has now been charged
after she tied her three year old Irish Setter to the back bumper
of her car and dragged the dog for half a kilometre along a gravel
road ... she then took the badly injured dog to the vet for treatment.

<P>
Initially the SPCA said they would have to let the woman keep
the dog... but now officials say if they can prove that she is
unfit to care for the dog, then they can take the animal away.
The SPCA will keep the dog until court proceedings against the
woman are complete. 
<P>
The act of cruelty against the dog was, according to its owner,
to teach it a lesson, for leaving the yard. 
<HR>

<H3>Scarborough Murder </H3>

<P>
A Toronto woman is dead and her common law husband in jail ...
the thirty nine year old victim was found early this morning in
a house in the Brimley and Kingston Road area of Scarborough.

<P>
Thirty five year old Thomas Brennan is charged with second degree
murder. Police are asking for the public's help in determining
Brennan's actions leading up to the murder. 
<HR>

<H3>Churchill Crash </H3>

<P>
Dental records will be needed to identify a person who died in
a fiery head-on crash in Mississauga today. Two cars collided
along Winston Churchill Boulevard near highway 401, causing one
car to flip on to its roof and burst into flames. The accident
happened around 3:00 a-m. 
<P>
It's believed the person who died was a woman. One person in the
other car suffered injuries described as non-life- threatening.

<P>
So far this year, 21 people have died in traffic accidents in
Peel Region -- the same number of fatalities for all of last year.

<HR>

<H3>Parachute Down </H3>

<P>
There were two fatal skydiving accidents this past weekend. A
40 year old aurora man fell more than 15-hundred metres to his
death Sunday near Baldwin, south of Lake Simcoe. Neil Montgomery
was an experienced skydiver, but his parachute did not open. 
<P>
And on Saturday, a parachuting instructor in Quebec died after
colliding with another skydiver during a formation jump. 
<HR>

<H3>Heart Study </H3>

<P>
There is more evidence tonight that women are every bit as predisposed
to heart disease as their male counterparts. A recent study conducted
at Toronto's Women's College Hospital disproves the traditional
theory that women just don't get coronary artery disease.... and
as Jamie West reports tonight heart disease for both men and women
is the number one killer in north America... 
<P>
<I>The five year study of 167 women and 348 men found that female
patients developed coronary artery disease to a greater extent
and at a younger age than previously thought. </I>
<P>
<I>Cardiac surgeon Dr. Stephanie Brister performs hundreds of
coronary by-pass operations each year at Hamilton General Hospital.
A third of her patients are women. </I>
<P>
<I>And so the medical community says Brister is working and has
been working to ensure proper diagnostic techniques are developed
for women. To Dr. Brister the results of the Women's College Hospital
study come as no surprise but... conventional thinking women were
protected for life from heart disease by the female hormone estrogen,
has proven to be wrong. Younger women in their late 40's and early
fifties are having heart attacks and occasionally the classic
symptoms of crushing chest pain and jaw numbness are present...
and if you feel the symptoms the advice is to speak up... </I>
<HR>

<H3>Dirty Dancing </H3>

<P>
The courts have declared illegal. Bylaws have banned it. But lap
dancing is again slowly grinding its way into strip bars across
metro Toronto and other communities in Ontario. 
<HR>

<H3>Food Banks </H3>

<P>
The largest ever food drive in Ontario was kicked off this afternoon.
Nearly 200 Ontario food banks have joined forces for a co-ordinated
two-week effort starting today. 
<P>
The summertime food drive was first held last year... and organizers
say the reason is simple...- rapidly falling food supplies. At
the current rate of usage, 110 food banks could run out of food
some time in August. 
<P>
Also, an internal food drive by Hamilton firefighters is going
public this week. Food can be dropped off at Hamilton firehalls
until Sunday. 
<HR>

<H3>Highway 407 </H3>

<P>
Commuters stuck on the 401 highway north of Toronto each day could
have some relief by the end of the year. That's when the first
phase of highway 407 is due for completion. The new toll superhighway
will link highway 410 in Brampton to highway 404 in Markham. 
<P>
By 1998 the highway will link highway 403 in Oakville to highway
48 in Markham. New electronic technology will be used to collect
the tolls. 



<P>
