<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, July 26, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Hijacking 
<LI>TWA 
<LI>CAA Photo Radar 
<LI>HTA Changes 
<LI>Karla Parole 
<LI>Medical Spinal 
<LI>Twoonie Theft 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hijacking </H3>

<P>
The hijacking of a Spanish airliner is over. A police spokesman
says the lone hijacker surrendered and was taken into custody
by the FBI at the Miami International Airport. 
<P>
The Iberia Airlines jet -- with 231 people aboard -- was hijacked
by a man claiming to have a bomb after leaving Madrid on a flight
to Cuba. 
<HR>

<H3>TWA </H3>

<P>
Investigators call it an &quot;extraordinarily important&quot;
find. Search crews have found two of the four engines from TWA
flight 800 on the ocean floor, off New York. They could provide
crucial physical evidence of what happened. 
<P>
All 230 people aboard the plane were killed when it exploded after
taking off from New York's Kennedy International Airport last
week. 
<HR>

<H3>CAA Photo Radar </H3>

<P>
The Canadian Automobile Association is calling on Queen's Park
to bring back photo radar if speed limits go up. The provincial
Tories have indicated they're looking into raising speeds to 120
kilometres an hour on the 400 series highways. The auto club says
there should be zero-tolerance of anyone exceeding that limit.
As Dwight Ryan reports, drivers have varied views on the subject.

<P>
<I>Ontarians either loved it or hated it. Photo radar was one
of the most controversial programs introduced by the New Democrats
during their term in office at Queen's Park. Detractors called
it a cash cow. And the provincial Tories saw it as an election
issue. When the Progressive Conservative's steamrolled into the
Ontario legislature with a majority.. photo radar was mothballed.
</I>
<P>
<I>At this roadside service centre in Grimsby drivers have mixed
views. Even truckers can't agree on what's best for road safety.
The Progressive Conservatives will take another look at increasing
speed limits when the legislature resumes in the fall. </I>
<HR>

<H3>HTA Changes </H3>

<P>
A conservative MPP is going to war, not only with drunk drivers,
but also with passengers who ride beside them. Jim Brown the Tory
member for Scarborough west, plans to bring in a private members
bill that would penalize both the driver and passengers. 
<HR>

<H3>Karla Parole </H3>

<P>
The woman who was convicted in the sex slayings of teens Kristen
French and Leslie Mahaffy could be out on the street as early
as next year. Prison sources say Karla Homolka is a model inmate
and could be granted day parole early next year, and full parole
by the summer. 
<P>
Homolka is serving a 12 year sentence for her part in the murders.
And although she will be eligible for early parole, parole board
officials are expected to be under pressure from the victim's
families and the public to keep her behind bars for her full sentence.

<HR>

<H3>Medical Spinal </H3>

<P>
A new report out this morning is providing some hope for those
suffering from paralysis. Many could one day walk again. As researchers
target regeneration and repair of spinal cord injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Twoonie Theft </H3>

<P>
Thieves in Montreal have made off with three-million dollars worth
of two-dollar coins. They stole a tractor-trailer filled with
boxes of the coins from a CN Railway yard last Saturday but Montreal
police delayed releasing details of the heist. 
<P>
The coins had just arrived in Montreal from the Royal Canadian
Mint in Winnipeg. CN Rail police say security was tight and they
have no idea how the thieves made off with the coins. 



<P>
