<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, July 25, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Ontario Quakes 
<LI>Baby Custody 
<LI>Grade 13 
<LI>Palladini - Agregates 
<LI>Flight Recorders 
<LI>Clinton Security 
<LI>Burundi Coup 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Ontario Quakes </H3>

<P>
We may have thought we were immune to natural disasters but new
evidence tonight shows otherwise. A group of scientists says southern
Ontario could be a prime candidate for a major earthquake. The
evidence comes after three research dives on the bottom of Lake
Ontario. 
<HR>

<H3>Baby Custody </H3>

<P>
A legal battle is brewing over custody of an eight-week old Ottawa-area
baby born with a pellet lodged in his brain. The baby was released
from hospital yesterday in good condition. He is under the care
of the Children's Aid Society. But his family has now decided
to seek custody of the infant at a hearing next Wednesday in Smiths
Falls. 
<P>
The baby's mother is accused of trying to kill her son with a
pellet gun on May 28th, two days before she gave birth. 28 year-old
Brenda Drummond is charged with attempted murder. 
<HR>

<H3>Grade 13 </H3>

<P>
Ontario's secondary school system will remain a five-year plan
a little while longer. Plans to get rid of grade 13 have been
pushed back from September 1997 to 1998. 
<P>
Education minister John Snobelen says more consultation is needed
before the four-year plan is phased in. Ontario is the only province
with grade 13. 
<HR>

<H3>Palladini - Aggregates</H3>

<P>
It was seven years ago that sand and gravel truckers staged a
noisy demonstration outside the Ontario legislature. The liberal
government bought their argument that they were being harassed
by transportation ministry officials over weight restrictions.
...and placed a moratorium on enforcement of the weight rules.
But the party's over, and aggregate truckers will now face tough
new rules. Dwight Ryan has the story. 
<P>
<I>Ontario transportation minister Al Palladini is heralding a
new partnership between Queen's Park and truckers hauling aggregates
that will help maintain our roads. Again sand and gravel truck
drivers will have to meet maximum weight limits with evenly distributed
loads. </I>
<P>
<I>A moratorium on enforcement has been in place since the truckers
circled Queens Park seven years ago. They convinced the former
liberal government that they were being treated unfairly. But
Palladini says our roads have been suffering now for too long.
</I>
<P>
<I>While the trucking industry is being praised for helping shape
the new rules, ministry officials are busy convincing drivers
that reduced loads and more paperwork are in their best interest...
Woodbridge trucker Bruno Bartucci says complying with the new
rules will be difficult. </I>
<P>
<I>A new enforcement unit armed with computerized equipment will
carefully monitor the haulers. But Palladini says his officials
will be patient. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Flight Recorders </H3>

<P>
In world news tonight, investigators are said to have found nothing
unusual on the flight and data recorders from TWA flight 800.

<P>
CNN reports, officials have listened, at least once, to the cockpit
voice recorder and have looked at the readout from the flight
data recorder. The absence of anything unusual on the recorders
could indicate an explosion aboard that knocked out the devices.
But investigators say a detailed examination of the recorders
is needed before any conclusions can be drawn. 
<HR>

<H3>Clinton Security </H3>

<P>
Airline security meanwhile, is getting tougher in the US. US president
Bill Clinton has announced that airlines will search more baggage
by hand. There will also be pre-flight inspections of every plane
flying to and from the United States. 
<HR>

<H3>Burundi Coup </H3>

<P>
Burundi's military has seized power in the central African country.
A military spokesman says the coalition government headed by an
ethnic Hutu has been overthrown. The newly installed president
is a member of the rival Tutsis. The two groups have waged a civil
war in recent years that has claimed more than 150-thousand lives.



<P>
