<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, July 24, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Boat Search 
<LI>Domestic Abuse 
<LI>M.P.'s - Cuba 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Boat Search </H3>

<P>
An extensive air and water search was called off late today for
a group of teenagers, who are believed to have stolen a row boat
last night, from a beach in east Toronto. 
<P>
Police say the search will not resume until there is more positive
evidence that they are still out on the lake. 
<HR>

<H3>Domestic Abuse </H3>

<P>
Toronto's crown prosecutors want to establish a separate courtroom
to deal with what they call the ``epidemic'' of people accused
of battering their partners. In a memo obtained by the Toronto
star, the prosecutors urge their boss to push for a pilot project
that would see significant changes to the way domestic assault
cases are tried. Those changes include the separate courtroom
along with special training for both police and crown attorneys
so they could better prosecute the alleged assailants. 
<P>
If approved by Toronto's top judges, the court would begin trying
cases in September. The pilot project would then be reviewed after
one year. 
<HR>

<H3>MPs - Cuba </H3>

<P>
If the Helms-Burton Law is an excellent piece of international
legislation, then so is the Godfrey-Milliken law. So say two liberal
members of parliament who plan to introduce a private members
bill that parallels the U.S. anti-Cuba legislation. 
<P>
But as Dwight Ryan reports, the two government members made their
announcement with their tongues planted firmly in their cheeks.

<P>
<I>U.S. president Clinton fired the first volley when he signed
into law the Helms-Burton Act. Companies doing business with Cuba
could be punished by the U.S. executives of those companies and
their families could be banned from visiting America. </I>
<P>
<I>Now Canada's fighting back. At least two liberal MP's are.
John Godfrey, and Peter Milliken, both descendants of United Empire
Loyalists, are about to introduce a private members bill that
parallels the Helms-Burton Act. The renegade MP's say restitution
would be in the billions. Each claims ownership of a property
in the U.S. and they want them back. </I>
<P>
<I>The government members say if the Helms-Burton law is a great
piece of international legislation, then so is the Godfrey-Burton
law. Author- historian Christopher Moore helped draft the Godfrey
Burton law. They'll introduce their bill in September. </I>
<P>
Indiana republican Dan Burton, a co-author of the Helms-Burton
law, said the Canadian MP's plan isn't worth responding to. Senator
Jesse Helms refused to comment. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

