<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, July 23, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Economy - Interest 
<LI>Wallaceburg Hostage 
<LI>Oshawa Rape 
<LI>Day Care Woes 
<LI>Ottawa - Wildlife 
<LI>Licence Plates 
<LI>Olympics 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Economy - Interest </H3>

<P>
We're on the road to recovery. Canada's economy is set for a turnaround.
We've heard it all before, but federal government figures once
again show that our limp economy could pick up the pace in the
coming months. 
<P>
For the ninth month in a row, the federal government's economic
barometer.. the composite leading index.. has risen. And interest
rates are falling as the feds try to get us to spend our money.
As Dwight Ryan reports, the plan appears to be working. 
<P>
<I>Mark Debruyn-Smith is having a great year. The Hamilton real
estate agent has sold more houses so far this year than any other
year. He says buyers, particularly first time buyers have waited
long enough. Housing sales throughout southern Ontario are on
the increase. New housing starts are beginning to recover from
their lowest point in 35 years. </I>
<P>
<I>Despite double-digit unemployment, consumer confidence is increasing.
The Bank of Canada's plan to spur the economy with lower rates
appears to be working. At 4.75 percent, the central rate is now
at its lowest point in two and a half years. Chartered banks have
lowered their prime by another quarter point and mortgage rates
are falling. </I>
<P>
<I>Economists feel the low interest rate policy will soon pay
off. Its a view shared by Warren Jestin, chief economist of Scotiabank.
</I>
<P>
<I>In the meantime, the retail sector waits for recovery. So does
the auto industry where sales continue to lag. Mark Debruyn- Smith,
meanwhile, hopes the resale housing boom he's experiencing will
continue. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Wallaceburg Hostage </H3>

<P>
Police have seized two air rifles from a house in Wallaceburg
where a little girl was held hostage. The six year old girl, was
held against her will for several hours yesterday morning, before
being released around 8:30 a-m. A man was arrested around noon.

<P>
29 year-old Alan Chauvin of Wallaceburg is charged with 12 offenses,
including forcible confinement and assault with a weapon. 
<HR>

<H3>Oshawa Rape</H3>

<P>
A man from Oshawa showed little emotion today as he appeared in
court on charges in the rape and beating of a 14-year-old girl.
The girl was sexually assaulted, severely beaten and left along
railway tracks on July 14th. 
<P>
20 year-old Michael Kobylanski is charged with aggravated sexual
assault and aggravated assault. Kobylanski was remanded in custody
until his next court appearance July 30th. 
<HR>

<H3>Day Care Woes </H3>

<P>
A survey by child care advocates, warns that thousands of day
care spaces in Ontario have disappeared, since the Harris government
came to power. And according to the survey, the reason for the
decline in spaces is cuts in transfer payments to municipalities.
<HR>

<H3>Ottawa - Wildlife </H3>

<P>
The World Wildlife Fund is going to court to try to slow down
the development of a diamond mine in the northwest territories.
The conservationists want a federal judge to review plans for
the mine. They say a federal environmental panel that approved
the plan, failed to look at all the issues. 
<P>
Fund spokesman Kevin MacNamee says the federal panel should have
made sure that arctic wilderness areas would be protected. 
<HR>

<H3>Licence Plates </H3>

<P>
Ontario car owners can now get five new types of licence plates
to show the world where their loyalties lie. The new plates sport
logos of Ontario's pro-sport teams such as the Toronto Blue Jays,
the Maple Leafs and the Hamilton Tigercats... Scouts Canada, the
Ontario Lacrosse Association, and Sir Wilfrid Laurier University.

<P>
Graphic plates cost 50-dollars over and above the regular plate
price, with personalized plates going for 175 dollars. Two dollars
from the sale of each plate will go to the organization whose
logo is featured. 
<HR>

<H3>Olympics </H3>

<P>
As we mentioned earlier, the latest numbers from Statistics Canada
suggest Canada's economy is continuing to improve. Well, in Atlanta,
merchants had predicted a boom in their economy, thanks to the
summer Olympics. However, the much anticipated economic boost
has gone bust. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

