<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, July 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Que. Flood 
<LI>Welland Re: Flood 
<LI>Drummond 
<LI>Brighton Crash 
<LI>Holiday Liquor 
<LI>Pakistan Air Bomb 
<LI>TWA Update 
<LI>O'Hare Bomb 
<LI>Olympic Transit 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Que. Flood </H3>

<P>
Residents of the flood-stricken Saguenay region of Quebec are
trying to put their lives back in order. At least eight people
were killed in flash floods over the weekend. 
<P>
Major Pierre Bettez of CFB Bagotville says it's hoped the worst
is over. Bettez says they're now working on reuniting people who
got separated during the evacuation operation. 
<P>
Damage from the flooding is estimated in the millions of dollars.

<HR>

<H3>Welland Re: Flood </H3>

<P>
Seven people are dead. Seven thousand were evacuated as a result
of the flash floods that ravaged the Saguenay region of Quebec
this weekend. While relief flood relief efforts in Ontario are
still being organized, Francophone communities in the province
are watching the graphic pictures of the devastation with anxiety.
<HR>

<H3>Drummond </H3>

<P>
The case of an Ottawa-area woman accused of trying to kill her
unborn son with a pellet gun, returns to court September 16th.

<P>
In court today, the lawyer for Brenda Drummond argued the case
should be dismissed because a fetus is not a human being. Lawrence
Greenspon added Drummond is being treated for depression in hospital.

<P>
Drummond's baby Johnathon was born May 30th with a lead pellet
lodged in his brain. He's in stable condition in hospital after
having the pellet removed. 
<HR>

<H3>Brighton Crash </H3>

<P>
The Transportation Safety Board today issued a report on the November
1994 Via Rail train derailment near Brighton. It says rail passengers
in Canada have been exposed unnecessarily to risks, particularly
in emergency situations. It notes passengers in the Brighton derailment
had to flee the train &quot;under life-threatening conditions.&quot;
It also says the rail, laid across the track by vandals, which
caused the derailment, wouldn't have been there if work crews
hadn't left it behind. 
<P>
The board is calling on Transport Canada to design federal standards
for emergency operations. 
<HR>

<H3>Holiday-Liquor </H3>

<P>
It'll be a lot easier to buy beer, wine or liquor on the August
fifth civic holiday. Three times the number of beer and liquor
stores will be open on the holiday Monday than last year. 
<HR>

<H3>Pakistan Air Bomb </H3>

<P>
In world news tonight, police say the death toll has risen to
nine, in a bombing at the international airport in Lahore, Pakistan.
A report says the bomb exploded near a lounge at the airport.
The bomb blew up as Pakistan International Airlines flight 315
was leaving for the southern port city of Karachi. Police say
it may have been intended for that plane. 
<HR>

<H3>TWA Update </H3>

<P>
New York's governor says the searchers off the coast of Long Island
have made a significant find. He says they've found a large piece
of the wreckage of TWA flight 800. 
<P>
George Pataki also says the bodies of additional victims of the
air disaster have been found. His comments came at the end of
a memorial service on the Long Island shore near the site of the
crash. 
<HR>

<H3>O'Hare Bomb </H3>

<P>
Chicago authorities are investigating a security breach at O'Hare
International Airport. Someone managed to place a small, explosive
device right out on the tarmac last night.  Some anonymous phone
calls had airport officials and passengers on edge. 
<HR>

<H3>Olympic Transit </H3>

<P>
Running smoothly is an Olympic dream for a supervisor with the
Hamilton Street Railway. 34 year old Jim Dahms has spent nearly
a year helping to design the transit system in Atlanta for the
96 summer games. 
<P>
It's been his responsibility to set up schedules for the 3-thousand
drivers who'll be carting visitors to their Olympic destination.
But despite all the planning and scheduling, transit in Atlanta
has hit a snag. 



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

