<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, July 18, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>TWA 
<LI>Doc-Patient Roster 
<LI>Murray Tapes 
<LI>Bureaucracy War 
<LI>Kennedy 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>TWA </H3>

<P>
A major U.S. network says investigators are looking at the possibility
a small missile might have blasted TWA flight 800 from the air.
The report is from ABC News. 
<P>
The network says two things suggest the possibility of a missile,
reports from eye-witnesses who described something looking like
a flare heading towards the plane before it exploded, and word
that a major Arabic newspaper received a warning of an attack
on an American target about the time the Boeing 7-47 exploded
into a fireball off Long Island last night, shortly after takeoff.

<HR>

<H3>Doc-Patient Roster </H3>

<P>
Ontario could be on the threshold of a new form of health care,
where patients may have to sign contracts with a family doctor,
in exchange for better medical service. 
<P>
One of the by-products of such a system would be the virtual elimination
of doctor shopping&quot; by patients. 
<HR>

<H3>Murray Tapes </H3>

<P>
It will be a few more months before provincial police wind up
their investigation into lawyer Ken Murray's handling of the Paul
Bernardo videotapes. 
<P>
OPP detective superintendent Wayne Frechette says once the probe
is completed this fall, a report will be handed to the attorney-general
who will determine if charges will be laid. 
<P>
Investigators are trying to determine if Murray, who was Bernardo's
lawyer, withheld evidence by not turning over the crucial tapes
for 15 months. The tapes played a key role in Bernardo's conviction
in two sex-killings. 
<P>
Murray denies any wrongdoing and says he is being made a scapegoat
for police mistakes. 
<HR>

<H3>Bureaucracy War </H3>

<P>
The Harris government has embarked on a plan, which it hopes will
limit the maze of government regulations that business has to
wade through, in order to operate. 
<P>
A set of guidelines approved by cabinet, would require bureaucrats
proposing new regulations, to fill out an eight page form. The
form asks whether alternatives were fully explored, whether cost-benefits
were analyzed and whether interested parties had been consulted.

<P>
The new system which goes into effect Monday, would make it harder
for regulation-happy bureaucrats to get their raft of red tape
approved by cabinet. 
<HR>

<H3>Kennedy </H3>

<P>
The race to succeed Ontario Liberal leader Lyn McLeod is in full
swing with the entry this week of Gerrard Kennedy. Kennedy, a
former food bank director, officially launched his leadership
bid Tuesday. 
<P>
He and caucus colleague Dwight Duncan from Windsor, are considered
front-runners in the race to replace Lyn McLeod. 
<P>
The party's leadership convention will be held November 30th in
Toronto. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

