<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, July 16, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Great Lakes Quality 
<LI>Cuba Decision 
<LI>Netanyahu Woes 
<LI>JAMA Drug Testing 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Great Lakes Quality </H3>

<P>
A warning tonight on the effort to clean up the great lakes. An
environment report states that government cut-backs, could seriously
affect the research and clean up of the international waterway.

<HR>

<H3>Cuba Decision </H3>

<P>
Canadian companies that do business in Cuba have escaped the immediate
threat of lawsuits from Americans disenfranchised during the Cuban
revolution nearly forty years ago. 
<P>
Today, U.S. president Bill Clinton agreed to let the lawsuit provisions
of the Helms-Burton act become law. But at the same time, he imposed
a six-month moratorium on the ability of Americans to actually
file lawsuits in U.S. courts. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>At stake is the fate of nearly six-thousand American-owned
properties seized by the Cuban government in the wake of the 1959
revolution. More than a hundred foreign companies, including Canadian
ones, are believed to be using these properties for profit. </I>
<P>
<I>In March, the United States approved the controversial Helms-Burton
law, in an effort to tighten economic sanctions on the Fidel Castro
government. That law has already allowed the U.S. to deny visas
to shareholders and top executives of foreign companies that do
business in Cuba, like Canada's Sherritt International Corporation.
</I>
<P>
<I>Another provision of the Helms-Burton law, approved by president
Clinton today, gives Americans the right to sue foreign companies
that operate on lands forfeited by U.S. citizens during the Cuban
revolution. By passing the lawsuit provision, Clinton appeases
Cuban-American voters as he heads towards November's presidential
election. </I>
<P>
<I>By imposing a six-month delay on the ability to file lawsuits,
Clinton appeases U.S. trading partners who have threatened to
take their own retaliatory actions against the states.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Netanyahu Woes </H3>

<P>
Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to office on a
campaign of hard-line security pledges ....but Netanyahu the candidate..
and Netanyahu the leader, face vastly different challenges.. and
when it comes to relations with Arab leaders, the prime minister
is having to consider the big picture as well as local concerns.

<HR>

<H3>JAMA Drug Testing </H3>

<P>
From Ben Johnson to silken Laumann, Canada has had it's share
of controversy over doping at the Olympics... Dr. Robert Kaufmann
looks at how medical science is trying to stay one step ahead
of the athletes in the race for clean and fair competition. 



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

