<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, July 15, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Indy Update 
<LI>Dutch Hercules 
<LI>UK Air Show 
<LI>Oshawa Rape 
<LI>Drug User Fees 
<LI>Breast Feeding 
<LI>N.I. Calm 
<LI>Royal Divorce 
<LI>Sultan B-day 
<LI>Ballroom Win 
<LI>Internet Taxes 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Indy Update </H3>

<P>
An inquest may be held into the fatal crash at the Indy car race
in Toronto. Dr. Robert Huxter, says it could take six weeks to
conclude the investigation into yesterday's crash. At that time,
he'll determine whether an inquest is warranted. 
<P>
Thousands were horrified when a car driven by rookie driver Jeff
Krosnoff, sailed into the air and crumbled as it smashed into
the chain link fencing along the back straight-away. The 31-year-old
driver and a volunteer race marshal, 44-year-old Gary Avrin of
Calgary, were both instantly killed. 
<HR>

<H3>Dutch Hercules </H3>

<P>
A Hercules cargo plane belonging to the Belgian military, crashed
today at Eindhoven Air Force base in Holland. Military authorities
confirm 26 people died in the crash. Dozens were hurt. 
<P>
Dutch television reports, say the four-engine turbo-prop carried
four crew members and 50 Dutch military musicians, on a flight
from Italy. Eindhoven is located about 200 kilometres south of
Amsterdam.
<HR>

<H3>U.K. Air Show </H3>

<P>
Yet another disaster at a vintage aircraft exhibition. A second
world war fighter plane crashed and exploded at a British air
show yesterday, killing the pilot. 
<P>
Thousands of spectators watched in horror as the &quot;Lockheed
P-38 Lightning&quot; lost control. Witnesses say the plane flew
low across the runway and either touched the ground or another
plane, cartwheeling across the runway and bursting into flames.

<HR>

<H3>Oshawa Rape </H3>

<P>
A 14-year-old Oshawa girl is expected to survive a vicious weekend
attack, but police say it will be some time before they can talk
to her. The girl is in critical condition after she was beaten,
sexually assaulted and abandoned beside railway tracks. 
<P>
The girl was reported missing about 3 a-m yesterday by her parents,
and found 12 hours later by a boy taking a short cut through the
area. So far no arrests have been made. 
<HR>

<H3>Drug User Fees </H3>

<P>
Seniors groups say the province is forcing them to choose between
drugs, food or paying the rent. That's their reaction to new fees
that started today. 
<P>
Low income seniors and people collecting welfare now have to pay
a two-dollar fee for each prescription. Seniors with higher incomes
will also have to pay a 100-dollar deductible, plus dispensing
fee. 
<P>
Many pharmacies say they'll absorb the new fees. 
<HR>

<H3>Breast Feeding </H3>

<P>
And, surprising statistics from a study published in the Canadian
Medical Association Journal. Half of all 523 hospitals surveyed
indicate an alliance between medical centers and manufacturers
of baby formula. As Alex Reynolds reports, advocates of breast
feeding are alarmed. 
<P>
<I>An instinctive function... breast feeding raises eyebrows,
in public places, as well as the question of natural versus manufactured
nourishment. The Medical Journal Study indicates commercial interests
are being served in maternity wards. </I>
<P>
<I>Of 523 hospitals surveyed, half routinely gave newborns commercial
formula. This tends to lead nursing mothers to believe the hospital
supports the principle of formula feed, thereby interfering with
normal breast feeding practices. </I>
<P>
<I>The natural method is supported by McMaster Medical Centre,
as well as Hamilton Civic Hospitals. We were unable to contact
officials at St. Joseph's hospital.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>N.I. Calm </H3>

<P>
In Northern Ireland, there are appeals for calm...after weeks
of escalating violence... capped by a huge bombing this weekend
at a luxury hotel. 
<HR>

<H3>Royal Divorce </H3>

<P>
The prince and princess of Wales have begun divorce proceedings.
A judge has granted them the first stage of a divorce that will
become final August 28th. 
<P>
Neither Charles nor Diana attended the three-minute hearing, in
a drab London courtroom. 
<HR>

<H3>Sultan B-day </H3>

<P>
Prince Charles was however on hand to celebrate the 50th birthday
of the man considered to be the richest person in the world. 
<P>
The Sultan of Brunei marked his birthday in grand style with a
military style parade followed by a private concert given by Michael
Jackson. The million dollar bash is expected to last 15 days.
<HR>

<H3>Ballroom Win </H3>

<P>
First they were the tops in Canada, now in North America. Beverley
Cayton-Tang seen here in the pink skirt, and Robert Tang have
won the North American amateur standards competition in ballroom
dance. They danced their way to the top this weekend in Philadelphia.

<P>
We profiled the Tangs two weeks ago while they were practicing
for the upcoming competition. In a field that's been dominated
in Canada at least by French couples, Beverley and Robert are
the first Ontario couple in 24 years, to become number one in
North America. 
<HR>

<H3>Internet Taxes </H3>

<P>
Technology is supposed to make life easier. But in some cases
...it complicates things. Take the Internet for example. companies
say selling products in cyberspace is very confusing. As they
spend money trying to figure it all out ...consumers end up paying
the bill. 



<P>
