<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, July 11, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Bernardo-Police 
<LI>French Promo 
<LI>Tennessee Tourist 
<LI>Cabinet 
<LI>Sherritt 
<LI>Autism-Dolphins 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo-Police </H3>

<P>
The judge probing the Paul Bernardo murder investigation has issued
a scathing indictment of what he termed, police &quot;bungling,
and gross incompetence&quot;. 
<P>
In the report, Justice Archie Campbell says that if the investigation
had been done right, Kristin French and Leslie Mahaffy probably
would be alive today. 
<HR>

<H3>French Promo </H3>

<P>
And tonight on Final Edition, reporter Lauran Sabourin will bring
us an exclusive interview with Donna French, she is the mother
of one of Paul Bernardo's victims... Kristen French. 
<HR>

<H3>Tennessee Tourist </H3>

<P>
In other news tonight, police in Tennessee are investigating the
apparent murder of yet another Canadian tourist. The body of a
31-year-old Vancouver man, was found at a construction site just
east of Knoxville. No name has been released, but police say it
appears the man was beaten to death. 
<HR>

<H3>Cabinet </H3>

<P>
Tensions between Canada and the United States continue to rise
over the controversial Helms-Burton bill. Yesterday, Washington
moved to bar top executives at Sherritt International from entering
the U.S. The Canadian company, which runs a nickel mine with the
Cuban government, is being penalized for doing business with Fidel
Castro. And although the Canadian government is discussing possible
retaliatory measures, not everyone believes the American threat
is real.
<HR>

<H3>Sherritt </H3>

<P>
Officials at Toronto based mining company Sherritt International
meanwhile, say the company has no intention of leaving Cuba. Instead,
officials say they plan to continue to take advantage of the new
investment climate in Cuba. 
<HR>

<H3>Bertha </H3>

<P>
A group of Wiarton-area soccer players are among those affected
by an evacuation order for the coast of South Carolina. The state
governor issued the order because of approaching hurricane &quot;Bertha.&quot;

<P>
The Wiarton girls team is in Myrtle Beach for a combination soccer
camp-tournament. &quot;Bertha&quot; is aiming toward Cape Fear,
North Carolina, and could hit land tomorrow. 
<HR>

<H3>Autism-Dolphins </H3>

<P>
A Burlington family has turned to a Niagara Falls waterpark to
help their autistic son. After learning that dolphins can sometimes
encourage autistic children to communicate, they requested a special
private visit to Marineland. Annette Hamm and cameraman Larry
Fay went along. 
<P>
<I>While most kids are thrilled by a show like this for some it's
just too much to take in. Especially for kids like Justin Learn
of Burlington. The ten year old is autistic. </I>
<P>
<I>When Justin got a pass to Marineland from his ball team, his
mom asked for a private audience with the dolphins. She'd heard
about studies being done in Florida using dolphins to help autistic
kids communicate. While he didn't speak, Justin did respond well
during his dolphin encounter. </I>
<P>
<I>Marineland officials get requests for private audiences with
the dolphins every day. They stress this was a special wish granted
to Justin on his birthday, and they can't handle other requests.</I>



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

