<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, July 10, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Visas Denied 
<LI>Florida Boycott 
<LI>Car Pollution 
<LI>Ont. Licence Plates 
<LI>Cocaine Boy 
<LI>Bernardo Report
<LI>Self Employed 
<LI>O.A.C.
<LI>Strawberry Aftermath 
<LI>Kevorkian 
<LI>Northern Ireland 
<LI>Belfast Violence 
<LI>Bertha 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Visas Denied </H3>

<P>
Washington has decided to bar the top shareholders and officers
of a Canadian firm from entering the United States. The step is
being taken under the &quot;Helms-Burton Act&quot; that punishes
non-American firms which do business with Cuba. 
<P>
Sources in the American capital say the Canadian firm is Sherritt
International, which mines nickel and cobalt in eastern Cuba.
It's head office is based in Toronto. The entry ban is to take
effect in six weeks. 
<HR>

<H3>Florida Boycott </H3>

<P>
Oxfam - Canada meanwhile, is leading a coalition of churches and
aid groups in seeking a boycott of Florida to protest the US laws
against Cuba. 
<P>
The coalition says the legislation is hindering efforts to provide
aid in the Caribbean country. 
<HR>

<H3>Car Pollution </H3>

<P>
Ontario motorists could soon be facing another fee when they go
to renew their licence stickers. Ontario is working on a program
of mandatory pollution tests for cars and trucks. 
<P>
Management Board chair Dave Johnson, says nothing has been finalized,
but the testing might start on cars anywhere from two to five
years old. 
<HR>

<H3>Ont. Licence Plates </H3>

<P>
Ontario licence plates will soon look a little bit different.
Another character is being added to the plates, because the province
is running out of licence plate combinations. 
<P>
New seven-character plates will be introduced in December. Personalized
plates will soon be available with up to eight-characters. 
<P>
Transportation ministry officials say the new plate combinations
should last at least 100 years before they'll have to add even
more characters.
<HR>

<H3>Cocaine Boy </H3>

<P>
A four-year-old Toronto boy has been handed over to Children's
Aid officials, after his mother was accused of feeding him crack
cocaine and prescription drugs. 
<P>
A doctor discovered in late May, that the boy had been given cocaine
and prescription drugs. The 28-year-old mother faces four charges
including criminal negligence causing bodily harm. 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Report </H3>

<P>
The long awaited Campbell Report will be released tomorrow. That's
the government's report into the handling of the Paul Bernardo
murder investigation. We will have extensive coverage of the details
of that report on our newscasts throughout the day beginning at
noon. 
<HR>

<H3>Self Employed </H3>

<P>
More Canadians than ever, are turning to self-employment as a
way to make a living. Federal figures show that in 1994, 2.2-million
Canadians earned at least some money, by creating their own job.
That's an increase of nearly six per cent over the previous year
-- and the largest increase since 1987. 
<P>
The biggest hike came in Oshawa, where the number of self-employed
people jumped by 10.5 per cent. 
<HR>

<H3>O.A.C. </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Arts Council has released a study showing arts groups
generate more tax revenue for the province, than they get in funding.
The Informetrica study found that in 1994-95, 850 non-profit arts
groups raised 50-million dollars in Ontario tax revenues -- topping
the 42-million dollars in funding they received from the province.

<P>
The groups were also responsible for almost seven-thousand jobs
in the province. 
<HR>

<H3>Strawberry Aftermath </H3>

<P>
Niagara's strawberry season is winding down. 1996 has been a banner
year for growers in the peninsula.... thanks to the berry scare
south of the border. Lauran Sabourin has the story. 
<P>
<I>As far as many consumers are concerned this year California
berries aren't much better than poison. Fears of parasitic contamination.
Contamination with the parasite cyclospora that made more than
one thousand people sick. </I>
<P>
<I>Fruit Haven farms in Niagara on the Lake has been doing a booming
berry business this year. A pick your own operation that draws
berry eaters from all over. Strawberries, raspberries. People
aren't afraid to eat the home grown product. </I>
<P>
<I>At the local markets around Niagara strawberries are selling
briskly. Selling so quickly shelves are nearly empty. </I>
<P>
<I>Berry season in Niagara is extremely short. A couple of weeks
and you've missed it. For consumers here who wait months for the
opportunity to get out in the fields and pick, it'll take a lot
more than a parasite scare south of the border to turn their noses
up at the home grown harvest.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Kevorkian </H3>

<P>
Dr. Jack Kevorkian has dropped off another body at a Detroit-area
hospital. The death of Rebecca Badger of California, is the 33rd
assisted suicide Kevorkian is known to have attended since 1990
-- and the fifth since his third acquittal in May. 
<P>
Kevorkian's lawyer says the 39 year old woman -- who suffered
from multiple sclerosis -- had been meeting with Kevorkian for
months. 
<HR>

<H3>Northern Ireland </H3>

<P>
The British government is preparing to send a large force of troops
back into northern Ireland. For three days, police and Protestants
have fought over rights to celebrate an ancient victory on the
battlefield. That 300-year-old battle threatens to claim a new
casualty...the peace process in northern Ireland. 
<HR>

<H3>Belfast Violence </H3>

<P>
Britain is sending another one-thousand troops to northern Ireland
to quell the worst street violence in a decade. The trouble broke
out, when police halted a Protestant march through a catholic
enclave. 
<P>
Angered by police efforts to prevent the march, gangs of Protestant
youths attacked officers with gasoline bombs and rocks, set fire
to vehicles and blocked streets with burning barricades last night
and early today. 
<HR>

<H3>Bertha </H3>

<P>
The evacuations are under way in the American southeast ahead
of hurricane &quot;Bertha.&quot; Florida has ordered 500-thousand
people out of the way of the storm now churning northwest across
the Bahamas. Up to 50-thousand people are under evacuation orders
on North Carolina's outer banks. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

