<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 07/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, July 9, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Smoking Wars 
<LI>Waterloo - Smoking 
<LI>Middleton Funeral 
<LI>Attack Update 
<LI>Net - Clinton 
<LI>Mandela - London 
<LI>Bertha 
<LI>S.A. Snow 
<LI>Volcano Update 
<LI>Obese Man 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Smoking Wars </H3>

<P>
It looks like a battle is shaping up between the cities of Toronto
and North York over who can attract the most smokers. It has all
come about because of Toronto's complete ban on smoking in bars
and restaurants. 
<HR>

<H3>Waterloo-Smoking </H3>

<P>
In Waterloo meanwhile, a bylaw to clear the smoke from the region's
bars and restaurants was given an unexpected boost last night.
Waterloo city council reversed an earlier decision and approved
the region's controversial smoking bylaw. 
<P>
Under the new law, all food courts and malls would become entirely
smoke free immediately. 
<HR>

<H3>Middleton Funeral </H3>

<P>
For the second time this year, residents of Belleville have said
goodbye to a teen killed while on vacation out of the country.
A line of family, friends and strangers stretched for a block
outside the Bridge Street United Church prior to an emotional
funeral service for 17-year-old Rebecca Middleton. 
<P>
The grade 11 student was brutally raped and murdered last week
while visiting a friend in Bermuda. 
<P>
Last march, 18-year-old mark Fyke was shot to death in Florida.

<HR>

<H3>Attack Update </H3>

<P>
British police are still on the hunt for a man, who went on the
rampage at a school yard near London yesterday. 
<P>
Monday's machete attack in Wolverhampton followed an argument
between a man and woman outside the school ground. the man hopped
the brick wall and starting attacking the school group. Seven
people were injured, including three young children. Police believe
the man is hiding out in an apartment overlooking the school.

<HR>

<H3>Net - Clinton </H3>

<P>
Israel's new leader has won a strong statement of support from
US president Bill Clinton. 
<P>
In their first official meeting since Benjamin Netanyahu became
prime minister, president Bill Clinton today declared America's
commitment to Israeli security. Netanyahu said Israel is eager
to make peace, but only if all parties fight terrorism and keep
their promises. Clinton agreed, saying Israel must feel secure
as it makes peace with Arab neighbors. 
<HR>

<H3>Mandela - London </H3>

<P>
Thousands of flag-waving children gave nelson Mandela a hero's
welcome in Britain today. The crowd cheered and chanted the South
African president's name, as he inspected royal guards in a ceremony
attended by the Queen and prime minister John Major. 
<P>
Mandela says he wants to thank the people of Britain for their
support during the long years of apartheid. He and his daughter
Zenani will spend four days in London as a guest of queen Elizabeth
at Buckingham palace. 
<HR>

<H3>Bertha </H3>

<P>
The howling winds of hurricane &quot;Bertha&quot; are getting
closer to the Bahamas. Forecasters say Bertha will likely spare
Florida but not Carolinas. 
<HR>

<H3>S.A. Snow </H3>

<P>
In South Africa, thousands of motorists were stranded and remote
villages left totally isolated, as the worst winter snowstorm
to hit the country in 50 years, entered it's third day. 
<P>
Three men have frozen to death in the mid-winter cold snap. police
say several people have suffered minor injuries following a rash
of car accidents due to poor road conditions. Up to two meters
of snow has fallen in some areas, that's the highest in 50 years.

<HR>

<H3>Volcano Update </H3>

<P>
And mother nature continues to flex her muscles elsewhere on the
globe. 
<P>
In New Zealand Mount Ruapehu volcano is spewing glowing rocks
bigger than cars. it's the volcano's biggest eruption in several
weeks. Authorities say there's no need to evacuate people living
nearby, but scientists are warning onlookers and thrill-seekers
not to get too close. 
<P>
Ruapehu burst into life last September and again last month, in
its most spectacular eruptions in half a century. 
<HR>

<H3>Obese Man </H3>

<P>
He was said to be one of the heaviest men in the world, weighing
nearly one thousand pounds. Michael Hebranko of Brooklyn, New
York, was removed from his home by forklift, to be hospitalized
two months ago for severe obesity and its side effects. Now, Michael
Hebranko .. has gone back home. 


<P>
