<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wedesday, June 26, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Morin Inquiry 
<LI>Bernardo Report 
<LI>Blinds 
<LI>Gerber Foods 
<LI>Bar Owners Mad 
<LI>Video Gambling 
<LI>Saudi Explosion 
<LI>Israel Attack 
<LI>Greece Funeral 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Morin Inquiry </H3>

<P>
The Harris government has finally launched a public inquiry into
the wrongful arrest and conviction of Guy Paul Morin. 
<P>
Eighteen months ago, Morin was cleared in the death of his nine
year old neighbor. 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Report </H3>

<P>
Solicitor general Bob Runciman says he's expecting &quot;significant
recommendations&quot; about policing in a report on the Paul Bernardo
investigation. Justice Archie Campbell, conducted the investigation,
into how police handled the Bernardo case and he'll give his report
to Runciman tomorrow. 
<P>
Bernardo is serving an indefinite sentence after being declared
a dangerous offender, following his conviction of first-degree
murder in the sex-slayings of teenagers Kristen French and Leslie
Mahaffy. Runciman says he expects Campbell will make recommendations
on how policing should operate in Ontario. 
<HR>

<H3>Blinds </H3>

<P>
Fears over lead in window-blinds is leaving health officials swamped
with calls from worried consumers. Health Canada has set up a
toll-free warning number to answer consumer concerns after it's
warning that some imported mini-blinds contain lead. If you want
more information on the danger of the blinds or where to dispose
of them call toll free 1-800-651-3131.
<HR>

<H3>Gerber Foods </H3>

<P>
One of the oldest baby food makers plans to add some healthier
choices to its menu. Gerber says it will offer more starch and
sugar-free foods within the next six months. 
<P>
With the change, 121 of Gerber's 190 products will be free of
starch and sugar. Gerber executives deny the move is related to
a consumer group's charge, the company deceived the public about
the nutritional value of some of its baby foods. 
<HR>

<H3>Bar Owners Mad </H3>

<P>
Restaurant and bar owners in Toronto are furious with the city's
Board of Health. They say a proposal, by the board, to make eateries
and drinking spots in Toronto virtually smoke free by next year,
will cost them millions of dollars in revenue. 
<P>
If the proposed bylaw is passed by city council next week, smokers
will be confined to small, sealed-off areas. Other municipalities
are expected to follow suit if the bylaw is passed. 
<HR>

<H3>Video Gambling </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Liberals used a new tact in their battle to stop the
Harris government from bringing video lottery terminals to Ontario.

<P>
Today, Liberal caucus members rolled out a VLT machine at Queens
Park. Between 20 and 40 thousand of these machines are to be installed
at race tracks and casinos later this year. The Liberals say these
machines, which they dubbed the crack cocaine of gambling, will
eventually be allowed in neighborhood bars and restaurants. 
<HR>

<H3>Saudi Explosion </H3>

<P>
Prime minister Chretien has offered his sympathies to the families
of the victims of the truck bombing in Saudi Arabia. Chretien
also condemned the bombing as the work of cowards. 
<P>
Yesterday's attack killed 19 Americans and wounded more than 300
others. US president Clinton has vowed to hunt down and punish
those responsible. And the Saudi government is offering a three
million-dollar reward for information leading to arrests. 
<HR>

<H3>Israel Attack </H3>

<P>
Three Israeli soldiers are dead following an ambush near the border
between the West Bank and Jordan. The Israeli army says the soldiers
were patrolling near a Jewish settlement. The attackers apparently
came across the border from Jordan. 
<HR>

<H3>Greece Funeral </H3>

<P>
Greece's political elite, foreign dignitaries and 100-thousand
followers, braved sweltering heat for the funeral of Andreas Papandreou,
the socialist leader who was elected prime minister three times.

<P>
Central Athens was packed with Greeks who had arrived from all
over the country to pay their last respects to Papandreou. He
was one of his country's most loved, influential and controversial
leaders this century. 
<P>
The 77-year-old Papandreou died of a heart attack Sunday. Although
he held no national office at the time, he was given a full state
funeral. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

