<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, June 25, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Health Blinds 
<LI>Sexual Assault
<LI>Rent Controls 
<LI>G-7 Departure 
<LI>Singapore 
<LI>Netanyahu 
<LI>Charles Ireland 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Health Blinds</H3>

<P>
One of North America's largest blind producers says virtually
every inexpensive plastic mini-blind in Canada likely contains
lead that could pose a health risk to children. 
<P>
A Royal Plastics official estimates 99 per cent of the mini-blinds
are made in China or Taiwan, where rules are lax on lead content.
Health Canada has issued a warning that PVC mini-blinds should
be removed from windows immediately. Lead poisoning can retard
motor skills and cause brain damage in children. 
<HR>

<H3>Sexual Assault</H3>

<P>
Even hardened Toronto police officers have been taken aback by
this investigation. A 15-year-old Toronto boy is to undergo a
psychiatric assessment after being charged with sexually assaulting
his mother. 
<P>
Police say the woman was taken to hospital and treated following
the assault almost two weeks ago. One detective said he had never
heard of a similar case in his 20 years on the job. 
<P>
The youth has been placed in the care of the Children's Aid Society.

<HR>

<H3>Rent Controls </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is proposing changes to the province's
rent control laws. Changes that are aimed at getting more rental
units on the market. But neither tenants or landlords are happy
with the changes.
<HR>

<H3>G-7 Departure </H3>

<P>
Prime Minister Chretien is on his way to Italy for a meeting with
that country's prime minister. Chretien will also have a private
audience with Pope John Paul on Thursday. Then, it's on to Lyon,
France for the group of seven meeting. 
<P>
The G-7 is made up of the world's top seven industrial nations
-- Canada, Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Italy and the US.
Last year, the G-7 meeting was held in Halifax. 
<HR>

<H3>Singapore </H3>

<P>
Prosecutors in Singapore are demanding that a Canadian, convicted
of possessing and consuming marijuana, be jailed for up to 40
years. 
<P>
43-year-old Ronald Wilson McCulloch of Toronto, escaped the gallows
this week when prosecutors reduced the charges from trafficking.
Reduced charges are rare in Singapore which has hanged more than
120 convicted drug traffickers, including westerners, in its relentless
drive against narcotics smuggling and drug abuse.
<HR>

<H3>Netanyahu </H3>

<P>
Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu says he's eager to resume
peace talks with the Palestinians and Israel's neighbors. 
<P>
He issued the statement as he and US Secretary of State Warren
Christopher held their first face-to-face meeting in Jerusalem.
Christopher failed to reach a hoped-for agreement with Netanyahu
to pull Israeli troops in the West Bank out of Arab areas of Hebron.

<HR>

<H3>Charles Ireland </H3>

<P>
Police were everywhere as Prince Charles began his first visit
to northern Ireland since the collapse of an IRA truce in February.
Police marksmen stood rooftop guard at Belfast docks, while officers
in rubber dinghies patrolled the waters. 
<P>
Charles arrived today on the royal yacht Britannia -- which is
shadowed by a warship -- for a three-day visit. Charles has been
the target of anti-British protests during previous visits. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

