<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, June 24, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Peterborough Protest 
<LI>Hampton-House 
<LI>Quebec Riot 
<LI>Dallaire Court 
<LI>Arab Summit 
<LI>Hurricane Alma 
<LI>Shuttle Activity 
<LI>Paula Jones 
<LI>Hillary Book 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Peterborough Protest </H3>

<P>
Several thousand people rallied in Peterborough, Ontario today
in the labor movement's fourth major protest against the provincial
government. 
<P>
Speakers accused the Tory government of destroying the fabric
of society while benefiting the rich. Many government services
and some businesses were also shut down by pickets. 
<P>
Union members are protesting cuts to jobs and social services,
as well as new labor legislation. 
<HR>

<H3>Hampton-House </H3>

<P>
Newly elected NDP leader Howard Hampton took his seat in the legislature
today, amid accolades from all sides of the house. But that didn't
deter the NDP leader from launching a wholesale attack on the
government.
<HR>

<H3>Quebec Riot </H3>

<P>
Police admit they were caught off guard when rioters started pelting
the National Assembly with bottles and rocks during a riot in
Quebec City. 
<P>
Windows were smashed and businesses in the city's old quarter
were looted in violence that began after a rock concert that was
part of Quebec's Fete Nationale celebrations. The early morning
riot spread to the National Assembly where damage is estimated
at 200-thousand dollars. 
<P>
Premier Lucien Bouchard says he's &quot;very dismayed&quot; by
the damage done to the legislature. But he rejects any suggestion
that there was a message for politicians in the attack. 
<HR>

<H3>Dallaire Court </H3>

<P>
Police say the man accused of breaking into 24 Sussex Drive last
fall told them he would have tried to kill the prime minister
had he come face to face with him. Andr&eacute; Dallaire's statement
was included in the charges read in an Ottawa courtroom today.

<P>
The 34-year-old Dallaire pleaded not guilty to attempted murder,
break and enter, being unlawfully in a dwelling and possession
of a weapon. 
<HR>

<H3>Arab Summit </H3>

<P>
Arab nations and Israel are still adjusting to new Mideast realities,
following the election of the new hard-line Israeli government.

<P>
The 21-nation Arab Summit concluded in Cairo yesterday. Delegates
left generally supporting the land-for-peace principal that has
helped advance the Mideast peace process. The big question is:
will new prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu continue offering Israeli
land?
<HR>

<H3>Hurricane Alma </H3>

<P>
The season's first pacific hurricane pounded Mexico's southern
coast with four-metre waves today. Hurricane &quot;alma&quot;
has killed at least three people, collapsed shanties and downed
trees and power lines. 
<P>
Hundreds of people were evacuated to emergency shelters as &quot;alma&quot;
lashed the pacific coast. News of the damage has trickled in slowly.
Telephone contact is cut with parts of the area and road travel
is extremely difficult. 
<HR>

<H3>Shuttle Activity </H3>

<P>
The crew of Space Shuttle Columbia, which includes Canadian astronaut
Dr. Bob Thirsk, got a wake up call today from David Bowie's &quot;space
oddity.&quot; 
<P>
More workouts are on tap today, as Columbia astronauts study the
effects of weightlessness. One crew member says the exercises
are actually more comfortable in space. But NASA expects the sessions
to become more difficult, as the crew gets weaker from prolonged
weightlessness. 
<HR>

<H3>Paula Jones </H3>

<P>
Paula Jones' sexual harassment suit against U.S. president Clinton
is on hold until after November's presidential election. 
<P>
The American Supreme Court today agreed to decide whether Jones'
lawsuit should be delayed while Clinton remains in office. The
court likely will hear arguments this fall -- with a decision
not likely until 1997. 
<HR>

<H3>Hillary Book</H3>

<P>
President Clinton's wife, meanwhile, is also in the news tonight....
a new book by Watergate reporter Bob Woodward, tells of conversations
the first lady allegedly had with long departed personalities.


<P>
