<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, June 21, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>1st Min. 
<LI>NDP-Evng. 
<LI>Teen Swarming 
<LI>Weeping Workers 
<LI>Bourassa Cancer 
<LI>Cancer Rate 
<LI>Kevorkian 31st
<LI>Unabomber Wrap 
<LI>Diana 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>1st Min. </H3>

<P>
Canada's first ministers are tip toeing through a constitutional
minefield in Ottawa today. 
<P>
The morning session was devoted to renewal of the Canadian federation
and, specifically, the requirement that the amending formula be
discussed by 1997. It's a session in which Quebec premier Lucien
Bouchard won't be participating. 
<HR>

<H3>NDP-Evng. </H3>

<P>
Ontario's New Democrats have vowed to never again introduce legislation
that would destroy collective agreements. Meeting in Hamilton,
NDP delegates are fully cognizant of the fact that the social
contract led to their downfall. 
<P>
<I>The convention lacks spark. The nearly 2000 delegates from
across Ontario are painfully aware of the fact that the last time
they met here in Hamilton they were in government. And so a major
part of this weekend event is to rebuild the party...to put it
in a position where it can again form the government. To that
end, a lot of Tory bashing can be heard. </I>
<P>
<I>Organized labour is still trying to come to terms with the
previous NDP government's social contract legislation. Collective
agreements were summarily ripped up and unions felt betrayed.
That issue came to a head this afternoon.. </I>
<P>
<I>But delegates eventually overwhelmingly approved a resolution
promising never to again introduce legislation that would destroy
collective agreements. </I>
<P>
<I>Federal NDP leader Alexa Mcdonough says the winds of change
are blowing in the new democrats' direction. She told a subdued
audience that election victories in British Columbia and Nova
Scotia are just the beginning. </I>
<P>
<I>When the convention wraps up tomorrow, there will be a new
party leader. Former cabinet ministers Francis Lankin, Tony Silipo,
Howard Hampton and Peter Kormos are seeking the top post.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Teen Swarming </H3>

<P>
A 14-year-old boy who was swarmed at a Toronto subway station
last night, is improving in hospital. The boy was attacked by
at least five youths at the Kennedy subway station. 
<P>
He was grabbed on the platform and forced onto the last car of
a subway train, where he was beaten with broken bottles and steel
pipes. 
<P>
He escaped about 20 minutes later. His condition has been upgraded
from poor to good. 
<HR>

<H3>Weeping Workers </H3>

<P>
The Harris government has privatized the subsidized dining operations
at Queens Park. The staff are complaining they are being offered
less hours and drastically reduced wages by the new company taking
over. 
<HR>

<H3>Bourassa Cancer </H3>

<P>
Robert Bourassa has been diagnosed with melanoma. It's the third
time the skin cancer has struck the former Quebec premier. 
<P>
Bourassa checked into hospital a week ago and was first said to
have an inner ear infection. But an official with Notre-dame Hospital
says tests found it was melanoma. 
<HR>

<H3>Cancer Rate </H3>

<P>
The cancer rate for men in Ontario is nearly one-quarter higher
than it is for women. A new study says more than 200-thousand
males have been stricken by the disease in the last decade. 
<P>
The Ontario Cancer Treatment and Research Foundation says lung,
prostate and colo-rectal cancer cases, are partly to blame for
the 23 percent difference in the sexes. 
<P>
The cancer rate for Ontario men between 1980 and 1991 was 311
out of every 100-thousand. that compares to 254 of every 100-thousand
women. 
<HR>

<H3>Kevorkian 31st. </H3>

<P>
A 67-year old Ohio woman with a painful neurological disease died
last night with the help of Dr. Jack Kevorkian. It's his second
assisted suicide this week and the 31st since 1990. 
<P>
Lawyer Geoffrey Fieger says Bette Lou Hamilton of Ohio, had been
consulting Kevorkian for seven months. The lawyer doesn't say
how Kevorkian helped the death, or how Hamilton committed suicide.

<HR>

<H3>Unabomber Wrap</H3>

<P>
Theodore Kaczynski will be moved to Sacramento, California to
face charges in four Unabomber attacks. A federal judge in Helena,
Montana, has granted the government's request to move Kaczynski.
But authorities won't say when the move will take place. 
<HR>

<H3>Diana </H3>

<P>
Another royal is in the news tonight... this time it's prince
William, the eldest son of prince Charles and princess Diana.

<P>
William, who has become a teenage heart-throb amongst British
school girls, celebrated a birthday today with a visit from his
royal mom. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

