<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, June 18, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>By-election 
<LI>Ministers GST 
<LI>Wilson - Malpractice 
<LI>Tsubouchi - Welfare 
<LI>Ombudsman Report 
<LI>Mahaffy - Justice 
<LI>Saskatchewan Boy 
<LI>Palma Court 
<LI>Unabomber 
<LI>Russia Politics 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>By-election </H3>

<P>
Sheila Copps is on her way back to Parliament Hill after easily
winning the Hamilton East federal by-election. 
<P>
Copps captured almost twice as many votes as her nearest rival
in yesterday's by-election... in the riding she has held for 12
years. 
<P>
Copps is expected to once again be appointed deputy prime minister
and heritage minister ... portfolios she lost when she quit her
seat seven weeks ago, fulfilling an election promise to resign
if the liberals didn't scrap the GST. 
<HR>

<H3>Ministers GST </H3>

<P>
The GST is stealing the spotlight at the finance ministers meeting
in Fredericton. Federal minister Paul Martin had hoped to focus
on reforming the Canada Pension Plan -- to save it from bankruptcy.
But so far he's been listening to complaints and demands over
the GST. 
<P>
Alberta, for example, is dead set against forcing taxpayers to
compensate provinces to merge their taxes with the federal levy.

<HR>

<H3>Wilson-Malpractice </H3>

<P>
Good news for expectant mothers in the province. Ontario health
minister Jim Wilson announced today that the government will restore
its contribution towards malpractice insurance for obstetricians,
in an effort to persuade doctors to continue delivering babies.
<HR>

<H3>Tsubouchi-Welfare </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government has announced it is setting up computerized
career centres, to help get people on welfare back to work. 
<P>
Social services minister David Tsubouchi says the new &quot;Ontario
Works&quot; centres, will provide the tools for the unemployed,
to find work. 
<P>
The Harris government meanwhile, could face more problems with
its tough new welfare rules. A provincial review board says denying
welfare to 16-and- 17-year-olds, is discriminatory and violates
the charter of rights. The review board ruled in favor of a 16-year
old Belleville girl. 
<HR>

<H3>Ombudsman Report </H3>

<P>
In her annual report, Ontario's ombudsman is warning the government
about its plan to privatize some services. Roberta Jamieson has
told the government to make sure people can still complain about
services sold to the private sector. 
<P>
Her office received 29-thousand complaints about government ministries
and agencies last year -- half from people with incomes less than
30-thousand dollars a year. 
<P>
Jamieson worries the government's move to trim costs could make
life worse for those who need public services the most. 
<HR>

<H3>Mahaffy - justice </H3>

<P>
Debbie Mahaffy is appeared before a commons justice committee
today that's holding hearings on proposed amendments to the so-called
<I>faint hope clause</I>. That's a provision that allows killers
serving life to apply for a parole hearing after serving 15 years
in prison. 
<P>
Mahaffy, whose 14-year-old daughter Leslie, was murdered five
years ago by Paul Bernardo, says the amendments proposed by the
justice minister don't go far enough. She adds that victims and
their families were not given sufficient time to prepare for the
hearing. 
<HR>

<H3>Saskatchewan Boy </H3>

<P>
In Saskatoon, a hushed court heard some gruesome details in the
case of a seven year-old Saskatchewan boy killed last year. 
<P>
The prosecution told the court a 14-year-old boy killed and skinned
his young playmate -- then cooked his flesh on a stove at home.

<P>
Sandy Charles is accused of luring seven-year-old Johnathan Thimpsen
into a bush last July. Thimpsen was stabbed several times, then
beaten with a rock and a bottle. Charles has pleaded not guilty
to first-degree murder and is being tried in adult court, so his
name can be used. 
<HR>

<H3>Palma Court </H3>

<P>
The man charged in the Victoria Day slayings of three Toronto
prostitutes, appeared in court today and was remanded in custody
until July 10th. 
<P>
30 year-old Marcello Palma of north York, could spend the summer
awaiting a chance at bail however. His lawyer, says the crown
will not disclose its evidence in the case for at least two months.
Palma cannot apply for bail until the crown makes that disclosure.

<P>
He is charged with first-degree murder in the shooting deaths
of transvestite Shawn Keegan, transsexual Thomas Wilkinson and
Brenda Ludgate. 
<HR>

<H3>Unabomber </H3>

<P>
Unabomber suspect Theodore Kaczynski now faces a ten-count indictment.
He was charged today, for the first time, in the Unabomber crimes.

<P>
The indictment from a grand jury in Sacramento, California accuses
Kaczynski of four of the 16 bombings. Two of them were fatal attacks
in Sacramento. Two others involved mail bombs allegedly mailed
in Sacramento. 
<P>
Kaczynski was arrested in April at his Montana shack. 
<HR>

<H3>Russia Politics </H3>

<P>
A shakeup in Russia's government could pave the way to re-election
for president Boris Yeltsin. Yeltsin has appointed retired general
Alexander Lebed as his new national security advisor. Lebed finished
third in the first round of presidential elections. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

