<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, June 17, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton East By-election 
<LI>Housing Coops 
<LI>Russian Elects 
<LI>Trucker Charged 
<LI>Church Fire 
<LI>Lebanon Explosion 
<LI>IRA Bomb 
<LI>New Zealand Volcano 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton East By-election</H3>

<P>
In just a few hours the polls will close and we'll know if Sheila
Copps will return to Ottawa. The veteran MP quit last month, fulfilling
a promise made in the 1993 election that if the GST didn't go,
she would. 
<P>
Dwight Ryan joins us now from the Copps headquarters in Hamilton
east. 
<P>
<I>Out for a stroll on election day, Sheila Copps appears relaxed.
After all, the Liberals have reigned in Hamilton east for more
than 30 years and the Copps name in Hamilton is synonymous with
community service. </I>
<P>
<I>New Democrat Wayne Marston has said from the beginning that
its a two way race between him and Sheila Copps. He'll find out
tonight just how close a race it is. Marston and Copps are the
only two candidates of thirteen in the race who live in the riding.
</I>
<P>
<I>A recent spectator poll showed Tory Angie Tomasic in third
place. The feisty bank manager was out with supporters this morning
searching for support. Tomasic isn't worried about the Reform
party competing for the right wing vote. Its also something that
doesn't bother Reform candidate Andy Sweck. </I>
<P>
<I>Voter turnout was heavy at this polling station. And voters
we spoke to led us to believe that it will be far from a Liberal
landslide.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Housing Coops </H3>

<P>
In other news tonight, more than 30 Ontario housing co-ops took
the Harris government to court today in an effort to make the
housing ministry live up to contracts for the building of almost
17-thousand non-profit housing units.
<HR>

<H3>Russian Elects </H3>

<P>
Turning to world news, with a run-off ballot in the works for
the Russian presidency, Boris Yeltsin and his chief rival are
both courting a tough, former general. 
<P>
Yeltsin has already met with Alexander Lebed, who ran third in
yesterday's election. Communist challenger Gi-nawdy Zoo-gah-nawf
plans to offer Lebed a top job in the government. He has also
hinted the ex-general would suffer if he doesn't accept. 
<HR>

<H3>Trucker Charged </H3>

<P>
A trucker from Florenceville, New Brunswick, who is charged in
a deadly crash in Massachusetts remains behind bars. Bail for
Austin Kilcollins was set at 200-thousnd dollars, but he hasn't
come up with the money. 
<P>
Three young children and two of their grandparents were killed
Saturday, when a truck smashed into the rear of their minivan
as it sat in a freeway breakdown lane. 
<P>
Kilcollins entered no plea at his arraignment today on charges
that include vehicular homicide. 
<HR>

<H3>Church Fire </H3>

<P>
The rash of church fires in the American south appears to becoming
an epidemic. Fire gutted the hills of a Baptist church near Rocky
Point North Carolina overnight. The pastor of the black church
says he's not sure whether it was arson. 
<P>
And in suburban Atlanta, authorities are calling an early morning
fire at a church suspicious. It heavily damaged the former sanctuary
of a Baptist church, where most of the congregation is white.

<P>
There have been fires at 35 black churches, and 23 white churches
over the past 18 months. 
<HR>

<H3>Lebanon Explosion </H3>

<P>
At least six Palestinians were feared dead and 16 wounded by a
huge explosion at Lebanon's largest Palestinian refugee camp today.

<P>
The blast ripped through the home of an explosives expert in Yasser
Arafat's Fatah Faction, in a camp in southern Lebanon. The cause
of the blast is not immediately known. 
<HR>

<H3>IRA Bomb </H3>

<P>
In Manchester England, engineers spent today assessing the damage
caused by Saturday's bomb blast. More than 200 people were injured,
but no-one killed, when a bomb exploded in the heart of the northern
English city, which was packed with tourists attending the European
soccer championships. 
<P>
Multi-party talks at Stormont Castle near Belfast today were overshadowed
by the bomb attack. But politicians on all sides are determined
to continue the peace process. 
<HR>

<H3>New Zealand Volcano </H3>

<P>
New Zealand's Mount Roo-a-pay-you volcano is staging a spectacular
eruption. It's sending huge clouds of steam and ash high into
the sky. 
<P>
The renewal of volcanic activity came only days after officials
had downgraded the alert status of the mountain. There were no
reports of injuries but the area was being evacuated as a precaution.


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

