<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, June 14, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Driving Crackdown 
<LI>Truck Safety 
<LI>Cop Shot 
<LI>Toronto Shooting 
<LI>Toronto Stabbing 
<LI>Freemen Follow 
<LI>Jail Abuse 
<LI>Forest Fires 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Driving Crackdown</H3>

<P>
Beginning Monday police forces across the province will be cracking
down on aggressive drivers. Reckless and speeding drivers account
for the lion's share of accidents on the roads. And as Lauran
Sabourin reports the statistics are staggering. 
<P>
<I>Every day on average there are over 600 vehicle collisions
in Ontario. That's one every two minutes. Someone is injured in
an accident every six minutes. And every nine hours someone is
killed on Ontario roadways. </I>
<P>
<I>Constable Terry Marino is an OPP officer based in Burlington.
Every day he's traveling the highways. And every day he sees drivers
only inches away from a accident. </I>
<P>
<I>Unsafe lane changes. Following too close. Excessive speeding
are what the police are going to keeping a close eye on over the
next two weeks. Speeders with illegal radar detectors who try
to hide the evidence once they're pulled over. It's cat and mouse
game the police usually win. The penalty for having a radar detector
is 165 dollars. The penalty for speeding can run much higher.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Truck Safety </H3>

<P>
Starting this summer, a new American regulation will require all
Canadian transport drivers to be tested for drugs before they
can enter the United States. And, most Ontario truckers have no
quarrel with the new law. 
<HR>

<H3>Cop Shot </H3>

<P>
A Mountie and a civilian were killed today in a shooting near
Lunenberg, Nova Scotia. The RCMP say officers responded to a domestic
dispute and that a male officer -- a 29-year veteran of the force
-- was shot when he approached a suspect. The suspect was then
shot by backup officers. No names have been released. 
<HR>

<H3>Toronto Shooting </H3>

<P>
Toronto police are searching for four suspects after a man was
killed after a robbery attempt at a roadhouse restaurant this
morning. 
<P>
Police say the armed suspects entered the restaurant just after
three this morning. They say they ordered the 10 or so workers
and their friends to the floor and fired several shots. When the
suspects fled on foot, a doorman gave chase and was later shot
after a fight. Dead is 23-year- old Raymond Saikkonen of Toronto.

<HR>

<H3>Toronto stabbing </H3>

<P>
more violent youth crime... this time in Toronto where a 17-year-old
youth remains in stable condition in hospital after being stabbed
in the lobby of a Toronto movie theatre. police say the boy was
stabbed twice in the chest and once in the side of the head last
night. they say he was attacked after a verbal dispute with four
other teens. 
<HR>

<H3>Freemen Follow</H3>

<P>
Fourteen members of the Montana Freemen face charges that include
circulating bogus cheques and threatening to kill a federal judge.
They surrendered yesterday. 
<P>
The FBI says nobody got any plea bargains in the surrender agreement...
and lessons learned in previous stand-offs led to the peaceful
resolution. 
<HR>

<H3>Jail Abuse </H3>

<P>
The province's child advocate says it was a mistake to take inmates
who rioted at a youth centre in Goderich to an adult jail. 
<P>
Judy Finlay says they were treated like dangerous adult offenders
at the London's Elgin-Middlesex Detention Centre ... and that
may have led to allegations of inmates being beaten and strip
searched when they arrived from Goderich. 
<P>
She says young offenders can't be treated like adults. 
<HR>

<H3>Forest Fires </H3>

<P>
Open campfires, and brush and grass burning, have been banned
across northwestern Ontario. The province has imposed the ban
because of the rising number of forest fires in the region. 
<P>
There are more than 250 fires burning in the province, most in
northwest Ontario. Fires have forced the evacuation of more than
100 people from Fort Hope, 220 kilometres north of Geraldton,
because of smoke. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

