<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, June 13, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Video Lottery 
<LI>OPSEU Inquiry 
<LI>Baby Shot 
<LI>Children Fire 
<LI>Forest Fires 
<LI>Salaried Doctors 
<LI>Same Sex 
<LI>Japan Crash 
<LI>Copter Crash 
<LI>Strawberries 
<LI>Strawberry Crop 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Video Lottery </H3>

<P>
Watch out Las Vegas! Ontario could soon be vying for the reputation
as the gambling capitol of North America. 
<P>
The Harris government today, paved the way for the introduction
of video gambling into the province. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Inquiry </H3>

<P>
The man responsible for security at Queen's Park says he was unaware
the riot squad was used against striking civil servants until
he watched the evening news. 
<P>
Speaker Al McLean told an inquiry that the security plan called
for the OPP riot squad to be on standby and use force if necessary.
McLean says he was aware of some disruption on the OPSEU picket
line, but he didn't know the riot squad had been called in until
he saw it on television. 
<P>
McLean also says while he's responsible for security, he relies
on his staff to do the job. 
<HR>

<H3>Baby Shot </H3>

<P>
The baby who was shot in the head with a pellet gun before his
birth has regained consciousness. Fourteen-day old Jonathan Drummond
has been moved off the critical list at the Children's Hospital
of Eastern Ontario in Ottawa. Whether he'll ever fully recover
isn't known. 
<P>
His mother -- 28-year old Brenda Drummond -- is charged with attempted
murder. She's undergoing a psychiatric assessment. 
<HR>

<H3>Children Fire </H3>

<P>
There may be an inquest into a house fire that killed four Kitchener
children and injured their mother this week. That word comes from
Dr. Karen Acheson, the regional coroner. 
<P>
Investigators are sifting through the charred remains of the house,
trying to determine what caused the blaze. Reports the children
had been playing with a lighter before the fire started Tuesday
morning have not been confirmed. But fire officials say that is
the suspected cause of the fire. 
<HR>

<H3>Forest Fires </H3>

<P>
Fire officials in northern Ontario are asking that crews from
outside the province be brought in to help fight forest fires.
The forest fire count in the north has reached a hundred and seventy
three -- with more than 100 new fires burning today. Officials
are also seeking a ban on open fires. The fires are not threatening
any communities. 
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 40 new forest fires have started in the past
24 hours in northern New Brunswick. Frequent lightning strikes
are causing trouble. Four-hundred firefighters are battling the
blazes and waterbomber aircraft are being brought in from Nova
Scotia and Maine. A total of 60 fires are burning. But no communities
are threatened. 
<HR>

<H3>Salaried Doctors </H3>

<P>
The Harris government will pay doctors up to a hundred and ninety
four thousand dollars a year to go into under-serviced areas of
the province. Under a new plan released today the province will
also foot overhead costs and pay for vacation time, as well as
continue education of doctors who agree to go to 21 areas, mainly
in northern Ontario. 
<P>
Health minister Jim Wilson says if the plan is successful, doctors
in larger communities may be taken off fees for service and become
salaried. 
<HR>

<H3>Same Sex </H3>

<P>
Gay rights organizations are hailing a Canadian Human Rights Commission
decision on spousal benefits. The Commission says that the federal
government and companies such as banks, that are federally- regulated,
must provide same-sex couples the same benefits they give other
couples. 
<P>
Complaints filed by two federal employees led to the decision.

<HR>

<H3>Japan Crash </H3>

<P>
Japanese police say there were hundred and seventy two survivors
among the two hundred and seventy five people aboard an aging
Indonesian plane that went down today. The jet was engulfed in
flames after a failed takeoff from a Japanese airport. 
<P>
A police spokesman says 12 passengers -- who had been unaccounted
for and feared still trapped in the plane -- have been found at
local hospitals. The cause of the fire is still not known. 
<HR>

<H3>Copter Crash </H3>

<P>
The death toll in a Wednesday night collision of two blackhawk
helicopters climbed to 18 today as investigators sought to explain
Australia's worst peacetime military accident in decades. 
<P>
Officials confirmed that the helicopters, flying in darkness,
had their headlights turned off. The pilots were flying with night
vision glasses. Ten crew members were taken to hospital, three
were in critical condition. 
<HR>

<H3>Strawberries </H3>

<P>
Health Canada is warning that American-grown strawberries should
be thoroughly washed before eating. The berries have caused several
cases of parasitic infection across North America, including 21
cases in Canada -- all of them in Toronto. 
<P>
Symptoms include diarrhea, fatigue and abdominal pain. 
<HR>

<H3>Strawberry Crop </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Ontario's strawberry season is almost here. The harvest
is 12 days behind schedule. And as Lauran Sabourin reports this
is the big weekend for the strawberry festivals in the peninsula
and organizers are getting nervous. 
<P>
<I>Strawberry growers haven't seen anything like it. For weeks
when they look out the window they seen nothing but rain. So much
rain the fields don't dry out. The large green berries take a
long time to ripen. </I>
<P>
<I>John Fedorkow is a strawberry grower in Niagara on the Lake.
He's been wandering around his fields looking at what kind of
crop this late harvest will yield. </I>
<P>
<I>Retailers are getting anxious. Consumers have been asking them
when the Ontario strawberries will be on the shelves. For now
retailers are continuing to put California berries out. But they
aren't moving very well since health officials warned the public
they may be tainted with infectious parasite. And that if you
do eat U.S. berries they should be thoroughly washed. </I>
<P>
<I>Tainted berries late crops have been bad news for the strawberry
festivals. They're hoping that if the weather's nice and they
can get pickers out in the fields they'll have the first crop
of Ontario strawberries this weekend. </I>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

