<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, June 12, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Workfare-Tsubouchi 
<LI>Workfare Reaction 
<LI>Palladini-TTC War 
<LI>Teller Shot 
<LI>Timmins Water 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Workfare-Tsubouchi </H3>

<P>
Social services minister David Tsubouchi came to Niagara Falls
today to unveil his government's plan that would see welfare recipients
work for their welfare cheque. 
<P>
Niagara will be one of 20 provincial test sites for the first
phase of the Workfare program. But as Lauran Sabourin reports
this morning anti poverty and labor activists disrupted the conference
and accused the government of acting like nazis. 
<P>
<I>Labor activists see Workfare as exploitation. The government
sees it as implementing a change in philosophy from a hand out
to a hand up. Twenty Ontario communities have been signed up for
the first phase of this project. Regions that include Hamilton
Wentworth, Halton, Peel and Brant County. </I>
<P>
<I>In all it's estimated that 54 thousand welfare recipients will
be put to work. Able bodied welfare recipients. In the first phase
seniors, the disabled and single parents are exempt. </I>
<P>
<I>Critics worry Workfare will take jobs away from those already
employed. Others charge that labor activists are just being fearmongers.
</I>
<P>
<I>Despite all of the fanfare with today's announcement the government
still hasn't' worked out the details. It claims this program it
will put people back to work. Make them more employable. But it's
not quite sure yet how this plan will be executed.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare Reaction </H3>

<P>
Not all Ontarians or municipalities are enamored with the Harris
government's Workfare program announced today. Many say it doesn't
work and isn't fair. 
<HR>

<H3>Palladini-TTC War </H3>

<P>
A war of words has broken out between the Toronto Transit Commission
and the minister of transportation, Al Palladini, over his call
to cut the fat out of the system. 
<P>
Monday Palladini said the TTC was the worst transportation system
in the country. Now he's changed that to the worst operated transit
system in the country. The TTC wants an apology. 
<P>
Another Harris minister Al Leach, who used to head up the TTC
says its record speaks for itself. And its always been the top
transit operation in North America. 
<HR>

<H3>Teller Shot </H3>

<P>
A Canada Trust teller in North York is lucky to be alive after
being grazed by a bullet during a holdup this morning. 
<P>
Police say the 42-year- old woman was shot after three men burst
into the bank. She was treated at hospital for a head wound and
released. 
<P>
Police are searching for the three suspects, who took off in a
car that was later found abandoned with the motor running.
<HR>

<H3>Timmins Water </H3>

<P>
First it was floods, now hot, dry weather has prompted Timmins
to order a cut in water use. The city has issued a ban on watering
lawns. 
<P>
Mayor Vic power says water consumption is increasing and the city
wants to ensure there's enough water for emergency crews. Residents
will be fined if they're caught watering lawns between 10 in the
morning and seven in the evening. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

