<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, June 11, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Fire Deaths 
<LI>Kingston Fire 
<LI>Police Shooting 
<LI>Bluewater Cover-up 
<LI>Ipperwash 
<LI>Doctors Leaving 
<LI>Public Donations 
<LI>Oshawa Casino 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Fire Deaths </H3>

<P>
We begin tonight with the tragic story of four Kitchener children...
killed early today as the family house burned down. Their mother...
27-year-old Leanne Dumbroskie ... had to be restrained by neighbors
from going back into the house. She was taken to hospital suffering
from first-degree burns to her face, smoke inhalation and shock.

<P>
The kids ... all under 10 years old... may have been playing with
a lighter. 
<HR>

<H3>Kingston Fire </H3>

<P>
A man died in a row house fire in Kingston this morning. Police
have identified the victim as 52-year-old Gerald Percy McGinnis.

<P>
The man had been pulled from the fire by a neighbor and his body
was found in a lane behind the row houses. Firefighters say the
blaze started in a bedroom of one of the units. 
<HR>

<H3>Police Shooting </H3>

<P>
A man was shot dead by police while officers were making an arrest
in east end Toronto this morning. Wayne Rick Williams died in
hospital less than an hour after the shooting. 
<P>
Jim Harding of the special investigations unit says there are
unconfirmed reports the 24-year-old man was brandishing a knife.
Police had been called after complaints a man was breaking car
windows with a crowbar. 
<HR>

<H3>Bluewater Cover-up </H3>

<P>
Ontario's corrections minister says he wants to know if managers
at the Bluewater Centre for Young Offenders near Goderich, spent
the week-end destroying documents. Documents that may substantiate
allegations that inmates were beaten. 
<HR>

<H3>Ipperwash </H3>

<P>
Negotiations on the transfer of camp Ipperwash to the Kettle and
Stoney Point First Nation have been put on hold. The two sides
were to have met today and tomorrow but band spokesman Don Cloud
says it will likely be the first week of July before talks resume.

<P>
Scheduling conflicts, and a need to clarify some issues, are being
cited for the delay. The negotiation committee says it needs more
time to examine all aspects of returning the land, including an
environmental review and clean-up of the site. 
<HR>

<H3>Doctors Leaving </H3>

<P>
If you can't beat 'em ..... quit. That seems to be the answer
for Ontario doctors who are leaving the province in ever-increasing
numbers... because of frustrations with the provincial health
care system. 
<P>
Rising malpractice costs, government clawbacks, increased taxes;
and a sharp decline in respect ... are leading many specialists
out of the province, and even ... out of practice. Scot Urquhart
reports: 
<P>
<I>In the Hamilton office of Dr. Peter Giammichele, hangs a sign
of the times. It's not something he likes to talk about ... no
interviews ... </I>
<P>
<I>But across the street at St. Joseph's hospital; the chief of
orthopedic surgery says the departure of his colleague is no surprise.
Dr. Brett Dunlop says government policies are chasing doctors
out of the system; and a shortage is looming. Dr. Giammichele
is the only practicing surgeon dealing with rheumatoid arthritis,
in the Niagara peninsula. From Niagara Falls, west ... patients
will now have to travel to London for treatment. </I>
<P>
<I>Doctors and specialists in particular; say they are being squeezed
by costs, bashed by taxes, insulted by government, and blamed
for failures in the health care system. </I>
<P>
<I>That may sound like a lot of whining by over-paid professionals,
but according to this man; it's not. Harold Pomerantz is a chartered
accountant with more than a dozen doctors as clients. He sees
the bottom line. And, he says, it isn't good.</I>
<P>
<I>In fact, Pomerantz believes that while doctors have become
easy targets for public frustration with health care ... the truth
is, that many of them aren't paid well enough. And so Brett Dunlop
predicts we will see the backs of many doctors, both young and
old ... as mounting frustration drives them out of the system,
for good. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Public Donations </H3>

<P>
Queen's Park is making it more attractive for people to donate
money to hospitals, libraries and cultural organizations. 
<P>
A bill introduced in the legislature today would help those kinds
of groups establish crown foundations. Donations would then be
treated like money given to universities. 
<P>
Currently, anyone donating to local organizations can claim a
tax credit of up to 50 per cent of their annual income. The new
law would raise that to 100 per cent. 
<HR>

<H3>Oshawa Casino </H3>

<P>
Casino backers in Oshawa have rolled snake-eyes in a city referendum.
Oshawa residents voted 65 per cent against the casino proposal
yesterday. 
<P>
Mayor Nancy Diamond is disappointed, as she saw the casino as
a job creator. The &quot;no&quot; vote against linking up with
any greater Toronto area government was even more resounding --
94 per cent rejected that proposal. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

