<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, June 7, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Train Derails 
<LI>Woman Crushed 
<LI>Truck Blitz Results 
<LI>Greyhound 
<LI>GM CAW 
<LI>Ont. Hydro Report 
<LI>Mother Evng 
<LI>Spies - Court 
<LI>Inventor Dead 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Train Derails </H3>

<P>
If you're a commuter, living west of Toronto ... you were probably
late for work this morning. The Friday morning rush was filled
with much hurry, but little speed; thanks to a train derailment,
in Mississauga. Scot Urquhart reports: 
<P>
<I>It wasn't a typical weekday rush hour. No trains on the tracks.
No commuters on the platform ... no cars in the parking lot. They
were all ... out here. </I>
<P>
<I>No trains to Toronto. A rough start for eastbound commuters
like Derek McDonald ... actively seeking work, resume in hand.
And this, was the source of Derek's frustration. Four cars of
a CN rail freight rain ... derailed near an overpass, at Mississauga
road and Lakeshore ... at five in the morning. </I>
<P>
<I>The wreck barely bothered area residents there is no estimate
on the cost of this wreck ... certainly, it will be expensive.
This fully loaded car carrier can attest to that. But Ian Thomson
says, number crunching is not a priority now; safety, and restored
service, are: no help for these commuters ... but with luck things
should be much easier, when the Monday morning rush, rolls around.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Woman Crushed </H3>

<P>
A 16-year-old Burlington girl is dead, and charges have been laid
against a Prince Edward Island man, following a strange incident
in Mississauga. 
<P>
Sarah Harding died when she slipped under the wheels of a tractor
trailer as she was trying to leave the cab yesterday. Witnesses
say the girl was clinging to the side before she was crushed to
death. The driver was stopped by police half an hour later. 
<P>
31-year-old Kevin Adams is charged with criminal negligence causing
death and failure to remain at the scene of an accident. 
<HR>

<H3>Truck Blitz Results </H3>

<P>
The continent wide annual truck safety blitz ended last night
at midnight... and the results are in from the first two days
of the massive three day effort. 
<P>
Forty per cent of all the trucks pulled over in Ontario were deemed
to be unsafe and were pulled off the road. Just over eight hundred
trucks were taken out of service by the Ministry of Transportation
on Tuesday and Wednesday. That's out of two thousand vehicles
that were checked over. A total of 343 charges were laid. 
<P>
The most common defects involved brakes, tires and suspensions.
The blitz is held every year in Canada, the US. and Mexico. 
<P>
Transportation minister Al Palladini announced recently that fines
for truck safety violations will be increased, with the maximum
fine for serious repeat offenders rising to $5,000 from $2,000.

<P>
The Ontario Trucking Association is taking exception with the
way the ministry is portraying truck safety. The association says
if forty per cent of all the trucks on the road were unsafe, there
would be a lot more accidents involving trucks on the road. 
<HR>

<H3>Greyhound </H3>

<P>
The federal government has reversed the national transportation
agency and given Greyhound Airlines its wings. Transport minister
David Anderson says the company offers a unique mix of air and
bus service and it's in the public interest to allow it to operate.

<P>
The NTA had turned Greyhound down twice, but Anderson says Greyhound
has been able to satisfy ownership requirements, and will launch
its airline with the help of a British Columbia charter carrier.

<HR>

<H3>GM CAW </H3>

<P>
The Canadian Auto Workers suggests it will choose General Motors
as its strike target this fall. Many of the CAW's 700 delegates
wrapping up a meeting in Toronto say the union's current shoving
match with GM will probably erupt into a strike. The major issues
are money and the contacting out of work. 
<HR>

<H3>Ont. Hydro Report </H3>

<P>
A government study released today, recommends that Ontario Hydro
sell off a third of its generating capacity to the private sector.
The report says such a move will lead to lower prices for electrical
power and more choice for power users. 
<HR>

<H3>Mother Evng </H3>

<P>
A Carleton Place woman accused of shooting her unborn baby, was
formally arraigned today on charges of attempted murder and use
of a firearm. 
<P>
The formal charge alleges 28-year-old Brenda Drummond tried to
kill her unborn son with a gun. Defence lawyer Lawrence Greenspon
questions the charge, saying there's nothing in the criminal code
dealing with a baby injured in the womb that survives and is born.
Crown attorney John Waugh says he's confident the charges will
stick. 
<P>
Drummond was released on bail and will undergo a 30-day psychiatric
examination. 
<HR>

<H3>Spies - Court </H3>

<P>
Two Russian spies known as Laurie and Ian Lambert appeared before
an immigration and refugee board adjudicator this afternoon for
a brief deportation hearing. 
<P>
The married couple was arrested May 22nd after they applied for
passports using the names of 2 dead babies. Former intelligence
officers say the Lamberts are not unusual...that Canada is still
awash with Russian secret agents. It's said those agents spend
years mastering Canada's language and popular culture before coming
here and assuming false identities, personalities and life histories.

<P>
The Lamberts surprised a federal court Wednesday by dropping their
claim to be Canadians .. wanting instead to go home rather than
face years behind bars. But they're lawyer says their admitting
nothing about why they've been in Canada for the last 6 years.

<HR>

<H3>Inventor Dead </H3>

<P>
A St. Catharines man who invented the process still widely used
to make instant mashed potatoes, has died. Edward Asselbergs was
69. He died of a massive stroke Tuesday. 
<P>
Asselbergs was a food research scientist with Agriculture Canada
when he developed the technique of drying potato flakes that were
transformed into mashed potatoes when water was added. He patented
the process in 1961 -- but he didn't make a lot of money from
it because 95 per cent of the proceeds went to the federal government.


<P>
