<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, June 5, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Obstetricians Fight 
<LI>Welfare Numbers 
<LI>Sears 
<LI>Russian Spies 
<LI>Russia/Chechnya 
<LI>Habitat Beirut 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Obstetricians Fight </H3>

<P>
A survey of Ontario doctors has found almost 500 of them intend
to stop delivering babies this year. The College of Physicians
and Surgeons questionnaire was sent to 23-hundred doctors who
billed OHIP last year for delivering a baby. 
<P>
The college says 30 per cent of those who replied said they either
have stopped delivering babies or intend to do so. The reason...
rising malpractice insurance costs combined with the province's
10-per-cent clawback of all fees claimed by doctors. 
<P>
Faced with the revolt, health minister Jim Wilson has promised
pregnant women he will find doctors to deliver their babies. 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Numbers </H3>

<P>
Is the revolution over? The common sense revolution of Mike Harris
seems to have hit the wall, on the social welfare front. 
<P>
After months of decline ... social welfare claims are on the rise
again. Why? Well, as Scot Urquhart reports... no one seems to
know, for sure.
<P>
<I>After nine months of decline ... welfare in Ontario... is on
its way back up. Social Services minister David Tsubouchi calls
that an adjustment in the system .... but an adjustment to what?
Does it mean the welfare system has bottomed out? </I>
<P>
<I>But in the next breath ... Tsubouchi is suggesting that when
Workfare comes in later this month, the numbers will go down again.</I>
<P>
<I>This man doesn't necessarily agree. He is Don Jaffary of the
Social Planning and Research Council of Hamilton Wentworth. His
organization is just wrapping up a study on why welfare numbers
declined in Ontario ... under the Harris government.</I>
<P>
<I>In other words the Tories may have been lucky. Welfare reforms
may have come at exactly the same time as the employment market
improved. </I>
<P>
<I>Underneath the numbers national experts believe there is still
a core of the population that is depressed and hurting because
of government budget cuts.</I>
<P>
<I>Ross says the upside to this experiment, is the degree of serious
discussion concerning the responsibilities of individuals, and
governments to society as a whole. The down side, in his view,
is the irresponsible way, which governments have shirked those
responsibilities.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Sears </H3>

<P>
A Sears employee killed in an apparent murder-suicide had complained
of unwanted advances from the manager of the Chatham store who
died with her. 
<P>
Police say 56-year-old Theresa Vince made an informal complaint
to Sears officials, but decided to deal with the matter on her
own. 
<P>
The bodies of Vince and 57-year-old Russell Davis were discovered
on Sunday. Vince was about to retire. 
<HR>

<H3>Russian Spies </H3>

<P>
A man and woman accused by the federal government of spying for
Russia say they just want to go home. The pair, who used the names
Ian and Laurie Lambert, made the announcement at a federal court
hearing in Toronto. 
<P>
Next comes a deportation hearing, but that is seen as a mere formality
and the pair could be back in their homeland by week's end. At
this point, the details of the government's case against the accused
spies remains under wraps. 
<HR>

<H3>Russia/Chechnya </H3>

<P>
In Moscow meanwhile, Russian and Chechen negotiators are meeting
for a second day to try to enforce a four-day old cease-fire.
And in the war-torn streets of Grozny... peace is still far from
reality. 
<HR>

<H3>Habitat Beirut </H3>

<P>
The once flourishing economic center of the middle east is slowly
being rebuilt. Only long term stability will return Beirut to
its former status. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

