<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, June 4, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Auto Insurance 
<LI>Baby Shot 
<LI>House Explosion 
<LI>Palma 
<LI>Truck Check 
<LI>Kingston 
<LI>Israel Meeting 
<LI>Jet Down 
<LI>Tianamen Anniversary 
<LI>Harris-Port Weller 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Auto Insurance </H3>

<P>
The Harris government, today gutted the &quot;no-fault&quot; auto
insurance plan put in place by the former NDP government. 
<P>
The new legislation would cut accident victim's benefits by more
than half, and get tough on un-insured drivers. 
<HR>

<H3>Baby Shot </H3>

<P>
An Ottawa-area infant remains in intensive care in critical but
stable condition after apparently being shot in the head. 
<P>
Police say a woman in her 20's gave birth to the baby boy in her
bathroom Thursday afternoon. The infant was taken to hospital,
first in Carleton Place and then Ottawa, after the father came
home a few hours later. 
<P>
The Ottawa Citizen and Ottawa Sun both quote sources as saying
a bullet was found in the baby's head. Police won't confirm the
reports.
<HR>

<H3>House Explosion </H3>

<P>
Police are probing the causes of house fires this morning in two
separate parts of the province. 
<P>
In Kingston, an early morning blaze destroyed a frame home and
two cars parked in the driveway. Damage is estimated at 100 thousand
dollars. 
<P>
And in Kitchener, one person was injured this morning when an
explosion ripped through a duplex. 
<HR>

<H3>Palma </H3>

<P>
The man accused of gunning down three prostitutes made his first
court appearance in Toronto this morning. Marcello Palma has been
remanded in custody until his next appearance June 18th. 
<P>
The 30 year old Palma, was brought back to Toronto yesterday from
Halifax, where he was arrested during the weekend. He faces three
counts of first-degree murder in connection with the deaths of
19-year-old Shawn Keegan, 31-year-old Thomas &quot;Deanna&quot;
Wilkinson and 25-year-old Brenda Ludgate. They were all found
shot to death May 20th. 
<HR>

<H3>Truck Check </H3>

<P>
Truckers across North America encountered unexpected safety checks
today. Roadcheck '96 began at midnight and will continue across
Canada, the US. and Mexico for 72 hours. 
<P>
250 ministry of transport inspectors are checking trucks in Ontario
in the &quot;round the clock&quot; enforcement blitz. Transportation
Minister Al Palladini says many truckers operate safe vehicles,
and those who don't will be forced off the road. 
<HR>

<H3>Kingston </H3>

<P>
Changes are in the works for Canada's women's prisons. Solicitor
General Herb Gray is appointing a deputy commissioner to oversee
women's prisons. All federal facilities will also get women's
emergency response teams -- and one, as yet unnamed, prison will
be staffed by female guards. 
<P>
The changes follow the riot at the women's prison in Kingston
and the strip search of several inmates by male guards. 
<HR>

<H3>Israel Meeting </H3>

<P>
Outgoing Israeli prime minister Shimon Peres has met with his
successor Benjamin Netanyahu. It's their first meeting since Peres'
defeat in national elections last week. 
<P>
The two men discussed the Handover of power. Army and intelligence
officers have already started to brief Netanyahu on security matters.

<HR>

<H3>Jet Down </H3>

<P>
An investigation is under way into the downing of a US fighter-bomber
by a Japanese naval destroyer. The plane was towing a target during
military exercises about 25-hundred kilometres west of Hawaii,
when it was hit. 
<P>
A spokesman for Japan's navy, says a problem with a rapid-fire
weapon system is suspected. The two people aboard the jet ejected
safely and were picked up in good condition by a rescue helicopter.

<HR>

<H3>Tianamen Anniversary </H3>

<P>
It's the seventh anniversary of the day Chinese tanks crushed
pro-democracy rallies in Beijing. Today, Tianamen Square was filled
with people, but only one woman tried to lay flowers at a monument
-- and she was dragged away. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris-Port Weller </H3>

<P>
Port Weller Dry Docks in St. Catharines was celebrating today.
A dedication ceremony was held for the 18 million dollar refit
of the Captain Henry Jackman. 
<P>
This is the first bulk carrier to be dedicated on the great lakes
since 1990. The ship is named after Ontario lieutenant governor
Hal Jackman's grandfather. Jackman and premier Mike Harris were
on hand for the ceremony. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

