<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 06/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, June 3, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Evng Palma 
<LI>Sears Murder Suicide 
<LI>Ontario - YOA 
<LI>Deadbeat Parents 
<LI>Crime Convention 
<LI>Outlaws Arrest 
<LI>Hostage Standoff 
<LI>Ipperwash Economy 
<LI>Quebec Rally Charges 
<LI>Arafat Major 
<LI>New Netanyahu 
<LI>Kennedy Sworn 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Evng Palma </H3>

<P>
Marcello Palma is back in Toronto. The man accused of shooting
to death three Toronto prostitutes on the Victoria Day weekend
landed at Pearson Airport this afternoon. 
<P>
He had been escorted by police from Halifax, where he was arrested
Saturday. A police van was waiting on the tarmac to whisk Palma
away to process him on the first-degree murder charges he faces.
Palma has a bail hearing scheduled for tomorrow. 
<HR>

<H3>Sears Murder Suicide </H3>

<P>
Police in Chatham have released the names of two people killed
today in what appears to be a murder-suicide at a Sears store.

<P>
The bodies of 57-year-old Russell Davis and 56-year-old Theresa
Vince were found in the offices of the store in downtown Chatham.
Police say it looks like Vince died of multiple gunshot wounds,
while Davis killed himself. Two handguns found at the scene both
belonged to Davis. 
<HR>

<H3>Ontario - YOA </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is asking Ottawa to make significant changes
in the Young Offenders Act, and to get tough with criminal kids.
The changes would see children under the age of 18 become far
more accountable to the law. 
<HR>

<H3>Deadbeat Parents </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the Ontario government is planning changes to make
it tougher for so called &quot;deadbeat parents&quot; to escape
their responsibilities. 
<P>
A published report indicates the move would help children get
court-ordered money due to them. And that the government is prepared
to boost the number of enforcement officers and increase the number
and authority of workers manning telephone assistance lines. 
<P>
Attorney General Charles Harnick is expected to take the proposals
before cabinet for approval later this month. 
<HR>

<H3>Crime Convention </H3>

<P>
Police officers from across the continent have gathered in Niagara
Falls for the annual Crime Stoppers convention. And as Lauran
Sabourin reports the program's goal is to have more citizens putting
even more criminals behind bars. 
<P>
<I>In the 20 years that Crime Stoppers has been in operation tips
from citizens have helped solve over 555 thousand felony cases.
And helped recover 3.2 billion dollars in property and narcotics.
</I>
<P>
<I>Impressive statistics. But critics charge that Crime Stoppers
is nothing but a police snitch line. People are reluctant to come
forward out of fear of retaliation from the accused. And out of
frustration over the demands the justice system puts on witnesses.
</I>
<P>
<I>In Niagara region alone the calls to are up significantly.
Criminal convictions as a result of Crime Stoppers tips are up.</I>

<P>
Canada has set up a national toll free number for tips. Instead
of calling your local office the number to call now is <B>1-800-222-TIPS
(8477)</B>. Your information will be directed to your local police
force. 
<HR>

<H3>Outlaws Arrest </H3>

<P>
In a continuing crackdown on motorcycle gangs Niagara police have
laid additional charges against an outlaws gang member. 
<P>
Thirty eight year old Claude Longval is facing two prostitution
related charges. Longval was arrested last month during a police
sweep of biker hangouts. 
<HR>

<H3>Hostage Standoff </H3>

<P>
The woman held hostage in her home near Cranbrook, British Columbia
last week says she feels sorry for the young man and woman who
held her captive. 
<P>
Leanne Campbell, who is nine months pregnant, says the pair wound
up in trouble because of their childhood. The suspects made a
court appearance today and were remanded to July 8th to face several
charges, including unlawful confinement and attempted murder.

<P>
The hostage taking came to a peaceful end Saturday morning. 
<HR>

<H3>Ipperwash Economy </H3>

<P>
The camping season is upon us, and tourist operators at Ipperwash
say it doesn't seem like it... the area surrounding one of the
most beautiful waterfront parks is suffering from a double whammy:
a long recession and fears over last summers' troubles with local
natives... the lack of business is costing the area millions.

<HR>

<H3>Quebec Rally Charges </H3>

<P>
A senior official of the federal Liberal party has been charged
under Quebec's Referendum law for hiring buses to take &quot;no&quot;
supporters to a unity rally in Montreal last fall. 
<P>
Aurele Gervais -- the party's communications director -- faces
possible fines amounting to five-thousand dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Arafat Major </H3>

<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat today said he &quot;respects
the choice of the Israeli people.&quot; Arafat arrived in London
for a two-day visit. 
<P>
British officials say prime minister John Major will have some
reassuring words for Arafat, about the continuation of the peace
process. 
<P>
Also today, US president Clinton has written Arafat, along with
the leaders of Jordan, Syria, and Egypt, re-stating US commitment
to peace. 
<HR>

<H3>New Netanyahu </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, a decidedly more diplomatic tone from Israel's prime
minister-elect. Benjamin Netanyahu has put hard-line supporters
on notice, saying he is in charge of policy. 
<P>
There were indications that Israel would now cancel all deals
with the Palestinians, but aides say Netanyahu won't do that.

<HR>

<H3>Kennedy Sworn </H3>

<P>
Former Toronto food bank director Gerard Kennedy has taken his
seat in the Ontario legislature. Kennedy was sworn in this morning
after winning the York south by-election last month. He has been
named the Liberal Associate Critic for both Consumer and Commercial
Relations and for Housing. 
<P>
Kennedy is seen by many political observers as a strong candidate
for the Liberal party leadership. Lyn McLeod has said she'll step
down as leader at a party convention this fall. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

