<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/31/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, May 31, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Holidays Act 
<LI>Hostage Latest 
<LI>Seized Vehicle 
<LI>Russian Spies 
<LI>Netanyahu 
<LI>Irish Peace 
<LI>King City Summit 
<LI>Cuts - Growth 
<LI>Fergus Rescue 
<LI>Ozone 
<LI>Leary Obit 
<LI>WCB Demo 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Holidays Act </H3>

<P>
Christmas shopping could take on a whole new meeting in Ontario...
the law that makes it illegal for most Ontario stores to open
on statutory holidays has been ruled unconstitutional. 
<P>
Judge H.W. Silverman of the Ontario Court of Justice ruled today
the Retail Business Holidays Act violates the Charter of Rights
and Freedoms by forcing stores to close on holidays. Silverman
calls the &quot;forbidden days&quot; in the act an &quot;irrational,
illogical, unreasonable&quot; restriction on business activity
and workers' rights to earn a livelihood. 
<P>
Silverman was ruling on a charges of opening on a statutory holiday
leveled against two drugstore chains, Hy and Zel's and Herbies,
plus the Kitchen Table chain of food stores. 
<P>
The act prohibits most stores from opening on Christmas Day, Boxing
Day, and six other holidays. The act was amended several years
ago to allow Sunday shopping. 
<P>
Defence lawyer Tim Danson says he hopes the government won't appeal
the decision. The solicitor general's office says it will review
the decision. 
<HR>

<H3>Hostage Latest </H3>

<P>
The hostage crisis in BC is into day three and no sign of letting
up yet... the doctor of the pregnant young woman being held hostage
is posted outside the house near Cranbrook where his patient is
being held. 
<P>
Dr. Edgar Turski says he is worried about Leanna Campbell, but
if he had to pick a patient to go through this ordeal, he would
have chosen her because of her strong character. Campbell is nine
months pregnant and due to give birth any time now. 
<P>
She is the prisoner of a 21-year-old man and a 19-year-old woman
who are wanted for violent robberies in Alberta. They shot and
hit a police officer in the chest as they took Campbell's home
by siege. He has recovered. 
<P>
The latest demand from the hostage takers is to see the newspaper
coverage of their story. 
<HR>

<H3>Seized Vehicle </H3>

<P>
Metro Toronto police have issued an appeal for triple murder suspect
Marcello Palma to surrender. And they are denying reports that
they think Palma has fled to Italy. Palma is wanted in connection
with three prostitute killings in Toronto on May 20th. 
<P>
Last night Toronto police towed away a red pickup truck owned
by Palma. The truck was located in an industrial park in Concord,
northwest of Toronto. 
<P>
Police have a Canada wide warrant out for Palma, and are concentrating
on the Montreal area, as they know he has a brother there. 
<HR>

<H3>Russian Spies </H3>

<P>
A hearing date has been set in the Russian spy case. A Toronto
couple will appear in federal court in Toronto next Wednesday.

<P>
Lawyers for Laurie and Ian Lambert will argue their arrest and
detention is unconstitutional. If the federal court agrees the
government has enough evidence to prove the two are spies, they
will face a deportation hearing. 
<HR>

<H3>Netanyahu </H3>

<P>
Palestinians say they expect Israel's new prime minister to honor
Israel's commitments in peace agreements. It's the first official
response from the Palestinians to the election of right-winger
Benjamin Netanyahu as Israeli prime minister. 
<P>
A Palestinian cabinet minister says Yasser Arafat's government
won't re-negotiate anything. But just what that will mean isn't
certain. 
<HR>

<H3>Irish Peace </H3>

<P>
Britain and Ireland say an Irish Republican Army cease-fire is
still a must -- before its political allies sit at talks on Northern
Ireland's future. 
<P>
The party, Sinn Fein, has done well in an election held to determine
who takes part in the peace talks. 
<HR>

<H3>King City Summit </H3>

<P>
There won't be any scrums outside a meeting of world leaders being
held in king city ... newspaper magnate Conrad Black is holding
a secret summit of international big wigs including the Queens
of Netherlands and Spain, and our own Prime Minister. 
<P>
It's the annual Bildeberg's Conference, and we'll not know what
it's all about, because participants must take an oath of silence.

<HR>

<H3>Cuts-Growth </H3>

<P>
A University of Toronto study predicts Ontario will lose thousands
of jobs over the next three years. And that the government's tax
cuts will slow down economic growth. 
<HR>

<H3>Fergus Rescue </H3>

<P>
A dramatic river rescue has captured headlines this week... we
have a first hand account from the chief of police who put his
life on the line to help save a little girl trapped in a dam in
Fergus. 
<HR>

<H3>Ozone </H3>

<P>
The manmade chemical assault on the atmosphere's ozone layer is
beginning to ease and researchers say the ozone hole high above
the earth should start closing within 10 years. 
<P>
Ground level readings show a decline in the amount of ozone-destroying
chemicals in the air for the first time since the compounds were
put into common use more than 30 years ago. 
<HR>

<H3>Leary Obit </H3>

<P>
Timothy Leary has dropped out, for good. The Harvard professor
turned guru of  LSD who encouraged the '60s generation to &quot;turn
on, tune in, and drop out,&quot; died in Los Angeles. 
<P>
The seventy five year old Leary was suffering from cancer. When
he learned of his terminal illness, he said he was looking forward
to death as the ultimate trip. 
<P>
A close of Leary's says they will try to launch his remains into
outer space. 
<HR>

<H3>WCB Demo </H3>

<P>
The Mike Harris government is determined to go ahead with changes
to the Workers Compensation Board. 
<P>
Cam Jackson, the minister responsible for the board, says its
in serious financial trouble. But, injured workers say he's wrong.
That story from Dwight Ryan. 
<P>
<I>Injured workers aren't happy with proposed changes to the Workers
Compensation Board. They claim that the WCB is not experiencing
financial difficulties, that in fact it has billions of dollars.
Still the government claims unfunded liabilities, the difference
between the board's assets, and the cost of its obligations to
injured workers, is nearly eleven billion dollars. </I>
<P>
<I>Vince Bellerba was injured on the job ten years ago. He doesn't
buy the government argument. </I>
<P>
<I>Jackson meanwhile promises that injured workers and others
will have a chance to offer input before any changes are made.
</I>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

