<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, May 27, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Road Safety 
<LI>Safety Survey 
<LI>Brant-Reform/Tory 
<LI>Stowaways 
<LI>Somalia-Sentence 
<LI>Quebec-Referendum 
<LI>Swimsuits 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Road Safety </H3>

<P>
The Harris government is getting serious, about highway safety.
A new get-tough policy on drinking drivers and unsafe trucks,
was announced by transportation minister al Palladini. Fines on
Ontario highways will be increased to as much as 20-thousand dollars.

<HR>

<H3>Safety Survey </H3>

<P>
The best way to find out about safety on the highways ... is to
ask the people who drive them, every day. That's what the OPP
is doing, this month. 
<P>
They began this morning, on the 401 near Kitchener; with a safety
survey blitz, that will last until June 25th. 
<HR>

<H3>Brant-Reform/Tory </H3>

<P>
Members of Canada's political right wing met over the weekend
in Alberta. Despite the absence of Tory and Reform leaders, delegates
agreed that the only way to beat the liberals in the next federal
election is to join forces. 
<P>
As Dwight Ryan reports, the testing ground will be the riding
of Brant, where Tories and conservatives will unite to field one
candidate. 
<P>
<I>It was a sad night for the political right. In October of 1993,
Canada made a turn to the left. The once powerful federal Tories
were reduced to just two, liberal Jean Chretien would be prime
minister with a commanding majority. </I>
<P>
<I>But those further to the right, the western based Reformers
were also celebrating. Now, three years later, the Reformers are
shooting themselves in the feet and their credibility with many
voters is at an all time low. </I>
<P>
<I>Tory leader Jean Charest travels the country trying to convince
us that his party will return. For the time being, he and his
one fellow Conservative sit silent in the house, denied official
party status. But what if the Tories and the Reformers were to
join forces. </I>
<P>
<I>Riding Association president Jeff Coles has just returned from
the winds of change conference in Alberta. He says a combined
candidate makes perfect political sense. </I>
<P>
<I>The prospect of facing a combined opposition in the next federal
election doesn't phase the popular current member, revenue minister
Jane Stewart.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Stowaways </H3>

<P>
A Taiwanese ship, that may have been the scene of three murders,
is free to leave Canada, at any time. However, eight crew members
and a Romanian hostage, are seeking to remain in Canada, rather
than the depart with the ship. 
<P>
The group told Canadian authorities a horrific tale of how three
stowaways were murdered on board the ship. Two were set adrift
on a raft made of oil drums; a third was apparently tossed overboard,
on the high seas. The fourth stowaway, was discovered, and sheltered
by crew members, who now want off the boat. 
<P>
The RCMP is frantically seeking a legal method to hold the ship,
and charge those responsible. But, because the alleged crimes
were committed on the high seas; Canadian authorities say, they
have no jurisdiction to stop the ship from departing Canada. 
<P>
At the moment, they are talking to authorities in Taiwan, to see
if the country that owns the ship will intervene, and request
Canadian involvement. 
<HR>

<H3>Somalia-Sentence </H3>

<P>
A commanding officer in the Canadian Airborne Regiment has been
sentenced to three months in jail, for his part in the Somalia
affair. Major Tony Seward, will also be drummed out of the military.

<P>
Seward was convicted of negligent performance of duty in 1994;
for telling his troops that they could abuse prisoners taken in
Somalia, during a UN peacekeeping mission in 1993. 
<P>
Seward was originally sentenced to a severe reprimand by court
martial. But prosecutors appealed the sentence as too lenient;
and won jail time. Seward is the first and only officer so far,
to be jailed for the beating, torture and murder of a 16 year
old Somalia boy by Canadian soldiers. 
<HR>

<H3>Quebec-Referendum </H3>

<P>
The issue is closed, according to Quebec's chief returning officer
... but Alliance Quebec; the anglophone rights group, isn't satisfied.

<P>
Pierre Cote, today released his report on irregularities in the
Quebec referendum. More than 86-thousand rejected ballots: ...
most of them, &quot;no&quot; votes, were reported, but Cote concluded
that the spoiled ballots were a less significant threat to democracy
... than the huge federalist rally held in downtown Montreal,
just three days before the vote. 
<P>
Alliance Quebec has rejected the report, and is demanding a full
government investigation, of the matter. 
<HR>

<H3>Swimsuits </H3>

<P>
It's official. May 24th has passed, and the summer swimsuit season
is upon us. If that strikes fear and dread into your heart, you
are not alone. 
<P>
Although the industry sells more than a billion dollars worth
of swim wear every year; most of it to women ... those who buy
the suits ... do so, with great reluctance. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

