<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wenesday, May 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Harnick - Crowns 
<LI>Grand River Rising 
<LI>Jobs - Health 
<LI>Mitral Valve 
<LI>Foam Homes 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Harnick - Crowns </H3>

<P>
The province's crown attorneys say they are busier than ever with
not enough staff and too much work. Still, the attorney general
says they won't be exempt from provincial cutbacks. 
<P>
But Charles Harnick told a Guelph audience today that rumours
of massive layoffs are just that ...rumours. Dwight Ryan has that
story. 
<P>
<I>Ontario's attorney general has unveiled a blueprint for change
for Ontario's justice system. The province's crown attorneys have
been on pins and needles since the Tories came to power nearly
a year ago. They know that thousands of civil servants are to
lose their jobs...and they know that their ministry isn't exempt.
</I>
<P>
<I>They also know that they're up to the necks in work. Harnick
admits they're not having an easy time of it. But still the rumours
persist that Ontario's prosecutors will face massive layoffs.
</I>
<P>
<I>Harnick says more will be done to help victims of crime and
that his government will refocus its resources on serious and
violent crime. </I>
<P>
<I>The attorney general assured crown attorneys that they'll have
an important role in deciding what changes are made.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Grand River Rising </H3>

<P>
Flood levels in the grand river continue to rise with the crest
expected to reach Caledonia at seven p.m. tonight and Dunnville
by seven a.m. tomorrow morning. 
<P>
As Kathy Renwald reports the flood damage has been confined to
low lying areas, but the fast flowing river poses a serious threat
to safety for recreational users. 
<P>
<I>The Lafortune Campground on the Grand River is an unfortunate
place to be for trailer owners. The trailers are nearly up to
their axles in alligators. </I>
<P>
<I>In Middleport the river washes against the trunk of trees,
and dandelions are floating at the waters surface. </I>
<P>
<I>Underneath the Lorne Bridge in Brantford the Grand River races
by during its crest at midday. Its flowing 29 times faster than
the average summer volume. There is no urban flooding predicted,
but the Grand River Conservation Authority is doing all it can
to manage dams and maintain flood storage. </I>
<P>
<I>Before the weekends story Jim Reid said he was fishing in the
Grand in a spot where water was just to his knee now he says the
water there has risen to three times his height. </I>
<P>
<I>The authority now says that fishing and canoeing on the grand
during this high water peak is foolish.. still the allure of the
water on a spring day is strong ..this student waded into the
grand river.. not for a picnic ..but for a peaceful place to study.
With sporadic rain in the forecast, the conservation authority
will remain on flood alert.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Jobs-Health </H3>

<P>
New research shows that just thinking you might lose your job,
can make you sick... literally. The university study suggests
that things like high blood pressure, allergy symptoms, arthritis,
heart disease, and mental illness &quot;all increase in workers
whose jobs are threatened or lost&quot;. 
<P>
Environment Canada was so worried about this that it hired an
expert to counsel employees during a recent downsizing. 
<HR>

<H3>Mitral Valve </H3>

<P>
It can cause chest pain, a racing heart and fatigue, but it's
not a heart attack. It affects mostly women and symptoms can often
be written off as &quot;all in her head.&quot; But in fact, the
cause is an abnormality of the heart known as Mitral Valve Prolapse.

<HR>

<H3>Foam Homes </H3>

<P>
For years now, builders have been looking for new ways to make
their homes more earth-friendly and energy-efficient. Those efforts
have sometimes resulted in homes that look pretty silly. Well,
now there's a new kind of home, one that saves wood, saves energy,
and looks normal. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

