<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, May 20, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Muskoka Storm 
<LI>Biker Follow 
<LI>Shuttle Endeavour 
<LI>FBI Explosion 
<LI>Lee-Taiwan 
<LI>Iraq Oil 
<LI>Game Wars 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Muskoka Storm </H3>

<P>
There was very little time for swimming, boating, tanning or even
fishing this long weekend as mother nature turned ugly on cottage
country. 
<P>
Gusting winds, thunderstorms and flooding were the norm making
this May 24th Victoria day weekend one to remember. 
<P>
<I>Cottagers and campers will be talking about this May long weekend
for years to come. Two violent storms systems passed through central
Ontario wreaking havoc. </I>
<P>
<I>On Saturday, high winds brought the roof came down on dozens
of boaters at crates marina in Orillia. The storm took out Hydro
to more than 10-thousand customers, six thousand in the Bancroft
area, and three to four thousand in the Muskoka, Huntsville and
Bracebridge areas. </I>
<P>
<I>Hundred more went without power because of lightening strikes
in Bruce County. Ontario Hydro hopes to have electricity restored
by later today. </I>
<P>
<I>A dozen children were sent to hospital after a severe thunderstorm
moved through Manitoulin Island. About 700 girl guides and boy
scouts from across the province were attending &quot;Rendezvous
96&quot;, a big camping expedition. The storm hit suddenly, knocking
down tents, old sheds and tree branches. Twelve of the children
suffered broken bones, sprained ankles, shock and hypothermia
but they weren't kept in hospital. </I>
<P>
<I>Timmins residents woke up to a higher Mattagami River today
-- 48 centimetres higher. Levels are expected to continue rising
because of the release of water from too-full Hydro dams and spring
runoff. The water is rising so quickly some wooden barricades
installed by police have floated away. Roads near the river are
flooded and some campers outside Timmins are stranded by washed-out
roads. Some flood-zone residents have left their homes but many
are staying put.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Biker Follow </H3>

<P>
Two rival motorcycle gangs clashed at Queen's Park yesterday.

<P>
Members of the Paradice Riders and Satan's Choice began a peaceful
protest over what they see as discrimination against bikers. As
Lauran Sabourin reports, this incident comes a day after a clash
between police and the Paradice Riders in Niagara Falls. 
<P>
<I>The clash erupted after police tried to arrest a Paradice Rider
gang member. Police fired pepper spray into the angry mob of bikers.
Because of the high winds both police officers and bikers were
hit by the spray. </I>
<P>
<I>About 100 Paradice Riders arrived in Niagara Falls for an annual
long weekend party. Police warned the bikers and the public that
they would be keeping a watchful eye on the Paradice Riders. </I>
<P>
<I>The group was confronted by the police when they came off the
highway in the city. Cops checked the identification of each biker.
One charge of breach of recognizance was laid. </I>
<P>
<I>The Paradice Riders left the city Sunday morning.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Shuttle Endeavour </H3>

<P>
It was like watching a giant helium balloon inflate. Except this
one is in space, and it's filled with nitrogen gas. 
<P>
NASA's experimental, inflatable antenna swelled to its full shape
this morning, about two hours after the shuttle &quot;Endeavour&quot;'
released a satellite and the inflatable device. 
<P>
Canadian Marc Garneau and the shuttle's five other astronauts
watched the antenna inflate to the size of a tennis court. It's
hoped the 14-million-dollar experiment will be a model for future
inflatable spacecraft.
<HR>

<H3>FBI Explosion </H3>

<P>
Police in Laredo, Texas, are investigating an explosion outside
a building that houses the FBI. No one is reported injured. 
<P>
There's no word on the cause of the explosion, which blew out
windows but caused no structural damage. The FBI says it has no
evidence it was the target. 
<HR>

<H3>lee-Taiwan </H3>

<P>
Taiwan's president Lee Teng-Hui offered today to make a ``journey
of peace'' to China but rejected Beijing's demand to halt his
drive to raise the island's international profile. 
<P>
In his inaugural address after being sworn in as the first popularly
elected president, Lee repeated Taiwan's desire to reunite eventually
with China. 
<P>
Lee offered to hold a direct exchange with China's leaders to
open ``a new era of communication and co-operation'' between the
breakaway province and its ruling government in Beijing. 
<HR>

<H3>Iraq Oil </H3>

<P>
In a move expected to result in lower gasoline prices, Iraq finally
has agreed to a UN plan to sell some of its oil. 
<P>
Under the terms... Saddam Hussein may sell a billion dollars worth
of oil every 90 days, with the profits going toward food and medicine
for his people. 
<P>
The UN Security Council put a plug on Iraqi oil exports after
the 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The UN Secretary General says the
new agreement is a win-win situation for all sides. 
<P>
Iraq could have had the same deal years ago. Nevertheless, it
was welcomed by Iraq's UN ambassador, who said Iraqi oil could
be flowing in a month. 
<HR>

<H3>Game Wars </H3>

<P>
The battle lines for the blaster buck are being re-drawn this
week at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles...also
known as E-3. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

