<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, May 17, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Gypsy Warning 
<LI>Toronto Stabbing
<LI>Teen Rapist 
<LI>Toronto Rape 
<LI>P4W 
<LI>Niagara Bikers 
<LI>Pinery 
<LI>Senators 
<LI>Niagara Heroes 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Gypsy Warning </H3>

<P>
May 24th. The Victoria day weekend. Today, summer begins in Canada
... unofficially. And the return of warm weather means two things:
allergy season, and a jump in street crime. 
<P>
Niagara Regional Police have issued a warning to tourist operators
in the falls, as the start of the lucrative tourist season, kicks
off. As Lauran Sabourin reports, professional pickpockets and
thieves have moved in to the honeymoon city and are preying on
unsuspecting victims. 
<P>
<I>The most recent incident occurred yesterday at a souvenir store
in the Skylon tower. An unsuspecting tourist, the man carrying
the black bag over his shoulder is jostled by three women. One
woman comes up behind him. Slits the bag with a knife and steals
his wallet and credit cards. </I>
<P>
<I>Niagara Falls furrier Barry Lang knows first hand how these
professional thieves operate. Last month two couples walked into
his Queen Street store. They distracted Lang by asking him to
calculate the GST rebate on a coat. This is a man whose store
in covered with surveillance cameras. Who has a keen eye for suspicious
behavior. And even he didn't see the woman stuff a full length
fur coat inside her coat. </I>
<P>
<I>With every trick these pickpockets use the cops are one step
behind them. While security personnel may be on the lookout for
pickpockets, the pickpockets are always on the lookout for victims.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Toronto Stabbing</H3>

<P>
In Toronto, there is increasing concern not only about crime;
but about who is committing the crime. A street fight ended with
the stabbing death of a 15-year-old Toronto boy last night. 
<P>
Witnesses say his attacker, was a young teen who taunted, and
cursed his dying victim. Andr&eacute; Matthews was pronounced
dead at hospital, with a stab wound to the throat. Police have
arrested and charged a 17-year-old young offender. Police say
the stabbing was likely sparked by a previous dispute. 
<HR>

<H3>Teen Rapist </H3>

<P>
Many blame the Young Offenders Act for the increase in crimes
committed by youth. 
<P>
Police say a 13-year-old metro girl has been raped -- but her
suspected assailant is too young to be charged with the crime.
They say an 11-year-old boy appeared unruffled when he was nabbed
yesterday. He apparently is fully aware of his rights, and calmly
told officers he was too young to be charged. 
<P>
Police say they have a thick file on the boy, and believe he's
responsible for a string of other crimes. They call the suspect
one of the &quot;untouchables&quot;; kids under the age of 12,
who cannot be charged under the Young Offenders Act. 
<HR>

<H3>Toronto Rape </H3>

<P>
In Ottawa, the case sparked a heated exchange in the commons,
between Reform party members, and the Liberal government. 
<P>
The government argued, that a commons committee is currently reviewing
the entire Young Offenders Act; and no matter how low the age
limit ... there will always be exceptions to the rule. The reformers:
however, slammed Ottawa, for not lowering the age for young offenders
earlier this year, when amendments to the act were passed in the
commons. 
<HR>

<H3>P4W</H3>

<P>
For those who can be charged under the law; prison is frequently
the end result. Until this year, there was only one prison for
women, in all of Canada. 
<P>
The Kingston Prison for Women is closing; to be replaced by five
regional centres. However, the opening of one of those centres:
in Kitchener, has now been delayed for a second time. 
<P>
The move follows severe security problems stemming from the opening
of a similar prison, in Edmonton. That has prompted a full security
review of the Kitchener facility.
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Bikers </H3>

<P>
In Niagara, police believe that they may have to make a few arrests,
this weekend. 
<P>
The Victoria Day holiday is a traditional time for motorcycle
gangs to get together; to celebrate the arrival of spring. However,
with increasing tensions between rival gangs in southern Ontario
... police are gearing up, for what could be a busy weekend. 
<HR>

<H3>Pinery </H3>

<P>
And another traditional gathering point for the May 24th celebration;
the Pinery, will close this weekend, for the first time in 57
years. that ... because of an ongoing dispute between the province,
and native groups occupying parts of the park. 
<P>
The natives say they have no intention of abandoning the areas
of the park, now under their control. As a result, the gates of
the park will remain firmly closed, over the weekend. 
<HR>

<H3>Senators </H3>

<P>
And the holiday weekend is also the time when thousands of Canadians
puff pot ... as part of their party ritual. 
<P>
Marijuana is still illegal in this country; but in Ottawa this
morning, the senate was busy trying to change that. A group of
Tory and Liberal senators who are members of the Commons Legal
and Constitutional Affairs Committee say; they will recommend
changes to current drug legislation, that would decriminalize
the possession of small amounts of marijuana, and hashish. 
<P>
The senators say, punishment for possession has failed as a deterrent;
and merely serves to clog up the court system. They believe that
education would be a better weapon in the fight against drug abuse.
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Heroes </H3>

<P>
Crime, is not all that is making news today, however. Heroism
has a part, as well. 
<P>
Three men from Niagara Falls have been honored in Ottawa. They
were presented this morning with medals of bravery for an incident
in Niagara Falls three years ago. 
<P>
Craig Garner, Raymond Gionet and William van Dongen tried to save
two children and a woman from being burned alive by her estranged
husband. He was holding his family hostage in a van, doused them
with gasoline and was threatening to light his lighter. 
<P>
Garner, Gionet and van Dongen pulled the two children to safety.
They got the woman out of the van just as her husband ignited
the gas. He died in the fire, and his estranged wife died later
of her injuries. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

