<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, May 15, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Child Abuse Case 
<LI>QP Garden 
<LI>Welfare Caseload 
<LI>CBC Deadline 
<LI>Chretien 
<LI>Boating Inquest 
<LI>Bicycle Deaths 
<LI>Bosnian Return 
<LI>Bangladesh 
<LI>Valuejet Update 
<LI>Valuejet Suits 
<LI>Whitby Crash 
<LI>Flying Cab 
<LI>KKK 
<LI>Car Hirings 
<LI>Census Mail 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Child Abuse Case </H3>

<P>
Social services agencies responsible for children are in the spotlight
today... this after the verdict in what is being described as
&quot;the ultimate case of child abuse&quot;. 
<P>
A Toronto couple has been convicted of second-degree murder in
the April 1994 death of their six-month-old daughter. Court was
told Sara Podniewicz (pod'-nee-wits) suffered 24 broken bones,
including 16 ribs, that led to fatal pneumonia. 
<P>
Michael Podniewicz and Lisa Olsen, both crack addicts, face automatic
life sentences. The father had a record of child abuse... and
the family was on the books with social services.
<P>
The prosecutor in the case wants to know why the family wasn't
more closely monitored.
<HR>

<H3>QP Garden </H3>

<P>
More arrests at Queen's Park today... planting a vegetable garden
at the Ontario legislature landed six people in jail today. 
<P>
The members of Toronto Action for Social Change were charged with
mischief after rooting a few plants on the legislature lawn. Laura
Berman of Foodshare says gardens in city parks should be used
to grow vegetables instead of flowers since food banks don't provide
fresh produce. 
<P>
One of the men arrested called it a victory garden, saying the
Harris government is waging a war against the poor. 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Caseload </H3>

<P>
Queen's Park won't be taking &quot;no&quot; for an answer when
it comes to Workfare. Communities refusing to take part in the
province's work for welfare benefits program could see their social
services funding cut off. 
<P>
Some communities, including Ottawa, Kingston and Hamilton, are
digging in their heels, saying they won't participate in Workfare.
But a social services ministry official says it's &quot;a mandatory
program&quot; and municipalities who don't comply will be cut
off. 
<P>
Meanwhile, Ontario's welfare rolls are getting smaller. The province
reports the number of people on social assistance dropped for
the ninth month in a row in march. There are still 1.2-million
people in Ontario on welfare. But social services minister David
Tsubouchi says the number has dropped by 129-thousand since last
June. 
<HR>

<H3>CBC Deadline </H3>

<P>
In just over one week, seven thousand employees at the CBC could
be on strike. That's the strike deadline set by the corp.'s three
unions after a decision was made not to put the latest contract
offer to the workers. 
<P>
Canadian Media Guild spokesman Dan Oldfield says the unions hope
it won't come down to a strike, but he calls the public broadcaster's
last and best offer a &quot;folly.&quot; 
<P>
CBC president Perrin Beatty says he has no plans to lock employees
out. And acting heritage minister Lucienner Robillard says she
will not interfere in the bargaining process. 
<HR>

<H3>Chretien </H3>

<P>
Prime Minister Chretien told a big American and Canadian TV audience
this morning that Canada isn't likely to use force to keep Quebec
in confederation. 
<P>
He reiterated his assertion to ABC TV's &quot;Good Morning America&quot;
that he would not accept a vote of 50 per cent plus one from Quebeckers
to secede. But he said a clear vote on a clear question would
mean that Quebec could separate peacefully. 
<P>
Yesterday in the commons, Chretien stressed Quebec wouldn't be
allowed to leave Canada without agreement from the rest of the
country. 
<HR>

<H3>Boating Inquest </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris agrees with an inquest jury that it is about
time the province consider licensing boaters ... but he says it's
an issue complicated by age and native rights. 
<P>
An inquest into the boating deaths of two Mississauga teens has
resulted in recommendations for sweeping changes to recreational
boating. The coroner's jury would like to see licensing and mandatory
training for boat operators. 
<P>
The two Mississauga girls were killed on the Trent Severn Waterway
in 1991 when a personal watercraft crashed into their canoe. 
<P>
The jury says government should regulate boating and develop legislation
similar to the highway traffic act. Right now, there are few restrictions
on who can operate a vessel. 
<HR>

<H3>Bicycle Deaths </H3>

<P>
Two nine-year-old Newmarket boys are in critical condition in
hospital after the bike they were both on was struck by a car.

<P>
The boys were thrown five metres by the impact. They were rushed
to Toronto's Hospital for Sick Children with severe head injuries.

<P>
Witness Alan Tough says he saw the boys fly through the air..
police say the two boys were on the same bike and neither was
wearing a helmet. 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnian Return </H3>

<P>
The suffering of the children... that's what a group of Canadians
can't forget after visiting Bosnia ... when the bombs stopped
and the air cleared in Bosnia, thousands of orphaned and hungry
children were left wandering the streets. 
<P>
A Canadian funded orphanage recently opened in Bosnia. But the
St. Catharines based Bosnian Children Relief says so much more
needs to be done. 
<P>
Anyone wishing to help the children can send donations to Bosnian
Children Relief, 77 Pelham road, St. Catharines Ontario. L2S 1S3
.
<HR>

<H3>Bangladesh </H3>

<P>
Medical teams and soldiers have been sent in to care for thousands
of people injured in one of the deadliest tornadoes ever in Bangladesh.
They'll also search for hundreds of people who are still missing.

<P>
The death toll is around 500, although another 500 remain unaccounted
for in the wake of Monday's tornado. About 50-thousand people
were hurt as the system swept through 80 villages in the country's
northern plains. 
<HR>

<H3>Valuejet Update </H3>

<P>
There's new information on a possible cause of Saturday's crash
of a Valuejet DC9 in the Florida everglades that killed 109 people.

<P>
Investigators say plane suddenly lost power and plunged to earth
-- possibly due to an explosion in the cargo hold. Data from the
flight recorder is being analyzed by the US national transportation
safety board. 
<HR>

<H3>Valuejet Suits </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the first lawsuits have been filed in the wake of the
crash. the suits blame Valuejet and a Miami maintenance company
for alleged negligence. 
<P>
And one of Valuejet's DC9's returned to the Atlanta airport today
after controllers spotted a vapor coming from the jet. Officials
say nothing was wrong with the plane. But passengers were shaken
in light of Saturday's crash. 
<HR>

<H3>Whitby Crash </H3>

<P>
A 75-year-old Guelph man has died in an accident on the 401 Highway
in Whitby. 
<P>
Provincial police say the man was killed instantly when the motorhome
he was driving rear-ended a tractor trailer that had slowed because
of traffic. A passenger in the motorhome was treated for minor
injuries and released. The truck driver was not hurt. 
<HR>

<H3>Flying Cab </H3>

<P>
A police chase ended in a spectacular accident early today in
Toronto. 
<P>
Police say a taxi cab was stolen in the Queen and Ossington area
and was taken north. The driver lost control of the vehicle hitting
two parked cars. The cab flew through the air and bounced off
a third car before smashing into a tree. 
<P>
A man and woman in the taxi were injured. A 13-year-old girl in
the back seat was shaken up. 
<HR>

<H3>KKK </H3>

<P>
A man who had &quot;white supremacists rule&quot; and &quot;KKK&quot;
painted on a door on his front lawn faces weapons charges in Toronto.

<P>
Emergency task force officers raided the North York home last
night after a neighbor who complained about the racist slogans,
had a machine gun pointed at him. Police seized a machine gun,
two rifles, two handguns and a shotgun from the home. 
<P>
Fifty-three- year-old John Depledge faces numerous weapons charges.

<HR>

<H3>Car Hirings</H3>

<P>
A positive spin on things from the president of Ford Canada ...Mark
Hutchins says in spite of soft sales, the future is bright for
jobs in the automotive industry. 
<P>
Hutchins says industry-wide, 250-to-300 thousand people will be
hired in the next seven years or so. And he says in spite of a
major restructuring, hundreds of thousands of new recruits will
be needed to replace retiring autoworkers. 
<P>
Hutchins adds they will be looking for a new generation of skilled
autoworkers who can read, write and understand computers. 
<HR>

<H3>Census Mail </H3>

<P>
Did you forget to put your census form in the mail? Well, Census
staff say it's not too late. 
<P>
Forms were supposed to have been mailed back yesterday, but Stats
Canada says those who forgot can still do it now. Follow-up work
will be done for the rest of the month to ensure that all questionnaires
are returned. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

