<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, May 14, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OMA Newser 
<LI>Palladini Pothole 
<LI>UI Vote 
<LI>Charest Niagara 
<LI>Kevorkian Verdict 
<LI>School Bus Hijacking 
<LI>Value Jet Tues. 
<LI>Simpson Tues. 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OMA Newser </H3>

<P>
The future of your health care system in Ontario is not very bright.
That according to the Ontario Medical Association, who today launched
a public awareness campaign, warning taxpayers that continued
funding cuts to healthcare will create a critical situation for
patients by the turn of the century... Jamie West reports....

<P>
<I>Simultaneous news conferences were held across the province
by the Ontario Medical Association, their concern is that quality
patient care has continued to erode over the last decade, along
with healthcare funding. </I>
<P>
<I>Waiting lists of between 6 months and two years exist for orthopedic,
cardiac and cataract surgery. And the government continues to
demand more service for less money. </I>
<P>
<I>Doctors say funding shortfalls have forced them to become back
room dealers, begging and borrowing support services for their
patients that need them most ...while patients themselves overuse
a system that they've never had to pay for out of pocket ... the
annual health budget for Ontario is 3.8 billion dollars. </I>
<P>
<I>The OMA says that last year doctors had their wages clawed
back by 800 million dollars because of an overrun on service provided.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Palladini Pothole </H3>

<P>
Traffic slowed to a crawl on Highway 400 north of Toronto this
morning as transportation minister Al Palladini helped road crews
fill potholes. 
<P>
Palladini denies the shovel slinging was a publicity stunt, saying
the road-work has to be done. 
<P>
About 140-million dollars for road maintenance was included in
last week's provincial budget. But at least one trucker was not
impressed with the delay and gave Palladini an unfriendly salute.

<HR>

<H3>UI Vote </H3>

<P>
Thousands of unemployed Canadians will soon notice some changes
in unemployment insurance. 
<P>
The controversial UI reforms passed third and final reading in
the house of commons today are scheduled to go into effect July
first. 
<P>
The liberal bill aims to cut two-billion dollars from the unemployment
insurance system, and get people away from the idea that it's
an income supplement program. In fact, the legislation will even
change the program's name, to Employment Insurance. 
<P>
The bill has been a controversial one since its inception... even
some liberal MP's have voiced their opposition. 
<HR>

<H3>Charest Niagara </H3>

<P>
Federal Progressive Conservative party leader Jean Charest is
in Niagara today on a campaign to rebuild his party. 
<P>
The conservatives were nearly wiped out in the last election.
And while Charest wants to talk about the economy, the constitutional
showdown between Ottawa and Quebec is putting national unity back
on the agenda. 
<HR>

<H3>Kevorkian Verdict </H3>

<P>
Doctor Jack Kevorkian has been legally vindicated for a third
time. This afternoon, a Michigan jury acquitted the retired pathologist
of two counts of assisted suicide, on their third day of deliberations.

<P>
Kevorkian had attended the suicide of two seriously-ill, but possibly
not terminally ill, women, in 1991. He said the judicial system
has been trying to &quot;lynch&quot; him.. and called on the medical
profession to set-up guidelines for physician assisted suicide.

<HR>

<H3>School Bus Hijacking </H3>

<P>
In Salt Lake City, a school bus hijacking came to a sad end today,
with the death of the 15-year-old hijacker. 
<P>
Police say the young boy shot and wounded the bus driver, then
took the wheel and drove off, leading authorities on a high speed
chase. Authorities say the boy apparently died when he crashed
the bus into a house. 
<P>
They say the bus may have been moving at more than 50-miles per
hour on impact. No other students were on the bus during the chase
and subsequent crash. 
<HR>

<H3>Value Jet Tues. </H3>

<P>
Search crews continue to comb through the swamps of the Florida
everglades at the crash site of Value-jet flight 592. 
<P>
Remains of the 109 victims of Saturday's crash, continue to be
recovered... but officials have given up hope they'll find any
bodies intact. That will make identifying them difficult. 
<P>
About 30 divers, working in 15-to-20 minute shifts, are focusing
their efforts on finding the cockpit voice recorder.. the second
of the plane's so-called &quot;black boxes&quot;. 
<P>
Officials believe the flight data recorder that was retrieved
yesterday, will be useful in the investigation.
<HR>

<H3>Simpson Tues. </H3>

<P>
OJ Simpson takes his British road show to prestigious Oxford University
today, where he goes before a thousand members of the oxford debating
club to tell his story. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

