<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, May 3, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Herbal Ecstasy 
<LI>Blood Warning 
<LI>Alzheimer Water 
<LI>Human Rights Newser 
<LI>Gas Prices 
<LI>Twain 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Herbal Ecstasy </H3>

<P>
A warning tonight about a new fad that could have fatal consequences.
Police and health authorities say a product called herbal ecstasy,
available in stores throughout the region, is gaining wider use,
and could lead to tragedy. Jamie West reports. 
<P>
<I>Love and light, warmth and spiritual awareness...the promises
of a 100 percent natural, 100 percent legal and 100 percent potentially
fatal drug called herbal ecstasy. It's widely available among
dance club goers and ravers. </I>
<P>
<I>In the US the drug has been tied to as many as 15 deaths, young
people taking too much and in some cases mixing it with alcohol.
It's main ingredient ephedra, derived from the Chinese ma huang
herb. </I>
<P>
<I>Jay Dilio runs Spiritual Smoke a downtown Hamilton paraphernalia
shop. He brings herbal e in from the US through a Kitchener based
distributor</I>
<P>
<I>Double the recommended dose of four pills- exactly what killed
a US teenager while vacationing in Florida. Not true according
to this undercover vice and drug officer. </I>
<P>
<I>The US based manufacturer of herbal ecstasy, Global World Media
Corporation last year sold 300 million dollars worth of the product.
On the street it sells for a dime to a dollar a pill. </I>
<P>
<I>Despite warnings right on the package the US Food and Drug
Administration is now issuing it's own warning against using ephedra
products like herbal e. But Global World Media Corp. is already
one step ahead...and herbal ecstasy two is now on the market stateside
and heading for Canada...it's ephedra free ...but contains derivatives
from the Kava Kava plant...a plant with narcotic properties.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Blood Warning </H3>

<P>
Toronto's Hospital for Sick Children has sent out 525 letters
to parents whose children received blood products last year that
may be infected with a potentially deadly virus. 
<P>
The Canadian Red Cross says some lots of blood products were prepared
from blood donated by people who developed croytz-feld yah-kob
disease. The disease is a degenerative brain illness. Symptoms
can take up to 30 years to develop. 
<HR>

<H3>Alzheimer Water </H3>

<P>
Researchers are calling it the strongest evidence to date, that
high levels of aluminum in drinking water can cause Alzheimer's
disease. 
<P>
A University of Toronto study found that Ontario residents with
Alzheimer's are 1 to 2 times as likely to have lived in areas
where the drinking water contained more than 100 micrograms per
litre, of aluminum. That level is exceeded by many municipal water
plants, including two of the four plants in the Toronto area.

<P>
Aluminum is used by treatment plants across Canada to remove solid
wastes from drinking water. 
<HR>

<H3>Human Rights Newser </H3>

<P>
All eyes in the gay community across Canada will be on parliament
hill next week, for the free vote on the government's gay rights
bill. Although there seems to be enough support to pass the bill,
one lobby group isn't taking any chances. 
<P>
Meanwhile, 30 people protested in Parry Sound today, against Ottawa's
gay rights bill. Their anger was directed at the area's Liberal
MP who is in favor of the bill. The protesters say Andy Mitchell
doesn't represent the views of his rural constituents. 
<HR>

<H3>Gas Prices </H3>

<P>
We are being hosed, at the gas pumps. So say federal NDP members,
who will promote a gas boycott by consumers, beginning Monday.
It's true that prices are rising at the pumps, but as Scot Urquhart
reports ... major oil companies may not be entirely to blame:

<P>
<I>It's almost guaranteed to make Canadians grumble ... gas prices
climbing from the high fifties ... to 60 cents a litre and more.
How do consumers feel about it?</I>
<P>
<I>Richard O'Farrell of Imperial Oil says Americans are going
through gas, like water ... sucking the tanks dry across the continent,
and driving prices up. In addition, some major refineries had
to shut down for unscheduled maintenance... that during a harsh
winter, in which refiners used crude oil to make heating oil rather
than gas ... hence, a shortfall in the spring. Adding to the demand,
a rising number of gas-guzzling vehicles on the road, and higher
speed limits, across north America. </I>
<P>
<I>But if you still get the feeling that you're being gouged ...
the CAA says ... perhaps you should look at the government, instead
of the gas companies: and Dave Connolly says, prices may go even
higher, this summer: </I>
<P>
<I>So we asked the professionals how to save money on gas... you
can also use the self serve pump ... pay attention to what you're
pumping.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Twain </H3>

<P>
Country singer Shania Twain will return to her northern Ontario
roots on August 15th for a &quot;special day of recognition&quot;.
The mayor of Timmins, Vic Powers, says city council will honor
her by declaring the highway which runs through the city Shania
Twain Way. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

