<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 05/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, May 1, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Copps Quits 
<LI>Harris - Copps 
<LI>5.5 GST 
<LI>Gays Apology
<LI>Dying Mom-Cancer 
<LI>Van Gogh 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Copps Quits </H3>

<P>
The election race is on, in Hamilton east. Sheila Copps made it
official today: she resigned. The deputy prime minister was emotional
as she confronted the unspoken rule... that politicians, are only
as good as their word. Scot Urquhart reports: 
<P>
<I>It was the toughest decision of her career ... but Sheila Copps
says, she had to listen to the voice within.</I>
<P>
<I>Copps admitted, that despite public posturing to the contrary;
she struggled with her promise to resign; over the GST.  And although
there are signs that liberal strategist Milt Lewis may be right:
he concedes that the issue of the GST could be a campaign millstone.</I>
<P>
<I>There is really only one place to take the true political pulse
of Hamilton ... and the reaction from the donut shop, was mixed.
And that face in the crowd admits, she's learned a hard lesson,
about politics.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Harris - Copps </H3>

<P>
Ontario premier Mike Harris says Sheila Copps has done Canadian
politicians a favor. Harris says politicians who make campaign
commitments should &quot;resign or go back to the people&quot;
if they break their word after being elected. He says by resigning,
Copps has restored some integrity to the political process. 
<HR>

<H3>5.5 GST </H3>

<P>
And still more fall-out from the much hated goods and services
tax. Today an angry Ontario premier, Mike Harris accused the federal
government of bribery in compensating Newfoundland for merging
its sales tax with the GST. Harris says the GST should be uniform
across Canada. 
<HR>

<H3>Gays Apology</H3>

<P>
Reform MP Bob Ringma has apologized for comments he made about
homosexuals. Ringma said he would dismiss or &quot;move to the
back of the shop&quot; a gay or lesbian who might be offending
customers. But after coming under heavy fire, Ringma apologized,
saying he fully believes in equality for all. He then stepped
down as Reform party whip. 
<HR>

<H3>Dying Mom-Cancer </H3>

<P>
The young son of a woman who told police she was dying and had
been robbed of all her money, will receive a share of the money
donated by the public. 
<P>
Police and CIBC officials decided to conduct a poll to decide
what to do with the money. 10 percent of the 94 thousand dollars,
still in the fund, will be given to the woman's son. The remainder
will be distributed to programs for children and abused women,
kidney research and food banks, but the bulk will go to cancer
research. 
<HR>

<H3>Van Gogh </H3>

<P>
Money never seems to be scarce when it comes to the artworld.

<P>
A rare Vincent van Gogh cafe scene, led sales of impressionist
and modern paintings at Christie's Auction House last night. It
was the first major art auction of the spring season. Van Gogh's
&quot;Interieur d'un Restaurant&quot; sold for 10.3 million dollars.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

