<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, April 30, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>NDP - Tax Cut 
<LI>Harris - Polls 
<LI>Gays - Ringma
<LI>Tasmania Massacre 
<LI>North Ireland 
<LI>Coma Rape 
<LI>Obesity Seiden 
<LI>Spring? 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>NDP-Tax Cut </H3>

<P>
More than 100 thousand Ontario residents contacted by the NDP,
have returned postcards, criticizing the government's planned
tax cut. And according to party spokesmen, it's the biggest response
to a mailing the Ontario NDP has ever received and proves there
are serious reservations about the tax reduction. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris-Polls </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris maintains that his government's policies are
not anti women, even though two recent public opinion polls show
that the majority of women do not support the Harris government.
The premier blames the bad image on others and says his government
will have to do a better job of communicating its policies. 
<HR>

<H3>Gays - Ringma</H3>

<P>
Reform MP Bob Ringma's remark that he would fire &quot;or move
to the back of the shop&quot; a homosexual or member of an ethnic
minority, is being criticized. But there are indications Reformers
support him. 
<P>
Ringma told the Vancouver Sun if he were a businessman, he would
get rid of gay or black employees whose presence turned off bigoted
customers. Gay rights activist John Fisher is appalled. But other
Reform MP's defended Ringma's stance. 
<HR>

<H3>Tasmania Massacre</H3>

<P>
Australian authorities clamped tight security around the man charged
in connection with the massacre of 35 people, and warned an angry,
grieving community not to seek vengeance. 
<P>
Australian Martin Bryant, described as a wealthy and eccentric
loner, was charged at his hospital bedside with one count of murder.
But more charges will follow. 
<HR>

<H3>North Ireland </H3>

<P>
Canada's former top soldier may be called back into duty in the
northern Ireland peace process. The Irish government has suggested
retired General John de Chastelain be asked to chair decommissioning
talks to run parallel to all-party peace talks that are to start
June 10th. 
<P>
Ireland's deputy prime minister raised the prospect in a speech
to British and Irish parliamentarians last night. 
<HR>

<H3>Coma Rape </H3>

<P>
A baby born to a woman in a coma-like state is home with his grandmother.
The family's lawyer says the family plans to formalize details
of guardianship. 
<P>
The woman was raped while in a Rochester, New York, nursing home.
She gave birth last month. 
<HR>

<H3>Obesity Seiden </H3>

<P>
Americans fighting obesity have some new ammunition. Yesterday
the food and drug administration approved the first new anti-obesity
drug in 20 years. It alters the a brain chemical to make people
feel full. 
<P>
But critics say the drug can cause brain damage or a rare lung
disorder. The FDA concluded those risks were remote. But some
doctors have other concerns. 
<P>
The drug is scheduled to go on sale this summer. 
<HR>

<H3>Spring? </H3>

<P>
Death threats against Wiarton Willie ... weathermen in hiding
... snow in Timmins ... overcoats in April. There is only one
question on the minds of Ontario residents these days .... where
is spring? 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

