<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, April 29, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Dueling Polls 
<LI>Eves-Budget Date 
<LI>School Councils 
<LI>Cop Shot 
<LI>Tasmania Shooting 
<LI>Colby 
<LI>Reeve/Kidder 
<LI>Rent Opens 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Dueling Polls </H3>

<P>
Two new public opinion polls have been released... and they give
a conflicting picture of the support the Harris government is
getting from Ontarians. 
<P>
One poll has the Tories in the lead, while the other puts the
liberals out in front.
<HR>

<H3>Eves-Budget Date </H3>

<P>
The provincial budget will come down Tuesday May 7th. Finance
minister Ernie Eves made the announcement today in the legislature.

<P>
It's expected to contain a 14 percent provincial &quot;income
tax&quot; cut for Ontarians. Eves says he is determined to go
ahead with the tax cut, even though a survey shows most Ontarians
will save it not spend it. 
<HR>

<H3>School Councils </H3>

<P>
Are you fed up with the education your child is getting at school?
If you are, you're not alone. 
<P>
Thousands of parents across the province are demanding a chance
to have a greater say in what happens in the classroom... and
this summer, they'll get it. The Ministry of Education will institute
school councils, to begin work this fall. Scot Urquhart has more:

<P>
<I>We all talk about it ... but sometimes it seems that no one
does anything about it... education in Ontario has become a puzzle
where the pieces are increasingly hard to fit.</I>
<P>
<I>Marlene Gibson is a parent.... and she is not only for supporting
her local school, but getting other parents involved as well.
And that's where school councils come in. The province has decreed,
that every school shall have one by the end of June; comprised
of parents, that will advise and direct the local board of education
on how to implement provincial policies in neighbourhood schools.
But isn't that what publicly elected school trustees are for?</I>
<P>
<I>The new councils will piggy-back on the services of existing
parent groups, rather than replace them. Nominations for council
members close in public schools May 10th; elections will be held
in every school on the 23rd. Anyone interested in serving on a
school council, should contact their neighbourhood school principal.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Cop Shot </H3>

<P>
A mortally wounded Montreal police officer lay on the ground in
a pool of blood for about 15 minutes, before a passer-by attempted
first-aid and then used the police radio to call for help. 
<P>
Andr&eacute; Lalonde, who was two months away from retirement,
was shot when he stopped a vehicle because of a noisy muffler.
He died in hospital about two hours after the shooting. Officers
later found the suspect car. 
<P>
The slain officer was 51 years old and the father of two adult
children. 
<HR>

<H3>Tasmania Shooting </H3>

<P>
Australian police have identified the man they are holding in
the massacre of at least 34 people in Tasmania. 
<P>
Police sources say he's 28 year old Martin Bryant -- a man with
a history of psychological problems. Two of the 19 people wounded
are Canadians. 
<HR>

<H3>Colby </H3>

<P>
The former head of the CIA, William Colby, has been reported missing
from his vacation home in Maryland. 
<P>
Coast Guard divers and helicopters are searching for Colby who
has been missing since Saturday night. His canoe was found last
night .. about a quarter-mile from his home. 
<HR>

<H3>Reeve/Kidder </H3>

<P>
Actor Christopher Reeve has offered his &quot;Superman&quot; co-star,
Margot Kidder, a job. The New York Post says Reeve called Kidder
last week, to wish her well after hearing how she had suffered
a breakdown in Los Angeles. 
<P>
Reeve, who was paralyzed in a riding accident last year, said
if his health permits, he'd like the Canadian-born actress to
join him in a production of the two-character play &quot;Love
Letters.&quot; 
<HR>

<H3>Rent Opens </H3>

<P>
Much excitement in New York tonight....&quot;Rent&quot; opens
on Broadway. The modest musical was quietly launched off-Broadway
in February, and created a sensation. It became the show to see.
Critics were unanimous in their praise ....the public responded
enthusiastically. &quot;Rent&quot; became an immediate hit. 
<P>
Labeled as the breakthrough musical of the 90's, the rock musical
is generating the kind of excitement &quot;Hair&quot; and &quot;A
Chorus Line&quot; did in their time. Inspired by Puccini's &quot;La
Boheme,&quot; &quot;Rent&quot; is a joyous and turbulent musical
that celebrates a community of young east villagers as they struggle
with the soaring hopes and tough realities of today's New York.

<P>
Even before its Broadway opening tonight, &quot;Rent&quot; was
awarded the ultimate accolade ....winning the 1996 Pulitzer Prize
for drama. 
<P>
Unfortunately, Jonathan Larson, the show's 35-year-old composer,
lyricist and librettist was never aware of the show's impact.
He died of an aortic aneurysm following the final dress rehearsal.

<P>
Entertainment reporter Alex Reynolds says we'll see the show in
Toronto this fall. David and Ed Mirvish today announced they have
secured the Canadian rights to the musical. 
<P>
The show, which Larson seven years to create, has become his legacy.
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

