<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, April 23, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>GST Merger 
<LI>Tsubouchi 
<LI>Principals-Cuts 
<LI>Prince 
<LI>The Monarchy 
<LI>Chernobyl 
<LI>Dudayev Dead? 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>GST Merger </H3>

<P>
Ontario premier Mike Harris says he rejects the idea of federal
dollars being used to pay for sales tax harmonization in Atlantic
Canada. 
<P>
The plan calls for the merger of the federal provincial sales
tax systems in Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and Newfoundland into
one national tax. The rate will be 15 percent in the three provinces,
down from current combined rates. 
<P>
As part of the plan, the federal government will pay the three
Atlantic provinces 961 million dollars over four years to make
up for losses of provincial revenue. Harris suggests that amounts
to bribing the three provinces with tax money from other provinces,
and he says &quot;that's wrong&quot;. 
<P>
The new tax takes effect April first 1997. All services covered
by the GST before the changes will be subject to the new tax.

<HR>

<H3>Tsubouchi </H3>

<P>
It has yet to result in a single fraud conviction. But social
services minister David Tsubouchi says Ontario's welfare snitch-
-line will soon pay off. 
<P>
The telephone hotline has taken 15-thousand calls since it opened
last October. Tsubouchi says suspected fraud cases must be investigated
and processed through the courts -- all of which takes time. 
<P>
The snitch line has cost 170-thousand dollars so far, but Tsubouchi
estimates it will eventually save taxpayers about 25-million dollars
a year. 
<HR>

<H3>Principals Cuts </H3>

<P>
A group of high school principals from across Ontario, are warning
parents that the Harris governments plans to reform the education
system, could cause real damage to Ontario students. 
<P>
The principals want the government to slow down and engage in
more consultation. 
<HR>

<H3>Prince</H3>

<P>
Prince Charles is visiting Canada for the first time in five years.
He arrived in Ottawa today aboard a Canadian forces jet. 
<P>
The last time he visited Canada he was accompanied by his two
sons and the Princess of Wales. 
<P>
His royal highness will visit Hamilton Friday, to attend the official
opening of the Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum of which he is
the patron. 
<HR>

<H3>The Monarchy </H3>

<P>
And while the Prince enjoys his week long visit to Canada, the
Ontario wing of the Federal Liberal party will be asked this weekend
to vote on a policy that would abolish the British monarch as
Canada's head of state. 
<P>
The vote will be held at the wing's annual general meeting in
Windsor beginning Friday. Similar debate over the future of the
monarchy is taking place on both sides of the Atlantic.
<HR>

<H3>Chernobyl </H3>

<P>
Firefighters say they've doused a large fire near the Chernobyl
nuclear plant in Ukraine. Officials disagree over how much radioactive
dust the fire might have sent into the air. 
<P>
The world's worst commercial nuclear disaster occurred at the
Chernobyl plant ten years ago this week. 
<HR>

<H3>Dudayev Dead? </H3>

<P>
It's unclear whether Chechen rebel leader zhoh-car Dudayev is
alive or dead. The itar-tass news agency says Dudayev was killed
in a missile attack this week in Chechnya. But the independent
Interfax news agency said that report is untrue. 
<P>
Interfax quotes an aide to Dudayev as saying the Chechen leader
is alive and working as usual. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

