<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, April 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Nunziata Dumped 
<LI>Gray Cancer 
<LI>Snobelen 
<LI>Workfare Plan 
<LI>Pickering Nuclear 
<LI>Motts-Grape Growers 
<LI>Homolka Parole 
<LI>Pavarotti-Toronto 
<LI>Bombeck Obit 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Nunziata Dumped </H3>

<P>
The Liberals have booted one Toronto MP out of caucus and a second
has quit. 
<P>
John Nunziata ran afoul of party brass by voting against the budget,
in effect, casting a vote of non-confidence in the government.
Liberal whip Don Boudria says governments stand or fall on whether
they have the confidence of the commons on budgetary matters.
And that by voting against the budget, Nunziata has shown he no
longer supports his government. 
<P>
An aide says Nunziata will take a few days to consider his political
future, but he is expected to sit as an independent in the house
of commons. His colleague, Dennis Mills, says he will join Nunziata
in sitting with the independents. 
<HR>

<H3>Gray Cancer </H3>

<P>
Solicitor General Herb Gray has been diagnosed with throat cancer.
A statement from his office says the 64 year old veteran Ontario
MP had tests at an Ottawa hospital that turned up small cell carcinoma
of the esophagus. 
<P>
While he's undergoing treatment, he'll be cutting back on his
activities as solicitor general, government house leader, and
liberal MP for Windsor west. 
<HR>

<H3>Snobelen </H3>

<P>
Education Minister John Snobelen says the Tory caucus is &quot;solidly
behind&quot; his efforts to reform the province's education system.
That's despite criticism from two backbenchers. 
<P>
Tory MPP Bill Murdoch told a radio station, that Snobelen &quot;doesn't
know what he's doing.&quot; And under pressure from students,
Quinte MPP Doug Rollins acknowledged the government lied when
it said the cuts wouldn't hurt the classroom. 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare Plan </H3>

<P>
One of premier Mike Harris's election promises was to devise a
system that would force welfare recipients to work for their money.
And while the Tories continue to iron out the wrinkles, a group
of welfare recipients in the Peterborough area, have taken the
bull by the horns and devised their own Workfare program... a
program they claim does work. 
<HR>

<H3>Pickering Nuclear </H3>

<P>
Energy Minister Brenda Elliott says the Bruce and Darlington nuclear
plants are not affected by a shutdown of reactors at the Pickering
Power Station. 
<P>
Ontario Hydro says the operating systems at those plants are different
than the one that caused problems last week at Pickering. Hydro
shut down all eight reactors at Pickering after detecting a flaw
in a secondary safety system. 
<P>
Greenpeace says the shutdown was intentionally delayed to avoid
embarrassing the Prime Minister who has been in Romania promoting
Candu technology.
<HR>

<H3>Motts-Grape Growers </H3>

<P>
And then, ... there were none. Ontario's one and only grape juice
processing plant, is closing down. That will not only put nearly
200 people in St. Catharines out of work but as Scot Urquhart
reports, it's going to put a big squeeze on the Ontario grape
industry, as well: 
<P>
<I>It was only one contract .. but it was a big one ... for Cadbury
Beverages in St. Catharines.  There is no indication why the Ocean
Spray contract was lost ... but it means that 170 workers at this
plant will be out of a job, at the end of the year. </I>
<P>
<I>They are represented by the United Food and Commercial Workers
.... our calls to the union, were not returned. But plant employees,
are not the only ones affected ... this plant is the only grape
juice processing plant, in Ontario. Fully one third of all grapes
grown in Niagara ... were handled here. That means a big hit ...
for grape growers, too.</I>
<P>
<I>But even though the closure may force some of his growers into
bankruptcy; John Neufeld recognizes that the Cadbury decision,
was strictly business: and not all grape growers, were devastated
by the news: so much so, that Tom Greensides isn't going to cut
back on his juice grapes ... he's going to put more in.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Homolka Parole </H3>

<P>
Corrections Canada says a leaked letter written to convicted killer
Karla Homolka may have breached prison security. 
<P>
Spokesman Ron Fairley says if the letter was taken from Homolka's
cell, the warden will investigate the theft. The letter, written
by Homolka's sister Lori, indicates Karla may apply for an escorted
temporary absence pass from the Kingston prison for women. 
<P>
Lori suggests that Karla should dye her hair and return to St.
Catharines. She says people are stupid and even if they bumped
into her, no one would know who she was. 
<HR>

<H3>Pavarotti-Toronto </H3>

<P>
The opera super singers are coming to Canada. It was announced
today the three tenors will perform in Toronto next year ....their
only north American appearance.
<P>
Tickets, ranging in price from 25 to four hundred and 50 dollars,
go on sale in May. Alex Reynolds reports. 
<P>
<I>Luciano Pavarotti, Placido Domingo and Jose Carreras will appear
January 4th, 1997, at the SkyDome. </I>
<P>
<I>The rotund tenor made a whirlwind 40 minute stop at Pearson
airport to launch the venture. He says television and large stadiums
are reaching the masses. </I>
<P>
<I>These massive concerts are winning fans for opera. I asked
the maestro about the next generation of tenors, particularly
the spectacular Roberto Alagna. </I>
<P>
<I>Sports impresario Peter Pocklington is co-producing the SkyDome
sing-in. So the three tenors juggernaut continues ....Pavarotti,
Domingo and Carreras bring their singing act to Toronto...in what
should be the biggest concert this country has ever seen.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Bombeck Obit </H3>

<P>
Housewife turned columnist Erma Bombeck has died. The woman who
poked gentle fun at life in the suburbs passed away today at a
San Francisco hospital. 
<P>
Bombeck had been diagnosed with breast cancer in 1992 and underwent
a mastectomy. Shortly afterwards she received a kidney transplant
after her kidneys began to fail. Erma Bombeck was 69. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

