<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, April 17, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Mulroney 
<LI>Liquor Laws 
<LI>Harris-Benefits 
<LI>Student Demo 
<LI>Tax Reform 
<LI>Lebanon Update 
<LI>Quickie Divorce
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Mulroney </H3>

<P>
Brian Mulroney says an allegation that he was involved in an airbus
kickback scheme was the &quot;most devastating&quot; experience
he has ever faced. 
<P>
The former prime minister made the comment during testimony at
a pre-trial hearing in his 50 million dollar libel lawsuit against
the Justice Department and RCMP. 
<P>
Under oath, he called the allegations grotesque lies and monstrous
falsehoods. He also accused the government of fascism for not
sharing its evidence with him when he first sought it last November.

<P>
Although they felt he was sometimes out of line, government lawyers
said they had no objections to Mulroney's tirade. 
<HR>

<H3>Liquor Laws </H3>

<P>
Starting May first, bars in Ontario will be allowed to stay open
until 2 a.m. That's an hour later than current regulations permit.

<P>
Golfers will also have more opportunity for a nip on the back
nine. The sale and consumption of liquor will be allowed on golf
courses if the course already has a liquor licence and if they
apply for a licence amendment. 
<P>
The changes in drinking laws are part of a modernization movement
according to the Tory government 
<HR>

<H3>Harris-Benefits </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says there is nothing wrong with the Conservative
party paying his expenses. 
<P>
According to the Globe and Mail, those expenses include a golf
club membership, a tuxedo and dry cleaning bills. 
<HR>

<H3>Student Demo </H3>

<P>
The big yellow protest found its way to Queen's Park today. 300
students marched to the Ontario Legislature to deliver a huge
yellow banner. A banner with thousands of names on it ..calling
on Premier Mike Harris to reverse the cutbacks to education spending.

<P>
The Conservatives are cutting one billion dollars in funding to
schools, colleges and universities. 
<P>
In contrast to a violent demonstration by students earlier this
year....this one was peaceful. 
<HR>

<H3>Tax Reform </H3>

<P>
Two of the province's largest taxpayers organizations are calling
on the Harris government to bring in property tax reform based
on unit assessment for the whole province. 
<P>
Unit value assessment is based on physical measurement only ..such
as square footage of the buildings and the size of the lot. This
differs from market value assessment which is based on real estate
prices which vary from year to year. 
<P>
Both the Ontario Taxpayers Federation and the Confederation of
Ratepayers association say the big plus for unit assessment is
stability. 
<HR>

<H3>Lebanon Update </H3>

<P>
In world news tonight, an Israeli jet attacked villages near the
southern Lebanon port of Tyre today... this after Hezbollah guerrillas
fired three salvos of rockets onto northern Israel. 
<HR>

<H3>Quickie Divorce </H3>

<P>
A judge in London today took the first step towards granting a
divorce for Britain's Prince Andrew and the Duchess of York. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

