<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, April 16, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Cheese Stink 
<LI>Credit Cards 
<LI>Homolka Petition 
<LI>Shooting Inquest 
<LI>Brantford Diabetic 
<LI>Speed Limits 
<LI>Hospital Demo 
<LI>Welfare Cases 
<LI>Ontario-Privatization
<LI>Day of Protest 
<LI>Harris Quebec
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Cheese Stink </H3>

<P>
There could be more holes in this story; than you'd find in any
imported cheese. Ottawa wants to bring in tough health regulations
that might ban some types of foreign cheese from entering the
country, including parmesan cheese. 
<P>
But as Scot Urquhart reports; the proposals may have more to do
with producing healthy profits for Canadian manufacturers; than
they do with protecting the health of Canadians: 
<P>
<I>Ottawa says, this stuff could kill you ... but even health
minister Dave Dingwall admits his bureaucrats cannot site even
one specific instance ... in which someone got sick from eating
unpasturized cheese. </I>
<P>
<I>Nevertheless ... Health Canada is considering new regulations
that would take a big slice out of foreign cheese imports, by
banning cheeses made from unpasturized milk. Cheeses like French
brie; and Italian parmesan.</I>
<P>
<I>In the kitchens of La Cantina ... one of Hamilton's best Italian
restaurants ... parmesan is a staple more common than salt. Owner
Tina Grande says they could survive without Italian imports but
it wouldn't be the same.</I>
<P>
<I>And without one documented case of illness there is a question
of whether the proposed federal regulations are really designed
to protect the health of consumers or instead, to duck around
international GATT agreements by using a so-called health issue,
to put up a trade barrier against foreign imports. </I>
<P>
<I>You know, oddly enough... the new government regulations were
drafted after consultation with Agriculture Canada, the National
Dairy Council of Canada, and the Dairy Farmers of Canada. </I>
<P>
<I>Anyone other than those interested parties who may wish to
comment on the issue should contact Health Canada, before the
end of May. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Credit Cards </H3>

<P>
You probably didn't need a government report to tell you this
... but Canadians are paying too much interest on their credit
cards. 
<P>
The report blames the major banks for dragging their feet when
it comes to passing on lower rates... right now.. the cards charge
up to twelve percentage points higher than the prime.. 
<HR>

<H3>Homolka Petition </H3>

<P>
In Ottawa today a committee demanded that the federal government
hold an inquiry into Karla Homolka's plea bargain. 
<P>
Homolka got twelve years for her role in the deaths of Kristen
French and Leslie Mahaffy in exchange for her testimony at the
first degree murder trial of her ex husband Paul Bernardo. 
<P>
The committee says there is no way Homolka should get off so lightly
for her part in the girls murders. 
<HR>

<H3>Shooting Inquest </H3>

<P>
An inquest will be held into the mass murder in Vernon, BC 
<P>
BC's Attorney General says the enormity of the tragedy requires
the most thorough scrutiny possible. He says an inquest jury will
be able to examine every aspect of the killings of nine members
of the Gakhal and Saran families. They were shot on Good Friday
by Mark Chahal, the estranged husband of one of the victims, who
then took his own life. 
<P>
The RCMP is also holding an internal investigation of how the
mounties handled events that led to the shooting. 
<HR>

<H3>Brantford Diabetic </H3>

<P>
Fallout today after a man charged in a quadruple fatal car crash
back in 1994 walked away from court with his licence intact. 
<P>
The fiery accident happened near Brantford... Gordon Wood was
charged with four counts of dangerous driving causing death. Yesterday
those charges were dropped. 
<P>
The mother of one of the four people killed is outraged. Connie
Dickerson of Hamilton says Wood should not be allowed to drive.
The Canadian Diabetes Association has been drawn into the controversy
and says that Wood's medical condition is rare, and doesn't mean
diabetics in general should be taken off the road. 
<HR>

<H3>Speed Limits</H3>

<P>
It appears the drive to raise speed limits on major Ontario highways
has shifted into low gear. 
<P>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman says he's not enthusiastic about
raising the maximum limit for cars to 120-kilometres an hour.
Runciman is in charge of the OPP which polices the 400-series
highways. 
<P>
However, transportation minister Al Palladini says the government
is still considering the higher speed limit and insists he's not
at odds with his cabinet colleague on the issue. Palladini says
he's confident any proposal will make safety a priority. 
<P>
But, Runciman says he's steadfastly opposed to any move to raise
speed limits in urban areas. 
<HR>

<H3>Hospital Demo </H3>

<P>
Hospital workers hit the picket lines today in Toronto, to protest
layoff notices to some 840 employees at Toronto Hospital. 
<P>
The Canadian Union of Public Employees who represents the workers
says they must unite to fight cutbacks that are happening at all
hospitals across the province. 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Cases </H3>

<P>
The number of welfare cases in Ontario has dropped for the eighth
straight month. 
<P>
Statistics for February show another 36-hundred people stopped
collecting welfare. The Harris government has tightened eligibility
and slashed benefits to trim welfare costs. 
<HR>

<H3>Ontario-Privatization</H3>

<P>
Any provincial agencies sold to the private sector are expected
to face a tough approval process. 
<P>
A published report indicates the province will designate a privatization
minister...and specifics of the move to sell off government agencies
will be included in the may budget. 
<P>
Among provincial assets or services up for privatization are TVOntario,
the LCBO, parts of Ontario Hydro, road maintenance operations
and more than 80-thousand public housing units. 
<HR>

<H3>Day of Protest </H3>

<P>
Back in February, labour shut down the city of Hamilton for two
days to protest the Harris government's cutbacks. 
<P>
Well another day of protest is coming up... and Waterloo is the
target... with public transit, garbage pickup, and recreational
facilities being affected. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris Quebec</H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says politicians should not get hung up over
language in defining Quebec's role in Canada. 
<P>
Prime Minister Chretien says he is ready to replace distinct society
with a new proposal to call Quebec the &quot;main home&quot; of
French language and culture, in north America. 
<P>
Quebec Deputy Premier Bernard Landry calls the proposal ridiculous
and meaningless. But Ontario's Premier Harris applauds the proposal.
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

