<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, April 15, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Pension Reform 
<LI>Moms - OSAP 
<LI>Dying Mom 
<LI>Casino Follow 
<LI>Contraception 
<LI>Somalia 
<LI>Lebanon Monday 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Pension Reform </H3>

<P>
Is the Canada Pension Plan going broke? Will we have to pay an
arm and a leg to save it? Those are just two of the many questions
Canadians want answered by our federal politicians. 
<HR>

<H3>Moms - OSAP </H3>

<P>
Critics of an Ontario government plan to push college and university
students off welfare... say it will backfire. Within the next
two years, the Tories want single parents and married couples
attending school who are currently on social assistance to apply
for student loans. 
<P>
Some student groups fear that may prevent some welfare recipients
from getting a better education to get off the system. Annette
Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>June O'Raw wants to wash her hands of the welfare system. A
single mom, she's been supported the last seven years by family
benefits. Last month, she started making arrangements for a better
life, by applying to a hairdressing school. </I>
<P>
<I>Stopped by an Ontario government announcement last week that
single moms on assistance who want to go to school would have
to get off welfare, and have their schooling funded through OSAP
like everyone else. </I>
<P>
<I>Student groups warn that under the government's new plan it
will be harder for those who want to get out of the welfare trap
to help themselves. </I>
<P>
<I>June O'Raw doesn't plan to spend nearly that much on her education,
but she finds the waiting unacceptable. She doesn't want to start
her 10 month course in May, only to find out part way through
her benefits are gone. </I>
<P>
<I>O'Raw says she understands the mess Ontario is in, but urges
the Tory government to stop hitting the ones who are trying to
get off the system. The government will implement its plan to
get students off welfare in the next two years.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Dying Mom </H3>

<P>
A public opinion poll will determine which charities get more
than 112 thousand dollars collected for a Toronto mother who was
reported to be dying of cancer. 
<P>
Bank officials say money donated to Donna Mercier will be handed
to charities chosen in a poll of 400 Toronto area residents. Some
money may go to her seven year old son. 
<P>
Police say Mercier lied to them last week, when she reported her
purse had been snatched. Pollster Angus Reid has offered to conduct
the survey for free. 
<HR>

<H3>Casino Follow </H3>

<P>
What's old is new again. That's the case in Niagara Falls; where
residents have known for two years that eventually they would
hear the official announcement that finally came today. 
<P>
The province of Ontario will build a gaming casino in the city.
<HR>

<H3>Contraception </H3>

<P>
The Canadian Abortion Rights Action League says as many as half
the number of abortions performed in this country could be prevented,
if women were more aware of a safe, and cheaper alternative. 
<P>
&quot;CARAL&quot; is calling on governments and pharmaceutical
companies to do more to educate doctors and the public about the
availability of emergency contraceptives, better known as the
morning-after pill. Doctors say emergency contraceptives are highly-effective
in averting unintended pregnancies. 
<HR>

<H3>Somalia </H3>

<P>
The Canadian Forces has unearthed some missing documents, forcing
an adjournment of the Somalia inquiry until Friday. 
<P>
Lawyers say they need time to examine the six boxes of new documents,
a computer data disk and some crucial Canadian airborne regiment
files that had gone missing. Some of those missing logs date back
to 1993, during Canada's mission to Somalia. 
<P>
They were found in a filing cabinet at CFB Petawawa, home base
of the Canadian Airborne Regiment, after last week's cross country
defence department search. 
<HR>

<H3>Lebanon Monday</H3>

<P>
In world news tonight, another fiery day in southern Lebanon.

<P>
Israeli aircraft continued to bomb Hezbollah targets in Beirut
and southern Lebanon while Hezbollah guerrillas retaliated by
sending more rockets crashing down on Northern Israel. 
<P>
This is the fifth straight day Israel has attacked Lebanon and
although there is no word on casualties from today's attacks,
28 people are reported dead since the fighting began last week.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

