<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, April 12, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Dying Mom 
<LI>Giving 
<LI>Guelph Riot 
<LI>Tory Ads 
<LI>Youth Jobs 
<LI>Food and Wine Expo 
<LI>Cat Reunion 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Dying Mom </H3>

<P>
Police in Toronto say a woman whose tale of woe prompted the public
to donate more than 100 thousand dollars never had her purse stolen.
But they still believe Donna Mercier is very ill, and deserves
the public's sympathy. 
<P>
Mercier has been charged with public mischief, and police say
they are now consulting with lawyers about what to do with the
money donated to help her and her son. They also say despite the
charge they believe the young mother is terminally ill. 
<HR>

<H3>Giving </H3>

<P>
There is some concern, meanwhile, among those entrusted with raising
funds for major charities, that this incident could undermine
the generosity of contributors. 
<P>
But there is also optimism at both the United Way and the Chedoke
McMaster Hospital Foundation, that those who give will now see
the value of contributing to reputable charities. Anthony Pooley
reports. 
<P>
<I>The outpouring of generosity for Donna Mercier and her son...
with contributions from both Canada and the United States underscores
the willingness of people to help one another... especially those
in dire need. </I>
<P>
<I>But when the 27-year- old woman's story turned out to be highly
questionable... those who gave could well have developed an aversion
to giving.</I>
<P>
<I>At the United Way of Burlington and Hamilton- Wentworth...
fund -raiser Barry English has to oversee a drive to raise more
than 6 million dollars a year... money that community based agencies
need to pay for a variety of charitable endeavors. </I>
<P>
<I>Ursula Evans is in charge of fund-raising for the Chedoke-
McMaster Hospital Foundation... another major organization that
seeks millions each year in financial donations from the community...
notably through the annual Mother's Day Telethon on channel 11.
She sees the outcome of the Donna Mercier incident a little more
positively. </I>
<P>
<I>But in the end, it could well be the reputable charities that
benefit. For it is clear that donated money ends up being used
in the way contributors expect it to be. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Guelph Riot </H3>

<P>
Ontario Tory supporters were given a rough ride as they gathered
for a fundraising dinner in Guelph last night. 
<P>
A police officer was punched in the head and three people were
arrested when rowdy protesters confronted the Tories as they gathered
for the 100 dollar a plate dinner. The guest speaker, Finance
Minister Ernie Eves, avoided the crowd by slipping in a side door.
Two of those arrested face assault and trespassing charges, the
third was let go. 
<HR>

<H3>Tory Ads </H3>

<P>
The Harris government wants to make sure the public gets the right
message about the 1.6 billion dollars in spending cuts, announced
yesterday. 
<P>
Today government ads ran on radio and in major newspapers across
Ontario, putting a positive spin on the cuts and layoffs of government
workers.
<HR>

<H3>Youth Jobs </H3>

<P>
Heritage Minister and Deputy Prime Minister Sheila Copps chose
her hometown to announce a new initiative to create jobs for students.

<P>
At Mohawk College today, Copps said another ten million dollars
will be added to the pot for 350 students to work at national
parks and historical sites across Canada. Museums, libraries and
other cultural institutions will also be offered funding to create
800 new positions. Many will involve opportunities for young people
to travel to other parts of the country to work in another language.

<P>
Copps says the private sector will also be encouraged to do more
to create jobs for youth. 
<HR>

<H3>Food and Wine </H3>

<P>
The perfect pairing of wine and food is a combination that draws
crowds to shows and conventions every spring. Right now the First
Wine and Food Expo in Hamilton is showcasing the wines of the
Niagara region. Kathy Renwald reports. 
<P>
<I>Gone are the days of pairing wine just with cheese. Now the
foods are exotic as the wines are award winners.</I>
<P>
<I>At the Wine and Food Expo at the Hamilton Convention Centre
you can hit the books about wine or pick the hands on route. And
when your palate is perplexed.. then its time for a cleansing
ale. </I>
<P>
<I>Micro brewery products have about 5 per cent of the beer market.
Along with beer there are things to crunch on... lots of lectures
about low fat here.. and the healthful aspects of wine. </I>
<P>
<I>The Food and Wine Expo continues through Sunday at the Convention
Centre.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Cat Reunion </H3>

<P>
It's been almost two weeks since Scarlett the cat, rescued her
five kittens from a fiery building in New York City. 
<P>
Now the kittens, who have been in foster care for the past week,
have been reunited with their heroic mom. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

