<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, April 10, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Salaries-Pensions 
<LI>Johnson-Cuts 
<LI>Dying Mom Follow 
<LI>Adoptions 
<LI>30-Hour Week 
<LI>Canadian Killed 
<LI>Tyson Sex 
<LI>Royal Media Spat 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Salaries-Pensions</H3>

<P>
Members of the Ontario Legislature are getting a pay cut. 
<P>
Finance Minister Ernie Eves says MPP's will lose their tax-free
allowances and benefits under legislation introduced today. Also
gone is the gold-plated pension plan. 
<HR>

<H3>Johnson-Cuts</H3>

<P>
Tomorrow the Harris government will outline how it expects to
chop between 4- and 5-and-a-half billion dollars in government
spending, over the next fiscal year. 
<P>
Chairman of the Management Board, Dave Johnson, says the long-overdue
fiscal restructuring, will be aimed at delivering core services
at a lower cost. And he says the government may get out of the
delivery of some services, altogether. 
<P>
Johnson is expected to announce the final number of government
workers to be cut very soon. Some 15-hundred have already received
their notices. At least 13-thousand are expected to be let go.

<HR>

<H3>Dying Mom Follow </H3>

<P>
Metro Toronto police are checking out the story of a woman whose
reported purse snatching and battle with cancer prompted an outpouring
of sympathy and cash. 
<P>
So far more than 112 thousand dollars has poured in for the woman,
who said she was dying, and for her young son. 
<P>
Detective Sergeant John Sillotts says police are now following
up on calls from people who have discredited the woman. He says
they will hold onto the money, until they are sure the woman's
story is true. 
<HR>

<H3>Adoptions </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says his government can't be blamed for the
woes of families on welfare. 
<P>
A Simcoe County Children's Aid Society worker says some families
are considering giving their kids up for adoption because of cuts
in welfare support. 
<P>
Though the Premier has doubts about the story, Finance Minister
Ernie Eves indicated some action might be taken. 
<HR>

<H3>30-Hour Week </H3>

<P>
Less work for some, more work for all ... and a chance to share
the wealth more evenly. That's the idea behind the 30 hour work
week. 
<P>
Toronto Mayor Barbara Hall has kicked off a debate on the issue;
that has angered the business community; encouraged social advocates;
and sent economists scrambling to their computers. Scot Urquhart
has more: 
<P>
<I>Toronto Mayor Barbara Hall knows how hard it can be, to help
.... but although she was harangued by the poor ... Hall has more
than nickels and dimes on her mind ... when it comes to ways to
help. she has floated the idea of a 30 hour work week; as a way
of spreading the work around, and sharing the wealth in Canadian
society. </I>
<P>
<I>But the Hall proposal has been panned by business; and McMaster
University economist Alan Harrison says; the so-called gap between
rich and poor, may in fact be little more than a sliver. </I>
<P>
<I>Labour unions on the other hand, say Hall is right on the mark.
 From the steelworkers point of view, corporate Canada can afford
to be a little more generous. </I>
<P>
<I>But Harrison sees an economic price; that social advocates
may not ... employment costs, payroll costs, benefits, payroll
taxes ... all of them make it very expensive to add a worker to
a company ... and in this area Harrison says, various levels of
government could help. </I>
<P>
<I>It seems then, that no matter how you look at it; when it comes
to the 30 hour work week ... someone, somewhere, will have to
pay.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Canadian Killed </H3>

<P>
A man shot while vacationing in Trinidad, is the fifth Canadian
murdered on the Caribbean island in the last two years. 
<P>
Police say 27 year old Kurt Hosein of Thornhill, Ontario, was
shot while sitting in a car with his cousin, outside a relative's
home in a suburb of port of Spain Sunday night. A newspaper reporter
says a stolen car the assailant is believed to have used, has
been found. Police are checking it for forensic evidence. 
<HR>

<H3>Tyson Sex </H3>

<P>
Boxer Mike Tyson could be facing more legal problems. Police are
investigating a woman's complaint of sexual battery against Tyson,
stemming from an alleged incident at a Chicago nightclub. 
<P>
Tyson has not been charged, but the owner of the club is already
speaking up in his defence. 
<HR>

<H3>Royal Media Spat </H3>

<P>
For the first time since the days when kings could chop off the
heads of those who displeased them, Britain's royal family is
taking up arms against intrusions, hounding, and teasing by the
media. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

