<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, April 9, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Fyke Killer 
<LI>Victim Evng
<LI>COPE-Booze 
<LI>Budget Cuts 
<LI>Somalia Document 
<LI>Parole 
<LI>Oklahoma Bombing 
<LI>Chernobyl Anniversary 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Fyke Killer </H3>

<P>
Although a mentally disabled teenager has already confessed to
the murder of a Belleville high school student, police in Daytona
Beach Florida, now say they have the real killer. 
<P>
17 year old John Rainey turned himself in to police and was charged
today with the first degree murder of Mark Fyke. 
<P>
Fyke was killed in a botched robbery during spring break. Police
had been holding 18 year old Donald Shoup who turned himself in
after the shooting. A Daytona beach newspaper says investigators
knew a short time later that Shoup was not the killer. 
<HR>

<H3>Victim Evng</H3>

<P>
In Toronto, a dying mother quietly thanked hundreds of generous
strangers today, ... people who gave her money and gifts after
she was robbed on a city street. 
<P>
Last week, the 27 year old woman had her purse snatched while
walking in Toronto. She lost a small amount of cash, her identification
and health card and a bus ticket to Winnipeg, where her son may
be sent to live when she dies. 
<P>
Soon after her plight became public, donations from across Canada
began to pour in, but now the woman says enough is enough. The
young mother who has cancer, has asked that an account which has
collected over 70 thousand dollars, be closed, and that help stop
pouring in. 
<P>
The 27 year old woman, asked that her identity remain secret,
fearing an abusive partner. 
<HR>

<H3>COPE-Booze </H3>

<P>
A group of food retailers uncorked an old debate today, urging
the province to allow supermarkets and corner stores to sell beer
and wine. 
<P>
The Coalition for Ontario Private Enterprise says stores that
handle alcohol could be regulated with a strict series of rules
ensuring that no one under age is sold a bottle. The organization
even released draft legislation on how the idea could come about.

<HR>

<H3>Budget Cuts </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris has not ruled out more spending cuts on top
of the eight billion dollars in cuts already announced. 
<P>
Harris was asked today about reports his government is going to
cut another 4.3 billion dollars. The Premier said the government
has no plans for such spending cuts at this point in time. But
Harris was quick to add... times can change. 
<HR>

<H3>Somalia Document </H3>

<P>
Military personnel across the country have begun the momentous
task of combing their files for documents related to Canada's
ill fated Somalia mission. 
<P>
The order for the one day sweep through defence department files,
came after important documents in the investigation disappeared.
Although some Somalia related documents were found today at CFB
Petawawa, a base spokesman has described them as nothing more
than routine paperwork. 
<P>
Critics have called the search nothing more than a public relations
ploy, but it too may be backfiring. 
<HR>

<H3>Parole </H3>

<P>
A coalition of social groups wants the federal government to retain
a controversial section of the criminal code that allows convicted
murderers early parole. 
<P>
Those convicted of first degree murder receive an automatic sentence
of life without parole for 25 years. But section 745 allows them
to apply for parole after 15 years. 
<P>
Reform MP's say that's a lenient loophole that should be closed...
some critics disagree. 
<HR>

<H3>Oklahoma Bombing </H3>

<P>
The first of many pre-trial hearings in the Oklahoma City bombing
trial began today in Denver, the new site for the trial. 
<P>
Defendants Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols are demanding reams
of government documents they claim is evidence that might help
their case. The hearings are being held under the most extraordinary
security the city has ever seen.
<HR>

<H3>Chernobyl Anniversary </H3>

<P>
It's been almost ten years since the Chernobyl nuclear reactor
exploded a cloud of radioactive poison into the air. 
<P>
This week, experts and politicians from around the world have
gathered in Vienna to discuss the impact of the accident and what
can be done for its survivors. But for many victims, no amount
of discussion will ever help. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

