<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, April 4, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>School Reform 
<LI>Fergus Walkout 
<LI>UI-Young 
<LI>Workfare-Rxn 
<LI>Cop - Silence 
<LI>Unabomber 
<LI>Crime Profits 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>School Reform</H3>

<P>
A group called the Coalition for Education Reform warns that Ontario's
education system is headed for disaster. And that the Harris government
is preparing to devastate high school education. 
<HR>

<H3>Fergus Walkout</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, students from across the province continue to protest
cuts to the education system. 
<P>
Today, hundreds of students in Fergus, north of Guelph ... walked
out of class; after the Wellington Board of Education sent out
layoff notices to more than 300 employees, including one hundred-eleven
teachers. The protest mirrored similar walkouts earlier this week,
in Niagara falls, Belleville, and Belle River. 
<HR>

<H3>UI-Young </H3>

<P>
And it seems that young people are the most discouraged of all,
when it comes to looking for work. 
<P>
New figures from stats can show the jobless rate dropped to 9.3
percent in March ... down three-tenths of a point from February.

<P>
But analysts say some 30-thousand young adults, gave up looking
for work completely.... while another 20-thousand, lost jobs they
already had. 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare-Rxn </H3>

<P>
The desperation over unemployment comes just as the province is
beginning to take the wraps off of its new, Workfare scheme. 
<P>
The plan is to make able bodied recipients work for their welfare
cheques ... but many people are still wondering just how it will
work, and perhaps ... how it won't. Annette Hamm has more: 
<P>
<I>Before venturing out as a self proclaimed starving artist Paul
Benvenuti was on welfare. If worse comes to worse he says he'd
do anything other than go back on welfare under the new Ontario
Works Program. </I>
<P>
<I>The province will give communities 100 million dollars to create
17 hours of work a week for every person on general welfare assistance,
except those who are disabled, over 65 or those with kids under
3. The jobs may include digging ditches or painting rec centres.
</I>
<P>
<I>Susan West of Hamilton Wentworth's Social Planning and Research
Council agrees. She feels rather than make work projects, taxpayers
money would be better spent retraining welfare recipients with
real job skills for real jobs that are open. But the man behind
Workfare insists his plan will be a made in Ontario solution.
</I>
<P>
<I>Ontario Works will begin this year in 15 as yet unnamed municipalities.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Cop - Silence </H3>

<P>
Members of the government, meanwhile ... took a moment in the
provincial legislature to pay tribute to OPP Constable Michael
Gula. Gula was struck and killed as he stood at the side of the
QEW near Niagara Falls, Tuesday night. 
<P>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman characterized Gula as a well liked
and dedicated member of the OPP, who was involved with his community.

<P>
67 year old Frank Jacob Vanderkley has been charged with failing
to remain at the scene. He made a brief appearance in court and
was released on a thousand dollars bail; pending his next appearance,
May 2. 
<HR>

<H3>Unabomber </H3>

<P>
Police in the United States, meanwhile, are confident that they
have found the man that has eluded them for nearly two decades.

<P>
A Montana hermit: Theodore John Kaczynski; has been arrested and
held on charges of possessing the components of a bomb. Police
say that he ... is the infamous Unabomber: 
<HR>

<H3>Crime Profits </H3>

<P>
It's been done in the United States for quite a while ... but
federal authorities here in Canada have now signed agreements
with four provinces, to share the proceeds of property seized
by customs and the RCMP, in drug raids. 
<P>
Ontario, BC., New Brunswick and the Yukon, have signed the deal.
Authorities say the money will help them to keep criminals from
profiting from drug crimes. 

<P>
