<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, April 3, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Tax Cut Fight 
<LI>Johnson-Harassment 
<LI>NDP Debate 
<LI>Double Murder 
<LI>Pit Bull Attack 
<LI>Laparascopy Study
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Tax Cut Fight </H3>

<P>
Visible hardships caused by massive cuts in provincial spending
are prompting some Ontarians to wonder if it's all worth it. 
<P>
There are those who suggest that the deepest wounds are being
inflicted as the Harris government attempts to find ways to finance
its promised tax cut. So today, a lobby group issued an appeal,
asking Ontarians to tell their legislators to scrap the planned
tax cut, and restore some of the spending that has been axed.
But the premier remains adamant. 
<HR>

<H3>Johnson-Harassment </H3>

<P>
The chairman of the Management Board of the Ontario Cabinet says
he won't stand for any harassment of government workers who crossed
the picket lines during the recent civil service strike. 
<P>
Dave Johnson says he has heard rumors of some government employees
giving others the cold shoulder. Johnson says if it doesn't stop,
disciplinary action will be taken. 
<P>
Johnson also says the announcement of the layoff of some 13-thousand
government workers will come before the spring budget in may.

<HR>

<H3>NDP Debate </H3>

<P>
Provincial New Democrats will be electing a new party leader this
summer. 
<P>
Welland- Thorold MPP Peter Kormos and three other delegates are
vying for the job vacated by former Premier bob Rae. 
<P>
Nearly three hundred people showed up to hear the contestants
debate the issues last night. Ian Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>There are the heart and sole of the New Democratic Party, shop
stewards, community activists, riding executive members ...each
one a new democrat 365 days of the year. </I>
<P>
<I>It's people like Scot who will pick a new party leader this
summer. And under the leadership of either Francis Lankin, Howard
Hampton, Tony Silipo or Peter Kormos a more mature New Democratic
Party will emerge.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Double Murder </H3>

<P>
A Bowmanville man faces two counts of second-degree murder after
his daughter and his mother were found stabbed to death. 
<P>
The two were found in their home yesterday morning. Police have
identified the victims as six-year-old Jennifer England and 74-year-old
Marion Johnston. Charged is 45-year-old Ronald England.
<HR>

<H3>Pit Bull Attack </H3>

<P>
A Kitchener father had to use a baseball bat to fight off a pit
bull attacking his 4-year-old daughter today. 
<P>
The incident and similar attacks have resulted in calls for controls
on both the dogs and their owners. Kitchener City Council is now
considering a by-law that places a series of specific controls
on pit bulls and their owners. 
<P>
But they may need a change in provincial law to allow them to
single out a particular breed. 
<HR>

<H3>Laparascopy Study </H3>

<P>
There's a medical marvel that's been around for almost ten years,
and it's just now beginning to get the recognition it deserves,
and no wonder, with healthcare budgets being cut, Laparoscopic
surgery is being viewed in Ontario as a perfect way to cut out
disease, cut hospital stays, cut costs and cut recovery time.
Jamie West reports. 
<P>
<I>Dr. Adrian Park and his colleagues at Hamilton's St. Joseph's
Hospital are just back from the 5th World Congress of Laparoscopic
Surgery in Philadelphia. </I>
<P>
<I>Park and his partner Dr. Mehran Anvari travel the world teaching
surgeon's how to use the laparoscope, a narrow tube inserted into
the patient's abdomen through the navel allowing the surgeon to
see inside and perform operations using tiny cutting instruments
inserted through tiny incisions... the patient's abdomen is filled
with gas to create an open field to view all the abdominal organs.
</I>
<P>
<I>This patient will have her gall bladder removed...it will take
about a half hour and she'll likely go home later the same day.
The large open incision method for this operation would have included
a minimum 5 day hospital stay and 6 weeks of recovery at home.
</I>
<P>
<I>Dr. Park would like to see more doctors using this proven technique,
but he would like to ensure proper training before unqualified
surgeons jump on the bandwagon. </I>
<P>
<I>30-year old Julie Dinardo is a patient who suffered from ulcerative
colitis ... 43-year old Darla Vincent a kidney recipient...had
a an enlarged adrenal gland removed... and 43-year old Maria Italiano
underwent stomach surgery... Park says St. Joseph's hospital taking
the lead in Laparoscopic surgery couldn't have come at a better
time.</I> 


 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

