<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, April 2, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Women's Centre Woes 
<LI>Bowmanville Slaying 
<LI>Ipperwash Firearms 
<LI>Molester Released 
<LI>Virus Blocker 
<LI>Women - Pain 
<LI>Welfare Clothes 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Women's Centre Woes </H3>

<P>
We begin tonight with the story of a shelter for abused women
in Niagara falls. 
<P>
Nova House is operating under a cloud of controversy, amid complaints
from former residents and employees that management is throwing
money away while staff are being laid off and services cut. Local
politicians are beginning to question how taxpayers money is being
spent. And as Lauran Sabourin reports tonight... the shelter is
now the focus of an outside review. 
<P>
<I>The shelter's annual budget is 430 thousand dollars a year.
Salaries account for the lion's share of that budget. </I>
<P>
<I>To save money the board is considering closing the shelter
at midnight. </I>
<P>
<I>Willie Tracey calls himself a concerned taxpayer. He's been
questioning where and how the shelter's money is being spent.
</I>
<P>
<I>Responding to an ad in the local newspaper former residents
at Nova said they too were concerned about the cutbacks. &quot;Women
get abused and killed any day. How can you tell a desperate woman
not today dear, come back later. Later, in some cases might be
too late, or she might end up in the hospital like I did.&quot;
</I>
<P>
<I>Current and former employees at Nova complain that closing
the shelter at night isn't necessary. They say they've seen money
being thrown away; on a housekeeper whose primary function is
to buy groceries, on a child care worker who only works during
the day while the kids are in school. Toddlers are looked after
by their mothers. Jobs that are filled by friends and relatives
of Nova House board members. They say friends and family members
are hired while abuse counselors are being laid off or forced
to leave. </I>
<P>
<I>Sonia Sentinel was an abused woman. She stayed at Nova House
for four weeks last year. Sonia says she was ignored and at times
ridiculed by certain staff members. </I>
<P>
<I>Board members at Nova House refused to discuss these allegations.
They say the operation is under review. A consultant has been
hired. A report should be filed by the summer.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Bowmanville Slaying </H3>

<P>
Durham Regional Police are questioning a man in his 30's after
a six-year-old girl and her grandmother were slain in Bowmanville.

<P>
Police arrived at the home around 7:30 this morning. The victims
were apparently stabbed to death. No names have been released
yet.
<HR>

<H3>Ipperwash Firearms </H3>

<P>
Investigators probing last year's deadly standoff at Ipperwash
Provincial Park haven't found any weapons that police allege sparked
the shooting. 
<P>
Provincial police say they shot and killed 38-year-old Anthony
&quot;Dudley&quot; George last September because he had a gun.

<P>
The Chippewa who were occupying the park, near Sarnia on Lake
Huron, maintain they were not armed. Ontario's Special Investigations
Unit has been probing the shooting for more than seven months.

<P>
George's family has launched a wrongful death lawsuit against
Premier Mike Harris... alleging he directed police to use severe
action against the protesters. The premier says he gave police
no such orders. 
<HR>

<H3>Molester Released </H3>

<P>
Texas prison officials now say it could be a couple days before
an admitted child molester is released. 
<P>
Larry McQuay claims he has molested more than 200 children and
will do it again if released. Prison officials say they're making
sure he's served all his required time. 
<HR>

<H3>Virus Blocker </H3>

<P>
A new drug for combating AIDS has hit the Canadian market. 
<P>
The manufacturer of Invirase says it's not a miracle cure for
the deadly disease. But Hoffman-Laroche says when combined with
drugs like AZT, it delivers an effective one-two punch to help
people live longer. 
<P>
The drug inhibits the enzyme HIV protease, which helps the AIDS-virus
mature in the body. 
<P>
Invirase is now available in four countries, but can cost a patient
78- hundred dollars a year. Hoffman- Laroche is working with officials
in the provinces to get subsidies for AIDS patients. 
<HR>

<H3>Women - Pain </H3>

<P>
When it comes to chronic pain do women suffer more than men? A
newly released Stats Canada study indicates that in general women
do suffer more mental and distress as well as physical pain. But
as Jamie West reports ...there are a several logical reasons why
that is the case.... 
<P>
<I>Differences between men and women are nothing new. But when
it comes to consumption of healthcare and which group suffers
more pain the numbers seem to go against women... Stats Canada
says that one in five women suffer chronic pain compared to one
in seven men... </I>
<P>
<I>Dr. Chris Ricci is a chronic pain specialist at Hamilton Civic
Hospitals.. according to statistics consumption of pain medications
is also higher among women at 88 percent, compared to men at 74
percent... </I>
<P>
<I>Dr. Ricci is quick to point out that big ticket healthcare
items like joint replacement and heart surgery are virtually equal
among both genders... and that women are better communicators
of their healthcare needs than men... </I>
<P>
<I>It was not clear whether the Stats Canada analysis took into
account the fact the women live longer than men, but did say all
forms of chronic pain increase with age.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Clothes </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says there are no plans to cut the clothing
allowance of children on welfare. 
<P>
He says he doesn't know where these stories come from. The Globe
and Mail says it has obtained government documents about a plan
to reduce spending on the poor by 743- million dollars. 
<P>
The report added the province might raise rents in public housing,
charge welfare recipients drug-plan user fees and cut spending
for the physically and mentally handicapped. 
<P>
Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi says cuts for the handicapped
have not been discussed. 



<P>
