<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 04/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, April 1, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Edwards Quits 
<LI>OPSEU Returns-CUPE 
<LI>Tainted Water 
<LI>Train Derailment 
<LI>Hospital Cuts 
<LI>Florio Bunten
<LI>Passover Feast 
<LI>April Fool's 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Edwards Quits </H3>

<P>
The head of Canada's prison system has quit. John Edwards resigned
today after reading Justice Louise Arbour's report into the 1994
disturbances at Kingston's Prison for Women. 
<P>
The report blasts the prison service, saying it showed a disturbing
lack of commitment to the ideals of justice. Judge Arbour says
there is no evidence of a willingness to reform, and it appears
only tighter judicial control will lead to changes. 
<P>
Arbour's report says guards ignored the law by placing six prisoners
into segregation cells in April 1994. When that raised tensions
to the boiling point, the correctional service again ignored the
law and ordered an all-male emergency response team into the prison
... which strip searched female prisoners. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Returns-CUPE </H3>

<P>
Thousands of Ontario public servants returned to work today, following
five weeks on strike against the Harris government. 
<P>
But thousands will soon be out of a job, as Queen's Park gets
set to pare their ranks by more than 13-thousand. And there are
animosities among OPSEU members because of those who crossed picket
lines and went to work. To make matters worse, someone called
in a bomb scare... delaying the return to government business
at the Ontario Legislature. 
<HR>

<H3>Tainted Water </H3>

<P>
A Burlington company has been hired to help purify the drinking
water in Collingwood. 
<P>
Zenon Environmental will provide emergency treatment equipment
to the town to eliminate a deadly parasite that somehow got into
local waters. 
<P>
Residents in the Georgian Bay community have been buying bottled
water or boiling their own after 127 people became sick with a
flu like disease. Attempts to pinpoint the source of the elusive
bug continued today, with sampling of the local water supply at
the towns outdated treatment plant. And the search will likely
expand throughout the spring to nearby rivers which flow through
cattle grazing pastures of the Niagara Escarpment. 
<HR>

<H3>Train Derailment </H3>

<P>
Ontario Northland Railways officials suspect sabotage or accidental
tampering to be behind a train derailment near North Bay. 
<P>
The train's engineer noticed something wrong with a track switch
yesterday and hit the emergency brake. That caused five of six
cars of the Toronto-bound train to jump the tracks. The cars remained
upright. 
<P>
fifty passengers were on the train and there were no serious injuries.
A railway spokesman says it could have been vandalism or a passing
truck that hit the switch. 
<HR>

<H3>Hospital Cuts </H3>

<P>
A 4.6- million-dollar shortfall means job cuts at Peel Memorial
Hospital in Brampton. 
<P>
President Bruce Harbor says 200 jobs must be eliminated through
layoffs, early retirements and resignations. Workers will start
finding out which jobs are getting the ax tomorrow. Twenty-nine
beds are also being closed. 
<HR>

<H3>Florio Bunten</H3>

<P>
There may have been jury tampering in the so-called &quot;trial
of the century&quot;. 
<P>
A report on the CBS public affairs program &quot;60 Minutes&quot;
raised the possibility last night in an interview with a juror
who was dismissed because a letter implicated her in a post-trial
book deal. But there is mounting evidence that the letter was
a fake. 
<HR>

<H3>Passover Feast </H3>

<P>
Passover begins this Thursday, and Jews around the world will
begin a special week long diet to celebrate. This year, shopping
for Passover items is better than ever, with stores continuing
to improve their selection. Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>Over the last couple of weeks, grocery shoppers may have noticed
large kosher displays in many supermarkets. Retailers are gearing
up for the biggest food event of the Jewish calendar ... Passover.
</I>
<P>
<I>Jack Wright is a service consultant for the Fortino's Supermarket
at Dundurn Plaza in Hamilton. He says the selection of kosher
for Passover foods has increased quite a bit over the past few
years, as modern conveniences are added to the traditional staples
Jews took with them during their hurried exodus out of Egypt in
biblical times. </I>
<P>
<I>The thin bread is the basis for the bland, Passover diet, which
includes Unleven products, or those which don't rise. Any products
with these symbols, which mean they are approved by a rabbi for
cleanliness, are suitable for Passover. </I>
<P>
<I>Many of the items are displayed on white paper, another symbol
of cleanliness. Even selected liquor stores are expanding their
kosher products. Passover begins at sundown on Thursday, and continues
for a week.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>April Fool's </H3>

<P>
If you woke up somewhere in England today and forgot it was April
first, you might have gotten your leg pulled by made-up stories
in London's fun-loving newspapers. 
<P>
One paper reported that a royal Internet war is in the offing,
with both the Queen and Princess Diana setting up rival web pages.

<P>
Another carried a story about new key rings and refrigerator magnets
carrying pictures of Britain's new bewigged judges. Another had
a made-up ad on the latest innovation in cars: an IDS or insect
detection system from BMW designed to protect windshields from
insects. 
<P>
Another carried an ad on a &quot;new ...left-handed&quot; Mars
chocolate bar. 


 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

