<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, March 29, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Deal? 
<LI>Milton Theft 
<LI>Trail Dispute 
<LI>Martin-GST 
<LI>Copps - Quebec 
<LI>Freemen Friday 
<LI>France Raid 
<LI>Japan HIV 
<LI>Mad Cow Justice 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Deal? </H3>

<P>
There's no quick end in sight to the Ontario government workers
strike. After high hopes of a tentative settlement yesterday,
negotiators are still hashing out details at the bargaining table
in Toronto. 
<HR>

<H3>Milton Theft</H3>

<P>
A former Vice-President of the Royal Bank's brokerage house has
been charged with bilking investors out of almost six million
dollars. 
<P>
RCMP arrested 53 year old Christopher Edmunston Horne today at
his home in the posh Toronto neighborhood of Rosedale. He faces
13 counts of fraud and theft. 
<P>
Police allege that between 1987 and 1994, clients funds were illegally
channeled through an account under his control. 
<HR>

<H3>Trail Dispute </H3>

<P>
A Burlington home owner is hot on the trails of the Niagara Escarpment
Commission. 
<P>
He's angry the commission won't let him sever his land for development.
To fight back, he's decided to block access to the Bruce Trail
from his property. Annette Hamm has the story. 
<P>
<I>Harry Zahoruk is putting up his last fight against the Niagara
Escarpment Commission. The Burlington lawyer is denying access
to part of the Bruce Trail, which runs through his 65 acre property.
</I>
<P>
<I>The fight started when Zahoruk applied to sever his land to
build a home for his partner. But the commission said no. The
original 100 acres where Harry Zahoruk lives was divided once
into 6 parcels of land, and the commission's plan only allows
one severance in the Niagara protection area of the escarpment.
Zahoruk proposed that if he was allowed to sever the land again,
he'd give the Bruce Trail Association a parking lot and permanent
right of way on his land. </I>
<P>
<I>Joan Little is chair of the Niagara Escarpment Commission.
She doesn't want the Bruce Trail used as a pawn in the dispute,
and fears giving Zahoruk his severance would set a dangerous precedence.
And it appears Harry Zahoruk won't. He's ready to give up and
sell his property.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Martin-GST </H3>

<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin has rejected Ontario's claim that
merging its provincial sales tax with the GST will suck billions
out of the pockets of consumers. 
<P>
Martin says the federal government's plan for GST harmonization
will bring in no more money than the current sales-tax system.
Ontario has so far rejected Martin's overtures to merge its provincial
sales tax with the GST, into a new 15 percent national sales tax.

<HR>

<H3>Copps - Quebec </H3>

<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Sheila Copps says there's no way Quebec
delegates working out of Canadian embassies, will be allowed to
peddle separation. Copps was responding to comments by Quebec
International Affairs Minister Sylvain Simard. 
<P>
The PQ government has announced it will close 13 of 19 foreign
delegations. Simard said some Quebec representatives will work
out of Canadian embassies around the world, and could sell sovereignty
along with trade. 
<HR>

<H3>Freemen Friday </H3>

<P>
Tensions remain high in Montana today, where a showdown between
federal authorities and a right wing separatist group drags on.
Several of the so-called Freemen are hold up on a farm... while
two others in the group went to court today. 
<HR>

<H3>France Raid </H3>

<P>
French police killed three suspected robbers in a Shootout near
the northern city of Lihl, site of next Mondays group of seven
meeting. A fourth suspected robber, who fled the scene, was later
killed by Belgian police. 
<P>
French officials insist the clashes today, and an attempted car
bombing last night, involved criminals not terrorists. The bomb
was discovered about 300 metres from the hall where G-7 labor
and economics ministers open a conference on Monday. 
<HR>

<H3>Japan HIV </H3>

<P>
Japan's government and five drug companies have agreed to compensate
people who've been infected with the AIDS virus through untreated
blood. 
<P>
Last month, the government admitted it knew of the risks, but
still didn't pull the blood products off the market. as part of
today's settlements, the government and drug makers also apologized.
In all, nearly two thousand people in Japan, mostly hemophiliacs,
became infected with HIV in the 1980's because of untreated blood.

<HR>

<H3>Mad Cow Justice </H3>

<P>
The world health organization will hold an emergency meeting in
Geneva next week to discuss the possible dangers of &quot;mad
cow disease&quot;. Health experts plan to make safety recommendations
at that time. 
<P>
Consumer panic ensued after British scientists linked the disease
to a condition in humans. But, what is considered a crisis in
one culture can be considered divine intervention in another.


 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

