<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, March 28, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Latest 
<LI>Long Term Health 
<LI>MUMC Business 
<LI>Sick Kids Boss 
<LI>Midwife 
<LI>Red Cross 
<LI>Booze Bust 
<LI>French Ban 
<LI>Spy Deadline 
<LI>Freemen Standoff 
<LI>Hijackers Thursday 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Latest </H3>

<P>
Ontario's first public service strike is all but over. And an
agreement could be announced later tonight. 
<P>
Earlier today, hundreds of striking civil servants made a final
show of strength, as they again made people wait fifteen minutes
before letting them enter the Ontario legislature. 
<P>
OPSEU President Leah Casselman was wildly cheered by her supporters
at a noon-hour rally. Casselman told fellow members that negotiators
have just one issue to resolve .. details on a return to work.

<P>
If a contract deal is reached tonight, voting could take place
tomorrow, and government workers might very well be back on the
job as early as Saturday. 
<HR>

<H3>Long Term Health </H3>

<P>
In other news tonight, the sick and frail will be getting more
help at home, but nursing homes are facing cuts. 
<P>
Health Minister Jim Wilson announced a dramatic shakeup of community
based health care today. Wilson has allocated an additional 170
million dollars for homecare, but is chopping 30 percent funding
from nursing homes. 
<HR>

<H3>MUMC Business </H3>

<P>
And with provincial funding of hospitals expected to be cut to
the bone over the next the decade; the &quot;business&quot; of
healthcare in Ontario is getting the attention of hospital administrators
like never before. 
<P>
As Jamie West reports tonight ...Hamilton's Chedoke McMaster Hospitals
are turning to it's staff to invent new &quot;revenue generating
ideas&quot; that will ensure continued high quality patient care...

<P>
<I>Chedoke McMaster teamed up with the McMaster University's Michael
DeGroote School of Business to create a fast track marketing course
for health care workers. </I>
<P>
<I>Nancy Carter a registered pediatric nurse was one of 30 candidates
chosen to take the course out of some 300 who applied. </I>
<P>
<I>Inside the classroom with the help of business instructors
small groups develop their revenue generating plans that's just
one of 600 hundred ideas already generated in the class... the
course is intense.. consisting of 16 four hour sessions, the initiative
will be evaluated by hospital brass in six months to see how many
of the money making ideas are in practice at that time. </I>
<P>
<I>The hospital's goal is to reduce it's reliance on government
funding by 50 percent within 10 years. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Sick Kids Boss </H3>

<P>
And while some hospitals in Ontario are doing what they can to
trim costs, it's been learned the President of the Hospital for
Sick Children in Toronto, is one of the highest paid health administrators
in the country. 
<P>
Information obtained under a provincial disclosure act, shows
that Michael Strofolino earns about 500 thousand dollars a year....
that's about five times the salary paid to the premier. 
<HR>

<H3>Midwife</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the Harris government plans to appoint an unemployed
car salesman to a provincial body that oversees midwives. 
<P>
Dan Callaghan worked for an auto dealer in Petawawa from 1990
to 1995. He also ran for the Tories in the Renfrew North riding
last June but lost to the Liberal incumbent. 
<P>
Some members of the legislature are questioning Callaghan's qualifications
and his interest in midwifery. 
<HR>

<H3>Red Cross </H3>

<P>
The Red Cross will no longer stop parents from storing blood intended
for their children. The blood agency is reversing its policy after
a national outcry. 
<P>
But the provinces will have to agree to pay for the program. The
issue arose after a Quebec couple went to court to win the right
to donate blood for their son's surgery. 
<HR>

<H3>Booze Bust </H3>

<P>
RCMP say they have smashed a Canada wide alcohol and tobacco smuggling
ring. 
<P>
So far 170 people have been arrested with more expected. the raids
took place in Ontario, Quebec and BC. 
<P>
The mounties say five organized crime groups, including Asian
gangs, were involved in smuggling through the Akwesasne reserve
in eastern Ontario. 20 million dollars worth of alcohol, tobacco,
drugs and weapons have been seized. 
<HR>

<H3>French Ban </H3>

<P>
The families of Paul Bernardo's murder victims won't be allowed
to take part in a Supreme Court hearing on closed courtrooms.

<P>
The high court ruled the families could not help it decide on
when the media can be banned from reporting on cases. The CBC
will argue tomorrow that freedom of the press was violated when
a new Brunswick judge refused to make public the details of a
sex assault case against a Moncton politician. 
<HR>

<H3>Spy Deadline</H3>

<P>
A Reform MP has gone public with what she says is proof a Russian
agent infiltrated Canada's intelligence service. Val Meredith
released claims that a member of CSIS met secretly with Russian
spies and that CSIS brass, protected him.
<HR>

<H3>Freemen Standoff </H3>

<P>
An armed standoff is now, into its fifth day in Jordan, Montana.

<P>
US federal agents have surrounded a farm where a dozen or so people,
who refuse to acknowledge governmental authority, are holed up.
the so-called &quot;freemen&quot; are wanted for allegedly writing
bad cheques and threatening local officials.
<HR>

<H3>Hijackers Thursday </H3>

<P>
In Cairo, Canadian diplomats welcomed back 59 Canadian tourists
following a frightening journey that took them on an unscheduled
visit to Libya. 
<P>
The group was among 145 passengers aboard an Egypt-air jet, hijacked
yesterday. Three armed hijackers surrendered shortly after landing
in Libya. 
 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

