<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, March 27, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>Bomb Threat 
<LI>Castillo Surrenders 
<LI>OPSEU Wednesday 
<LI>Hydro Rejects 
<LI>Teacher Cuts 
<LI>Spy-Follow 
<LI>Anik 
<LI>Egypt Hijacking 
<LI>Assassin Sentence 
<LI>Menendez Sentencing 
<LI>Spacewalk 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bomb Threat </H3>

<P>
Part of downtown Hamilton is shut down, following a bomb threat
in the cities downtown core. Staff and prisoners at the provincial
courthouse were evacuated around 10:30 this morning after a bomb
threat was called in. 
<HR>

<H3>Castillo Surrenders</H3>

<P>
In other news tonight, a former model wanted in a huge armored-car
heist has surrendered to police in Toronto. 
<P>
Police had been looking for a female suspect since last August's
holdup of a Loomis truck. 28 year old (ee-da) Catillo is the fifth
person charged. Among the others arrested is a Toronto police
officer. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Wednesday </H3>

<P>
There has been a setback in the talks between the government and
the civil service union. 
<P>
Management Board chairman Dave Johnson says he is confused by
union tactics, and it may be another two weeks before an agreement
can be reached. 
<HR>

<H3>Hydro Rejects </H3>

<P>
Ontario Hydro workers have almost unanimously rejected the last
contract offer from the utility. 
<P>
Members of the Power Workers Union voted 98.5 percent against
the offer. Union President John Murphy calls the result an overwhelming
message to Hydro that its last offer was clearly unacceptable
to the membership. 
<P>
Contract talks broke off last month but will resume in early April.

<HR>

<H3>Teacher Cuts </H3>

<P>
The public school system in Hamilton is about to lose a rash of
energetic young teachers... those who enthusiastically share both
work-time and spare-time with their teen-aged charges. 
<P>
But despite their energy and dedication... they have received
lay-off notices. It is a system based on seniority... and they
simply don't have enough in this time of major cutbacks. Anthony
Pooley has a couple of their stories. 
<P>
<I>Who among us can say that during our school years we were not
moved in some positive way by at least one teacher? A teacher
like Glenn Cooke, perhaps, a high school science teacher at Delta
Secondary School. Once the layoffs announced by the school board
take effect, his particular teaching specialty will all but cease
to exist at Delta... but that's not all... who will the coaches
be next September? Who will coach gymnastics, as Corie Pillinini
does now? </I>
<P>
<I>This is a 12-hour day for the energetic, 28-year-old Geography
Department head at Delta. Once classes have concluded, she will
turn her attention to the school gymnastics team. </I>
<P>
<I>And for all of their hard work ... commitment to their profession
... commitment to the development of Hamilton's youth... their
reward comes one day in an envelope... a layoff notice. </I>
<P>
<I>Glenn Cooke and Corie Pillinini are only two examples of the
extent to which the system of education is being robbed... robbed
of the talented young professionals gifted in reaching out to
disillusioned teen-agers... robbed in the name of beleaguered
taxpayers who have told those they elect that they simply can't
afford to pay any more in taxes. Painful times, indeed. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Spy-Follow </H3>

<P>
The Solicitor General has ordered Canada's intelligence service
to explain allegations of a Russian spy inside the agency. 
<P>
Herb Gray has given CSIS documents which a reform MP says proves
a spy exists. The MP is threatening to make the documents public
in 24 hours.
<HR>

<H3>Anik </H3>

<P>
Telesat Canada, the crown agency that carries Canada's communications
satellites, says the Anik E-1 has lost half of its power... and
it may be lost forever. 
<P>
Experts maintain that a disconnected solar panel is to blame for
yesterday's satellite trouble which took several television stations
temporarily off the air and interrupted everything from computer
to pager systems. Service has been restored to most clients via
Anik E-2 but Telesat says its doubtful Anik E-1 can be fixed.

<HR>

<H3>Egypt Hijacking </H3>

<P>
Canada's Foreign Affairs department has confirmed the 59 Canadian
passengers aboard a hijacked Egypt-air jetliner... are safe. 
<P>
Earlier today, the hi-jackers commandeered the plane in Luxor,
Egypt and forced the pilot to fly to Libya where the plane eventually
landed. The hijackers demanded to meet with Libya's leader Moammar
Gadhafi before surrendering to authorities. 
<HR>

<H3>Assassin Sentence </H3>

<P>
In Israel today, has convicted Yigal Amir and sentenced him to
life in jail for the November murder of prime minister Yitzhak
Rabin. 
<HR>

<H3>Menendez Sentencing </H3>

<P>
The sentencing phase in the murder trial of Erik and Lyle Menendez
began today in Los Angeles. 
<P>
A California jury must decide if the brothers will spend the rest
of their lives in prison, or be put to death for killing their
parents. 
<P>
The defense is expected to call friends and family to testify
the two were sexually abused. Prosecutors say the young men killed
their parents, to inherit their fortune. 
<HR>

<H3>Spacewalk</H3>

<P>
NASA says two &quot;Atlantis&quot; astronauts accomplished all
their objectives in a six hour spacewalk today. It was the first
spacewalk by Americans outside Russia's space station &quot;Mir&quot;.

<P>
The two spacecraft have been linked since Saturday. They'll separate
tomorrow. 
 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

