<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, March 26, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>
<UL>
<LI>OHIP Hunger Strike 
<LI>Teen Surrenders 
<LI>Jails-Essential 
<LI>Harris-Fingerprints 
<LI>Derailment 
<LI>Que. By-elections 
<LI>Oscar Wrap 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OHIP Hunger Strike</H3>

<P>
A Sudbury father has won his battle to have OHIP pay for his dying
daughters' life saving treatment, in an American hospital. But,
the man had to resort to drastic measures before OHIP officials
would change their mind. 
<HR>

<H3>Teen Surrenders </H3>

<P>
In Oakville, a young man, presumed drowned after he slipped into
a creek while running from police, has turned himself in. 
<P>
Police spent several hours last night searching the waters and
banks of 16 Mile Creek, looking for the 19 year old. But he apparently
was in the water only a short time, before pulling himself out.

<P>
He surrendered to police this afternoon. The man had been running
from police investigating three break-ins, when he jumped over
a steep embankment and into the water. 
<HR>

<H3>Jails-Essential </H3>

<P>
Queen's Park is on its way to court, seeking an order to compel
jail guards designated essential to work. This as guards refused
to show up at about half of the provincial jails. Anthony Pooley
has the details. 
<P>
<I>The Niagara Detention Centre in Thorold is just one of several
provincial jails where essential personnel are refusing to work
... some say it's just too dangerous without their striking colleagues
to bring staff up to an acceptable complement; others claim they're
not being paid. So management is staffing jails. </I>
<P>
<I>Queen's Park claims OPSEU is not honouring its essential services
agreement... although the Hamilton Wentworth Detention Centre
remains staffed with a skeleton unionized crew. But for his part,
Management Board Chairman Dave Johnson believes that ongoing contract
talks to end the public service strike should be separated and
distinct from the situation at the jails. </I>
<P>
<I>Although the government claims that half of the province's
49 jails are affected, the union claims essential workers are
failing to show up at only 11 of them. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Harris-Fingerprints </H3>

<P>
Metro Toronto may soon become the only municipality in Canada,
to fingerprint welfare recipients. 
<P>
If metro council approves the move, people drawing welfare in
Toronto will be required to carry a bank card with an electronic
strip bearing a digitized reading of their fingerprint. 
<P>
Meanwhile the province of Ontario is also looking at bringing
in a similar province-wide ID card. But Premier Mike Harris says
there are still some concerns about privacy of information. 
<HR>

<H3>Derailment </H3>

<P>
It could take a couple of days to clear the wreckage from a CN
train derailment north of Orillia. 
<P>
13 cars left the tracks early today. About 60 people were evacuated
because some of the cars contained hazardous materials. They returned
home when it was found none were leaking. 
<HR>

<H3>Que. By-elections </H3>

<P>
One seat for the Bloc, none for Reform and five for the Liberals.
That sums up the outcome of the six federal by-elections yesterday
in Ontario, Quebec and Newfoundland. 
<P>
Prime Minister Chretien's national unity strategy remains intact
with the election of rookie cabinet ministers Stephanie Dion and
Pierre Pettigrew in Montreal. And the Chretien government says
the results show that Canadians endorse its policies.
<HR>

<H3>Oscar Wrap </H3>

<P>
And from Ottawa to Los Angeles now, where the results of yet another
group of voters were announced. the 68th annual Academy Awards
were handed out last night and the big winner was the Scottish
epic &quot;Braveheart&quot;.
 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

