<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, March 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Harris-Latest 
<LI>Org. Radio Ads 
<LI>GST
<LI>GM - Outsource 
<LI>Summer Weather 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Harris-Latest</H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says his government could stop spending cuts
at 8-billion dollars, and still end up with a balanced budget.

<P>
It is thought that points to a strong possibility that there won't
be any new spending reductions in the spring budget. 
<HR>

<H3>Org. Radio Ads </H3>

<P>
A right wing lobby group has launched a radio ad campaign in four
cities, designed to keep the Harris government's tax cut promise
on the front burner. 
<P>
Ontarians for Responsible Government is running the spot announcements
in Hamilton, as well as Toronto, London and Kitchener. Anthony
Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>That is the gospel according to Ontarians for Responsible Government,
a right wing lobby group that regularly speaks out in support
of measures taken by the Harris government. </I>
<P>
<I>They're running radio ads in four Ontario cities, including
Toronto and Hamilton. And their view is clear. </I>
<P>
<I>But liberals generally and Hamilton East MPP Dominic Agostino
specifically are lining up to urge the governing Tories to abandon
their promise of a tax cut... suggesting that the pain of the
government spending cutbacks is simply too excruciating to bear.
</I>
<P>
<I>So as the polarization and the OPSEU strike continue... the
line-ups get longer on both sides of the battle line... while
bewildered taxpayers look on. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton ... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>GST</H3>

<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin wants to talk to the provinces first,
and he won't comment on a report that Ottawa is close to harmonizing
provincial sales taxes with the GST in Atlantic Canada. 
<P>
Martin met with Newfoundland Premier Brian Tobin this morning
in St. Johns. While not denying the report, Martin says Tobin
has some concerns and that a lot of details still have to be worked
out. 
<P>
In Ottawa, the Reform Party attacked the government over the issue.
During question period, Reform MP Deborah Grey accused the liberals
of trying to buy votes in Monday's federal by-elections. 
<HR>

<H3>GM - Outsource </H3>

<P>
Seventeen thousand laid off General Motors workers in Canada will
begin heading back to work tomorrow. 
<P>
The strike in Dayton, Ohio which resulted in part shortages at
GM plants throughout North America has been resolved. 
<P>
But as Lauran Sabourin reports, although the strike is over, the
main issue that led to the dispute still hasn't been settled.

<P>
<I>An overwhelming acceptance vote in Dayton. But not necessarily
a victory for the union. </I>
<P>
<I>The issue is outsourcing. Having General Motors parts made
by outside companies. Outsourcing is the number one issue for
the Canadian auto workers. The number one issue at GM St. Catharines
plant. </I>
<P>
<I>St. Catharines will lose 750 jobs when its axle plant moves
to Buffalo. St. Catharines has lost 32 hundred jobs since 1989.
Another 15 hundred may disappear by September. And the union can
make no promises when it all will end.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Summer Weather</H3>

<P>
If you've just about had it with winter this year, you're not
alone. Although spring officially arrived in Canada two days ago,
many Canadians are still facing sub zero temperatures and snowfall.

<P>
It's been a long winter, and spring is definitely taking its sweet
time getting here.... but get ready to dust off those shades and
pull on those shorts because Environment Canada is predicting
a warmer summer than average. 
 <P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

