<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, March 21, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Latest 
<LI>Court - Pensions 
<LI>Zundel - Court 
<LI>Charest Deal 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Latest </H3>

<P>
A public inquiry into Monday's violent picket demonstration around
Queens Park, could begin in two weeks. That was the word from
Deputy Premier Ernie Eves today. 
<HR>

<H3>Court - Pensions </H3>

<P>
A group of former Stelco workers will get full pensions, the Supreme
Court of Canada has decided. 
<P>
The decision came today following a 5-year David versus Goliath
battle. And as Anthony Pooley reports tonight ... the former staffers
won the fight not only at the supreme court ... but at every other
level as well. 
<P>
<I>The big question was always whether Stelco's golden boot, given
to about 700 staffers about six years ago... was part of a corporate
re-organization ... and whether that number was significant enough
to warrant a partial pension plan wind-down to provide full pensions
for those who qualified at their normal retirement date.</I>
<P>
<I>Appearing before a tribunal 3 years ago, Stelco lawyer Mark
Frieman argued that the two criteria must be connected. Stelco
lost that round and several others... including their application
to appeal. That was thrown out today by the Supreme Court of Canada.
</I>
<P>
<I>Stelco did not make a statement today... but Frieman told us
that the next step in the process is compliance... staring with
the preparation of a wind down report for the pension commission.
All of that should pave the way for full pension benefits. </I>
<P>
<I>Ex-Stelco staffer Art Frewin led the charge on behalf of about
60 ex-staffers. He is understandably ecstatic over today's decision.
</I>
<P>
<I>But just as important as the victory of David over Goliath
is the precedent set by the decision and the general tone of various
rulings... that to the larger extent, pension law exists to protect
the pension rights of workers... not the rights of company shareholders...
and that the money in pension plans belongs to the workers...
not the corporation. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Zundel - Court </H3>

<P>
Holocaust denier Ernst Zundel is fighting Ottawa's decision to
deny him Canadian citizenship. 
<P>
Zundel, who calls himself a model Canadian citizen, says he has
no criminal record and sees no reason why he should be labeled
a security risk by Canada's security intelligence review committee.

<P>
Today Zundel appeared before the Federal Court in Ottawa, claiming
the committee is biased and therefore in no position to judge
his eligibility to stay in this country. 
<HR>

<H3>Charest Deal </H3>

<P>
Conservative Leader Jean Charest lashed back at the Reform Party
for accusing him of making deals with separatists. 
<P>
The Reform Party says it has proof Charest forged an alliance
with the Bloc. The accusations are another symptom of by-election
fever. <P>

