<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, March 20, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Public Inquiry 
<LI>Johnson-Talks 
<LI>House Picket 
<LI>Workfare 
<LI>Menendez Verdict 
<LI>Shaw Preps 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Public Inquiry </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is willing to call a public inquiry into
the violent confrontation between police and strikers outside
the legislature. 
<P>
Deputy Premier Ernie Eves says he'll discuss the issue tomorrow,
with opposition house leaders. 
<P>
Several picketing civil servants were injured when a baton- wielding
provincial police riot squad stormed through a crowd of strikers.
The squad was brought in to help conservative members get to work.

<HR>

<H3>Johnson-Talks </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, there has been some movement in contract negotiations
between the government and its striking workers. 
<P>
The government is studying the latest proposal which includes
some concessions on the part of the union. Management Board Chairman
Dave Johnson, says there is still a long way to go, but the two
sides are slowly inching closer to a deal. 
<P>
Negotiators are meeting around the clock under a mediator -imposed
news blackout to resolve the strike, which is now into its fourth
week.
<HR>

<H3>House Picket </H3>

<P>
And while both sides struggle towards reaching some sort of compromise,
a Hamilton family is going through a personal hell because of
the strike. A new tactic employed by the union has struck too
close to home. 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare</H3>

<P>
Welfare recipients in Ontario could find themselves working on
community improvement projects beginning this spring. The move
is part of &quot;the Ontario Works Plan&quot;, a key promise during
the conservative government's election campaign last spring. 
<P>
About 1.2 million Ontarians are on welfare, roughly 10 percent
of the provincial population. 
<HR>

<H3>Menendez Verdict </H3>

<P>
A Los Angeles jury has convicted Erik and Lyle Menendez of killing
their parents. 
<P>
The first degree murder convictions mean both brothers are eligible
for the death penalty. 
<P>
The brothers claimed they killed their parents to end years of
abuse. The state said they killed to get their parents money.

<HR>

<H3>Shaw Preps</H3>

<P>
Well it may look like winter outside but spring has arrived and
that means the tourist season is also about to begin. 
<P>
In Niagara-on-the-Lake, the Shaw Festival is a flurry of activity
as the company prepares for the opening of its 35th season next
month. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

