<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, March 19, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Protest Inquiry 
<LI>MPP's Pay Raise 
<LI>Public Housing Sale 
<LI>Human Rights 
<LI>Airport Update 
<LI>Disco Fire 
<LI>Coma Rape Birth 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Protest Inquiry </H3>

<P>
Opposition parties at Queens Park are demanding a public inquiry
into the way a provincial police riot squad handled a massive
rally at the Ontario Legislature yesterday. 
<P>
A few people were injured when the squad cleared the way for MPP's
to get into the building. OPSEU strikers and their supporters
were blocking the entrance to protest the lack of progress in
a strike that has now entered it's third week. 
<HR>

<H3>MPP's Pay Raise </H3>

<P>
Provincial politicians won't be getting a pay raise this year.
Premier Mike Harris says he'll personally guarantee it. 
<P>
A published report says MPP's would automatically get a five percent
pay hike when the social contract expires in April. 
<P>
Meanwhile, there's no deadline for the government's pledge to
overhaul politicians pay and gold trimmed pensions. 
<HR>

<H3>Public Housing Sale </H3>

<P>
A new report, compiled by members of Ontario's Public Housing
Authorities, is urging the Harris government to rethink its plans
for privatization. Such a decision, the report concludes, could
save money in the short term, but could have devastating effects
down the road. Annette Hamm explains. 
<P>
<I>Cathy Smith, her husband and three kids have lived in their
tidy east mountain home for the past twelve years. </I>
<P>
<I>Their rent is geared to income, about a quarter of their gross
pay. Since the Ontario government announced it wanted to get out
of the public housing business last year, Cathy has been fighting
to keep them in. </I>
<P>
<I>When Cathy and her family were living in private housing back
in the 1980's half of their income went towards rent. Housing
authorities across the province fear that could happen to many
more families if the government hands public housing to the private
sector. </I>
<P>
<I>A report compiled by housing groups across the province, calls
for changes to be made to the public housing system before moving
to privatization. They call for less red tape in decision making
and administration. </I>
<P>
<I>The public housing report has been approved by the Ontario
Housing Council, and is now in the hands of the ministry of housing.
</I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Human Rights</H3>

<P>
The Chretien government faces strong criticism from the Canadian
Human Rights Commission for delaying further protection for gays.

<P>
Human Rights Commissioner Max Yalden told parliament today the
delays amount to &quot;acquiescence in intolerance&quot;. He says
the delays make gays and lesbians the victims of special treatment
because they don't have the same rights as everybody else. 
<P>
Justice Minister Allan Rock says parliament will further protect
gays... one day. 
<HR>

<H3>Airport Update </H3>

<P>
A power failure at Toronto's Pearson Airport caused radar screens
to go blank in the air traffic control tower today. 
<P>
Airport spokesman Bruce Reid says they now have an alternate power
source, but the system is only working at 60 to 70 percent capacity.
Reid says they hope to have the system running at full speed by
tomorrow morning. 
<P>
Earlier today, some planes on their final approach had to be brought
down by controllers using their eyes and radios. Most other planes
were diverted to other airports. 
<HR>

<H3>Disco Fire </H3>

<P>
In international news, a disco fire in the Philippines is being
called the worst ever in that country's history. 
<P>
Firemen have removed the bodies of 150 people from the smoking
ruins. As many as 50 others are believed to be buried under the
debris. 
<HR>

<H3>Coma Rape Birth </H3>

<P>
Doctors in Rochester, New York, say a baby boy, born to a raped,
comatose woman, is now breathing on his own and will likely survive.

<P>
The baby was born yesterday, eight weeks premature, weighing just
two-pounds 11-ounces. His 29-year-old mother suffered head injuries
in a car accident more than 10 years ago, and was raped at a Rochester-area
nursing home. 
<P>
Doctors believe this to be the first case of someone getting pregnant
and giving birth while in a coma.  
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

