<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, March 15, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Baby Deaths? 
<LI>Blood 
<LI>Karla Report 
<LI>Zundel 
<LI>Police Shooting 
<LI>OPSEU Scuffle 
<LI>Collenette
<LI>Commons-Language 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Baby Deaths? </H3>

<P>
A coroner's investigation says that as many as 150 babies who
died from apparent sudden infant death syndrome over the last
10 years, may actually have been victims of abuse. 
<P>
This today from Ontario deputy coroner Dr. Jim Cairns. And as
Anthony Pooley reports tonight... there is another syndrome which
is actually a form of abuse. 
<P>
<I>There are probably significantly more babies dying each year
from abuse than originally believe, says the Ontario Coroner's
Office after a lengthy investigation. In fact, Deputy Coroner
Dr. Jim Cairns, who did the review, believes that a number of
deaths originally attributed to Sudden Infant Death Syndrome or
SIDS may actually have been caused by abuse and even murder. </I>
<P>
<I>Of the 1400 or so deaths attributed to SIDS over the last 10
years, between 100 and 150 of them may well have been caused by
parental or other care-giver abuse. Those findings do not surprise
Hamilton pediatrician Dr. Shuba Wahi. infants... and signs of
infant abuse... are her particular specialty. </I>
<P>
<I>Indeed, there is another syndrome that kills babies... and
this one is decidedly abuse. It is called shaken baby syndrome...
and in some cases, the abuse is deliberate... in others it is
care giver ignorance that results in injury to infants. in any
case, a rigorous new protocol is designed to result in more accurate
pathological findings in the future. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton.... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Blood </H3>

<P>
The Canadian Red Cross says it's found another way to make Canada's
blood supply safer. 
<P>
Canada's blood collection agency has gained FDA approval to bring
in a new, more effective HIV test, that will be able to detect
the AIDS virus in its earliest stages... something current blood
testing has been unable to do. 
<P>
The Red Cross hopes its new testing procedures will help save
more lives, but there are some concerns about the cost, effectiveness
and potential misuse of the system. 
<HR>

<H3>Karla Report </H3>

<P>
A report on the Karla Homolka plea-bargain deal is to go to the
Ontario government today. 
<P>
In return for testimony against her ex-husband, Paul Bernardo,
Homolka was sentenced to 12 years for her role in the sex slayings
of two Ontario schoolgirls. Last November, Ontario's Attorney
General asked a judge to conduct an independent review of Homolka's
deal.
<HR>

<H3>Zundel </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government has dropped a charge of promoting hatred
that was filed against holocaust- denier Ernst Zundel. 
<P>
Lawyers for the Attorney General's ministry say there isn't enough
evidence to proceed. Holocaust survivor, Sabin (sit-run) who pressed
the charge, says the government didn't do enough in the case.

<HR>

<H3>Police Shooting</H3>

<P>
The special investigation unit has been called in after metro
Toronto police shot and killed a man who was pointing what appeared
to be a gun. 
<P>
The man, in his early 20s, was pronounced dead at hospital soon
after the shooting. The incident began when two officers answered
a call about a person at the rear of a shopping mall with a knife.
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Scuffle </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government and its striking employees have agreed
to impose a news blackout on all contract talks. Both sides feel
more progress will be made by keeping the negotiations private.

<P>
And in another development today, tempers flared as a picket of
a land registry office in Toronto turned ugly. 
<HR>

<H3>Collenette</H3>

<P>
Defence Minister David Collenette is challenging Bloc Quebecois
MP Jean-Marc Jacob to prove his allegations. 
<P>
Jacob has said Ottawa looked into the formation of a Quebec army
in the event of separation. But Jacob says he has no proof. Collenette
assured the commons today that the military leadership authorized
no discussions about splitting the armed forces. 
<HR>

<H3>Commons-Language </H3>

<P>
Parliament has been exposed to some very unparliamentary language
from a Bloc MP. 
<P>
Yvon Loubier was heard to utter the &quot;f-word&quot; during
a heated exchange with the minister of Indian affairs. The outburst
caps a rowdy week in which the language of parliament was tinged
with blue. 

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

