<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, March 14, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Scotland Aftermath 
<LI>TV Violence 
<LI>OPSEU 10% 
<LI>TTC Strike 
<LI>Quake Streeters 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Scotland Aftermath </H3>

<P>
Police in Dunblane, Scotland are trying to determine why Thomas
Hamilton killed 16 children and their teacher. 
<P>
When the shooting ended, Hamilton turned a gun on himself. Several
children were injured and at least one child is in critical condition.

<HR>

<H3>TV Violence </H3>

<P>
The federal broadcast regulator has handed down a television violence
policy using v-chip technology. Broadcasters and cable companies
must start to follow the new rules by this September. Anthony
Pooley has the details. 
<P>
<I>It is called the v-chip... a device designed to block certain
appropriately encoded t-v programming... notably that containing
gratuitous violence that experts believe can do permanent psychological
harm to children under 11. It is the cornerstone of the federal
broadcast regulator's t-v violence policy, unveiled today by CRTC
Chairman Keith Spicer. </I>
<P>
<I>Among other things, the policy compels broadcasters to encode
programs so that offensive ones can be blocked by the v-chip...
and it compels cable companies to offer v-chip devices for a low
monthly fee beginning in September. </I>
<P>
<I>The broadcast industry must come up with a violence rating
system. If American broadcasters haven't started encoding shows
by January, cable companies and the distributors of U.S. signals
will have to come up with an alternative method. </I>
<P>
<I>And the CRTC also wants to see broadcasters come up with more
top quality, non violent shows aimed at kids. </I>
<P>
<I>The CRTC conducted exhaustive public consultations last fall.
Today's policy announcement responds to the concerns raised in
those venues. </I>
<P>
<I>Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU 10%</H3>

<P>
Striking civil servants are disputing government claims that five
thousand government workers are crossing the picket lines. 
<P>
The government is saying more and more public sector employees
are returning to work every day, despite the OPSEU strike which
has dragged on for 18-days. 
<P>
Management Board Chairman Dave Johnson says the longer the strike
goes on ..the more people cross the picket line. The union says
many of the 5-thousand members who have crossed the picket lines
are management. 
<HR>

<H3>TTC Strike </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, a strike could be brewing at the Toronto Transit Commission.

<P>
The city's unionized transit workers have voted 98 percent in
favor of rejecting the city's most recent contract offer. Their
collective agreement expires at the end of the month. 
<HR>

<H3>Quake Streeters </H3>

<P>
A mild earthquake rattled Montreal and Ottawa this morning, shaking
beds and spooking pets. But there were no injuries or damage.

<P>
The tremor measured 4.5 on the Richter scale and was centered
about 90 kilometres north of Montreal.<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

