<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, March 13, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Hydro Brownouts 
<LI>OFL Labor Protest 
<LI>OPSEU - Jails 
<LI>QP &amp; TTC Pickets 
<LI>Russian roulette 
<LI>Di 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hydro Brownouts </H3>

<P>
Ontario is facing yet another labor dispute and this one could
lead to wide spread power shortages across the province. 
<P>
The 15 thousand unionized employees at Ontario Hydro could be
in a legal strike position by next month. In preparation, the
giant utility is making plans to shut down all of its nuclear
reactors. 
<HR>

<H3>OFL Labor Protest </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Federation of Labor has announced the next site for
a day of protest against the Harris government. It will stage
a protest in the Cambridge- Kitchener -Waterloo area on April
19th. 
<P>
This time around the OFL says it's campaign is aimed at employers
who favor the Harris government's agenda. Previous protests have
been staged in London and Hamilton. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU - Jails </H3>

<P>
As the province-wide strike by civil servants enters its third
week, negotiators for the Ontario government and OPSEU entered
their third day of mediation today. 
<P>
Despite repeated reports that rank-and-file support for the strike
is wavering, a number of picket lines actually bolstered their
numbers today. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>An early-morning show of strength by OPSEU members at Oakville's
Syl Apps Centre, home to high risk young offenders. Pickets blocked
managers from entering and leaving Syl Apps. Union members complain
essential workers are being forced to follow an illegal work schedule.
</I>
<P>
<I>At the Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Detention Centre, there's
no sign support for the strike is weakening, despite complaints
from inmates inside the jail that guards are taking their frustration
with the government out on prisoners. </I>
<P>
<I>A spokesman says the guards are buoyed by the fact mediators
continue to talk to government and OPSEU negotiators in Toronto.
In Hamilton, Deborah Walker, Channel Eleven News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>QP &amp; TTC Pickets </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is seeking an injunction to keep open a
pedestrian tunnel in Toronto that its striking workers have dubbed
&quot;scab alley&quot;. It's not clear when a ruling will be made.

<P>
For the last two mornings, OPSEU and supporters from other unions
have blocked the entrance to the tunnel, which leads from the
subway to the legislature and other government buildings. They
say the tunnel allows workers to avoid picket lines. The union
members want it closed until the strike is over. 
<HR>

<H3>Russian Roulette</H3>

<P>
An 18 year old Mississauga man has died in hospital after playing
a game of Russian roulette. 
<P>
Peel Regional Police say three friends were in the basement of
a Mississauga home last night when one of them passed around a
.38 caliber revolver. Witnesses say Matthew Mastro-Martino put
the gun to his head and fired. 
<P>
An 18 year old is facing a string of weapons related charges.

<HR>

<H3>Di </H3>

<P>
Princess Diana's love life is once again in the British tabloids...
but this time, it's not her impending divorce from prince Charles
that's making headlines.
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

