<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, March 8, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Talks 
<LI>Canhotto-Sentencing
<LI>TTC Inquest 
<LI>Toronto Murder #12 
<LI>Women's Day 
<LI>March Break Travel 
<LI>Unemployment Rate 
<LI>Jobs 
<LI>Leasing Clip 
<LI>GM Plants 
<LI>Hamas House 
<LI>Terror Summit 
<LI>Seal Video Charges 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Talks</H3>

<P>
There has been a break in the provincial government workers strike.
The two sides will go back to the bargaining table on Sunday.

<HR>

<H3>Canhotto-Sentencing</H3>

<P>
The OPSEU strike is being blamed for a delay in the sentencing
of two Cambridge residents in the manslaughter death of two-year-old
Kira Canhotto. 
<P>
The girl's mother, 24-year-old Maria Canhotto, and 57-year-old
neighbor Daniel Aguiar were to have been sentenced in the exorcism
case today. But the OPSEU strike has prevented the completion
of pre-sentencing reports. 
<P>
The judge has adjourned the sentencing to April 12th. 
<HR>

<H3>TTC Inquest</H3>

<P>
A coroner's jury has recommended that an outside agency review
safety in the Toronto Transit Commission. 
<P>
The jury released 18 recommendations today into the subway crash
last August 11th which killed three people. The jury feels the
TTC, the Metro Toronto and Ontario governments should review the
legislation affecting all railway operations in the province,
particularly relating to subways. And that the subways safety
system should be reviewed every two years... the jury also says
Metro Toronto and the Ontario government must commit to proper
funding of the TTC. 
<P>
The jury feels under-funding of the TTC since the 1980's has jeopardized
safety. 
<HR>

<H3>Toronto Murder #12 </H3>

<P>
Metro Toronto police are asking the intended victim of yesterday's
fatal shooting in York to come forward ... police say a young
gunman jumped out of a car and began firing wildly at someone
walking along the sidewalk... but police say the gunman missed
the intended victim and instead shot a thirty one year old woman
carrying a baby .
<P>
Her ten year old son was by her side. 31-year-old Linda Delellis
died a short while later in hospital. Investigators want the man
they believe was the target of the shooting to come forward and
identify the killer if possible.
<HR>

<H3>Women's Day </H3>

<P>
International Women's Day was celebrated across the country today
in different ways. 
<P>
In Toronto, it was a number of demonstrations, including one incident
of civil disobedience. The intersection of King and Bay in downtown
Toronto, the heart of Canada's business section was blocked by
dozens of women demonstrating against cuts by the Harris government.
They staged a sit-in, in the middle of the street, blocking streetcars
and other traffic . 
<P>
After five minutes, police moved in and arrested those who refused
to move. Police say they will be charged with mischief. 
<HR>

<H3>March Break Travel </H3>

<P>
March madness is on. Not the US. basketball tournament: the Canadian
version. The last minute dash out of winter's grasp, and into
the sun. Scot Urquhart reports... 
<P>
<I>It's one of the busiest travel times of the year in Canada
... march break. </I>
<P>
<I>12 thousand passengers went through Pearson Airport today ...
thousands more headed down the road ... to the US. border ...
</I>
<P>
<I>And this is what they are heading for: cold weather and cold
economy.... travel agents are busy, and Canadians are fed up.
</I>
<P>
<I>Dave Hunter wrote the book on traveling south; literally ...
he says if you want to avoid the crowds on the i-75 ... don't
stick to your usual schedule: time shift your lunch too. Two o'clock
is good ... and you'll miss most of the crowds. </I>
<P>
<I>And if you want to save on gas ... Hunter says don't fill up
at night, fill up in the morning, when gas is cooler and more
dense. </I>
<P>
<I>And when you finally reach your little piece of paradise; remember
the cardinal rule: don't look like a tourist: don't leave valuables
where thieves can see them in a rental car. If you do... you probably
wont, be bringing them home. Don't flash money around ... and
don't wander around in areas off the beaten path especially after
dark. </I>
<P>
<I>And one final tip if you're driving home at the end of march
break ... the i-75 will be closed in Toledo ... take the 475 by-pass
to stern road ... and then head east... back to the highway. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton Scot Urquhart, Channel Eleven News.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Unemployment Rate </H3>

<P>
Some good news on the economic front as Canadians digest the contents
of the budget. 
<P>
There was more solid job growth in February, but the overall unemployment
rate stayed put at 9.6 per cent. 
<P>
Statistics Canada said employment grew by 44,000 jobs during the
month, well over half of them full-time. 
<P>
In the golden horseshoe the unemployment rate rose slightly in
Toronto, Hamilton and the Niagara area.
<P>
Meanwhile, the American economy produced 705-thousand jobs last
month, cutting the US jobless rate to 5.5 per cent. Analysts had
expected about 300-thousand new jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Leasing Clip </H3>

<P>
There's a report that Ottawa is going to allow the banks into
the car leasing business and that has car dealers fuming... the
leasing of cars and other small home appliances is a growth business.
And many are asking if the cash rich banks really need any more
money... but analysts say its the wave of the future. 
<HR>

<H3>GM Plants </H3>

<P>
A strike at two General Motors brake plants in Dayton, Ohio has
idled some of the company's assembly plants here in Ontario. The
two car plants in Oshawa, and another in Delaware have been forced
to cease production today. 
<P>
As many as 65-hundred workers in Oshawa have been told not to
report to work until further notice. The Ohio strike is into its
fourth day. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamas House</H3>

<P>
Israel and the Palestinians teamed up to take further punitive
steps against Islamic militants ... a top Hamas official was arrested...
and a Palestinian house in the West Bank was dynamited by Israeli
forces... 
<P>
The house belonged to the suicide bomber responsible for last
Sunday's attack that killed eighteen people. Four suicide bombings
have killed sixty one Israelis in the last few weeks. 
<HR>

<H3>Terror Summit </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile Prime Minister Jean Chretien will be attending next
week's summit on terrorism in Egypt. 
<P>
President Clinton and Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak will be
co-chairmen of the conference on fighting the threat terrorism
has on the mid-east peace process. 
<P>
The summit follows the four suicide bombings in Israel since February
25th that have killed a total of 61 people. 
<HR>

<H3>Seal Video Charges </H3>

<P>
Four Newfoundlanders who are seen on an amateur video have been
charged with breaking the seal hunt laws. 
<P>
The video was used in an anti-sealing campaign by the British-based
International Fund for Animal Welfare. The charges against the
four, who are from petty Harbour, include the illegal use of a
rifle and a gaff to hunt seals. 
<P>

