<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, March 6, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Locals-Budget
<LI>Tool Kit
<LI>Casket Store
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Locals - Budget </H3>

<P>
Call it deficit reduction without tears or taxes. Finance Minister
Paul Martin delivered a good news budget today that adds muscle
to his deficit fighting strategy with minimal sting for ordinary
Canadians. 
<HR>

<H3>Tool Kit </H3>

<P>
In other news tonight, Education Minister John Snobelen has unveiled
his long promised &quot;tool kit&quot; to help Ontario school
boards deal with deep spending cuts. 
<P>
The province will delay construction of new schools for at least
a year and will look into hiring non-teachers as counselors and
librarians to help school boards save money. Legislation will
also be introduced to allow boards to negotiate the number of
sick days teachers get. 
<HR>

<H3>Casket Store </H3>

<P>
It's already accepted in the United States and most of Europe,
and now shopping for a casket outside of a funeral home has begun
here in Canada. 
<P>
Two Burlington brothers have just opened up &quot;The Casket Store&quot;,
trying to make a departure from traditional funeral arrangements.
Annette Hamm paid them a visit. 
<P>
<I>Alex Carey and his brother Stan want to make shopping for the
last thing you'll need on earth a bit like shopping for a piece
of furniture. They've opened a showroom on Burlington's Harvester
Road as a lower cost alternative to buying a casket in a funeral
home. </I>
<P>
<I>In many cases, Carey says caskets here cost fifty per cent
less because their overhead is lower. Like a retail store, they'll
deliver what you buy when you need it. </I>
<P>
<I>Most of their clients so far are families who know a death
is imminent. </I>
<P>
<I>Knowing people may be a little afraid of the product at first,
Alex encourages them to take a hands on approach. He wants customers
to feel the fabric they or their loved ones will rest in. He encourages
you to pull on the handles or lift the lid. </I>
<P>
<I>Eventually, the Carey brothers want to expand into floral arrangements
and monuments, making their store a one stop shop for funeral
products. </I>
<P>
<I>In Burlington, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News.</I>  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

