<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, March 5, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU - QP 
<LI>Ont. Resp. Gov. 
<LI>Snobelen-Cuts 
<LI>Brantford VON. 
<LI>Budget Advance 
<LI>Child Support 
<LI>Israel Follow 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU - QP </H3>

<P>
Most of southern Ontario is still digging out from the latest
winter storm. And the strike by provincial civil servants hasn't
help matters any. 
<P>
<I>The storm that swept across the southern and central parts
of Ontario, dumping anywhere from ten to fifteen centimetres of
snow.. closed schools, stopped school buses and brought morning
rush hour to a virtual standstill in most communities. </I>
<P>
<I>The Ministry of Transportation says 250 snow plows and sander
trucks were called into service. That's about a hundred fewer
than usual. </I>
<P>
<I>Management Board chairman Dave Johnson says the government
and the striking civil service union have agreed to do more to
keep the province's highways clear. Transportation Minister Al
Palladini says in some areas the plows are not getting out fast
enough. He says safety is his main concern. </I>
<P>
<I>Meanwhile, a business lobby group called Ontarians for Responsible
Government says its time to end OPSEU's monopoly on snowplowing.
Its calling on the Harris government to pass legislation immediately
that would allow for contracting out of snow plowing services.
</I>
<P>
<I>Cabinet ministers had to run the gauntlet to get inside the
legislature building today.. and had to put up with some vitriolic
comments from government workers. </I>
<P>
<I>Another group of protesters in the shadow of the snow shrouded
parliament buildings.. carried placards to show the public how
many services are being affected by the strike. The union is still
upset about some government workers who sneak through an underground
tunnel to get to work. In Toronto, Bob Ireland, Channel 11 News.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Ont. Resp. Gov. </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, a group called Ontarians for Responsible Government,
wants snowplowing contracted out. It says the government should
immediately pass legislation to allow private contractors to sand,
salt and plow the roads. 
<P>
The organization says it's time to end the union monopoly on highway
snowplowing. Adding, it's intolerable that motorists should have
to risk their safety driving on dangerous highways. 
<HR>

<H3>Snobelen-Cuts </H3>

<P>
The Peel Board of Education has handed out about 500 layoff notices
to teachers and teaching assistants. 
<P>
The Peel board is just one of many across the province, firing
teachers to deal with government cuts. In light of the layoffs,
Education Minister John Snobelen says he doesn't want to see larger
class sizes. The education minister is expected to announce the
long awaited tool-kit this week, to help school boards cut some
400-million dollars from their budgets. 
<HR>

<H3>Brantford VON </H3>

<P>
And provincial cutbacks, and the changing needs of clients, have
forced the Victorian Order of Nurses to radically restructure
home care service it provides in Brant and Haldimand- Norfolk.
And the changes could have a profound impact on both the pay,
and the hours worked by the nearly 300 home-makers currently employed
by the VON.  Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>The Brant-Norfolk- Haldimand branch of the Victorian Order
of Nurses is contracted by the provincially- funded home care
agency to provide everything from personal care to light house-keeping
duties for home care clients. </I>
<P>
<I>Right now the VON's 280 visiting homemakers are mostly casual
employees, who work at their own convenience. But changing home
care eligibility rules, and client needs, have forced the VON
to shift the hours of its home-making workforce. Home-makers have
also been invited to work in three new VON programs, but for twenty
to thirty per cent less pay. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Budget Advance </H3>

<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin says the deficit's back is broken,
but tomorrow's budget is too soon for tax relief. 
<P>
Martin says the annual deficit, as a percentage of the country's
total production, has dropped from six percent in 1993 to four
percent or better this year. And he predicts the government will
hit it's two percent target for 1998. 
<P>
Martin says the government would like to reduce taxes, but the
higher priority is preserving social programs ... however reform
leader Preston Manning is calling that a feeble excuse. 
<HR>

<H3>Child Support</H3>

<P>
The federal government is said to be on the verge of announcing
a major overhaul to Canada's child support system .... parts of
which may be introduced in tomorrow's budget. 
<P>
The Globe and Mail claims Ottawa is planning to scrap the requirement
that divorced parents, receiving child support, pay taxes on that
money. The reforms could also see non custodial parents, in most
cases, men, being unable to claim their payments as a tax deduction.

<HR>

<H3>Israel Follow </H3>

<P>
The military wing of the militant Islamic group Hamas is promising
to stop its attacks on Israelis. But it's not clear if the pledge
will end the recent wave of suicide bombing in Israel. Responsibility
for most of those attacks was claimed by what appear to be Hamas
renegades determined to go on with the violence.  
<P>

