<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, March 4, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Strike - Scabs 
<LI>Barrie Snow 
<LI>Cuts - New Jobs? 
<LI>Suicide Bombings 
<LI>Campaign 96 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Strike -Scabs</H3>

<P>
There was more unrest at the province's jails on this, day eight
of the OPSEU strike. 
<P>
The union says prisoners at Toronto's Don Jail plugged toilets
and lit fires after they were let out of their cells en masse.
And at the Hamilton jail, a hunger strike by 12 female inmates
is slowly spreading to the male population. 
<P>
Last week, in an attempt to quell problems at the Hamilton jail,
the labor relations board issued an order that would prevent no
more than one third of inmates out of their cells at any one time.
But the Solicitor General says, despite the growing unrest, the
government opposes extending that ruling to all jails.
<HR>

<H3>Barrie Snow </H3>

<P>
And the government is threatening to ask the Ontario Labor Relations
Board to order OPSEU to comply with an essential services agreement
on &quot;clearing roads&quot;. 
<P>
Yesterday, one person suffered a heart attack following a 38-vehicle
pileup on highway 400 north of Barrie. It was the second major
highway chain-reaction collision since the OPSEU strike began.

<P>
Police complain ministry snowplows failed to respond to their
calls until after 7 a.m. yesterday. That has Transportation Minister
Al Palladini angry. Under the essential services a agreement,
plows don't have to go out until 12 centimeters of snow has fallen.
<HR>

<H3>Cuts - New Jobs? </H3>

<P>
Will everyone in Ontario soon be unemployed? It might seem that
way when you see the stories of layoffs and jobs cuts, almost
everywhere you turn. 
<P>
13-thousand public sector jobs are on the line, when it seems
the economy is already in rough shape ... how will we ever survive
that kind of a hit? Well according to some economic analysts,
things may not be as bad as they seem: 
<P>
<I>Thirteen thousand of these civil servants will lose their jobs
soon ... as the provincial government cuts back. It seems that
everyone knows someone, who is out of work ... why then ... are
the unemployment and welfare numbers so good? </I>
<P>
<I>At the end of January ... Hamilton had the lowest unemployment
rate in the country ... below seven percent. Ontario as a whole
... was below nine percent .... and while both numbers were up
... the increase was virtually negligible. </I>
<P>
<I>At the same time ... the welfare roles were going down ...
in part due to changes in the system; but no matter how you look
at it, the numbers don't jibe ... with the job cuts we're hearing
about. </I>
<P>
<I>Alan Harrison is the chairman of economics at McMaster University
... he says things are not as bad as they seem ... and in fact,
the economy is actually growing.</I>
<P>
<I>Nick Catalano agrees. He is the Director for Economic Development
in Hamilton Wentworth. He says big jobs losses are being offset
by small companies who are adding staff a dozen or two at a time:
and so, will the loss of 13 thousand jobs cripple an already fragile
economy? it may be too early to tell.</I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton Scot Urquhart Channel Eleven News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Suicide Bombings</H3>

<P>
The Israeli cabinet is meeting in emergency session to discuss
how to deal with a Hamas campaign of terror. 
<P>
A day after Israel declared war on the militant Islamic organization,
a bomb exploded in a Tel Aviv shopping district. 12 people, including
the suicide bomber, are confirmed dead. 
<HR>

<H3>Campaign 96</H3>

<P>
U.S. Senator Bob Dole has won the endorsement of house speaker
Newt Gingrich in the race for the Republican Presidential Nomination.
Dole was in Buffalo today garnering support for tomorrow's super
Tuesday primaries.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

