<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 03/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, March 1, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Jails-Labour Bd. 
<LI>Barrie Riot 
<LI>Workfare
<LI>RCMP Officer Shot 
<LI>Terrorist 
<LI>Peru 
<LI>Menendez 
<LI>Kevorkian 
<LI>Blank Twoonie 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Jails-Labour Bd. </H3>

<P>
On day five of the Ontario public service strike, the union cranked
up the pressure to a media audience, while there were signs that
the solidarity of some jail guards is beginning to weaken. 
<HR>

<H3>Barrie Riot </H3>

<P>
And still with the OPSEU strike, part of the Barrie Jail was evacuated
today after inmates started a fire. 
<P>
A spokesman says a number of inmates lit bedding on fire and threw
it out of the cell area. A corrections service riot squad was
called in to quell the disturbance... minimal damage was reported
and the situation is now under control. 
<HR>

<H3>Workfare</H3>

<P>
Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi says plans for workfare
are on schedule, and he has no intention of leaving community
groups out of the loop. 
<P>
This today in response to a published report suggesting that municipalities
would take on the task of getting those on welfare to do community
work in exchange for their cheques. Anthony Pooley has the details.

<P>
<I>&quot;Workfare&quot;... it's the notion that those who receive
social assistance do community work in return for their welfare
cheques ... and while they do it, they're developing skills that
can be parlayed into a salaried job somewhere. </I>
<P>
<I>Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi says that his ministry
has been meeting with community groups... and they will be in
the loop once the final plans are unveiled. </I>
<P>
<I>As to the notion that such an undertaking might replace other
workers... indeed, Hamilton- Wentworth's Social Services Chairman
wants local consultation ... something the minister says will
soon happen through local MPP's. </I>
<P>
<I>Ted McMeekin says he's not in favour of simply setting up hoops
for those collecting welfare... but... still, the minister is
playing his cards close to the vest in terms of specific plans,
saying only that they're right on target. McMeekin is frustrated
by the lack of specifics.</I>
<P>
<I>In Waterdown... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>RCMP Officer Shot </H3>

<P>
Police in Sault Ste. Marie report no arrests in the wounding of
an RCMP officer who was grazed by a bullet as he left work early
today. Two shots were fired at the officer as he was getting into
a car. 
<HR>

<H3>Terrorist </H3>

<P>
Solicitor General Herb Gray has ordered an RCMP report on how
a convicted Irish terrorist received security clearance to work
on renovation of the parliament buildings. 
<P>
Malachy McAllister had been convicted of attempting to kill a
police officer and was ordered deported from Canada two years
ago. The Reform Party calls the situation a shocking blow to the
safety and security of Canadians. 
<HR>

<H3>Peru </H3>

<P>
The Canadian embassy in Lima, Peru says there were no Canadians
aboard a Faucett airlines plane that crashed into the Andes mountains.
Early reports from the airline had indicated two Canadians were
among the 123 casualties. 
<P>
The embassy in Lima says the plane tickets may have been purchased
here but no Canadian citizens were aboard the flight. The Boeing
7-37 apparently caught fire in flight and slammed into a hillside
in southern Peru. 
<HR>

<H3>Menendez </H3>

<P>
For the second time, the fate of Erik and Lyle Menendez is in
the hands of a jury. 
<P>
A Los Angeles panel began deliberations today in the highly publicized
murder case. The brothers are being retried for the 1989 shotgun
killings of their parents. Their first trials ended in hung juries.

<P>
The defence says the Menendez brothers had been sexually abused
and killed out of fear for their lives. The prosecution says they
killed to inherit their parents multi-million dollar estate. 
<HR>

<H3>Kevorkian </H3>

<P>
Dr. Jack Kevorkian says he sometimes cries after attending suicides.
Kevorkian has taken the stand in his assisted suicide trial in
Pontiac, Michigan. Kevorkian told the jury he feels obligated
to help who are suffering. 
<HR>

<H3>Blank Twoonie </H3>

<P>
Chalk up another one against the Royal Canadian mint. 
<P>
A Hamilton couple aren't sure what their new two dollar coin is
worth ... because it's blank. Steve Gratoni picked up the coin
at a CIBC branch in north Hamilton this morning, and when he brought
it back home his wife Doris noticed there was no polar bear, no
queen and no engraving on the coin. <I> </I>
<P>

