<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/29/96</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, February 29, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Jail Negotiations 
<LI>RRSP Deadline 
<LI>Jordan Verdict 
<LI>School Bus Shooting 
<LI>F. Lee Bailey 
<LI>New Rating 
<LI>Grammy Winners 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Jail Negotiations </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is seeking a court order to ensure striking
jail guards abide by an essential services agreement. 
<P>
The Ontario Labor Relations Board has given OPSEU and the government
a deadline of tomorrow morning to make a deal on staffing levels
at jails during the civil service strike. But the government wants
the court order as insurance. 
<HR>

<H3>RRSP Deadline </H3>

<P>
An annual ritual continues at this hour in financial institutions
and brokerages everywhere. The ritual is last minute RRSP investors
busy sheltering money from the taxman in a number of ways. But
as Anthony Pooley reports tonight... one way is more popular than
the others this year. 
<P>
<I>The deadline for sheltering a little money from the much maligned
taxman is upon us ... and with that comes the usual last minute
line-ups. </I>
<P>
<I>Financial advisors, brokers and institutions will be burning
the midnight oil to get RSP's in before the clock strikes twelve.
</I>
<P>
<I>The number of Canadians saving extra money for retirement rises
each year... and the reason for it may be in the results of an
Angus Reid poll released today. It reveals that only 61 percent
of respondents believe that the Canada Pension Plan will play
a significant role in their retirement income. And faith in CPP
diminishes as the survey sample gets younger. In Hamilton... Anthony
Pooley... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Jordan Verdict </H3>

<P>
The man accused of killing Michael Jordan's father has been found
guilty of first degree murder. 
<P>
James Jordan was killed as he napped in his car along a north
Carolina roadside in 1993. 
<P>
Late this afternoon, 21 year old Daniel Green was found guilty
of first degree murder, first degree robbery and conspiracy. He
could face the death penalty. 
<HR>

<H3>School Bus Shooting </H3>

<P>
Doctors in St. Louis are trying to save a baby after the teenage
mother was shot and killed on a school bus. 
<P>
Police say a teenage gunman wounded the driver and then began
firing at the bus. Two bullets killed the pregnant 15 year old.
The baby is in critical condition.
<HR>

<H3>F. Lee Bailey </H3>

<P>
A federal judge in Florida has ordered attorney F. Lee Bailey
to begin serving a six month jail term for contempt of court.

<P>
The sentence was handed down a short time ago when Bailey failed
to turn over millions of dollars in cash and stock. Bailey says
the money is his as payment from a convicted drug trafficker he
represented. His attorneys are expected to appeal. 
<HR>

<H3>New Rating </H3>

<P>
50 years from now, people may wonder how there ever could have
been t-v programs without ratings. 
<P>
American TV network executives met in Washington today to discuss
their pledge to begin rating programs for sexual and violent content.

<HR>

<H3>Grammy Winners </H3>

<P>
What a night for Canadians at the 38th annual Grammy awards. Superstar
Alanis Morrissette walked off with four awards. Joni Mitchell
won a pair of statues, and country singer Shania Twain, of Timmins
picked up an award for best country album. Kathy Renwald reports.

<P>
<I>Morrissette performed a melancholy and uncensored version of
her winning hit &quot;You Ought to Know&quot; and moments after
went to collect her Grammy for best rock song. Morrissette and
her American producer also won best rock album award for &quot;Jagged
Little Pill&quot;. Morrissette also won best rock vocal for &quot;You
Ought to Know&quot;. </I>
<P>
<I>Shania Twain of Timmins and her producer husband Robert Lange
won the best country album Grammy for &quot;The Woman in Me&quot;.
Twain beat Trisha Yearwood and Dwight Yokum among others in the
category. </I>
<P>
<I>And a Canadian with a legacy of carefully crafted music...
won for best pop album of the year.. Joni Mitchell collected the
honors for &quot;Turbulent Indigo&quot;, beating the music machine
muscle behind Madonna and Mariah Carey.</I>
<P>
<I>Other Canadians to collect Grammy awards.. jazz musician Rob
McConnell ..for a recording with Mel Torme. The luck of St. Catharines
polka king Walter Ostanek ran out last night... he lost in the
best polka album category. </I>
<P>
<I>The thank you speeches were generally tame ..but Bobby McFerrin
lectured teachers on the importance of music in the classroom.
</I>
<P>
<I>Jazz great Dave Brubeck was honored with a lifetime achievement
award song of the year honors went to Seal for &quot;Kiss From
a Rose&quot;.... and all in all a good night for Canadians with
Alanis Morrissette winning four major Grammies. </I> 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

