<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/28/96</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, February 28, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>London Pileup 
<LI>OPSEU Day Three 
<LI>Inspectors-Court 
<LI>Ontario Hydro 
<LI>Tories Poll 
<LI>Liberal Mood 
<LI>Windermere Burns 
<LI>Royal Divorce 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>London Pileup</H3>

<P>
At least one person was killed in a huge chain reaction pile-up
on highway 401 near London this morning. 
<P>
As many as 15 ambulances were called to the scene after 30 cars
and trucks slammed into each other on the slippery highway. Witnesses
call the accident scene a mangled mess, with some cars going into
the ditch and others into nearby fields. 
<P>
The crash is being blamed on extremely slippery conditions after
London was hit by a sudden snowfall this morning. 
<P>
Although the accident comes on the third day of a province-wide
strike by civil servants that has affected snow removal operations,
OPSEU president Leah Casselman says when the storm hit, workers
came off the picket line to run salters and sanders. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Day Three </H3>

<P>
And while the strike may not have caused the horrible pile-up
on the 401, it is causing problems at provincial jails and detention
centers across the province. 
<HR>

<H3>Inspectors-Court </H3>

<P>
Other casualties of the OPSEU strike are the 300 meat processing
plants across the province that rely on provincial inspectors
to operate.... plants that could go out of business before this
dispute is resolved. Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.

<P>
<I>L &amp; V Poultry in Beamsville normally slaughters and packs
80 thousand birds a week. But this week a processing line is idle.
The loading dock empty. </I>
<P>
<I>Today the company began operating with a skeleton staff. The
chickens on this line, chickens that L &amp; V were contracted
to buy from poultry producers were slaughtered and killed by a
larger processing company. A company that has federal inspectors
on staff. an additional cost to the company that it says it can't
afford. But it can't afford to lose customers either. </I>
<P>
<I>Three poultry inspectors work at L &amp; V ...inspectors that
are now on the picket line. Predictions are that the strike will
last about three months. L &amp; V managers says under these conditions
they will be lucky to last three weeks. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Ontario Hydro</H3>

<P>
And still more labor trouble could be brewing in the province.
Talks have broken off between Ontario Hydro and the power workers
union. 
<P>
The current contract expires march 31st, and the two sides, which
have been meeting since December, appear to be miles apart. 
<HR>

<H3>Tories Poll </H3>

<P>
And despite all the labour unrest across the province, a new poll
suggests the Harris conservatives are holding their lead in party
popularity. 
<P>
The survey by Angus Reid-Southam News suggests the Tories have
the support of 46 percent of decided voters. That puts them just
slightly ahead of their share of the popular vote in last June's
election. 
<P>
The poll gives the opposition Liberals 36 percent support, with
the NDP coming in with 15 percent support. 
<HR>

<H3>Liberal Mood </H3>

<P>
With the government's throne speech now out of the way, prime
minister Chretien had some time to do a little bit of parliamentary
house cleaning today. 
<P>
Chretien helped swear in 25 new parliamentary secretaries this
morning. The old team of the so called &quot;ministers in training&quot;
was fired last week. 
<P>
Some backbench Liberal MP's are calling the process unfair, claiming
the decision may even force them to retaliate against their own
government by voting against upcoming bills. 
<HR>

<H3>Windermere Burns </H3>

<P>
One of the &quot;grand old ladies&quot; of Muskoka has been lost.
Windermere house, an historic posh resort on lake Rosseau, was
destroyed by fire last night. 
<P>
The resort was being used as a set for actress Geena Davis' latest
film, &quot;The Long Kiss Goodnight.&quot;  No word on how the
movie will be affected. 
<HR>

<H3>Royal Divorce </H3>

<P>
What could be Britain's most anticipated divorce is finally going
to happen. Princess Diana has agreed to end her marriage to prince
Charles.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

