<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/27/96</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, February 27, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Locals - Throne 
<LI>OPSEU Day Two 
<LI>Cuba Planes 
<LI>Axworthy-Cuba 
<LI>Belgium Pileup 
<LI>France Wines 
<LI>School Uniforms 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Locals - Throne </H3>

<P>
The federal government is prepared to give up substantial powers
to the provinces and create a new social union to keep the country
together. 
<P>
In a speech from the throne, it promises to back out of areas
such as labor training, forestry, mining and recreation. In return,
the government wants provinces to agree to common principles for
social programs and guaranteed access to social services across
the country. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Day Two</H3>

<P>
Neither side is budging in the escalating strike by thousands
of Ontario government workers. The union says by midnight tonight,
all public service employees, except those designated as essential,
will be off the job. 
<HR>

<H3>Cuba Planes </H3>

<P>
The Clinton administration says it has &quot;concrete evidence&quot;
that top Cuban officials approved the downing of two civilian
planes from Florida. 
<P>
Officials say a transcript of radio transmissions show the attacking
MIG pilots, knew they were firing on unarmed civilian aircraft
during the weekend.
<HR>

<H3>Axworthy-Cuba </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy says a bill
before the US congress that would punish Canadian companies that
trade with Cuba, contravenes international law. 
<P>
The bill would deny access to American markets, to firms with
commercial links to Cuba. Axworthy says Canada has taken sufficient
measures by condemning the weekend incident. And he warns, that
US. action against Canada is no solution.
<HR>

<H3>Belgium Pileup </H3>

<P>
A nightmarish accident today on a motorway in Belgium. At least
17 people died and dozens were injured, in a blazing 120-vehicle
pileup in thick fog on a highway in the northwestern part of that
country. 
<P>
Dozens of cars and trucks were piled in a mess of tangled metal.
Police say thick fog touched off the massive pileup.
<HR>

<H3>France Wines </H3>

<P>
The Bordeaux wine industry says it has been severely hit by boycotts
over French nuclear testing in the south pacific. 
<P>
Spokesman Hubert Bouteiller says it will take several years to
repair the damage. He says the boycotts were the worst disaster
for Bordeaux since a 1991 frost cut production in half. 
<P>
French president Jacques Chirac says that, overall, French exports
have been unaffected by calls for boycotts over the tests in French
Polynesia, which ended last month.
<HR>

<H3>School Uniforms </H3>

<P>
School principals in the US are overwhelmingly in favor of uniforms
for their students. 
<P>
According to &quot;USA Today&quot;, a survey finds that 70 percent
of school principals believe violence would be reduced if pupils
were required to wear uniforms at school. The thinking is that
kids wearing designer clothes to school, are more likely to be
targets of crime. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

