<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, February 26, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Ont. On Strike 
<LI>Evng Education 
<LI>Hospital Cuts Follow 
<LI>Ranger Arrested 
<LI>Israel 
<LI>N. Ireland Update 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Ont. On Strike</H3>

<P>
For the first time in its history, Ontario's civil service has
been hit by a strike. jails, ambulance services, driver's licence
bureaus, psychiatric hospitals and snowplow operators are just
some of the services affected. 
<P>
Over 25 thousand public sector workers walked off the job this
morning but that number could swell to 55 thousand mid-week if
an agreement isn't reached. 
<HR>

<H3>Evng Education </H3>

<P>
It's Black Monday for employees with the Hamilton Board of Education.
This afternoon the board announced the layoff of more than one
thousand employees, that includes 437 secondary and elementary
teaching positions. 
<HR>

<H3>Hospital Cuts Follow </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, despite a campaign promise not to chop any money from
health care, hospitals in southern Ontario are reeling from the
massive spending cuts imposed by the Harris government. Lauran
Sabourin has that story. 
<P>
<I>While Hamilton East MPP Dominic Agostino is charging that Premier
Mike Harris should lose his job, Harris policies are guaranteeing
that hundreds possibly thousands of health care workers in the
province will lose theirs. </I>
<P>
<I>The numbers are sobering. Hamilton Civic Hospitals had its
budget slashed by 14.6 million dollars and St. Catharines General
loses 3.5 million from its budget. These spending cuts mean hundreds
of jobs are at stake. </I>
<P>
<I>St. Catharines General has made serious efforts to cut costs
over the years: wings have been shut off; beds have been closed;
a closed wing that looks like it belongs in hospital in Bosnia.
The rooms are empty. No lavish spending here. </I>
<P>
<I>But St. Catharines General has to search for ways to cut back
the budget even more. Budget cutting that the public will notice.
Factory-like health delivery that will have little effect on quality.
St. Catharines General the busiest in the peninsula has been searching
for ways to move more patients more efficiently through the system.
But it feels the government may not have looked at those numbers
closely enough. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Ranger Arrested </H3>

<P>
A man wanted in the August slayings of two metro Toronto sisters
was denied bail in a Scarborough court today. 
<P>
20 year old Rohan ranger was remanded in custody. He'll be back
in court March 11th. 
<P>
Ranger, who was returned from Jamaica yesterday, and his cousin
Adrian Kinkead, are charged with first degree murder in the deaths
of Marsha and Tamara Ottey. 
<HR>

<H3>Israel </H3>

<P>
Israel's prime minister is keeping his country on the road to
peace. Shimon Peres told the Israeli legislature today that working
for peace is the only &quot;correct choice&quot; Israel can make.

<P>
The comments come following weekend bombings by Islamic suicide
bombers which killed 27 people. 
<HR>

<H3>N. Ireland Update </H3>

<P>
Soldiers carrying assault rifles are standing guard outside the
Queen's London palace today. 
<P>
The extra security measures were imposed after police found bomb
making equipment and documents at the house of an Irish republican
army guerrilla. 
<P>
The heightened security comes as British diplomats and Sinn Fein,
the political representative of the Irish republican army, met
for the first time since IRA bombs in London broke a 17 month
cease-fire.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

