<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, February 23, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Day of Protest 
<LI>Tory Convention 
<LI>Casselman Invu. 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Day of Protest</H3>

<P>
Thousands of placard waving demonstrators filled the streets of
downtown Hamilton today to protest Ontario government spending
cuts and labor law changes. 
<P>
As many as 25 thousand people took part in today's &quot;Day of
Action&quot;, and estimates are that number could triple as even
more demonstrators head to the steeltown for yet another march
planned for tomorrow. Reporter Dwight Ryan has been covering today's
events. 
<P>
(Dwight) Donna, today's rally was the first of two days of action
sponsored by the Hamilton and District Labour council. In December,
workers and their supporters attempted to shut down London...
to no avail... this time, the city of Hamilton ground to a halt
as the downtown core was sealed off. 
<P>
<I>They gathered at Dundurn Park in the shadow of Dundurn castle.
Such a historic setting was appropriate, since it was in Hamilton
that the organized labour movement in Canada began. </I>
<P>
<I>Determined to get their message through to Mike Harris and
his Tories, they marched arm in arm through the streets of Hamilton.
But along the route, there was at least one indication that not
everyone is unhappy with the Mike Harris government. </I>
<P>
<I>Crowd estimates were as high as 25-thousand. Downtown Hamilton
was sealed off with no traffic coming into or leaving the city
core. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton police stood by nervously hoping the protest would
remain peaceful. Tactical squads from Halton, Toronto and the
OPP stood by if needed. The crowd eventually poured into Copps
coliseum for an afternoon rally. </I>
<P>
<I>The demonstrators were fired up by a succession of speakers,
including Leah Casselman, the head of OPSEU. Her 67-thousand government
employees are set for a province-wide strike at midnight Sunday.
</I>
<P>
<I>CUPE leader Syd Ryan and Canadian Labour Congress chief Bob
White never got to speak as the program dragged on and the crowd
dispersed. But for Mike Harris and his Progressive Conservatives,
meeting a block away at the fortified Convention Centre, the message
was clear. That thousands of Ontario residents are unhappy with
his common sense revolution.</I> 
<P>
(Dwight) and Donna, organizers say this Hamilton protest won't
go unnoticed by Mike Harris and his government. They promise to
dog the premier throughout his term at Queens Park and that the
Hamilton shutdown will not be the last. 
<P>
The Action Days committee says 75-thousand people will take part
in day two of their protest. Hamilton downtown will again be shut
down when the demonstration starts again tomorrow.
<HR>

<H3>Tory Convention</H3>

<P>
(Donna) thanks Dwight. And as Dwight mentioned, tomorrow, labour
will take to the streets one more time, to show it's displeasure
with Tory policy... as the Ontario conservatives convene in this
city. 
<HR>

<H3>Casselman Invu.</H3>

<P>
One person who did agree to an interview today is a woman poised
to lead Ontario civil servants on their first strike... I spoke
with Leah Casselman, president of the Ontario Public Service Employees
Union from Copps Coliseum earlier today.  
<P>

