<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, February 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Talks 
<LI>Harris Niagara
<LI>Protest Opponents 
<LI>Prison Suicide 
<LI>Kids 
<LI>Nfld. Elex 
<LI>Diana 
<LI>Pavarotti 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Talks</H3>

<P>
The union representing the province's civil servants have given
the Tory government an ultimatum.... if there's no contract agreement
by midnight Sunday, members of the Ontario public sector employees
union will hit the picket lines. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris Niagara</H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris is in Niagara Falls tonight... the premier
is accepting accolades on behalf of the city's Chamber of Commerce...
originally, organizers had hoped this would help boost the premier's
image, however, on the eve of a union rally in Hamilton, opponents
were quick to take advantage of the situation. 
<HR>

<H3>Protest Opponents</H3>

<P>
There are those who don't agree with what organized labour is
doing. Some represent groups that advocate the measures being
taken by the Harris government; others are just ordinary folk
who don't want to see the regular business of any city grind to
a screeching halt. Anthony Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>As preparations continue for the huge organized labour demonstration
tomorrow and Saturday, there are those who believe that the province's
unions are barking up the wrong tree. Not the least of those is
Gerry Nichols. He represents a right wing lobby group that supports
the Harris government ... a group that believes the majority of
Ontarians do not support the position of organized labour. </I>
<P>
<I>Indeed, Ontarians for Responsible Government thinks the days
of protest will be a huge flop. But it isn't only right wing lobby
groups that are astounding up to be counted in their anti- protest
view. Some ordinary people don't want to see the protests, either.
</I>
<P>
<I>Still, the notion of a big flop for the protest days certainly
tests credulity. More than that, ORG president Colin Brown...
who originally made the prediction ... will be far away from here
this weekend... apparently on a pre-arranged business trip that
could not be canceled. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Prison Suicide</H3>

<P>
An inmate at the prison for women in Kingston has been found hanging
in her cell. 
<P>
A corrections Canada spokesman says the 31 year old was found
dead in her cell last night. She had apparently torn up a pillowcase
to make a noose. 
<P>
Officials won't release her name ... all they will say is that
she was from Hamilton and was serving five years for robbery,
assault, theft and fraud. 
<HR>

<H3>Kids </H3>

<P>
Victims rights groups want to see some action from Ottawa on reforming
the justice system. Today a nation wide alliance gave the government
a list of 67 ways to protect the country's children. 
<P>
One of the demands is that the faint hope clause that allows first
degree murderers to apply for parole after serving less than 15
years be changed. 
<HR>

<H3>Nfld. Elex .</H3>

<P>
Newfoundlanders are choosing who will represent them in the provincial
legislature. And, with blue skies and unseasonably warm temperatures,
the voter turnout is expected to be high. 
<P>
When he cast his ballot at a community hall outside corner brook,
Premier Brian Tobin refused to predict the outcome of the election.
<HR>

<H3>Diana </H3>

<P>
Britain's Diana, Princess of Wales, is in Pakistan on a visit
that is being touted as both charitable and political. 
<HR>

<H3>Pavarotti </H3>

<P>
Superstar tenor Luciano Pavarotti is said to have fallen for his
secretary. He's 60 ... she's 26. 
<P>
An Italian gossip magazine quotes Pavarotti as saying they're
&quot;very happy&quot;, but the situation with his wife of 35
years is &quot;delicate&quot;. there are rumors a divorce is pending.
 
<P>

