<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, February 21, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Insurance Hikes 
<LI>Cigarette 
<LI>OPP Raid-Runciman 
<LI>Van Smirnis 
<LI>Olson 
<LI>Johnson-OPSEU
<LI>Buchanon 
<LI>Australia Euthanasia 
<LI>Potty Killing 
<LI>Old Woman 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Insurance Hikes</H3>

<P>
One of Ontario's largest auto insurance companies warns if the
Harris government goes ahead with proposed changes to the auto
insurance system, premiums will go through the roof. 
<HR>

<H3>Cigarette </H3>

<P>
Health Minister David Dingwall is hinting he'll move to get tobacco
ads off the street. 
<P>
For the first time since 1989, the tobacco companies are pushing
their wares in billboards and newspaper ads. 
<P>
Dingwall says the ads appear to focus on young people, even though
the tobacco companies said they would not do that. 
<HR>

<H3>OPP Raid-Runciman </H3>

<P>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman is backing OPP tactical units that
burst into two Ontario homes by mistake this past week. 
<P>
In the early hours of Monday morning, OPP officers, armed with
a search warrant, crashed in the door of a Caledonia home. However,
after a quick search of the house, they realized they had made
a mistake. The same thing happened Saturday to an Orangeville
family. 
<P>
Runciman says the province should be proud of the OPP emergency
tactical force, for the dangerous work it does. However, Runciman
does say he will looking into the intelligence work behind the
decisions of the tactical team.
<HR>

<H3>Van Smirnis </H3>

<P>
The day after Kristen French's body was found, Paul Bernardo's
best friend suggested police check out Bernardo. Now Van Smirnis
is seeking the 100 thousand-dollar reward offered by the Toronto
Sun newspaper soon after French's murder. 
<P>
Police documents suggest Smirnis' May 1st, 1992, tip was passed
on to both Halton and Niagara regional police. Bernardo was questioned
less than two weeks later but he wasn't arrested for another nine
months.
<HR>

<H3>Olson </H3>

<P>
Serial killer Clifford Olson won't get a hearing before the Supreme
Court of Canada. 
<P>
Olson was fighting his 1992 transfer from the Kingston Penitentiary
in Ontario to the special segregation unit at the Saskatchewan
penitentiary in Prince Albert. 
<P>
Olson was moved after he was found with a key to his handcuffs
and leg irons. 
<HR>

<H3>Johnson-OPSEU </H3>

<P>
The chairman of the Management Board of the Ontario Cabinet, says
a strike by public sector workers may be inevitable. 
<P>
Dave Johnson says that's because the province can't afford the
union's demands. Meanwhile, the civil service union and the government
can't agree on whether there is a news blackout on negotiations.
The union says there isn't. But the government says both sides
agreed to one. 
<HR>

<H3>Buchanon </H3>

<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy doesn't like what US presidential
hopeful Pat Buchanon is saying about trade agreements with Canada.

<P>
Axworthy says the right wing republican should take a close look
at those trade accords, because they have created hundreds of
thousands of jobs on both sides of the border. 
<P>
Buchanon, who won his party's New Hampshire primary last night,
has been calling trade accords with Canada a job killer. 
<HR>

<H3>Australia Euthanasia </H3>

<P>
The parliament of Australia's northern territory has passed what's
believed to be the world's first law giving dying adults the right
to end their lives. 
<P>
Doctors will be able to help consenting patients to kill themselves
provided the patients are of sound mind and have less than a year
to live. 
<HR>

<H3>Potty Killing </H3>

<P>
In New York City, the father of a two year old boy has been arrested
after telling police he beat his son to death while trying to
toilet train him. 
<P>
Kevin Mikell's body was bruised, had cigarette burns and a dislocated
arm. The child had been under the care of the city's child protection
agency but was returned to his parents within the last year. 
<HR>

<H3>Old Woman </H3>

<P>
The woman believed to be the world's oldest person celebrated
her 121st birthday today. 
<P>
Several hundred guests attended a party for (zhen) Calment in
a small town in the south of France. Calment was born February
21st, 1875 and is listed in the Guinness Book of World Records
as the oldest living person.  
<P>

