<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, February 20, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Kinkaid Arrival 
<LI>Abbotsford Killer 
<LI>Bomb Venue 
<LI>Protester
<LI>Caledonia 
<LI>More OPSEU 
<LI>Pacifier Recall 
<LI>Mint Problems
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Kinkaid Arrival </H3>

<P>
Police officers armed with machine guns greeted the arrival of
triple murder suspect Adrian Kinkead at Toronto International
Airport late this afternoon. 
<HR>

<H3>Abbotsford Killer</H3>

<P>
Woman and children in Abbotsford, British Columbia are once again
being told not to walk the streets alone. 
<P>
A man, claiming to be the killer of a 16 year old girl, has the
city terrified after taunting police again by phone. They say
he called them from a pay phone last night. The man is believed
to have desecrated her grave by ripping up her headstone, writing
on it and leaving it on the roof of a radio station news cruiser.

<HR>

<H3>Bomb Venue </H3>

<P>
In world news tonight, a US judge says the defendants right to
a fair trial is the top priority, so he's moving the Oklahoma
bombing trial to Denver. 
<P>
The head of a bombing survivors group says the decision is disappointing,
but he agrees a fair trial is vital. 
<P>
The bombing ten months ago, killed 169 people and injured more
than 500.
<HR>

<H3>Protester</H3>

<P>
Demonstrator Bill Clennett says despite what he calls the aggression
of Jean Chretien last week, he will not press charges against
the prime minister. 
<HR>

<H3>Caledonia</H3>

<P>
Provincial police in Cayuga are apologizing profusely to a Caledonia
couple tonight. 
<P>
John and Jean Goddard were awoken from their sleep yesterday morning
by the sound of their front door being smashed in by tactical
officers. The couple was forced to the floor at gunpoint and tied
up while officers executed a search warrant on their home. 
<P>
Police had been acting on a tip that the Goddard's were operating
a marijuana growing operation. Police admit they were wrong and
will pay for damages to their home. 
<HR>

<H3>More OPSEU </H3>

<P>
As of next Monday, tens of thousands of Ontario government workers
are in a legal strike position. Although the government says the
cupboard is bare, the union remains optimistic an agreement can
be reached. 
<P>
Still, both sides are miles apart on their estimates of what such
a deal will cost. Dwight Ryan has that story. 
<P>
<I>In a downtown Toronto hotel, last ditch talks continue between
the union representing tens of thousands of government employees
and the government. In numerous rooms spread throughout the massive
hotel, the two sides try to hammer out an agreement with the help
of mediator John Mather. </I>
<P>
<I>Neither side will say how its going. but management board chairman
Dave Johnson told reporters Monday that the union's demands would
cost the province more than two billion dollars. And he said the
current offer is all there is, no matter how you slice it. </I>
<P>
<I>The Ontario Public Service Employees Union represents 67 thousand
provincial government workers. Of those 12 thousand are deemed
essential workers, the other 55 thousand earned the right to strike
back in 1994. </I>
<P>
<I>The unions scoffs at the government figures in the meantime,
the talks drag on and no strike date has yet been set. </I>
<P>
<I>In Toronto, Dwight Ryan, Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Pacifier Recall</H3>

<P>
Health Canada is warning consumers to stop using the &quot;Fun
'n Fruity&quot; pacifier from Playskool. 
<P>
The nipple could tear off and choke a child. The affected pacifier
is model 3-1-0-5. They have mouthguards in the shape of an apple,
orange or grapes, with green handles attached. 
<P>
No problems have been reported, but some nipples tore off during
recent routine tests by Health Canada. 
<P>
About 12-hundred of the pacifiers have been sold since October.
They can be returned to the store where they were bought for refund
or exchange. 
<HR>

<H3>Mint Problems</H3>

<P>
It was introduced just yesterday, but already the new two dollar
coin may be a bust. 
<P>
Hamilton resident Mabel Decaire accidentally dropped one of the
newly minted coins and it split into two pieces... a silver colored
ring and a tiny gold disc the size of a shirt button.  
<P>

