<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, February 16, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>School Boards 
<LI>Voter Turnout 
<LI>Chretien Clip 
<LI>Kinkead Search 
<LI>Shooting Club 
<LI>Ipperwash Arrests 
<LI>Ski Fatal 
<LI>Tanker Spill 
<LI>Niagara MVA 
<LI>Hampton Running?
<LI>Chrysler 
<LI>Auto Preview 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>School Boards</H3>

<P>
The province can do without half of its school boards... that's
the bottom line in a report from an education task force. 
<P>
The report says a hundred and twenty million dollars could be
saved ... the school boards are fixing for a fight. 
<HR>

<H3>Voter Turnout </H3>

<P>
Civil servants from across Ontario, turned out in heavy numbers
to vote on the latest contract offer from the provincial government.

<P>
The members of OPSEU are facing massive layoffs, and union executives
say the government offer does nothing to protect their jobs ...
or their pensions. 
<P>
Up to 80 percent of the union membership is expected to vote,
province wide. OPSEU expects to receive a strong mandate to strike
from its membership, but many are saying that the vote could be
extremely close. 
<HR>

<H3>Chretien Clip</H3>

<P>
It's been the topic of the day ... the Prime Minister throttling
a protester in Hull, Quebec yesterday was the issue at water coolers,
and on talk shows all day long... some of the newspaper headlines
across the country included: the Shawinigan Scuffler, Bully or
Hero, Hull Hogan, True Grit, By the Throat, and Bring on Bouchard.

<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Sheila Copps says security for Chretien
was not adequate because the RCMP didn't form enough of a &quot;wedge&quot;
to block protesters from reaching the Prime Minister... and she's
calling for a review of how the Prime Minister is protected when
he meets with people in a crowd. 
<P>
Meanwhile, the man involved in the altercation with the PM isn't
saying whether he will file a complaint or not. The RCMP say if
a complaint is filed, they will investigate but it's up to the
crown to decide whether to file charges. 
<P>
Chretien himself has refused to answer any questions about the
incident today. 
<HR>

<H3>Kinkead Search </H3>

<P>
The massive manhunt for 20-year-old Adrian Kinkead in Toronto
has resulted in dozens of false alarms. Kinkead is the prime suspect
in three murders and two gunpoint rapes. 
<P>
At least four times yesterday, heavily-armed police officers swooped
down on bus stops, subways and apartments after getting calls
from people who thought they saw the fugitive. Today is the fifth
day of the search for Kinkead who is wanted in the stabbing deaths
of two Scarborough sisters and a subway ticket taker. 
<P>
There are reports this morning that frustrated investigators now
think Kinkead may have fled the city. Investigators now say Kinkead
has been ruled out as a suspect in the slaying of Toronto nanny
last weekend. Her body was found in the stairwell of a high-rise
apartment. 
<HR>

<H3>Shooting Club </H3>

<P>
A man is in critical condition after he was shot in the chest
at a nightclub in suburban Toronto early today. 
<P>
Police say the 32-year-old man and his girlfriend were leaving
the Epiphany night club in North York when they were approached
by several men. One man pointed a handgun and fired without provocation,
hitting the man in the chest. 
<P>
Police say the victim underwent emergency surgery for the life-threatening
injury at Sunnybrook Medical Centre. No suspects have been arrested.

<HR>

<H3>Ipperwash Arrests </H3>

<P>
Five months after a deadly incident at Ipperwash Provincial Park
in Ontario, police have issued arrest warrants for two aboriginal
protesters. The warrants are in connection to the incident where
protesters drove through a fence with a car and a school bus,
injuring an officer. 
<P>
Police have not yet made any arrests in the death of protester
Dudley George or in injuries suffered by two other protesters
shot during the melee.
<HR>

<H3>Ski Fatal</H3>

<P>
A 26-year-old Mississauga man has died in a skiing accident near
Collingwood. 
<P>
Police say Jeffrey MacNeil lost control while going over some
moguls yesterday and hit a tree. He died a few hours later at
Collingwood Hospital from massive internal injuries. It's not
known yet if there will be an inquest. 
<HR>

<H3>Tanker Spill </H3>

<P>
Environmental workers are racing to contain a growing oil spill
from a grounded oil supertanker off western Wales. 
<P>
The &quot;sea empress&quot; has already lost 6.8-million litres
of its cargo. Scientists say the eight-kilometre long slick will
likely pose a threat to wildlife on the Welsh coast. 
<P>
The Liberian registered tanker was carrying a full load of north
sea crude oil from Scotland to the US.
<HR>

<H3>Niagara MVA </H3>

<P>
Niagara residents are getting a closer look at just what market
value assessment will mean to them ... their assessments have
arrived in the mail...and as Dwight Ryan reports.. there are some
happy people... and some not so happy people. 
<P>
<I>Ideally, market value assessment means fairer taxes for everyone.
Those who were paying too little would pay more... those whose
taxes were too high would pay less. </I>
<P>
<I>In the Niagara region homeowners and business people are finding
that MVA often seems more unfair than fair. </I>
<P>
<I>Restaurant owner Wayne Fertich found that he'd be facing a
tax hike of 75%. But the 1992 value of his property, determined
by regional officials, was 125 thousand dollars more than he paid
for it in 1992. Fertich got a tax assessor to take another look.
Even so, his taxes will go up by nearly fifty percent.</I>
<P>
<I>At the Brass and Wicker House, Luba Yewman learned that her
taxes would skyrocket to 15 thousand a year. But regional officials
had made a mistake. She'll find out Monday what the final figure
is. </I>
<P>
<I>Grimsby residents are getting more information at MVA open
houses offered by the region. Overwhelmingly they are unhappy.
Those unhappy with their assessment have the right to appeal.
In Grimsby, Dwight Ryan, channel 11 news. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Hampton Running? </H3>

<P>
The race to replace Bob Rae is starting to get a little crowded.
Rainy River MPP Howard Hampton plans to announce on Monday whether
or not he will seek the Ontario NDP leadership. 
<P>
Hampton says he's backed by nine of the party's 10 northern MPPs,
plus a lot of former members. 
<P>
Hampton is married to Sudbury East MPP Shelley Martel. 
<P>
Toronto MPP Tony Silipo, Welland Thorold's Peter Kormos and former
cabinet minister Frances Lankin are already in the race. 
<HR>

<H3>Chrysler </H3>

<P>
A day after Ford announced it's creating 150 new jobs in Oakville,
there's word Chrysler will expand its operations in Ontario. 
<P>
The Globe and Mail says the automaker will soon announce that
it's spending a half billion dollars to overhaul its Brampton
assembly plant. The move would make the plant the sole producer
of 1998 l-h model sedans, which include the Dodge Intrepid, Eagle
Vision and Chrysler Concorde. About 32-hundred people work at
the Brampton plant, turning out one thousand cars a day. 
<HR>

<H3>Auto Preview </H3>

<P>
Are they talking about sex or cars... the Canadian International
Auto Show is underway in Toronto at the Metro Toronto Convention
Centre and SkyDome runs for nine days.. and the way car makers
talk about their vehicles is downright salacious. 
<P>
It's ten bucks to get into the world's biggest garage...and feast
your eyes on everything from a Lada to a Lamberguini... futuristic
models are also on display including a smart car, which barely
requires the aid of a driver. 
<P>

