<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, February 14, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Killer Evng 
<LI>Olbr-OPSEU
<LI>Bulbrook Noon 
<LI>Simpson 
<LI>Tunnel 
<LI>Singapore Druggie 
<LI>Girl Tethered 
<LI>New Zealand Whales 
<LI>Pet Dental Care 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Killer Evng </H3>

<P>
One of the largest manhunts in Toronto's history continues today
for a man being sought in connection with three killings. 
<P>
20 year old Adrian Kincaid is wanted in the slayings of teenage
sisters Tamara and Marsha Ottey of Scarborough and subway ticket
collector Dimitrija trah-ches-kee. Police say DNA evidence has
linked all three killings. 
<HR>

<H3>Olbr- OPSEU </H3>

<P>
The first-ever strike vote by unionized provincial civil servants
will begin as scheduled tomorrow. However, the Ontario Labor Relations
Board will also hold a hearing tomorrow to determine whether OPSEU
is giving its members &quot;fair and reasonable access&quot; to
the vote. 
<P>
The decision came today after the board heard a complaint from
a civil servant that OPSEU's voting arrangements make it too hard
to cast ballots. 
<HR>

<H3>Bulbrook Noon </H3>

<P>
A hemophiliac infected with HIV from tainted blood says authorities
have reversed themselves and agreed to give him compensation.

<P>
Mark Bulbrook had intended to complain to a Toronto news conference
today abut a decision not to give him compensation unless his
children gave up their right to sue governments and blood agencies.
But Bulbrook says the Canadian Blood Agency phoned him late last
night to tell him he would receive compensation and his children
could keep their right to sue. 
<HR>

<H3>Simpson </H3>

<P>
The depositions resumed today in Los Angeles for the OJ. Simpson
civil trial. On the hot seat today... Kato Kaelin, Simpson's former
houseguest. 
<HR>

<H3>Tunnel </H3>

<P>
Rescue workers in northern Japan say it may take several more
days before they can reach 20 people trapped inside a highway
tunnel. Crews today finally blasted apart a 50 thousand tonne
boulder that collapsed on the tunnel Saturday. 
<HR>

<H3>Singapore Druggie</H3>

<P>
A 43 year old Canadian may be put to death in Singapore. Ronald
Wilson McCulloch is charged with drug trafficking after police
discovered 1.3 kilograms of marijuana in his house. 
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy says consular officials
have visited McCulloch in prison and provided some legal advice.

<P>
A drug trafficking conviction in Singapore means an automatic
sentence of death by hanging.
<HR>

<H3>Girl Tethered </H3>

<P>
A 15 year old girl who had been ordered tethered to her mother,
is back in the custody of the state of south Carolina. A judge
says she needs the structure. 
<P>
She was ordered tethered two months ago after being charged with
several crimes. But her mother is now in the hospital. 
<HR>

<H3>New Zealand Whales </H3>

<P>
In New Zealand, rescue teams are desperately trying to save 27
pilot whales that beached at a popular tourist spot. 
<HR>

<H3>Pet Dental Care </H3>

<P>
This Valentine's Day, how would you like to kiss someone who hasn't
brushed their teeth in years? It happens more often than you think
... whenever people cuddle up with their cats or dogs. 
<P>
While dog breath may be a standing joke, it's also a sign your
pet may have gum disease. Annette Hamm takes a look at how to
keep your best friend smiling and healthy. 
<P>
<I>Gum disease is no laughing matter for dogs or cats. But studies
by the Canadian Veterinary Dental Society show more than 80 per
cent of dogs and 70 per cent of cats show signs of it. The older
the animal, the more prone it can be to gum disease. </I>
<P>
<I>A veterinary dental cleaning, while Dean (a cat) is asleep,
will remove the tartar and keep infection from setting into his
gums. To prevent this kind of cleaning from having to take place,
you can try to rub your pets teeth clean with a brush or a cloth
over your finger. Simply giving them hard food to crunch on isn't
enough to keep their teeth healthy. </I>
<P>
<I>Ignoring your pets mouth could cause tooth loss or even heart
and kidney disease. You can keep your pet feeling great by checking
in with your vet to see what kind of dental program you should
start on. </I>
<P>
<I>February is national pet dental health month, and many clinics
are offering dental specials. In Hamilton, Annette Hamm, Channel
11 News.</I>  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

