<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, February 13, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Vs Govt. 
<LI>Labor Clip 
<LI>Home Invasion 
<LI>Cancer Clip 
<LI>Japan Tunnel 
<LI>Monster Court 
<LI>Tallest Building 
<LI>Balsam Obit 
<LI>Oscar Nominations 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Vs Govt. </H3>

<P>
The Harris government and its civil service union are waging war
in an advertising campaign, as the public sector workers prepare
for a strike vote. 
<HR>

<H3>Labor Clip </H3>

<P>
Two of three experts on a federal panel on labor law recommend
no law be brought in to ban the use of replacement workers during
strikes. 
<P>
Labour Minister Alfonso Galiano promises changes to the Canada
labor code by summer, but first plans more consultation with labor
and business. As it is now, only Quebec and BC have anti-scab
legislation. 
<HR>

<H3>Home Invasion </H3>

<P>
The mother of a slain Toronto area teenage girl is appalled that
a 12 year old charged with manslaughter might get bail. 
<P>
The boy is to appear again in youth court in Scarborough on Thursday.

<P>
Tracy Christie will urge the federal justice minister to get rid
of the Young Offenders Act when she meets with him next week.

<P>
16 year old Christie Christie was shot and killed during a home
invasion last month. Four youths are charged. 
<HR>

<H3>Cancer Clip </H3>

<P>
Cancer continues to be a major killer in Canada and the numbers
are expected to rise. 
<P>
More than 116 thousand Canadians had a bout with cancer in 1993
and over 56 thousand people died. The Canadian Cancer Society
predicts 130 thousand new cases this year. And by 2010, it's estimated
there'll be twice as many cancer cases as there were in 1990.

<P>
The direct cost of treating Canadians with cancer is now about
3 and a half billion dollars a year. 
<HR>

<H3>Japan Tunnel </H3>

<P>
Rescuers are struggling for a fourth day to blast their way into
a highway tunnel where 20 people lie beneath a huge boulder. 
<P>
The latest dynamite explosion, as with two previous efforts, chipped
away only a small part of the 70-thousand-ton slab. Rescue workers
say they will set off further explosions until the slab is blasted
off the tunnel. The boulder has trapped 20 people since Saturday
morning. 
<HR>

<H3>Monster Court </H3>

<P>
An appeal court has acquitted the man convicted of being &quot;the
monster of Florence&quot; sexual serial killer, reopening one
of Italy's most sensational criminal mysteries. 
<HR>

<H3>Tallest Building </H3>

<P>
Malaysia will soon have the world's tallest skyscraper. The shell
of the 88 story twin towers was completed today. 
<P>
When crowned with decorative spires, the buildings will surpass
the world's tallest building, the Sears Tower in Chicago. 
<HR>

<H3>Balsam Obit </H3>

<P>
Martin Balsam, a veteran Hollywood actor who won an Oscar for
the 1965 film &quot;A Thousand Clowns&quot; and appeared in scores
of films including &quot;On The Waterfront&quot;, was found dead
this morning in a Rome hotel. he was 76. The cause of death was
not immediately clear. 
<P>
Balsam appeared in the movies &quot;Twelve Angry Men&quot;, &quot;Marjorie
Morningstar&quot;, &quot;Breakfast at Tiffany's&quot;, Tora! Tora!
Tora! &quot;Psycho&quot;, and &quot;St. Elmo's Fire&quot;.
<HR>

<H3>Oscar Nominations </H3>

<P>
The Oscar nominations have been announced in Hollywood. Mel Gibson's
movie &quot;Braveheart&quot; picked up ten nominations. 
<P>
&quot;Apollo 13&quot; has nine. &quot;Babe&quot; and &quot;Sense
and Sensibility&quot; picked up seven each. 
<P>
The winners will be announced March 25th in Los Angeles. 
<P>
 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

