<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, February 8, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Riot Follow 
<LI>Johnson--OPSEU 
<LI>Lankin Runs 
<LI>Bernardo Tapes 4 
<LI>Latimer Appeal 
<LI>Oregon Flooding 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Riot Follow </H3>

<P>
Four students charged in a violent protest at the Ontario legislature
have been charged with intimidating parliament. 
<P>
The little known charge carries a maximum penalty of 14 years.
Two police officers were hurt when hundreds of students stormed
queen's park yesterday to protest government cutbacks. 
<HR>

<H3>Johnson--OPSEU</H3>

<P>
With provincial civil servants getting ready to vote on strike
action, the government is getting worried that its final offer
is not being communicated to the rank and file. 
<P>
With a point by point sign, Management Board Chairman Dave Johnson
attempted to show that civil servants are getting a good deal
both in pay and pension benefits. 
<P>
OPSEU members will vote on the offer late next week. 
<HR>

<H3>Lankin runs </H3>

<P>
Another New Democrat has tossed a hat into the leadership ring.

<P>
Former Cabinet Minister Frances Lankin has announced her candidacy
to replace former leader Bob Rae. 
<P>
Lankin, a Toronto area MPP, had served in Rae's government as
Minister of Health, Economic Development and Trade, and Chair
of Management Board. 
<P>
Lankin and maverick New Democrat Peter Kormos are the only two
candidates to officially announce their candidacy. MPP's Howard
Hampton and Tony Silipo are also expected to join the race. 
<P>
The new NDP leader will be chosen in June. 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo tapes 4 </H3>

<P>
The families of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy's right to religious
freedom was violated by a judge who allowed sexually explicit
videotapes, to be played in open court. 
<P>
That argument was made today by the lawyer representing the families.
They are fighting to have the law changed to prevent evidence
deemed as pornographic from ever being played in public. Lauran
Sabourin has more. 
<P>
<I>The arguments are complex. The issues not easily understood.
Tim Danson lawyer for the French and Mahaffy families made the
case today not only were the families rights violated by the playing
of the tapes but so were Kristen and Leslie's rights to privacy.</I>
<P>
<I>The families put the blame for what they see as a violation
of their rights squarely on the shoulders of justice Patrick Lesage.
Tim Danson says that Judge Lesage should have foreseen the harm
that making the audio tapes and subsequent transcripts available
to the public would have caused the families. </I>
<P>
<I>That the court should have foreseen that if the verbatim transcripts
of the tapes were available that books like Nick Pron's &quot;Lethal
Marriage&quot; would be written. </I>
<P>
<I>Even if the families lose the battle in this court the matter
will be appealed all the way to the Supreme Court. They see this
case as a way of showing that Kristen and Leslie's life was more
than a brutal murder. They see it as some good to come out of
a tragedy. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Latimer Appeal </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the Supreme Court of Canada has agreed to hear the
appeal of a Saskatchewan farmer convicted of killing his severely
disabled daughter. 
<P>
Robert Latimer was sentenced to life in prison with no automatic
chance of parole for ten years. 
<P>
In 1994, a jury convicted him of killing his 12 year old daughter
Tracy with carbon monoxide to end her suffering from cerebral
palsy. 
<P>
Last year, it was revealed that police had questioned potential
jurors in the case on issues of euthanasia, abortion and religion.
Some of those people ended up on the jury that convicted Latimer.
<HR>

<H3>Oregon Flooding </H3>

<P>
The worst flooding in 30 years has much of northwestern Oregon
under water tonight. 
<P>
Days of heavy rain and melting snow has sent rivers and streams
raging over their banks. Thousands have fled their homes, and
hundreds of roadways are closed.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

