<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, February 7, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Student Protest 
<LI>Cabinet -Polls 
<LI>Eves Clip 
<LI>Bernardo Videos 3 
<LI>Plane Crash 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Student Protest </H3>

<P>
What started out as a peaceful demonstration by students at Queen's
Park has turned violent. 
<P>
Late this afternoon, the front doors to the legislature were smashed
in and about 100 students jammed inside chanting anti-government
slogans. At least two people were arrested. 
<P>
The demonstration was one of several held in cities across Canada
to protest against cuts in federal funding to the provinces for
post-secondary education. Jamie West reports. 
<P>
<I>At Hamilton's McMaster university...the day started with a
few songs and a leaflet campaign. </I>
<P>
<I>Students say wealthy corporations are getting richer at the
expense of students just trying to get by ... to make their point
all entrances to the campus were sealed off for a brief time and
all drivers turned away ...including some not sympathetic to the
cause. </I>
<P>
<I>The day had been billed as a shutdown of the campus but organizers
of an afternoon rally seemed to be working hard at motivating
the crowd. </I>
<P>
<I>A couple hundred students also converged on Queen's Park to
voice their outrage at the government, they say is creating a
two tiered system for higher education. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton Jamie West, Channel Eleven News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Cabinet -Polls</H3>

<P>
For the first time since the provincial election, the Harris government
no longer enjoys the support of the majority of Ontarians. According
to the latest public opinion poll, the liberals have surged into
the lead.
<HR>

<H3>Eves Clip</H3>

<P>
Provincial governments are pushing for wholesale changes to federal
social programs that would allow governments to charge fees for
health services, and combine provincial welfare programs with
unemployment insurance. 
<P>
The report of &quot;The Ministerial Council of Social Policy Reform
and Renewal&quot; also calls for raising the pension age from
65 to 67. 
<P>
Although Ontario endorses the over-all report, Finance Minister
Ernie Eves says raising the pension age will only save one half
of one per-cent.
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Videos 3 </H3>

<P>
The families of slain teenagers Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy
say they were treated like second class citizens by the court
during Paul Bernardo's first degree murder trial. And today, a
constitutional expert agreed. 
<P>
Kathleen Mahoney said that when the families petitioned the judge
to ask that the tapes not be played in open court, they were not
treated as equals but given less standing than Bernardo. 
<P>
The families have launched a court battle to have a section of
the criminal code that allowed the public to hear the videotapes
declared unconstitutional. Lauran Sabourin reports. 
<P>
<I>In her affidavit filed with the court Donna French said that
the videotapes were the most vile desecration of their daughter
imaginable. And that no human being should ever experience what
they did fighting Paul Bernardo and the media. </I>
<P>
<I>But during that battle the families always felt that their
torment over the tapes was never understood by the court. The
fact that the court entertained the media requests to see the
videotapes just added injury on top of injury. There is no provision
in the law that allows victims families to have their say in a
criminal case. And for that reason constitutional expert Professor
Kathleen Mahoney says the families equality rights were violated.
The fact that the public was allowed to hear the anguished words
of Kristen and Leslie violated their freedom of speech. </I>
<P>
<I>The families position is that a section of the criminal code
that allowed the tapes to be heard in the public courtroom is
unconstitutional. It violates the victims families equality rights.
In this case it violates Kristen and Leslie's right to free speech.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Plane Crash </H3>

<P>
More victims of a doomed charter flight have been recovered off
the Dominican republic. The US Coast Guard reports at least 105
bodies have been brought to shore. 
<P>
The plane was carrying tourists home to Germany, when it crashed
into shark infested waters last night. 
<P>
So far there are no reports of survivors.  
<P>

