<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, February 5, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Eves-Budget 
<LI>OPSEU Talks 
<LI>Lankin-Heritage 
<LI>Advocacy-Newser 
<LI>Bernardo Tapes-Court 
<LI>CBC Poll 
<LI>Home Sales 
<LI>TTC Inquest 
<LI>China Quake 
<LI>Mass Grave 
<LI>Deep Freeze 
<LI>Cold Wine 
<LI>Tobacco Contribution
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Eves-Budget </H3>

<P>
Ontario's Finance Minister Ernie Eves is being very cagey, about
how the government's promised tax cuts will affect the economy
and our pocketbooks. 
<P>
Eves appeared before pre-budget hearings today and he still won't
say when the much touted tax cuts will comes. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Talks </H3>

<P>
The province says it plans to table a final contract offer to
its unionized workers tomorrow -- two days after negotiations
broke down. 
<P>
Management Board Chairman Dave Johnson suggests the offer won't
contain the job security provisions the union wants. But he says
the offer will be &quot;generous and fair.&quot; 
<P>
The province's 67-thousand unionized employees could be in a strike-lockout
position in less than three weeks. 
<HR>

<H3>Lankin-Heritage </H3>

<P>
A member of the former NDP government says a Toronto Sun story
about the Rae government bleeding a hundred million dollars from
the Northern Ontario Heritage Fund, is a lie. 
<P>
Former Northern Affairs Minister Gilles Pouliot calls it a Tory
fabrication, to divert attention from the current budget cuts.

<P>
Another former cabinet minister in the Rae government, Francis
Lankin says 60-million dollar of surplus money was taken from
the fund, and given back to the government for deficit reduction.
Premier Mike Harris, who is in Switzerland is reported to have
ordered an investigation into where the money has gone. 
<HR>

<H3>Advocacy-Newser </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Advocacy Commission is on the Tory government chopping
block ...today a legislative committee is looking into the Harris
government's proposed bill nineteen which would abolish the 18-million
dollar commission, as well as amend the consent to treatment and
substitute decisions act. 
<P>
But commission members say the Tories' plans will rob the vulnerable
of protection... and they called on the government to set up a
non profit corporation to represent people with disabilities,
and frail seniors. 
<P>
The government argues that the authority over the care and protection
of the mentally incapable should be handed back to families. 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Tapes-Court </H3>

<P>
The families of slain teens Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy
were back in a St. Catharines court today. 
<P>
The families are fighting to have the law changed to protect the
privacy of future victims of sexual assault.
<HR>

<H3>CBC Poll </H3>

<P>
Confirming what radio talk shows have already indicated... a poll
suggests that Canadians are not too hot on the idea of a tax on
their phone, cable and satellite t-v bills to finance the CBC.

<P>
A review committee recommended last week that federal funding
stop and a seven and a half per cent tax be levied on consumers
to raise the billion dollars the CBC needs each year. But a poll
by &quot;Insight Canada Research&quot; finds 66 per cent of the
12-hundred people questioned, oppose the tax idea. Only 19 per
cent support it.
<HR>

<H3>Home Sales</H3>

<P>
Another poll reveals that one in four Canadians plans to buy a
home in the next two years, but those buyers are likely to be
middle-aged and more affluent. 
<P>
A housing survey by the Angus Reid Group suggests families that
have outgrown their homes are expected to be the main buyers through
1996 and '97. This group is between the ages of 35 and 54, with
household incomes of more than 80-thousand dollars a year. 
<HR>

<H3>TTC Inquest </H3>

<P>
More disturbing testimony at the inquest into last summer's fatal
subway crash... the inquest is on hold right now, as lawyers argue
behind closed doors. 
<P>
Earlier today a former Toronto subway operator has told the inquest
that equipment problems were common. Adolphus Williams says there
were often broken phones on subway trains. Williams was driving
the subway train immediately behind the two that crashed -- killing
three female passengers. He says during his first few days as
a subway driver, he worked with another rookie -- and was surprised
there wasn't even a supervisor to meet them on their first run.
<HR>

<H3>China Quake </H3>

<P>
Two aftershocks have jolted terrified survivors of China's largest
earthquake in eight years as they shivered in freezing temperatures.

<P>
The Saturday night magnitude-seven quake in southwest china killed
250 people and injured 15-thousand others. Officials say more
than 186-thousand homes have collapsed leaving hundreds of thousands
of people homeless. A massive relief operation is now underway.

<HR>

<H3>Mass Grave </H3>

<P>
Senior UN sources say an investigation is under way into reports
that Bosnian Serbs used death ovens to burn Muslim victims during
the 1992 ethnic cleansing campaign. 
<P>
Meanwhile, UN special envoy for human rights, Elizabeth Rehn,
looked shocked after seeing the site of a possible mass grave
close to the former Bosnian government enclave of Srebrencia.
Human remains were scattered all over the bleak mountain clearing.

<P>
Officials estimate that up to 500 people were cut down by gunfire
on the mountain. 
<HR>

<H3>Deep Freeze</H3>

<P>
Record cold temperatures are now being blamed for seventy five
deaths throughout the United States ...and as was reported ...the
next victim might be the Florida fruit crop. 
<HR>

<H3>Cold Wine </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Niagara area grape growers say they're concerned about
the current extreme cold snap. 
<P>
Wine grapes are susceptible to prolonged exposure to the cold.
Karl Kaiser of Inniskillen Wines says growers have been watching
their vines closely. Some have already sustained minor damage
with temperatures dropped below minus-18 for several nights in
a row. He says emergency pruning will have to take place at some
farms to prevent the damage from spreading. 
<P>
But the deep freeze is supposed to end in this part of the world
over the next couple of days.
<HR>

<H3>Tobacco Contribution </H3>

<P>
No big surprises in a consultants report released today outlining
the economic impact of Ontario's 323-million dollar tobacco industry.

<P>
What is new, is a solid facts and figures that communities in
the tobacco belt can use for future economic planning. Annette
Hamm has the story. 
<P>
<I>The study confirms what most people in southern Ontario's tobacco
belt already knew. The tobacco industry has a major impact. Especially
in the region of Haldimand Norfolk, where the industry makes up
10 per cent of the gross domestic product. </I>
<P>
<I>The 250-thousand dollar study, funded largely by the Ontario
and Canadian governments shows more than 17-thousand full and
part time workers depend on the crop. The study focused only on
tobacco production and manufacturing, not health issues surrounding
cigarettes. </I>
<P>
<I>Tobacco is a labour intensive crop. if there's a 33 per cent
decline in tobacco production, as the consultants warn could very
well happen, more than 23-hundred jobs will be lost. That would
be like shutting down the Cami Automotive plant in Ingersoll.
</I>
<P>
<I>The independent consultants hope their study will convince
provincial and federal governments to think twice before making
decisions affecting the tobacco industry. They also hope area
governments will use their data in future economic planning. in
Tillsonburg, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News. </I> 
<P>

