<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 02/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, February 1, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Bernardo Tapes 
<LI>Home Alone 
<LI>MTO. - Trucks 
<LI>Train Derailment 
<LI>Bomb Update 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Tapes</H3>

<P>
The families of slain teens Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy
won a small victory today. 
<P>
A judge in Toronto ruled that the copies of the sexually explicit
videotapes held by Paul Bernardo's defense team be destroyed.

<HR>

<H3>Home Alone </H3>

<P>
Police acting on a tip from a concerned citizen found two young
children home alone in a London apartment early this morning.

<P>
Police say they had to use force to enter the apartment. Inside,
they found a 21 month old girl and her ten month old brother as
well as some marijuana plants. Their 18 year old mother has been
charged. 
<P>
The children have been turned over to the care of the Children's
Aid Society. 
<HR>

<H3>MTO. - Trucks </H3>

<P>
Inspectors from the Ministry of Transport faced another dismal
set of statistics as they completed a truck safety blitz, this
time in Ancaster, near Hamilton. 
<P>
22 vehicles were inspected and ten were pulled out of service.
As Kathy Renwald reports, the ministry laid 10 charges after the
day long safety blitz. 
<P>
<I>Ministry of Transport inspectors found everything from barely
there brakes.. to sheared bolts on tires.. as they flagged down
trucks on highway 2 in Ancaster today for the safety blitz. </I>
<P>
<I>Inspector Chris Davies say the MTO hopes the safety blitzes
are effective ..but the high failure rate raises questions. </I>
<P>
<I>Davies says it was disheartening to see 50 per cent of the
trucks fail the safety inspection in the first hour. This wasn't
a random blitz ..inspectors were looking for older trucks.. trucks
that haul scrap and are prone to more tire problems.. trucks hauling
thousands of pounds of steel that can shift if not properly secured.
</I>
<P>
<I>After runaway truck wheels killed 2 people on Ontario highways
last year.. Transport Minister Al Palidini promised a crackdown..
but its been a promise without much punch. </I>
<P>
<I>The Ontario Safety League is pushing for higher fines and more
inspectors to keep unsafe trucks off the road. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Kathy Renwald Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Train Derailment</H3>

<P>
A freight train carrying hazardous chemicals derailed in the San
Bernardino valley of southern California this morning, killing
at least one member of the crew. The subsequent fire has been
burning all day, sending toxic fumes into the air for miles. 
<HR>

<H3>Bomb Update </H3>

<P>
The death toll now stands at 73 from Wednesday's terrorist bombing
in Sri Lanka's capital. 13 more bodies were dug out of the charred
wreckage a day after the blast.  
<P>

