<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, January 30, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Support Services 
<LI>Omnibus Day After 
<LI>WCB Reform 
<LI>Home Invasion 
<LI>Students Snow 
<LI>Quads Born 
<LI>New AIDS Drug 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Support Services </H3>

<P>
The Harris government's proposed plan to shutdown eight regional
family support plan offices, has sparked fear among employees
and advocates of the program. 
<P>
The family support plan helps collect child support and searches
out deadbeat parents who fail to make payments. ..as Jamie west
reports tonight, employees of the largest office, located in Hamilton...
say a shutdown will literally break an already overburdened system....

<P>
<I>Louise Carboneau is treasurer of OPSEU local 205. and says
not only are the government's figures not accurate, but the 70
employees of this family support plan office in Hamilton are more
than earning their keep. </I>
<P>
<I>Cheryl Lafreniere is a Hamilton attorney specializing in family
law. She says the system isn't perfect, but a possible move to
centralize the program in Toronto and introduce a 1-800 fee for
service phone line will only hurt her clients... and those paying
support will also be hurt.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Day After</H3>

<P>
The Harris Tories have pushed their omnibus bill through the legislature.

<P>
It was passed last night despite a rowdy day of protests, and
although the bill has passed, don't expect to see all the provisions
of introduced at once.
<HR>

<H3>WCB Reform </H3>

<P>
The province's Workers Compensation Board could be the next target
of government cuts. 
<P>
A government report released today suggests cutting benefits and
rehabilitation for injured workers. The paper recommends narrowing
the range of injuries or illnesses that would qualify someone
for compensation. 
<P>
Cam Jackson, the minister responsible for Workers Compensation
Reform, says the WCB is &quot;out of control&quot;. Jackson says
he also wants to drop employer premiums to help Ontario become
more competitive. 
<HR>

<H3>Home Invasion </H3>

<P>
A teenage girl was shot and killed in a home-invasion robbery
in east Toronto last night. 
<P>
16 year-old Christie Christie was hit by a blast from a sawed-off
shotgun in her Scarborough home. Police say two people then ransacked
the apartment before fleeing. 
<P>
Investigators say the shooting was likely drug related. 
<HR>

<H3>Students Snow </H3>

<P>
Over the past 24 hours, snow squalls, snow falls and high winds
have wreaked havoc with drivers in Ontario's Grey and Bruce counties.
Many roads have now been reopened but driving conditions still
aren't that great. 
<P>
Richard Thomas tells us conditions were so bad last night, many
students ended up sleeping at school. 
<HR>

<H3>Quads Born</H3>

<P>
A Buffalo couple is counting it's blessings... four times over,
following the birth of quadruplets Saturday night. 
<HR>

<H3>New AIDS Drug </H3>

<P>
Researchers say they may have, by far, the most potent treatment
yet, for people with AIDS. It's an experimental drug that's proving
very effective in slowing down the growth of the virus.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

