<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, January 26, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Exorcism Verdict 
<LI>Harnick-Justice 
<LI>Hydro-Private 
<LI>Conservation Cuts 
<LI>Late Letter 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Exorcism Verdict </H3>

<P>
Two people have been convicted of manslaughter for killing a two
year old girl during a bizarre exorcism ritual last year. 
<P>
The girl's 23 year old mother and 57 year old neighbor were convicted
today in the killing of Kira Canhotto. 
<P>
The toddler choked to death last January, while being force-fed
water at a home in Cambridge. 
<HR>

<H3>Harnick-Justice </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Ontario's Attorney General says he wants to slim down
the province's justice system. 
<P>
Charles Harnick told the Canadian Bar Association today the government
plans to shift most civil and criminal cases out of the court
system. He also said he wants a new &quot;court services agency&quot;
to manage the justice system without involving his ministry. 
<HR>

<H3>Hydro-Private</H3>

<P>
A study released today says that Ontario Hydro should be privatized...
and competition should be allowed in the delivery of electrical
power. But there are differing views on whether dumping the debt-
ridden utility would mean lower or higher Hydro rates. Anthony
Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>Add Ontario Hydro to the public utilities endangered species
list. Sir Adam Beck may well have been turning over in his grave
today as Hydro's current president Allan Kupcis heralded the possible
demise of the giant, debt-burdened electrical utility. </I>
<P>
<I>A proposal prepared for the Harris government recommends the
privatization of Hydro by the year 2000, and an end to its monopoly,
suggesting cheaper power would come as a result. </I>
<P>
<I>But Power Workers' Union president John Murphy has a decidedly
different view of the situation. He cites US figures that show
private electrical utilities charge their customers more than
the public ones. The study was done by a committee headed by Donald
Macdonald, a former liberal cabinet minister under Pierre Trudeau.
</I>
<P>
<I>The final report is due by the end of April. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Conservation Cuts </H3>

<P>
Ontario's conservation authorities have been braced for funding
cuts for the past couple of years. Bill 26 is speeding up the
process. 
<P>
Under the bill, municipalities can decide if they'll continue
to fund conservation authorities. Annette Hamm takes a look at
where the authorities are headed. 
<P>
<I>Flood control was the main mandate when conservation authorities
were formed in the late 1940's. It still is, but many authorities
expanded into recreational areas. </I>
<P>
<I>Now, faced with provincial and municipal funding cuts, many
are turning back to the basics of watershed planning and management.
That could mean dropping programs many people associate the authorities
with. Education programs for school kids could be among the first
to go. Depending on staff levels, special events may be dropped.
</I>
<P>
<I>For several authorities, visitors will pay for parking this
year where they've never paid before. Park gate admissions will
rise. Only self sufficient campgrounds and nature centres will
survive. </I>
<P>
<I>For the Grand River Conservation Authority, the cuts mean ploughing
under an 800-thousand dollar farm program. Many authorities are
looking for alternative private funding to keep their programs
alive. </I>
<P>
<I>But for those who can't come up with extra money, the head
of Hamilton Region's Conservation Authority worries the end may
be near with no municipal backup. </I>
<P>
<I>But whatever budget cuts conservation authorities face this
year, they'll see again in 1997. Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Late Letter </H3>

<P>
62 years ago Jim Post was supposed to get a brochure from a national
sales training association in Chicago. It never came - that is
until today. 
<P>
Beth Bailey is the letter carrier in the neighbourhood where Post
used to live. She finally tracked him down at the Windsor nursery
home where he now lives now. And today Jim post got his mail.

<P>
 
<P>

