<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, January 23, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>KPMG - Hamilton 
<LI>Can. Pension 
<LI>Cashing RRSP's 
<LI>Subway Inquest 
<LI>Snowmobilers 
<LI>Kormos Runs 
<LI>Firefighters B-26 
<LI>School Funding 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>KPMG - Hamilton </H3>

<P>
The nation's economy is expected to grow by 2.5-percent this year,
and Hamilton will maintain its competitive advantage. This according
to survey result's from some of Canada's leading economic thinkers,
prepared by KPMG. 
<P>
But as Anthony Pooley reports tonight, other economic forecasts
are not so optimistic. 
<P>
<I>It has been said that if one asks the same question of 10 different
economists, there could well be 10 different answers. Case in
point: KPMG's annual survey of economic expectations released
today. The results are based on the predictions of 30 private
sector economists, and optimistically predict that the Canadian
economy will grow by 2.5- percent this year ... fueled by auto
and export industries, especially those that sell to the US, which
in Canada means most of them. </I>
<P>
<I>The only problem is this ... a number of other private sector
economists have revised downward the 1996 growth predictions they
made last year. For example... today Scotiabank's global economic
outlook predicted a 1.8 percent economic growth rate, citing a
lack of income growth, depleted savings, and high debt loads for
most Canadians. </I>
<P>
<I>They do agree on one thing, though. Unemployment is expected
to remain at about 9-and-a-half percent. </I>
<P>
<I>The dollar is expected to remain below 80- cents u-s during
1996, but soft consumer spending and government cutbacks will
take their toll on the economy this year. In Hamilton... Anthony
Pooley Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Can. Pension</H3>

<P>
A member of the Canada Pension Plan Advisory Board says there's
nothing wrong with the plan. 
<P>
Monica Townson says Ottawa's push to reform the retirement income
system is motivated by ideology, not money. 
<P>
Townson says it is incorrect to say the pension plan is broke
and facing a crisis because the population is aging. She told
an Ottawa news conference the debate over the plan has been hijacked
by those like the Reform Party, which would replace it with mandatory
RRSP's.
<HR>

<H3>Cashing RRSP's </H3>

<P>
Thousands of people under retirement age, withdrew billions of
dollars from their RRSP's in 1993, to cope with financial crises.

<P>
Statistics Canada says a record 650 thousand individuals under
the age of 65, withdrew 3 and a half billion dollars. The figure
represents a 31 percent increase from 1990 and a six percent jump
from 1992. 
<HR>

<H3>Subway Inquest </H3>

<P>
The rookie driver involved in a fatal subway crash in Toronto,
says he was terrified behind the wheel. And Robert Jeffrey told
a coroner's inquest today that he didn't feel comfortable with
the amount of training he received. He also apologized to the
families of the victims. 
<P>
The accident killed three women and injured about 30 passengers
last august. It was Jeffrey's second day on the job as a subway
driver. 
<HR>

<H3>Snowmobilers</H3>

<P>
Provincial police say alcohol was a contributing factor in a snowmobile
accident that killed four men. 
<P>
Divers found nine full bottles of beer on the bodies of the snowmobilers
who drowned last Saturday when their machines plunged through
thin ice. 
<P>
One of the men who died, had fallen through ice on a snowmobile,
on two previous occasions. 
<HR>

<H3>Kormos Runs </H3>

<P>
NDP &quot;bad boy&quot; Peter Kormos is the first official candidate
in the race to replace retiring leader Bob Rae. 
<P>
Kormos says the NDP has gone too far to the right and he wants
to bring it back to its social democratic roots. 
<P>
Ten days ago, former premier Bob Rae announced he was leaving
politics to join a law firm. A new leader will be chosen at the
NDP convention this summer. 
<HR>

<H3>Firefighters b-26 </H3>

<P>
Firefighters from across Ontario are accusing Premier Mike Harris
of lying to them. 
<P>
Hundreds of firefighters swarmed onto the front lawn of the Ontario
legislature today to protest the government's controversial omnibus
bill. They claim it threatens public safety, by eroding the quality
of fire fighting service in the province. 
<P>
The firefighters also accused Premier Mike Harris of breaking
a campaign promise.
<HR>

<H3>School Funding </H3>

<P>
Is it an issue of discrimination? or, is it a bid to get the public
to pay for private schools? 
<P>
The Supreme Court of Canada began a two day hearing in Ottawa
this morning, that could determine whether Ontario will pay for
religious schools in the province. Scot Urquhart has more in this
report. 
<P>
<I>Suzie Adler took her case to a higher court, this morning.
The highest court in the land. </I>
<P>
<I>Her fight, is to force Ontario to fund a Jewish school, for
her daughter: but this perceived shackle on religious freedom,
is viewed quite differently by the province who see these schools
doing something else: crossing the line into the realm of private,
specialty schools. </I>
<P>
<I>George Petrusma doesn't deny, that his institution sees education
from a different perspective: and for many of these students,
the examination of life from a Christian view, is a good thing:
whether all taxpayers should stand with them; and pay for that
point of view, is for the court to decide: Scot Urquhart, Channel
Eleven News. </I> 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

