<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, January 22, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Bill 26 Latest 
<LI>OPSEU Strike 
<LI>Kormos-NDP Leader 
<LI>Drownings 
<LI>Jobless Finances 
<LI>Simpson Deposition 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 Latest </H3>

<P>
One week from tonight, the province's controversial omnibus bill
is scheduled to pass through the Ontario legislature. But today
a group of opposition MPP's promised to break rank with their
own parties' and do everything possible to delay passage of that
bill. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Strike</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, unionized government workers in Ontario say they're
waiting for a final contract offer from the Harris government
before taking a strike vote. 
<P>
At a union rally in Sudbury today, OPSEU president Leah Casselman,
said her members are prepared for the worst. 
<P>
65 thousand OPSEU members could hit the picket lines next month,
something they've never done before. Lack of negotiations, pensions
and job security are the main stumbling blocks to an agreement.

<HR>

<H3>Kormos-NDP Leader </H3>

<P>
Ontario's former Consumer Minister Peter Kormos is expected to
announce his bid to lead the NDP tomorrow. 
<P>
The MPP for Welland Thorold would be the first to formally declare
his candidacy to replace outgoing leader Bob Rae. 
<P>
Kormos has called a news conference for tomorrow morning, but
is being non committal about its purpose. However, it is no secret
that the Welland MPP has been thinking about replacing Bob Rae
as leader of the party. 
<HR>

<H3>Drownings</H3>

<P>
Tragedy struck southern Ontario this past weekend as icy waters
claimed the lives of six men in two separate accidents. 
<P>
Four friends died in a lake northwest of Peterborough when they
drove their snowmobiles into an open patch of water Saturday.
OPP divers pulled their bodies from 12 mile lake yesterday. 
<P>
And last night, a father and his stepson died trying to save their
dog in a lake near Mississauga. The men, aged 42 and 24, fell
through the ice trying to reach the dog, which survived. 
<HR>

<H3>Jobless Finances</H3>

<P>
Thousands of Canadians are losing their jobs. It seems everyone
knows someone who is out of work. But losing your job isn't the
end of the world ...and a Hamilton financial advisor is offering
seminars on how to survive the transition. Dwight Ryan has the
details. 
<P>
<I>Down-sizing, re-structuring, no matter what its called, people
continue to lose their jobs. And as governments continue their
cuts, more job losses will come. </I>
<P>
<I>If you've been right-sized, re-focused, or re-engineered out
of your job, you are facing one of life's most stressful situations.
Chances are times will be tough...at least for a while. </I>
<P>
<I>Financial Advisor Rebeckah Schnurr offers counseling to the
worried jobless. She believes keeping as much of your severance
away from Revenue Canada is a good start. And on the upside you
now control your pension dollars. Chances are the way you invest
it will pay more than you were getting. </I>
<P>
<I>And Schnurr says forget about those accelerated mortgage payments
..at least for now. Creditors often bend the rules until you're
working again. </I>
<P>
<I>As well, Schnurr says benefit packages usually end when you
lose your job. But you can shop around for independent coverage.
Then free-lance your skills. </I>
<P>
<I>Rebeckah Schnurr believes when one door closes, two will open.
And that losing your job at least got you out of the rut you didn't
like anyway. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Dwight Ryan, channel 11 news. </I>
<P>
Rebeckah Schnurr of Berkshire Securities in Hamilton is offering
two noon-hour seminars on personal finances after a job loss.
information is available by calling Kelly at 905-529-5505..
<HR>

<H3>Simpson Deposition</H3>

<P>
OJ. Simpson is believed to be spending his first day giving a
deposition for the April civil suit filed against him by the families
of murder victims Nicole Brown and Ron Goldman. He's doing so
in the west Los Angeles office of the Goldman's attorney.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

