<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, January 19, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Bill 26 - Hamilton 
<LI>Boards-Snobelen 
<LI>AG Museum Future 
<LI>Harris Form 1 
<LI>Rae New Job 
<LI>Pension Clip 
<LI>Loomis Robbery
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 - Hamilton </H3>

<P>
Health Minister Jim Wilson today tabled 69 amendments to the government's
controversial omnibus bill. 
<P>
The key amendment shelves a plan to create a new group of inspectors
with the power to investigate doctors and seize the confidential
records of patients. Under the changes a special body of physicians
would have to give the government permission to collect and disclose
patient records. 
<P>
The amendments came on the last day of hearings on the bill in
Hamilton, where healthcare was the hot topic and some presenters
were hot tempered. Jamie West reports.... 
<P>
<I>Those sentiments were echoed by a number groups and individuals
attending the hearings at the Hamilton Convention Centre many
were angry that they did not receive standing to present their
concerns to the committee.</I>
<P>
<I>Dr. Gordon Guyatt's Medical Reform Group says Ontario is well
on it's way to a two tiered health care system. </I>
<P>
<I>The proceedings were interrupted briefly by protesters, who
just one floor below held a shadow hearing to protest the fact
that they were refused standing. </I>
<P>
<I>NDP Finance Critic Frances Lankin attacked today's announced
healthcare amendments to bill 26. She says the 69 changes will
allow the government to bypass the house anytime they want to
make changes to healthcare laws. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Boards-Snobelen</H3>

<P>
Ontario 's public school boards want the Harris government to
phase in funding cuts over a longer period of time. 
<P>
The government says it will cut 400-million dollars from provincial
schools by September this year. 
<HR>

<H3>AG Museum Future</H3>

<P>
Since last November, the month the Harris government announced
it was cutting funding to the Ontario Agricultural Museum, there
has been a groundswell of grassroots efforts to save it. 
<P>
The museum is set to close for good in March of next year. But
as Annette Hamm tells us, several organizations are sowing the
seeds for a new start. 
<P>
<I>It's supposed to be quiet this time of year at the Ontario
Agricultural Museum in Milton. The museum usually doesn't open
for visits until the spring, but this spring could be its last.
</I>
<P>
<I>Because of provincial funding cuts, half of the museums 52
workers will lose their jobs this year ... and the site will close
for good march 31, 1997. </I>
<P>
<I>The museum's collection of 15-thousand artifacts is expensive
to display. An audit two years ago shows the museum costs 31 dollars
per visitor to run. </I>
<P>
<I>The museum is so important that a newly formed organization,
the Agricultural Museum Preservation Committee, wants to work
with farm machinery and seed companies to raise money for the
site. Closing the 80 acre site forever seems to be a worst case
scenario. </I>
<P>
<I>The museum will be open for business this year, but on a reduced
basis. </I>
<P>
<I>In Milton, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Harris Form 1</H3>

<P>
And a footnote to a story we ran Wednesday. 
<P>
A Burlington doctor had issued a form one under the Mental Health
Act, asking police to pickup Ontario Premier Mike Harris for psychiatric
assessment. However, in a news release this afternoon, Halton
Regional Police stated that following a review of the document
it was decided the document was invalid and would therefore not
be acted upon. 
<HR>

<H3>Rae New Job</H3>

<P>
Former Ontario Premier Bob Rae has a new job. Rae will join one
of Canada's largest law firms next month. 
<P>
Rae, who announced his resignation as NDP Leader last weekend,
will become a partner at Goodman Phillips and Vineberg on February
7th. That's the same day he officially leaves politics. 
<HR>

<H3>Pension Clip</H3>

<P>
Ottawa is looking at some big increases in Canada Pension Plan
premiums. 
<P>
The Toronto Star quotes sources as saying that a report due for
release with the next federal budget, will recommend doubling
those premiums over the next four years. 
<P>
Without bigger premiums, the plan will not have enough money to
cover it's obligations as baby boomers begin to retire in the
next century. But not everyone is in favour of the idea. 
<HR>

<H3>Loomis Robbery </H3>

<P>
A surprising twist today in the investigation into a three million
dollar armored car robbery in Toronto. 
<P>
Two more people, including a Toronto police officer, were charged
today in connection with the holdup. 
<P>
Last august, an armed man wearing a police uniform, made off with
three million dollars in a Loomis truck. A Loomis employee was
charged last September. Today, a Woodbridge man and a Metro Toronto
Police Constable face similar charges.  
<P>

