<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, January 18, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Justice Delays 
<LI>Crime Clip 
<LI>Immigration Charges 
<LI>Barnett Death 
<LI>Leach-Amendments 
<LI>McLeod-Bill 26 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Justice Delays </H3>

<P>
The head of the province's crown attorney's association predicts
a breakdown of the province's justice system if feared layoffs
take place. And Paul Vesa says if the feared cuts do occur, a
lot of criminal cases are simply going to be lost. 
<HR>

<H3>Crime Clip </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Canada's Crime Prevention Council is warning federal
politicians that cuts to social programs will lead to a dramatic
increase in crime. 
<P>
The council's chair says that unless the government eases up on
its defect fighting course, crime in this country could double
within the next five to ten years. 
<HR>

<H3>Immigration Charges </H3>

<P>
Two Canadian immigration officers are under arrest, and nine others
face charges, after the RCMP cracked a conspiracy to smuggle as
many as 150 illegal aliens into Canada. 
<P>
The scam involved a plan to sell business visas to Asians attending
a mythical trade show. And that investigation led to the discovery
of a ring that brought women into the country illegally to work
as prostitutes. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Five police forces and Canada's Immigration department co-operated
in a lengthy investigation that culminated in the arrest of eleven
people. </I>
<P>
<I>An official says the visas were offered to as many as 150 people
for thirty-thousand dollars apiece. The business Visa investigation
also uncovered a secondary operation that smuggled women into
Canada for the purposes of prostitution. </I>
<P>
<I>Police have charged eleven people, including two immigration
officers who worked at Pearson International Airport. </I>
<P>
<I>Canada's Immigration Department says an independent assessment
of its procedures will now be expanded to include entries at airports
and border points, in Toronto, Deborah Walker, Channel Eleven
News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Barnett Death</H3>

<P>
The head of Ontario's special investigations unit blames a &quot;regrettable
news report&quot; for causing an uproar against police in Toronto
today. 
<P>
A Toronto newspaper claimed the SIU had decided no charges would
be laid against a metro Toronto police officer who shot a black
man earlier this month. 
<P>
The SIU says it's probe into the death of Tommy Barnett is still
in the early stages, but Barnett's family is making demands of
their own. Annette Hamm explains. 
<P>
<I>Tommy Barnett's family describes his shooting death as a continuing
brutal assault by metro police against blacks. </I>
<P>
<I>22 year old Barnett was shot three times by a metro sergeant
after he reportedly pulled out a sword and started waving it around.
Some witnesses say Barnett ignored warnings to drop the sword,
which he allegedly pointed as police approached him. </I>
<P>
<I>Members of Barnett's family and the Black Action Defence Committee
called their news conference just hours before the province's
Special Investigations Unit denounced a news report the unit had
cleared the officer involved of any wrongdoing. </I>
<P>
<I>Despite family and public demands, the SIU says it can't give
a date when it's work will be complete. The Black Action Defence
Committee is demanding it's own independent investigation and
autopsy in the Barnett case. Annette Hamm, channel 11 news. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Leach-Amendments</H3>

<P>
The New Democrats say Municipal Affairs Minister Al Leach should
resign over his gaffes on bill 26. 
<P>
NDP house leader Dave Cooke says government amendments to the
cost cutting bill contradict Leach's claim that municipalities
would not have the power to levy new gasoline, income and sales
taxes. 
<P>
Before Christmas, leach had offered to resign if bill 26 were
to allow such taxes. Cooke says leach &quot;either misled the
legislature or did not understand his own legislation.&quot; 
<HR>

<H3>McLeod-Bill 26</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the provincial Liberals have called for 150 changes
they want made to the government's omnibus bill. One of those
changes includes separating the bill into seventeen parts. 
<P>
Liberal Leader Lyn McLeod says the government is stumbling around
like a crazed pit bull, with no idea where its going but determined
to do as much damage as possible along the way. 
<P>
McLeod says she found yesterday's amendments to the health section
of bill 26, offensive. McLeod says if the jumbo bill is passed,
you might as well advertise Ontario as &quot;the home of the user
fee&quot;.  
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

