<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Monday, January 15, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>NDP Leadership 
<LI>Snobelen-Teachers 
<LI>Smoking Clip 
<LI>Kitchener Fire 
<LI>GTA Reaction 
<LI>Genie Awards 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>NDP Leadership </H3>

<P>
Less than 48 hours after their leader announced he was leaving
politics, the battle over control of Ontario's New Democratic
Party has already begun. <BR>
In a speech Saturday, former Ontario Premier Bob Rae accused some
labor leaders of burying their &quot;heads in the sand&quot; for
failing to try to understand the changes taking place in the economy.
But one MPP who is contemplating a run at the leadership, Peter
Kormos, disagrees saying the party needs to veer sharply to the
left if it is to survive. 
<HR>

<H3>Snobelen-Teachers</H3>

<P>
While it was in power, the NDP lost a lot of support from teachers
unions across the province... but now it appears the Tory government
is finding itself in the same situation. 
<P>
A weekend teacher protest at Queen's Park attracted thousands
opposed to education cuts. But the province's education minister
is sticking to his guns. Dwight Ryan has the story. 
<P>
<I>By some estimates, thirty thousand teachers and their supporters
marched on Queen's Park over the weekend. Their message was clear
...they're mad as hell, and they're not going to take it anymore.
</I>
<P>
<I>The Tories say they will slash 400 million dollars from the
massive education budget. It represents just three percent of
the nearly 14 billion dollars the province spends on education
each year. </I>
<P>
<I>In a question and answer forum, Snobelen was short on specifics.
Snobelen has angered teachers by saying they should spend more
time in the classroom. Teachers meanwhile say Saturday's protest
is just the beginning. </I>
<P>
<I>In Burlington, Dwight Ryan, Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Smoking Clip </H3>

<P>
They may be getting the message that it's &quot;harmful to their
health&quot; still new information from Statistics Canada today
shows that more and more kids are lighting up. 
<P>
In the first ever national survey of its kind, Statistics Canada
found that one in seven Canadian youths, aged 10 to 19, smokes
cigarettes, this despite knowing of it's harmful effects. Peer
pressure appears to be the reason for the habit. Almost three
out of four young smokers said they started because their friends
did. 
<HR>

<H3>Kitchener Fire</H3>

<P>
Police say a candle dropped by a teacher caused a big fire at
a school in Kitchener. The entire east wing of Wilson Avenue Public
School was destroyed yesterday. 
<P>
The candle was dropped in a junior kindergarten room but police
have not said what it was being used for. No one was hurt in the
fire, but a teacher in the school at the time was treated in hospital
for &quot;emotional stress.&quot; Classes were canceled today.

<HR>

<H3>GTA Reaction</H3>

<P>
A controversial report which recommends the elimination of five
regional governments in favour of one large greater Toronto area
will be tabled tomorrow. 
<P>
But even before it is submitted, opposition to the proposal continues
to grow. 
<HR>

<H3>Genie Awards </H3>

<P>
The Canadian film industry has honored its own, and the top honor
goes to &quot;La Confessional.&quot; 
<P>
The film won the award for best motion picture at the 16th Annual
Genie Awards in Montreal last night. 
<P>
&quot;La confessional&quot; also won a best feature film director
award for the work of Robert Lepage. But it was &quot;Margaret's
Museum&quot; that picked up the most genies -- six in all. <I>
</I>
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

