<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, January 12, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Subway Murder 
<LI>Gayle Appeal 
<LI>Mafia Funeral 
<LI>Jail Suit 
<LI>Bob Rae Future 
<LI>Bill 26 - Hamilton 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Subway Murder </H3>

<P>
A 15-year-old boy has been stabbed to death at a subway station
in suburban Toronto. 
<P>
Police say it happened at around four o'clock this afternoon at
the Kennedy station. It has been closed indefinitely. 
<P>
The boy's name has not been released. Metro homicide detectives
are investigating. 
<P>
Last year, a subway ticket collector was stabbed to death during
a robbery at nearby Victoria Park Subway Station. 
<HR>

<H3>Gayle Appeal </H3>

<P>
Clinton Gayle will appeal his conviction. 
<P>
He was convicted of first-degree murder yesterday in the shooting
death of Metro Toronto Police Constable Todd Baylis during a fight
in June of 1994. Gayle was also convicted of attempted murder
for wounding Baylis's partner Mike Leone. 
<P>
Justice David Watt sentenced Gayle to life in prison with no chance
of parole for 25 years. Gayle's lawyer, Michael McLachlan, says
there are several possible grounds for an appeal. 
<HR>

<H3>Mafia Funeral </H3>

<P>
A North York baker reputedly linked to organized crime was laid
to his final rest today. 
<P>
38-year-old Frank Loiero was gunned down, Mafia-hit style, in
a Woodbridge store parking lot last Sunday night. Police suspect
hit men used silencers on their guns as they pumped as many as
a dozen shots into Loiero. 
<P>
The dead man was still wearing expensive jewelry and was carrying
5 thousand dollars in cash when his body was found. 
<HR>

<H3>Jail Suit</H3>

<P>
Guards at Toronto's Don Jail say overcrowding of inmates there,
constitutes a powder keg, just waiting to explode. And the guards
fear for their lives. 
<HR>

<H3>Bob Rae Future</H3>

<P>
There is speculation tonight that former premier Bob Rae is getting
set to resign as leader of the Ontario New Democratic Party. 
<P>
If Rae does throw in the towel, it will be at tomorrow's meeting
of his caucus. Rae has also scheduled a news conference for twelve
thirty at which he's expected to discuss his future plans. 
<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 - Hamilton</H3>

<P>
Ontario's safety is in danger. That's the warning from fire fighters
and police at hearings into the province's bill 26. 
<P>
As it stands now, the cost cutting bill would allow towns and
cities to charge user fees for such things as police and fire
services. Annette Hamm has details from the hearings in Hamilton
today. 
<P>
<I>Imagine being charged a user fee if firefighters had to respond
to your emergency. The president of the Ontario Professional Firefighters
Association says it could happen unless changes are made to the
Harris government's bill 26. He cites a proposal by the City of
North York. </I>
<P>
<I>Police officers trying to avoid layoffs crowded the subcommittee
hearing. A delegation representing more than 23-thousand officers
and support staff warned the committee that more personnel is
the best tool in fighting crime. </I>
<P>
<I>Although the subcommittee will return to Hamilton next Friday
to deal with health concerns, both Liberal and NDP MPP's complain
the hearing is moving too far too fast. </I>
<P>
<I>The hearings have to wrap up before the legislature votes on
bill 26 January 29th. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News. </I>
<P>
 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

