<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Thursday, January 11, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Gayle Verdict 
<LI>Cop Shooting 
<LI>Tweed Murder Arrest 
<LI>Canhotto Sentenced 
<LI>Subway Inquest 
<LI>Hydro Firings 
<LI>Bill 26 Hearings 
<LI>Agostino-Gas Tax
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Gayle Verdict </H3>

<P>
Clinton Gayle has been convicted of first-degree murder in the
killing of a Metro Toronto Police Constable and the attempted
murder of another officer. 
<P>
This in the shooting death of constable Todd Baylis in June 1994
and in the wounding of Baylis's partner, Constable Mike Leone.

<P>
Jurors reached the verdict this afternoon after deliberating since
late yesterday morning. 
<HR>

<H3>Cop Shooting </H3>

<P>
The special investigations unit says a sword was found where a
police officer fatally shot an unidentified man in Toronto last
night. 
<P>
The SIU says two officers were on an unrelated call when they
saw a man standing on the road holding a sword. 
<P>
Witnesses say the man was approached and ordered to drop the sword...
but instead threatened officers with it. He was shot when he got
within a few metres of them. 
<HR>

<H3>Tweed Murder Arrest</H3>

<P>
A Thornhill man who lives across the hall from an elderly couple
who were stabbed to death has been charged with their murders.

<P>
Bill and Phyllis Tweed, who were in their 80's, were killed in
their apartment on Boxing Day. Twenty-two-year- old Joel Clark
is charged with two counts of second-degree murder. He's being
held without bail until a court appearance February 16th in Newmarket.

<HR>

<H3>Canhotto Sentenced </H3>

<P>
A Cambridge woman whose granddaughter died while she was attempting
to rid the child of evil spirits is going to jail. 
<P>
Forty-three-year- old Ana Maria Canhotto of Cambridge has been
sentenced to two years less a day. She told the court she believed
the devil killed the two-year old child as an act of vengeance.

<HR>

<H3>Subway Inquest 4 </H3>

<P>
A physician from Sunnybrook Health Science Centre in Toronto says
if he had been called earlier, he might have been able to save
one of the victims of last August's subway crash in Toronto which
claimed three lives. 
<P>
Doctor Andrew McCallum told a coroner's inquest into the crash
today that he attempted to save a 22-year-old woman whose legs
were pinned under a huge chunk of metal. He amputated her leg
with a fireman's saw at the scene. She died later. 
<P>
He also said rescuers faced horrific conditions in the tunnel
where the two trains collided, describing it as hot and dangerous
with wreckage everywhere. The inquest continues. 
<HR>

<H3>Hydro Firings </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government is being accused of trying to silence critical
thinking at Ontario Hydro by getting rid of eight members of Hydro's
board of directors. 
<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 Hearings </H3>

<P>
A traveling government roadshow on the controversial omnibus bill
stopped in Niagara falls today. 
<P>
Bill 26 would give Ontario's conservative government sweeping
new powers. Powers the government says it needs to reduce the
province's debt. While opponents are charging that the government
has gone too far, proponents say it hasn't gone far enough. Lauran
Sabourin has more in this report. 
<P>
<I>Conservative and pro bill 26 members on one side of the room.
Opposition members on the other. Listening to the few representatives
who managed to get on the agenda. </I>
<P>
<I>People who are recommending changes to the controversial legislation.
Peter Kormos rebel MPP and champion of the underprivileged got
under the skin of those in favor of the legislation. Legislation
better known as the bully bill. A reference to the fact not everyone
who wanted to make a presentation was not on the list. the government's
justification for bill 26 is that the amendments will help it
reduce the province's staggering debt. But to the opponents that
debt is being reduced on the backs of those who can least afford
to pay.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Agostino-Gas Tax?</H3>

<P>
No municipal gas tax. That assurance comes from the Harris government;
which has stated publicly, that it will close any loopholes in
its proposed jumbo bill, that might allow cities to use the legislation
to charge municipal taxes on items like gasoline. 
<P>
But that promise did not stop Hamilton East MPP Dominic Agostino,
from going on the offensive, today. Agostino insists, that the
tax will happen; and in fact, handed out leaflets denouncing the
&quot;Mike Harris gas tax: at an east end Hamilton gas station&quot;.
<P>
The provincial panel conducting public hearings on the jumbo bill
convenes in Hamilton, tomorrow. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

