<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, January 10, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>French/Mahaffy Fund
<LI>PST - GST 
<LI>Hearings 
<LI>Subway Inquest 
<LI>Toronto Pot Bust 
<LI>Judge Suspended 
<LI>Credit Card Scam 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>French/Mahaffy Fund </H3>

<P>
A powerful, and emotional appeal for financial assistance; featuring
super-model Linda Evangelista... was issued today by supporters
of the families of Leslie Mahaffy, and Kristen French. 
<P>
The French-Mahaffy Legal Assistance Fund; is looking for public
support to continue a legal battle over controversial videotapes,
shown to jurors at the Paul Bernardo trial. Scot Urquhart takes
a look, at this unusual case: 
<P>
<I>The battle is over ... but the war, goes on: but wait a minute
... those tapes have already been sealed by the court; so what
is the purpose, of the fund? </I>
<P>
<I>So, the legal assistance fund is trying to prevent that development;
at any cost: a target that will mount a court case to keep the
sealed records, sealed.</I>
<P>
<I>Jeff Manishen is a noted criminal lawyer. But no matter how
long the odds ... the families of Kristen and Leslie are determined
to ensure that their worst emotional nightmare never comes to
pass.</I>
<P>
<I>In Burlington Scot Urquhart Channel Eleven News.</I>
<HR>

<H3>PST/GST</H3>

<P>
Remember the 1993 election when Prime Minister Chretien promised
to scrap the GST? Well, that day has not yet come...but there
is much talk about taxes. 
<P>
On a trade mission with Chretien, Premier Mike Harris says Ontario
may be close to harmonizing the provincial sales tax with the
federal GST. Marci Ien reports from Queens Park. 
<P>
<I>When Canadian cash registers ring up sales ...there may soon
be no more separate provincial and federal sales taxes added to
the bill. Word from Premier Harris ...who is on an Asian trade
mission with Prime Minister Chretien...is that Ontario may be
close to harmonizing the provincial sales tax with the federal
GST. </I>
<P>
<I>Liberal MPP Monte Kwinter says the move is a positive one ...as
long as Ontario taxpayers don't pay a price. </I>
<P>
<I>Finance Minister Ernie Eves was cautiously optimistic. He says
talks about merging the taxes are still ongoing. </I>
<P>
<I>In Toronto, Marci Ien, Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Hearings</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile... legislators listening to public input on the Harris
government's controversial jumbo bill refused to extend hearings
at their Kitchener whistle stop today. So some of the dozen or
so groups waiting for their kick at the can went unheard. 
<HR>

<H3>Subway Inquest 3</H3>

<P>
New Toronto subway trains will be equipped with speedometers,
says police Staff Sergeant Alan Staples, who testified at the
inquest into last summer's crash that killed three passengers.
The trains now in service don't have speedometers and drivers
must rely on experience and a system of lights to know how fast
they are going. 
<P>
But Staples says lack of speedometers wasn't the main cause of
the crash.
<HR>

<H3>Toronto Pot Bust</H3>

<P>
Just days after police stumbled onto a hydroponic marijuana farm
in Mount Hope, metro Toronto police have made a similar discovery.

<P>
After obtaining a search warrant for an unrelated matter, detectives
say they found a hydroponic lab in full swing in a North York
condominium. They seized the equipment and about 100 marijuana
plants. The plants alone are worth 30-thousand dollars. 
<P>
A North York man has been charged, but police haven't released
his name pending further investigation. 
<HR>

<H3>Judge Suspended </H3>

<P>
Quebec judge Jean Bienvenue has been suspended pending an investigation
into remarks he made from the bench, while sentencing a woman
to a prison term for killing her husband. The judge likened the
victim's suffering to that of Jews during the holocaust, and said
women can sink to lower levels than men. 
<P>
He later apologized... but refused to resign, prompting a review
by the Canadian Judicial Council. 
<HR>

<H3>Credit Card Scam </H3>

<P>
A Toronto man faces 120 fraud related charges in connection with
a quarter- million-dollar bogus credit card scam, uncovered during
a nine month investigation by three police forces and the Canadian
Bankers Association. 
<P>
Police say the names and personal information of people answering
a newspaper job ad was used to obtain credit cards which would
be run up to the limit and then destroyed. 
<P>
Charged is 48- year-old Alexander Polychronopoulos of Toronto.

<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

