<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 01/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Tuesday, January 9, 1996 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>OPSEU Strike Looms 
<LI>Anarchy Clip 
<LI>Trade Trip 
<LI>Mourning Mitterand 
<LI>Toronto Mugging 
<LI>Subway Inquest 
<LI>Blizzard 
<LI>Anemia - Blood 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Strike Looms</H3>

<P>
Ontario's civil service union is threatening to shut-down the
province. The union has been negotiating with the Harris government
for over a year on its current contract. 
<HR>

<H3>Anarchy Clip</H3>

<P>
A new survey reveals that today's youth... members of so- called
generation &quot;x&quot;... are twice as likely to cheat on their
taxes as other Canadians. What's more... they believe those who
pay in full are fools. 
<HR>

<H3>Trade Trip</H3>

<P>
Prime Minister Jean Chretien along with seven provincial premiers
and more than 300 Canadian business people are in Bombay, India,
tonight. 
<P>
The visit is part of a week and a half long Asian trade mission,
expected to generate more than two billion dollars in business
for Canada. 
<P>
Analysts say it's also about boosting Chretien's public image.
But the plan could backfire if human rights issues are ignored.

<HR>

<H3>Mourning Mitterand </H3>

<P>
Governor-General Romeo Leblanc and Deputy Prime Minister Sheila
Copps are en route to Paris tonight where they'll represent Canada
at Thursday's memorial service for former president Francois Mitterand.
They will join Foreign Affairs Minister Andr&eacute; Ouellet,
already in Paris on business. 
<P>
Mitterand died in his sleep yesterday... eight months after leaving
office. He was suffering from prostate cancer. France's longest-serving
president was 79. 
<HR>

<H3>Toronto Mugging </H3>

<P>
A 37 year old man is recovering in hospital after a mugging in
downtown Toronto this afternoon. 
<P>
The victim had his wallet stolen and collapsed after he ran to
a parking attendant for help. The man had no vital signs when
the police arrived. Paramedics revived the man. 
<P>
The suspect is still at large. 
<HR>

<H3>Subway Inquest </H3>

<P>
The rookie driver of a Toronto subway train involved in a fatal
crash needed to rely on experience to know how fast he was going
because the trains don't have speedometers, an inquest was told
today. 
<P>
The inquest into the subway accident last Aug. 11 that killed
three passengers has been told that driver Robert Jeffrey was
behind the wheel for two days when he ran three red lights. 
<P>
Yesterday, jurors heard there were warnings about flaws in the
Toronto subway system three months before a fatal crash. But the
consultants who issued the warnings were fired before senior managers
read their reports. 
<HR>

<H3>Blizzard </H3>

<P>
In Newfoundland today... schools, government offices and businesses
remained closed while remnants of the blizzard of '96 swept across
the Avalon and Bonavista peninsulas. And much of the American
east coast is still bogged down after this week's storm. 
<P>
Authorities say it could be days before all the streets are plowed,
and airline flights are back to normal. the storm is blamed for
the deaths of at least 80 people in the US. 
<HR>

<H3>Anemia - Blood </H3>

<P>
Every year, 300-thousand Canadians require blood transfusions
either to prevent anemia or to treat it. But there may be new
hope. Canadian researchers say a new therapy called E-prex may
put an end to blood transfusions for many cancer patients. Marci
Ien explains. 
<P>
<I>Harvey Wayne is a cancer patient...and like most cancer patients
who undergo chemotherapy ...blood transfusions had become a way
of life. ...a way to combat anemia...a condition that is more
likely to occur if a patient is being treated with chemotherapy.
</I>
<P>
<I>Chemotherapy does more than destroy cancer cells... it also
wipes out red blood cells ...the ones that carry life-giving oxygen
to the body. That's where E-prex comes in. The drug is a genetically-
engineered version of the same hormone that stimulates red blood
cell production in human bone marrow. In essence ...E-prex gives
red blood cells a kick-start...and that's good news at a time
when people are worried about the safety of the blood system.
</I>
<P>
<I>E-prex has been used to treat kidney dialysis patients who
suffer dangerous anemia for several years. It's hoped by next
year...the drug will allow elective surgery patients of forego
transfusions. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Marci Ien, Channel 11 News. </I> 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

