<HEAD>

<TITLE>"Patsy!" A Musical Tribute to Patsy Cline</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="patsyc.jpg">
<H1>Patsy Cline</H1>

</CENTER>

<HR>

<P>
During a recording career that spanned only about six years, Patsy
Cline built a body of work that stands alone among country and
pop singers. Her country background filled her music with heartfelt
emotion while her impeccable vocal control and Owen Bradley's
elegant production broke down all the barriers between country
and pop music.  She was one of the most popular singers of her
time, and today, more than 30 years after her death, she is still
one of the most popular recording artists.
<P>
Patsy Cline's music has never gone out of style, as evidenced
by the 15 albums still available from MCA - more than any other
MCA Nashville artist.  Ever since the 1985 movie about her life,
starring Jessica Lange, Cline has been among the top-selling artists
on the label.  Her &quot;Greatest Hits&quot; album was certified
gold in 1985, platinum in 1987, double platinum in 1989 and triple
platinum in 1991 with actual sales surpassing 3.5 million pieces.
<P>
Patsy Cline was born Virginia Patterson Hensely on September 8,
1932, in Gore, Virginia.  Her family moved to Winchester, about
50 miles away, when she was in grammar school.  As a teenager,
she began singing with country bands on the radio and in local
clubs.  At the age of 16, she made her first trip to Nashville
to audition for the Grand Ole Opry.
<P>
In the early 1950s, a bandleader suggested she use a different
first name, and she adapted her middle name to Patsy.  Her last
name came from Gerald Cline, to whom she was married from 1953-57.
 As Patsy Cline, she was signed by Four Star Records in 1954.
 A distribution deal with Decca led to her first recordings with
legendary producer Owen Bradley in 1955.
<P>
In 1956, Cline joined the cast of the &quot;Town and Country Time&quot;
radio show in Washington D.C., which was hosted by Jimmy Dean.
 Early in 1957, she became an overnight sensation.  She appeared
on Arthur Godfrey's &quot;Talent Scouts,&quot; a network television
program, and Decca released <I>Walkin' After Midnight</I>.  Ironically,
she had fought against recording the song, feeling it was not
country enough.  By March in 1957, it was a country smash and
#12 on the pop charts.  Her personal life also took a sharp turn
in 1957, as she divorced Gerald Cline, and married Charlie Dick.
<P>
Cline's chart success sputtered a bit after <I> Walkin' After
Midnight</I>, until she left Four Star and signed directly with
Decca in 1960.  Her subsequent recordings have become pop as well
as country classics, including <I>I Fall To Pieces </I>(#12 pop)
and <I>Crazy</I> (#9 pop) in 1961 and <I>She's Got You</I> (#14
pop) in 1962.
<P>
On March 5, 1963, one month after the day she recorded <I>Sweet
Dreams</I>, Patsy Cline was killed in a plane crash.  She had
performed at a benefit in Kansas City the night before.  Along
with fellow country stars Lloyd &quot;Cowboy&quot; Copas and Hawkshaw
Hawkins, she was flying back to Nashville in a private plane piloted
by her manager Randy Hughes.  After a refuelling stop in Dyersberg,
TN., the plane encountered bad weather and crashed, killing all
aboard.
<P>
Patsy Cline's music continued to grow in popularity after her
death.  Album sales averaged 75,000 per year through the 1960s
and 1970s.  Sales increased after her role in Loretta Lynn's career
was dramatized in the 1980 movie &quot;Coal Miner's Daughter&quot;
(with Beverly D'Angelo playing Cline).  In the early 1980's, producer
Owen Bradley used modern technology to merge Cline's vocals into
a successful duet with Jim Reeves, who dies in a plane crash in
1964.  In 1985, her original recordings created some stunning
moments in &quot;Sweet Dreams&quot;, the film story of her recording
career, and her marriage to Charlie Dick.
<HR>


