<HEAD>

<TITLE>About Canada Caption Inc.</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../gifs/caplogo.gif"></CENTER>
<H1><CENTER>Canada Caption Inc.</CENTER></H1>
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>Model Corporate Citizen: &quot;a lean, mean, non-bureaucratic
machine.&quot;</CENTER> </H3>

<P>
At Canada Caption Incorporated (CCI), the three-and-a-half year
old organization dedicated to increasing the amount and improving
the quality of  captioning in Canada, the working vocabulary is
noticeably different from that of other charitable and non-profit
organizations.  Words like innovation, flexibility, entrepreneurial
and aggressive - more often the jargon of Fortune 500 enterprises
- are not just part of the CCI lexicon; they're part of every
day practice and cutting-edge achievement.
<P>
Established on January 1, 1992 by Executive Director <A HREF="beverley.htm">Beverly Ostafichuk</A>,
CCI began recruiting finical support to help underwrite the costs
of captioning in Canadian programming.  It negotiated with broadcasters
and captioning facilities to ensure the highest quality service
for captioning users and advanced the image of its corporation
sponsors using billboard overlays for on-air recognition across
the entire viewing audience.
<P>
Today, the Oakville Ontario based CCI is well on its way towards
achieving its goal of 100% captioning on Canadian programming
by the year 2000.
<P>
Captioning has always been squeezed inside a fiscally-boundaried
catch-22: the only way to bring down the cost of captioning is
to increase the volume of captioning, and the only way to increase
volume is to break down the cost.  CCI attacks the problem and
finds economically viable solutions that not only work to the
advantage of the deaf and hard of hearing community (who receive
more and better captioned programs) also benefit corporate sponsors
(who receive partial tax receipts for financial support and recognition
as involved and responsible corporate citizens) and not the largest
captioning subcontractor in the country and its high volumes mean
greater savings, all of which pushes them closer to fulfilling
their mandate. 
<P>
As captioning costs become more reasonable and broadcasters bring
such activities in-house, CCI's role will undoubtedly change.
 Ostafichuk and the rest of the forward-thinking staff are already
planning the next evolution of CCI.  In keeping with their proactive
approach, they are at the forefront of technological innovation
in the captioning industry.
<P>
Through Captioning Awareness Week and through their everyday battles
and triumphs, CCI is expanding the captioning market to benefit
all users.  In addition to the deaf and hard of hearing, captioning
will benefit senior citizens, young children learning to read,
and adult learners as well.  CCI is working to publicize the proven
advantages of captioning to further increase demand, decrease
the cost and increase the accessibility of captioning.  In other
words,  CCI is taking entrepreneurial means towards charitable
ends.
<P>
In the past, a few organizations have monopolized the captioning
industry and hoarded information - not to mention profits - to
the disadvantage of the deaf and hard of hearing.  Ostafichuk
is determined to wipe out those monopolies and the only way to
do so it to compete on a level playing field with an unending
supply of creative ideas and professionalism.
<P>
&quot;We have to constantly stay ahead of the status quo, constantly
re-evaluate our business plan,&quot; she say. &quot;I don't think
that kind of entrepreneurial thinking exists in charities.&quot;
<P>
It is that entrepreneurial model that has attracted world-wide
attention and which Ostafichuk is hoping to export, &quot;especially
to developing countries where illiteracy is high.&quot;  Ostafichuk
has been invited to numerous international conferences to speak
about the CCI model and how it may be applied.  &quot; I talk
to anyone who will listen&quot; she says.  &quot;I try to convince
people that you have to communicate on the same level as big corporations.
 You can't go in with a pity-me attitude.  If you have a plan
and the statistics, it can be done.&quot;<HR>

