<HEAD>

<TITLE>Glossary of Captioning Terms</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<H1><CENTER>Glossary of Captioning Terms</CENTER></H1>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><B>Autoscroll - </B>A message set to be displaced over and
over again at a specific speed (i.e. a brief overview of an emergency
situation) until a Real-time captioner can be brought online
<LI><B>Caption</B> - The explanatory comment or designation accompanying
any pictorial illustration.  Designed specifically for the deaf
and hard of hearing, a caption explains both dialogue and relevant
sounds.
<LI><B>Captioned Program</B> - A program in which the audio portion
is translated into visual cues, rendering the program more meaningfully
to the targeted audience.
<LI><B>Decoder</B> - A device used to recover the component signals
from a composite (encoded) video source.
<LI><B>Closed Captioning</B> - Captions are hidden in the broadcast
signal and require some type of decoding circuitry to access them.
<LI><B>Electronic Note Taking</B> - Captioning that is done using
the computer keyboard rather than a steno keyboard which consists
of a summary of broadcast events dialogue rather than a verbatim
record.  Typically only used when a real-time-time captioner is
unavailable or not feasible, i.e. at a business meeting.
<LI><B>Encoder</B> - A device that processes one or more input
signals into a specified form for transmission and/or storage.
<LI><B>Federal Communications Commission (FCC)</B> - The federal
agency empowered by law regulate all interstate radio and wireline
communications services originating in the United States.
<LI><B>Line 21</B> - In order to accurately reproduce a scene,
the scanning must be done in an organized manner.  In both the
camera and television receiver, the scanning of target or screen
is done by an electron beam moving in horizontal lines across
the target plate or screen.  At the same time the horizontal beam
gradually moves down the screen.  When the beam reaches the bottom
of the screen, it is sent back to the top to continue scanning.
 There are 525 (NTSC) horizontal lines in the complete picture.
 The 21st horizontal line is referred to as Line 21.
<LI><B>Live Display</B> - Captioning prepared in advance, as a
script which is hand fed during live event or broadcast.  May
include formatting information but not timing information, and
the captioner can rearrange the order of the captions at will.
 
<LI><B>National Television Systems Committee (NTSC)</B> - The
North American broadcast television standard since 1953 , using
a 525 line composite colour television system.
<LI><B>Offline Captioning</B> - Captions added to a videotape
after it is produced by before it is aired or distributed.  Off-line
captioning systems use time codes to synchronize captions to the
tape and precisely place captions.
<LI><B>Online Captioning</B> - Online captioning is performed
&quot;live&quot; during an event or broadcast.  Online captioning
may be a combination of real-time, live-display, autoscroll and
electronic notetaking.
<LI><B>Open Captioning</B> - Open Captions are captions which
are not hidden in the broadcast signal and therefore, do not require
decoding circuitry in order to be seen.
<LI><B>Phase Alternating Line (PAL)</B> - The broadcasting standard
of the UK, New Zealand, Australia, Europe and the  Indian sub-continent,
using a 625 line, 50 field composite colour television system
derived from the NTSC system. PAL-M is the PAL sub-system used
in South America which is not compatible with PAL elsewhere.
<LI><B>Paint-on</B> - Paint-on is a style of displaying captions
in which the caption appears on the screen letter by letter as
if it were being painted on to the video frame.
<LI><B>Pop-on</B> - Pop-on is a style of displaying captions in
which the caption is quickly displayed on the screen.
<LI><B>Real-time Captioning</B> - Captions written live by a stenocaptioner
using a stenotype keyboard.
<LI><B>ReCap(TM)</B> - Captioning conversion technology which
enables captions created in the PAL/SECAM television broadcast
standards to be decoded, saved and re-encoded during conversation
to the NTSC television broadcast format and vice versa.
<LI><B>Roll-up</B> - Two, three or four lines of text that &quot;scroll&quot;
upward.  New words are added on the bottom line, as it fills up,
all the lines slide up to make room for the next.
<LI><B>System Electronique Couleur Avec Memoire (SECAM)</B> -
The broadcasting standard used in France since 1960, using 625
lines and 50 fields.  Gradually being phased out in favour of
PAL.
<LI><B>SMPTE</B> - A timecode format that conforms to SMPTE standards.
 SMPTE timecode consists of an 8-digit number specifying hours,
minutes, seconds, and frames.  Each number identifies one frame
on the video. 
<LI><B>Timecode</B> - A standardized numeric coding convention
used to uniquely identify segments of video by numbering each
sequential frame.
<LI><B>Vertical Blanking Interval (VBI)</B> - This is the blanking
portion at the beginning of each video field.  The VBI contains
equalizing pulses, vertical sync pulses and vertical interval
test signal (VITS).
<LI><B>Video Tape Recorder</B> - A device that permits audio and
video signals to be recorded on to magnetic tape.
</UL>
<HR>


