<HEAD>

<TITLE>CCBE November 1996 Newsletter</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">

<P>
<CENTER> <IMG SRC="../images/ccbe.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> </CENTER>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>This News Letter is provided with the permission of
<P>
BROADCAST + TECHNOLOGY
<P>
CANADA'S BROADCAST MAGAZINE </CENTER>
<P>
Information on BT can be obtained by contacting:
<PRE>
          Jacquie Loney
          General Manager and Advertising, 
          6 Farmers Lane, 
          P.O. Box 420, 
          Bolton, Ontario, 
          L7E 5T3    CANADA
</PRE>

<P>
Telephone:(905) 857-6076 or Toll Free: 1-800-567-8833 (CANADA &amp;
USA) <HR>

<H2><CENTER>Newsletter for November 1996</CENTER></H2>
<HR>

<H2>1996 CCBE Convention</H2>

The 1996 CCBE Convention is the ideal opportunity to network and learn from your peers in the broadcast and video production industry.   Also, networking in the computer sense is an important aspect of broadcasting technology and you will have the opportunity to educate yourself in computer networking as well as a wide array of technical subjects at the convention.
<P>

The cost for the convention is extremely modest when compared to most other conventions that are presented in our area.   Early registration is $120.00 November 1st 1996 and $140.00 afterward.  Included in the cost is a Delegates Buffet , two breakfasts, several coffee breaks, a business luncheon, and the CCBE Awards Banquet. 
<P>

Also, by the time you read this, some lucky delegate will have won a A Winter Getaway trip to the value of $1500.00.
<P>
     The 1996 CCBE Convention, will be held on Saturday November 16th and Sunday 17th November 1996, at the Regal Constellation Hotel, 900 Dixon Road, Etobicoke, adjacent to Toronto International Airport.   
The theme of this year's convention is Exploring Broadcast Solutions.   

<P>
The broadcasting convention season is in full swing and by the time this is read at least two of them will have past into history.   The World Expo was held in Los Angeles, California, October 8 - 12, 1996    This convention is a combined effort of NAB Radio, the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers (SMPTE), the Radio and Television News Directors Association (RTNDA)and the Society of Broadcast Engineers (SBE).   The CAB/WABE convention was held in Edmonton, Alberta, October 27 - 29, 1996.   I will report on these conventions in future newsletters.    
<P>

Next is the Spectrum 20/20 Dollar and $ense Conference that is sponsored by the Radio Advisory Board of Canada (RABC) and Industry Canada.    Spectrum 20/20 will be held at the Chateau Laurier in Ottawa November 20 & 21st 1996.   Spectrum, as a subject, does not sound like the material that makes an interesting conference.  However, I was pleasantly surprised when I attended my first Specrum 20/20 conference in Montreal several years ago. There, spectrum assignment in the L-Band was being discussed and with it Canada's entry into the Digital Audio Broadcasting era.   At another Spectrum 20/20 a speaker discussed an interesting little item like what happens to fibre optic cable during a nuclear attack.   I remember at the time discussing this little gem with Wayne Stacey and deciding the fate of fibre optic cable might be the least of our worries in such circumstances.
<P>

I tend to pick up items that might be of interest for the CCBE newsletter, some I use, others become dated and are discarded.  One such item was from the 1996  NAB.     A study was circulated in the newsroom to the effect that broadcasters' competitors have access to large blocks of "free" spectrum and shows that far from being a boring subject, spectrum assignment is not without controversy.   According to the study, common carriers have access to 10,000 Mhz, Cable 1500 Mhz, DBS 1000Mhz and broadcasters, 1600 broadcasting stations use only 402Mhz. 
<P>

I look forward to the November conference in Ottawa in order to keep up-to- date with spectrum issues in Canada.  
<P>
  Thanks to Dave Storey and CHCH-TV in Hamilton the CCBE Newsletter can be accessed on the Internet at http://www.chch.com/engine/ccbe.htm
<P>

