<HEAD>
<TITLE> </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/release1.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN=RIGHT><I><B>November 26, 1996</B></I></H2> 

<CENTER>
<H2>New community supporters on board as Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police, Y95, The Spectator, CHCH-TV and Food Share kick off this year's</H2>
<I><H1>Christmas Community Food Drive</H1></I>
</CENTER>

<P>
The <B>Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police, Y95, The Spectator,
CHCH-TV </B>and <B>Greater Hamilton Food Share</B> have, once
again, joined forces to urge the community to give generously
to <I><B>The Christmas Community Food Drive</B></I> commencing
<U>Saturday, November 30, 1996, </U>and concluding <U>Tuesday,
December 24, 1996, at 12 noon</U> with a public sing-a-long at
Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police Headquarters. <BR>

<P>
The food donations collected from the public will be distributed
by <B>Food Share</B> to: <B>The Good Shepherd Centre, Mission
Services of Hamilton, Neighbour to Neighbour, St. Matthew's House,
Wesley Urban Ministries, Operation Blessing, Crossfire Assembly,
Welcome Inn </B>and <B>Living Water Ministry</B>. A portion of
the food donations will also go to Burlington's <B>Salvation Army
Christmas Bureau</B>.<BR>

<P>
Last year, the above-mentioned five organizations united their
respective food drive campaigns to create a stronger, more expansive
effort to feed the less fortunate in our 'neighbourhood.' The
amalgamation proved successful and attracted the active support
of two prominent businesses: the <B>Sheraton Hamilton Hotel </B>and
<B>Midtown CARSTAR Collision Centre</B>. This year, many of the
campaign's tried and true practices will continue, along with
fresh initiatives and new partners. <I><B>New</B></I> this year:
<BR>

<P>
<B>Midtown CARSTAR Collision Centre</B> -- has volunteered to
make collections at all drop-off locations and deliver the donations
to Food Share's warehouse and Burlington's Christmas Bureau, in
addition to canvassing their suppliers, customers and all area
CARSTAR stores for food donations. <BR>

<P>
<B>Fortino's Supermarkets Shopping Spree</B> -- during Y95's 'Food
Share Friday' broadcasts, originating live from three different
regional police stations, 3 shopping sprees will be given away
for Fortino's Supermarkets at their Dundurn/King location. Fortino's
Supermarkets will then match the total amount in dollars for the
food collected during each of the sprees.<BR>

<P>
<B>Yuk Yuk's Food Share Night </B>-- the comedy venue is donating
a night of entertainment to Y95 contest invitation winners. The
people attending the evening must bring a minimum food donation.
Fortino's Supermarkets will match the total amount of food donated
on that night.<BR>

<P>
<B>Wal-Mart Stores Donate A Buck Campaign</B> -- Food Bank vouchers
will be handed out by all Hamilton Wal-Mart greeters and cashiers.
Customers wishing to help their neighbours in need simply return
the voucher to the cashier and a dollar will be added to their
bill. All proceeds will go to support Greater Hamilton Food Share.
<BR>

<P>
Similar to last year, the <B>Sheraton Hamilton Hotel</B> will
again donate 50 cents to Food Share for every room booked during
<I><B>The Christmas Community Food Drive</B></I> campaign.<BR>

<P>
As in the past, drop-off locations for food donations include
<B>most major food store outlets </B>in the Hamilton area, <B>CHCH-TV
</B>(between 9:00 a.m. and 7:00 p.m.) and the four main <B>Hamilton-Wentworth
Regional Police stations</B> (open 24 hours). <B>The Spectator
</B>will provide a complete listing of participating sites.<BR>

<P>
Suggested non-perishable food items for donation include: canned
meats, canned vegetables, beans with pork, peanut butter, powdered
milk, canned fruit, macaroni and cheese dinners, rice, pasta,
infant formula and cereals.<BR>

<P>
<B>The Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police, Y95, The Spectator,
CHCH-TV </B>and <B>Greater Hamilton Food Share</B> are committed
to <I><B>The Christmas Community Food Drive</B></I>. However,
it is the generosity of the Greater Hamilton community that will
determine the success of the endeavour. <I><B>The Christmas Community
Food Drive</B></I> commences <U>Saturday, November 30, 1996,</U>
and concludes <U>Tuesday, December 24, 1996, at 12 noon</U> with
a public sing-a-long at Police Headquarters. <BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
