<HEAD>

<TITLE>"Dallas: J.R. Returns", on CHCH-TV.</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/release1.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN=RIGHT><I><B>October 21, 1996</B></I></H2> 

<CENTER>
<H1>&quot;Dallas: J.R. Returns&quot;</H1>
<H2>on CHCH-TV.</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>
The slander, affairs and excessive lifestyles resume in great
style, when J.R. Ewing comes back to Dallas to take Ewing Oil
away from his longtime adversary, Cliff Barnes, in the new made-for-television
movie, <I><B>Dallas: J. R. Returns</B></I>, airing <U>Friday,
November 15, 1996 (9:00 - 11:00 p.m.)</U>, on <B>CHCH-TV</B>.
<BR>

<P>
Reunited in the continuing story of the popular series, that mesmerized
the world for 12 years, are <B>Larry Hagman, Patrick Duffy, Linda
Gray</B> and <B>Ken Kercheval</B>.  <B>George Kennedy, Omri Katz</B>
and <B>Audrey Landers </B>also reprise their roles.<BR>

<P>
In <I><B>Dallas: J. R. Returns</B></I>, J. R. (Hagman), who has
been living in exile in Europe for the last five years, astounds
everyone when he returns to Dallas to take Ewing Oil away from
his long-established foe, Cliff Barnes (Kercheval).<BR>

<P>
During his absence, Bobby Ewing (Duffy) has been running Southfork
and Sue Ellen (Gray) has been residing in London.  However, J.
R.'s latest move brings the entire clan back to Dallas and the
opulent, corrupt life faithful viewers came to know so well, resumes.
<BR>

<P>
Original series producers Leonard Katzman and Lee Rich serve as
executive producers with Rich Heller.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>Dallas: J. R. Returns</B></I> airs <U>Friday, November 15,
1996, at 9:00 p.m.</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>, simulcast/<B>CBS</B>.
<BR>
<BR>

