<HEAD>

<TITLE>CHCH presents Neil Simon's "Jake's Women".</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../gifs/bkgd.jpg">
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/11s.gif"> <I><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: February
14, 1996</B></I>
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H1>CHCH has Neil Simon's</H1>

<H1><I>&quot;Jake's Women&quot;</I></H1>

</CENTER>

<P>
A writer, going through a trial separation, travels back and forth
between his past and present, reality and his rich imagination,
uncovering some truths, some pain, and a great deal of laughter
in <I><B>Jake's Women</B></I> airing <U>Sunday, March 3, 1996,
(9:00 - 11:00 p.m.)</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>.
<P>
Starring in the two-hour television movie are <B>Alan Alda, Anne
Archer, Lolita Davidovich, Julie Kavner, Joyce Van Patten, Mira
Sorvino </B>and<B> Kimberly Williams.</B>
<P>
In <I><B>Jake's Women</B></I>, Jake (Alda) is a writer with a
problem.  To put it in his words his &quot;mind has a mind of
its own.&quot;  His fictional characters are so real, they actually
become real.  And, when life becomes too much, well, Jake simply
retreats into his fertile imagination, delightfully blurring the
lines of reality and fantasy, which often leads him into trouble.
<P>
Now, after eight years of marriage, Jake's wife Maggie (Archer)
feels she is suffocating and that Jake no longer communicates.
 A six-month trial separation is suggested.   This, of course,
causes Jake to seek sanctuary in his imagination -- from his wise
and humorous sister, Karen (Kavner), and his eccentric analyst,
Edith (Van Patten).  
<P>
Jake also travels back in time to his first marriage and to his
cherished Julie (Sorvino) who died in a car crash.  They had a
child, Molly (Williams), to whom Jake is devoted.  Maggie knows
Jake is haunted by thoughts of Julie and that she is <I>wife number
two</I>.
<P>
As the separation period progresses, Jake recognizes his loss
-- as does Maggie.  Their predicament is aptly summarized by Maggie
when she says, &quot;We're like two people reaching out for each
other with both hands tied behind our backs.&quot;
<P>
Experience Neil Simon at his Pulitzer Prize-winning best as he
touches our hearts while making us laugh.  <I><B>Jake's Women</B></I>
airs <U>Sunday, March 3, 1996, at 9:00 p.m.</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>,
simulcast/<B>CBS</B>.
<P>

<CENTER>
