<HEAD>

<TITLE>CHCH Seeks Ontario Expansion</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../gifs/bkgd.jpg">
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/11s.gif"> <I><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: January
30, 1996</B></I>
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H1>CHCH-TV Seeks Ontario Expansion</H1>

</CENTER>

<P>
<B>CHCH-TV</B> has filed applications with the Canadian Radio-television
and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) seeking<B> </B>amendments
to its broadcast license which would allow rebroadcast transmitters
to be established in nine Ontario markets: London, Kingston, Peterborough,
Muskoka, North Bay, Sudbury, Sault Ste. Marie, Timmins, and Thunder
Bay. 
<P>
The <B>CHCH</B> program schedule will provide these communities
with a significant amount of new programming options.  While <B>CHCH</B>
is available in a few of the markets on cable, on average 60 %
of the programs in the <B>CH</B> schedule are not seen in the
nine markets the station proposes to serve, including such programs
as <I>Highlander, The Hardy Boys, Nancy Drew, Maple Leaf Hockey
on Eleven, Jane Hawtin Live!</I> and <I>Canada Tonight</I> --
<A HREF="../../wic/wic.htm">WIC Western International Communications Ltd.'s</A>
national newscast which originates from Vancouver.
<P>
These applications, combined with the station's previously filed
requests to establish a programming undertaking or rebroadcast
transmitter in Ottawa, would increase <B>CHCH-TV</B>'s coverage
of the province, permitting the station to fairly compete in a
market totally dominated by regional broadcast systems.
<P>
&quot;<B>CHCH-TV</B> competes in arguably the most competitive
television market in North America where the dominance of regional
systems and consolidated station ownership has inextricably changed
the competitive landscape of the marketplace. The Commission's
approval of these applications will ensure that <B>CHCH</B> is
able to compete equitably in the future and is of paramount importance
to the long term interests of <B>CHCH</B>,&quot; states Jim Macdonald,
president and chief executive officer, <B>CHCH-TV</B>. 
<P>
Most new viewing options come with a price tag and <B>CHCH</B>
is confident that the introduction of a new 'free' service, containing
a substantial selection of quality programming, will be well received.
<P>
<B>CHCH-TV</B> is owned by <B>WIC Western International Communications
Ltd</B>., and is a subsidiary of <B>Westcom TV Group Ltd</B>.
 <B>WIC</B> is an integrated Canadian communications, broadcast
and entertainment company with its head office in Vancouver, British
Columbia. <B>WIC</B> is the only Canadian broadcasting company
operating in television, pay television, radio and satellite network
services.
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <BR>
| <A HREF="../../prog/prog.htm">Visit the CHCH Programming Department</A>
| <A HREF="../../default.htm">Return To The CHCH Home Page</A> |
