<HEAD>

<TITLE>"Project ALF", a two-hour family movie on CHCH-TV.</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../gifs/bkgd.jpg">

<P>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/11s.gif"> <I><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: January
24, 1996</B></I> 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 
<H1><I>&quot;Project ALF&quot;</I></H1>

<H2>A Two-Hour Family Movie on CHCH-TV</CENTER></H2>

<P>
The life of the only living alien, Alf, is put in jeopardy when
the army tries to determine if he should live or die. Eventually,
good wins out over evil in <I><B>Project Alf</B></I>, airing <U>Saturday,
February 17, 1996, (9:00 - 11:00 p.m.)</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>.
<P>
<B>Martin Sheen, Jensen Daggett, William O'Leary, Miguel Ferrar</B>
and <B>Ray Walston </B>star.
<P>
 
<P>
In <I><B>Project Alf</B></I>, the military must resolve whether
they will let Alf live or die.  One army major (Sheen) is of the
opinion that Alf is a tremendous threat and needs to be terminated.
 However, another major and captain (Daggett and O'Leary) believe
Alf is a fine character, who could offer insight into relations
with other aliens.
<P>
As the comedic mayhem unfolds, Alf's life is ultimately placed
in peril, particularly when the major and captain sneak him off
base and take him to the residence of a former astronaut (Ferrar).
 This former astronaut, as it turns out, has a vendetta against
the government and plots to sell Alf to the top bidder. 
<P>
<I><B>Project Alf</B></I>, filled with all the elements that made
the long-running half-hour television series a delight, airs <U>Saturday,
February 17, 1996, at 9:00 p.m.</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>, simulcast/<B>ABC</B>.
<P>
