<HEAD>

<TITLE>"Bye Bye Birdie", A Musical Classic on CHCH-TV</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../gifs/bkgd.jpg">

<P>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/11s.gif"> <I><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: November
21, 1995</B></I>
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H1>BYE BYE BIRDIE</H1>

<H3>A MUSICAL CLASSIC ON CHCH-TV</H3>

</CENTER>

<P>
A publicity stunt invented for a  popular, hip-gyrating rock-n-roll
star is filled with hilarious complications in one of America's
best-loved musicals, <I><B>Bye Bye Birdie</B></I>.  The new adaptation
for television of this venerable favourite airs <U>Sunday, December
3, 1995, (8:00 - 11:00 p.m.)</U> on <B>CHCH-TV</B>.
<P>
<B>Jason Alexander, Tyne Daly, Vanessa Williams, Chynna Phillips,
George Wendt</B> and <B>Marc Kudisch</B> star in the delightful
parody of '50s sensation Elvis Presley . 
<P>
In <I><B>Bye Bye Birdie</B></I>, Conrad Birdie (Kudisch) is an
adored, singing phenomenon.  On the eve of his joining the Army,
his manager, Albert (Alexander), and his devout secretary, Rosie
(Williams), arrange for Conrad to make a final appearance on <I>The
Ed Sullivan Show</I>.  The plan is to have Conrad  bestow a &quot;last
kiss&quot; on a sweet, innocent-faced youth 
<P>
-- Kim MacAfee (Phillips) -- on a national live telecast originating
from Sweet Apple, Ohio.
<P>
The scheme, simple enough in premise, becomes fraught with problems,
which are compounded by Kim's disapproving father (Wendt) and
the arrival of Albert's meddlesome mother (Daly) in Sweet Apple,
who frantically tries to put a halt to Rosie and Albert's developing
romance.    
<P>
Composer Charles Strouse and lyricist Lee Adams created the character
Conrad Birdie.  Many of the great songs that live on from their
beloved musical include &quot;An English Teacher,&quot;  &quot;How
Lovely to be a Woman,&quot; &quot;We Love You, Conrad,&quot; 
&quot;Honestly Sincere,&quot; &quot;One Last Kiss,&quot; &quot;A
Lot of Living To Do,&quot; &quot;Spanish Rose,&quot; and &quot;Put
on a Happy Face.&quot;
<P>
The spirited three-hour television adaptation of <I><B>Bye Bye
Birdie</B></I> airs <U>Sunday, December 3, 1995, at 8:00 p.m.</U>
on <B>CHCH-TV </B>(simulcast/ABC).
<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
