<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/22/95</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, December 22, 1995 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Omnibus Hearing 
<LI>OPSEU Pensions 
<LI>St. Thomas Shooting 
<LI>Unruly Mob 
<LI>Barrie Fire 
<LI>Jose Castro Out 
<LI>Coyote Bodies 
<LI>Salsa Guy 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Hearing </H3>

<P>
A national senior citizen's group says Ontario is the slowest
of all provinces to approve new drugs on the market. 
<P>
The charge came on the last day of public hearings on the omnibus
bill before the new year. 
<HR>

<H3>OPSEU Pensions</H3>

<P>
And the union representing Ontario public servants says if bill
26 passes, it will allow the Harris government to &quot;loot&quot;
their pension plan... and &quot;cheat&quot; them out of millions.

<P>
This after a court ruling overturned a cabinet order exempting
the government from topping up pensions of laid off civil servants.
OPSEU President Leah Casselman says the Tories are now trying
to block access to millions of dollars in pension funds through
the proposed omnibus bill. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Thomas Shooting</H3>

<P>
A 42-year-old man is in hospital in critical condition after he
was shot in the stomach early today at his country home just south
of St. Thomas. 
<P>
Another man... believed to be a factory co-worker of the victim
is charged with attempted murder. Brian Crocker was shot at more
than once ... and 44-year- old Robert Woodford of Malahide Township
is the man accused of firing those shots. 
<P>
He will remain in custody through Christmas. Police have not yet
determined a possible motive. 
<HR>

<H3>Unruly Mob </H3>

<P>
Guelph police used pepper spray to break up a brawl outside a
bar this morning. 
<P>
Police say trouble started when two men started throwing punches
inside the palace hotel. More fights started when about 250 people
spilled out onto the street. 
<P>
Eighteen police officers were sent to the bar and a nearby parking
lot. The crowd was so unruly that city police called in reinforcements
from nearby OPP detachments. 
<P>
Three men were detained by police. Twenty- year-old Michael Lumber
of Georgetown and 25-year-old Steve Nadalin of Fergus are charged
with causing a disturbance. 
<HR>

<H3>Barrie Fire</H3>

<P>
An early morning fire has razed a storage barn full of equipment
used for the Barrie fair. 
<P>
The blaze sent thick black clouds billowing over highway 400.
More than two dozen firefighters battled flames that punched a
hole through the roof of the building at the Barrie Fairgrounds.

<P>
No one was injured. The cause of the fire hasn't been determined.

<HR>

<H3>Jose Castro Out </H3>

<P>
A Portuguese man responsible for a deadly hit-and- run accident
in Toronto was released from jail today after serving one-third
of his one-year sentence. 
<P>
Jose Castro returned to Canada from his home in Portugal to face
trial. Castro was convicted of leaving the scene of an accident
after he ran over and killed seven-year-old Kara Parman in 1993.
He returned to Toronto last March, saying he was haunted by the
little girl's death and ashamed of his flight. 
<HR>

<H3>Coyote Bodies </H3>

<P>
There was a grisly discovery in Mississauga last night. Someone
found a bag containing the carcasses of three coyotes. Two had
been skinned while one was intact. 
<P>
Animal control officers are not sure if the coyotes were in fact
from the area or had simply been dumped there by a hunter or farmer.
Police were called in and are investigating. 
<HR>

<H3>Salsa Guy </H3>

<P>
The city of Guelph is a little spicier these days ... thanks to
some fancy salsa work by a Chilean native. 
<P>
He's turned a favourite recipe into a lucrative business, selling
his salsa at stores in Guelph and also at farmers markets in Guelph,
Kitchener and Toronto. Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>Rodolfo Hennings always knew he had salsa in his heart. Now
he's pouring his heart out for a living. </I>
<P>
<I>His fresh Chilean Salsa has been a long time favourite at parties,
but it wasn't until last March that Hennings decided to take the
plunge, leaving his job as a machinist. </I>
<P>
<I>But a salsa maker he is. Six days a week, Rodolfo enlists his
friends and family for help in the kitchen. Onions are chopped
on Mondays, tomatoes on Tuesdays, then garlic, coriander, lemon
and a mix of spices are prepared on Wednesday and Thursday. Friday
is when it all comes together, and Saturday they go to market.
And not a batch is packaged from this spicy storefront without
a taste from the chef. </I>
<P>
<I>Little by little, Rodolfo is trying to mass produce those flavors
of Chile a little faster and easier, but he's willing to put in
a lot of elbow grease to make it taste just right. All he really
has to worry about it keeping up with demand. </I>
<P>
<I>In Guelph, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News. </I>
<P>
<I> </I>
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

