<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/21/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Thursday, December 21, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Missing Child 
<LI>Love Canal Update 
<LI>Harris-Jobs 
<LI>Plane Crash 
<LI>Angola Crash 
<LI>Train Wreck 
<LI>Hamilton Place-CPI 
<LI>Big Birds 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Missing Child</H3>

<P>
A mother and stepfather from Stevens Point, Wisconsin, are pulling
out all the stops, leaving no stone unturned in the quest to find
their daughter. 
<P>
Jessica Mullenberg was abducted last September... and may have
been sighted recently in waterloo. 
<P>
<I>Monica and Jake Bourget are on a quest to find Monica's daughter
... who police believe was abducted from Eau Claire Wisconsin
last September by a family friend. </I>
<P>
<I>The FBI and police in Eau Claire say there's a good possibility
13-year-old Jessica Mullenberg was brought to the Waterloo area
by 38-year-old Paul Oliver. A man and girl fitting the description
of the two were spotted by several people. </I>
<P>
<I>Jessica disappeared in September after Oliver received permission
from her father to take her to a work project. </I>
<P>
<I>Posters featuring their pictures are being be distributed in
the Kitchener- Waterloo and Cambridge areas. Anthony Pooley ...
Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Love Canal Update</H3>

<P>
Occidental Chemicals has agreed to pay 129-million dollars US
to cover Washington's cleanup costs at New York State's Love Canal.

<P>
It was dug in the 1890's for an abandoned Hydro-power project
in upstate New York, and became a dump site during the second
world war. Twenty-two- thousand tons of chemical waste was buried
there from 1942 to 1953. 
<P>
Love Canal attracted attention in the late 1970's and early 1980's
when hundreds of families from the Niagara falls, New York neighborhood
were forced to leave their homes. 
<HR>

<H3>Harris-Jobs </H3>

<P>
Premier Mike Harris says his deepest regret about 1995 is that
Ontario was shortchanged on job creation. 
<P>
But Harris still predicts he will exceed his goal of 725-thousand
jobs over the next three years. 
<HR>

<H3>Plane Crash </H3>

<P>
Rescuers used chain saws today to rescue a girl who survived a
fiery American Airlines crash in Colombia. 
<P>
The girl, who is one of four survivors, is trapped under a fallen
tree. 
<P>
The Boeing 7-57 smashed into a mountain near Cali last night on
a flight from Miami. there were 164 people... mostly Colombians
... on board. FBI agents and a team of Boeing engineers are headed
to the crash site to help investigate. 
<HR>

<H3>Angola Crash</H3>

<P>
More than 80 children were killed in a Zairian charter plane which
crashed in Angola earlier this week. 
<P>
The fact that the tragedy occurred was not revealed until today.
141 people in all died in the crash. Overloading on the Lockheed
188 Electra appears to have been the cause of the crash. 
<HR>

<H3>Train Wreck </H3>

<P>
At least 75 people have died in a train wreck near Cairo. Egyptian
officials say more than 100 were injured when one train plowed
into the rear of another in heavy fog. 
<P>
Emergency crews are still swarming over the twisted wreckage looking
for survivors... and bodies. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Place-CPI</H3>

<P>
It may be a major scam... perpetrated on concert goers, and the
artists they paid to see. 
<P>
The former owners of Concert Productions International; or CPI
... are the targets of a growing fraud investigation involving
phony taxes collected from venues; that were legally tax exempt.
As Scot Urquhart reports; one of the venues involved ... was Hamilton
Place: 
<P>
<I>Michael Cole says, it's a lie ... and he is going after the
Toronto Star.</I>
<P>
<I>Cole and his partner Arthur Fogel; were the target of a newspaper
investigation; which claims the pair routinely charged a ten percent
entertainment tax to artists playing at the CNE, O'Keefe Centre
and Hamilton Place ... even though the venues were tax exempt.
</I>
<P>
<I>Debra Vivian of HECFI ... the body which operates Hamilton
Place theatre says, her organization had no part in the alleged
scheme: but she admits; Cole and Fogel could easily have withheld
a ten percent tax, without the knowledge of HECFI.</I>
<P>
<I>But Cole says; they never collected any taxes at Hamilton Place;
and reports to the contrary; are completely false. </I>
<P>
<I>The two men recently sold their interest in Concert Productions
International. However, they will still be the subject of a Metro
Toronto Police fraud investigation, and in their own defence they
will launch a libel suit against the newspaper; which Cole says
will run, into double digit millions. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, Scot Urquhart Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Big Birds </H3>

<P>
A big bird could be coming soon to a supermarket near you. Low
in fat and cholesterol and high in protein and iron, this new
product could catch on fast with those watching what they eat.
Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>This bin of red meat in an Ancaster supermarket is raising
a lot of questions ... mainly, what is it?</I>
<P>
<I>It's Emu, part of the fastest growing livestock industry in
north America. Sobey's of Ancaster is the only retail store in
Ontario selling this meat. The supermarket is doing a pilot for
the Emu Association, but plans to keep selling the product after
the pilot is over. </I>
<P>
<I>Although Millen says sales haven't been that great the first
two weeks Emu has been in the store, Emu producers could easily
catch consumers on the wave of healthy eating. Emu is higher in
protein and high than either beef or chicken, and it's lower in
cholesterol and fat. The big drawback is the price. Emu producer
Dave Doxey explains part of the high price is because their marketing
is still in its infancy. </I>
<P>
<I>With only 400 farms in Ontario, producers can't keep up. Doxey
says he doesn't want Emu to compete with chicken or beef, he simply
wants to provide an alternative to other meats on the market.
In three to five years, he predicts as more consumers become aware
of Emu, the price will eventually fall. </I>
<P>
<I>In Carlisle, Annette Hamm, Channel 11 News. </I>
<P>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

