<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/19/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Tuesday, December 19, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Omnibus Hearing 
<LI>Bill 26 - Doctors 
<LI>Bronx Shooting 
<LI>Kids - Violence 
<LI>Zundel- Droege- Court 
<LI>Angola Plane Crash 
<LI>Japan Volcano 
<LI>Tuzla: NATO Arrives 
<LI>Tobacco Clip 
<LI>Bankruptcies 
<LI>Milton No GO 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Hearing 2 </H3>

<P>
The province's teachers say the Harris government's omnibus bill
takes Ontario to the brink of dictatorship. And the Toronto board
of trade thinks user fees are just the ticket for keeping municipal
costs down. 
<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 - Doctors </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile... Ontario doctors may stage some job action to protest
the omnibus bill. 
<P>
Ontario Medical Association President Dr. Ian Warrack couldn't
say if that would involve a strike. The OMA predicts doctors could
also leave the province and Canada in growing numbers. 
<P>
The OMA appeared before public hearings on the omnibus bill in
Toronto today. the group's counter-attack came a day after Health
Minister Jim Wilson suggested doctors have inflated the cost of
health care. 
<HR>

<H3>Bronx Shooting</H3>

<P>
New York City police say two more people have died in a shoe-store
shooting in the Bronx. That brings the death toll to six. One
of the dead is a boy age 12 or 13. It's not clear if the dead
were customers or employees. 
<P>
The suspect was shot and critically wounded by police in a gunfight
outside the store. Police describe the incident as a robbery gone
awry. They say the gunman entered the store, announced a holdup
and began shooting. 
<P>
Less than two weeks ago eight people were killed in Harlem when
a gunman opened fire in a clothing store and then set fire to
the building. 
<HR>

<H3>Kids - Violence </H3>

<P>
Call them soft targets. They are easy to hit, and easy to destroy.

<P>
We aren't talking about the war in Bosnia ... we're talking about
the children; inside Canadian homes. Scot Urquhart has more: 
<P>
<I>The story is all too common... in Hamilton ... a father of
two, locks his children in the car inside a rented storage locker
... and all of them die. In Cambridge a two year old toddler chokes
to death; in a botched exorcism. In Toronto... a father pours
gasoline over his children and their home ... and sets a townhouse
on fire ... </I>
<P>
<I>Statistics Canada says; children under the age of eleven are
at serious risk in this country ... and the homicide rate for
children under the age of one ... is twice that of the adult Staff
Sergeant Mike Shea says; </I>
<P>
<I>The Child Abuse Branch of the Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police
has seen a marked increase in the number of reported cases of
violence against children and more often than not ... strangers
are not involved.</I>
<P>
<I>At the Community Child Abuse Council of Hamilton Wentworth
... Brenda Symons Moulton, deals with the problems, every day.
The council says the keys to stopping the violence are prevention,
and support. </I>
<P>
<I>But while families, friends and neighbours may be able to help
more ... the government is about to do less: and if society can't
protect the defenseless ... who can? In Hamilton, Scot Urquhart,
Channel Eleven News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Zundel- Droege- Court </H3>

<P>
Holocaust revisionist Ernst Zundel and Heritage Front founder
Wolfgang Droege appeared in court in Toronto today in separate
cases. 
<P>
Zundel has been charged by a holocaust survivor with promoting
hatred. his hearing was rescheduled to February. 
<P>
Droege is charged with criminal contempt of a federal court order
not to put hate messages on the Heritage Front's telephone hotline
back in January. Droege may be back in court late next month if
lawyers in the case can agree on a date. 
<HR>

<H3>Angola Plane Crash</H3>

<P>
A chartered plane flying from Zaire to Angola has crashed in a
remote region of Angola, killing 139 of the 144 people on board.
<P>
The plane crashed Monday night, but the incident was not reported
until Tuesday evening. Details were vague, but transport officials
in Zaire said most of the passengers were Angolans. A spokesman
is quoted as saying ``there were 139 people on board, plus five
crew. There were only five survivors.'' 
<P>
The cause of the crash was not known. But officials identified
the plane as an Electra belonging to Trans Service Airlift, one
of several air charter companies operating in Zaire. No other
details were immediately available. 
<HR>

<H3>Japan Volcano </H3>

<P>
In Japan, white volcanic ash is covering the ground near Mount
Hossho. 
<P>
The volcano - on the southern island of Kyushu - has ended its
two-month silence, spewing smoke and ash about two-thousand meters
into the air. 
<P>
October's activity was the first in the Kuju range in 257 years.
There's concern over more intense activity ... and scientific
observers have been sent to the area. 
<HR>

<H3>Tuzla: NATO Arrives </H3>

<P>
NATO formally took over peacekeeping duties in Bosnia from the
United Nations today. 
<P>
NATO troops and equipment continue to pouring into the war-torn
country as alliance commanders prepare to take over formal command.

<HR>

<H3>Tobacco Clip </H3>

<P>
Canada's three cigarette companies plan to start advertising next
year. The Canadian Tobacco Manufacturers Council says the ads
won't appear on television or radio, nor will they target minors.

<P>
The three companies -- Imperial Tobacco, RJR Macdonald, and Rothmans
Benson and Hedges say their code complies with criteria the Supreme
Court suggested in September, when it struck down a federal ad
ban as unconstitutional. 
<HR>

<H3>Bankruptcies</H3>

<P>
Business and personal bankruptcies soared in Ontario in October
by almost 32 percent to 26-hundred 64 from one year earlier. 
<P>
For the first 10 months of the year, Ontario saw more than 23-thousand
individuals and businesses go belly up... 11.6 per cent more than
the just under 21-thousand that did so in the first 10 months
of 1994. 
<HR>

<H3>Milton No GO </H3>

<P>
January fifth is the last day for off peak go- train service to
Milton. 
<P>
Bus service from union station will be increased to partially
compensate. Only peak rail service will be provided starting January
eighth, with five trains in the morning and another five in the
evening. GO Transit blames poor ridership for the decision. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

