<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/18/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Monday, December 18, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Omnibus Hearings 
<LI>Tories - Police 
<LI>Tories Tag 
<LI>Sales Tax Fraud 
<LI>China-Town Murder 
<LI>Ipperwash Charges 
<LI>Storm-Blood 
<LI>Women Smoking 
<LI>Fisheries Clip 
<LI>Bosnia Unload 
<LI>Russian Elections 
<LI>France Resumes 
<LI>US Shutdown 
<LI>Diana Christmas 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Hearings </H3>

<P>
Public hearings on the Ontario government's controversial omnibus
bill are now under way. 
<P>
The first day of hearings saw health minister Jim Wilson taking
the heat. 
<HR>

<H3>Tories - Police</H3>

<P>
Is the Tory government cleaning house? That's the claim of a labour
leader in Brantford who was fired from the city's police services
board. 
<P>
As Marci Ien reports, Garry Marshall is just the latest casualty
of the Tory ax. 
<P>
<I>Garry Macdonald made the comment after the throne speech in
September...and the subsequent storming of the legislature. A
riot that saw several injured in battles with police. </I>
<P>
<I>Brantford Tory MPP Ron Johnson says Macdonald's words were
inappropriate... and brought the case to Solicitor-General Bob
Runciman's attention. Macdonald says that hidden Tory agenda is
to relieve all NDP appointed police board members from their positions.
A claim that Ron Johnson denies. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Tories Tag </H3>

<P>
And another note, Garry Macdonald is not the only person with
NDP ties to be dismissed from a police board. 
<P>
Last Friday, former Ottawa mayor Marion Dewar was fired from her
job as chairwoman of the Ottawa-Carleton Police Services Board.

<HR>

<H3>Sales Tax Fraud</H3>

<P>
Sales tax evasion is soaring in Ontario. The provinces' Finance
Ministry says incidents of sales tax fraud have increased six
hundred percent in the last seven years. And, the amount of money
being scammed is up dramatically too. Average evasion was 19-thousand
dollars in 1988 ...now it's 130-thousand. 
<P>
A St. Catharines businessman, 49 year old Mohamed Munshi, is one
of the latest retailers convicted of sales tax evasion. The operator
of two &quot;Smokers Place&quot; outlets in the Niagara peninsula
has been fined 40-thousand dollars for failing to remit 98-thousand
dollars in taxes owing. Ontario collects about 9 billion dollars
a year in retail sales tax. 
<HR>

<H3>China-town Murder</H3>

<P>
Police in Toronto are continuing their investigation into a shooting
at a Chinese restaurant that left one person dead and three others
injured. 
<P>
The dead man was found outside the Jun-Jun restaurant, with an
AK 47 rifle next to him. It's not clear if he was the gunman or
if there was another shooter. It's believed some people involved
in the incident took off in cabs before police arrived. 
<HR>

<H3>Ipperwash Charges </H3>

<P>
A noisy demonstration outside a Sarnia courthouse this morning.

<P>
About two dozen natives are protesting charges laid against five
people during the occupation of Ipperwash Provincial Park last
September. The five face several weapons and assault charges.
The protesters are also angry about being left out of talks aimed
at the formal return of Camp Ipperwash to natives. 
<HR>

<H3>Storm-Blood </H3>

<P>
A recent snowstorm has caused a big drop in blood donations. That's
forced some Ontario hospitals to cancel surgery. 
<P>
Supplies at the Toronto blood centre, which supplies blood and
blood products to 61 hospitals, are at critical levels after poor
weather canceled one large clinic and lowered turnouts at others.
The centre's director says it will postpone more elective surgery
unless supplies increase. 
<HR>

<H3>Women Smoking</H3>

<P>
Despite years of warning about of the dangers of cigarettes, the
number of smoking related deaths continues to rise. Especially
among women. 
<P>
While death rates for smoking related cancers among men have stabilized
after doubling between 1950 and 1985, the rates for women has
quadrupled, and are still growing. 
<HR>

<H3>Fisheries Clip</H3>

<P>
Despite years of protest from animal rights activists, the Canadian
government has increased the hunting quota for Atlantic seals.
The quota increase is huge ... 35 per cent, and is part of a new
groundfish conservation strategy. 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Unload </H3>

<P>
After days of weather delays, NATO planes are landing in Tuzla.

<P>
The first US combat troops will move American troops and equipment
into Bosnia, preparing the way for NATO's 60-thousand member operation.
But as the NATO buildup continues, a sniper's bullet has caused
the first casualty in Sarajevo since the Bosnian peace plan was
signed last week. 
<P>
A 30 year old woman on a streetcar was wounded after a bullet
hit her. 
<HR>

<H3>Russian Elections</H3>

<P>
Although preliminary returns from Russia's election won't be complete
for two more days, Russia's communists seem to be holding their
lead. 
<P>
The communists have garnered 22 per cent of the vote for seats
in parliament. Canadians who observed the election say the voting
was fair and open. 
<HR>

<H3>France Resumes </H3>

<P>
Regular transit schedules have resumed in France, after a month
long strike by public employees. 
<P>
Rail workers and other public service workers voted last Friday
to end their walkout over the government's deficit cutting package.
Fares for trains, subways and buses will be free until service
is back to normal. 
<P>
With Christmas just a week away, and their savings running low,
the workers simply lost momentum. 
<HR>

<H3>US Shutdown </H3>

<P>
And while the French transit system opens up, the American government
is facing another partial shutdown ... the second in a month.

<P>
Several US tourist attractions have temporarily shut down, because
there isn't enough money to pay people to work there. 
<P>
A quarter of a million federal workers were sent home today. Both
the Republicans and Clinton administration are blaming each other
for the shutdown. But the two sides have agreed to meet, possibly
to discuss a new balanced budget proposal. 
<HR>

<H3>Diana Christmas</H3>

<P>
There'll be a little more elbow room at the table for Christmas
dinner at Buckingham palace. 
<P>
At the last minute, Diana the Princess of Wales has changed her
plans and will not spend Christmas with the royal family. It's
the first time since she separated from prince Charles three years
ago that Diana will be apart from her sons during the holidays.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

