<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/15/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Friday, December 15, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Session Ender 
<LI>Last Call 
<LI>London Doctors 
<LI>Doctors Going South 
<LI>Tax Cuts 
<LI>Bernardo Costs 
<LI>Guard Evening 
<LI>Morgentaler - Pope 
<LI>Feds Overhaul 
<LI>Interac Bust Up 
<LI>Ethanol Plant 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Session Ender </H3>

<P>
Ontario will never be the same ... those words from Premier Mike
Harris of the province...and the opposition agrees with him. 
<P>
The first session of the Ontario legislature ended last night.
It started with a riot... and was highlighted by an all night
sit in by MPPs. 
<HR>

<H3>Last Call </H3>

<P>
And there are still many more changes to come down the pike from
the Tories. 
<P>
One under consideration now is to extend bar hours past one o'clock...
until two or three in the morning. Consumer Affairs Minister Norm
Sterling says changing drinking hours would help Ontario bars
compete with those in other provinces and the United States. 
<P>
The idea is receiving mixed reviews... positive from many bar
owners and patrons...but not so positive from the group, Mothers
Against Drunk Driving. The groups says it will lead to more carnage.

<HR>

<H3>London Doctors</H3>

<P>
Doctors in London are banding together to beat the Tory government's
omnibus bill... a new political action committee of doctors says
bill 26 gives politicians ultimate control over the medical profession.

<P>
The doctors say they'd better speak up now, before it's too late..
and the system is damaged beyond repair. 
<HR>

<H3>Doctors Going South</H3>

<P>
Bill 26 is just another reason for Ontario doctors to leave this
province and head south... and this weekend a conference will
give them the know how they need to take their skills to the United
States. 
<P>
Up to seventy doctors are expected at the conference in St. Thomas
which will teach them how to move their practices to the US. The
conference is hosted by a Toronto company that specializes in
recruiting disenchanted Canadian physicians to the US. 
<HR>

<H3>Tax Cuts </H3>

<P>
The Harris government is being advised to delay tax cuts if it
wants to meet its deficit target. 
<P>
The Dominion Bond Rating Service says it may become necessary
to cut more spending and to hold off on the promised tax cuts,
in order to trim the deficit as much as the government wants.

<P>
Harris has promised to cut personal income tax rates by 30 per
cent and to cut eight-billion dollars in spending. The bond rating
agency says no can do. But cabinet minister Dave Johnson says
the tax cuts will come regardless. 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Costs</H3>

<P>
The country's most expensive murder manhunt will officially shut
down by year's end. 
<P>
A skeleton crew of detectives is still cleaning up paperwork of
the Green Ribbon Task Force. But by the end of the year, just
over two weeks away now, all of the investigators will return
to their regular duties. 
<P>
The task force spent 8-million dollars to bring Paul Bernardo
to trial for their deaths ... the costliest murder manhunt in
Canadian history. 
<P>
The costs include nearly 20-thousand dollars for office furniture,
19-hundred dollars on counseling for task force members and 31-hundred
dollars for hotel rooms police used for surveillance of Bernardo's
ex-wife Karla Homolka. 
<HR>

<H3>Guard Evening </H3>

<P>
A provincial jail guard has been charged with sexually assaulting
female inmates at the Hamilton Wentworth detention centre. 
<P>
The charges come after a seven month OPP investigation. Police
say the assaults are alleged to have occurred between 1990 and
1995 and involve five women. 
<P>
33 year old Marc (ree'-al) of Welland appeared for a bail hearing
on three counts of sexual assault and five counts of breach of
trust. He has been remanded in custody until Monday when his case
will be moved to Waterloo Region.
<P>
(ree'-al) has been working as a correctional officer at the centre
since April of 1990. 
<HR>

<H3>Morgentaler - Pope</H3>

<P>
Abortion doctor Henry Morgentaler has effectively accused Pope
John Paul of inciting pro-life fanatics to commit acts of violence
against doctors who perform abortions, as well as their families.

<P>
He has written a letter to the pontiff in which he says he and
other abortion doctors have been demonized by religious conservatives.

<P>
All of this at a Toronto news conference today. Anthony Pooley
reports. 
<P>
<I>Without a doubt, it is the single most controversial and divisive
moral issue of our time, pitting pro-choice against pro-life,
with the latter's fanatical fringe occasionally resorting to violence
against those who perform abortions, exemplified by this bombing
of a clinic more than three years ago and recent gunshots fired
at physicians in Ancaster and Vancouver. </I>
<P>
<I>Abortion doctor Henry Morgentaler believes it is the strong
rhetoric surrounding religious dogma that incites fanatics to
commit these acts, while targeted physicians and their families
live in mortal fear. </I>
<P>
<I>For his own war of words, Morgentaler has targeted the single
largest religious denomination that dogmatically denounces abortion.
More than that, he suggests that the moral influence of the leader
of the Roman Catholic Church ... Pope John Paul the second ...
and the power of his anti- abortion rhetoric ... extends well
beyond the faithful.</I>
<P>
<I>In a letter to the pope, Morgentaler is seeking unequivocal
denunciation of the violence, and moderation of rhetoric. And
he has also written to the Canadian Council of Catholic Bishops,
seeking dialogue with them. No one from the church would agree
to an on-camera interview. In a written statement, the council
says that it will continue to stand up for human life both inside
and outside the womb, and to condemn all forms of violence against
human life. As for dialogue... it is unlikely. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Feds Overhaul </H3>

<P>
The federal government is working on a piece of legislation that
would give it new, far-reaching powers. 
<P>
The Ottawa Citizen newspaper says deputy ministers have been briefed
on a plan to restructure the public service. The plan would make
it easier for Ottawa to reach its goal of cutting forty five thousand
jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Interac Bust Up</H3>

<P>
Canadian consumers may soon be able to get their money in new
ways at new places ... and they'll do it for less. 
<P>
The Competition Bureau has loosened the monopoly on the Interac
system held by banks and trust companies. 
<P>
Now, retailers and insurance companies will be able to join the
Interac electronic banking network. That could mean lower services
charges for automatic teller withdrawals and debit card purchases.

<HR>

<H3>Ethanol Plant</H3>

<P>
Good news for Ontario corn farmers and for the quality of our
air. 
<P>
Not on the list of government cuts is provincial money to build
a multi-million dollar ethanol plant in Chatham. The government
pulled the plug on the funding two months ago, but Agriculture
Minister Noble Villeneuve has come to a five million dollar financial
support agreement. The plant would manufacture ethanol from corn
.. and would supply a market for up to thirty million bushels
of Ontario corn. 
<P>
Ethanol is blended into gasoline to produce an environmentally
safer fuel for all cars. It's available at over two hundred and
fifty outlets throughout the province...and at some Sunoco stations.

<P>
