<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/14/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Thursday, December 14, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Bosnia Peace Pact 
<LI>Signing Reax 
<LI>Winter Slush 
<LI>Sault Roof Down 
<LI>Green Ribbon Probe 
<LI>Justice Clips 
<LI>Rape Privacy 
<LI>Canton Promo 
<LI>Gas Tax? 
<LI>OMA-Bill 26 
<LI>Emergency Wilson 
<LI>United Church 
<LI>Agostino-Pledge 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Peace Pact </H3>

<P>
Just three minutes... that's how long it took to sign an agreement
to end nearly four years of war in the former Yugoslavia. 
<P>
It has been a war characterized by the most brutal and horrific
fighting and atrocities in Europe since the end of the second
world war... but today diplomats and world leaders called on all
sides to grasp this opportunity for peace. 
<P>
The agreement was struck in Dayton, Ohio last month and leaves
Bosnia in a divided state. Sixty thousand NATO forces will be
put on the ground to monitor the implementation of the peace pact.

<HR>

<H3>Signing Reax </H3>

<P>
It seems not everyone has read the peace pact. 
<P>
While most Bosnians were watching the signing of the peace deal...
and cautiously celebrating the end of the brutal war, shelling
started in Sarajevo. Just a hint of what the NATO troops including
Canadians will have to contend with. 
<HR>

<H3>Winter Slush </H3>

<P>
Today's morning rush hour was hell, as old man winter unloaded
everything in its arsenal upon beleaguered commuters. 
<P>
There was snow followed by sleet followed by rain... and then
fog... as Anthony Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>What a day! It snowed overnight, then just as commuters were
set to head into work, it started to rain and suddenly, even the
best plowed roads turned to sheets of ice as highways and byways
filled to the brim with morning rush hour traffic. </I>
<P>
<I>Then as the temperature rose to above freezing, roads became
slushy as well as icy, making driving treacherous. There were
dozens of minor accidents. </I>
<P>
<I>Those lucky enough to have the day off had plenty of work cut
out for them... with portable snowblowers and shovels as the implements
of choice. </I>
<P>
<I>School busses did not run, although some school boards kept
classrooms open for those who could get there. Numerous other
community activities were canceled, and some agencies and centres
remained closed for the day. </I>
<P>
<I>And on top of everything else, this afternoon, fog became a
factor, resulting in limited visibility for ground and air traffic
alike. At Pearson International Airport, both incoming and outgoing
flights were delayed. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Sault Roof Down </H3>

<P>
And you would be wise to double-check before you head out anywhere
tonight...a number of events have been canceled across southern
Ontario and plane delays are still possible with fog causing some
problems. 
<P>
And problems still for areas in the northern part of the province..
part of the snow-packed roof at a mall in Sault Ste. Marie came
crashing down this morning. 
<P>
Witnesses say the roof at Station Mall rumbled like thunder before
caving in -- no injuries have been reported, except for one woman
suffering from shock. 
<P>
The Soo has been hit with 175 centimetres of snow in the past
week. 
<HR>

<H3>Green Ribbon Probe </H3>

<P>
An internal report on the Green Ribbon Task Force and its work
investigating the murders of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy
will not be made public at least not for now ..Lauran Sabourin
has the details. 
<P>
<I>In a tersely worded statement the chairperson of the Niagara
Police Services Board told the media that the internal review
on the Green Ribbon Task Force investigation of the murders of
Kristen French, Leslie Mahaffy and Tammy Homolka would not be
released today. </I>
<P>
<I>The board said it didn't want to make this document public
because it will be a key part of the much larger provincial probe
into the Green Ribbon Task Force and metro Sex Assaults Squads
handling of the case against Paul Bernardo. And the second investigation
into the controversial plea deal made with Bernardo's ex wife
Karla Homolka. </I>
<P>
<I>Chairperson Melva Snowling would reveal little about the internal
report. It was chief Grant Waddell who initially and apparently
in consultation with the board lawyer who recommended that the
report which is more than 100 pages be made public. He has changed
his mind...</I>
<HR>

<H3>Justice Clips </H3>

<P>
Justice Minister Allan Rock has introduced a bill that would crack
down on stalkers and those who prey on prostitutes, especially
young ones. 
<P>
Any stalker who kills would automatically be convicted of first-degree
murder. The legislation would also make it easier for child prostitutes
to testify against their pimps. It also raises minimum jail terms
to five years for pimps who coerce those under 18 into prostitution.

<HR>

<H3>Rape Privacy </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the Supreme Court has ruled that those accused of sexual
assault have a right to the medical records of their alleged victims...
and that includes the notes of counselors and psychologists who
have helped the victims recover. 
<P>
Women's groups say the ruling could stop victims from reporting
the crimes...for fear of the public humiliation. 
<HR>

<H3>Canton Promo </H3>

<P>
And also in Ottawa today, now that Lucien Bouchard has stepped
down as leader of the Bloc Quebecois, the Reform Party is making
its move to replace the Bloc as the official opposition and immigration
rules are being changed to target abusers of our welcome matt......
we'll have more on those stories on Canada tonight at six thirty.

<HR>

<H3>Gas Tax? </H3>

<P>
Despite what the premier says ...opposition parties at Queens
Park say that the voluminous bill 26 will allow municipalities
to levy new taxes ..including a tax on gasoline. 
<P>
Ernist Town, a township of 11 thousand people in eastern Ontario,
has asked the government for permission to level a gas tax to
pay for local road maintenance. And other municipalities believe
they should be able to do the same.. once again however the government
denies it will happen. 
<HR>

<H3>OMA-Bill 26 </H3>

<P>
The Liberals took on the cause of doctors in the house today...the
Ontario Medical Association is warning the public that the Harris
government's omnibus bill 26 will give the Minister of Health
the power to decide what medical treatment is appropriate. 
<HR>

<H3>Emergency Wilson</H3>

<P>
The province is expanding a pilot emergency medical project that
has proven effective in saving lives. 
<P>
Specially-trained ambulance attendants in Essex county, Halton
and Peel regions, Simcoe county and Muskoka carried symptom relief
medications and heart defibrillators with them over the past year.
And Health Minister Jim Wilson says at least five people's lives
were saved as a result. Wilson says the project will be expanded
to cover 90 per cent of Ontario. 
<HR>

<H3>United Church</H3>

<P>
The United Church of Canada wants governments to stop what it
calls a &quot;growing war&quot; against the poor. 
<P>
In a letter to be read during sermons at four-thousand churches
on Sunday, the church blasts political leaders who use what it
calls &quot;dangerous rhetoric&quot; to divide communities. It
says people are now being grouped according to those who have
enough income to pay taxes, and those who are sick, disabled,
unemployed or in need of education and medical care. 
<P>
A church spokeswoman says the letter doesn't single out any particular
government, but arose out of a concern that governments have been
unfairly targeting the poor. 
<P>
The church also wants January 7th designated as a day to discuss
ways to protest cuts, including a refusal to keep any tax breaks
promised by Ontario Premier Mike Harris that are funded by cutbacks.

<HR>

<H3>Agostino-Pledge</H3>

<P>
Hamilton Liberal MPP, Dominic Agostino got a Christmas wish today.
His private members' bill to add Canada to the oath of allegiance
taken by provincial members of parliament, received the all important
second reading today. 
<P>
Last spring Agostino was prevented from taking his seat in the
legislature as an MPP, because he tried to change the oath of
allegiance, to include Canada as well as the Queen. So the determined
MPP introduced a private members bill to change the oath. Today
the bill came to a vote in the legislature. 
<P>
Education Minister John Snobelen brought some extra Tories into
the house in an effort to defeat the bill ..but to no avail. It
passed second reading 36 to 16. Agostino was astounded at Snobelen's
tactics. 
<P>
Agostino's bill in all probability be come law next spring. 

<P>
