<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/13/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Wednesday, December 13, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Plane Crash 
<LI>RCMP Report 
<LI>OMA. - Omnibus 
<LI>Hospital Charges 
<LI>Child Care 
<LI>Child Reax 
<LI>Finance Meet 
<LI>Legal Aid Deal 
<LI>Harris-Head Tax 
<LI>Cheap Lunches 
<LI>Cochran Speaks 
<LI>Durham Fire Deaths 
<LI>Brain Surgery 
<LI>Winter Storm
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Plane Crash </H3>

<P>
Italian police say all 45 people on board a Romanian airliner
died today when it crashed on takeoff at Verona. 
<P>
The plane went down about one kilometre from the end of the runway,
slamming into the ground in snowy, windy weather. 
<P>
A fierce fire raged after the crash, but it's unclear yet whether
the flames broke out before or after the plane went down. 
<P>
Most of the victims are believed to have been Italians. It's not
clear where the aircraft was heading. 
<HR>

<H3>RCMP Report </H3>

<P>
Poor training and weak policies are to blame for the break-in
at the Prime Minister's residence. 
<P>
That's the bottom line of a long awaited report on the RCMP's
failure to prevent the break-in and it's slow reaction time to
the Prime Minister's call for help. An intruder armed with a knife
made it all the way to the PMs bedroom door. 
<P>
Solicitor General Herb Gray says the report is somewhat vague
for a reason. To ensure the fair trial of the man accused of attempting
to kill the PM. 
<HR>

<H3>OMA. - Omnibus </H3>

<P>
The Ontario Ministry of Health is about to be deluged by thousands
of faxes from disgruntled physicians, seeking prior approval for
even the simplest medical procedures. 
<P>
It's part of a planned protest against new, sweeping government
powers over just about every aspect of a physician's practice,
called for in the notorious Omnibus bill 26, expected to become
Ontario law early next year. 
<P>
Anthony Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>Is the day finally here when government bureaucrats and politicians
are looking over the shoulders of every physician, second guessing
what they do and how they do it? Ontario's doctors believe that's
what will happen if bill 26 passes without revision. That's the
notorious omnibus bill that touches just about every aspect of
the lives of Ontarians. </I>
<P>
<I>Doctors throughout Ontario gathered in various venues today
to listen to the president of their association via satellite
hook-up. The OMA says that bill 26 would: -erode patient confidentiality
through the publication of medical records; -scrap partnership
agreements between doctors and the government; -result in a complete
government take-over of medical care, including the empowerment
of bureaucrats to contradict medical decisions; -strip doctors
of hospital privileges without the right to appeal; -and forbid
doctors from practicing in certain regions of the province. </I>
<P>
<I>Physicians will also be asking their patients to sign petitions
and mail in post cards opposing the bill 26 measures. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton... Anthony Pooley... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Hospital Charges </H3>

<P>
Also under the omnibus bill, thousands of hospital patients would
be forced to pay room and board. 
<P>
Any patient waiting for a place in a nursing home or a chronic
care hospital would be charged nearly twenty seven dollars a day,
to stay in the hospital. Right now those charges are picked up
by OHIP. 
<P>
Up to five thousand people could be effected by the charge. That's
how many people on any given day are in hospital waiting for other
care. 
<HR>

<H3>Child Care </H3>

<P>
Ontario Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi says he doesn't
know whether or not he'll cash in on Ottawa's new day care offer...
Human Resources Minister Lloyd Axworthy is offering the provinces
and aboriginal groups 720-million dollars for child care over
the next three to five years. 
<P>
The provinces would have to match the federal cash dollar for
dollar to qualify. 
<HR>

<H3>Child Reax.</H3>

<P>
The Ontario Coalition for Better Childcare says it is &quot;somewhat&quot;
pleased with Ottawa's plans for more daycare spaces, but mostly
confused. Coalition President Kerry McCuaig says the plan is &quot;vague&quot;.

<P>
There is concern over the government not calling the plan a national
child care program. And they are worried about the regulation
of day care. 
<HR>

<H3>Finance Meet </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, in Ottawa, the country's finance ministers are talking
about tinkering with your pension... specifically, the possibility
of raising the qualifying age for the Canadian pension plan from
65 to 67. 
<P>
However the ministers have agree that that would only be as a
last resort. 
<HR>

<H3>Legal Aid Deal</H3>

<P>
The Ontario government and the law society have come to an agreement
which will see the backlog of legal aid bills paid. 
<P>
But the announcement made by Attorney General Charles Harnick,
does not sit well with a good portion of the legal profession,
and may present problems for the poor and illegal immigrants.

<HR>

<H3>Harris-Head Tax</H3>

<P>
More assurances from the Tories that their jumbo bill will not
allow municipalities to charge a head tax or impose new sales
or incomes taxes. 
<P>
Premier Mike Harris says there is no way his government will it.
Harris says through the omnibus bill, local governments will be
able to charge user fees ..but no new taxes. 
<P>
Municipal Affairs Minister Al Leach said yesterday, that if the
bill gave the right to municipalities to levy a head tax, he would
resign. 
<HR>

<H3>Cheap Lunches </H3>

<P>
And there will be no such thing as a cheap lunch at Queen's Park
anymore. 
<P>
MPPs meals at the Queen's Park dining room will no longer be subsidized.
That decision from the legislature's board of internal economy.

<P>
The subsidies had been eating a three million dollar deficit into
the legislature's food services group for the last three years.

<HR>

<H3>Cochran Speaks </H3>

<P>
The OJ. Simpson tour of lawyers continued today ... yesterday
it was prosecutor Marcia Clark ...today it's lead defence lawyer
for Simpson, Johnny Cochran. 
<P>
Flanked by body guards, Simpson's lead defence lawyer told a news
conference in Toronto today that many of the racial issues raised
by the Simpson trial are relevant to Canada because systemic racism
exists in every society. 
<P>
He insists he is not trying to profit from the killings that led
to the OJ Simpson trial. However, unlike Marcia Clark, Cochran
was willing to comment on the trial. Cochran is to speak to a
full house tonight in Toronto. 
<HR>

<H3>Durham Fire Deaths</H3>

<P>
Two bodies -- believed to be those of a mother and daughter --
have been found in the burned remains of a farmhouse near Toronto.

<P>
The house near Mosport burned yesterday... and today police are
trying to determine for certain who the victims are... they believe
they are a 56-year-old woman and her 17-year-old daughter. But
investigators say dental records will have to be used... no word
on the cause of the blaze yet. 
<HR>

<H3>Brain Surgery </H3>

<P>
Canada's first endoscopic brain surgery was performed at St. Michael's
hospital in Toronto and today the patient is going home. 
<P>
Last week, doctors removed a portion of an extensive pituitary
tumor from the base of the patient's brain. The instruments were
inserted through the nose. 
<P>
Doctors say the advantages to this kind of surgery include less
scarring, a faster recovery period, decreased medical costs, and
potentially fewer complications. 
<HR>

<H3>Winter Storm</H3>

<P>
Southern Ontario is in for a whallop of winter... a winter storm
watch has been issued for a region extending from Windsor east
to the Toronto area, and as far north as Muskoka. 
<P>
Several areas already hit by blinding snowsqualls... environment
Canada says the messy weather will include up to fifteen centimetres
of snow... and then freezing rain. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

