<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/12/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Tuesday, December 12, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Roof Collapse 
<LI>Bad Weather 
<LI>Animal Charges 
<LI>MPP Compensation 
<LI>Curling Banished 
<LI>Kicked Out Of School 
<LI>Marcia Clark 
<LI>AIDS Drug 
<LI>Mill Fire
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Roof Collapse </H3>

<P>
The massive snowfall across the province is taking its toll again
today... the roof of the Midland Mirror Newspaper offices collapsed
under the weight of the heavy snow. 
<P>
One employee was trapped when tons of snow and debris crashed
into the building. Christine Roberts was pulled out of the rubble
by rescuers and taken to hospital. But she is reported to be just
fine after her ordeal. 
<HR>

<H3>Bad Weather</H3>

<P>
Schools and highways were closed again today in some parts of
the province menaced still by snowsqualls... snowfall records
were still being smashed as more snow fell overnight and today
in the Barrie-Orillia area... the snowbanks just keep getting
bigger and bigger. ... and snowsqualls from lake Huron and Georgian
Bay continued to paralyze areas from Goderich to Owen Sound. 
<P>
To give you an idea of just how much snow has come down, Environment
Canada says the Orillia area normally receives 280 centimetres
of snow each winter, but more than that has already fallen, about
295 centimetres here are the figures for the past few days alone...
80 centimetres of snow fell on Fort Erie on Sunday -- that doubles
the previous one-day December record set in 1977. 
<P>
106 centimetres fell on the Owen Sound area over the past three
days. 
<P>
And 140 centimetres, that is nearly five feet, landed on Sault
Ste. Marie since this past weekend. 
<P>
In Michigan, the storm was blamed for at least five deaths...
as blizzards and unseasonably cold weather froze schools, and
businesses and left motorists stranded on highways...or for the
lucky ones ...at service stations and motels. 
<P>
And yes, more snow.. and more cold is on its way.. another ten
centimetres is due Thursday and this frigid air is around for
a bit too.
<HR>

<H3>Animal Charges </H3>

<P>
With the frigid weather comes a stern reminder not to leave your
animals outside in this cold... not only could the animals suffer
serious injury and even death...but you can be charged with neglect
as well.
<HR>

<H3>MPP Compensation</H3>

<P>
Provincial politicians started running for cover today in the
wake of a government commissioned report which advocated giving
MPPs 110 thousand dollars a year in salary. Premier Mike Harris
quickly said he would veto the proposal. 
<HR>

<H3>Curling Banished</H3>

<P>
And the man who led the charge against bill 26 has been kicked
out of the legislature.
<P>
Liberal MPP Alvin Curling staged an 18-hour sit-in at the Ontario
legislature to protest the jumbo bill. 
<P>
Speaker Al McLean has barred Curling from the house until next
spring. 
<P>
However government house leader Ernie Eves has said he is willing
to meet with the opposition parties to see if a compromise can
be worked out. 
<P>
Curling's protest began around four o'clock in the afternoon last
Wednesday, when the opposition parties protested the Tory government's
plans to pass the bill by Christmas. he declined to vote on a
routine motion and refused to leave his seat when the sergeant-at-arms
tried to have him removed. 
<HR>

<H3>Kicked Out of School </H3>

<P>
There'll be no more school for two boys who caused fifty thousand
dollars worth of damage at a Hamilton public school last month.

<P>
The boys, aged 10 and 11, broke windows, smashed computers, threw
paint and emptied fire extinguishers at Westview Middle school.
Citing it as a very serious case of vandalism the board of trustees
with the Hamilton Board of Education expelled the two boys. 
<P>
Cheryl Macpherson says what her son did was wrong, but so is the
board's decision. Some might say the punishment is too harsh,
but according to the Hamilton Board of Education it is based on
Ministry guidelines and broad-based community support. 
<P>
The parents may apply to have their children re-instated in six
months. 
<HR>

<H3>Marcia Clark </H3>

<P>
OJ Simpson prosecutor Marcia Clark spoke out against domestic
violence for the first time since the double murder trial ended.

<P>
She told an audience at Roy Thompson Hall last night that society
has to treat spousal abuse seriously because it is a crime...
and she urged people not to turn a blind eye if they witness domestic
violence but to get involved. 
<P>
Clark also spoke to reporters but did not discuss the famous trial
of the former footballer.
<HR>

<H3>AIDS Drug</H3>

<P>
A new drug that has shown remarkable results on AIDS patients
has been approved for sale in Canada. 
<P>
The drug was developed in Canada and received US approval a few
weeks ago. 
<P>
As Dwight Ryan explains, some scientists believe &quot;3-t-c&quot;
is the greatest Canadian contribution to medical science since
insulin. 
<P>
<I>Scientists are quick to say that the drug 3TC is not a cure
for </I>AIDS<I>. But combined with AZT, the most commonly used
anti-HIV drug, 3TC is showing remarkable results. </I>
<P>
<I>Discovered and developed in Canada, 3TC was this week approved
for sale by Canada's health protection branch. </I>
<P>
<I>Scientists at Montreal's Biochem Pharma discovered the drug
six years ago. The rights were sold to the British based pharmaceutical
company Glaxo Wellcome who then conducted further testing in Mississauga
and brought it to the market. </I>
<P>
<I>Unlike some drugs, HIV patients have few side effects from
taking 3TC along with AZT. And the amount of </I>AIDS<I> virus
in the blood is often reduced by as much as 90 percent. </I>AIDS<I>
patients and activists are understandably excited about the government
approval given to 3TC. But for many, the discovery comes to late.
Dwight Ryan, Channel 11 News.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Mill Fire </H3>

<P>
A massive blaze at a mill in Methuen Massachussetts injured at
least two dozen people, many of them critically.
<P>
Firefighters have been working on the blaze all night and day...
at the peak the texture factory complex was completely engulfed,
sending flames as high as a hundred and fifty feet into the frigid
night sky. 
<P>
More than a hundred firefighters from thirty communities were
brought in to battle the tremendous fire. 
<P>
Malden Mills is the largest employer in the town about twenty
five miles north of Boston. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

