<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/11/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Monday, December 11, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Ontario Deep Freeze 
<LI>Deep Freeze Tag 
<LI>London Protest 
<LI>Protest Reaction 
<LI>Marleau Smoking 
<LI>Holiday Booze 
<LI>Work Women 
<LI>Loomis Update 
<LI>Homicide Child
<LI>Sinkhole
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Ontario Deep Freeze </H3>

<P>
It was an awesome sight... four feet of snow reported in parts
of Ontario and the US... and it happened fast ...very fast.
<P>
A series of vicious storms paralyzed large areas... and as the
snowbanks rose, the temperatures tumbled. 
<P>
As Lauran Sabourin reports it is all going into the record books.

<P>
<I>Ontario's cottage country was buried under four feet of snow
this weekend. Blinding snow that stranded unprepared motorists
in three foot drifts. </I>
<P>
<I>Conditions so treacherous the major highways including highways
69 and 169 were closed. Snowmobiles and four wheel drive vehicles
were the only way to get around. </I>
<P>
<I>Although snow squalls were forecast for the area the storm
still left many people asking where this storm came from. </I>
<P>
<I>Snow drifts are what people in the southern end of Niagara
and buffalo are digging out of this morning. Forty inches of snow
off of lake Erie were dumped on the region. The heaviest 24 hour
snowfall on record. </I>
<P>
<I>A state of emergency was declared in the city. The national
guard was called out to help clear clogged streets. Streets so
impassable that vehicles were ordered off the roads. </I>
<P>
<I>The area where the snow was being dumped looked like a barren
arctic wasteland. So much snow that people are comparing this
storm to the blizzard of 77. </I>
<P>
<I>Areas of the province that escaped the snow will still remember
this weather system. Over the weekend record low temperatures
were recorded at the Hamilton weather office. Another record breaking
night is expected this evening.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Deep Freeze Tag </H3>

<P>
The following highways in central Ontario remain closed: 
<P>
highway 11 Orillia to Barrie; highway 400 Barrie to highway 89;
highway 26 from Staynor to the junction of 26 and 27; highway
21 Owen sound to north of Goderich and highway 10 Owen sound to
Hepworth. 
<P>
In southwestern Ontario snow and wind has closed several highways,
including highway 8 from Clinton to Goderich; and highway 4 from
Clinton to Blyth.
<HR>

<H3>London Protest</H3>

<P>
It wasn't the weather that shut down the city of London...but
the first of what the unions say will be a series of strikes to
protest government cuts ...thousands of people marched through
the city ...with an aim to shut down London. 
<P>
NDP leader Bob Rae says today's shutdown of London should act
as a wake-up call for the Harris government. A call for the Tories
to slow down their irresponsible right-wing agenda. 
<HR>

<H3>Marleau Smoking </H3>

<P>
The federal government wants a complete ban on tobacco advertising.

<P>
Health Minister Diane Marleau released a blueprint today that
would prohibit tobacco ads, restrict other promotions such as
endorsements by celebrities and would clamp down on cigarette
sales to minors. It would also penalize arts and sports groups
by cutting funding to groups that receive money from tobacco companies.

<P>
Marleau's proposed measures are stronger than those contained
in the tobacco products control act, which was gutted by the Supreme
Court of Canada in a September ruling. 
<HR>

<H3>Holiday Booze </H3>

<P>
For the first time in Ontario, beer and liquor stores will be
open on a Sunday. 
<P>
Stores, employees and the government have all agreed to keep booze
outlets open on Christmas Eve from 11 a-m to 6 p-m. 
<P>
Brewers of Ontario vice president C.J. Healey says it wasn't difficult
to get government approval for the trial Sunday opening. He says
he expects sales to be brisk and store employees have welcomed
the extra day of sales. 
<P>
All beer stores in the province will remain open on December 24th,
and most liquor stores. 
<HR>

<H3>Work Women</H3>

<P>
There's no getting away from, women do more work than men... end
of story. 
<P>
The latest stats can survey showed that women at every stage of
their lives did more unpaid work than men, that means housework
and child care. And men enjoy on average a full hour more of leisure
time a day than women. 
<HR>

<H3>Loomis Update </H3>

<P>
A man remains in hospital under police guard tonight, after a
Shootout between Loomis guards and three masked men. 
<P>
It happened at the Cloverdale Mall last night. The Loomis guards
were delivering cash to a bank in the mall, when they were fired
at by the three. The guards returned fire and hit one in the neck.

<P>
None of the guards was hurt and no money was taken. The suspects
fled... and police made one arrest after a man staggered into
a hospital with a gun shot wound in the neck. 
<HR>

<H3>Homicide Child</H3>

<P>
A 31-year-old Toronto woman is charged with second-degree murder
in the beating death of her four-year-old daughter. 
<P>
Rosina Boateng was charged even before an autopsy into the death
of her daughter, Afua, was completed. 
<P>
Metro Toronto police found the child's body Saturday afternoon
in the family's Etobicoke apartment. Police say she died from
a severe beating. 
<HR>

<H3>Sinkhole </H3>

<P>
And from San Francisco, something that sounds like a bad science
fiction movie... a monster sinkhole swallowed a monster home in
a chi-chi neighbourhood called Sea Cliff. 
<P>
Bit by bit, the house slipped into the widening crater, until
it suddenly caved in. Eleven other homes have been evacuated and
trees and cars are precariously leaning at steep angles. 
<P>
The sinkhole is about sixty feet deep, two hundred feet wide,
and one hundred and fifty feet long. 
<P>
Workers say the collapse started when a sewer line broke. And
the combined sewer and rain water weakened foundations in the
area. Weather related flooding and power outages are hampering
efforts to contain the damage. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

