<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/08/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Friday, December 8, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Municipal User Fees 
<LI>Bill 26 Mock Hearing 
<LI>December 11th Promo 
<LI>Police-Runciman 
<LI>Hunter re: Bernardo 
<LI>Bernardo House 
<LI>CBC Cuts 
<LI>Tree Shortage 
<LI>AIDS Pennies 
<LI>Final Red Rocket 
<LI>Doggie Show 
<LI>Bosnia Aid 
<LI>France Strikes
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Municipal User Fees</H3>

<P>
At least a couple of mayors think the idea of users fees for services
is a good idea... the province's controversial omnibus bill would
give municipalities new powers to tax residents and sell city
run services. 
<P>
Both North York Mayor Mel Lastman and Mississauga Mayor Hazel
McCallion make no apologies for being behind user fees. Lastman
says he would charge to use skating rinks, swimming pools, some
city hall services and false fire alarms. Hazel McCallion also
favours fees for false fire and police alarms and use of the library.

<HR>

<H3>Bill 26 Mock Hearing </H3>

<P>
Even though the government has agreed to public hearings on its
all encompassing omnibus bill, the NDP caucus today started its
own consultations with the public on the jumbo bill. 
<HR>

<H3>December 11th Promo </H3>

<P>
It'll be a taste of Paris in London on Monday ... that's Paris
France and London Ontario... that's when unions are threatening
to shut down the city to protest the Tory government's deep spending
cuts. We'll have full coverage from London on Monday. 
<HR>

<H3>Police-Runciman</H3>

<P>
There could be fewer police chiefs across Ontario once a government
review of police structure and financing is complete. 
<P>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman says he wants to see if police
services can be restructured to add more front-line officers and
cut administration costs. Runciman plans to announce the review
in the legislature next week. 
<HR>

<H3>Hunter re: Bernardo</H3>

<P>
A group of citizens is concerned that the inquiry into the Karla
Homolka plea deal is being kept secret. The group leaders, who
also spearheaded a 300-thousand name petition against the deal,
held a news conference at Queen's Park this afternoon. 
<P>
They have a number of specific questions they want answered. The
questions include whether new charges will be laid against Homolka.
 They want to know if copies of the sexually explicit videotapes
are circulating in Florida. And was the plea bargain politically
motivated? 
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo House</H3>

<P>
It cost Ontario taxpayers $95,000 to buy the now-demolished house
where Paul Bernardo tortured and killed teenagers Kristen French
and Leslie Mahaffy. 
<P>
The house was reduced to a pile of rubble Tuesday and hauled to
an undisclosed site to be buried. Owners Brian Delaney and Rachel
Adams still retain title to the land. The payment covered only
the house rented to Bernardo and his former wife, Karla Homolka.

<HR>

<H3>CBC Cuts </H3>

<P>
The CBC cuts have begun. More than six hundred jobs disappeared
yesterday as three hundred and twenty seven pink slips went out..
and three hundred and twelve jobs were eliminated through voluntary
resignation, early retirements and not filling vacancies. 
<P>
The job cuts are the first in an attempt to trim two hundred and
twenty seven million dollars in government funding... next fiscal
year should see another one thousand jobs go. 
<HR>

<H3>Tree Shortage </H3>

<P>
Word from Ontario's Christmas tree growers is, if you're waiting
to buy your tree until prices drop, forget it. 
<P>
Bad weather in the north means the next shipment of trees may
not come at all, and there could be a shortage. Still you can
go and cut your own as Dwight Ryan reports. 
<P>
<I>Many of the Christmas trees that we buy here in southern Ontario
are grown way up north. And despite the lack of snow here, there's
plenty in the north. So much in fact that a mid season shipment
of trees may not arrive. </I>
<P>
<I>Hubert will harvests and sells Christmas trees at his Lynden
Ontario farm. He also heads up the Christmas Tree Growers Association
of Ontario. </I>
<P>
<I>Wills says if there's no let up in the weather up north, many
consumers may find themselves out of luck. And so more and more
people may be going to rural tree farms. and when you take it
home, remember to look after it. </I>
<HR>

<H3>AIDS Pennies </H3>

<P>
A St. Catharines woman is raising money for AIDS research, one
penny at a time. 
<P>
Thirty seven year old Katrina Rice is asking Niagara area students
to bring a penny to school next Valentine's Day so they can be
deposited into a special bank account. 
<P>
Rice hopes that the campaign can be expanded across the country...
she asked <I>Tonight Show </I>host Jay Leno to support the campaign
and he sent her the first penny. 
<HR>

<H3>Final Red Rocket </H3>

<P>
It was the last day for the old TTC red rocket ... the original
street cars have been in use for more than fifty years on the
streets of Toronto. 
<P>
The car was given a police escort and was decked out in ribbons
for its final ride. TTC supervisors were pleased with all the
fuss for the nostalgic trip, but wished the police cruiser would
have picked up the pace so their schedules could be met. 
<P>
Two of the old cars will be restored and kept for posterity. 
<HR>

<H3>Doggie Show</H3>

<P>
And Toronto went to the dogs today as the Seventeenth Annual Credit
Valley Dog Show gets underway at SkyDome... this weekend thousands
of top dogs from around the world will vie for championships,
titles, top dog glory in both obedience and confirmation square
offs. 
<P>
It is one of the largest dog shows in north America... proceeds
from the three day event will be donated to the Lions' Foundation
of Canada for their canine vision school in Oakville... 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Aid</H3>

<P>
Turning officials from Canada and 49 other countries, as well
as international organizations are in London, trying to find a
way to build a lasting peace in Bosnia. 
<P>
The delegates include Foreign Minister Andr&eacute; Ouellet. They
will try to create a climate of stability, setting up new political
and constitutional arrangements and a &quot;free-market&quot;
economy and kick-starting economic reconstruction. 
<P>
US Secretary of State Warren Christopher speaking at the conference
said that the NATO mission in Bosnia is historic because it brings
together for the first time several European armies working side
by side ...and the only enemy in Europe now, is war itself. 
<P>
Next week, the US Senate will vote on whether or not to support
sending twenty thousand Americans to join the NATO force, but
the outcome is irrelevant, the mission will go ahead. And preparations
are well underway and so is the jockeying for position. 
<HR>

<H3>France Strikes </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile talks are scheduled between trade unions and the Conservative
government in France to settle the three week old strikes that
have crippled the country. 
<P>
The talks will be have a mediator and a compromise on plans to
cut pensions, welfare and education funding will be sought. 
<P>
There was some violence again today as public transport and trains
came to a standstill for the fifteenth day in a row. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

