<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/07/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Thursday, December 7, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Campbell Bernardo
<LI>Legislature Protest
<LI>Wilson Gives
<LI>Rural Doctors
<LI>Past Protests
<LI>Welfare Tomorrow
<LI>Truck Inspections
<LI>Chlorine Water
<LI>Davies Funeral
<LI>Bosnia Canada
<LI>Paris Paralyzed
<LI>Jackson Update
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Campbell Bernardo </H3>

<P>
The Ontario government has appointed a senior judge to probe the
police investigation of the Paul Bernardo murder case. 
<P>
Solicitor General Bob Runciman says &quot;various aspects of the
investigation&quot; that led to murder charges against Bernardo
will be reviewed. Justice Archie Campbell of the Regional General
Division Court in Toronto will begin his work by reviewing a report
on the Green Ribbon Task Force investigation into the murders
of Leslie Mahaffy and Kristen French. That report is being prepared
by the Niagara Regional Police. 
<P>
Campbell will also look at a report on the so-called Scarborough
rapist investigation being prepared by Metro Toronto police. Runciman
says the circumstances surrounding Tammy Homolka's death and autopsies
performed on her will also be reviewed. 
<P>
Campbell is to report back to the Solicitor General by march 31st
with recommendations. Runciman says Campbell's report will be
made public, provided it protects people's privacy and there are
no legal proceedings under way. 
<HR>

<H3>Legislature Protest </H3>

<P>
An all night sit-in, led to negotiations... and now they've got
a deal. 
<P>
The stalemate was broken at Queens Park today as opposition parties
reached agreement with the government over its jumbo cost cutting
bill. The agreement came after an all night sit-in by MPPs in
the legislature . 
<HR>

<H3>Wilson Gives </H3>

<P>
Prior to the deal being struck Ontario's Health Minister backed
down from a proposal that would have given him sweeping new powers
to inspect and disclose the personal health records of private
citizens. 
<P>
Jim Wilson said he would amend the omnibus bill to satisfy the
concerns of Ontario information and Privacy Commissioner Tom Wright.

<P>
Meanwhile, the Ontario Medical Association is warning the Tories,
that its omnibus bill will cause an exodus of doctors from this
province. 
<P>
The OMA says, quote, unprecedented, almost unlimited, control
over the delivery of medical services is handed over to the government
in the bill. And word that the government will pull out of the
doctors malpractice insurance program will especially effect doctors
who deliver babies or staff small town emergency rooms, or those
who perform high risk procedures.
<HR>

<H3>Rural Doctors </H3>

<P>
And rural doctors are unimpressed by the government's decision
to pay them seventy dollars an hour to work nights and weekends
in the emergency wards. 
<P>
The money was to act as an incentive to doctors so rural areas
would be ensured emergency service. 
<P>
The Society of Rural Physicians says seventy bucks isn't enough.
Rural doctors serve about three-thousand patients on average,
compared with less than one-thousand for city physicians. 
<HR>

<H3>Past Protests </H3>

<P>
The method used to gain today's deal... involved violating the
rules of order, and it is a new opposition stall tactic. But Ontario's
legislators are certainly no strangers to bogging down the business
of government. 
<P>
As Anthony Pooley reports tonight ... the current Premier adroitly
used the good, old fashioned filibuster when he sat on the other
side. 
<P>
<I>Whether through filibustering or this latest method, part of
the politics of the opposition side of the legislature is to throw
obstacles in the path of government measures that members opposite
feel are moving things too far too fast. </I>
<P>
<I>Even so, disobedience to the rules of order as a tactic is
rare, if not unprecedented. But then, so is the kind of omnibus
legislation that is being attacked. </I>
<P>
<I>Premier Mike Harris himself is remembered for his own brand
of filibustering when he sat opposite government benches. The
issue then... as it is now... government spending. </I>
<P>
<I>And Liberal MPP Sean Conway, who was right smack dab in the
middle of the current round of stalling, once lamented the extent
to which the opposition could delay government business. Of course,
Conway was House Leader for Premier David Peterson at the time.
The issue ... Sunday shopping. </I>
<P>
<I>And let's not forget the one man filibuster of Welland- Thorold
MPP Peter Kormos against liberal auto insurance measures.</I>
<P>
<I>Anthony Pooley ... Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Tomorrow </H3>

<P>
Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi missed all the excitement
in the house.. but he had some of his own, in Kitchener at a conference
on welfare... protesters smacked his car with placards and yelled
at the minister as he arrived. 
<P>
They are calling the Tory government's changes to the welfare
system, Workfare. Inside the conference, there were delegates
from all across north America tackling the problems of welfare...
the meeting was not interrupted by the protesters ...but there
was a police officer on every door. 
<HR>

<H3>Truck Inspections </H3>

<P>
The safest trucking companies in Ontario are about to get a break.

<P>
A pilot project launched by the province today will reward companies
with excellent safety records. Their trucks will not be forced
to stop at every weigh scale they pass. 
<P>
Transport trucks are now required by law to pull into inspection
stations whenever weigh scales are open. But OPP officers say
the publicity surrounding truck safety problems, increased inspections
and a coroner's inquest into truck related deaths doesn't seem
to have made much difference. 
<HR>

<H3>Chlorine Water </H3>

<P>
One of Ontario's top water experts says a study linking chlorine-treated
water to bladder and colon cancer must be followed up to determine
where the problems are. 
<P>
Goff Jenkins of the Environment Ministry say hundreds of potential
derivatives from the chlorination process need to be studied before
changes are made to the water-treatment system. 
<P>
A study has suggested 10 to 13 per cent of bladder and colon cancer
cases in Ontario may be caused by decades of drinking and bathing
in chlorine-treated water. 
<P>
Many towns and cities use chlorine to reduce harmful bacteria
and viruses in drinking water supplies. 
<HR>

<H3>Davies Funeral </H3>

<P>
Funeral services were held today for Canadian literary giant Robertson
Davies. 
<P>
About 500 family members, friends, and fans attended the simple,
half-hour ceremony at trinity college chapel in the University
of Toronto. 
<P>
Davies died of a stroke last Saturday at the age of 82. His remains
are to be cremated and his ashes scattered near his home in Caledon,
Ontario. 
<P>
A public celebration at 7:30 tomorrow night at Convocation Hall
at U of T. 
<P>
Margaret Atwood, Timothy Findley, John Kenneth Galbraith and Globe
Arts Critic Robert Fulford are among those who will speak. 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Canada</H3>

<P>
Ottawa is asking for more talks with NATO to decide how Canadian
troops will be used in Bosnia. 
<P>
Canada has offered to send up to one-thousand soldiers, which
could include a combat battalion and a headquarters group. They'll
likely come from CFB Petawawa, Ontario. But the federal government
is asking for more say over how the soldiers will be deployed.

<HR>

<H3>Paris Paralyzed </H3>

<P>
Teachers have now joined a massive public workers' strike in France.

<P>
In Paris, nearly 70 per cent of teachers walked out to protest
government plans to overhaul French social security. And thousands
more marched in other parts of the country. And striking workers
shut down Orly airport in Paris for an hour. 
<P>
Demonstrators marched on the runways until they were removed by
police. 
<P>
Public transportation workers have been on strike for two weeks,
paralyzing traffic the dispute also has affected mail delivery,
hospitals and schools. 
<HR>

<H3>Jackson update </H3>

<P>
Lisa Marie Presley arrived at a New York Hospital under heavy
security to visit her super star husband... Michael Jackson spent
the night in a New York hospital after collapsing from extreme
low blood pressure.....the 37 year old singer is said to be recovering
well. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

