<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/06/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>


<H2>
<CENTER>
Wednesday, December 6, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Legis-Standoff 
<LI>Women's Demo 
<LI>Lap Dance Reversal 
<LI>McKnight Follow 
<LI>Bernardo-Water 
<LI>OJ to Speak 
<LI>Bus Crash 
<LI>Welfare Rebates 
<LI>Canada-Bosnia 
<LI>Bosnia Troops 
<LI>France Strike 
<LI>Japan Arrest
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Legis-Standoff </H3>

<P>
A Mexican standoff in the Ontario legislature! 
<P>
Opposition MPP's have refused to leave the chamber after refusing
to vote on the controversial omnibus bill. Some are calling it
a war zone. 
<HR>

<H3>Women's Demo </H3>

<P>
A demonstration in Toronto to mark the sixth anniversary of the
Montreal massacre quickly turned into a protest against Harris
government cutbacks. 
<P>
100 chanting women blocked part of a downtown intersection during
the morning rush hour. 22 were arrested and charged with mischief.

<P>
Activist Linda Torney says the economic havoc wreaked by Harris
and his corporate buddies is a form of violence against women.

<HR>

<H3>Lap Dance Reversal </H3>

<P>
An unusual twist to a familiar story. Welland city council has
changed its mind about lap dancing. 
<P>
Just two weeks ago, council voted to ban dirty dancing after hearing
a presentation from anti-lapper Katharine Goldberg. But a lawyer
for strip bar Roman's Babies told councilors that business at
Welland's only club has dropped about thirty-five percent. 
<P>
After re-considering, council reversed its decision. 
<HR>

<H3>McKnight Follow </H3>

<P>
And while violence against women is abhorrent; how much worse
is the case of those who profit from such violence? CAVEAT has
taken aim against convicted Hamilton killer, Dr. Robert McKnight;
and the hefty insurance policy ... that is paying him 60-thousand
dollars a year. Scot Urquhart has that story: 
<P>
<I>As Dr. Robert McKnight sits in Warkworth Prison, collecting
five thousand dollars a month in disability payments ... victim's
groups are reacting with horror.</I>
<P>
<I>CAVEAT founder Priscilla Devilliers says McKnight is not only
profiting from his crime, but taking taxpayers for a ride, as
we pay 81-thousand dollars a year for each inmate kept in a federal
prison. </I>
<P>
<I>She says the criminals themselves should be paying user fees.</I>
<P>
<I>But Devilliers admits, there is not much that CAVEAT can do
about the McKnight situation; she says it's up to the court of
public opinion ... the policy holders of Sun Life Trust; and the
doctors who are paying stiff insurance premiums, to provide Bob
McKnight with 60-thousand dollars a year.  And Devilliers sees
the McKnight case, as just another example of Canada's soft handling;
of hard criminals. </I>
<P>
<I>In Burlington, Scot Urquhart Channel Eleven New.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Bernardo-Water </H3>

<P>
And inmate Paul Bernardo got an unexpected shower today at Kingston
penitentiary. 
<P>
Another inmate tossed mop water through a slot in Bernardo's Plexiglas
cell front. The slot is used to pass food through to Canada's
most famous prisoner. 
<P>
Apparently the two prisoners were arguing before the water was
tossed. 
<HR>

<H3>OJ to Speak </H3>

<P>
It appears CNN is about to win the OJ interview sweepstakes. 
<P>
OJ Simpson says he'll give Ted Turners' all news network his first
unrestricted interview since the murder trial. Network Legal Analyst
Greta van Susteren says Simpson insisted there be no ground rules
for the interview. 
<P>
No date has yet been set for the CNN interview. 
<P>
Simpson was acquitted of killing his ex-wife Nicole and her friend
Ronald Goldman. He faces a civil suit by their families in April.

<HR>

<H3>Bus Crash</H3>

<P>
Two children are dead and two are badly injured in a collision
between a school bus and a trash truck in Los Angeles. 
<P>
Authorities say the truck sideswiped the bus carrying 48 children
this morning. A fire department spokesman says one of the injured
children is in critical condition and the other is serious. Most
injuries to the other 44 children were minor. 
<HR>

<H3>Welfare Rebates </H3>

<P>
Thousands of welfare recipients will get a rebate this month,
to make good on a campaign promise made by Premier Mike Harris.

<P>
The rebate is connected to a promise to allow welfare recipients
to get a job and earn back part of the money lost after the government
cut social assistance rates by 22-per-cent. 
<P>
Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi told the legislature
today the adjustments will be retroactive to October first. The
Social Services Minister says he hopes the rebate cheques will
be in the hands of welfare recipients before Christmas. 
<HR>

<H3>Canada-Bosnia </H3>

<P>
The question about what Canada's contribution to the NATO force
being sent to Bosnia has been answered. 
<P>
Just moments ago Defence Minister David Collenette announced that
Canada will send one thousand troops to Bosnia, with deployment
to begin almost immediately. 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Troops </H3>

<P>
In the meantime, a military base in northern Bosnia- Herzegovina
welcomed its first airplane in more than 18 months today. The
passengers will prepare the base for many more flights. 
<HR>

<H3>France Strike </H3>

<P>
In France, the biggest strike in nearly a decade is about to get
bigger. 
<P>
Already there's no mail, buses or trains. and now the strike is
about to spread from the ground to the skies. 
<HR>

<H3>Japan Arrest</H3>

<P>
South Korea isn't the only Asian nation putting some of its biggest
politicians behind bars. An anti-corruption campaign in Japan
has nailed its newest target, a former labour minister in the
middle of a twenty-seven million dollar loan scandal. 
<P>



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

