<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/05/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>

<H2>
<CENTER>
Tuesday, December 5, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Bernardo Evng 
<LI>McKnight-Money 
<LI>Gun Control 
<LI>Montreal Engineers 
<LI>Chretien Intruder 
<LI>Omnibus Walkout 
<LI>Immunization 
<LI>Rent Control 
<LI>Ontario Welfare 
<LI>New Coin
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Evng</H3>

<P>
The house where Paul Bernardo and Karla Homolka committed their
heinous acts of rape and murder, came down in a cloud of dust
this morning. 
<P>
A volunteer demolition team ripped into the building and had it
reduced to a pile of rubble within an hour. A convoy of dump trucks
carried the debris to a nearby landfill where it was buried under
ten feet of dirt, to dissuade would-be souvenir hunters. 
<P>
The Green Ribbon Task Force has wanted to destroy the house since
1993, and the neighbours have been waiting for months to see the
macabre tourist attraction leveled. 
<P>
Among the many who gathered to watch the destruction was Leslie
Mahaffy's mother, Debbie. Kristen French's niece Talon waited
until the demolition was complete so she could put flowers on
the site where Kristen and Leslie were murdered. 
<P>
Another house will likely be built one day, but the address will
be changed ...so there will never again be a &quot;57 Bayview&quot;
in Port Dalhousie. 
<HR>

<H3>McKnight-Money </H3>

<P>
At the moment there is no federal law to prevent criminals from
profiting from their crimes ... but many people say, there should
be. And some are pointing to the case of a convicted killer from
Hamilton; to prove their point. Scot Urquhart has that story:

<P>
<I>January, 1994. McMaster University professor Janet McKnight,
is murdered in her home. Her husband, doctor Robert McKnight;
is arrested at the scene; and eventually convicted of her murder.
He is sentenced to life in prison, with no chance of parole for
17 years. Lawyers have filed an appeal for that term of eligibility;
but they will not appeal the conviction. </I>
<P>
<I>Bob McKnight is now serving his sentence in Warkworth Penitentiary.
But every month as Bob McKnight counts the days ... he may also
be counting the balance in his bank account ... because Bob McKnight
... convicted murderer, receives five thousand dollars a month
in disability payments, through a group insurance policy provided
by the OMA, and Sun Life. </I>
<P>
<I>Joyce Lindsay is Janet McKnight's sister. She believes the
disability payments, are outrageous, and she wants them stopped.
Lindsay questions the validity of the claim; filed on the basis
of depression. There is also some question as to the timing; doctor
McKnight was arrested in January 1994 ... the claim was filed
a month later; while he was in custody.</I>
<P>
<I>The OMA ... will also say nothing; citing confidentiality.
There are rumours, that Sun Life is moving to cut off the payments
... and in fact, may have done so already. But if they have; no
one has told Bob McKnight. From his prison cell in Warkworth Tuesday
morning; McKnight confirmed that to the best of his knowledge,
he is still receiving five thousand dollars a month; and to those
who suggest that he is profiting from crime: &quot;I can see their
point of view. It's nice to receive the money. I am in debt ...
to my lawyers for example ... that money will go towards defraying
some of those costs. It's not like I am salting it away. The public
image is that doctors are wealthy ... I should stress that I have
no financial resources on the outside at the present time ...
I have lost everything.&quot; Some would ask by comparison ...
who has lost more. </I>
<P>
<I>In Barrie, Scot Urquhart Channel Eleven News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Gun Control</H3>

<P>
Justice Minister Allan Rock's controversial gun control bill received
royal assent and became law today. 
<P>
Bill C-68 requires the registration of all firearms and crack
down on the use of guns by criminals. Prime Minister Chretien
calls it the toughest gun law in the western world. 
<HR>

<H3>Montreal Engineers </H3>

<P>
The event that sparked the gun control bill will mark its sixth
anniversary tomorrow... in the time that has passed since Marc
Lepine went on a shooting rampage killing fourteen female students
at a Montreal engineering school, there are more women with the
faculty than ever before. 
<HR>

<H3>Chretien Intruder </H3>

<P>
The man charged with trying to kill the Prime Minister has been
remanded in custody for more psychiatric examinations. 
<P>
Thirty four year old Andr&eacute; Dallaire of Montreal will be
back in court on January fourth. Dallaire was charged after last
month's break in at the PM's residence. An intruder made it all
the way to the door of the Prime Minister's bedroom armed with
a knife. 
<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Walkout</H3>

<P>
It seems Finance Minister Ernie Eves has bowed to pressure brought
on by the opposition over the so called omnibus bill. 
<P>
Today, New Democrat MPPs walked out of the legislature en masse
to protest the bill. 
<P>
Meanwhile, labour groups hand delivered their own message to the
Harris government to nix bill 26. Finance Minister Ernie Eves
now says there will be more debate and public hearings. 
<HR>

<H3>Immunization</H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, Health Minister Jim Wilson has announced a 4.5-million
dollar plan to give Ontario's children and young people a second
vaccination against red measles. 
<P>
The immunization campaign will involve two million elementary
and high school students. A single dose of vaccine is currently
administered during infancy, but that fails to protect five to
10 per cent of the population. 
<P>
Ontario's Chief Medical Officer of Health has called for a mass
vaccination campaign as there has been an increase in the incidence
of measles and they can have serious complications. 
<HR>

<H3>Rent Control </H3>

<P>
Ontario will begin lifting rent controls next spring, but only
on luxury tenant housing to begin with. the rest is to follow
in 1997. 
<P>
Municipal Affairs Minister Al Leach says controls will remain
on low-end rental stock until a new system is designed to protect
tenants. And Leach says buildings for people with special needs,
such as seniors and the disabled, may be protected by rent control
indefinitely. 
<P>
Leach also says rent control exemptions on new buildings will
continue indefinitely to encourage more construction. 
<HR>

<H3>Ontario Welfare </H3>

<P>
Ontario's welfare caseload dropped by almost 22-thousand people
last month. 
<P>
The decrease of 1.6 per cent over October represents almost 10-thousand
households. Social Services Minister David Tsubouchi says it's
not clear if Tory policies were the defining factor in the lower
numbers, but he hopes so. 
<P>
Poverty groups say people have just given up going after the paltry
sum the Tories are offering. 
<HR>

<H3>New Coin </H3>

<P>
The doubloon is a step closer to your pocket...the first two-dollar
coins started rolling off the presses today at the Royal Canadian
Mint in Winnipeg. 
<P>
The coin is 28 millimetres in diameter, has a bronze centre, an
outer rim of nickel, and features a polar bear standing on an
ice floe. But don't look for the doublooney at banks and stores
just yet. It will be February before the coin goes into circulation.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

