<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/04/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
</CENTER>
</H1>

<H2>
<CENTER>
Monday, December 4, 1995
<IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H2>


<UL>
<LI>Bernardo Home Preps 
<LI>NATO -Bosnia 
<LI>Bosnia Clip 
<LI>Krop Viz 
<LI>Rural Doctors 
<LI>Omnibus Bill 
<LI>Arts -Cuts 
<LI>France Strike 
<LI>Queen Mum 
<LI>Santa Mandela 
<LI>Peel Cops Toys 
<LI>Trolley Cars 
<LI>Davies Obit
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo Home Preps </H3>

<P>
The former home of serial killer Paul Bernardo will be demolished
tomorrow morning. 
<P>
Workers from 12 demolition crews will arrive on the scene at eight-a.m.,
to begin the task of destroying the house where teenagers Kristen
French and Leslie Mahaffy were held captive and murdered. 
<P>
A steady stream of gawkers made one final trip today, to see the
infamous site.
<HR>

<H3>NATO-Bosnia</H3>

<P>
The Bosnian Serbs are planning a December twelfth referendum to
challenge the peace accord reached in Dayton, Ohio.
<P>
Meanwhile, the first troops of the NATO peacekeeping force that
will monitor the implementation of the peace deal have arrived
in Sarajevo. 56 British troops and equipment landed in the Bosnian
capital this morning. 
<P>
The advance contingent will set up communications for 25-hundred
other soldiers, who will arrive over the next few weeks. And the
first lot of Americans also arrived. twenty thousand US troops
will take part in the peacekeeping mission. 
<HR>

<H3>Bosnia Clip </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, in the House of Commons, the debate over whether or
not Canada should send any troops to Bosnia started in earnest
today. 
<P>
Defence Minister David Collenette indicated Canada will join the
NATO force, if only to preserve our international reputation.
Collenette says every NATO country will be participating. 
<P>
Collenette wouldn't say how many troops would be sent but it will
cost seventy million dollars. A final decision on Bosnian troop
deployment will be made by cabinet on Wednesday. 
<HR>

<H3>Krop Viz </H3>

<P>
Patients and supporters of Dr. Joseph Krop demonstrated outside
the offices of the Ontario College of Physicians and Surgeons.

<P>
Dr. Krop is a practitioner of alternative medicine, and has been
accused of incompetence and professional misconduct by the college.
However, his patients say Krop's consideration of diet and environment
is sensible and works. 
<P>
Krop's lawyer says the charges against him should be dropped,
because it has taken six years for the case to be heard. 
<HR>

<H3>Rural Doctors </H3>

<P>
The provincial government says it will help rural hospitals provide
24-hour emergency medical care. 
<P>
Health Minister Jim Wilson has introduced a plan to pay doctors
in small towns and cities 70-dollars an hour for night work and
on weekends and holidays. The payments should relieve the problem
of doctors not wanting to work odd shifts in rural emergency wards.
About 67 communities currently don't have full-time emergency
services. 
<HR>

<H3>Omnibus Bill </H3>

<P>
Opposition parties at Queens Park say the Harris government can
no longer be trusted. 
<P>
They hounded the government again today for bringing in an all
encompassing bill which will give the government unprecedented
powers. 
<HR>

<H3>Arts-Cuts </H3>

<P>
Actors, writers and directors have banded together to fight the
Harris government's cuts to cultural funding. 
<P>
Dozens of entertainers told a Queens Park news conference that
it is wrong for the government to say spending on arts and culture
is helping to create Ontario's deficit, when the arts create thousands
of jobs and generate 10-billion dollars or five per-cent of Ontario's
gross domestic product. 
<P>
The group says culture also defines our Canadian identity. And
for that reason alone we cannot afford to let it disappear for
a lack of funding. 
<HR>

<H3>France Strike </H3>

<P>
France's Prime Minister has called an emergency cabinet meeting
as a public workers strike spreads. 
<P>
The eleven day strike has crippled the country's cities as public
transportation has almost ground to a halt, stranding nearly one
million commuters. And the students have staged violent protests
as well .. the reason... government cutbacks..., 
<HR>

<H3>Queen Mum</H3>

<P>
The Queen Mother left hospital today, walking gingerly after having
her right hip replaced 18 days ago. 
<P>
The 95-year-old mother of the Queen smiled and waved at photographers
from the steps of King Edward the eighth Hospital for Officers.

<P>
The most popular member of the royal family has enjoyed robust
health until quite recently when a number of ailments have required
medical attention. 
<HR>

<H3>Santa Mandela </H3>

<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela has been named International
Santa Claus of the year. 
<P>
The award, which includes a 100-thousand dollar prize, honors
Mandela's work with children. It was chosen by a foundation in
Greenland, which claims to be the homeland of old saint nick.

<HR>

<H3>Peel Cops Toys </H3>

<P>
Peel Police were playing Santa as they held their annual toy drive.

<P>
The police take donations of Canadian Tire money, and then go
on a shopping spree. The toys are then given to the Salvation
Army and the charitable group distributes them to needy kids for
Christmas. 
<HR>

<H3>Trolley Cars </H3>

<P>
And a familiar sight in the streets of Toronto will soon be no
longer. 
<P>
The old trolley cars that have been in use for more than forty
years, will be retired at the end of this week. 
<P>
Two of them have been restored and will be kept for historical
interest... but they will no longer run any routes. 
<P>
Many passengers say they'll miss the old trolleys, even though
they were hot and stuffy in the summer months, and cold and drafty
in the winter. 
<HR>

<H3>Davies Obit </H3>

<P>
Readers around the world are mourning the death over the weekend
of internationally acclaimed author, Robertson Davies. 
<P>
The Canadian literary giant died in hospital in Orangeville. He
had pneumonia. 
<P>
Davies works included three trilogies, the most famous being the
Deptford trilogy including the renowned novel, Fifth Business.

<P>
In addition to his writing, Davies was a teacher, critic, playwright
and newspaperman. His publisher said the author's genius lay in
his ability to create an accurate picture of Canadian life, while
making you aware of human nature in all its variety. 
<P>
Davies had a knack of crystallizing revelations in one perfectly
crafted sentence. He won the Nobel prize in 1993. 
<P>
There will be a public memorial for Davies on Friday evening at
University of Toronto's Convocation Hall. 
<P>

<CENTER>
