<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 12/01/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Friday, December 1, 1995 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Eves Speaks 
<LI>Tory Poll 
<LI>UI Reforms 
<LI>Jobless Rate 
<LI>Reform Radical 
<LI>Unity 
<LI>Cop Funeral 
<LI>Basketball Death 
<LI>Baby Anne 
<LI>MADD Launch 
<LI>World AIDS Day 
<LI>French Strike 
<LI>Malle Funeral
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Eves Speaks </H3>

<P>
Fresh from being called a liar, Premier Mike Harris adamantly
rejected reports that his election promise on tax cuts might get
watered down. 
<P>
But his Finance Minister Ernie Eves wasn't quite so adamant about
possible changes to the promised tax cuts. Both men made post
mini-budget speeches at a combined Canadian and Empire Clubs in
Toronto today. 
<HR>

<H3>Tory Poll </H3>

<P>
Despite massive cuts this week, the Ontario Tories are still holding
a solid lead in decided voter support. But a new poll does indicate
that the honeymoon is waning. 
<P>
An Angus Reid poll released today indicates the conservatives
have 50 per cent of decided voter support. The Liberals are next
with 30 per cent while the New Democrats had 19 per cent support.
The poll says Tory support has dropped eight points since an October
poll, while the Liberals gained five points and NDP gained three
points. 
<HR>

<H3>UI Reforms </H3>

<P>
A major reworking of the unemployment insurance system was introduced
in the commons today by the federal government. 
<P>
Under the proposals, benefits will be cut, Canadians will have
to work longer to qualify for UI, and benefits will last up to
40 weeks instead of the current 50. 
<P>
Those and other changes are expected to save up to two-billion
dollars, which will be re-directed toward job-training and income
supplement. 
<P>
Human Resources minister Lloyd Axworthy -- who is responsible
for the UI overhaul -- says the system desperately needs updating.
Axworthy says it was set up 50 years ago when unemployment was
low and people held the same jobs for life. 
<HR>

<H3>Jobless Rate </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile the job market remains fairly static in Canada. 
<P>
The national unemployment rate was unchanged last month, still
standing at 9.4 per cent. Hamilton continues to have the lowest
jobless rate in the country at 5.9 percent. 
<P>
Toronto's employment picture brightened slightly. It came in at
7.8 percent, while the St. Catharines/ Niagara area experienced
an increase in its jobless rate to 8.6 per cent. 
<HR>

<H3>Reform Radical </H3>

<P>
Ominous activity in Quebec today... fourteen radical separatists,
including a former FLQ bomber, are starting a new political party
in Quebec. 
<P>
Members of the National Liberation Movement feel Quebec's current
leaders are too soft on separation. Raymond Villeneuve was an
FLQ bomber back in the early seventies when violence marked the
separatist movement. And that has raised concerns about the activities
of this new group. 
<HR>

<H3>Unity </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, the controversial shortcut to recognizing Quebec as
a distinct society is on its way through the house of commons,
as quickly as possible.. 
<P>
The government introduced a motion today limiting debate on the
part of the legislation that gives the regions a constitutional
veto. The motion has angered the Reform Party and the western
provincial leaders, who don't like being lumped in together, and
don't like Quebec getting any special treatment. 
<HR>

<H3>Cop Funeral </H3>

<P>
Some 15-hundred police officers from across North America were
in Montreal today for the funeral of a fallen colleague. 
<P>
Constable Odette Pinard -- a 30-year-old mother of two -- was
shot four days ago while sitting at her desk at a community policing
office. More than 50 investigators are on the case, and at least
800 people have been interviewed. despite that, police say they
have no suspects and no motive. 
<HR>

<H3>Basketball Death </H3>

<P>
A 19-year-old student who collapsed during a school basketball
practice in Toronto, has died. 
<P>
Sheldon Aberdeen of Oasis High School crumpled on the court at
Bloor Collegiate around eight thirty this morning. The coroner's
office is investigating. 
<HR>

<H3>Baby Anne </H3>

<P>
The Children's Aid Society of Toronto held a news conference this
afternoon to update reporters on the baby Anne case. 
<P>
She's the infant who was found abandoned in a cardboard box. The
Children's Aid Society has been awarded interim care, and on December
twentieth the Society will seek to have permanent wardship so
that the adoption process may begin. 
<P>
Baby Anne has a foster home for Christmas, and hospital staff
say she's up to the event. Efforts to find the baby's parents
have so far failed. 
<HR>

<H3>MADD Launch </H3>

<P>
The LCBO store at Queens Quay in Toronto has been wrapped with
a 500-foot ribbon, officially launching the month-long red ribbon
campaign. Mothers Against Drunk Driving chair, Tony Carvalho and
LCBO chief Andy Brandt led the ceremonies. 
<P>
The program encourages people to tie one on ...by putting a red
ribbon on their car aerial in a show of support for getting drunk
drivers off the road. 
<P>
Throughout December, all Ontario LCBO stores will offer the red
ribbons to customers... and coin donation boxes will be displayed.

<HR>

<H3>World AIDS Day </H3>

<P>
Today is world AIDS day. A day to recognize that 20 million people
around the globe are HIV positive. A quarter of them have developed
full blown aids. 
<P>
While there is still no cure for the deadly disease, the federal
government is terminating funding for its national AIDS strategy.
Combined with cuts from Queen's Park, AIDS activists are up in
arms. Dwight Ryan has the story. 
<P>
<I>Members of Toronto's gay community slam the government for
cutbacks. While countries around the globe are marking world AIDS
day, Canada is in the midst of phasing out its national AIDS strategy.
</I>
<P>
<I>The program won't be renewed for a third term when it runs
out in 1998. Toronto gays say its time to get more active. </I>
<P>
<I>McCaskell says Canadians must realize that AIDS and HIV are
not gay issues. In fact the population group facing the biggest
increase in AIDS and HIV is heterosexual women. They in turn often
have babies that are HIV positive.</I>
<P>
<I>The Canadian college of family physicians has now introduced
a comprehensive guide for members of the medical community who
find themselves dealing with AIDS patients more often. Many of
them children. </I>
<P>
<I>Twenty million people in the world have HIV. Four and a half
million have developed full blown AIDS.</I>
<P>
<I>In Toronto, Dwight Ryan, channel 11 news.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>French Strike </H3>

<P>
France has been crippled by a massive strike by public workers...
trains, busses, planes are ground to a halt...and so is the traffic
in the country's major cities... hospitals are also effected,
and the French are become weary and worried about how long it
will go on. 
<P>
Union workers are protesting a government move to cut back on
their pensions. 
<P>
Meanwhile, students have waged their own campaign demanding more
government spending... a campaign of violence.
<HR>

<H3>Malle Funeral </H3>

<P>
Many of France's leading stars from the French cinema paid their
last respects to French director Louis Malle today. 
<P>
The funeral was held at the church of St. Sulpice in Paris. Malle
leaves behind his wife, actress Candice Bergen and their daughter.
He died of lymphoma at their Beverly hills home. Malle was known
for films such as pretty baby, Atlantic city, and my dinner with
Andr&eacute;. 
<P>

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

