<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Evening News: 11/29/95</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../../images/evening.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
On-Line Archive
<H2>Wednesday, November 29, 1995 <IMG SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</H2>

</CENTER>
</H1>

<UL>
<LI>Mini Budget 
<LI>Labor Demo 
<LI>Highway Safety 
<LI>Needle Machine 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Mini Budget </H3>

<P>
Never before has Ontario seen anything like it ... that's what
analysts are saying after today's mini budget from the Tories.

<P>
Municipalities, educational institutions, and health care will
strongly feel the financial squeeze as the Harris government cuts
5.5 billion dollars to get its fiscal house in order. Finance
Minister Ernie Eves says he will balance the provincial budget
while boosting economic growth to create jobs. Bob Ireland has
more from Queens Park. 
<P>
<I>Currently the Ontario government spends one million dollars
an hour more than it receives in revenues. Interest costs alone
on the provincial debt amounts to nine billion dollars. The government's
money goes out in grants to hospitals, universities, colleges
and municipalities. and those areas got hit the hardest in Ernie
eves economic statement. </I>
<P>
<I>As a result, the trickle down effect will mean every Ontarian
will share in the pain. Transfers to school boards will be cut
by 400 million dollars in the next fiscal year.  But they are
warned not to get it back by raising local taxes. </I>
<P>
<I>Funding for colleges and universities will be reduced by 400
million. But next year universities will be allowed to increase
tuition fees by a base ten per-cent, and be given the discretion
to increase costs to students a further 10 per-cent. College fees
will go up 15 per cent. </I>
<P>
<I>Hospitals will see their grants cut by 1.3 billion dollars
over the next three years. But more money will be made available
for treatment of brain injuries and immunization programs. </I>
<P>
<I>Effective June first next year seniors and welfare recipients,
receiving benefits under the Ontario drug benefit program will
have to pay an extra two dollars for each prescription. And families
with incomes over 24-thousand dollars a year, will be asked to
pay a deductible 100-dollars a year. </I>
<P>
<I>The government will reduce funding to municipalities by one
billion dollars. Grants for municipal recycling will be phased
out. Libraries, and local transit grants will be reduced. </I>
<P>
<I>Finance Minister Eves says, unconditional and road grants will
be folded into a single block fund. And municipalities will have
the flexibility to spend according to their priorities. Municipalities
will also be given the power to charge user fees for some services
like garbage collection to name just one. </I>
<P>
<I>Liberal Leader Lyn McLeod accused the Harris government of
taking money out of health care and education to pay for his future
30 percent tax cut. </I>
<P>
<I>NDP leader Bob Rae calls the economic statement a dishonest
document. </I>
<P>
<I>Finance Minister Eves is projecting real growth this year of
2.1 per-cent.. and 3.1 per-cent by 1997. He also predicts inflation
will stay below two per-cent through the next three years. </I>
<P>
<I>At Queens Park, Bob Ireland, Channel 11 News. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Labor Demo </H3>

<P>
Government workers demonstrated in front of a Canada Employment
Centre in Ottawa today to protest expected federal cuts to unemployment
insurance. 
<P>
Under changes to be announced Friday, about 100- thousand families
would lose U.I. benefits, while about 35 thousand families would
get more. That's because benefits will be pegged to family rather
than individual income. And it will be tougher to qualify in the
first place. 
<HR>

<H3>Highway Safety</H3>

<P>
A pilot program was launched in Kitchener today that will see
motorists helping others who are in trouble. 
<P>
Called Highway Help, the program is expected to be province-wide
by this time next year. The story from Dwight Ryan. 
<P>
<I>Thousands of motorists pull off to the side with health or
vehicle problems each day. But few people are willing to help,
often fearing for their own safety. </I>
<P>
<I>A new program introduced today in Kitchener is designed to
help alleviate the problem. Called Highway Help, motorists will
be given signs to display on their drivers' window. Passers-by
are encouraged to call police on their cellphone or C.B. radio
...but not to stop. </I>
<P>
<I>Chief Kevin McAlpine of Peterborough is president of the Ontario
Association of Chiefs of Police.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Needle Machine </H3>

<P>
For health care workers the disposal of used needles has become
a critically important procedure, especially since the beginning
of the AIDS epidemic. The question has always been ... what is
the best method? 
<P>
Well a Brantford entrepreneur thinks he has the answer in a machine
that eats the potentially deadly bits of metal.... Jamie West
reports... 
<P>
<I>And it appears Ralph Haines has done just that. The Needle
Eater is being gobbled up by dentists and doctors faster than
the Brantford production line can keep up... </I>
<P>
<I>There are at least 50 known blood born pathogens that can be
transmitted through used needles... </I>
<P>
<I>After 17 years of selling insurance Haines was bitten by the
entrepreneurial bug. 149 days from the drawing board the Needle
Eater was born. An electrical charge incinerates the needle and
seals the end of the syringe that can then be put in the regular
garbage. The machine can handle thousands of needles before the
residual ashes needs to be emptied.</I>
<P>
<I>The modest assembly line produces about 100 Needle Eaters a
week. Diabetic models retail for 99 dollars, and are available
through the Canadian Diabetic Association. Larger hospital use
machines sell for about 249 dollars.</I>
<P>
<I>In Brantford Jamie West Channel Eleven News. </I>
<P>

